description: The climb directly to the left 20 Clicks. Sit/squat start on left crimp and right on the jug. Work up and over the lip using a crux crimp on to easier ground. Top out straight up.

name: Embrace the Chaos (aka Branded for Life)
description: A fun little problem that doesn't get much attention.  Sit start in the corner with your left hand up on a crimp/flake and your right hand on a gaston sloper.  There is a small left foot that will let you tension up and toss in a massive dropknee.  Move right hand up to the slot, rock around the arete on jugs, then follow the arete to the top.  Downclimb until you can hop over onto the top of Gran Torino.    This problem can also be done by pulling up to the lip on the left and following it back to the jugs out right, but where's the fun in that?

name: Freezing Point Depression
description: Great holds, cool moves, and one of the better moderates in the woods.  It starts in the middle of the face, traverses to the arete, and then climbs up to a good topout.  Sit start with your right hand on the obvious flake and left hand on a good sidepull.  Pull off the ground and bump up to another left hand sidepull.  Pop a right foot up, then move left hand into the undercling at your waist.  Transition over to the right and bump out to a nub on the arete.  Fall into a sidepull with your left hand and fight the barndoor.  Slap up to a jug right hand and make a couple of moves to gain the lip directly above.

name: Freezing Point Direct
description: Good hold.  Easy move.  Good hold.  Big move.  Bad hold.  Even bigger move.  Good hold.  Topout.  Woohoo.  A crimpy, powerful problem that starts and ends as for Freezing Point Depression without sharing a single move.  Sit start with the nice flake in the middle of the face and pull up to a left hand crimp in the horizontal.  Make a big move up and right to a crimp, before fixing your feet and pulling straight up to the lip.    To make the last move slightly easier, use a sketchy sidepull for your left hand and then pull up to the lip.

name: Giving Up Skin for the New Year
description: Start with your left hand in a cool undercling pocket and right crimping a crystal. Find a foot (higher than you want) and lunge for a good edge up and right. Top out.

name: Gran Torino (aka The Bitch)
description: Obvious bald low-ball boulder on the right just before warm up area, by V2 My Ass.    Start sitting on the right on a nice jug, then move up and left using the super-hard fine grained slopers and the start hold as your only foothold. Keep moving left fighting the urge to poop yourself or fall (or both), until you reach the other jug wayyyy out left.  Let your foot cut and top it out.  Shouldery and slopey and worth a laugh.    Check it out in the film Uncommon Ground

name: Infinite Sullen
description: To the right of Giving Up Skin, locate another low start on a weird sidepulldercling and an decent edge. Make a hard move or two into more moderate climbing.

name: My Ass Face
description: A tall, mostly smooth and intimidating face. Slab climbing on crystal crimps and interested features. Pray that your feet hold and work your way up the face. Super technical, but a V1 once you figure it all out.

name: Not Giving Up Skin
description: Skipping the crux first move of Giving Up Skin for the New Year yeilds a fun moderate in the sun on the forgotten boulder.  Stand start, reaching high to the right hand flake. Left hand on any slopey thing you find, and get a high right foot to reach a fun series of sidepulls to a sloping top out.

name: Rio's Sharp Problem (aka Oil & Water)
description: Climbs the face up and left.  Sit start with right hand on a big flake, left hand on a sidepull with good feet.  Bump left hand up to another sidepull, move right hand onto a sloping hold, and stand up to a painful crimp.  Work your feet up and (crux) grab a jug at the lip.  Topout.      Really good if you can deal with the sharp crimp.

name: Slabbin' In My Dreams
description: To the right of V2 My Ass, there is a tall blunt arete, this route climbs up that arete. The crux comes at about 12 feet when you need to trust a smear and reach high to a good sloper.

name: V2 My Ass
description: Stand start the left angling arete.  Reach high with the right hand and get a high right foot.  Lay back the arete to the left, the crux is getting up over your feet in the first few moves.  With the right beta it really is V2 (get your left foot in the high scoop.)

name: v2 my Ass Sit
description: The sit start to v2 my A**. Start at the base of the arete on a left-leaning sloper rail and climb into the stand start via some heinous slopers and terrible feet.

name: All Purpose
description: Sit start on the arete on the backside of the boulder. Pull on edges and work up and right using crimps, sidepulls, and body tension before a big move to the top out this great climb.  Great climb for a friction heavy day, miserable if it is humid.

name: Barndoor
description: This problem is so inviting. A really long slopey arete that goes from left to right. Start on two good side pull crimps; pull up to the slopey arete and continue right on really good feet. Top-out at the highest point of this boulder.

name: The Bloody Nose
description: sit start and climb the positive holds on the blunt nose. The sit start is the crux because of the weird holds, they are not as positive as the holds on the rest of the route. From the start pull up and climb the flakes and decent feet to the top out. The top out can be a little dirty but its all there.

name: Cat and Mouse
description: Sit start on small edges and decent feet, move up and left to an edge and gain the fun topout.

name: El Scorcho
description: Start sitting on the left arete. There are a couple different options for starting holds. I used a terrible sidepull crimp for my right hand and a slightly better sidepull crimp, around the corner from the arete, with my left hand. Pull off the ground with difficulty and slap up and right to an angled sloper on the lip. Match the lip with the left hand and fight for a couple more moves to reach better holds. Throw a heel on and press out a reasonably easy mantel. The first few moves are definitely the crux.    Short and stout! Good conditions definitely help. But, no matter what the conditions, this climb will likely destroy your skin.    I can't say I recommend this climb, but it might be worth doing if you've run out of things to climb or you consider yourself a masochist.

name: Firecracker
description: Start with both hands on a decent face hold, then move up and to the left past the crack.  Move up again to the top (some tricky foot beta will help) and mantel the finish.

name: Firecracker Arete
description: A powerful problem that starts with the right hand low in the crack, that runs straight up the boulder. Left hand on a small edge on the arete. Use real good feet to power up to a positive crimp. Move left foot to a bad, but sticky foot. Bump right hand up in the crack (crux for me). One last throw to a sloper and the "business" is done. Then top out on good slopers.

name: Janet Gets a Wirebrush
description: Start standing with your left hand on a good crimp/edge on the arete. Your right hand can start matched on this hold, or on small holds out right. Pull on, grab a fragile undercling/sidepull with your right and slap to a fairly bad sloper on the arete. Now sort out a way to get yourself to the top! Top out at the apex of the boulder.

name: Never Ending Scrubber
description: Start standing with both hands on a good, high flake. Pull off the ground and work left via slopers, edges and eventually jugs, finishing at the apex of the arete.

name: Pinkerton
description: Although listed as V2 in the guidebook, this tricky face climb doesn't feel anything like V2 even on the best of days.  Stand start with a pair of crimps at about the 4' level and choose how you will proceed.  Either power into the undercling with small feet and then toss for the good crimp, or skip the undercling with a toe hook and grab a high left edge before reaching up to the crimp.  Stick the lip and mantle over.  It's fun either way.

name: The Pocket Problem
description: A quick, five move problem that is both dynamic and shouldery, but the holds are friendly.  Start standing with two cool pocket-like holds above your head, plant a foot on the large shelf and dyno up and left to a very specific spot on the faint arete.  Plant a right foot on one of the small nubs and power out left again to the flat jug shelf.  Match and finish up.

name: The Pop Tart
description: Sit start on the right side of the huge flake. Move up into the jug then progress up with good feet to a slopey top out. This is a fun balancy route.    or an alternate description...    This is a really good V0. Start on a huge flake that looks like the head of a dog. The flake also continues down right. Find feet and move right hand above head up to a pretty good sloper. Bump right foot up into the flake onto an awesome foot. Bump right hand up and left (crossing over your head) to a good crimp with a killer thumb catch. Pull up and match. Next get high feet and stand up. Super fun!

name: Rubber Cement
description: A short, powerful problem.  Sit start on a good flat hold on the arete.  Finesse your way up into two underclings at waist level, then step high and slap out right for the crystal (crux).  Crimp hard and stand up to a better hold out left before topping out.    Someone attacked this problem with a brush not long ago and yielded new but useless holds out left.

name: Sharp Arete
description: Start sitting at the bottom of the arete on some sharp quartz holds. Move leftwards along the arete via sharp quartz slopers, crystals, edges and jugs to a somewhat tricky top out. This climb is kind of like a slightly harder, much sharper version of 'General Lee'.    If you can tolerate the pain, this climb is actually fairly enjoyable.

name: Valley Girls
description: A crimpy, dynamic climb that is unfortunately a bit cramped due to the tree.  Sit start with your back to the flora with two crimps and follow the crimps out right until making a big move up to a hold on the faint arete.  Pull on through to the top.

name: Folded Ducks
description: Start on the back arete (away from the trail) on two sidepulls in some folded, orange rock with big feet.  Pull hard and throw left to the small crimp on the face.  The feet are surprisingly awkward but huge. Work on sidepulls and crimps on the face and arete to the top slopers.  Watch out for the branches!

name: Horn Over My Pockets
description: Start in the big, lowest crack/pocket to the right of the face next to "Folded Ducks." Feet are awkward and deceptively hard to figure out. Pull off the ground to two more spaced vertical pockets, hit the pinch then the horn.  Top out on the big, bad holds.  Don't grab the sapling like I did and missed the (possible)FA.

name: Anaconda
description: This is the blunt arete to the right of lumberjack. The stand went back in the day of "Rio" and felt V8. A few years back Vasya did the sit. Start on a small  pinch with your right and your left on a side pull, stand up into a very powerful under cling and slap right hand to a good side pull muckle your feet and body up squeezing so water comes out of the rock. The climb feels like 2 stacked V8s to me but really needs more opinions

name: General Lee
description: Start on the undercling sitting, and move up and left to grab the sloping lip. Hope it feels good, because there are more slopers coming. Follow the sloping lip left and find the wierd sloper on the fin on the top out, mantle up to the rounded fin.   The whole time I'm on this climb (short as it might be) I am having so much fun hanging onto these slopers, don't try to skip the moves, enjoy them!

name: Jeremy's Sick Crimps
description: A  one move wonder. Grab two small crimps. The right one is really thin and a little bit higher up than the left crimp of which is slopey. Grab the holds pull of the ground and shoot for the slopey lip of General Lee. Top out the same for General Lee.

name: Lumberjack
description: A burly, technical climb.  Start from a sit with some crimps on the face.  Some good footwork and a little luck will get your hands onto the arete above, and some better footwork and more luck will get you onto the slabby top.  The crux is getting established on the slabby topout, but the burly start and the slab above are not to be taken lightly.  Super fun!

name: The Next Message
description: This problem climbs a crack that splits a 45-degree overhung wall on small island in a pond. Start with both hands low in the crack and make a hard move to a juggy fingerlock. Set your feet, maybe pause on a poor intermediate, and jump to a crystally ball on the lip of the boulder, then press it out. Short, powerful, and aesthetic.

name: Reverse Scoop
description: Start in the stripped flakes on next to the left arete on the back side of the boulder. Make a crux first move than climb easier ground to the top. This problem isn't splendid but worth a go it you are in the area. Walk off to the right of the route.

name: The Scoop
description: Super-sharp crimps!   Start on the slab/rock and get close to the slightly overhanging short face, grab some sharp crimps and climb the relatively uninteresting face trending right up to slopers for the top out.   This climb routinely stumps climbers solid at the grade. This climb is not beta intensive, it just has wierdness that results in pulling hard and going up.

name: Teachers Pet
description: This problem is fun and good intro to bouldering on something that is a little taller. Start on the large hold about ten feet right of The Scoop. Work your way up on big holds to an easy top out. The crux is moving to the lip and it involves a long move but with great hands.

name: Ambiguous Bang
description: Stand start with a right hand sloper and low left hand crimp. Pull on to the wall and make a blind smack to a sloper ball and then figure out how to topout.

name: Amnesia
description: A great route that combines lots of burl and reach with a bit o' technique.  Start under the roof and climb out on decent holds, then onto the face on some crimps.  Get yourself established and make a big move to the left to a small rail.  From there the moves get easier, pinch a cool quarts nob and top out.

name: The Certain Other
description: The stand start to child of the storm starts with a LH on the good crimp rail and RH in the thin seam crimp, both at face level. Move up and left into the groove above. Hard first move(s) and a top out that's more difficult than you'd like.

name: Child of the Storm
description: Sit start, move right and up on bad crimps, then deadpoint up to bad crimps with body tension, left hip in and stick the flake without barn-dooring. Top out left on slopers and weird pinches. On the FA Dave Graham uses his knee to aid him in the wet rock mantle.

name: Da Luvah
description: Stand start with hands above head on a good high sloping hold.  Put a foot on the belly of the boulder and surge way out right to a jug that's only a bit higher.  Then rock up onto a left foot, getting as much weight off your hands as possible, and streeetch up the sloping arete, possibly matching on a terrible sloper to get to the finishing jugs.  The middle match move is tenuous.

name: Jon's Arete
description: Climbs the beautiful, powerful arete and face right of the tree.  Sit start with a right hand jug beneath the arete and a left hand sloper (under the roof in the crack) with your feet underneath the roof.  Pull up left hand to a sloping seam, heelhook with the right foot and bump up successive, worsening crimps near the arete with your right hand to a good jug.  Stand tall from the jug to reach the lip and topout.    Usually wet for days after rain.    An easier version, although somewhat awkward, uses the sloping seam with the right hand allowing you to pull up to some flakes behind the tree.

name: Jon's Arete Right
description: Sit start as for Jon's Arete and climb up and right utilizing a good right heelhook until you can snag the pocket like jug. From here come in and match. After matching hands head out right to a decent sidepull, and then climb up and right on the arête.

name: Rat Fish Dyno
description: This is a quick one-move wonder for those with a big wingspan and strong fingers. On the face on the backside of the swirly boulder, locate the unusual black triangular pinch. Grab this with your right hand and find one of two sloping dishes out left for your other hand. Put a foot on the wall and dyno for the sloping lip of the boulder. Catch it and top out. It takes nearly a six-foot wingspan just to grab onto the starting holds, so the grade is arbitrary at best - it's v-impossible if your reach is too much less than 6'.

name: The Rose (of Confrontation)
description: This problem feels impossible without the right beta.  Crouch at the lowest part of the arete and trend right and up using severely sloping holds on the lip of the arete.  Funky footwork and tenaciously slapping the slopers the right way are the ticket to success.  An interesting mantle caps this short, but fierce beauty.  Sick downclimbs are found on the opposite arete/face of the Rose.

name: Sit and Deliver
description: Sit start to Stand and Deliver. Start sitting on two decent holds directly below the left start hold of Stand and Deliver, they are the lowest usable holds. Make a slightly awkward move into an undercling pinch with your left hand. From here use some trickery to set up your feet and throw right hand around the corner to the non-existent sloper. Now finish up Stand and Deliver, two hard compression moves and a big move to a good crimp get you to better holds to top out.  In my opinion the sit adds a lot of quality to this classic line

name: Slash
description: A substantial amount of discussion on the page for Jon's Arete  is actually about this climb, so I figured I'd add it.  I welcome any corrections from the area experts.    Start with your hands low in a slopey seam (with your right hand where your left hand might start for the neighboring "Jon's Arete").  Move up and left to a climbing gym style crimp that is unfortunately located behind a tree.  Continue up the slanting crimp rail and top out as per Jon's Arete.    The crux is probably avoiding the tree.  If you or your clothing touch it, even a little, your send is worth nothing.  Your friends are spotting you, but they are also waiting to yell "dab!" at the slightest contact.    This climb feels a grade or two easier than Jon's Arete and would be the more natural line if it weren't for the tree.

name: Stand & Deliver
description: One of the best boulder problems anywhere. Great rock and great movement. Start standing with your right hand on the arete and your left hand on the undercling/pinch hold on the face (shorter types may have to stack pads to reach the best spot on the arete). Squeeze hard and get your feet onto the boulder, then start moving up - either left or right hand will work, though going with the right hand first definitely favors taller climbers. Sometimes a heel hook is used on the left. After these first couple moves to get established on the obvious sloper on the face and the better crystally feature on the arete, the difficulty eases off a bit. Deadpoint to the high crimp on the face and work to the top using a heel hook on the arete. Mantel it out and celebrate.       Note: this can also be done from a sit start, at around v12. Start sitting at the obvious holds on the sloping ledgy bit, grab the pinch/undercling with your left hand, bring your feet up high and turn in to make a huge, controlled move to the arete. Then finish the stand start.

name: Swirley Flake
description: Choose from an assortment of quartz crimps. Figure out a way to pull off the ground and establish on the flake above. Once established on the flake, follow small but good edges to the top.     Not sure if something has broken on this (it looks like something has) but this climb is fairly technical at the grade. Harder than its neighbor to the right.     Not a great climb by any means, but worth doing if you're in the area and looking for something different.

name: Swirley Slab
description: The easiest way down off the Swirley boulder that is still rock climbing.  Really a great warmup or a proud tick in its own right.  Start with a sharp crystalline hold for the right hand and high flake for the left hand.  Smear or micro edge the feet on and work up the flake to good holds above and a great topout.

name: The Topout Problem
description: As the name implies, the crux of this one is topping out. Start on the ugly glue-reinforced flake at head height and make a hard move or two to get established on the sloping lip of the boulder. Throw your heel up over your head into an insecure dish and begin the hard process of rocking over. There are some small edges and divots high up on the slab that will eventually help to you get your weight onto your heel and stand up, if you make it there!

name: Uncle Climax
description: Grab two small sloping crimps above head height.  Pull a campus move to the sloping dish above with the left hand.  Squeeze and put your feet on the wall.  Then make a big move with the right hand to a really small crimp way up there (can be difficult to see in poor light).  A low percentage move, perhaps.  Then reset the feet and hands and go for the lip.  Nice jug up there.  Snag it and top out.  Really good, maybe classic.

name: Black Lung (boulder)
description: A short and powerful overhanging arete on good rock. Sit start with a slopey right hand sidepull undercling feature and a decent slopey left hand undercling left of the arete. Pull on a make a few compression moves up before executing a good topout.

name: Tragic Visions
description: A good ole fashioned Blair Woods condition dependent one-mover. Sit start with a sloper shelf for the right hand and a jug left hand crystal undercling. Pull on, match then decipher how to reach the lip and topout.

name: American Fat
description: Start on an undercling and a decent left hand and climb up the rounded arete with small slopey crimps and good feet. The crux is getting off the ground, but by getting your but in the right position it is fairly easy.

name: Annie Oh
description: Sit start and climb up and right following the jugs to the good top out. If you cant find a big hold you must have missed something. The crux is at the top but the holds are still very large.

name: B Becca
description: Another hard Pawtuckaway one-mover that you may just want to just keep walking past. Start with an undercling for your left, and either a sidepull or an undercling for your right. Pick from the myriad of usable feet and pull on to the wall with difficulty, a long move/dyno or a bad intermediate gets you to the jug.

name: Black Widow Action
description: Sit start on the right side of the face with a crimpy, fingery flake and try not to roll down the hill.  Make a difficult pull up and left to the jug in the middle of Doing Daddy Long Legs and finish up that problem.

name: Burt Gives Blow Jobs
description: Sit start the arete with hands on each face and both feet on the left.  Move up with the right hand to a gaston and then up again to a sloper.  Work the feet up and mantel over the top (crux.)  There's a small, bad hold way up for the right hand to help with the mantel.

name: Damn the Man (aka Turkjiggistan)
description: This problem may be short, but a lot of people can't get off the ground.  Sit start with two slopers on the lip, the left of which is crystally, and make a crux move to the big juggy pinch in the middle of the climb.  Finish straight up on crimps.    There used to be a little tree growing at the base of the climb which was not in the way.  Someone ripped it out.

name: Dirty Frown
description: Stand start with your hands on a good sidepull. Find what feet you can and pull up to a good crystal above the lip. Move your feet around to find the best position for you. Pull hard and mantel the problem for the top out.     Have fun on this one it's got an interesting top out.

name: Disposable Stitches
description: Sit Start as you would for Pop On Top and traverse left to the arete of Scared for Life. The key is staying low and using some interesting beta to get established on the arete, which is also the crux. The top out is slopey.

name: Doing Daddy Longlegs
description: A classic problem that is also a great Warm-up.    Start crouching on the lowest jug in the middle of the face, then move up and right to the next jug before moving on to sloping ground with a hidden positive hold that helps the topout. Be mindful of where the footholds are, they disappear once you start to topout.

name: Doing Daddy Longlegs Direct
description: Start on the sharks tooth and the edge or side pull as you would for the sit start variation but instead of going to the jugs out right climb straight up to a slopey top out.

name: Doing Daddy Longlegs Sit Start
description: The crux is getting off the ground. Sit Start with right hand on sharks tooth and left hand on and edge or side-pull just above it. Make a strenuous move to the jug that starts the regular problem. This move is made difficult by awkward feet and the slope of the hill you start on.

name: Eurotrash
description: Sit start at the bottom of the very round and mossy arete. The crux is getting off the ground, unless the moss is wet and slippery.

name: The Extra Ion
description: At first, I wasn't impressed, but this problem grew on me.  It has some tiny, bad holds, a crux deadpoint, and beat the hell out of my fingers.  Sit start the rear arete with some decent edges, pull up to a terrible sloper on the arete, then work your feet around and fight a savage barndoor as you deadpoint up to a very thin three-finger crimp.  Slap up to a good sidepull and finish up with a few easy moves to the top.

name: The First Class Variation
description: This is a right-hand start to Burt's. Start sitting around the arete to the right with your right hand on a small sidepull and your left on the arete. Throw left hand up, and match right hand on the arete (crux). Move left until you can join Burt's for the topout.     This is a cool variation that adds a few more hard moves to a classic problem.

name: Forget Your Feet
description: Stand start with good crystals at head height. Find your feet and pull up to another crystal. Bring your feet up higher and mantel the problem.

name: In Too Deep aka (Easy Slope)
description: Stand start with hands at head height in a good dish/jug. Get your feet on and pull up to gain good holds. Top out the problem.    Try to not use the tree for help up this thing.     This will be a good thing for beginner climbers to get on since it's only a few moves with big holds.

name: Pickled and Ferm
description: Right hand in rounded out seam, left hand around corner on shallow slope, thuggish left hand move to crystal nubs,and top out

name: Pop on Top
description: Good Warm-up.   Start in the middle of the face and work up and a tiny bit to the right.   Fun Problem!   Top-out is a great time if you like flat top-outs, bring chalk if it is warm. There are no positive holds for the topout.

name: Red Fish
description: While this short arete may have once been a low quality V2, some holds broke and now it's an overlooked V4 with a V8ish variation.  Pull on to the arete using bad hands and feet and pop for the lip, then top it out.  Exiting left is the easier version.    The V8 variation uses the arete for the left hand and poor crimps on the wall right of the arete to start.  Dyno big with your right hand to a hidden jug and top it out.

name: Scarred for Life
description: A fun blunt arete.  Stand start with your left hand on the arete and right on an undercling, balance and deadpoint to a good crimp and head up to a slopey topout.  Good warm-up.    Watch out for the ledge rock if you fall.

name: Shark Attack
description: Start standing with your right hand on a small sidepull crimp and left on the arete. Bump up the arete, hit a higher sidepull, and work out the slopey top. Heel hooks are your friend.

name: Sloper Sport
description: This is a short but sweet run and jump problem. It literally has no holds, so you are forced to charge at the wall, place your foot on, and viciously jump to the sloping lip. Actually, it's easier in sneakers than climbing shoes. Difficult, friction-dependent, and frustrating but kind of fun if you like this sort of thing. It will feel v-impossible in the summer, guaranteed

name: Throwing Trumps
description: A dynamic, short problem up the face moving left.  Sit start as for Burt Gives Blowjobs, then move left hand up to the rail.  Cross with the right hand and match the rail, set up your feet, and dyno for the lip.  Topout on jugs.

name: Todd's Big Egg
description: Start left of Burt Gives Blowjobs at the hole waist height, sit and moves right on flexing flakes to top out still shy of Burt Gives Blowjobs.   Fun moves, use it as a great warm-up for other problems in the woods.

name: Valley Jams
description: An offwidth crack - some people love this thing and others treat it like the plague.  Sit start with a toe jammed in the crack beneath the overhang and find a way to get off the ground.  If you reach back far enough there are hidden jugs, although it can be climbed either way.  Struggle upwards until you can layback on larger holds and topout.  If you're smart, you'll tape your hands or forearms.

name: Good Beer Buzz
description: Although not usually clean due to lack of traffic, this problem is better than its neighbor.  Stand start the low angle face on the right of the arete and climb straight up to a semi-highball topout.

name: Lactose
description: A great warmup or beginner problem that starts beneath the left side of the overhang.  Sit start with two good fingerslots in the crack and use a large left foot.  Pull up to a crimp or power straight up to a crystally jug.  Work straight up on good holds and then repeat.

name: Lemon Twist
description: Sit start with the small rock in between your legs. Grab the sidepull jug and undercling it with both hands. Choose your feet wisely and make a couple of hard moves straight up following the crack. Stick the good hold and finish up and right on slopers in the crack.

name: Morning Spank
description: A fun, albeit short climb that is usually worth cleaning the pine needles and spider webs off of.  Right of Smoothie and V-8, locate the short crack and arete atop the short boulders.  Wedge a pad or two on top so you don't fall through the hole.  Sit start with a left hand in the crack and right hand on the arete.  Pull up and slap up the crack until you can reach over the lip to better holds.  Topout and rejoice in the obscurity.

name: The North Face
description: Even with the 1-minute approach, this highball doesn't see much love.  Sit start as for the Welcome Crack with a sidepull and a right arete and pull up into crimps & sidepulls before standing tall on an undercling and reaching around a small roof to better holds.  Finish straight up.

name: Orange Juice
description: Another great warmup or beginner problem that starts beneath the left side of the overhang right of Lactose. Sit start with a good right-hand jug and either a left heel hook or a high right foot in the cave.  Power up to the same crystally jug as on Lactose and finish straight up.  Try not to get your fingers stuck in the start hold.

name: Slice
description: A very short beginner problem or something to warm up on.  Sit start the short ass end of the boulder before the "cave" feature, left of Lactose with good slopey holds.  Pull off the ground and reach up for the top of the boulder before topping out.  Named after a crystal on the rock that sliced open a finger or two before breaking.

name: Smoothie
description: A long, fun problem with some great beta.  This line moves left to right up the overhanging side of the boulder and links Lactose into V-8.  Sit start with hands in the small slots formed by the crack and left foot on a good block.  Move right hand to the good jug, get a kneebar, and cross left hand up to a quartz crimp.  Change the kneebar to a heelhook and slap a sloper on the lip before bumping into the crack (crux).  Another heelhook will help the transition into the better holds.  Finish up the crack.

name: Tequila Sunrise
description: An uninspiring and crumbling face.  Stand start the right end of the face by the arete and head up with large although questionable holds.

name: Utter Arete
description: A slopey traverse that nearly becomes a highball at the end.  Sit start at the base of the boulder on the right side of the face.  The holds are usually buried under pine needles and leaves.  Pull up to the arete/lip out left and move around the corner to follow the lip up and left before mantling over and finishing.

name: V-8
description: The drink, not a bouldering grade.    A tricky crack that actually climbs quite well with the right beta.  Squat start at the lip of the roof with a two handed jug in the crack.  Follow a jug and a sidepull up the crack to the crux and figure out how to stand up on the face.    A much more difficult variation starts 10-15 feet down in the lowball cave and climbs into the start.    Smoothie links Lactose into this climb as a worthy moderate.

name: Welcome Crack
description: Starts in a scooping dihedral and makes a few akward moves up, then traverse left on the crack to the jugs.  The crux is getting around the arete.  After you reach the jugs shake out, chalk up and climb up.  It's easy but high.

name: "Skink, Skank, Skunk"
description: Sit-start the large sidepull feature. Go up to a jug in the middle of the overhang before hucking for the apex and holding a massive swing. Classic.

name: Wetworks
description: Sit-start the left-side of the brittle-looking overhang facing the stream on a pair of edges. Make a few hard moves up the overhang on some thin holds, before venturing up the slab on some questionable rock.

name: General Dynamics
description: Stand start the nice overhang on a crimp rail at about shoulder height. Power up to a good incut crimp, then smack up to a good sloper rail before smacking the giant sloping shell-shape bulge. Once here, a few hard moves over a high foot gain a giant jug!

name: Private Label
description: Sit start the left-side of the overhang with a pinch on the arete and a shallow pocket for the right. Smack up to some slopers and figure out how to latch the incut crimp on the overhang. From here, slap to another left-hand pinch and figure out how to top-out.

name: Barnyard Crack
description: Though This problem in not in the guide book i don't know why... It is a great problem for just about anyone... I have used it in my warm up circut and im sure newer boulderers would love to work to send it as it is not too hard not too high and really fun...    Sit start down and left then climb the right angling crack to the top out... Though some crack skills help you can get by without...

name: Bought The Farm
description: A nice little diversion for those that have the ups.  Grab the big jug in the middle of the Barnyard Crack and set your feet.  Now fly straight up to the slopers at the lip with one, two, or three hands and hope that friction is on your side.  A fun, slopey topout awaits and might get ugly for some.

name: Classic Crack
description: Start on the right/low end of the crack on a juggy hold with a really good foot (yes a good foot at pawtuckaway, but dont get your hopes up for more)... Traverse up and left to a good but tiny crimp, the feet become miserable smears and you continue left along the seam past a very small pod or 2 in the crack that serve as sloping crimps... From here finish with a reach to the end...     I think its V2 for tall folks and a little harder for shorter types... enjoy...

name: The Cooper Problem
description: This super crimpy bulge may be a lowball, but the beta is interesting and the dynamic crux is somewhat fun.  Sit start to the left on two obvious crimps.  The right crimp is smaller now than it used to be due to breakage.  Pull off the ground and slap right into better holds, then prepare to dyno up to a good three finger crimp before finishing with a very easy topout.  Warm up your fingers before touching this one and consider using a dropknee or two.  Great for solo missions, but this problem would be far better if the first half was a bit higher off the ground.

name: Hay Fever
description: An obvious arete with a juggy start and a crux finish.  Sit start with the large jug at the base of Classic Crack.  Pull up and climb the arete directly above to reach the lip and try not to do an impersonation of a beached whale as you work up over the top.

name: Plowed
description: A quick face climb that might seem puzzling until you get your body position just right for the start.  Sit start as for Barnyard Crack at the base of the crack and make a long reach or deadpoint straight up to a good hold with your left hand.  Alternately, use the small crimps and make more moves to reach the good hold.  Match and power up to the slopey top before working right and mantling the lip.    Somewhat of an eliminate due to its proximity to the arete, but fun nonetheless.

name: Unnamed
description: A short but somewhat fun problem that starts on the same crimps as the Cooper Problem. Instead of moving right, slap left to a crimp around the bulge, work your feet up, and top out straight up and left. Awkward and powerful.

name: Unnamed  2
description: This short problem climbs the short face to the right of The Cooper Problem with a short flake.  Did I mention that it's short?  Climb the flake up to the lip and pull over the top.

name: Unnamed aka Jed's Arete
description: Looking for a quick tick? Here's a short problem with a one move crux. Sit start left of The Cooper Problem with a small right hand crimp and a bad left hand on the faint arete. Using the good left foot, pull hard and slap up to a decent slopey hold. Don't blow it and finish up the face to the top. This one used to be a little more difficult...

name: Whitewash
description: A fun, low angle arete with a massive undercling sit start.  Starting on the left side/downhill side of the arete, grab the undercling with both hands and paste your feet on the platform below.  Pull up to a left hand crimp and then the arete.  Follow crimps and good holds up the arete to a somewhat slopey topout.

name: Aroma  Therapy
description: The crux is right off the ground... Start with a left foot on a small hold then reach the arete with your right hand and get your right foot on a slopy foot hold... Keeping that right foot on will prove to be the crux... Once you stand up on the foot more moderate crimping gets you to the top out...

name: Bolt On Top
description: There is no bolt on top, but there used to be.  Highball    This spectacular slab is a classic and committing intro to the grade. Beginners, visitors and locals often swarm this climb simply due to it's quality. This may sound annoying, but their pads will save your butt if you fall. This is the classic line for the grade at Boulder Natural and Pawtuckaway.    Stand start on good crimps about 4 feet left of the big sidepull flake feature that is the start of Sandy Landing(v0)directly below a big flakey jug halfway up the wall. A few fun crimpy moves get you to the jug. Grab a good crimp, and make the crux reach to a good edge. Injuries could occur from falling off of this move. Hit the lip and mantel.  Original description: "Climb the face with ease and top out this great highball with a flat landing."

name: Conceptual Therapy
description: Sit start with a good right hand sidepull on the arete and a decent undercling for your left hand underneath the boulder. Pull on and slap left hand to the pinch above and make sustained moves on crimps up and left to the sloping lip and topout.

name: Dilemma Tree
description: Sit start with you right hand on a sidepull to the right of the arete and left hand on any of the bad holds on the left. Pull of the ground and work up the arete to an obvious gaston with difficulty. Then top out.

name: Gene Therapy
description: Start right of the Arete and work left of the arete on your way to a high topout.   Climb the Crimps to the cool topout.   Classic at the grade.    V3 called Aroma Therapy if you start left of the arete and stay left of the arete.

name: Grab The Junk
description: This is a rarely climbed line, it has decent movement but nothing to draw it any regular attention.     Sit start with right hand on a crimp rail and left hand about 8 inches higher on another good incut. Work up the face using a gaston and crimps to reach the jugs near the top.

name: Realms, Regions, and Concepts
description: Good problem. Starts on crimps with solid feet. Short move to a crimp and then continue to a slopey (and good) hold. Follow it off right and up on slopers, then top out.

name: Runaway
description: The book calls this one v5. I thought it was soft, and I know other people agree it is soft. Start with opposing side pulls. Both side pulls are good. The crux figuring out where to put your feet. The huge foot isn't a sucker. Left foot on the huge foot and right way right smeared on good texture. Position your butt right to get yourself off the ground. Throw hard up and left to a good crimp, and match it. Move your feet up and find two slopers that are set kinda far apart. Next work you way to a good crimp and pull up and over the edge. Clean the crimp off. I fell from there crimping on pine needles...

name: Sandy Landing
description: Start on crimps and crimp you way to a slopey topout.   Usually done as a warm up, or part of a traverse.   This line tops out on tricky holds with wierd feet.   Careful descending this boulder, most folks go down by the tree (involves a 5 foot jump down).

name: Splendid
description: Climb the easy face to the left of the tree, there are good feet(an obscurity to P-way) and good hands. Its fun but over quick. There is no defined crux, if I had to pick one it would be the first move establishing yourself on the boulder. This problem is fun but not a classic by any means.    A sit start would bump the grade up a bit.    Descend this climb to get down.

name: Crank
description: Sit start as for 'Reward' and make the move up to the loose pinch. Once established on the pinch traverse right on little holds following a seam to a crimp where the seam turns up. Now tackle the crux. Without following the seam any further right make a long move to the lip. Footwork and some creative beta will get you through.

name: Hitman
description: Slopers, crimps, and fun all around.  This problem heads up a slopey left leaning arete to an easier topout.  On the left side of the Illmob face (the one with spray paint), there is a notch.  This problem climbs the arete on the faintly overhanging side on the left side of the notch.  Sit start with a good sidepull jug and finesse your way up and left on slopers and make a cool move to a crimp (crux).  Stick the lip and topout.

name: Illmob
description: Nearly every problem on this boulder is fun and a great place to warm up or spend the day if you aren't beyond playing on easy-moderate problems.  This problem climbs a short arete next to the trail.  Sit start on a large sidepull with decent feet.  Pull off the ground (crux) to a good left hand sloper.  Continue up the arete a few moves to an easy topout.

name: Mob Boss
description: The hardest problem on the Illmob Boulder!  These slopers are all about friction.  Sit start at the base of the slopey arete on the left side of the slab and try as hard as you can to even get off the ground.  Once you're up, toss for the better holds up and left, then follow the slopeyness to the left until topping out at the apex.  Enjoy.    Also fun as a stand start.

name: Mob Corner
description: Sit start just right of the tree on a good edge, now mantle and work up into the easy corner straight above. The mantle is the crux of the climb.

name: Reward
description: Sit start to the right of Hitman, in the seam. Left hand on a big undercling pinch and right hand on whatever works best for you in the seam. Use the good feet, stand up to the obvious pinch above your head, take care when grabbing this hold it is very loose. Grab a little nothing with your right hand, move your feet up grab the lip and top out.

name: The Ripper
description: Slopers, non-existent footholds, and the ever present need to squeeze make this a somewhat fun if not frustrating problem that might just make your chest ache.  Stand start on the Illmob face with a good crescent sloper below the crack for your left hand and a bad sloper on the right.  Starting is reach dependent, so shorter climbers might not be able to span the holds, but using the arete is a no-no if you can actually reach that far.  Work the technical feet on micro-edges and smears, then slap up left hand to a slopey sidepull in the short dihedral.  Finish straight up.

name: Rising Tide
description: A pretty good climb that would see way more attention if it was down in the Hobbit Hole Area, however up on this boulder it is neglected.    Sit start as for Mob Corner, follow the shelf up and link into the crack, follow the crack up and around to top out. Now wasn't that more fun than you thought it would be?

name: Scarface
description: Fun holds and good moves.  Great as a warmup or a project.  Stand start as for Tragedy of Dusk with the crimp in the middle of the face.  Traverse right to an obvious groove using good feet, and make use of a large crimp and a cool, sloping hold to get your feet up and stick the juggy lip.  Topout.    Variation - V3ish.  Sit start on the Illmob Arete, traverse into Scarface.  The good feet make up for lack of hand holds.

name: Tragedy of Dusk
description: A thin, low-angle face with an interesting high-step and balancy crux.  Stand start with a high left hand crimp, and a small right hand sidepull with good feet.  Pull on, bump right hand up to a good incut crimp, then use your feet on a few little nothings until you can actually free up a hand.  Balance straight up over the bulge to good holds.  Fun moves, more technical than powerful, but rarely climbed and the crimps are a bit sharp.

name: Trigger Happy
description: Sit start on slopers and move up and right following slopers and a good sidepull on the face. Once on the slopers with your left and sidepull with your right, get your feet situated and make a hard (crux) move with your right hand to a small crimp on the arete. Once you hit the crimp bring left hand up to another small crimp and work your way to the jug up and right using a couple other small crimps.

name: A Bear and a Bug
description: Sit start laybacking the crack. make a long reach up to the arete, throw a heel up and top out there or finish by traversing the arete over to the finish of essentials.

name: Ankle Biter
description: On the Essentials boulder.  Climb the arete from a sit to the top.  The challenge is the sit start.  I'm not sure if it has a different name but we called it this after having the healhook fail a couple times.

name: Bench Warmers
description: A fun little arete climb. Not a classic, but worth doing. Stand start at the base of the juggy arete that ends the crux on Bodacious. Make your way up it for a bit and then rock over onto the slab. Beware of pine needles as you walk up the slab.

name: Bodacious
description: A sloping lip traverse.  Sit start at the lowest part of the lip with both hands matched and a heelhook right on top of them.  Slap out the lip on non-existant holds to gain a jug at the arete.  Follow the arete to the topout.    Friction dependent.   youtube.com/watch?v=KvJJL3n…

name: Boulder X
description: Start standing in the middle of the arrowhead shaped boulder on some decent incut holds, the taller they are the easier the problem is. put on a foot and grab the lip, match and get a high right foot, then prepare to roll over onto your right foot as the hands that wait for you will offer little assistance with pulling the lip. Heel hook, slap, and use precise feet to send the crux mantle of this climb! You'll scare yourself on the crux of this great line.     Make sure your spotter is paying attention. In Fall 2005 a spotter received an elbow to the head on this climb and got a cracked skull and had to be transported out by the forest service/fish and game.

name: Boulder X Slab
description: Climb strait up the middle of the slab on marginal holds to the top. Using the left arete bumps the grade down a bit. Climb strait up the middle to stay true to the grade.

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: This is a really fun climb that doesn't get much attention.  This is due to the climb being located in an area I've never seen dry. If the marsh is frozen or it has been a really dry season then you shouldn't pass up the opportunity to climb this.    Start on obvious holds down to the right with good feet and work your way left.  Wrap around the arete and top out.

name: Essentials
description: Slab climbing that is Classic! Graham O adds: A classic slab climb that may be short, but involves cool holds, cool movement, and perfect rock. A must-do for anyone who likes slabs!     Start with high foot, balance up and find the rounded pocket, do a cool hand-foot match and top out on the jug.

name: Groovey
description: Climb the v groove left of the Boulder X Slab, if you use either arete it will be this grade if you try to do it using only features inside the groove it will be closer to v2.    The crux is right off the ground, climb up using small edges and decent feet. Descend off the backside of the boulder.

name: Headz Ain't Ready
description: I hate G-speak in the backwoods, but here it is.  If you do Boulder X but find yourself wishing there was more to it, have a look at the left arete.  From a low start on two good holds, slap and bump your way up the crimps on the face and slopers on the arete.  Fly out to the big key handhold on the lip with the right hand.  Then switch hands and get set on the mantle.  There is a foothold below the lip that can help with the mantle if you're silly pumped already, but there is no easy way to take the sting out of this move.  The mantle must be one of the very best single moves in the park.

name: The Impaler
description: This is a mostly ignored boulder problem due to the old sharp stump that used to be right in the fall zone. That stump has since been removed and this line deserves another chance.    Stand start by establishing yourself in the large undercling. Crimp and technique your way up to the slopers at the lip, figure out how to conquer them and a jug awaits you at the very top.    Due to years of neglect this boulder still has some loose rock on it and the top could use a bit of a scrubbing, but get out at climb it!

name: Know Hands
description: This is a great beginner climb as it makes you focus on your feet, however it won't pose much of a challenge for most.  Climb up the easy slab and pull onto the top.  Yep, that's it.  Now do it in sneakers without using your hands, and then do it barefoot while juggling chainsaws.

name: Piece o' Cake
description: This slab climb is similar to Know Hands as it can probably be done with no hands. Start with good feet in the middle of the slab and work up to the high point. If you choose to use hands there are plenty of good edges for you to choose from.

name: Poppers
description: Awesome one move wonder.   Start sitting and do an akward move to gain the arete and v-easy climbing to the topout.   Very worthwhile if you can find it.

name: Slot Machine
description: A sweet problem requiring some serious precision.    Start standing with right hand on the obvious chalked pinch/crimp and left hand on one of several options. The old left start hold broke, leaving a poor undercling hold. Figure out some foot trickery to enable you to pull off the ground and stand up left hand into the slot (crux). Match the slot and make a big move up and right to a juggy gaston on the lip, match and top out.

name: Super Smash Brothers
description: A great line with an amazing starting sequence!    Stand start with a sharp right undercling and left hand on the arête, foothold is just below left arête. Committing reach with left hand to slopey corner of arête. Dyno / deadpoint to small hold with right hand. Left foot pushes off of flake to help with the crux: matching on the small hold. Right hand shoots out to sharp flake on the right side of the face, and a final bump to a great jug finishes the route.    Once gaining the small hold with the right hand, there are many ways to get to the final jug. Matching on the small hold and bumping to the jug, climbing the left arête and crossing over, or a combination of both are all possible, making the last half of the route open to interpretation and beta-dependent.

name: Swamp butt
description: The start is the crux followed by easy climbing. Sit start with under arete with right hand on jug and left on the sloping edge. Move up on top of large flake and  than climb up the easy arete.

name: Tony's Problem
description: This line is overlooked due to it proximity to the classic, Boulder X. However it really should get a few more ascents.    Sit start on the thin crimp rail with your right and a lower left hand side pull crimp, make crux moves up to a decent left hand side pull. Work you feet around and make a intermediate move or two before hitting the good edge, a couple casual moves leads to the top out.

name: Touchdown Giants
description: Stand start on small crimps make a long move to the good horizontal crack that splits the face. From here make fun and enjoyable moves to the next horizontal crack just before the top. top out on easy ground.

name: Unknown slab left
description: Climb up the slab starting between the two trees to the highest point of the boulder.

name: Unknown slab right
description: Easy but fun little slab climb.

name: Anorexorcist
description: A fun, short power problem that climbs a bottomless block.  Sit start with both hands matched on a sloping jug rail on the bottom right corner.  Heel hook next to your hands to pull on and dangle before making a move out to the edges, bump left hand again, then match.  Rock up on the heel and around the arete to a crimp (crux) or the lip if you're long.    This problem is at 1:48  youtube.com/watch?v=i27SMGh…

name: Bones to Bits
description: One of the very best boulder problems at Pawtuckaway.  Don't climb too far unless you're sure of what you're doing.  A funky layback/kneebar keeps the"riff raff" away at the bottom.  A classic squeeze chimney follows which then pinches off at the top.  You must then leave the security of the chimney for the crux - a surprisingly awkward scrunch move makes the transition to the mossy slab above.  You really wouldn't want to pop off here.  Relish the summit (like being on the roof of a house!), then consider the options of getting down, possibly via the epic downclimb of a fat chimney on the opposite side.

name: Bulemia
description: A hard power problem that actually involves some technique. Hang start on the good rail as for "Anorexorcist". Bend your knees and extend your arms, your legs should be under the small roof. In one fluent motion, bring your legs and knees up towards your chest while doing a pull up and make a big campus move up and right to a jug on the arete. From here match and move up the arete and topout.    A fun sneaker problem, and good power training.

name: Confident Man
description: This is the very thin line of crimps up the overhanging wall to the left of Halcyon. Start with a sidepull and a very small right handhold and make an exceedingly hard move to a decent edge. Continue with interesting, difficult moves on decent edges to the lip, then top out and follow Halcyon up the slab to the top of the boulder. The crux is the first move, but the rest is no gimme.

name: Flakes of Life
description: Sit start next to Rio’s problem and make a few hard moves to a juggy flake system and mossy top out.

name: Halcyon
description: One of the proudest lines in the park. Start sitting on an obvious good undercling, then work up to a desperate move way left to a sloping, friction-dependent gaston. Stick this, then make a couple difficult moves on slopers (a couple ways to do this section, possibly with a kneebar) to the lip. Top out, then traverse left on crispy rock and continue up the slab to the top of the boulder.

name: Jaded
description: Located on the same boulder as Stegosaurus, this problem climbs the left underside arete from a sit.

name: The Morgue
description: Climb the grove through lots of little crimps and pockets. This is really tall and there is also a tree right at the bottom too. Very commiting. The Crux is at the bottom and it gets easy the higher you go.

name: My Little Pony
description: An overhanging power problem with a highball slab topout.  Sit start with the large flake (same start as Halcyon) and make two moves into the last of the good holds.  Make a large move with your R hand to a small crimp (crux) and drop into a better hold with your L.  Toss R to the lip, campus a few moves to the right, then pull a committing move to stand up on the slab.  Work your way straight up.

name: Outback
description: A cool climb, and a great little warm up.   Might actually be the best low grade problem of B. Natty.    Great unique holds that aren't sharp.     Sit start with the left arete for the left hand and a slopey sidepull rail for the right.   Choose from an array of feet, and make moves up and right via good holds.    A reach up gets you to the friendly juggy top.     A slightly harder variation starts with right hand on the right arete, and the left hand on the left arete.    Another variation involves left hand on a sloper under the small over hang, and the right hand on the arete.   Throw on a right heel and pull on with difficulty and make moves up and eventually to good holds. Grading is unknown.

name: Rio's Problem
description: Start with a good undercling for your left hand and a big slopey gaston a little lower with your right hand. Make a move with your right hand to a sharp sidepull/crimp strait above you. Next come up to another slopey sidepull/pinch with your left. Work your feet up and make a move to an edge, match, then on to easier finishing moves.

name: Stegasaurus
description: Although it doesn't look like much, this short problem climbs great and is usually dry.  Sit start on the left arete with your left hand on the arete, and right hand on a crimp.  Pull up and bump out right to the vertical pinch/crimp, work your feet and make a hard match.  A strong core, the right foot beta, and use of the thumb catch might make the move feel more realistic. Move right to a slopey rail as a gaston.  Use some technique to match the rail and move right to a crimp, before bumping up again with the right hand to a better crimp.  Use the sidepull with your left hand to assist in reaching the jugs above.  Alternately, from the rail, power up and left into the sidepull/undercling and fire out right for a better hold and the top.    The landing can be a bit muddy although the sticks will keep your pad rather clean.

name: Blaow
description: Start high on two crimps above head height (they are bad!!) Deadpoint all points off to jug up and left. It looks possible, but it isn't.    For a V5 boulderer I have decent crimp strenght. I can support my body weight on these crimps and pull up with feet on, but man i can't imagine what kind of training it would take for me to feel confident dyno-ing off these crimps.

name: Blaow's Cousin
description: A cool variation on a crimp testpiece. Start as for Blaow on two small crimps. Find your feet and instead of dynoing to the jug straight up, cross up and right to the cool sidepull pinch. Fire up and right to some better crimps then top 'er out.     A sweet jump start variation goes to this at about v7. Start holding the right starting crimp, find out which foot you want to keep on the ground, then jump and catch the sidepull pinch with your left hand. Finish up the same way.

name: Brett's Mom
description: Sit start on a good hold in the crack just right of the tree (same as for Glass Blower (aka Pygmies & Cornrolls)). Move up to a smiley face edge. A big move to a sloping rail over the lip, move right and up for the tough mantle (find a crimp for success!). Dynamic, delicate, fun!

name: Downward Spiral
description: The extended start to Ride the Lightning.  Squat/sit start with two holds in the crack and a good right foot.  Make a big move left to grab a sloper, drop right hand into the left start hold, then work your feet left.  Match the sloper (crux) and move to a jug or an undercling before grabbing the holds of RTL.  Finish on RTL.    The moves can be fun, unfortunately, the problem is wet most of the time.  It is rare to find it in climbable condition.

name: Evolution
description: Pull on from small crimps at about 6' high, both of which are from a small flake.  There is a small rail for both of your feet.  Make a big fun move to the right onto another small crimp at the top of a flake.  Work your way up that flake and reset your feet on the face below you.  Throw really big again to the right, aiming for a sloper.  Matel onto the less steep terrain (crux) and climb the easy slab topout.    There is a sit start which I was told is V11, it's all yours.

name: Flying V
description: Start matched on the obvious v-shaped crimp, try to find feet (which will likely pop anyways) and then pull a couple of hard moves up crimps before topping out.

name: Four Eyed Blues
description: Sit start to the right of Mr. Natural on small crimps or slopers on the arete. Pull on and make a few tedious moves to reach a mega jug and top out on the slab with confidence.

name: Further Down The Spiral
description: The extended sit start to The Three Graces.  Essentially this is Downward Spiral with the alternate ending.  Start as for Downward Spiral in the grove of trees with two holds in the crack and bust left to the perpetually wet sloper.  Continue left into the start of The Three Graces and finish it up.  As with Downward Spiral, if it's dry, climb it because it might be your only chance!

name: Glass Blower (aka Pygmies & Cornrolls)
description: Although wet most of the time, when dry, this crack traverse/dyno problem is great.  Sit start on a jug in the crack just right of the tree.  Follow the overhanging crack to the right with good feet.  Just past the tree, slot your L hand into a vertical crack, grab a bad crimp on the R face, and dyno R hand to the lip (crux).  Once you match the lip, you can work out a thrilling topout.    keith climbing Glass Blower 2013  youtube.com/watch?v=MIGV_eI…

name: Indiana jones
description: A one move wonder, start on a circular crimp and a low side pull. Pull on and jump to a jug then top out on jugs strait up.  If you try it, try it with lots of skin.

name: Innovator
description: This tricky arete is either super crimpy or powerful depending on your beta.  Either way, sit start with a good knob/jug for your left hand and your right on a small crimp.  Pull off the ground and get your right foot up below your right hand before dropping into a sidepull/undercling crimp.  Now you can either throw for a good rail or bump up slopers/crimps to get there slower.  Once you get your foot up on the starting jug, the climbing gets easy.  Finish up the arete to the top.

name: Monkey Crotch
description: For this one move wonder start left in a small seam and right on sloper both on the apex of the feature. Smear your foot out left and pull/slap up to the top.

name: Monkey Press
description: This mantle problem can be downright embarrasing seeing as how it's only 4 feet off the ground but more difficult than the topout of Ride the Lightning.  Sit start on large jugs at the lip of the roof and you'll notice there aren't any feet.  Swing a heel out left, then use a very thin crimp up and left to press it out and standup.  This can be fun to watch, but pray nobody is looking if you get spanked.

name: Mothra Stewart
description: Start on a hollow sidepull flake. Reach up to an undercling crimp in the roof above your head, a jug, a long move, and a hard bump get you to the key hold. Tension and good footwork get you to the jugs. Keep calm because the jugs get smaller at the top.

name: Mothra Stewart Left
description: A fun variation to a classic climb. Start as for Mothra Stewart but once you make the long reach and the hard match keep moving left for another move or two and make a huge iron cross to a far jug (crux) from there continue straight up the face on some smaller holds and topout high off the deck.

name: Mothra Stewart Variation
description: Left of the Mothra Stewart start is another super hollow flake that feels like it'll rip out.   The sit start starts here. Otherwise, I started out with my left hand here and my right hand up on a good sidepull. Crank up to a crumbly crimp and make your way right into Mothra Stewart and finish on the climb.    This guy is less reach dependent than the original and therefore more shorty friendly. If you're not tall enough to ride Mothra Stewart, check out the variation and have your ogre sized buddies do the original.

name: Mr. Natural
description: Sit-start on a thin crescent-shaped flake.  Move up thru decent edges and bulbs on the steep wall with keen footwork to a series of sharp diagonal crimps.  As the chalk disappears and the holds get worse, find your way to the top with inconspicuously small edges on the steep slab.

name: Pikachu
description: A fun problem that be climbed with long power moves or with short beta intensive trickery.     Start on a neat sloper/knob thing poking out of the rock that has a good ridge in it and a sloper to the right of this. Follow the lip to the left by slapping along slopers and some good crimps until you reach the little peak of the lip. From here, find the holds you wanna use and pull a tough mantle. Run up to the top.    Here's a video of the problem:  youtube.com/watch?v=Ov58IrL…

name: Polish Terrorist
description: Sit start of Terrorist.     Edited to Add 9-12-07. Thank you Tristan Perry.   The start is extreme lowball (scary, you're almost lying down) and it's really hard to pull off the ground, let alone get on with the rest of the problem. That is by far the hardest move on the entire problem. Small but positive crimps follow up and right to the rest of the Terrorist to gain the starting stance for Terrorist.

name: Revolution
description: A one move wonder.  Sit start with a crimp/gaston for your left hand and a small but good flake for your right.  The feet are decent, but once you pull off the ground, dyno with every bit of energy you can find (steal it from other people if you need to) and latch a crimp somewhere around 7' up.  Using another crimp and a jug up and left, topout through the groove.

name: Ride the Lightning
description: A classic and committing intro to the grade. Squat start with an obvious jug (flexes so pull down) and a right foot way out right and pop up to the crack with your right hand. Bring your left hand up and match in the crack. Step up to the starting jug and cross right hand to next crimp (bad). Left hand to bad undercling, then move feet, bump left hand to crimp below topout, move up feet into the crack and grab those slopers. Moving from the crack to the crimps and then the lip is the short crux.  Get a heel and mantle for all you're worth.  Make sure you climb up the back side to brush off pine needles. Not to be missed.

name: Squeeze Play
description: Start squatting to the right of the tree, squeeze through and move left.

name: Storm Pockets
description: Stand start on jug at above head height. Put on feet high on nubbins, deadpoint/dyno to next jugs up, Traverse right on delicate holds and pull over.   Note: The previous 3rd jug/rail to the left of the white spot on the face has blown off and the climb cannot be completed as previously described.  This problem will scare you with its height and the level of commitment required at first but it becomes mentally easier the more pads you have!

name: Storm Traverse
description: A cool sloper traverse that scales the appealing sloping arete from the very right side of the Mothra Stewart headwall all the way to the Storm Pockets topout. A fun problem that shares the crux with it's classic neighbor (storm pockets), which will feel even harder after all the pump. A good problem worth doing if you like this sort of thing.

name: Terrorist
description: Stand start with the obvious sloper ball in your right hand and a left hand on one of the low crimps.  Paste a foot in the corner and pull up to the sloping seam.  Rock up until you get a left foot on the starting crimp and stay balanced enough to free up a hand to crimp the higher seam.  Technique your way up the slab and topout on jugs.  More technical than powerful, but classic either way.

name: Terrorist Left
description: The left version of Terrorist. Although they share the same name, this climbs like an independent line. If you like Terrorist, you'll like this line too. Another bit of Pawtuckaway trickery.     Start on the chalked jug left of Terrorist that Squeeze Play starts on and head straight up. There's an obvious good spot on the arete/lip. Get your feet up, and from here figure out how the heck you're going to get onto the slab (crux).

name: Tessa
description: This route goes left off of the start holds of Mr. Natural. Start in the flake, reach left and then fire right to the gaston crimp. Proceed to traverse up and left into Warrior.Go hard and exit the slab to the right, or exit straight up to the jug (depends on how strong you’re feeling

name: The Three Graces
description: This is the obscure and slightly more difficult right variation of Ride the Lightning.  Start as for Ride the Lightning and get both hands up to the crack.  Rather than move left along the crack, undercling the top of it and bust straight up to a tiny crimp below the lip with your right hand.  Snag the lip and move left to pull the mantle.

name: The unknown v10
description: I can’t believe this hasn’t been added yet!! Don’t know the real name, but always tell peeps it’s “the unknown v10” This problem is the blunt Arête left of Revolution. Start on the left hand rail crimp either matched or with your right hand on the little ear under the face. The 3 start feet are very bad but more feet present themselves as you traverse into the top of Revolution.  I feel it’s v10 to the Revolution top out but if you want to seal  the deal complete the v6 top out and climb the whole Arête.

name: Up
description: Start on two underclings, then dyno to a jug. Trend right a little and finish on Storm Pockets.

name: Vintage
description: Fun moves on big edges and pinches take you through some dikey and potentially loose rock to the top of this blunt arete. Height and jumbled landing conspire to warrant a highball designation.

name: Warrior
description: This is the impressive right-diagonalling finger crack that splits the face between two arete problems. Good locks once you find them, though the crack is often wet.    "Graham O" feel that "This classic problem is a test of crack climbing and mental fortitude. Though obvious, aesthetic, and appealing, few decide to attempt it after seeing the landing. Those who decide to try it will be rewarded, as it is very unique for Pway and gives a New England climber a taste of the Buttermilks."

name: The Wizard
description: This is a never-done crimp problem that tackles the blunt prow directly below the topout of 'Pygmies and Cornrolls'. It's incredibly sharp and I highly recommend avoiding it unless you are desperate for a tick and even then I feel that you should think about it.    Sit start on a good RH sidepull and bad LH crimp. Bump your right to a sharp crimp, and decide how much you want the send. Do you want it so bad that you would be willing to lose enough skin/blood that you would be out for the day? If so, than continue onward! Jump for a good crimp, and keep an eye on your fingers as they start to throb and bleed. It'll feel like crimping a katana. Hit the slopey crack before jumping to the lip. Topout same as Pygmies and Cornrolls, and curse yourself for ever attempting this god-forsaken pile o' pain.

name: Woodfords Reserve
description: Sit start on a decent left hand crimp and a tiny right hand crimp pick some feet and make the crux move into a gaston up and right. From here, make a strenous move up to the jug below the lip. Hit the lip and top out.

name: Zap
description: Sit start, move up short overhanging face on sharp crimps to strange scooping topout directly above start.   Try this one with fresh fingers and watch them as they start to bleed.

name: Zap Left
description: Start on horn to the left of Zap sitting on a rock. Move right on crimps into Zap and finish the same. Fun line with a hard cross off the start and a nice feeling gaston on the first good crimp of Zap.

name: Cup of Tea
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Down In It
description: Sit start in the hole with large feet, right hand on a large side pull and left on a crimp. Climb up and left on jugs to the aerie then top out.

name: Downward Dog
description: This line goes straight up the big face next to Provia via good crimps. Grab the juggy lip and mantle. Definitely worth doing.

name: Due North
description: Start standing in the center of the tall slab, with the left hand on a gaston crimp and the right wherever. Head straight up the slab utilizing a shallow dish/pocket and good footwork to reach the juggy rail below the lip. Follow the rail up and left, topping out at the apex of the boulder.    I'm sure this climb has been done before. I feel like's it a purer and better option than 'North Slab', which is located to the left. And while it may be taller, the landing zone is much better.     Note that this problem can only be climbed when the stream bed is dry enough.

name: E-Z Cheese
description: The classic line at the grade in Boulder Natural. Stand start on a huge jug, set your feet and fire up and left to the cool triangular pinch. Grab a right crimp and bump to the jug on the lip up and right. Topout next to the tree.   Landing is a bit painful so don't botch the dyno/deadpoint/topout.    Sit start goes at V3.    If you used the gaston on the left, see Swiss Cheese

name: Feel The Pull
description: Sit down in the small corridor with your hands in the wide crack.  Climb the right arete formed by the crack up to better holds before making a big move to the top arete.  Commit to a spooky topout over a boulder and try not to blow it.

name: Fritz's Demise
description: This is one of my all time favorite routes. Start to the left of E-Z Cheese, traverse into the chimney created by the two boulders using the jugs on the left side of the chimney. The ground gets lower as you move out then becomes a hole straight through the boulders, if you get scared remember the boulder behind you and you can get a no-hands knee bar between the two boulders at any point on the traverse. Finnish at the end of the chimney where you come out on the other side of the stream by Bulletproof.

name: King Arthur
description: Despite it's scruffy appearance, all the necessary holds are clean and it's more fun than it looks.  Stand start to the right of the arete with a left hand on the arete and your right on a bad crimp.  Pull up and pop to the sloper (or use an intermediate crimp) before pressing it out to finish up.  Maybe a little sandbagged.

name: Kissing Cousins
description: A quick beginner problem.  Stand start and pull on to the low angle face to the right of the arete and climb straight up on good holds.

name: North Slab
description: A short slab climb that is also kind of spooky.  Starting right of the tree on a rock platform above the stream, step onto the wall using the good foothold.  Notice the lack of holds.  Smear straight up for a couple of moves until you can reach the good holds (the only holds), then make easier moves to the top.

name: Provia
description: While most people simply walk past this slightly overhanging arete, it deserves more love than it gets.  The movement is fun, the foot beta has a techy nature to it, and there are numerous ways to unlock the sequence.  Sit start with your right hand pinching the arete with the help of a good thumbcatch.  For your left hand you can either use the bad sloper or the small razor blade.  Pull off the ground and stand up into the left hand undercling.  Slap up the arete, work your feet, and then choose your adventure...    Method 1 - Dyno to a crimp a few inches below the lip and then topout on jugs.    Method 2 - Stick a small sloper with your left hand and bump your right up to the good rail.  Topout on jugs.    Method 3 - Stay tight and move your left hand into a tiny sidepull, then bump your right to the good rail.  Topout on jugs.    Maybe it's the rock sticking out of the ground that annoys people.  It's actually not in the way.

name: The Riverbed
description: Rising above the stream, this obvious shallow dihedral and the crux sit start is unfortunately only climbable when the water level is low.  When this is climbable, climb it!  Sit start in the streambed below the dihedral with some interesting pockets and power up to a sloper.  Make a few more moves to get yourself into the corner and follow the better holds straight to the top.

name: Seinfeld
description: A nice little face climb with the crux coming at the top.  Sit start a few feet left of the arete with a good rail.  Pull up right either to the arete or the large crimp.  Match the crimp then go left to a small crimp and either hit a sloper on the arete or the lip before topping out.

name: Steezy Cheese
description: Stand start on the good holds used for "E-Z Cheese" and "Swiss Cheese". Find a good foot and dyno up and left to the lip of the boulder before topping out. Pretty big move, but rocking onto the foot gets you there.

name: Swiss Cheese
description: This is the problem a lot of people send when they think they're doing EZ Cheese. It starts the same as  the classic cheese on the awesome jug, but immediately moves left into the gaston before moving to the lip and topping out. A little bit easier, a little less classic.

name: Bar of Soap
description: Sit-start with a right hand sidepull and a slippery slopey edge for the left. Pull on and fire up to a sloping rail, then go for the lip and topout. A squeezed line that is challenging and fun.

name: Battle Of The Bulge
description: Start standing with both hands matched on a slopey shelf/ledge. Make a hard pull left to a diagonal crimp rail/sidepull. Then move right and up via a small crimp and a few good, but hollow flakes to a tricky move to the lip.     A very good climb, with fun and engaging movement. Move delicately on the flakes!    There is a sit start to this problem. While it is a little bit harder, it  takes away from the quality of the line and is not really worth doing.

name: Bog of Eternal Stench
