description: Tall and Proud! At about 30 feet this is one of the tallest faces in The Swamp and all of Boulder Natural. Stand start with a jug and follow the dihedral up until making a crux move at about the 20 foot mark and continue up to small but positive crimps and top it out.      More of a mental battle than a physical. Realistically not harder than V2 but I suggest being comfortable climbing at least V5 before trying this. The landing is flat but a fall from the top could have consequences. Have fun be smart and be safe.

name: Chasm Crack
description: Climb the gorgeous fingercrack from a sit start. The crux comes down low, the second and third move. From the start on a left hand pinch and a finger jam/sidepull, pull hard with a drop knee to a two knuckle ring lock or wierd finger jam. Hang off this for a few painful seconds and slowly cross to another two finger jam higher up. Don't let it pop, and slap to a decent jug sloper deep in the crack. This move isn't too hard, and once you do it, you are in. Cross to the lie back jug and top out on a slightly technical face.

name: The Chasm
description: Start about 10 feet left of Chasm Crack on two low slopers. There is a little crimp on the arete for you to use. Make a couple moves up the arete and figure out how to get into the finish of Chasm Crack

name: Dauber
description: Sit start on a diagonal crimp rail with a few options for feet. Pull on and bust a hard deadpoint right hand up to a good two-finger crimp. Once you snag this, figure out how to reach the slopey-lip and then mantle over with slight difficulty.

name: Dookie Dyno
description: A hard crimp line that ends with a big dyno.     Stand start matched on a small crimp, with your right foot out right on a few options for feet. Make a hard and committing pull off of the ground and fire right hand up and right to another small crimp. Get your left foot on and pull harder than you want to to dyno/deadpoint your left hand up to the lip. Hold the swing, match and top out.

name: Enthusiasm
description: Start as for "Sar-Chasm", do the same first move out left to a large meathook. Flip the righthand into an undercling above the starting hold before getting a left heelhook out left on a glassy rail. From here deadpoint off the heel to a glassy lefthand sidepull Once here execute some extremely difficult foot moves up onto the start. Stay tight in the scoop feature and make a very strenuous and friction dependent move up to a bad sloper.  If you come out of the box in this position you will lose the friction and spin-off the boulder, stepping or kicking the slab directly behind will prevent an awkward fall, but could potentially result in a bruised heel(this happened to me on my first session).  Once this sloper is latched properly with the righthand, match and set the left foot in order to make another long tenuous and precarious lock-off out left to a large juggy sidepull in the upper part of the crack. Stay tight and fight another barndoor to match before reaching up righthand to a large pocket. Once on this pocket get a high foot and lock-off all the way up and left to a large jug and the lip of the tall boulder.  This problem is slightly contrived because an easier exit out left exists(Sar-Chasm), but personally this problem, although very difficult, flows naturally and very well and also incorporates a lot of full-body tension and the constant fear of greasing-off of smooth and friction dependent holds similar to "Stegasaurus" and "Lady Slipper".  Sorry for the beta spray down, but the specific line of travel could be confusing otherwise. Climbing the first half of "Sar-Chasm" then heading back right to the sloper for the big lock-off to the crack while avoiding the intro of glassy sidepulls, underclings and heelhooks is not the same problem. That is more of a variation to Sar-chasm that does not flow well but ends with the same sloper lock-off. (This is the only way this problem has been repeated so far, which technically is not a repeat for the second ascent.)

name: Eternal Love
description: This is a fun slab climb that is a little more challenging.

name: Fact and Fancy
description: Sit-start matched under the roof with an undercling slot and a super low foot. Bicep your way up the first move to a large rail. Match the rail and then accomplish a big-move up to a crimp at the lip of the boulder. From here, figure out how to topout.

name: The Gloryhole
description: Sit start on a left hand sloper rail and a right hand crimp. Pull on and throw out left to the three finger pocket. Bring the right hand in to the left hand sloper, then go to a left-hand sidepull jug. From here hit the lip right hand and grab a juicy pinch. Figure out how to top it out from here! Cool movement and unique holds!

name: Golden Hind
description: Once you imagine there are actually holds, stand start the center of the slab and climb straight up. tricky and delicate climbing, good luck!

name: Jungle Fever
description: A worthy and fun boulder problem.  Start out with matching slopers far right along the shelf.  Interesting footwork, including a bomber heel hook allow you to rock up to the next sloper.  Find the following sequence(s) using clean in-cut  crimps camouflaged within the green moss.  High feet get you to the lip at the right hand section of slab.

name: Kindly Kiting
description: A fun addition to the unique climbs in the swamp! While climbing this problem, you are opposing a barn door for most of the problem! Sound fun?    Sit start on two sidepull underclings and make a move up to a good sidepull crimp rail, rearrange your feet and get a far left foot and continue up the scoop. Fun to figure out!

name: Lapras
description: Sit start with the right hand on the arete and left hand Gaston on a slopey feature. Pull on using a jug foot and make a hard smack up to a sloper higher on the arete. Continue out to a jug and get on its back!

name: Lost At Sea
description: This fun climb requires a bit of power for the start and good technique/footwork thereafter.    Start sitting at the base of the hanging slab with your right hand on a good pinch on the arete (at about 3 feet) and your left hand on a low sidepull (at about 2 feet). Pull off the ground somewhat awkwardly and proceed directly up the slab using the arete out right and the hanging arete feature out left. A hidden undercling out left may be helpful for the starting moves.    Decipher a couple slab moves (a little harder for short folk) and top out using the juggy lip.    This can also be done from a stand start (v1+).

name: Mart Fart!
description: Smack!    Sit start with your right hand on a few choices of crimps, a bad right heel hook, and an obvious left hand crimp. Pull up and make a tough slap to the lip, match, grunt and top out.    Here's a vidayo of the climb:  youtube.com/watch?v=3wxexuv…

name: McCaber's Direct
description: Sit start in somewhat of a hole with a right hand side pull undercling and the left hand high on a crimp rail.  Pull on and set up to make a big move up to the shelf. Match hands and mantel the shelf. Once established on the shelf, get a high right hand press and a left hand smear with i high left foot. Trust it and get up top. Mental crux top out with a sketchy landing. Classic Kyle.

name: Methods of Escape
description: Start with right hand on triangle hold near the tree (same start hold of Slow Vibration) left hand on the rail. I use the the big shelf for feet and then traverse up and left via sloper pods and crimps. Grab small edge over lip and side pull out left to rock over onto the slab and top out.

name: Mist of Paradise
description: A superb slab climb with fun moves.

name: Most Mystic Moods
description: A new age hard and powerful classic that climbs a roof's slopey lip into an arete on friction dependent holds with a rad end sequence on excellent rock.Sit start matched with both hands on a slopey rib-like pinch on the lip of the roof, campus on or find a foothold to use. Move rightwards on slopers before spanning out to a crimp on the other side of the arete. A foot sequence is then followed by a huge cross in order to gain a dish-like crimp on the arete. Once on the lefthand crimp found on the arete, figure out how to make it out to the large blocky feature to the right. Once this large hold is in-hand, a few more hard moves gain the slopey top out!Truly a great problem that will see some traffic in the near future. Although the boulder problem can be a bit dabby in one section, there is a beta sequence that works well to avoid it.Click Here to see the video that features this climb.

name: Mouthful of Chalk
description: Start on the obvious diagonal rail at chest height. Make a big move up and right to a small gaston crimp. From here hard heel hooking and hidden holds will take you to the slopey lip. A jug up and right of the lip makes the top out easy.     The name is because Ethan Chase bit open a chalk ball to put on a stick so we could clean the top.

name: Mudblood
description: This climbs the little roof on the front of the Chasm boulder. Sit start beneath the roof with a mediocre right hand pinch and a couple choices for the left. Pull off the ground and pop to a crimp on the lip of the roof, match, then go again to the top. Topping out is easy.

name: Mystic Moods
description: Sit or squat start with a crimp/ pinch-like dish on the arete for the left hand and a crack gaston or pinch on the large block feature to the right. Find some feet to pull on to and figure out how to reach the large jug on top of the block feature. Once here continue up the arete and execute a huge lock-off to a sloper at the lip and continue to finish up slopers to top out. The feet are superb, so the top out isn't too bad.

name: The Nile
description: A decent little arete climb. Sit start with the right hand on the arete and left hand on a crimp. Pull on and hit the lip lefty. Ride it out left to a pyramid pinch and rock over to top out.

name: The Number
description: A hard technical problem with a crux topout on a blank slab. Sit start with a right hand sloper and a small lefthand pinch. Pull on backflagging and square up for the first move to a right hand sloper sidepull. From here bump the lefthand out to a bad seam and compress. Move your feet and go to an arete like feature with the right hand. Find your feet and stand up to increasingly worse holds. Get your feet up on the slab and balance your way up! Testpiece of the area!

name: Ore Chasm
description: Sit start the laser-cut arete with the right hand on a low pinch on the arete, and the left hand just left on a sidepull crimp. Pull on and smack up to the smooth feature on the arete. Continue up the arete with a few low left hand sidepulls and slopey right hand pinches with some incredible tension. The crux is the last move, and it is a bit scary. Once the flat lip is reached, there is a mega bucket out left.

name: Point of No Return
description: A beautiful and aesthetically pleasing left leaning arete. Sit start on top of a small boulder with a huge left hand flake and a right hand on the arete. Find the good foot options, and bump up the arete to a good thumb catch. From here execute the crux move going to a left hand crimp. From here keep it together and continue up the arete with good holds and good foot options. After matching the arete falling should not be considered an option, because the is a tall rock slab that you would land on and slide down.    Once near the point of the arete rock over the slab and grab a fin of jugs at the apex of the boulder. The mental crux is about 3 feet down from the apex, with a spicy move to a good, but thin hold on the arete. I crossed right hand to it and tried matching feet on the low crimp and cut feet. If you cut feet, take it, or you could be landing on your face.     This climb is an absolute classic and should be on everyone's list if you enjoy blood pumping highballs!

name: Poseidon
description: Start sitting on the awkward pointy rock at the base with your left hand on the arete and your right hand on a crimp sidepull and a good low foot. Use fancy footwork to bump the left hand up the arete and to gain an incut crimp with the right hand. All of this leads to a committing deadpoint/dyno to the flat lip. A few more moves lead to a rock over mantle typical of most of the problems on this side of the boulder.    Great rock, fantastic movement and a cool finish make this problem full value!    While the pointy rock is awkward and potentially dangerous, it's not really an issue for any move except latching the incut crimp with the right hand. Still, be safe!

name: Puddle Jumper
description: A really fun dynamic problem. Sit start with two small crimps and throw for the lip. Short and sweet. Logs can be used to fill in the puddle.

name: Pyramid Crack
description: An okay, short crack climb. Sit start and follow the crack up and slightly left.

name: Pyramid Poison
description: Grab a thin right hand crimp and a high left hand crimp. Find a foot and stand up to a jug. Slab your way up the rest.

name: Rolling Under
description: A fun warm up. Grab a right hand sloper sidepull and a good left hand crimp and power up to the lip and top out.

name: Sar-Chasm
description: A right sit start to the Chasm Crack that avoids the crux of the crack and adds it's own. Sit start 6' right of the crack on a slopey shelf. Make a big move up and left to a pinch, match next to it on a crimp, then make another big move to the jug in the crack. Finish up Chasm.

name: Shadow of the Colossus
description: This was formerly the "Cave Project".  All the hand hold are decent, but the feet and body position are strange.  Start at the bottom right of the face on a sharp, but good crimp rail.  Paste your feet and surf out left to a slopey rail.  Heel hook your hand and compress into a slopey, right-facing rail with your right hand.  Slap your left foot up and do a pretty hard move up and right to another decent sloping rail.  Do some magic footwork to get your right foot up on a incut foot.  Then surf out left to a mediocre undercling.  Walk your feet through, and set up for the crux.  Get a drop knee on a big slopey rail and a HORRIBLE smear with the left.  Twist your face into the wall and do a huge cross to precarious looking undercling pinch flake.  While it looks scary, its solid.  If you get here, paste your feet on some eh feet, and stand up really high to grab a hard-to-see edge with your left hand.  Then, move out right to a horn feature to top out.  Hard if you're short, slightly less heinous if you're tall like me (I'm 6 foot 1).

name: Slow Vibration
description: Fun and powerful! Sit start matched on the triangle hold in front of the tree with a good left foot and your choice of small right feet. Fire up right to the obvious edge, or move to a sidepull to work your feet first. Match the edge and stand up to grab the sloping lip before mantling over.

name: Stemmed Possibilities
description: Stand start with small incut crimp for the left hand and a right hand undercling. Get a high right toe and pull on with difficulty. As you pull on, the left toe naturally kicks up off the ground and hits the roof. Getting established onto the boulder is probably the physical crux. Once on the boulder press off that left hand and toe and reach up to a good hold in the horizontal split.    Figure out how to match hands and get a foot in the crack. From here trust the right toe and release both hands and lunge for the jug at the lip. This is the mental crux of the climb. Very unique and a combo of power, technique and finesse!    This is a really fun climb to get on with friends. Starting with both hands in the crack is around v1.

name: The Swamp Crack Direct
description: Start matched in the large crack and make a few moves to gain a high right foot to make a big right handed move. Get weird and find a way to top it out.

name: The Swamp Crack
description: Sit start matched in the large crack, work your way up and left on good holds. Some cool footwork and movement on this line. It's nice to have somewhere other than the zoo to warm up!

name: Swamp descent
description: Stand start the prow to the left of "swamp is on", make a few technical moves trending up and right into the same top out as for "swamp is on". Climbed more separately than I anticipated, the direct of this prow goes too, might be v3 range.

name: Swamp is on
description: Sit start at the right side the bulge with plenty of decent hand options but not much for feet. Power up righty to a bucket side pull, then it turns into a balancy slab climb, pretty much hands free to get established on your feet if you're not tall enough to reach the seam. Traverse up and right on good holds in the large crack at the lip until you can get your left leg up and rock over. Really fun!

name: Swampedelic Pop
description: Sit start with LH on an incut crimp rail and RH on a sloper on the arete. Pull off the ground and make your way left and up the arete. Two powerful moves were the crux for me but this line has some technical footwork and some tricky body positioning. Jake snagged the stand first, we're thinking that might be a v5. I sent the sit mid summer so it might be a grade or two easier come fall time.

name: Train Wreck
description: Stand start at the prow of the roof. There is a dike feature, and on either side there are some crimps. Pull on and make a hard move up right hand to an incut. Make a move out left to a good sidepull and balance up to a jug and top out.    There is potential for a low start as well.

name: Ammunition
description: Start as for Bulletproof, matched on the rail. Go up to the slopey lip (or okay crimps right next to it) and instead of following the slopey arete left like Bulletproof, continue straight up the slopey feature sticking out on the slab. Use weird techniques and body positions to power yourself up onto the slab. Walkoff the back.     This is a neat climb that's not as good as the classic it shares the start with, but is still worth your time.

name: Bloody Knuckles
description: I cleaned and climbed this line years ago... It may have been redone under another name but i had to dig out holds and broke one off as well (on my first try i busted the left hand crimp off skinning my knuckles across the rock giving the route its name)...    Might need to brush out some pine needles first but the climbing is great, the rock is solid and grippy, go for it... Sit down at crimps and pull on throwing for a grip out left, then a right hand move straight up gets you to a good hold and you pull on to the slab for the finish...

name: Brett Does Lawn Jobs (aka.- Keep it Subtle)
description: Start up at small block below shallow seam up. Work up and left on cimps to cruxy slopers. Move a bit left then up to the crack on Std.

name: Bulletproof
description: This lip traverse is friction dependent and usually chalked up.  Sit start under the roof on a good flake.  Move R hand to snag a sloper on the lip, and either use an undercling or slap L hand up onto a sloper around the lip.  Traverse left, utilize a heelhook, then head up the arete/jugs to the topout.   youtube.com/watch?v=i27SMGh…

name: Ceadas
description: One of the newer hard problems in the area, this is unfortunately only climbable when the stream dries up and the lagoon in the pit is gone.  Starting in the pit, climb the steep face on bad crimps and pinches until you can reach around the left arete to a sidepull flake before finishing up.  You may want to pad the low angle slab behind you in case of a backflop.

name: Death of the Blues
description: This climb is what remains of the old climb Blues Drift and it's an obvious highball. Starts on a great flat jugs with decent feet. Move left hand to crimpy lower side pull and high hand-foot match with right foot. Grab slopey crimp with right hand followed by a bump to a higher side pull with left hand. The crux starts with locking off the left hand while standing tall and reach up and right towards good side pull (intermediate crimps could help). Bring left hand up to a dirty crimp and bump right hand higher to the good arrete. Walk feet up to small foot holds (a right toe hook on arrete helps) and slowly bring left hand to flat jug at the top for a good top out.

name: The Dream of Life
description: If crimpy, technical highballs are your jam, I would highly recommend this climb.     Start on an undercling on the right side of the small roof and make a move to a left hand crimp. Above it, snag the slopey crimp rail and work your way up and left on delicate feet to two very positive crimps. Straight up to the top from there is very thin and requires delicate footwork and balance.     The lower half of the climb has some obvious flakey holds that should be avoided.    !!! IMPORTANT !!!    Please dismantle the log bridge/dam that is used as a landing for this climb after you are done working on it each time. It causes lots of water to flow around the boulder and increases the erosion/flooding on both sides. The water normally flows directly under the boulder and rarely around the sides. Please do this so we can preserve good relations with the park and abide by LNT principles. Thank you!

name: Gun Show
description: Sit start next to the tree on the left, using a left heel hook, an undercling for the right and a decent hold near the heel for the left. Move up to a higher undercling for the right, drop into a bad left hand crimp, set your feet and jump for the lip. Squeeze hard. Top out on jugs.    The bad left hand used to be better, but broke a few years ago. This got a V5 in the last guidbook (which I always thought was sandbagged anyway) and it's way harder now.

name: Hemlock Gate
description: I do love Pawtuckaway slabs... this one is good practice... Step on and do a few 5.9 slab moves to the top...    It looks like there could be a cool sit down start that as far as i know hasn't been done...

name: Kalbro
description: This awesome arete problem is tucked away in the heart of Boulder Natural. Start sitting and layback up the underside of the attractive overhanging corner, then flip your body to the slabby side of the arete and make a super fun and delicate smearing move to top out at the apex. If only it were longer! Pictures of this aesthetic problem have been featured far and wide.  The top out mantle crux is  very committing and can spit you off in a lot of different directions, make sure you have good pad coverage and multiple spotters at multiple angles

name: Kids With Guns
description: Sit start on a good crimp and right hand on the arete, pull up and grab a crimp with the left hand and adjust your feet now make the crux right hand move to a good sidepull near the arete and top out.    If this was taller it would be good but it is rather short...

name: Knuckle Dragger
description: A great, friction-dependent line that feels impossible until you figure out body position and slot your heel perfectly.  Just right of Bloody Knuckles, sit start with a good left hand sidepull and your right hand on the pinch of The Very Bad Idea.  Pull up and snag the severely sloping lip with your left hand before traversing up and left to reach the jug on Bloody Knuckles and finish as for that climb.

name: Missile Command
description: Tired of small crimps and sharp holds? Get on this  superb sloper testpiece then. Sit start with a good right hand crimp and a high left hand on the slopey lip. Pull on with good feet and make moves leftward on divots and awesome slopers. Get the right hand on the lip and make a big shouldery move from a divot way out left to the sloper sidepull. Tenuos footwork allows for a match in the same area with your choice of a pinch, crimp or divot. From here drop into the horn as for the first move of "Bulletproof" and match, or go big and hit more divots and finish up the arete with a heelhook.   Super pumpy and unique movement, along with friendly holds make this a good project and a sweet problem!

name: My Girlfriend
description: Another one that i cleaned long ago...This is a fun couple moves but its over so quick its kind of a bummer...    Start on the one hold on the wall (on the left)... Pull on to the wall and hit the sloping top... Move left on slopers untill you can throw a heel and press it out...

name: NRA
description: Friendly holds, gently overhanging, good feet, and a tricky topout.  Sound good?  Sit start next to the tree with a large crimp for your right hand and a low jug for your left.  Make a few moves up good holds until you gain the lip, then figure out how to rock over onto the slab.  Once you're through the crux, it's an easy romp up the slab.

name: One in the Chamber
description: Sit start on the sloping lip to the right of the Hemlock tree located behind "Ammunition". Pull on and move up to a small undercling sidepull before doing a hard move to a mono or two finger pocket. From here make a far reach off the mono before topping out in easier terrain.

name: Out of Ammo
description: Start about 6 feet to the right of the small hemlock tree. Sit start with a small right hand sidepull and the left hand above on the slopey lip. Choose from good feet and pull on. Start slapping and smacking your way left on slopers with divots, and crystals while fighting for friction. Make a hard move out left to a giant sloper sidepull and then make your way straight up via a crimp or a divot, and execute a hard move to a good hold and get established on to the slab for the top out!    This line seems like a more natural version of "Ammunition".    For some extra pump, keep going and send the mother, "Missile Command".

name: Power & Technique
description: An odd, yet fun climb that takes a little power and, you guessed it, technique a la footwork.  Then again, if you're tall, it will probably seem easier.  Sit start with both hands matched in the chalked up crack in the middle of the face.  Pull off the ground and gaston your left hand in another crack.  Move your feet around, then make a big move, left hand again, to a crimp above your head (crux).  Once you have the crimp, you can either continue straight up over the bulge on jugs, or traverse into the finishing crack on the Standard Route.

name: Slab-dercling
description: Start on the slab with a good undercling. Using the undercling for as long as possible work your feet up smears and friction a couple moves until good holds are reached and make the easy top out.

name: Standard Direct
description: A slightly more difficult & direct version of the Standard Route with a fun mantle move in the middle of the face.  Stand start a few feet right of the arete with an undercling directly below a slopey dish.  Pull off the ground and grab the hidden seam in the back of the dish.  Do what you have to do to be able to mantle the dish and reach up into the crack.  Once you're in the crack, it's a juggy romp up and right to the topout way off the deck.

name: Standard Route
description: An easy, fun highball with a low crux.  Stand start (or sit) the arete, and climb up and right to gain the juggy crack.  Once you're in the crack, continue up and right on great holds although the ground gets further and further away.  Topout and have a seat before climbing down.

name: Still Remains
description: climb up the right angled beginning finger to hand sized crack with some pretty solid toe hooks into a pretty good jug to match on, pull your foot into the triangular shaped hole and cantilever your knee in, turn your hips,layback on the wide crack at the top or treat it like an offwidth.

name: The Very Bad Idea
description: Crimp up an arete then finish up an exciting slab.  Sound like fun?  Sit start the arete to the left of the pointed stump with a right hand sloper and a good left hand pinch.  Pull up to a set of crimps, then using a cool left hand divot on the slab, make a scary move out right to a slopey sidepull that will help you get up onto the slab.  Finish up the slab to an easy topout.  Great movement, but try not to fall onto the spear.

name: Yosemite Arete
description: There is never chalk on this one.  Maybe because it's quite tall.  Fortunately, the crux is down low.  Start on the left side of the arete and slap up on technical ground with a few reachy moves and small feet.  Scary moves at a crack/corner lead to a horizontal crack already high off the deck.  Then make a great traverse left in the do-not-fall zone to the path of least resistance to the top (summit).  Downclimb cracks and chimneys on a different side.

name: An Unexpected Journey
description: Start out matched on the big side-pull (rail) and decent feet but in a slightly awkward location, step up and hit the horizontal crack, move your feet up and make a high step into the crack.  Finish up on easy slab moves.

name: Another World
description: Sit start on a rounded jug and a sidepull and balance/power your way up and left to slopers for slab topout.   The starting foot will find your shins if you aren't careful.   Hard for the grade, but fun and friction dependent.

name: Barnacle Bill
description: The painfully obvious crack.  Start with your hands on a shelf with a heel hook by your hands and prepare for judgement day.  Jam, crimp, thrutch, grovel your way across the left slanting crack till you can stand up into underclings and bring your feet up.  Then finish up the far left arete.  The book gives this V3, I think that it is much harder and never gets too much easier.

name: Bilbo's Revenge
description: Traverse the crack right until you reach a tree than topout.

name: Boredum
description: Sit start on a crimp rail and fire to the lip and make the casual top out.    The name of this route is very appropriate.

name: Charlie Horse
description: Crouch start same as Barnacle Bill (at the far right side of the crack) and follow Barnacle Bill up to that cool double jug/sidepull. At this point, the rest of the crack is off, as are both of the aretes. Climb straight up the blank face through terrible slopers and tiny knubbins. Top out on jugs.

name: Circumspect Ceiling
description: Inside the chimney to the left of lobster tail is a small cave with a crack running through it, sit start as far back as you can, use the wide crack to a welcoming jug and contortion yourself up the chimney to the top.

name: Crystal Method
description: Are you a fan of head injuries and awkward painful climbing?  Do you enjoy bouldering with a helmet and causing harm to your spotter when you fall?  If so, then this is the climb for you!  On the backside of the Zoo, this sharp arete rises out of a hole and while it doesn't look half bad, it is possibly one of the worst problems in the park.  Start at the base of the arete and climb out of the hole while fighting the barndoor into the other boulder, then as you finally reach the crux, try to avoid cracking your head open or knocking your spotter off of the boulder as you grunt for the lip.

name: Edges
description: Start on the obvious edges on the right side of the face with a large, good foot and climb straight up on crimps.  Topout over the awesome juggy lip.    V4+ as a sit start, and V7 if climbed as the finish of Sidewinder.

name: Fallen Ent
description: Start as for Bilbos Revenge but now that the tree has fallen you can traverse the whole crack to the arete for Hobbit Hole. The tree known as Chris?

name: Four Hole
description: Start standing with hands on nice holds and either make one move then dyno to the top, or work the flake up and left to the top for a more difficult but less dynamic option... the top out is easy making this a good one for firs time boulderers...

name: Gandalf
description: A fun little climb that never gets done. Definitely feels harder than John's Stand Up, but I'm pretty good at crimps so that probably helps. Stand start same as JSU, in the slopiest part of the crack used on Hobbit Hole. Grab a decent LH gas tone and scrunch your feet to the crack. Stand up in the crack, but rather than going straight up to the jug rail, move straight up. Grab a tiny right hand crimp and gun for a good sidepull. Cross over to a mossy edge and grab the juggy arete. Follow the arete to the lip and top out same as Hobbit Hole. It can also be done as a sit start (starting same as Hobbit Hole), which bumps it up to about v6-.

name: Gone in 60 Seconds
description: Climbs a bulge via really bad holds.  Sit/squat start with the two crimps at waist height.  Move up R hand to a sloper/crimp, then match next to it on a sloper.  Work your feet and make a hard move to a crimp (crux).  Stand up on the crimps and topout.    Named for a hold that ripped off.

name: Good Rips
description: Start at the base of the juggy flake that also serves as the start for Sidewinder. Continue up the flake and make a big move to the lip.  An intermediate crimp broke off years ago.  Mantle over to finish.    No, the tree is not "on".

name: Grilled Cheese
description: Sit start the very lowest part of the Mushroom Boulder on the sloping lip. Throw a heel and mantle straight up. Pretty dull, but worth doing once, I suppose.

name: Hobbit  Direct
description: Levitate off bad holds and pop to big crimp on arete, continue up easier ground on arete and downclimb route.   Hard sit start. The start feels like trying to squeeze a hippo between your legs.

name: Hobbit Hole
description: Crux is the beta, work your own out because everyone's is different for this climb. The climb is amongst the majority of the boulders in Boulder Natural (an area referred to as Gandalf's Lair). It is an obvious up and left slanting lower crack the follows the arete and jugs to the top of the boulder (downclimb route). Lots of climbers find the lower sidepull helpful to use with your left hand to pull the crux move out of the horizontal handcrack.

name: Jaws (Texas Chainsaw Massacre)
description: Two moves.   Sit start, hands up, mantle the buldge and hand foot match to gain the top out.    A worthwhile one-move-wonder.

name: John's Stand Up
description: Stand start at the crux of Hobbit Hole with a good fingerlock and get your feet on the wall.  Climb straight up with your choice of a gaston or a sidepull for your left hand and balance up until you can stand in the crack.  Finish up easier terrain.

name: Let's Call It "levitation"
description: This little route is the left facing arete between "mistaken identity" and "another world" there has been maybe a little more then 3 ascents of it just because it gets over looked.   Start left hand on a sloping pinch and you right hand lower on the arete squeezing a nothing divot. Get a heel hook and magically levitate up to a right hand crimp. struggle to keep the heel and mantle into "another world"    I called it V6+ , but the reality is I don't know...

name: The Lobster Pot
description: A fun and easy chimney climb as long as you don't fall and pinball your way down to the ground. Stand start and work your way up the left face towards the top of the "Shillings" arete with good hand and foot holds. Two-thirds of the way up you will transition over to the "Lobster" boulder for the top out.

name: The Lobster Tail
description: Start on the feature that looks like a lobster's tail. Climb up and right on easy ground (jugs and obvious feet). Downclimb/slide other slide on boulder.   This can be a good warm up in winter to get the muscles moving (do it in sneakers).

name: Manhole
description: Sit Start the arete to the left of The Wanderer. The first move is the crux, once you pull over the lip scurry up the arete and slab to the top.     The first move is fun but the rest is pretty bland. Not a bad problem to do if you have done all the other easy warm-ups in the area.

name: The Marathon
description: This climb starts on the north face of the mushroom boulder and goes clockwise to the topout by the tree on the south side of the boulder.   This problem is a very pumpy and challenging traverse with your hands and right heel up on the top and your left legs getting in the way the whole way around the boulder.

name: Mistaken Identity
description: This arete is what most people climb when they think they are on When I'm On My Own.  It is missing from the guidebook, but perpetually caked with chalk and was once vandalized by some idiots with a blowtorch.  A foot-long piece of stone dropped off the arete thanks to their carelessness.    Sit start the short arete and layback to the top, making use of the crimps on the left face, and also maybe a few high crimps on the right side.  Grab the lip and mantle up.

name: Power and Grace
description: A crimpy crux with feet in all the wrong places...Are we in Pawtuckaway or something?...    The beta varies, but it's either techy or a big throw at the crux...Then an easy top out....

name: The Professor
description: Sit start on shallow underclings. Pop out left to edge and cross feet. High heel with left hand in super-shallow dish. Super-thin crimp with the right hand. Pull hard and deadpoint to sloping topout holds.    Location of your heel will make this climb V6 for some and V-impossible for others. Accuracy of your heel placement is paramount.    As an alternative for 6ft+ climbers, It is possible to make a big move from the right undercling and left flake all the way to the top.

name: Ricochet
description: Sit start inside the cave like feature matched on a good hold in a crack. Move leftwards in the crack for a couple of moves, then get high feet and flip the hands to underclings. From here make a hard and long reach up and right to a large sloper shelf. A decent climb with some scrunchy movement and friendly holds.

name: Rio's Smaug Face Problem
description: This climb flies a bit under the radar because it's not in the guidebook, but it's deserving of more attention.     Start sitting with two obvious low edges and small feet. Make a hard move to gain a good edge and then continue upward via incuts and sidepulls to a delicate top out. Though the rock is somewhat fragile/hollow feeling, this is a really good climb with great flow to the moves.     The landing is a little spooky due to the possibility that you might fall down into a gap between the boulders and end up at the bottom of the start of 'Hobbit Hole'. Given that, it's a good idea to be fairly solid at the grade before climbing this or to have a few pads and spotters.

name: Shillings
description: This is the tall arete opposite of Hobbit Hole, its not a incredibly tough problem, just a heady problem because its tall. Just keep your head strong and you will be fine. Have fun and trust your feet.

name: The Shire
description: To the left of Hobbit  Direct is a tree and to the left of the tree is this route. Sit start with a good slopey hold on the lip and a small crimp down and left. Pick some feet and move over the lip using crimps and side-pulls to a long move to  good hold in the horizontal. Then scamper up the easy climbing to the top.    I had originally heard this was supposed more in the V4 range but it felt much easier. Let me know what you think... Did I start in the right place?

name: Sidewinder
description: This crimpy problem is one of the hardest in the Zoo Area.  It starts on Good Rips, goes left around the corner (under roof), and finishes on Edges.  Sit start on the good jug(s) and immediately toss a heel up with your hands so that you can grab a bad crimp out left with your left hand on the outside of the tunnel.  Don't hit your head as you move your right hand to a crimp just below your left.  Now that you're hanging horizontally, make the crux move up to a good edge on the face.  Control the swing, establish yourself on the face, and finish straight up.

name: Sisyphus
description: Traverse in from the left on a little arete, at the overlap grab some jugs, and do a spicy rockover to get to the top.  There's always some large branches in the stream to keep your pads out of the water.  Called Sisyphus because if you don't master the balance, you slowly teeter backwards toward the stream.

name: Smaug's Face
description: Highball line on the back side of the Smaug Boulder. Sit start at Bilbos Revenge and head straight up the dirty face. All the holds you need are cleaned up good.

name: Two Bits
description: This problem is listed as a project in the Kemple guide but it has been climbed many times.  Pull on to the face with the help of the left arete, and use tiny holds and delicate feet to dance your way up and slightly left towards the arete and notch.  Highly technical and somewhat scary moves will reward you with a thank-god-jug right before the top.  Although it can appear slightly scruffy, the climbing can be worthwhile.

name: The Wanderer
description: A fun slab climb. Work up the slab, there are a few different ways to go up and all seem around V0. A fun problem for your first time bouldering.

name: When I'm On My Own
description: A short, crimpy and powerful problem that suffers from a bad case of exfoliation.  In 2004 most of the holds fell off of the face, leaving the problem in its current state.  Its still fun if you have nothing better to do.  Sit start just right of the pocket on the Professor and layback a right hand sidepull with the help of a tiny crimp below the pocket for your left.  Snag the weird crimp in the seam with your left hand and gaston up to a crimp on the face.  Drop into the double gaston and dyno to the lip.     An incorrect grade and a missing problem in the guidebook have created confusion about this short climb and as a result, it is rarely tried, let alone climbed.  Although the guidebook description of climb broken edges trending right is correct, most people climb its neighbor, the left leaning arete, and mistake it for this problem.  For that problem, please see Mistaken Identity.

name: Zoo Traverse
description: A fun linkup of 3 boulders.  Start sitting as for Another World, follow edges left, swing feet onto the arete and transition over onto the arete next to When I'm on My Own, then handtraverse the lip to the left to get your feet on the starting hold of Jaws (Texas Chainsaw Massacre), now downclimb Jaws with a reverse mantle (crux), traverse left into the start of Hobbit Hole, and follow the Hobbit Hole crack to the end.    Long and pumpy.

name: Adventure Baby
description: Start on the 1.5 pad incut rail as for "My Way" and head up slightly left to a sharp-ish crimp.  Mantle this crimp and make your way up the steep slab above.  Stand start

name: Back At You With The Realness
description: A quick power problem.  Stand start with both hands on underclings using the high foot.  Pull on, power out right to the arete, and control the swing.  Finish up the easier arete.

name: Barbie's [--]
description: Start with hands on a low shelf. A few good holds to top out in the mud.

name: Barbie's [-]
description: Climb arete to follow the horizontal crack across the face to top out. It's a long, slabby slide down...

name: Charlie's Crack aka Crescent Crack
description: This is definitely one of the best hard crack lines at Pawtuckaway, though it's more about your crimp strength then your crack skills.     Climb the aesthetic, arching fingertip crack from a sit on the right. After a few easy opening moves, the business begins. Footholds are few and far between, so creativity and technique are rewarded. As you near the end of the crack, stem across to the left side of the corner, breathe and then finish up the easy corner.     Finger size will play a huge role in how difficult this feels. I could barely fit my fat fingers in most of the slots on this climb which made the climbing feel very thin!

name: Check your Head
description: This problem apparently begins standing, but may be done from a sitstart from the right for added difficulty.  A small edges around head level exist for the hands.  Hike your feet up to something and slap the pitiful slopers above.  Somehow get your weight on your feet, if possible, and crank upwards.  After the slopers, there are essentially no holds for quite a ways.  This is powerful and balancy series of moves...kind of an ungradable problem I think.  But it's very hard and requires strong tendons.

name: Check Your Head Sit
description: Sit start down and right of the V9 "Check Your Head" in a crack. Right hand high on a big pinch and left hand lower in the crack. Move up and left to a left hand crimp and come in righty using some foot trickery. From here execute a few more moves on small holds and then finish up a hard and tricky v9.

name: Chuckie's Torture
description: Over the winter of 2010-2011, a piece of rock broke off of the wall creating a hold where, before, there wasn't one. The original problem & sequence is unaffected, however, it created another way to climb the wall. Before the break, an ascent of this problem was rare and it's safe to assume the original problem hasn't been climbed in a while. Original Problem (Hard V9) It starts sitting with a few holds in a low horizontal crack.  Once you stand up into the underclings, a very long and tenuous move straight up to a flat, half-pad crimper gets you going.  Get your left hand up to a small crimp on the left, then you have to use your technical prowess to tick-tack your feet and hands up...until you can gain the monster jug in the middle of the rock.  A mantle on this hold is needed to top out.  This is a great challenge of fingerstrength and footwork. The flake and foot jug out right never even come into play. New Wave Version (V8) The most obvious way to climb the problem. Start sitting in the crack, stand up into the underclings and grab the creaky flake. Continue through the crimps and stick a foot in the start hold of Jugs to reach the jug before topping out. If you choose to eschew the huge foot, it bumps the grade back to a soft V9. If the flake weren't there, the huge foot wouldn't be a question as there is no way to reach it on the original problem.

name: Clingon
description: Start on the huge under-cling and make a big move to the good jugs on the traverse problem "Jugs". Follow the arete up to the top, staying to the right of "Tom's Problem".

name: The Dike Route Sit
description: Sit start with a left hand crimp flake and a black dike pinch for the right. Pull on and make a big move up to a war-like sidepull before continuing up the dike feature on some more unique holds until a series of crimps and slopers are reached. Another committing move gains the lip and leads to a nice exposed topout.

name: The Dike Route
description: A left leaning dike leaves a black streak through the right end of the boulder/cliff and makes for some fun moves.  The holds might be slightly atypical of the rest of the park, but different can be good.  Start standing and work up and left on crimps and edges to a topout that feels a bit high.

name: Fun in the Sun
description: This new addition (11/18/15) is probably the best warm-up at the upper uppers!  Start with a good right-hand crimp, a side-pull with the left hand and a good left foot.  Move right to good holds on the arete, and climb it to the top.  The crux is probably the first move or two, and the top is quite easy and fun.

name: Gabber's Route
description: Stand start with left hand on a jug and right in the crack. Reach high to a bomber fingerlock (crux) and continue up the crack. A sit-start variation is possible.

name: Good Lord! aka The Tip Rip Face
description: Like crimps?     Like really, really sharp, tiny crimps?    Then you're in luck because this is the climb for you!    Start standing with a few different options- either at left utilizing a good crimp flake or on the right using a high right crimp/gaston. Enjoy these holds because those are the last good ones you will grab until the top.    Pull off the ground and try to piece together a sequence that works for you using small technical feet and tiny sharp crimps. If you make it to the good horizontal, either traverse slightly left and up through a crack (harder, scarier and better) or bail right around the corner (easier, less scary, kind of lame). The top is often dirty and covered with pine needles so scope it out beforehand.    It isn't a four star classic, but it is hard, technical face climbing. If that's your thing, you'll love it.     The arete at right is not 'on' for this problem. This climb only utilizes holds on the face to the left of the arete.

name: Granny's Grunt
description: Let's be honest. There aren't a lot of truly good cracks to be found amongst the bouldering at Pway. This drives people to do crazy things, like thinking they actually want to climb 'Crack Of Pain' at Blair Woods. Why fawn over that quartz nightmare when you can actually climb a really good, comfortable finger crack?    This crack isn't super long, but it is quite fun and challenging, and not even that sharp. (Well, maybe a little. But nowhere near as bad as 'Crack Of Pain'!)    Stand start with some good fingerlocks and work your way up through some decent locks and small feet to a wonderful top out jug.    There is an easier variation that uses some holds to the left (mostly the arete), but the best way to climb this sweet little line is straight up, crack only!

name: The High Way
description: This problem continues the theme for this wall/boulder- technical slabby and vertical climbing!    Start standing around 5 feet to the right of the obvious crack that makes up 'Gabber's Route'. Choose starting holds from a couple of different options. (I went with the diagonal flake for my left hand and a high crimp/pocket for my right hand.) Head straight up via technical moves on an array of small crimps facing all sorts of directions. Near the top, the holds begin to run out. Stand delicately on some small feet to latch the distant, sloping lip and finish out easily.    This is a good test of crimp strength and slab climbing skills. A fun and worthwhile climb.    It should be noted that the crack at left is considered 'off' for this problem.

name: Inside Out (Standard)
description: Stand start and figure out the moves to make your way to the top of this right facing corner. A tricky start and finish on this one, makes for some enjoyable climbing.

name: Jedi Minds
description: An obvious, sharp left-leaning arete.  Sit start the base on the right and work your way up to the top.

name: Jugs
description: Start sitting on left side of boulder, traverse horizontal crack all the way to the arete and top out wayyy up there.   Keeping your feet on during the jug traverse can be difficult, but rest assured the crux is the topout move to a good hold that you can't see.

name: My Way
description: To the right of the V1 crack in the middle of the Font Boulder, start  on a large shelf at head height. Bump out to crimps trending up and rightward and try to find some footholds. Keep bumping, crossing, or whatever way feels best to climb crimps diagonally to the right eventually topping out on good holds behind the tree. The holds used to topout are good, but a fall here would not be the best thing considering the tree is right behind you. Kind of highball at the end I guess.

name: The Outback
description: This problem used to have a sit start, but some of the holds have fallen off. There is still potential for a sit start, but it will be hard, awkward and probably not that much fun.    In its current state, the climb goes from a squat start, starting with left hand on a bad sloper/pinch (just above a little crimp flake) and right hand on a good crimp out right (see beta photo). Pull off the ground, throw your left heel on and make fun compression moves to a fun mantle.     Though short, this climb is a lot of fun. It climbs similarly to 'Throng', so if you like that problem, you'll probably like this one!

name: Sitting Santas
description: A classic climb up the middle of the face on small crimps! Start  sitting slightly right on small crimps and trend left a little on edges and gastons to a tricky topout. Sharp.

name: Splitter
description: Sit or stand start and climb the splitter crack to the top.  The crack grows wider as you ascend and takes hands, fist, and stacked hands jams like a champ. Great for beginner crack climbers to practice on.

name: Taco Bell
description: Jug haul up the sweet flake on overhanging rock.  Then make progressively harder moves to the lip, and make a sketchy mantle (probably the crux) to top out.  Be solid or have a bail out plan for the top, since a fall could be ugly from the mantle.

name: Tectonic Plates
description: A diagonal crack splits this overhanging face.  Perfect undercling fingerlocks, slopers, small technical feet, and hard pulls are all part of the fun.  Start standing with dual underclings and tiny feet.  Make a large move left hand to a sloper on the lip, work your feet, and follow the crack to the right.  Once you grab the jugs, the topout through the notch will feel like cake.  Careful not to hit the tree if you blow it.    A sit start goes at V9-10.  The block on the left is not part of the problem.

name: Tip Rip Arete
description: A fun little problem with great movement for the grade. One of the best of the grade in the cliff boulders. Start about 3 feet right of that dreadful v6 crimp problem matched in an incut seam at the base of the arete. Using small feet and interesting layback moves, work your way up the sharp arete to a sloping ledge. From there, you can perform a somewhat exhilarating beached whale to topout.

name: Tom's Problem
description: This almost certainly isn't a new climb, but it took a bit of cleaning and I've never seen chalk on any of the holds nor is it in either of the guidebooks.     Grab the second set of jugs on 'Jugs' and go straight up, utilizing a high left foot, and a long lock off with a small intermediate for the left hand. Match a crimp and make another long move with the right hand to some crimps off the deck, keep it cool for the high top out as the feet are great but the hands are not so great. Other sequences are possible utilizing some worse sidepulls out right, so play around.    Can also be done from a sit, which adds a long move to the jugs but no real difficulty.

name: Unknown Crack
description: Sit start on the large feature to the left of the start for "Chuckies Torture". Head straight up the crack.

name: Vulcan Tip Rip
description: This highball face climb up the center of a sweet amphitheater is SHARP!  It's not named Vulcan Tip Rip for nothing.  Crank off the ground with crisp edges and very small foot holds.  Long, sick moves gain ground fast.  It would not be wise to fall at the top.  Despite the pain factor, this is definitely in the running for the best V3 at Pawtuckaway.  It's worth the hike up here to try this problem, but make sure you have some skin on your fingertips when you do.

name: Bates Route
description: Ascend blocky ledges through a lower angle left leaning dihedral. This fun romp comes to a halt when you reach a strange section where you will either have to exit the dihedral and do a slab move with out right, or grovel in a strange sideways position past a weird offwidth that tries it's hardest to spit you out.   Finish the weirdness and clip a two bolt chain anchor to lower off. This anchor can also be used to toprope Speckman's.

name: Bowltender to the B Team
description: Ascend the slab, then climb a sweet right-curving finger crack to the roof (same as F.O.T.D. to here).  Traverse left under the roof into a V-corner, and up this to a large bolck on top.  Belay from nuts in the block and down-climb 15 feet to a stance.

name: Crossroads
description: Start up the Bate's Route, extending your pieces as far as possible, and placing minimally in this 5.4 section. About half way up take right leaning crack through big moves in a steep juggy section  to an exposed pedestal rest. Take the time to plug good gear here, and stem right into a bottomless shallow scoop that leads to a vertical slightly run out face on good crimps. Stop at a small horizontal to place your tiny last pieces before continuing to the chains on more positive crimps. Your heart rate will likely come back down as you reach the massive clipping jugs.

name: Curiosity
description: Stick clip the first bolt and do some radical looking crimping and hucking to a set of lower offs.   This is the route just right of Heat Wave/Maximum Heat.

name: Devil's in the Details
description: An easy corner leads to a wild and committing boulder problem through a roof, finishing on a spooky face above.  Start at the base of the Bates route and Crossroads, and climb up an easy corner to a big ledge at the base of the roof. Climb up the corner into an awkward undercling crack and do a wild sequence out of the big roof to the pedestal rest on crossroads. Finish on the run out upper face of that climb (which should feel a bit harder this time around).  It's really good, I'd recommend figuring out the sequence in the roof before trying to lead it. Good thing you can check it out after lowering off Crossroads.

name: Dubuko
description: On the far left side of the Speckman's area, scramble up to an extremely long horizontal crack and traverse it to its terminus on the Bates route, and finish up on the Bates route. For more fun, when you reach Speckman's, climb up the 5.9 slab directly to the bolt anchor.  This thing is the "On the Lamb" of Pawtuckaway. It would be better if it was rotated 90 degrees.

name: Easier Said Than Done
description: A nice mix of slab and face climbing with a crack thrown in here and there.  Climb up the slab to the left of the arete past a bolt to gain the horizontal crack and move right to the arete.  Head up the short face to reach the sloping ledge above and then traverse off left into the trees.    For a more challenging finish, climb the 3rd pitch of The Exorcist straight up the bolted face (3 bolts) from the ledge.

name: The Edge
description: A nice adventure climb with superb exposure without having to get too high off the deck.     Start up the face just right of the big chimney and stay right of the curving flake until you get to a good belay spot. I recommend this even though the pitch is short as the route makes a hard left at this point. Speaking of which, look left and marvel at the amazingly inviting (and a little intimidating) leftward traverse. Follow this very obvious line which offers good hand holds and protection but smooth slabby feet toward a more vertical short off width section (don't be scared it's not hard). Atop this OW there is a perch that could work as another belay, or just continue up the low angle slab/arete to the summit (beware of some fragile flakes on the last 25-30 feet and little in the way of solid protection).    I highly recommend this to anyone looking for an enjoyable adventure at the grade and an opportunity to avoid the busier cliffs.

name: El Rayo X
description: This arete and face climb could use a little love before it fades into the lichen.  Starting at the left arete of the graffiti face, next to two trees, climb up into a large undercling and use small cracks out left to gain a somewhat vegetated stance below the upper wall.  Continue up the face past 3 bolts to the top.

name: Exorcist
description: Awesome crack and face climbing on a beautiful (albeit, crumbly) left arching crack. Just standing below this wall is awesome. One of the best trad lines in southern NH.

name: Friend of the Devil
description: An overhanging v-groove preceded by a crack that looks like ring locks all the way. I'm sure the face above is spicy too based on the number of pins.    If you have a better description let me know. I doubt many have done this route free.

name: Heat Wave
description: Near the left end of the cliff you cant miss this perfect left leaning crack coming out of a small cave. If you start down in the cave it's more like 5.12 and called Maximum Heat. For a challenging 5.11 (the way it's most often done)start off the rock and lean out for your first jams. Follow the crack system up and left to a mellow finish and a tree anchor.    I found the crux to be the first 2/3 of the steep climbing haha. really pumpy and sustained, by the time it lets up and you get a few good jams it feels just as hard due to exaustion. the upper 20-30 feet are mellow 5.7ish climbing thank god haha. a great route with good protection. do it.   It's steep, hard, funky and beautiful.

name: Homebase
description: Climb the vertical crack to the left of Heat Wave. There are 2 cruxes. Getting off the ground then an upper crux to reach a welcomed jug. The gear on the upper section could take over your holds making the moves quite tough.

name: The Immaculate Constriction
description: Jam a hand crack on the outside of Cheese-Its (same start as Cheese-Its?) to a rest.  Crank the short obvious crack past where there once was a raven's nest, then enjoy a left-leaning, flared chimney.

name: Lycra Sanction
description: Do a bouldery move to get established on a slab with holds, then climb up below a roof and make a step left into a dihedral with cracks. Relatively clean and safe, if this route gets some traffic it will become an area classic.

name: Maximum Heat
description: Maximum Heat is the low start to Heatwave. It's difficulty increase is derived from the even boulderier moves needed to gain the meat of the crack.    Follow the crack over the lip to some tat on a tree. if you're taking multiple burns or your second is capable of leading 5.6, build an anchor just above the lip and lower off, having your second rap from the tree.

name: Oh God!
description: Start up an easy layback crack to a large sloping ledge, then traverse right to the arete. Climb up the arete feature until you reach the horizontal crack of Dubuko, and finish on that route traversing the crack right.

name: Oh Hell
description: The direct finish of Oh God! Layback the same crack and climb the arete to the same horizontal, but keep crimping straight up past a bolt to an interesting friction groove. Do some shallow stemming through some cool huecos, past another bolt to a two bolt anchor.

name: The Pretty Flake
description: Standing below the big dark chimney look up and right to the low angle face above and the flake should stand out right away. Start by squeezing up a tight spot to get off of the ground and climb a slabby bit. Place pro and reverse right to gain the flake proper. Follow the beautiful flake with fun moves and perfect protection to its end. I traversed right to a nice belay here then climbed the money pitch of The Edge.     Recommended for sure.

name: Speckman's (Originally named Speckman's First Aid Climb)
description: A thin crack that tapers out just when you need it most, climb it to the horizontal break, then plug some good gear, rest, and finish the last 15 or so feet on perfect 5.9 edges.The protection is dubious and the crux is hard, but damn is the climbing good. When you are up there you may wonder how you are sticking to the rock at all, and when you fall it will probably be just as unexpected. Bring your footwork, crimping skills, extra skin, and laser focus to this fight.  The route used to hit the horizontal break, then trend right into the Bates route, however there was an "A3 Hooks" variation which climbs 5.9 edges directly above the break. The current free route goes to the horizontal break, and continues directly up through this "A3" section to a two bolt anchor at the top of the cliff.  Originally done at 5.6 A2, this route was reportedly freed in 1985 at 5.12-PG. According to the '95 Todd Swain Guide, the route was sometimes referred to as "Why are the pins so far apart?". The PG protection grade, "AKA" name, and one particular pin scar lead me to believe that there was at least one pin fixed in the crux on the first ascent that is no longer there, leaving the route a very scary test piece. When my friend heard that it was 'PG' he said, "Potential Ground-fall?".

name: Squeeze Play
description: An aptly named chimney climb that doesn't get wider than about 18" for most of its length.  Scramble up a few blocks and place the last of your pro for awhile before pulling into the very claustrophic chimney.  If you wind up facing the wrong direction it's going to be a challenge to turn around.  Friction your way up the smooth sides until you can stand up in an alcove.  Plug some gear in the cracks and climb the right wall of the alcove on jugs to a tricky topout.    An old guidebook calls this the best chimney in Pawtuckaway.

name: Strong John's Shelf
description: The crux involves passing a right leaning sloping rail on a steep overhang with poor feet, and mantling onto a dirty slab. Two bolts, hard boulder crux, dirty slab, probably no second ascent. Sound fun?

name: Sympathy for the Devil
description: One of the most impressive and most difficult climbs in the Den.  Starting on the Exorcist, climb the crack and corner to the top of the overhang and move right up the face past a few bolts before arching back left to gain the hard-to-miss vertical crack above.  Finish up the crack to the anchor.    The upper crack seeps frequently, marring an otherwise beautiful climb.

name: A Burnt Offering
description: Stand start with a large left-hand undercling on the arete, and the right-hand low on a small brittle undercling right of the arete. Pull onto the wall and make a hard move to the sloping lip before matching and topping out on slopers.

name: A Moment Of Light
description: This is another excellent addition to the Devil's Den scene, especially if you like crimpy, technical and tenuous highballs.     Start standing beneath the tall face with both hands matched on an obvious incut flake at 5 feet. Use a few small crimps to the gain the right facing feature above. Then use good footwork and lots of body tension to reach decent holds in the higher right facing feature (crux). A few more moves lead to the top and a fairly easy finish.    This is a 3 star line for aesthetics, but the rock is still a little flakey. This should clean up with more traffic, so hopefully people will get on it. A big thanks goes out to all the people that put effort into cleaning this line over the last year or so! Those efforts helped make this line a reality.

name: Aardvark
description: Start the nice overhanging arete by awkwardly sit-starting on another rock. Pull onto the arete and make a few fun moves up before making a hard compression move out left to some slopers and then execute a committing topout.   A fun line that is a beginner version of "Numb Thumb".

name: Advantageous
description: Sit start on the left arete of the face the faces the trail.    Make a strenuous move (crux) off the ground to better holds, continue up the arete making powerful and technical moves. The top out can be a little heady if at your limit.

name: Ant Farm
description: Sit start the bottomless arete underneath the prow. Get a high heel hook and grab some good crimps. Power your way off the ground and choose your next hold. Make your way up and right utilizing the smooth unique rock of the problem. Use some fancy footwork or power your way up the arete and then top out on the slab with care.

name: Aretascious
description: Sit start on the right arete of the face that faces the trail. Pull off the ground (crux) and make enjoyable moves to an mellow top out.

name: Arete To Arete
description: This is a fun linkup traverse that gives you another option on this boulder. It also serves as a great warm up if you're at this boulder to prepare for a day of hard climbing at the main Den areas.    Start standing (or sitting) as per 'Aretascious' and traverse left using holds in the seam and below until reaching the left arete. Either drop off and call it good, or finish up 'Advantageous' to get a few more moves in.

name: Ashes To Ashes
description: The test piece of Devil's Den bouldering, complete with a fingertip crack, non-existent feet, and a hard crux.  Sit start at the left end of the crack on the two good crimps and traverse right until the crack disappears.  Make a hard move up and right to gain the next crack, either with a heinous cross or an easier dyno and continue right into better holds.

name: The Bad Apple
description: Start standing with high crimps (see photo) and climb the seam via some technical footwork and core tension. Figuring out the beta is probably the crux on this one.    This is a unique climb on good quality rock, though somewhat awkward from a movement perspective. Definitely worth trying if you're in the area.    Technique will take you further than tugging will.

name: The Big Crimp
description: Start start on two triangular crimps. Pull on to the face with a few foot options and reach over to a good but sloping sidepull/ gaston, set the feet and make a hard move to the large rail next to the arete. Latch this and stay tight! A few moves up the arete gain a topout jug. A rad problem worth doing!

name: Big Gulp Project (Doing the Dew Sit-Start)
description: Start on LH undercling on left face, right on pinch edge on arete. Slap RH to higher crimp on arete, then bring LH to a small crimp at the same height on the left face. From here, either do a big dyno to the Doing the Dew start or a big LH deadpoint. Climb that problem to the top. The 2nd move is by far the hardest, but the first and 3rd hand moves are also fairly hard, and the foot movement between them is incredibly tenuous.

name: The Big Ocean
description: Start left hand on the heavily chalked hold to the right of the asshole and right hand out on the edge of the roof, jump up to get the right foot on.  Slap out on slopers, place the left foot and heel hook to the edge of the roof.  The crux is pulling up onto the face.  Top out and descend as for "Red"

name: Blue Devil
description: Sit start with the right hand on a bad sloping pinch on the arete feature. Find a small micro left-hand sidepull, and a foot before pulling onto the wall and jumping out left to the other arete. Keep compressing both aretes before moving up to a hollow jug flake for the topout.

name: Borealis
description: Stand start on the right-leaning tall arete and climb it using technical footwork and core. Execute a few fun balance power moves a few feet off the deck. Until better holds near the top can be reached.  An excellent problem that receives little attention.  Apparently, a sit-start does go, but it is quite awkward, and the feet are poor. By the looks and feel of it, the sit is around V8.

name: Bradley's Dyno
description: A fun one mover. Great for warming up and running laps on. Start with the left hand in the jug on the left facing flake, and the right hand slightly higher in a crack. Find your feet and hike them up. Trust your smears and fire to the good lip. Or just reach up.

name: Bridge of Immortals
description: One of the proudest lines at Pawtuckaway, this incredible arete towers over every other boulder in Devil's Den. Stand start matched on the arete and layback off of the boulder above the chasm. Pull on to the wall and make committing moves between small edges and sloper knobs found along the laser-cut arete. A lot of core tension, precise footwork and a good head leads to a very committing end sequence. Stab at the perpendicular arete/ lip before rocking over on a heel.

name: Broken Piercing
description: Sit start the short left-leaning arete on some juggy pinches. Make a few moves up the arete before figuring out which side you want to mantle on. This problem provides a good intro to arete-tension for those gyms\ rats who need their finger buckets and crimps in order to climb a route.

name: Camelio's Mantle
description: Stand start at the lip of the roof on a decent left hand sloper with a thumb catch and right hand on another sloper a foot to the right Campus off the ground and throw up a heel before pressing it out and balancing your way up the slab to the top.

name: Charon's Journey
description: This problem uses two different boulders. Sit start on the fin-like arete underneath the roof. Pull on and move up the arete before reaching out left to the lip of the cave. Traverse this sloping lip leftwards before grabbing a few unique pockets and executing an awkward mantel before reaching up to jugs and finishing at the apex of the boulder. A great way to warm up for harder problems in the Den.

name: Charybdis
description: One of the newest highballs in the Den! Stand start under the large roof to the left of "Numb Thumb" on the large sloping horizontal crack. This horizontal is found between the roof and the pedestal the roof sits on. Using the slabby pedestal for feet, reach out to the lip of the roof. Match the sloping lip of the roof before making a long move to a jug meat-wrap low on vertical rail feature. After taking a foot cut, swing up a foot and figure out how to get on top of the boulder utilising the large rail and a calm head!

name: Crushing Blow
description: Sit start with two underclings. Make a hard pull off the ground and smack up to the sloping arete. Match the arete then power up and right to the sloping lip and then top out on decent holds above the slab.

name: The Decomposing Walrus Project
description: A tall and proud line on the back of the Walrus Boulder with a crux move down low. Stand start with your hands on two sloping crimps in the horizontal seam and make a powerful first move to the sketchy looking flake above. Once you've made the first move continue up using sloping holds and the arete for a high off the deck finish on solid holds.

name: Demonic Blessing
description: Start underneath the overhanging prow with a right-hand rail and a small left-hand edge. Pull on with difficulty and make a hard move up to a good edge out left. Match, and then gun for the lip of the boulder. Once on the lip, a direct mantel is possible, or a traverse on slopers into the top out of "Red Right Hand".

name: The Devil Wears Prana
description: A powerful problem over a not so great landing. Stand start with the left hand on a smooth crimp on the lip and right hand next to it. Pull on and move out right to a decent edge. Figure out how to match and lock-off to a bad sloper and then top-out. Powerful and fun.

name: Devil's Right
description: This is a great arete climb that teaches a lot of fundamentals for outside climbing, especially for Pway!   Stand-start the left-leaning arete and pick some feet to pull on to. Using core and some foot smears, follow the arete up to improving holds at the top. The top-out is pretty easy, but the downclimb is a bit dirty and covered in lichen, a fall from the downclimb could be dangerous.

name: Devil's Trilogy
description: The bolted arete above Universal Socket that's probably more suitable as a boulder problem to the obvious lip. Start low, slap up edges on either side of the arete.

name: Dirt Devil
description: Sit-start the base of the left-leaning arete. Pull-on with some slick feet and body-tension and follow the arete up and left until jugs can be reached!

name: Doing The Dew
description: Start standing with both hands matched on a really high edge at around 8 feet or so. Shorter folks will have to stack some pads to reach the starting holds.     Pull off the ground and work up the faint dihedral/corner using some right trending rails. After establishing on the face, make some very tenuous moves to gain the lip high off the deck and holds that are not quite as good as you were hoping they'd be.     Technical and exciting climbing for the grade.

name: Eye Of The Devil
description: If you like Essentials but wish it were longer, then you'll love this route.     Start matched on a good flake crimp, pull off the ground with some difficulty and then head straight up using a slopey mono pocket, decent slopers and foot smears, tricky high steps, and a hard hand/foot match up high that could be avoided by trusting your feet on "eh" smears.    The giant flake at the top sounds pretty hollow, but I don't think it'll come off unless you're using a crowbar.     Personally I think the best way to get down is to walk to the arete to the left of where Red is, have someone place some pads and spot you, and then hop down.

name: Faint
description: Sit start with left hand on the arete, and right hand low on a small crimp side-pull. Get a right foot smear and pull on with difficulty. Move right hand up to a diagnol crimp rail and then bump the left hand up the arete with difficulty. Go right hand out to a good flake, and choose your feet wisely.    Grab the pinch on the arete and the small crack for the right hand and continue up the arete or do a small dyno to the top lip.    Starting one move in is still a sit start and is slightly better and goes at around v2. Start with the right hand on the diagnol crimp rail.

name: Family Feud
description: A fun warm up that would receive four stars in Boulder Natural!   Sit start on the giant sloper rail with a left hand sloper or sidepull, and a slightly sharp right hand meathook. Pull off the ground and make a difficult move to the lip, and then figure out how to match. From here mantel on slopers and a good left heel hook along with a good crimp rail.

name: Feeling For The Heavens (aka Slow and Pooky)
description: This excellent climb should be on everyone's tick list. Good edges and crimps lead to an exhilarating (but safe) top out high off the deck.     Choose from an assortment of holds at 6 feet. Pull off the ground and puzzle a way up to the jugs/large edges at 2/3 height. Take a breath, shake out and continue upwards to finish on good holds.

name: The Fern Gully
description: A fun and powerful problem! Stand start with both hands above the roof. There is a unique left hand mini pinch and a nothing sloper for your right hand. Compress the holds and figure out some foot beta. Move up right hand to a good crimp/ pinch feature and then fire up left hand to a side-pull crimp. From here get established on the slab and top out with good holds. Aesthetic and proud!

name: Fertile Mud
description: Sit start in the mud puddle matched on a bad sloper-crimp rail. Somehow find the positioning and friction required to get your butt off the ground a huck for the slopers at the lip. Core up and keep the feet up before traversing right to the apex of the short boulder before mantling.

name: Full Moon Fever
description: A super hard mantle testpiece. Start at the lip of the roof on a nice shelf feature. Mantle the shelf and somehow reach up to the next lip of the boulder. A tiny thumbdercling could potentially be quite useful!

name: Hidden Meanings
description: Sit start with the left hand low on the suspended arete, and the right hand on a knob for your thumb. Get a left foot on and pull off the ground. Make a hard toss up left hand to a decent spot on the arete. Bump the left hand and figure out what feet you want in order to make a big toss up right hand to a two finger crimp knob. Once here get a left foot jug and continue up the right leaning fin-like arete on improving holds. Super fun. The stand start is a great warm up.

name: The Hug Sit
description: Sit/squat start with a small crimp for your right hand and a slopey sidepull for your left hand. Pulling off the ground is hard and you have tiny feet. Stand up and make a desperate move with your right hand up into the slopey undercling. Then adjust feet and throw left hand up to the good crimp above. (At this point you are at the starting holds of The Hug)You can now get a high left foot and make a committing dyno move to the lip. The top is fairly flat and you can make a relatively easy topout at this point.

name: The Hug
