description: This modest looking climb is actually quite good, with powerful compression moves and a very fun dyno.    Start standing with your right hand on a sloper sidepull at 5-6 feet and your left hand on a high angled sidepull crimp at around 7 feet. Pull off the ground and make a long reach to get your right hand to a good hold on the right arete. Sort out some feet and dyno for the lip. Stick the swing and finish out with a mantle that is a bit more difficult than it first appears.    This climb is somewhat morpho since the span between the two aretes is fairly big. It might feel easy for tall folks. It might be impossible for those on the shorter side to make the span.    There is the possibility for this to be done from a sit start, using a small right crimp and a weird sidepull/pinch for the left. This feels signficantly harder. Perhaps v9ish?

name: Individual Medley
description: Great arete climbing up a beautiful squarecut corner!  Start standing and make a hard highstep move to gain the arete.  Stick with it until you get a sloping jug at about two-thirds height.  Gather your wits and courage, and figure out the best way to get to the top (hint: look way up high and to the left for a small positive handhold).  Be careful up there...this one's a thriller!

name: Initial Harmony
description: Sit start the aesthetic vertical arete with the right hand on a good sidepull found on the face, and the left hand pinching the arete. Pull on and layback the arete on pinches before hitting a sloper at the lip and committing to a mantle.

name: John's Problem
description: Another worthwhile addition to the awesome v5-v8's in Devil's Den. Start same as Feeling for the Heavens and follow it for a few moves. A about 2/3 of the way up, traverse right on good edges towards the obvious scoop. Cross to the scoop and make a scary deadpoint to a good crimp up and right. Snag the lip and top out. Not quite as good as it's classic neighbor, but still a blast.

name: Lady Slipper
description: This is a short boulder problem with incredible rock quality. Large smooth shelves and friendly pyramid-shaped pinches. Sit start in the pit matched on a large shelf. Pull on and move up to a pyramid before reaching for jugs at the lip. A tight but rather fun line that is worth checking out.

name: Leave It to Beaver
description: Start sitting on the right side of the boulder with a hanging, blocky arete to your left. Heel hooks and tension get you to a pinch and a sharp crimp. From here, make a big move and lots more tension lead to a slopey but solid topout.

name: Mr.Butterlips
description: Start on the pedestal below the boulder, reach for the good crimp on the lip, then follow the sloper lip out right to the jug top out above the jug.

name: Mud Traverse
description: This is a great lowball lip traverse that supplies the Den with an easy warm-up that also doesn't require a plethora of pads!  Sit start matched on the left side lip of the short boulder. (Just left of the mud puddle!) Pull-on and make a series of fun moves on large holds until you reach the bulging apex of the lip before executing the crux top-out!  This climb is great for beginners and experts alike.  Yes, it does go campus as well!

name: My Disguise is Seemless
description: Sit start with a small left hand crimp left of the arête and right hand incut sidepull. Pull on and crank up to a left hand crimp. From here set the feet up and move the right hand up to a good incut, and keep following the arête and the seams up and slightly left. A scrunchy and dabby introduction is followed by a slightly nerve racking finish above a boulder. A fun addition to the Den!

name: Myotis
description: Star under the roof of the boulder on a sloping horizontal rail. Find some options for feet and figure out how to spin around to jugs on the arete before finishing up with some compression and a somewhat tricky topout.

name: Naughty Devil Chick
description: Sit start with a left hand sloper pinch on the arete, and a high right hand crimp. Pull on and make a fun move up to a good meathook/ pinch. From here follow the arete up and right on slopers.    Starting with a low right hand could increase the difficulty quite a bit.

name: No One Knows
description: Not to be confused with the one-move wonder at Blair Woods, this hideous problem is really not worth it. It is dirty, condition dependent, tiny, a little sharp, contrived, and climbs even worse than it looks.    Sit start on the base of the very short arete with both hands on dirty, sloping nothings and an awkward right heel. Work your way up the short arete with mossy holds and slippery feet and finish the love up with a beached whale into the dirt. A candidate for the worst problem in the park.

name: Numb Thumb
description: Sit low and climb left up on the arete to highball topout.

name: Pretty Bloc Swag
description: A new contender for Pawtuckaway's best problem.  FA'd by Hayden Miller on 12/16/2011.    From Hayden's description on sendage.com:   "Start matched on left slopper rail. Move up through gastons and crimps to arete then compress your way to the lip. Exit left."    I will add that (as someone who has many years of improvement ahead to even have a hope of doing this climb) it looks like an absolute instant classic.    Note: The 4-star rating of this route is passed along from Hayden's sendage.com report, where he suggest 5 stars - the maximum possible on sendage.

name: Red
description: Sit start from good holds under a low roof, fire out to the lip with the right hand and then work out left and up the face to the arete.  try to avoid ferns and moss as you top out

name: Red Devil
description: Start on the left side sitting down. The is a good foot way to the left and very slopey holds heading up right. Make a few moves right before popping big to a decent arete way out right. Bear hug a few moves until you can gain a hollow jug and climb on top.    Sloper skills with a side of explosive power will be the recipe for this little number.

name: Red Right Hand aka Spitting Blood
description: This beautiful climb is a fantastic addition to the Devil's Den area.    Start sitting with both hands matched on the left side of the obvious wide rail. (The first ascentionist started with both hands matched on the sidepull feature.) Pull off the ground and move rightwards along the rail, using subtle beta, to eventually gain a good incut flake with the right hand. Then figure out a way to get your right hand to the arete/lip above (crux). This sequence is both powerful and technical.    Upon gaining the lip, traverse it leftwards to a monstrous top out jug. Throw a heel on and rock over. Done!

name: Reverse Traverse
description: This is a fun climb that teaches the fundamental of heel hooking in the direction of travel, a foot-first traverse!  Sit start matched on some good crimps on the right arete, pull on and make a powerful move up to some good slopers, then start traversing leftwards, at some point swinging the feet out left in the direction of travel may prove useful! Once the far left is reached, mantle the short boulder and grab some jugs!

name: The Ring of Bright Water
description: Sit start matched on a large crescent-shaped sloping rail. Pull on and make a hard move out right to another large sloping rail. From here compress up the two large rails before making a long reach up to an interesting lip encounter. Friendly and bullet-proof rock.

name: Ron Jon Surf Shop
description: Sit start matched on the leftside of the sloping lip of the boulder. Pull onto the wall and make a few hard moves out right over a sketchy landing before continuing the traverse around the corner and mantling on juggy slopers.

name: Scala
description: This is an outstanding arete climb that is unfortunately marred by its location and landing.    Start standing in the muddy area at the base and reach high with your right hand to find a pinch that works for you. Then use an undercling pinch with your left hand. Paste a foot somewhere and attempt to pull off the ground, fighting a vicious barndoor that tends to swing you towards the Dust Boulder. If you manage to get yourself off the ground, bump the left hand to a good edge (or the top) and reach with your right for a good pinch where the lip and arete meet. Then figure out a way to mantel the slabby pedestal. Once standing on the pedestal, press on for a few tenuous moves, with complete disregard for your safety. Or perhaps more smartly, bail to the top of the nearby boulder.    Now the downsides:    The base of this climb is often submerged, but seems to dry out after a few weeks without rain, particularly in the late summer through fall.     Unfortunately, one of the difficulties of this climb is to avoid dabbing the Dust Boulder (particularly on the start) since it is in such close proximity.     Lastly, once you have attained the lip of the boulder, falling is basically not an option as you would likely fall directly onto the sharp arete of the boulder behind you. So you should feel pretty confident at the grade if you are going to attempt this line.    All of that being said, this climb is quite good and is very worth of your attention! If it's dry, climb it!!

name: Scamper Slab
description: Start on a couple thin crimps then scamper your way up with some pretty small feet.  Stay balanced as you reach up to a pretty solid side pull.  From there you can go after a sloper or move to another crimp rail.  There is a crimp rail over the lip.  Grab on and scamper like you've never scampered before for a sketchy top out.  I'm told this is an FA but if you know more let me know!  Not certain about the grade either so I'd love some feedback.

name: Smoke on the Water
description: Stand Start at the end of "Up in Smoke" on the good slopers. Pull on and make some hard moves using mad core and some tricky footwork to traverse right on small holds and grab the Butthole with difficulty. From here keep moving right and make a hard left hand move to the sloper on the left side of the dihedral on "The Big Ocean". Get a magical right heel hook in the lower pocket and make a hard compression move to gain slopers and pinches for the right hand. Work out some more magic and top out as for "The Big Ocean".    This is a stellar line with some great movement and hard moves. Could potentially be the best of the three problems on this face.

name: Snip Snip
description: This is a very challenging sloper problem with an awkward crux mantle. Start low on the sloping lip and make hard moves up and right to poor slopers and figure out how to top this sucker out. Better than it looks and is a fight the entire way.

name: Surreptitious
description: This is the face that you see from the trail.    Stand start on big blocky holds and decent feet. climb up and left topping out just left of the arete. The crux is near the top when you have to make a move left to avoid the terrible slopers that continue straight up.

name: Throng
description: In comparison to most of the problems in Devil's Den, this one is a lowball.  It climbs up an overhanging triangular shaped face with two aretes and is a good way to ease into the grade.  Sit start with left hand on a blocky feature and right hand on the right arete.  Pull up and heel hook with your right foot to bump your hand up the arete.  Bump your left hand up to the next sidepull block and either make a lot of little moves or one big move to gain the jug on the arete up and left.  A dropknee may be helpful.  Follow the arete to topout in the ferns.    Occasionally a lagoon of sorts forms beneath the problem.

name: Tisk, Tisk
description: Start standing with both hands on a large triangular undercling at head height. (Kind of looks like a shark's tooth.) Figure out a way to pull off the ground and latch a good incut crimp up and left (crux). Use another thin crimp rail to reach the lip. Move slightly left and then up via a great hidden jug.    A worthwhile climb with cool holds and fairly good quality rock. Another fun line on this great boulder!

name: Tradster
description: Start with a few cool stemming moves to gain the crack. Layback the crack to a cruxy finish. You really have to commit to the layback to reach the jug at the top. Easy walk off.

name: The Tusk
description: I have been to the Walrus Boulder many times (mainly to work on Individual Medley) and have always stared at this arete. Upon getting the Underground Guidebook and discovering that it is a climb, I got on it and man it's cool!     Stand start at the bottom of a small ditch with two crimps on either side of the arete. Execute the difficult (possibly crux) process of pulling on via slippery heelhook. Make a cool, precise move to an almost non-existent sloper. Get an awkward left heelhook and gun for a good left hand crimp. Match and control the swing before grabbing a sloping pinch on the arete. Scrunch your feet up and gun for the lip. throw a heel and top out. I'm on the shorter side, so I may have described more moves than necessary, but the problem is really fun and I highly encorouge you to get on it!    This can also be done as a stand start from the good crimp, which bumps it down to about v3, and is also quite worthwhile.

name: Universal Socket (aka The Pocket Problem)
description: Begin by traversing a horizontal crack system to gain a series of good, incut monos (or two-finger pockets).  Yard up on these odd holds, taking care to use the right sequence.  Make a long, committing move to the left arete on a rounded sloping hold.  Then make another big move way off the deck to the positive holds at the top.  There could be cosequences to a fall here.  Mantle.

name: Up in Smoke
description: Start with both hands on the chalked hold to the right of the asshole, with the same rigth foot as for the Big Ocean.  Cross through with the right hand and work out the edge of the roof to the left.  Top out on the arete on the left side of the boulder.

name: Another Face
description: Choose your own adventure up the middle part of the slab... Start on a layback flake to a steep slab and follow the small foot holds up to the midway ledge... Continue straight up or go left to the cracked slab and the top...

name: Half Moon Crack
description: On the right side at the base of the dome find a right angling crack in the slab... Climb the crack until it gets thin then break out left on to the slab for a few moderate low angle face moves... The slab eases up so you can walk a few paces... move right around a bush and up a right facing corner to a stance... Navigate up the slab, there are a few choices... If your eyes are open and your footwork is honed you should find a moderate way to the top...

name: NLN
description: This is a much shorter and much more powerful way to get to the amazing finishing jug on The TVT. Look just below the jug on the left end of the inverted wall. There are a couple of sharp crimps to hang from to get started. There are poor feet down low and decent feet quite high.  Keith, who did it first did 2 explosive moves to the jug. I did it right after and used twice as many moves with my more delicate style (though there is no way around a little power on this one).  Not a bad little addition to this wall though the traverse is still the gem.  The name is an acronym concerning a technique we like to call a "lee-bar" which incidentally is not necessary on this problem...

name: Person on a ledge
description: Climb the arch crack. Make an interesting high step and mantle onto the ledge. Follow the easy arête above the shrubbery to the top.

name: Pine Tree Crack
description: The 25-30 ft crack on the left side of the cliff... The steepest route at the dome... Flaring jams and some slab work out right... Get you to a big pine tree on a ledge continue up the fun cracked slab to the top...

name: Slant Crack
description: Climb the left angling crack to a flake horn midway up.  Continue up from there on pretty good holds or keep traversing the crack to the left and up.    The left variation doesn't offer great protection (shallow) as the crack arches vertical... but placements before and after are fine.  The left variation is also a little more balancy (fun!).    Good feet pretty much the whole way.

name: Slipping Away
description: Hard moves off the ground on a small round sloper and a left side pull. Stand if possible and grab the flat rail above. Mantle the rail and follow easier climbing to the top.

name: The TVT
description: Another totally over looked and over due problem! I've been looking at it for years and just got around to cleaning it today. It climbs every bit as well as i thought it would.    It's a 20ft traverse to a top out but it makes upward progress with the slope of hill it's on so you are moving upward which feels nice. A steep wall with good feet (rare for Pway) and a mix of jugs and crimps with a sloper thrown in for spice.     Start on the nice ledge jug down and right under the overhanging wall. Climb a couple moves in the crack to get established on a good 2 hand jug. head left on smaller holds leading to a cruxy traverse through crimps on the steep face. These crimps lead you to a huge jug at the lip where you can catch a shake before the top out. The top out isn't hard on it's own but it seems hard when you are tired. enjoy...    Full name: The Turkey Vulture Traverse (incase you were wondering)

name: Bugland Arete
description: This climbs the most obvious line in the area, a tall white blunt arete that faces the pond.  Awesome big holds lead to a high, fun topout.  Stand start on waist high jugs with big feet.  Pull up and left to a bucket, match, stand up, and repeat.  The crux comes at the top.    A sit start bumps the grade to V1.

name: Bugland Direct
description: Crimpier and more committing than it's neighbor, but still fun.  Crimp, crimp, smaller crimp, gaston, crimp, dyno, mantle.  Woohoo.  Stand start right of the arete on two good crimps.  Pull on, cross right hand up to a smaller crimp, work the feet, then gaston a good hold.  Reach up right to a small white crimp and toss for a slopey jug at the lip.  Mantle over the top to finish.

name: Influenza
description: A one-move wonder, but a good one at that.  Sit start just right of the tree with the obvious undercling feature.  Pull off the ground with difficulty, toss for the lip, and with any luck you'll stick the jug rather than the sloper.  As with a lot of these climbs, it would be much better if it led to more climbing.

name: Malaria
description: Just right of Influenza, this climbs the short arete/corner that is visible from the trail. Sit start with a good left foot on the arete and a right smear on the face.  Pull off the ground with two underclings above head height (if you can't reach, then pop into them) and grab the lip.  Mantle over the top.  Did I mention that it's short?

name: A Product of Boredom
description: Stand start with a bad lefthand crimp in the seam and an even worst right hand in the same seam. Find the positioning and pull off the ground. Once established on the wall, pop to the lip and topout.

name: Busted
description: One quick move leads to a mantle and the problem is over far too quickly.  Sit start beneath the short bulge/roof with a left hand crimp and a high right hand sloper.  Pull off the ground and toss around the bulge to the lip.  Match and top it out.

name: Dwarf Arete
description: A low angle arete with great pinches and a crux first move.  Sit start the base of the arete on the right with both hands matched on a seam.  Put your right foot on the large hold.  Pull off the ground and slap up the arete.  Make a few moves up the nice arete and topout.  A great warmup with friendly holds.

name: Emperor's New Groove
description: A quick little arete with good holds and fun moves.  Sit start with the good right foot and a smear for the left.  Grab the sidepull on the arete with both hands and pop to the slopey edge on the left of the arete (crux).  Make a big move to the lip (possibly using an intermediate crimp for balance) and topout on good holds.

name: Freddy & His Fiddle
description: A surprisingly tricky arete with crystally holds and great friendly slopers.  Sit start right of a small rock with a slopey sidepull for your right hand and a large undercling for your left.  There is only one starting foot, so put your left foot on it.  Pull off the ground (crux) and gaston the crystal jug.  Match, then move left to a cool sloper, then straight up to another sloper on the top for the topout.

name: Horton Hears a Who
description: Want to squeeze some slopey aretes?  Yes?  Good.  Hopefully the friction cooperates.  This sweet little warmup hugs up the butt of the boulder for a couple of moves before letting you rock over the top on a great big jug.  Sit start in front of the tree with left hand on the left arete and right hand on the right arete.  Using a small, positive left foot, pull off the ground, heelhook, and follow the arete up until you can snag the obvious jug.  Pull over and stand up.  Now go back and do it again.

name: The Lost Dwarf
description: An embarrassing slab encounter that is more fun and more difficult than it looks.  Using two cool slopers on the right of the arete, stand start with a large foothold, then friction, lieback, smear, and slap up to the top.  Topout into the branches.

name: Rumpelstiltskin
description: This short, extremely fingery problem is the hardest in the Dwarf Boulders.  Sit start between Freddy & the Emperor with two terrible crimps in the thin seam.  With the decent foot hold, pull off the ground and out right to the edge on the arete of Emperor.  Match and finish straight up the arete to an easy topout.

name: Squat
description: Start sitting with left hand on a good crimp and right hand around the arete on a poor sloper. There are a couple options for the right foot and the left is a smear. Make a tough move of the ground and bump your right hand up the slopers to a slopey top out.

name: Can't Back Down
description: Great movement on a beautiful, isolated arete.  Once you see it, you'll probably want to climb it.  Sit start down and right next to the tree with your right hand on the arete and your left hand on the big sidepull on the bottom arete.  Heelhook and follow the arete up and left on slopers and crimps before figuring out the crux moves to transition into the topout.

name: Doozer Stick
description: A juggy warmup that climbs better than it looks.  Sit start between the two rocks with your feet beneath the small roof.  There are jugs for hands or a heel hook if you prefer.  Pull up and climb the face and arete on large holds to an easy topout.

name: Dreamshare
description: Although short, this problem has some fun movement.  Sit start on the right end of the boulder with both hands matched on the right rounded crimp.  Pull up and right to the lip, then slap for a hidden seam that will come in handy for the topout.

name: Farstucker
description: A fingery start leads into a slopey finish, but I wish this problem was longer.  Sit start beneath the small bulge with rounded crimps for each hand.  Pull up and left to the arete and struggle to topout.

name: Might Bite
description: Although this is only a three move problem, the fine grain slopey holds make it worthwhile.  Sit start with two good holds and pull up right to a slopey bowl.  Slap up left onto a massive sloper and hope you stick.  Bring your right hand up onto more slopers and top it out.

name: Mudhoney
description: A fun, sloping traverse that leads to a sloping topout.  Sit start down and left on a good jug with a good foothold.  Pull up and onto the lip and follow it rightwards for 5 moves until you reach the apex.  Mantle over to finish.

name: Philo & Gunge
description: Another juggy warmup on Fraggle Rock, this time tackling the central crack and bulge to its right.  Sit start at the base of the crack with large jugs on either side.  Pull off the ground and climb nice holds up the bulge to an easy topout.

name: Voodoo-U
description: If this was anywhere else, it would be perpetually caked with chalk.  Fun movement, fine grained slopers, and a flat landing combine to make for a really great problem.  Sit start beneath the bulge on a large, blocky two-handed jug and make a big move up to the sloping shelf above.  Match the slopers, traverse right until the shelf ends, and then make the crux move up to a sidepull.  Topout straight up on slopers.

name: Alcove Crack
description: Splitter crack in a corner. Crux is the topout.

name: Bartender
description: Sit start under the small roof in the crack, move to good holds over the lip and top out. Pretty fun for only climbing 2 feet isn't it?

name: Buddha's Belly
description: A very nice bulging undercling crack. Crouch start on good undercling slots and climb up and right as the crack turns into a layback flake. Continue all the way to a fun dihedral top out. Very high quality.

name: Burnout
description: A quick little problem put up at the end of the day.  Sit start with a decent left hand and right hand on the massive sloper wherever you stick.  Using a good right foot, power up and left to a loose jug, then climb easier moves to a ledge.  Drop off.    The jug might snap at some point making the problem harder, but the sloper is cool.

name: Confusion Fog
description: A short problem with great, friendly holds.  My only complaint is that it isn't longer.  Start squatting with the U-shaped jug in the middle of the face and pull up and left to the edges on the bulge above the crack.  Get your foot up and move out right to a large sidepull before topping out on easy, slopey terrain.    Variation - Rather than move right to the sidepull, topout straight up with a sloper above the bulge.

name: Crack
description: A very aesthetic crack climb. Stand start laybacking the crack and scrunch your feet up. Get a good ring lock and stand up to better holds above. Top out same as "Buddha's Belly".

name: Didjabringabeeralong
description: A long crack traverse leads into a vertical crack to topout.  Sit start at the left end of the wall.  Follow the rising diagonal crack right until you reach the arete before the corner.  Climb straight up to finish.

name: Dream On
description: A very nice little problem with great movement. Start on a cool hueco jug at chest height. Stand up to a sloper rail that will feel like a jug if you grab it right. Use some good albeit dirty crimps to top out.

name: E-Z Squeeze
description: Offwidth start to a squeeze chimney. At the top exit to the arete at a chockstone or tunnel under and pop out at the top.

name: Fire Tower Face
description: Enjoyable face climb right up top near the fire tower. Stand start by the hueco and head straight up on crimps. Good top out. Perhaps someone has more and better info on this route. Fill me in. Perhaps a sit had been done?

name: Fragile Masculinity
description: Highball face listed in the Underground Guidebook as a project. Line follows an obvious dike trending left to right up the center of the boulder. Stand start with opposing sidepulls in the center of the face. Crux is about halfway up. If someone else has climbed this in the past please let me know. Really fun climb and totally worth doing.

name: The Frog
description: Stand Start in the crack on just, move up on good holds to sloper for the top out.    Although it is not much to look at we found it pretty fun.

name: Headbutt
description: This is a fun climb with good movement and high rock quality that is unfortunately marred by the proximity of a large wedged block that hangs over the right side of the climb.     Start sitting with the left hand on a good angled edge at around 4 feet and the right hand on a low sidepull. Pull off the ground and bump the right hand to a good hold on the arete. From here, make a long move to the lip above without hitting your head on the large block (crux). Finish off with a tricky mantel, doing your best to not dab on the block.     This problem is #62 in the underground guidebook.

name: Hemlock Arete
description: Up the after on flakes and crimps.

name: Jesus Every Time
description: Big power moves on good holds makes this problem a lot of fun.  Sit start beneath the bulging boulder with a good edge, power up to the next juggy edge, then set up to dyno or use trickery to snag the slopey lip.  Top out.    The first move can feel huge, which is how the problem got it's name.  Every time someone sat down to climb, they uttered "Jesus."

name: Letterbomb
description: A fun, short, dynamic problem that revolves around two holds.  Pull onto the wall with a good diagonal pinch/jug.  Fire straight up to a flat hidden edge on the lip and topout with a few slopers.

name: Lichen the Arete
description: Climb the tall dirty arete. There is a harder sit start on the left wall of the arete. The moves are fun and it's pretty tall but flakey rock and lichen detract from the quality.

name: Masterlock
description: A very nice finger crack. Stand start on a good hold in the base of the crack and climb straight up on great locks and laybacks. Top out in the pine needles. Good problem with a flat landing right off the trail, should see more action.

name: Mellow Down Easy
description: An obvious right to left traverse with an interesting mantle to finish.  A great way to warm up or get pumped out.  Sit start beneath the tiny roof at the right end of the wall and start climbing across jugs and slopers all the way to the left arete.  Now, move straight up to two good holds and press until you're able to topout.  Although fun, the crack has a tendency to get dirty, so brush it off before you take a lap.

name: Midnight In A Perfect World
description: This is a very hard dynamic slab problem. Start by stemming in the scoop to reach left hand up to a small thumb-undercling. Match the thumb-undercling and reach out left to a terrible ripple of a crimp. Get your right foot very high on an insecure, glassy edge and generate enough momentum to launch you high and right to a good crimp on the edge of the scoop. You'll probably lose all other points of contact with the wall when you hit the crimp. Control it, match, then follow good flakes up and over the top. The finish is a little high but very easy compared to the rest. A very good problem for those that can appreciate a hard slab climb.

name: Mr. Big
description: From the obvious horizontal at head height, move up to bad slopers and make a big reach to a very slopey mono solution pocket. Get your feet up high and either bump to the slopey ball or make a hard lock off and cross to the ball. Once you've matched the ball, it's an easy move to the top. This problem is really unique for Pawtuckaway and looks much easier than it is. It's very friction dependent; long arms and good footwork will help too.

name: Nada
description: Jug, jug, arete, jug.  A nice, easy problem to stretch your muscles on.  Stand start with a jug in the crack on the left.  Move up right to another crack/jug, then make a fun move out right to the arete.  Topout with the help of another large hold.

name: ODB (Ol Dirty Boulder)
description: Start on a bad right hand and a good left sidepull. Thuggy first move then follow ok edges to the top. Hardest move on this is the first one to the good edge.

name: Over the Top
description: Dirty and some broken feet but it is all there. Start on the left rising flake and traverse across the crack, top out straight up in line with the tree. There are some decent crimps over the lip to help you top this problem out.

name: Pedestal Problem
description: Scamper up on to the pedestal and make a few moves to flat jug, then make committing moves into the thin crack and topout.

name: Proper Pooper Placement
description: Butt placement matters.    Start sitting with a RH crimp sidepull with a slopey thumbcatch and LH on a crimpy undercling. Figure out your feet and make a hard pull off the ground (crux) to reach the first slopey three finger crimp on the arete. Get a LH sloper and follow slopers up the arete to a precarious top out.

name: Reach for the V
description: Fun little lip traverse. Top out at the V shape in the rock.

name: The Remedy
description: An interesting face climb with a delicate start and a fun finish.  Stand start with large feet and two thin sidepulls.  Use a crimp and a gaston and fight the barndoor to reach better holds.  Topout straight up, joining Slither at its end.

name: Seams Easy
description: Start with both hands in the seam on two bad crimps, make move to upper right rail and top out. Crux is getting off the ground. Stand start goes much easier at V0.

name: Slither
description: Perfect height, great moves, and devious holds.  This powerful, delicate arete is a hidden gem and now one of my favorites in the park.  Sit start with a three finger jug for your left hand and a crimp for your right.  Slither up to two tiny crimps using a sidepull before powering into a gaston pinch.  With the help of another crimp and an undercling, make a hard deadpoint up to one of two crimps before snagging the flat sloping lip which feels like a jug.    V5 from the stand, starting by jumping to the gaston.

name: Sunset Arete
description: Sit start on right side of the arete and work yourself into the arete and up. The crux is sticking the first move and keeping your feet.

name: Tomahawk
description: Power into balance. Sit start with right hand on side pull and left hand on sloping rail. Pulling on the ground  is the hardest part of this climb, oh yeah and body position! Work you way straight up the face and top out directly over the start.

name: Unknown
description: Unknown if this has been climbed before, looking for input.   Stand start with left hand on thin side-pull and right hand in crimp dish. Pull on and make a RH move to a crimp rail, match, work feet, make a barn-door deadpoint/dyno to triangle three finger jug. Cross, and work your way right and to the shelf top out.  A sit start is likely doable.

name: V is for....
description: Stand start with right hand on flake and left hand on a bad sloping crimp. Set your feet and fire to the lip. This will either be a dead point for taller people or more of a dyno for people on the shorter side. Either way a super fun route!

name: What's Before Midnight
description: Stand start at the prow with a right hand sidepull sloper on the arete and a small left hand hold. Pull on with good feet and stand up to the undercling feature at about head height. figure out where to hold it and get a high left foot. Make a long reach and hard lockoff to an undercling at about 10 feet. Pull into it and figure out how to top out!

name: Zipper Junior
description: Nice flake / crack to a jug top out.

name: Country Road
description: Sit start on the jug undercling, pull up into the crack and climb it, topping out on good holds.    This would be a really cool line if it had 5 - 10 more feet of climbing, as it is so short I can't give it more than 1 star.

name: Cruciatus
description: Start in the obvious massive jug just to  the left of 'Light the Fuse'. Make a long move or your bump your way up with your right hand to a decent sidepull crimp, move your feet around and make use of the left hand side pull right above the starting hold. and stand up to the same high crimp as for 'Light the Fuse' and top out.

name: Light the Fuse
description: Stand start in the horizontal seam just to left off the tree. Make a big move up and left to a good crimpy-gaston work your feet out left and put all your weight into the gaston to match hand, stand up to a good crimp up and top out.

name: The Short One
description: Grab two crimps on in the quartz and dead point to the lip of the boulder and top out.    The crack is off limits.

name: A Boy And His Dog
description: This is a fun route that has crimps, slopers, and a little bit of compression too (and pinches, although you don't need to pinch them). It's a great fun little climb that's right along the short cut from the fire road to the lower slabs.     The regular line is a sit start, although you could also do a further sit start which feels about v5 and a stand which feels about v2.     Sit start on a good low left hold, and right hand on a good edge. Bump, slap, crimp, and squeeze your way up to the top. There's a good juggy sloper at the top to help with the funky topout. The downclimb is super obvious and you'll be looking straight at it when you top out. Now go do it again!

name: A River Runs Through It
description: This is a fun problem that ascends a left angling off width crack although doesn't get done a lot due to its proximity to a stream (literally under the start)     Start as low as you can in the crack (without getting wet) and layback and foot jam your way up and left. smack the sloper/jug at the end of the crack and mantle using a heel hook around left for the finish.

name: Beavers Attack From Above
description: Sit Start in a good flake and make fun moves up and right on positive crimps to an easy top out. A couple fun moves, but there are much better routes in the park.

name: Beavers Shoot from the Hip
description: Sit start on the sloppery bottom of the left-flowing flake. Feet under the roof.  Big move up/left to the slopers, then an easy, positive top out. Good feet the whole way.

name: Bloody Bath Water
description: Start sitting with both hands on a choice of edges on the obvious rail feature. Make a big deadpoint up and right to a crimp. Then use a unique shallow pocket and a few other holds to gain the lip of the boulder and a relatively easy finish.     A cool mix of power and technique with great movement.     This climb had apparently broken and been deemed unclimbable. Then it broke again and became climbable again. I never tried it previous to its current condition so I can't really comment too much on the history. However, in its current state, I found this to be an excellent climb and personally it's my favorite line on the wall. Originally graded v7. Felt somewhere in the v7/8 range to me.

name: Blue Skied Moon
description: Sit start with some hard body tension and some slopers that are barely usable on an aesthetic arete. Figure out your feet and what holds are actually possible to hold and make your way up the curved crescent arete, until you reach decent holds and can stand on the slab. There may be a few ways of doing the problem, difficulty may vary between v7 and v10.

name: Boulder-Rama
description: The very appealing looking crack underneath a roof of the Summit Boulder. Climb the left leaning crack around the roof, and then continue straight up to the top. Fun but would be more noteworthy if the route was longer.

name: Brother John
description: Sit start the short arete on a good blocky hold and make moves onto the sloping lip. Traverse the lip right using slopers and crimps topping out at the apex of the boulder on good holds.

name: Butt Slap
description: Just down from A river runs through it is this fun V4    Start standing with your left hand on a crack/seam up high. Use the small foot jibs on the face and stand up to a sloper. Move up and slap up the slopers on the top arete until you gain the good ledge and then pull the mantle.    A lot of fun and a dry landing just as long as the stream isn't flowing too strong.

name: Cast Away
description: Start on the Sucker Jug out right of With Confidence and traverse left onto With Confidence and Fido and continue up to the Topout. The rest of the problem is balancy and demands some interesting and subtle changes of weight. Don't blow it or your butt with be hurting sliding down the hill.

name: Cauliflower
description: Sit start with two crimps. Find a foot and pull onto the wall and move up to a right-hand crimp. From here dyno to the top of the boulder and take a crazy swing before topping out on jugs.  The right-hand crimp used for the dyno feels a bit chossy. When it breaks the dyno will have to go from the start holds and will likely be around V8.

name: Center Chimney
description: On the south side of the hill near the stream there is a short cliff band. There are 3 obvious chimneys. This is the center one. Quite fun but a little short.    Start off of a plate like rock. Use jams, jugs and chimney technique to worm your way up this boulderable route.

name: Comrad
description: This problem starts on the left edge of an overhanging chimney.  Get established below the overhang, with feet on a boulder and good holds to the right of the edge.  Make a lunge to a crimp, heelhook, and make tough slap moves over the bulge, finishing up the easy chimney that splits the slab.     I wondered if the FA had avoided the chimney, but I've convinced myself that it would be highly contrived (and really scary) to force oneself to beeline up the overgrown slab for a direct finish.  Who knows?

name: Cough Syrup
description: A techy & pumpy traverse topped off with a tricky finish to conquer the boulder. Good beta works wonders. This is the full line linking Mayonnaise into Miracle Whip. Sit start on the right in the crack, crimp your way left to gain the jug in the middle of the face, then follow edges up and left to the sloping topout of Shell n Dough. Roughly 17 hand movements and fun the whole way.   vimeo.com/80739597

name: Drive By
description: When walking from Round Pond to the Lower Slabs, there are several boulders on your right, this one is short but contains a lot of fun.    Sit start lay-backing the obvious wide crack (too wide for fists for me), make one tough move then get good feet and top out on jugs. This climb is much fun and can done a variety of ways, I have even tried inversion on it but that has shut me down so far.

name: Ethical Cleaning
description: Make a long reach to a small hold on a severely overhanging arete.  Then work up as high as possible and rock up onto the slab to finish on the slab.  Very fun.

name: Ethical cleaning Sit
description: A rarely done line that people walk by all the time. Start sitting matched on the obvious incut crimp down and left from the stand start and make powerful moves off of slopey seams to get into the stand start. Although this only adds 5 or 6 moves into the stand start, they are powerful moves that will get you pumped out quickly making the stand start an even bigger challenge.    A somewhat overlooked line that I thought was worth posting.

name: EZ's Problem
description: I have wondered if there could be a problem here for some time and when I was out filming with Ezra we finally figured it out and man its cool!    EZ's Problem Starts just left of Gums(V4) under the big overhanging flake. climb out left making a big cross to a crimp and then unwind to slap the undercling on the flake. finish by mantling up.

name: Fido
description: Spaced crimps, pop to jug on lip (don't go out right to sucker jug) continue up on crimps to highballish topout on slopers (remember to breath).   This climb is great, comfortable start with the stopper move right off the starting holds. A great way to break into V5.

name: Fido Low
description: A sit start to the classic Fido. Not quite as good because of the awkward process of pulling on, but worth doing if you love Fido (like me) but want to change it up a bit. Overall, a fun way to add some drama to an established classic.    Sit start with a LH on a sharp pinch directly below the starting hold of Fido and a LH on a good crimp in the faint seam out right. Bump your right hand to the start hold of Fido. Match or cross to the intermediate and pull that awesome deadpoint. Make your way up the face via good crimps to the juggy crack. Follow the crack to the finish and topout.

name: Flower Child
description: A relatively short power & compression problem with a crux toss up into the slopers of Flower Power.  Sit start the bottomless arete in front of the tree on the left side of the boulder.  Using a right hand sidepull/flake, a left hand pinch low on the arete, and a left heelhook, squeeze up to a triangular hold on the arete with your left hand.  Now for the fun crux.  Dyno right hand up to the slopers on the lip and hold the swing.  Finish up Flower Power.   youtube.com/watch?v=MIGV_eI…

name: Flower Power
description: Slopers, heelhooks, and fun.  This problem traverses the lip of an overhanging boulder with some good movement and tops out with positive holds on an arete.  Sit start the right side of the boulder with a left hand jug above your head and a massive right hand flake/jug.  Pull off the ground, heelhook, then follow the rising lip to the left.  Once you gain the top arete, rock over onto the face and run to the top.

name: Flower Traverse
description: A fun albiet lowball traverse on the Flower Boulder. Friendly holds and fun moves make for a great pumpy warmup.     Sit start the left arete then traverse the lip right until you reach a good hold above the bad landing, grab the lip and top out.

name: Free Base
description: On the next large boulder right of Tabasco. Without gaining much height, ascend the left diagonal crack until able to break out right via a second crack below the top.

name: Ghetto Knowledge
description: Climbs the left side of the tall face.  Stand start on a diagonal crimp at about head height.  Use small feet and deadpoint up and right to a small crimp, and then up into easier climbing.    Usually dry, but rarely climbed.

name: Gums (aka Timex)
description: This short problem always seems fun, although if you're just breaking into V4 bring an extra pad to protect the possible backflop off the crux.  Sit start in the cave on the juggy shelf (hopefully the birds aren't nesting on it) and pull out left to another large hold.  Fly out left to the hanging arete (crux) and pull over the roof onto the thin slab above.  Once you're standing, you can just run up the slab to top it out.

name: Hidden Agenda
description: Sit start by the dead tree matched on a good jug. Traverse left along the lip until you can offwidth the crack at the end. Eliminate the offwidth for a more difficult top out. I cleaned this up pretty well but it may still be crispy. The landing may be wet certain times of year.

name: Inside Corner
description: Stem up the corner using a mixture of technique and power to a high crux at the top. The top out is made easier if you use a flexing flake up and left, but it feels like a gamble because if it breaks it will result in a awkward fall. If you don't want to take the gamble, reach into the wide crack right of the top out for an awkward top out.

name: Italian Stallion
description: Climbs a highball scoop with a low crux.  Sit start with a sidepull and the jug.  Stand tall to reach a L sloper, heelhook, and grab a gaston just above the sloper.  Work slopers & crimps through the scoop heading left towards the obvious jug.  There is a hidden jug just right of that hold.  Follow a crack/jugline straight up to a high topout.    Always dry up to the finishing crack.

name: Jinx
description: Start same as Italian Stallion, but instead of heading up the scoop, break right on the juggy crack. When you reach the arete, follow it to the lip. A good crimp on the face can be used to help with the crux at the top part. Overall, pretty fun, but don't blow it at the top.

name: John's Problem
description: Start standing with hands matched on a good incut flake at head height. Find some feet and deadpoint/dyno to a decent edge/sidepull up and left. From here, figure out a way to get your feet established on the starting hold and then angle left on thin crimps and small feet to the finish.     The Kemple guidebook says to jump start, but I was able to do a normal stand start and it felt pretty much the same in difficulty. It also felt like the far more logical start.    The rock quality is somewhat questionable on this climb and many of the holds are hollow. This makes the finishing moves even more exciting! Still, this is a fun and worthwhile climb deserving of more traffic.

name: Josh's Dilemna
description: Sit Start just below the overhang on holds that are a little crumbly rock and makes moves up the arete and crack to the top. The rock is sharp but the moves are enjoyable.     The kicker block below the starting hands is on.

name: Life Aid
description: A lowball lip traverse that quickly becomes a highball. Good head game comes in handy for this short problem.  Sit start matched on the lip. Pull on and traverse the lip out left before mantling fifteen feet off the deck. A punt on the topout would not be okay.

name: Locomotive Breath
description: Follows a right leaning crack inside a corner.  The crack is rather large, and is probably best climbed as a layback, although there are face holds or try a jam if you're feeling bored.  Usually dry year round, but the topout may be wet.    With a few pads, the route is boulderable.

name: Mantlepiece
description: Sit Start in the corner using the big sloper jug with interesting stemmed feet. Pull up and go to the jugs n the horizontal above your head. Climb over the roofs to the right with move that feel like the Gunks. To an easy top out.

name: Mayonnaise
description: One of the best climbs in the area, this right to left traverse of the face will test your finger strength and footwork.  Pull off the ground on the right at the start of Snicker with the two good holds in the crack.  Make a long move out left to a gaston/fingerlock in the crack, grab the crimp just right of the crack with your right hand, then use some small crimps on the face to get the large flake out left.  Finish up the dike on flakes.

name: Miracle Whip
description: This right to left rising traverse is the second half of the problem Cough Syrup and starts on the jug in the middle of the face. Cross to a flat edge in the dike, then reach left to a crimp before dropping onto the knob. Crimping with crap feet will get you to the sloping topout of Shell N Dough, and Man, that rail looked so much better from the ground!

name: Motherf***er
description: A fun, tricky, power problem that starts on the nose of a boulder and follows rounded crimps and slopey holds up an arete to the topout.  Sit start to the right of Welcome to the Fold at the right end of the roof with your right hand on a good crimp and your left on a faint seam.  Using the good feet, float up to the rounded crimp up left, drop into the slopey arete with your right hand, then make a big move (crux) to the good sidepull out left.  Move up the slopey arete and figure out how to top out.

name: Near Life
description: A cool crack running up the center of a sharp arete.     Sit Start using the arete and crack and some interesting feet, I used a toe hook. Make crux moves off the ground to a good jug. Then finish more easily up the arete and crack to the top.

name: Obstacle Crack
description: Not once have I ever seen chalk on this wall.  Hopefully that changes when people realize that there are trad climbs over here.  Starting just right of the Black Fly face, climb into the so-called hole in the wall, then choose your exit.  This inventively named route follows the left leaning crack out left and past a chockstone to the summit.

name: Outside Corner
description: Squat start on the arete and make a powerful move (crux) up to a decent hold, then continue up the arete to a slabby scamper to the top.

name: Penguins in Bondage
description: Jam a left-angling crack to a small roof.  Move out right under the roof and follow the flared crack to a niche.  Finish on a straight-up crack.

name: The Pit
description: Stand start on some chossy crimps and do a huge move up left hand to a small ripple crimp. Figure out your body positioning and reach up to better crimps before executing a slopey top out above a pit. Really awesome movement if you can climb double digits. Otherwise, keep walking.

name: Professor Booty
description: Sit start as for Bloody Bath Water with the large rail. Make a committing first move with your right hand up to the broken crimp. From here make hard hand movements traversing right and staying low. Continue traversing right into the jug crimp of Fido. From here finish Fido. A pumpy techy traverse.

name: Right Chimney
description: On the south side of the hill near the stream there is a short cliff band. There are 3 obvious chimneys. This is the right most one.    Climb the chimney past the chockstone or squeeze around it through the lemon-squeeze hole.    Though not a bad way to spend a few minutes this is the least awesome of the chimneys so if you only have time for one... you know what to do.

name: The River Project
description: This is a stellar project that I discovered this summer. It's hard for me to believe this line hasn't been done yet, since it's located about 100 yards from the Round Pond parking, but it appears that is the case.    Start standing with your left hand on a sloping quartz edge at around 6 feet and your right hand on any one of a choice of smallish crimps at similar height. (There is one hold that seems like the most likely choice.) Pull on with some difficulty and make a big move to an angled edge with the left hand. Reset the feet and then throw again to the lip with the right hand. Hold the swing and pull a few remaining moves to top out.    This is one of the best undone lines I have seen at Pawtuckaway. And it's so easy to access. Someone needs to do it! It's kind of like a smaller version of 'Confident Man', with similar athletic moves between decent holds.     Not sure what the grade will be ultimately. Feels at least v10. Perhaps a bit harder. But I could be completely wrong. :)    This is an open project. So, send it and let us know all about it! I'll be glad to update the post. And take some pics or video because it would be cool to see.

name: Roadside Chimney
description: A nice change of pace, Roadside Chimney makes for an easy and quick climb on your way to other areas, or a worthwhile stop on it's own if you like chimneys.    Scramble up onto the block at the mouth of the chimney and dive right in. Chimney your way into the depths of the boulder and take either a tight, low line under the chockstones, or a wider, more awkward line between them. Work your way back and up until you emerge from the chimney on top of the boulder. Walk off on large fallen log or downclimb.

name: Rusty Mustad
description: I Put this problem up while exploring the hillside area. A short and fun problem off the beaten path from the hillside boulders. Sit start on the down-slope with a square nub and the juggy lip as the starting holds. Bump up to a nice jug above the lip then up to a sloping crimp up high in the corner. Work your way up to the mantel crux and top out to the right. Feet are bad unless you can stick a nice heel hook on the arete.

name: Sally
description: A quick little warm-up on good holds and a good beginner problem.  This problem climbs straight up the dike in the middle of the boulder starting with a huge jug at about head height.  Pull on, then follow flakes straight up.    A sit start is possible at a much stiffer grade.

name: Sally Sat Down
description: Technical and powerful. Sit start in the crack with a good right foot and a good left foot. Move up the crack then lunge for the jug, or use some finesse and do it static.    A great climb and close to parking area.

name: Sand Wedge
description: A decent problem with a few fun moves, although not as good as it's neighbor, Gums.  The two problems share the same start.  Sit start in the cave on the juggy shelf (hopefully the birds aren't nesting on it) and pull out left to another large hold.  Pull up and slightly left to a good crimp (crux), then finish up straight up into the bushes.

name: Seeing Red
description: This problem has suprisingly good movement for something that has been walked by and ignored for so long.  It climbs a thin face and an arete.  Start standing on the right side of the boulder with a two-hand blocky undercling and a large right foot.  With the help of a sloper pinch on the arete and some small crimps out left, work up to a good incut crimp out left, and finally the jug at the peak of the boulder.    A sit start has been done at roughly the same difficulty, but is nowhere near as good.

name: Sneaker Problem
description: A fun little problem with or without shoes.  Stand start on a good jug.  Either use the boulder on the right for feet, or campus up and left to another decent hold.  Bring a left foot up and pop for the lip, then mantle.      Can also be done as a campus problem, or a lip traverse L to R.

name: Sneaker Problem Sit
description: A fun party trick dyno into the classic V1 "Sneaker Problem". This variation to the problem uses the pedestal far out left due to lack of feet on the actual boulder. Sit start and reach high to a sloping left-hand pinch above the roof of the boulder, and grab a bad right-hand opposing crimp under the roof. Figure out where you want your feet on the block and execute a hard unwind dyno to the jug slot up and right. Core up and squeeze the left-hand and try to avoid dabbing the rock out right. From here match hands and do a v1 deadpoint to the lip before rocking over ta heel or a toe for the topout.  This is one of the best dynos I have done in the park and is a worthy addition. Initially, I was trying it without the pedestal, but generating momentum is extremely difficult, and it is much more enjoyable to use the jug foot.

name: Snicker
description: Although this climb is slowly falling apart, the holds may have finally stopped exfoliating and become a solid problem - that is, nothing has fallen off lately.  It climbs a short bulge at the right end of the boulder next to a tree.  Sit start with both hands in the crack, move straight up on crimps.

name: Snicker-Doodle
description: Sit start as for Sally Sat down, dyno and grab the jug and move right as if doing Mayonnaise backwards. Grab the crack with the right hand and bring the left in to a sharp crimp. Bump the left hand for the crux cross move and from here reach over right hand to the good hold on Snicker. Finish as for Snicker by moving up to a sharp flake and eventually a good hold. Top out with caution and try to avoid the tree.

name: Tabasco
description: Battle your way up the obvious left facing corner with an over-hanging crack in it (an overhanging layback!)The higher you get the harder the climbing gets.

name: Under The Box
description: A sweet little problem with a slew of different ways to go at it. Start on the two jugs, hugging the wall. Terrible feet to start, cross your left hand under to match with your right. Throw a high heel in the little pocket over to the right. Then it gets funky. Either shoot straight for the high right corner or a neat hand heel match and go left to a crimp and bump to the top. Either way, you end up standing on a rail, and have to use the "bunny ear" holds on the top to hoist yourself over. (The wall this corners into "MantlePiece" is obviously off, and if this doesn't get a ton of traffic, you may have to go up and dig the bunny ears out a bit, they have the tendency to get buried by foliage).

name: Unknown (Ship's Prow)
description: Sit start the sharp arete on good holds on the boulder just to the right of the problem Mantlepiece.

name: Welcome to the Fold
description: A great powerful problem that surmounts a bulge from underneath a small roof with a tricky topout.  Sit start under the bulge with a right hand crimp and a left hand seam over the lip.  Using the large right foot, float up to a nice rounded crimp with your right hand, then slap up left hand to a good sidepull.  Work up slopers on the arete until you can stand up and topout.    There is no real crux, but every move is fun.

name: With Confidence
description: Start on the jug of Fido and pull up with one bad foot and balance your way up the high topout.   Great climb to do before you try Fido from the bottom, so you don't freak out toping out Fido   Don't use the sucker jug out right.   Great Balance moves up good rock, but don't fall or you'll be sliding down the hill, pad and spotters too.

name: Babylon
description: Bablyon climbs the shallow, left leaning crack to the left of Lakeside Jam.  Using sharp crimps and precise feet, work through the V4 boulder problem without any protection and gain the ledge at about the midpoint.  Plug some gear and finish up the finger crack on Swift Premium.  A sketchy lead for sure.

name: China Dragon
description: Start up Lakeside Jam, then after the first rest break right up the right-angling crack, a few hard moves lead to a pretty good rest in a hand jam with good feet.... Then, another couple of hard moves in a desperate thin hand crack lead to a jug and more moderate climbing to the cliff top....    Challenging crack climbing on nice rock with a nice setting by the pond.... Now, if we could do something about the bugs....

name: China Dragon Right
description: This is another short route worth a run when the popular routes are taken or if you are entertaining a group on a busy day...    In my guidebook it is given 5.9 but the China Dragon finish is about the same difficulty as Lakeside Jam... The direct finish is harder so maybe they had that in mind...    A few steps right of the start of Lakeside/China Dragon there is a nice flake you can layback off the ground... A nice rest halfway up then either continue up left on another flake/crack to the top of Chins Dragons crack and on to the summit at 5.7... Or finish on an independent line straight up on a crack (harder)...

name: Lakeside Jam
description: The vertical line up the middle of the cliff.... Start on the twin cracks from the base, climb these to a good rest 10 to 15 feet off the ground.... Then, climb up and left to a ledge.... Rest again then up the offwidth to the finish.... The top is wide, so bring a big cam, run it out, or just top rope it....   Very fun if you know how to jam...hard if you don't....

name: Little Hungover You
description: A very sweet addition to this crag.  Great gear, great movement, and an obvious line.  Start up the fingercrack of Swift Premium for a few moves until the crack of Babylon crosses your path and exits out left beneath a small roof.  Undercling the edge of the roof and make a crux reach to a good hold in the crack to your left.  Mantle out left and follow the crack to its end.

name: Scramble-rama
description: On the left side of the cliff, there is a slabby face with cracks and holds making for an easy beginner route.... When I'm guiding and folks are having a hard time with the slippery climbs at the lower slab, I throw a rope down this and it gives them an easy way to make progress and learn a little about slab technique and cracks at the same time....

name: Swift Premium
description: Follow the slopping ramp with a crack from the left end of the crag heading up right to the rest ledge on Lakeside Jam (5.7).... Then, up the perfect and way too short finger crack above you to good solid holds for the top out....   Harder than it looks and more fun, too.... The climbing is cool, it's just over too quick....

name: Filling the Void
description: Climb the tall finger and hand crack left of the arete. A tricky press gains the crack. Get some good locks and make a few moves to good jams. Try not to look down.

name: Reaching Out
description: Climb the right to left facing crack. Start at the  beginning of the crack and climb straight up on small edges to get established. Using the small edge of the crack and smart feet continue to traverse left high off the ground until the shelf. Go straight up at that point. There is a V6 variation which starts at Filling the Void and follows the shelf into the crack.

name: Tinder Reviews
description: Great line up the obvious steep arete. Small edges and rails hold your attention as you climb delicately to the top and a nice hold. There is a sit start option as well. Consensus is V5.

name: Alive and Kicking
description: At the right end of the wall and tucked into its own little alcove, this route follows prominent features to tackle a short roof that might prove to be exciting for some.  Start to the right of the corner and traverse left on the large horizontal until a flake diagonals up and right.  Follow the flake out the roof to its end and mantle up onto the somewhat scruffy face above.  Finish up the face slightly left to the trees.

name: Crack to Nowhere
description: The defining moment of this climb is pulling the tricky, bouldery roof that you'll encounter halfway up.  The protection is good for the crux, but the 15 feet of slab afterwards might have you feeling a little nervous.  Starting at a head high block at the base of the crag, mantle up then follow a thin crack and face holds up to a ledge.  Traverse left for 15 feet beneath the roof until you can get into the handcrack with a small tree above.  Use whatever trickery you can to get over the roof and onto the face and low angle slab above.  Follow the slab up to another ledge beneath the 2nd roof, then climb the crack and flakes to the top.

name: Double Crutch
description: Climb a steep crack to a horizontal crack heading out left to the edge.

name: Finger Lichen Good
description: Wanting to work on your footwork?  Do you like climbs with an early crux?  Step on up.  Starting beneath the rusty bolt with a short overhang, surmount the overlap to stand up on the face above.  Climb straight up towards the left end of the first roof and aim for the slab with a left arching crack.  Follow the slab up and slightly right until you're at the second ledge.  Move right to the tree and the crack through the big roof and finish as for Crack to Nowhere.

name: Overhanging Corner
description: Use the same start as Seaver's Direct.  Climb face, step off right to a ledge, and traverse right to the overhanging corner.

name: Overhanging Corner Direct
description: Make a long reach over a low bulge and "struggle to get standing" (1995), then top out via O.C.

name: Overhanging Corner Right
description: Head up right of O.C.D. to a block.  Traverse 10 feet left, under Overhanging Coronary, to the corner and the end.

name: Overhanging Coronary
description: Ascend Overhanging Corner Direct to an awkward stance under a roof, which is a jutting block split by a crack.  Out this to the summit.

name: Seaver's Direct
description: 30 feet right of the regular route.

name: Seaver's Folly
description: Start at base of the thin crack running up the slab and follow the crack to a sloping stance below the roof. Step right and up into the wide crack at the base of the roof. Traverse right until the crack ends at a small shelf jutting out under the roof and mantle up. Finish up the easy slab to a large tree.

name: Beginner route
description: Start on a platform of roots and dirt... Head up the smooth slab (crux) to a good flake... The climbing eases up and heads to the left to finish where the book finishes....    Perhaps this was once a good beginner route but i find the beginning to be very slippery and not fun for new folks... If you have a little slab climbing under your belt its not too bad... As with most pawtuckaway routes the years of TRing have taken their toll on the friction...    A good lead if you are just getting in to leading trad but know how to climb pretty well... The first moves don't protect but once you get to the flake its all good gear...

name: Clingon
description: This chimney route is great for beginners having an issue with the slippery feet of Pawtuckaway. In my opinion this is the easiest route that Pawtuckaway has to offer. I would recommend this route for the youngsters.    I always wondered the name of this route and found the name on the net after my young daughter completed it. Let me know if it goes by any other name.

name: The Dike
description: Follow the Dike up the cliff. this is a good route for beginners.

name: Open Book
description: This climb is a great moderate for beginners (top-rope) who want to challenge themselves and competent leaders who want to scare themselves with the runout near the bottom and towards the top.    Start off the ground at a small corner and a polished high foot, smear your feet up the polish with a pinch on the left arete of the corner and your right hand desperately searching for a good hold, get into a standing position and make your way up to the very small gear placement about 15 ft off the ground then make your way up easier ground and eventually a slab to the top.

name: Pete's Tree
description: The obvious line on this section of the cliff, the crack system between the Flake Route and The Dike.  It starts on the right-angling hand crack (a few face moves are more fun.)  Climb up to a comfortable rest with a vertical seam leading to the left-angling finger-crack system.  The crux is getting into the second crack system, but it is easily protected with a medium nut or TCU.  Find the good feet on the face and finger locks.  The route is classic except for the last 5 feet which are just a little akward.

name: Pete's Tree Right
description: Not a bad climb and it doesnt see as much use as the "mega classic camper routes" so on a busy day you can still get a rope on it...    Start by getting up on a big detached flake/boulder leaning on the wall then climb the bulge above where the angling dike crosses it... That bulge is the 5.7 crux and once you are over that its a cruise to the top... There is an easier variation going around the bulge to the left...

name: Pete's Tree Right Variation
description: A fun and easier option to Pete's Tree Right.  Climb up on nice features and fairly good feet.  Pop up into the little scoop and step up to join up with Pete's Tree Right.  Avoids the more difficult start over the bulge.  Leadable but no protection at the start until joining Pete's Tree Right and some thinner crack features on that route.  Nice TR option for another short climb from a tree anchor above Pete's Tree.

name: Pete's Tree Variation
description: A fun friction slab finish to the classic Pete's Tree.  Climb the initial crack on Pete's tree to a stance at a triangular cutout at feet level.  Follow the shallow left leaning trough up to the left to finish near the top of the Flake Route.

name: The Flake Route
description: Although not actually named the Flake Route, it serves as a good description.  Jutting out from the scooped face of the boulder is a large block that happens to be a great starting hold.  Pull on and follow the crimpy flake up and left until you get your hands on the large slopey shelf.  Unfortunately, this is where the holds run out and the problem ends.  Drop off, or better yet, link into the start of the crack to the left and highball up the boulder.

name: Basic Crack
description: Climb crack to the right of Flash it, Fist to fingers

name: Flash it
description: Climb the left most slight overhanging and  diagonaling crack.

name: Leave the Lobster
description: Bolt line in the Middle of the Microwave Slab.     Climb the lower slab, under the first bolt, on good holds to the first horizontal break, place gear or just clip the 1st bolt and mantle up on to the slab and follow thin flakes and edges to the 2nd bolt and 2nd horizontal break. Mantle on to second ledge and proceeded thru the upper half of the route.       The upper portion of this route tends to seep long after it rains, around bolt 3 to the top.

name: Microwave crack
description: Work parallel cracks to the first horizontal break, step up and into crack jam, lay back crack to the top.    Belay from tree or build gear anchor in the block just behind the tree.

name: Stegosavius
description: Start at the face, right of the pillar, then ascend straight up to join the 5.5 face variation of Microwave Crack.

name: Won Hung Lo
description: Friction up lower slab to a small ledge. Work small inside corner crack to the top.    var: 5.8+ PG: At the mid way point one can traverse right to either join Leave the Lobster or Microwave Crack.

name: 4 point play
description: Sit start matched on a rail below the lip, pull on and slap to slopey jugs then mantle up on a cool step.

name: And1
description: The direct mantle of "free throw", make one or two moves out left and you're Scott free.

name: Break on through
description: Same start position as for "riders on the storm", except after pulling off of the ground make a hard match on the arete, then break on through to the other side of the boulder and climb it on the adjacent blank face and arete. Pretty core intensive  compression line that ended up being way harder than I thought it was going to be. Again, if the sit start feels impossible, I'd say try a little harder or just do it from the stand, it's fun!

name: Brick James bitch
description: Sit start the prow of the brick boulder and dyno to the slopey lip. Short and powerful massive lowball.

name: Bricky Ricardo
description: Awesome over hanging right to left traverse, sit start far right and ride the slopers to an exciting move near the end!

name: Don't trust the weather
description: Sit start matched on a jug, I ended up having my right heel matched as well, above my right hand. Make a big move out left to a flat textured rail, a couple more compression moves then you just gotta top her out. Sweet moves on cool holds I just wish it was further off of the ground.

name: Free throw
description: Another sloper traverse, neighboring "painless traverse", it's a little easier and not as good in my opinion. Sit start at the right end of the boulder and traverse left, it felt more natural to mantle immediately so that took some value away. Finishing move is pretty unique though!

name: Jake The Snake
description: Monster lowball. Sit start with a sick left hand perfect incut crimper and rh on some bs sidepull. Mega right dropknee, hit a rh crimp around the bulge (or gaston). Then massive (crux) stand up move to a sloper, match and desperate awkward mantle to glory. Classic.    I'd give this V3-V7 if I could because it's completely height dependent for the crux move.

name: Milestoned Arete
description: Sit start with right hand on the arete and left hand on the blank face, pull up, match the arete and find a way to the top!

name: The Outsiders
description: Sit start the Milestoned Arete but on the right side, pull up to some crimps and slab your way to the top up and right. There is a good crimp far out right.

name: The painless traverse
description: The name says it all, sit start far left with a left heel hook and left hand on the sloper lip, right hand in a massive undercling. I'm usually not a huge fan of traverses but this one surprised me with how fun it really was, climbed way differently than I had imagined.

name: Pharaoh
description: Climb the face of the pyramid side of the slab city boulder

name: Pyramid potion
description: Sit start matched on the arete and some technical body positioning will allow you to climb up the pyramid with ease. Awesome triangular feature for the finish.

name: Riders on the storm
description: Sit start with left hand high on the arete and right hand on the blank face, fight a barn door and make a cool move to a 2 finger pocket on the face. From there use a lot of core and some fancy foot work to top her out. If you're having a hard time getting of the ground then just do the stand, it's well worth it and probably a v3!

name: Start diggin'
description: Sit start matched on a good crimpy sloper under the belly of the boulder with a sweet left heel hook, pull up and slap to slopers and fight your way to the top.

name: Casual State of Mind
description: This line starts with a left hand pinch and right hand gaston and utilizes a high left start foot.  Shoot up and left (crux) to either a sloper or the shallow crescent shaped dish.  Look for the distinct horn out right and your halfway there.  Finish up with more positive holds and toss in in a sloping top-out for good measure.

name: Dead Center
description: Start sitting with both hands on a crimpy flake. Pull up to another good crimp (crux) and continue up the face on edges and rails to a slopey, but relatively straight forward top out.    An excellent and aesthetic problem on great rock.

name: Half Baked Over a Puddle of Mud
description: A rising arete traverse similar to Arrow in the Trailside area, just a tad higher and longer.  Sit start at the base (when the lagoon is dry) and follow the nicely sculpted arete up and left.

name: The Northern Gentleman
description: Stand start the arete with left hand on a good pinch on the arete and right hand low on a crimp, pick some feet and climb the arete making use of the crimps on the face with your right hand.    Pretty good climb, with a bit more traffic the crime should be a bit less sharp.

name: Pace Is The Trick
description: Start sitting with hands matched on the lowest incut crimp rail. Bump the left hand to one of two crimp gastons and then make a powerful pull to another small crimp rail that is a long ways away. Perhaps use a small knobby pinch to get there. If you make it that far, mostly good holds await. Follow these to an easy, but somewhat dirty top out just right of the tree.    Sharp, powerful, crimpy- in no particular order.    With some traffic, the top out will clean up nicely.

name: Right To Life
description: Sit start just left of the arete, to the right of Dead Center, on obvious opposing sidepulls.  A shouldery move off a bad crimp and possibly a worse intermediate gets you to better holds for a brief respite.  From there a techie sequence on crimps up the face takes you up and left to the initial lip.  Two more moves that can feel a bit desperate when you're tired gains an easy top out.    Great movement on perfect crimps.    Beware loose rock on the highest left crimp on the route.  Most of it has broken off but be warned.

name: Trending South
description: Start standing at the base of the faint corner/dihedral feature with the left hand on a sloper/sidepull and the right hand on a high crimp. Follow the shallow dihdedral on slopers, crimps and edges until rock leftward to gain the lip and an easy top out.    A good problem with fun movement and perfect rock.

name: Assisted Living
description: A great highball arete that requires a bit of technique and balance.  Sit or hang start at the base of the arete on the right and follow it up and left with heel hooks, smears, and arete pinches.  When it finally goes vertical, look for the jug out left and topout.  Be careful not to fall off into the tree.

name: Aurora Borealis
description: Essentially a topout problem that starts with a high jug on a slightly overhanging face and mantles over the lip.  Grab the jug, paste a high foot, and make a move to a good hold over the top.  Now, just figure out how to roll over and run up the short slab above.  Great moves and lots of fun that will clean up with a few more ascents.

name: Banditos
description: Although not as good as Counterclockwise, this arete provides a more moderate means of enjoying the classic moves up the face.  Sit start the right end of the face at the arete and try not to roll downhill.  Pull off the ground and immediately make a big move up to the jug.  Using a good high toe or a left heel hook, make another big move up to the left hand crimp jug, then go for the lip.  Topout.

name: Beginners
description: This might be the best practice trad pitch in the park. Quite easy and secure climbing on face holds and finger jams with perfect gear options all the way.    Yeah, it would be nice if it was longer but we can't have everything... Where would we put it.

name: Body Grind
