description: One day you're walking along and a chipmunk challenges you to sit start the lip of this cave and somehow wind up on top of the boulder.  He says if you fail that he'll take your nuts, but for whatever reason, you decide to give it a try.  After grunting and grinding and boulder humping pleasure, you succeed.

name: Call of the Wild
description: Sit start with a good flake and make cool moves out left into the other jug flake. Move up on crimps and throw out left to the arete. If you make it this far that was the easy part. Keep bumbing up the arete and use a tiny sidepull crimp with your right hand to get your feet up. Now make a desperate move to a far crimp out right on the slab. Snag this and hike your way up to the top!youtube.com/watch?v=cudxNHi…

name: Cornered
description: As you walk by, you'll find this one hard to miss.  A wide crack runs up the back of this right facing corner and gets steeper the higher you get.  Scramble up to the ledge and past the tree, then layback the crack and stem your way up.  It looks far easier from the ground, but it's fun while it lasts.

name: Counterclockwise
description: Three desperate moves followed by a classic romp up technical jugs to a high topout.  Stand start in the middle of the face with a crescent shaped crimp sidepull and poor feet and establish yourself on the wall with difficulty.  Shoot out right to a slopey knob feature before making a hard match.  Make another big move out right to a great jug, work your feet, and use a high left crimp to aid in sticking the lip.  There is a hidden two-finger pocket at the lip if you need it.  Try not to forget your footing and topout.

name: Counterclockwise Direct
description: Stand start matched on a sidepull flake as for "Counterclockwise", smear and pull of the ground. Make a burly move out right to a decent sloper crimp and step up on a good left foot. Stand up high to a good undercling feature. Once in control of the undercling, step through and reach up to a decent sloper crimp. From here gather some mustard and top her out!

name: Crash Pad Surfer
description: An obvious line with a large juggy flake that unfortunately ends before topping out the boulder.  Sit start at the base of the flake on the left, heel hook, and traverse to the right where the holds grow less positive.  Make a difficult crux move up and right to gain a gaston crimp rail, then stand up to the horizontal break with the help of a tiny crimp.  Drop off.

name: Cuckoo Clock
description: Stand start with the left hand on sidepull crimp in the seam, and the right hand on a sloper gaston. Pick a foot and pull off the ground. Rock over leftwards to a big sidepull flake. From here go up right hand to a dish on the lip. Get a high right foot and figure out how to topout! Bulletproof rock and fun movement!    Avoided the sidepull flake out left makes the problem slightly harder and more reachy.

name: Dirty Little Rabbits
description: Sit down, grab a good jug on the lip, toss a heel up and pull off the ground.  As you hang, you move a hand out right, and hope you stick to the sloper.  Further right you find a little edge and you pull your heel closer.  Another sloper lets you bump to a good hold on the arete, and then you mantle.  Done.    This short sloper traverse is fun albeit low to the ground, just watch your head if you blow the crux move.

name: The Finger Crack
description: When you look at this striking, thin finger crack that leads up a clean short wall to a very cool hueco-like dish at the top, the question is do you grab a rack or boulder it?  As a trad line it is probably a bit short, but as a semi-highball it shines.  The landing is flat, the balancy crux comes at mid-height, and the various finger locks are all bomber.

name: Flying Ninja Kick
description: Although it doesn't look like much, it climbs well with some fun moves.  Start low with both hands in the horizontal and make a move up and right to a shelf feature.  Use a higher crimp out left and a heel hook to reach the tricky hidden jug at the lip.  Now just top it out.  Barndooring off usually results in this climbs namesake.

name: Funny Games
description: Short and stout and fun with slopers.  This problem is essentially a direct finish to the start of Hairway to Steven.  Sit start with the right hand crimp sidepull and the smeared left foot.  Power up to the slopers and match before making a big move up and left to a small sloper right of the crack.  Get a foot up on the start hold and try like hell to stand up before running up the slab above.  Fun!

name: The Good Book
description: Do not miss this climb!  While the Horn may take the prize for best trad climb in Pawtuckaway, this beautiful inside corner runs a close second.  Start out atop a ledge with two jugs and large feet that will help you get established in the corner.  Employing a variety of techniques, layback, stem, smear, and jam your way up the climb with the use of the hand crack in the back.  Remember to keep your heels down or your calves will scream and if youre not used to smearing you might feel a tad insecure.  The crux comes early at a small roof, followed shortly thereafter by a lesser crux getting past the remnants of a tree.  Every move is easily protected, but above all, the entire climb is enjoyable, aesthetic, and fun.  It catches afternoon sun, dries quickly (the ledge at the base may not), and is the perfect excuse to get away from the crowds.

name: Hairway to Steven
description: Brilliant movement on slopers and a horizontal rail lead to a tricky topout.  Sit start on the left arete using a right hand crimp sidepull and a left foot smeared on the arete.  Power up to a sloper, then match before making the crux moves right to the rail.  Follow the rail to the arete, grab a hidden sidepull and eye the sidepull jug that will help you topout.  A spotter will keep you from rolling down the hill if you blow the top.

name: Harvest Moon
description: Friendly, slopey jugs, a flat landing, and a high topout combine to make for a very decent climb.  Sit start at the base of the arete on the right side of the boulder and move straight up using big holds.  Once you gain the lip, prepare for the crux and don't accidentally topple over the frontside of the boulder.  A great way to stretch out.

name: I Saw an X-Ray of a Girl Passing Gas
description: A bizarre, adventurous, and entertaining climbing experience that will hopefully get better with a little more scrubbing.  Walk up to the chimney, introduce yourself, and figure out how to establish yourself inside of it.  Look for a high crimp on the left side.  From there, squeeze upwards towards the light.  The crux is getting off the ground and I felt like a corkscrew.    Hard to grade this one.  Go on, give it a try.  An upside down sitstart might be possible.

name: Instant Hippie
description: This climb doesn't look like much, but it climbs amazing despite the fact that the top needs a lot more scrubbing.  A few fun juggy moves lead to a tricky slabby topout.  Sit start with a right hand jug and a low left hand sidepull.  With a decent right foot and a left heel hook, pull up and make a big move to a left hand jug.  Pinch the arete, then follow the arete up into the ferns.

name: Lady Sniff
description: Two big moves, good holds, and a lack of feet to start make this a worthwhile little problem.  Stand start with a horn-like jug in the high horizontal crack.  Pull on, get your feet set, and fire straight up to a hold that looks better from the ground.  Match, get set again, then make a move up and right to a good incut before topping out.

name: Magnificent Bastard
description: Once there was a little lowball roof hiding beneath leaves and dirt and now it's a worthy testpiece.  This climb might have a Napoleon complex from being so small, but it's fierce, agonizing, and tons of fun!  The beta is simple.  Sit start and mantle.  Use slopey fingertip seams and slopers and press your way onto the top of this thing.  It's well worth every bit of skin you give it.

name: Rainy Day Women
description: Surprisingly fun, although this problem may suffer from occasional seepage, so if it's dry, give it a go.  Grab some pads and a friend, sit start at the base of the crack on the right end of the wall and follow jugs up and left.  The landing is flat, the holds are good, and its high enough to be a bit of a thrill.  Enjoy.

name: She Had Armpit Hair Like a Wookie
description: A fun little climb with a variety of movement.  Sit start at the base of the right leaning arete with a good jug.  Pull up, lay back, and follow the arete until you can rock over onto the slab on the left.  Run up the slab for a couple of moves to the top.

name: Smiley Face
description: This excellent problems climbs the left hand side of the face (just right of a tree), starting on a good, hollow flake at 5 to 6 feet. Make a big move to the juggy rail above. Then traverse right along that rail for a few moves and top out left of the crack.    One of the best problems at Ridgeline. Worth doing on the way to the Den.    Note: The starting hold has broken a bit, making it a little harder than it originally was.

name: Western Esotericism
description: Although this short problem doesn't look like much, it provides a fun one move wonder. Sit start with a right hand undercling sidepull and lefthand sidepull edge. Pull off the ground with a small right foot. Square up and smear the left foot and toss up big to a jug three and a half feet up. Match hands and pull over the lip!

name: Wild Wild West
description: Sit start matched on a good hold and figure out a little bit of footwork trickery. Pull off the ground and move up to a sloper shelf. Match hands and climb leftwards using some small edges. Grab holds on the arete and execute a big move out right to a sidepull. From here move the feet up and finish up a mental crux slab topout! Great movement and a great adrenaline rush!

name: 3 Guppies in a Plastic Bag
description: A much harder version of Oblivious to Danger that avoids the holds out left and tackles the dihedral.  Start as for Oblivious to Danger and pull up into the undercling.  Cross to a gaston in the dihedral, then figure out how best to get into the good high undercling.  The lack of footholds complicates things.  Stand up to the decent hold at the lip and finish the highball top arete/slab to the peak.

name: [Redacted]
description: Three quick moves and it's over.  Yeah, so it's a bit short, but it's actually worth the time.  Start sitting to the right of the tree with a right hand sidepull and a strange left hand crimp with large feet.  Pull up with difficulty and snag a crimp before matching.  Toss straight up to a good jug and topout.

name: [Redacted]
description: This climb starts directly to the left of High Tech Issues on a crimpy flake at about head height. Moves right to a tiny edge of a sidepull and from there up to the High Tech Issues sidepull and top out as for that.    Was told this was a project back in November, its not on here or the new Pway guidebook. Just saw its possible FA on Saturday 12/27

name: A Swift Kick to the Head
description: Doesn't the name say enough?  This friction-dependent one move wonder is over way too quickly, and while the movement is fun, it would be a whole lot better if it led to more climbing.  Sit start the slightly overhanging short face with your right hand pinching the arete wherever you can find enough friction to hold on.  Pull on a crimp sidepull with your left hand to help control the inevitable barndoor.  The feet are obvious.  Now just pull off the ground and dyno to a good jug up and left.  Stick it, and topout.

name: A.T.P.
description: Start in the wide crack as you would for Creatine Buffer. Using a really weird start, make a hard move to get established in the crack. Once in the crack move left to the shallow dihedral and work up top the top.

name: Anasazi
description: A one-move dyno problem on the Balance Boulder.  Start with a sidepull crimp for your right hand and a slopey crimp seam for your left.  Get your right foot on a chip practically underneath the boulder and dyno (crux) to a horn at the lip.  Top it out.    Keeping the right foot on can be tricky for some.  At one point I wound up on my back underneath the boulder.

name: Annticipation (aka: Campfire Tales)
description: Start sitting with both hands on a horizontal jug in the blackened slightly overhung wall with good feet down and right. A back-step can setup a long reach for a left hand layaway and some more feet setup after that allow for a swing right to a sloper (crux) that sets up the exit moves using great crimps.

name: Arch Nemesis
description: This route is powerful.    Sit start on jugs and work your way up and left up the arete. This route is interesting and has some very slippery holds (which is a real rarity for Pway). Good foot work and body positioning will get you to the top out jugs.

name: Atlas
description: Start sitting on a smaller boulder (about 2 feet high) on a left undercling and a right crimp, with a left heel hook and a right toe under the boulder.  Bump up left to another crimp then make a powerful move right and then up, or just go straight up from the crimp.  Mantle the finish.    Used to be harder until the starting crimp broke and got bigger!

name: The Baby's Cry
description: A beautiful, striking arete that is both deceptive and frustrating.  It's about as much of a V3 as the dyno method on it's neighbor, the Crimp Problem, which is to say they're both probably sandbagged or skewed in favor of the taller climber.  If you're up to it, have a seat at the base of the arete with a right hand crimp and your left hand pulling on the arete.  Bump up the arete a few times, grab a terrible crimp with your right hand and decide if you want to keep bumping up the arete or dyno to the juggy lip.  I'll leave it to you to figure out the footwork.

name: Ball and Chain
description: Stand start on good holds just right of the tree and climb up the black rock to an easy top out. I found the crux to be right in the middle of the route. Generic climbing.

name: The Becoming
description: Great moves up a right leaning arete and scoop.  Start as for Iced Tea on the large undercling and pull out right to a crimpy sidepull in the scoop.  Work your feet across good edges and follow the arete up and to the right either by hugging the arete and small slopers out right or by laying back with a high left foot.  Harder than it looks.

name: Brain Supreme
description: This climb is a must if you want to complete all the highballs on the Big and Tall boulder, but otherwise you might want to walk past like you always do. The route is typically covered in pine needles, but if you are good on your feet and can keep a calm head then cleaning off needles as you go won't be a problem. From a stand start work up the blunt arete to the left of CREAM. Avoid working right and finishing CREAM. With some committing smears you will figure out a sequence to the top.

name: Brett's Problem
description: An odd yet semi-fun problem that climbs a short arete via a sloper, a crimp, and a heelhook/mantle.  Woohoo!  Sit start at the bottom of the arete with left hand on a great hidden sidepull and right hand on the jug.  Pull off the ground and heelhook the right start hold.  Mantle until you can reach up right hand to the sloper.  Free up your left hand to grab a crimp on the arete, then work up to the positive lip and topout.    May result in a cramping calf muscle.

name: Bring the Ruckus
description: This problem is a great one.    Start sitting just beneath the right facing corner with a very high right foot and a couple decent hand holds. Cam your knee in and get a great knee bar that you'll use through the next 2 moves, make a cool move to a hold out left then work that knee bar and grab the strangely oriented pinch up high on the bulge with your right hand. Grab sloped holds above, look around for feet then finish up the easy slab.    Downclimb the slab for the dismount onto your pad.

name: Call & Response
description: A fun rising traverse over a not so great landing.  Sit start or pull on to the rock at the base of the flake.  Follow the sloping flake up and left until you gain jugs near the arete, then topout straight up on good holds.  The first few moves are the crux, but a fall will usually result is bouncing off of a rock at the bottom.    With a spotter, there is nothing to worry about... unless they don't know how to spot.

name: Cause for Commotion
description: When reaching the top of the hill, one of the first lines that people notice is this sharp arete next to the trail.  There used to be two good flakes on the left of the arete, but both have now ripped off and the scars are quite obvious.  The quality of the line may have improved now that any loose rock is gone, but it doesn't climb quite like it used to.  Sit start with the good rail down low, or use an optional crimp out left along with the rail and pull up to the arete.  Grab the edge that is a foot lower than the flake used to be and work your way up the arete with techy feet to the jugs at the top.

name: Classic
description: start standing at the crack and smear on the wall to get off the ground. after that just climb up and have fun! There isn't too much of a crux on this route it is pretty strait forward. the finger jams that are on it are fantastic and the only bad thing i can think of the route is that it isn't long enough. i definitely recommend this problem. it was a blast when i did it and its great confidence booster for the not so skilled boulderer. the only wierd part of this route is the descent... it can be a little tricky

name: Cosmic Cam
description: Slopey feet, a few crimps, and fun moves.  Stand start at the nose to the left of the crack with a left crimp and a right sidepull.  Pull up to a set of decent crimps before working into a high, juggy flake.  Follow the better holds over to the flat top.  Might feel hard until you figure out the beta.

name: Crack Em Up
description: This line follows a thin seam up a steep slab. Start by getting as high as you can on the ramp below the boulder face This allows you to reach up to a 1/4 pad right hand crimp and and a left hand in the seam. A very high left foot gets you onto the boulder problem and into the increasingly widening seam.  Work up with the seam and with decent feet.  You can finish straight up the entire face or cut slightly left. (the rock cuts in to a roof below the face so this seemed to me, a very natural approach to the line).

name: Cream
description: A big, long highball flake with good holds the whole way.  This problem provides the highball topout for the problem Sauce (V3), but is plenty fun on it's own.  Grab hold and climb straight up, but keep your head, since the topout is high.      Watch out for an occasional snake on top.

name: The Creatine Buffer
description: Sit start on the wide crack and move up and right following the wide crack. The start is the crux and there are a few ways to pull off the ground I used a heel hook and a low right hand and and a left hand in the crack, but its up to you.

name: Crimp Problem
description: If you don't like crimps, try another problem, but the chalked-up shape of a crescent moon on the rock might suck you in for at least one try.  Grab the crimps in the moon, pull on the wall, and dyno for the lip.  Sounds easy, right?  Alternately, pull on, then gaston a right hand below the lip before popping for the top for an easier time.    For the full value, a soft V6, sit down on some decent crimps and crank into the stand start on the moon.

name: The Crimp Problem SDS
description: This is the sit start to the popular Crimp Problem. Start sitting with left hand on a positive crimp and right on an under-cling. Get you body position right and pull up to the small smile shaped crimp that marks the start of The Crimp Problem (V3).  Then finish up that problem.

name: Cut Up
description: A very deceptive crack climb that reverts to face climbing near the top.  Stand start with hands in the crack and pull up to get established.  Follow the crack for a few moves until you can stand up into the large black undercling and reach for a welcome jug.  A few more moves will deposit you on top.  Although given V0 in the guidebook, this felt far more difficult.

name: Debbie Does
description: Even shorter than its neighbor Midget Porn, this two move problem is for those with a short attention span.  Sit start with a left hand sidepull and a very small right hand crimp.  Pull off the ground and pop to a good slopey shelf.  Make one more move up and left to a jug and topout.

name: DJ Dan
description: Start sitting with a good left hand jug and a right hand pinch with a slopey right foot.  Pop up to the right hand jug (crux) and stand up to follow a few thin crimps up the low angle face.  Jugs at the top will assist with the easy topout.      The stand start is V0.    Not bad for something that rarely gets climbed.

name: Dopeman
description: This problem starts sitting on a good jug.  You maneuver yourself under an overhang, moving right, with your feet on a slick rock slab and try to stick the severely sloping crimp-rail with both hands.  Then, for the crux: you shoot a hand up, blindly grasping a very sloping, but nicely textured open hand grip.  More hard moves ensue, possibly making use of a heelhook to the right, eventually moving up to a nubbin that is a couple of feet above the sloper.  Moving left can reveal more sidepulls.  An awkward move to gain the slab finishes the hard part.  The slab above is still not trivial.  THIS PROBLEM IS AWESOME!

name: Double Deuce
description: Start standing with a low foot and two opposing crimp underclings. Establish yourself on the rock, find a higher foot and jump to the lip. A fun, goofy little problem. Worth a few attempts while you're here.

name: Elephant Back
description: Squat start on a rather crappy sloper/crimp with your feet on a huge foot hold. Work your way up the slopers find little delicate feet and a good sloper/crimp get a decent foot and reach for the huge jug for the end get both hands on the jug and get a foot up on the top of the boulder and rock over and up to the top     A little foot has broken off so it might make it a little harder to get your feet along with you without campusing across to get the good feet

name: Fanciness
description: Start with your right hand triangular crimp and your left hand on a blocky pinch with a high right heel and a low left foot. Make a series of compressiony moves with tricky feet to the slopey topout.

name: Flight
description: Sit start on the left side beside some boulders that get in the way.  Follow the flakes up and right. Top out (same as Call and Response) above the crappy landing.

name: Gadgetry
description: A short, burly problem.  Start crouched on a rounded arete, sitting on a not so comfortable stone, with a low crimp and bad feet.  Make a few hard moves to the right on crimps and then up on slopers.

name: Ghost Stories
description: I found this while doing Annticipation aka campfire tales. Start on the left arete with your right hand in a slot crimp and good feet. Go out right to a crimp (next to the one for campfire tales) figure out some beta to get to the left jug and then top it out. Top out is a little strange at first but once you get it its good. Stay on the face going around the arete is much easier. This shares none of the holds with campfire tales except the crimp.

name: Gimme Crack
description: This is a harder face problem then "The Hueco Problem" so if you like bouldering slab then you must do this one. Crux is getting off the ground it may not hurt to think palm... once established on the rock move up to better holds and a fun top out. The large crack used for the down climb is just to your left, if it is used it is a V0.

name: Golden Arches
description: Want to climb the concave, slightly overhanging face of the Old Gold/Arch boulder via a large slopey flake, a couple of crimps and a cool sidepull?    Next to Arch Nemesis, this problem has some of the best movement on the whole boulder and while the moves are obvious, it's not as easy as it looks.     Start low with a left crimp and a right hand pinch on the flake. The starting foot is for the right foot and it's the little chip in the corner formed by the flake. Pull up to a good gaston divot for your left hand and then grab the obvious right hand crimp. At this point your fingers might say "No!". Crank on the crimp to get your left hand up to the half moon shaped hold and figure out how to grab it. It's far worse than it looks. Get a left foot on the start crimp and stand up to the sidepull. Now just get to the lip, either with a scary little jump or a delicate couple of "princess" moves with your feet. Top out with a mantle. Solid rock, fun moves, and deserving of more traffic.

name: Hemlock
description: This is a short route but has a enjoyable move or two.    Sit start at the lowest point of the arete, using a heel make crux moves to a good jug. Once at the jug traverse the lip until you reach the big boulder and top out.

name: High Tech Issues
description: Big moves on crimps lead into a gaston, a pocket, then a jug before topping out a ways off the deck.  Like the sound of it?  This problem is rarely touched and probably a whole grade harder than it's neighbor, Maxim.  Sit start as for Maxim on the flake and the crimp, make a big move up and left to the next crimp, then figure out how to get into the giant gaston up and left (look for a hidden right hand crimp up high).  Using the gaston and a sidepull to the right of it, work your feet and cross up to the pocket before grabbing the horn of Maxim.  Top it out.  Techy, tricky, and really good.

name: The Hueco Problem
description: This is a fun face problem involving a tricky start. The crux is getting off the ground and getting your feet to stick. Start next to the right arete right in front of a small circular hueco (the origins of the name) use the hueco or other small hands and put your feet on and beg for them to  stick from here move up the face on increasingly good holds.

name: Iced Tea
description: Stand up into the large obvious undercling with your feet smeared on the sloping ledge below.  Reach up high for side-by-side crimps, work your feet, and snag the juggy lip before topping out onto the table-like summit of the boulder.  Trust your feet.

name: Ill Saint
description: An improbable and impossible looking face with tiny crimps and bad feet.  Start sitting on a dish-like hold at the lip of the overhang with a high right foot. Power up right hand to a slopey hold before moving through some microscopic crimps up to the topout.    A hold has broken near the top.  Condition of the climb is unknown.

name: Jailbait
description: Sit start the short overhanging face. Make a quick move to the lip and topout

name: Jelly Belly
description: An easy climb that uses the arete of Cause for Commotion on the left and the arete of the down climb on the right.    Stand start just to the right of Cause for Commotion near a tree and climb up the well feature face using the arete's on either side to an easy top out

name: The Jitterbug (aka Try Again)
description: A classic, albeit short, little climb that is more about technique than pulling power.  Stand start in the middle of the face with a good left hand crimp and a right hand undercling pinch.  Work those feet to stand up into the undercling and reach up into better holds.  Finish up to the top on easier terrain.

name: John's Problem
description: Start sitting in a bit of a hole. I started with my left on the large pinch and my right below it on a crimp/edge. Piece together a way to the top and avoid hitting the boulder behind you. Trickier than it looks and surprisingly powerful.

name: Just Stand Up
description: Super short problem, the problem it the short slightly overhanging arete. Sit start with one foot on each side of the arete, and hands on the obvious holds. Work feet around to left side then stand/mantle to top. Good for beginners to practice sit starts

name: Labrador Dreams (aka Tin Arete)
description: A slopey lip traverse.  Sit start with both hands matched on the lowest part of the lip.  Traverse left on friction-dependent holds until you can grab the back arete and mantle over onto the face and topout.    Due to aggressive brushing, the holds are becoming more polished.

name: Lip Sync
description: A short sloper problem.  Sit start to the left of the tree with a left hand undercling and a right hand on the sloping arete.  Pull up with good feet, follow the arete to the left and pop for the juggy lip.  Topout straight up.

name: Little Nicky
description: Cool lil climb if u get shut down by everything else.    Probably been done a million times, but didn't see it on here.    Start on monstrous flake, put a foot up high, balance on the flake and reach for the top. Arete off.

name: Maceo
description: Start one foot right of the tree on small crimps and a good really high foot or pick one of the smaller feet lower, grab some real small crimps and move up to a good hold. Like many of the face problems on this boulder the first move is the crux.

name: Maxim
description: The very high problem at the top of the hill, kind of in a small courtyard of problems, opposite Gadgetry.  Sit start with small crimps and cramped small feet.  Make a powerful move up to the left, traverseto the right around the faint arete, then up and back to the left for the 20+ foot topout.  After you grab the small horn the holds are pretty decent, but it's still pretty scary, dramatic, fun and hard.

name: Minion
description: This problem is so much better than it looks.  Although it is rarely climbed, it can be a lot of fun.  Start with a good left hand crimp and a bad seam for your right hand.  There is a good foot underneath.  Bump your right hand up to a better hold, then dyno up and left with your left to a slopey lip.  Campus over for a few moves until you can get your feet back on, then topout straight up.    Clean off the lip before you attempt it.

name: My Brothers Wife
description: Sit start on the large flake left of the arete. Pull up and get a large left foot then stand up and climb the arete using the good crimps and slippery feet. The top out is a jug.   Easier if you are tall.

name: No Pads Necessary
description: Stand start right at the waters edge, with an awesome hour glass shaped left hand start hold and good feet. Throw up right up to a great two pad jug and move feet to set up for the next 5 or so moves.  Trend left along great holds with good foot holds & smears.  Don't fall at the start or your be swimming in round pond!  Super Fun, just do it....

name: Nope Man
description: Sit start with the left hand on the starting rail for the right start of "Dopeman" and the right hand a few feet to the right on a square cut sloping pinch. Pull off the ground and move up to a blind hold before grabbing one of several options for the lefthand. Once here figure out how to reach high up to a sloping edge before standing up and balancing into a comfortable position utilizing a thumbdercling. Once here reach up to the sloping lip and grab a nice jug horn for the topout.

name: Oblivious to Danger
description: One of the best highballs in the park, this obvious face climb sat either dormant or unclimbed until late summer of 2011.  Start on two good edges to the right of Cream and pull up to a slopey undercling in the dihedral.  Stand up and reach for a left crimp (this move is shown in the photo), then bump your hand up the underclings.  Slap up right for the decent hold at the lip and decide whether or not you'll commit to what comes next.  Pull up to a sidepull crimp on the low angle arete and rock up onto the high slab.  Gather your nerves and continue up the arete to the top.    For the full line, tack on the two move sit start, or traverse in on Sauce for something much more difficult.

name: Oyster's Ridge
description: Sit start next to a rock on your right and pull up onto the good holds. Throw left hand out to the slopers and match. You have one good foot underneath near the ground. Bump right hand up to the better sloper and throw left hand to the far crimp, then bump left hand to the gaston crimp near the arete. Now for the crux! Right heal up on the bottom sloper and power your way straight up to the tooth undercling. Grab that get your feet good and work straight up.   youtube.com/watch?v=d8Utl7A…

name: Rock On
description: Listed as a V0 in the guidebook, but it doesn't feel like a V0, maybe after 20 repeats.... Highstep nubbins, or lean on your arms and use nubbins off to the side to start. Getting off the ground and reaching for the far up pinch was the crux for me.

name: Satan’s Half Sister Ali
description: From a stand climb the tall arete.

name: Sauce
description: Start sitting way low to the right of the obvious crack/flake that ascends the large hill-top boulder.  A few burly pulls lead to very sharp holds, which finally become jugs.  Whew.  The rest of the problem is more fun...layback or jam the fantastic flake twenty or so feet to the top of the boulder and imagine you're Michael Reardon soloing in Joshua Tree.  The easiest downclimb is off the backside.

name: Tin Can't
description: Did you use to wrestle in High-School? Good at mantels? Did you crush "Boulder-X", or cruise the top out of "Ride The Lightning?"? This problem is just waiting for you to tick it off then! My brother says he would pay to watch footage of this being climbed!    Sit start as for "Labrador Dreams" and make a move or two left and top out, or top out from the start holds. a bad heel and a hard press will get you onto the slab and eventually to the big hueco like pocket up top, where you can dip your raw fingers in crystal clear mosquito-larvae infested water.

name: The Tin Can
description: Sit start on two slopers to the right of the "Labrador Dreams" start holds. There is also a large undercling feature that might be useful, but is unnecessary. Traverse rightwards using some foot trickery to reach the good incut crack, mantel and top out with ease.

name: Toolshed
description: Just to the right of Gadgetry is a short arete squeezed by a block on the right. Sit start and make very awkward move off the ground, the crux being not swinging and touching the block to your right. After the start enjoyable easy moves lead to the top.

name: Unchained
description: This line is a full value V1, the holds are solid and the exposure comes quick.   Briefly follow the black streak as for Ball and Chain and then break left to climb the face. Keep trending left to the (apex) highest point of the boulder where you mantle the topout.

name: The Wet Spot
description: Sit start on a good left hand flake with a small nub for your right hand. Pick some feet and make a deadpoint to a good crimp up and right and do the fun top out.

name: The Whip
description: A big time classic! This line was one of the first climbed in the park. Though originally rated 5.9 as a trad line, today it gets most of it traffic from boulderers and is considered solid V2. Either way its a bunch of fun and a big tick for anyone who considers themselves a local.     Climb the obvious layback crack on "The Whip" boulder from a sit or stand. Cool moves lead to the crux at 2/3 height. The crux is a classic commitment move. No thank you jugs to toss to or hidden sidepulls awaiting discovery. The crux demands a committing step up on a good foot to reach an excellent finger lock. From the lock move up carefully on good holds and top out.

name: Wreck Em
description: An alright climb with decent movement over a disgusting landing.     Start on some decent holds down low then climb straight up following the arete.

name: X.L.
description: I'm surprised this route hasn't been posted already. Though not as popular as other highballs such as The Whip, this route offers good climbing on a striking crack. The commitment level is comparable to The Whip and over a worse landing. Start on a jug at waist height and stand tall to establish the crack. Cool moves lead to a committing smear to reach a great fingerlock. Once you establish the lock, take a breath and reach the lip.

name: Beer Crack (A.K.A. General Sherman)
description: Climb the obvious Finger tip crack on the boulder

name: The Outlet
description: Start sitting at the left side of short arete and climb up right to the top

name: The Arrow
description: this is a really fun little warm up for overlooked. on the same boulder as a V12, sit start down and right of a painted arrow on the rock. go hand over hand up the arete to the top. really really fun and a confidence booster for those who cant do overlooked

name: Bio-Dome
description: Stand start with a shallow incut flake for the right hand about six inches below the lip of the roof. Grab a lower gaston crimp for the left hand and pick from a choice of footholds. Bare down hard on that right hand and pull on to the wall. Make a big and committing move out left to a positive dish that will allow for the proper compression in order to hold the foot-cut.  Once on this dish, figure out how to match hands and then execute the same press/ mantle as for "Dome Piece".

name: Chunk O Blitz
description: Terrible slopers and difficult compression moves make this the most difficult problem in the Trailside Boulders.  Sit start with the left arete and a sidepull for the right hand.  Pull off the ground, then slap and squeeze your way up the aretes to reach a sloping jug and an easier topout.  This problem seems to keep breaking and is affectionately known to some as "Chunk O Shitz".

name: Current Reservation
description: This one is often lost in the shadow of it's famous brother Overlooked (v4). Even though we always have time to take another lap on one of the best problems in the park (or world) it can take a while to get curious about the other lines in the same area.    A pretty fun climb provided you have the requisite reach. The first move is rather large and might just be a show stopper if V6 is anywhere near your limit.      After the big initial undercling move navigate a crimp or two, a cool sloper move then find your way to the top.     Take care with pad placement cause the landing zone isn't perfect.

name: Dome Piece
description: Start on two sidepulls with a high foot and make a big move out of the roof to the lip.     The top out is more moderate. Don't blow it or you have to do that HARD first move all over again.

name: Fleet Street
description: This is the problem I've been looking for... I love the idea of off-width roof climbing but never tryed one... It also has kneebars and hand jams, its no wonder it went so long without being climbed, haha...    Start in the back of the cave as far as you can manage... Lay on your back and stick your feet up the crack... Do a sit up layback the edge with your hands and try to keep your back off the ground (its very low)... Scoot right like this till you can stick a kneebar and then a good hand jam... Get a nice stem rest before finishing up the hand crack above... the position is such that if you are not a solid crack climber you might be sketched...    I cleaned some chossy rock out and lots of spider webs... i still need to clean the top off a little better but its pretty much good to go...    follow the crack back down and right to get off...    id love to hear you opinion of the grade since ive never climbed this style problem before...

name: Fresh Supplies
description: Careful on this one... A bit heady with its crux at the top... I do need to clean it a little more but its good to go for sure...    Start off the chockstone in the chimney climbing the 15 foot wall above to a smooth top out... DONT FALL...

name: Gale Force
description: Starts with one hand on either side of the trapezoid shaped rock, then follow up on to the boulder above it using the arete, and ticked hold for right hand, stick right foot out and top out is cake.   Rock did not look clean and there were no chalk marks, but if this route goes by another name or already exists please edit*

name: Goldfinch
description: An absolute banger. Start with hands in the obvious horizontal crack and smear feet, make a big move to the jug on the lip. It is possible to dead point, but for style points go for a 3 points off dyno. Cross right hand onto a sloppy jug and move right and left hand out to sloppy crimps. Throw up a heal and rock over into a committing move to a sloppy crack (watch out for the small tree), the rest of the top out is easy, but don't fall.    The top out of this route needs to be further cleaned, still very doable but it definitely gets sketchy   This was formally named "Pretty girls with poor eye contact"

name: It's Only Tuesday
description: A great low ball mantel problem... It ended up being way cooler than i thought it would be...     Basically you start sitting with your choice of slopers and a few crimps... i went more right but you can do what works for you... mantel up and grab the arete and run up the slab...     do it... solid rock solid moves...    Here is a little video of the first ascent...  youtube.com/watch?v=wED-3ZL…

name: Looking Lonely
description: If you really like lowball boulder problems you will love this one... Otherwise you need not try it...    Sit On the ground at a good crimp in the left hand and a little something in the right heel out left... Mantel with a couple of bumps with the left hand...    I thought it was pretty fun if a bit short (understatement)...

name: Mermaid off the Port Bow
description: Sit start with hands on a good flat ledge... Mantel up and climb on easy crimps up the arete and top out...     A good beginner route other than the landing... Pads and spotters should make it safe...

name: Mr. Todd
description: This is really just a direct finish to Mrs. Lovett... Note quite as much fun as that route but still good... I found it to be a little harder...    After the first big move to a good hold top out straight up eventually gaining a good hold out right...    Again climb it and suggest a grade...

name: Mrs. Lovett
description: I cleaned this line out from under tons of dirt, and small plant life not really knowing how well it would climb... i was very happy with the outcome...    The problem climbs right to left along the lip of a cave following a series of different holds, heelhooks and fun moves to a nice top out right before you run in to a tree...    maybe a hard lower start could be done but this start works fine for me... try it and suggest a grade...    Video link... Check it out!  youtube.com/watch?v=bEvl9wH…

name: Only a Cardinal
description: This one is only 2 or 3 moves long...    Start sitting or squating on OK holds and make one or two powerful moves to a sloping hold above move a little left and throw a heel to mantel...

name: Overlooked
description: After bouldering all across the country this remains perhaps my very favorite problem. It is both technical and powerful and involves a greater variety of holds and movements than most boulders.    An amazing boulder problem involving crazy beta and full body fitness. Start under the lowest roof in the back of the cave on two hueco pockets in the roof with fairly poor feet but they are there. A few choices here but most people end up in a bat-hang in the wide crack then switch to a heel-toe-cam and make a cool move to the lip of the roof. The holds at the lip seem bad but feel good when you are on them. Sink your fingers in to the crack and pull the last crux getting out from under the roof to better holds and the top.    A really fun climb. Beta intensive.

name: Overlooked Right
description: A variation to one of the best climbs in the park. Very core intensive, and a slight mental challenge. This line features some incredible movement and should see more traffic.    Start as for "Overlooked" and match the lip via some heel-toe cams. Instead of going up to the crack, traverse right on the lip and get to the arete.   Find some good holds and take the foot cams out and core up!    Get a left heel cam on the lip and keep going up the arete with the left hand until you get to a good hold.    From here release the heel cam. Hold the swing over a poor landing and make a very committing move to a jug at the lip.   Next, keep it together and figure out how to top out on good holds.    Really good, might be a classic.

name: Parabola
description: Sit Start on a good edge and pick which of the many feet are possible and make a tough toss to the lip. Then top out.    This is a route that I found with chalk already on it. I dont know if it already goes by another name but let me know if it does and Ill be happy to change it.

name: Pirelli's Purse
description: The starting hold just begs to be used so i cleaned up a bit and its pretty fun... It does share a few holds with Shadows,Everywhere but it has its own line for sure...    Start hanging on a hold in a scoop 5 feet left of Shadows,Everywhere (v3)... Throw a heel (as there are no good feet under the roof) or campus the first move... Then mantel on to the slab and climb to the top staying left of the crack...

name: Poor Albert
description: This one may have been climbed before but i cleaned a good bit of moss off of it... I have only done the stand start which was fun but not too challenging... The sit start will go at a much harder grade and will be more fun i think...    Climb the middle of the slab/low angle face avoiding the escape to the arete out right... delicate climbing on tiny holds...

name: Shadows, Everywhere
description: This line is much like Fleet Street (v3) but a little cleaner and less spooky... I cleaned out a few stubborn chock stones to make the OW work... It may have been climbed before as it was cleaner than the rest of the rock (but not clean by a long shot) but never the way it goes now since i removed the stones from the crack...    I think more people will like this than Fleet Street... Give it a try...    There are, im sure, many ways to do it but i went with the same beta as Fleet Street For the most part with a few changes... I start laying back the off width with feet on the wall in front of me (you dont get to start laying down on this one), then stuff my legs in the crack and make a few moves to the right... Gain a crimp with the right hand and move your legs to get a knee bar... You can lean out left and work the knee bar up till you are able to stand in the corner... Up the corner above to the top (Same top as Pirelli's Purse (v1+)...

name: Shaving the Pope
description: This one starts with the first few moves of Only a Cardinal but continues traversing the slightly sloping lip leftwards... This makes the route so much more fun and the top out a little more moderate so i dont think the extra length changes the grade... Top out at the same spot as for Welcome to the grave...

name: She Gave Me Mono
description: An interesting one-mover problem with a neat pocket for the start.     Start with the little mono-pocket (it's possible to stack fingers in it, or get a thumb catch and turn it into a pocket-pinch), and the slopey crimp just to the right. Find some feet, pull off the ground and make either an outrageous throw around the mini-roof to the top or go to the lip of the roof then bump to the top. Either way your feet will probably cut at some point. Match and top out.     There used to be a better crimp but it has broken.

name: Toby
description: another worth while addition to the growing area... This is turning out to be a moderate climbers/warm up sanctuary...    This problem would be v1 if the starting hold    weren't so crimpy and or if there were any feet worth a damn under the roof... I decided to call it v2 cause you start by hanging full weight off of a small crimp and either throwing the upside down heel or a powerful campus move to the sloping lip... Once at the lip its more like v1ish as you press up on to the slab and smear your way up the easy but blank slab above...

name: Trailside
description: A nice lowball that never gets done but i like it better than the Arrow which is right around the corner at a similar grade...    Sit at a couple of good start crimps with one good foot and throw right for the arete... Bump that hand then top it out with ease...

name: Welcome to the Grave
description: I'm pretty confident this hadn't yet been climbed... It was very dirty when i found it and no an obvious line...    Start sitting in the dark corner underclinging the crack above you with your feet on the face in front... layback and kneebar (if you like) to gain a nice undercling pocket... Get another hold on the boulder that was over your head and find your way right to gain a cool moderate top out...

name: Bean Pole
description: On the far left end of the upper cliff (seperate from the rest of the cliff a bit) there are a few more often overlooked cool routes... The first one i was drawn to was the Bean Pole crack... A slightly inverted super thin fingercrack... For someone who loves fingercrack climbing (me) this one begs to be climbed...     Climb steep thin fingers to a horizontal break (crux) put in some gear and finish... A short but serious climb...

name: Beanstalk
description: ​Scramble 10 feet up to the left to a big bouldery ledge then move out onto the slab and head up.  I’m sure the patient could set up a TR anchor, would be nice to clean all of the pine needs.   This is less climbing than Jack and The Beanstalk but just as much falling.

name: Bishop
description: Essentially a three part climb, this route starts up a thin crack surrounded by jugs on the face and deposits you on a ledge.  From the ledge, climb the interesting blocky tower to its peak before stepping across the void to climb the short crack in the wall on the right.  Pull over onto the top and you're done.

name: The Chimney
description: This route is so perfectly "crafted" that it seems gym-like in that all the holds are just too perfect.... Basically the chimney on both side is peppered with protruding brick-like holds making what would be a tough chimney in to a walk...A good place to learn basic chimney technique....

name: Climber's Corner
description: This corner is often wet, which is nice 'cause then you have an excuse not to lead it.... However, when it drys out, it is a great climb to test yourself on....I've climbed harder grades, but this is one of the most strenuous leads I've done.... Be ready to sweat....    Starts out as a nice, hand crack leading up to a low roof the hand crack turns to off-width and the fun starts.... Climb out of the roof with awkward positioning and slippery feet till the crack turns to hands again.... A stance will let you catch your breath.... There seems to be options at the top, but I follow a thin finger crack and a few face moves to the top....

name: Desperate Depression
description: Until I re-cleaned this route and tried the moves, I didn't realize that its name was actually a description.  Desperate is right, especially if you're sick enough to lead it.    Starting nicely up a crack/flake and moving right to a jug, this climb turns stout and crimpy in a hurry.  From the jug, match on a crimp/sidepull and enjoy the hard sequence past a 3-finger single-pad gaston, a half-pad undercling, and a slopey pinch to gain a jug in the depression.  This is also your last gear placement if you're on lead.  Move left and make a large move to a crimp before hiking your feet and attempting to find a sequence that will get you to the lip.

name: Devilish Diversion
description: Balancy crimp start (crux) to a ledge 7 1/2 ft off deck, undercling, follow flake out right.    This is rated 5.6 in the 1995 Pawtuckaway guide, but is more of a boulder problem

name: Diagonal
description: Climb a somewhat chanenging bouldery start to gain the crack then with hands in the crack and feet mostly on the face make your way up and to the left... Eventually making a mantel move on to the top... The gear can be a little tricky but its all there once you get past the starting moves...  I think this route is better to lead than TR due to its traversing nature...  [2018 NOTE/Update- See COMMENT below that reads in part:"There's no good pro before the crack now that the flake is gone; there's a shallow pocket to the right but my .3 blew out of there when I fell. "  R Hall ]

name: Double Chin
description: This is a great crack to hone your hand jamming skills.... As with many upper cliff cracks, if it was longer it would be classic....    Start awkwardly to get around the tree...Actually you will have to use the tree at the start if you want it to be close to 5.6.... After that, hand jam past 2 small roofs (hence the name Double Chin) and up more jamming and some killer face holds to the top of the cliff....    Belay from the top on gear or from trees far back from the edge....

name: Double Jam
description: Jam and grovel your way up the double cracks using hand and fist jams and even butt jams to gain a rest ledge on the right.... Climb back to the left and place your big cam then fire the last few  feet....    A fun, beginner climb good for getting folks to think outside of the box....

name: Far Out Jam
description: A great route to grovel on as you ease your way in to the world of off-width cracks... The handcrack on the first half is killer as well...    Jam and layback your way up the nice handcrack while the wide crack looms above (do you hear the theme music from jaws?)... As the feet thin out and you get to the halfway mark you find things getting wider and more desperate... Arm-bars, knee-jams, hand-jams and a good serving of thrutching will get you to the top in no time...    have fun...

name: Far Out Jam Right
description: A few feet right of Far Out Jam is a large arching flake that rejoins Far Out Jam for its offwidth finish.  Pull off the ground with large, juggy hand holds and good feet and climb up until the flake becomes a pumpy undercling system that you can follow to the left.  Pay attention to your feet and hopefully you are not so short that you are forced to use the small slots beneath the undercling for hands.  Transferring from the underclings into the offwidth feels like the crux.  Now just grovel on up to the top.

name: Friction Slab
description: Direct start of Beanstalk - go right up the flake feature then shoot straight up and finish out on the same line.   Don’t fall.

name: The Horn
description: Slippery feet and good locks....   Start up the steep, finger crack using some polished feet outside  of the crack.... A tricky crux section of locking and perhaps a layback move will get your foot on the "horn" feature and an OK rest.... One more crux guards the top out involving a high, right foot, some power, and grace....    A very important climb for me....Probably the first "hard crack" I climbed, and it is still teaching me more than 10 years later...Climb it!

name: Kiddie's Korner
description: A short, somewhat grungy route that most people just walk by. Can be worth a stop if you're in the area.    Jam the short hand crack that ends at a leafy ramp with some trees on it. Wipe your hands on your pants when you're done. Can also be done as a moderate highball boulder problem.

name: Max Factor
description: This climb starts the same as No Answer and then follows the obvious tips crack out right. The climb is an eliminate as the original guidebook instructs to stay off holds in the large crack out left. Once you are committed to the tips crack though the line becomes natural and the use of holds out left isn't compelling. Top out on a nice ledge.

name: Ms. Pac Man
description: Take a chimney climb, add in a finger sized crack for gear, an optional bouldery start as well as a face climb finish, and you've got a fun route with a great view that hasn't gotten much love in a lot of years.  Near the left end of the Upper Cliff before reaching the trail to the top, a detached block creates a left facing chimney.  A couple of boulder ledges abutt the trail directly below.  Scramble up the ledges for the direct bouldery start (or bypass by walking around on the right).  Pull into the chimney with the aid of the finger crack and the arete of the block.  Plug and play up the chimney and crack, exit onto the top of the block and step across to the ledge.  If you stop here, you miss the great view from the top.    To continue, albeit runout, climb straight up the low angle, flake covered face to a cluster of trees.  Rig an anchor and enjoy the view of South and Middle Mountains, Round Pond, and North Marsh.  Belay here and walk off left.

name: No Answer
description: So the old guide book gives this 5.6+... I would feel like a bad person calling it that since i can run laps on .9s and .10s and this one gives me trouble... Feel free to give your vote if you think its a walk...    Anyway, climb the hand crack leading up to the off-width above... That is the hard part... I found that grunting was helpful...

name: Obscene Phone Call
description: Much harder than it looks! This route was once rated 5.6 but now is a stout 5.8....    The trick is knowing where to jam cause there are too many choices.... If you get the right locks, it will feel like hard 5.8.... If you don't, it will feel 5.10.... Practice makes perfect on this one, and that's what I like about Pawtuck crack climbing, hard work pays off and you will be a crack head in no time....    The crux is at the bottom, it eases quite a bit at the halfway mark....

name: PB & J
description: This short & spicy crack that climbs out a bulge and then up an arete is a decent intro to the grade, although it doesn't appear to get climbed too often.  A good scrubbing might make it more appealing.  Layback the crack to start and pull up right to a good crimp with your feet underneath the small overhang.  Work your feet up and follow the crack while you consider pulling an unprotected crux to a good stance.  Plug your "thank god" gear, then scramble up onto the ledge.  Finish up Double Jam on the left.

name: The Roof
description: This one seems to get harder every year...Though it is graded 5.7, I still feel like I'm going to fall every time I do the first moves.... The foot holds have been polished to a marble finish by years of use, you're welcome for the excuse, now forget the grade and climb the route 'cause it's still fun no matter how slippery the starting feet are....    Climb the crack up under the roof place a few good pieces and follow the crack out right and up to a ledge, find the good feet.... A great climb with good gear....  You can also exit the roof to the left or straight over at a harder grade but the right finish is the most fun....

name: Short Stuff
description: There are some decent holds inside the crack, not too many face holds. Just wonderful awkward off-width jamming.

name: The Start
description: I don't know who put the minus in the grade of this route but they were either wicked tough or really mean.... By modern standards, it would be given a 5.9 without second thought, but then again what do modern climbers know compared to our elders, how to sew cracks up with gear then talk about how hard they are.... OK, I'll shut up....    The next crack right of Double chin is The Start and the start is the crux.... Perhaps 15 feet of bad-sized, jam cracks (for me it is wide fingers/thin hands, purple or green Camalot.... I find it hard to do anything but slide out.... When you get it, though, it feels great and after the first part you gain a good face hold and better jamming to a stance, and more moderate climbing to the summit....

name: The Tramp
description: Follow a hand to fist size crack up a right facing ramp/corner feature. Good face holds and stances for placing gear. More of a stemming problem than a straight crack climb but a variety of moves made this really fun at a very mellow grade.  Easily top roped from a gear anchor in a crack above the top out.  We cleaned the crack out of years of dirt build up and a bit of lichen of the key face holds so hopefully it see's some more traffic and stays a bit cleaner. A great little climb.

name: Yellow Zonkers
description: This is the impressive off width to the left and around the corner from bishop. An incredible route with some tricky moves around the half way point and some good old fashion thrutching to make it up. this route is walked right passed usually and I hope will get some more play because it is a blast, bloody elbows and all.     I TR'ed it but it could be lead by the brave of heart. With one piece in the middle it would definitely be an exciting fall from the top.

name: Fleas
description: Either stick clip the first bolt or climb up easily to a flake and make a reach to clip the bolt. Climb the face trending left then right past 5 old 1/2" bolts. Surmount the block(crux) and boulder above then clip an anchor. 2 More bolts will lead you to the top/trees if you want to climb the extension. Rappel off or hike off Left w/ caution.   This climb is rated 5.7 in my old paper back guide...however due to lichen and some hidden holds I say it is 5.8+.   This area as mentioned does not see much traffic but if your up for something different at PWay...give it a go..

name: Huckleberry Hound
description: Climb a rounded arete on good crimps, past 3 bolts. Stand on the ledge and look up to the final bulge. Clip the bolt and pull up through the overhang (This protects with a number 4 (Optional)). Climb easily to the trees.

name: Black Jack Crack
description: Black Jack Crack is the best trad route at Rumney. Never mind that some people boulder the thing.    Locate the 30 foot tall splitter crack on the west face of the huge boulder. Follow the crack through various sizes to a crux at the top. Though it receives a boulder rating of V2, most people prefer to bring gear rather than face the offensive possibilty of a 30 foot grounder at the crux.

name: Hour Glass Crack
description: Not as clean and sweet as Black Jack Crack(5.10d) or even Queen of Spades (5.12a) but perhaps a good warm up lead or highball V0.    Climb the broken rock to the right of Black Jack Crack past many good holds and a few solid placements to the top of the boulder. The crux is the last move and the mantel so place a good piece and fire it.    Build a belay from gear at the top, then toprope Black Jack Crack cause everyone knows you wouldn't be on this boulder if it weren't for that crack.

name: One Eyed Jack
description: Highball boulder problem? Scary short trad climb? Fun top rope? its up to you.    This line climbs just right of a boulder problem called Rain Man which comes out of a damp cave facing the Umbrella Boulder. While the crux is a little awkward and not too memorable the top 2/3 of it is really fun and serves as a convenient if a little nerve racking moderate finish to it's lowball boulder problem neighbor.    Start by cruxing out up a shallow corner/ramp feature on sharp rock this section is a bit height dependent as you are moving toward a jug up and left. The sooner you can reach it the easier the route will feel. After you get the jug climb up the face to good holds and a small stance. after a nice short break here climb up and slightly left to a good spot to mantel on to the top of the boulder. With a rope the top out isn't too bad at all but with a spotter and a pad way down there it could get your heart racing a bit.

name: Queen of Spades
description: Here is another route that will never be a Rumney classic but I'll be damned if there isn't some really fun climbing on it. If you like techy crimping on not too steep rock (just slightly overhung) go for it. It does earn its R rating due to thin gear in the middle but the cruxes have ample gear for sure and there's always the old toprope style.    Start on a low rock next to the base of the boulder lean out and grab the thin crimps and commit. You can step out on to good feet (the whole route has really good feet) before making a move to good holds. Enjoy sequency moves on possitive holds through the middle section of the climb. This is where the gear is thin, many options but nothing great, I found a number 2 stopper to work well in the thin vertical seam to the left. At the last obvious good holds reach up and place gear in the pod/crack above and crimp and footwork your way through the crux to the finger lock finish before manteling to the top. there are many ways to do this last section look around at all the holds and see what works for you. If you are on toprope you might use the pod/crack for your hands but on lead I recommend gear in it.

name: Rain Man
description: A fun cave hidden between a boulder and a small cave just behind the umbrella boulder. Fun route that's fairly short and may be soft for the grade Start in the cave move out to a flake and then hit the crux which is a fairly good crimp out right then pop up to the jug above your head, then hands up to good holds on top. Top out and jump off. Pretty straight forward when you see it. This is a newer route and the holds as still a little rough on your hands, this route is ultra fun because of the inverted climbing for a few moves.    "Today i cleaned a route that climbs to the right of this problem and meets up at the jug "finish hold"... My line continues straight up the boulder to a pretty moderate though dangerous top out (5.8 or 5.9)... So though i didn't intend it, i have created a finish to this problem if anyone wanted to climb it..." this was from Lee this is an option if you dont want to jump off after the drop off... Thanks lee  Other possible variations going out left from this problem...looks hard!!

name: Suicide Kings
description: I admit that some of the routes I've cleaned at Rumney amount to licking the bottom of the ice cream bowl. Though i enjoy them they hadn't been missed they were just waiting for someone who cared. This one I feel has Much more to offer the average climber. It is now the second best line on this rock and worth doing for sure either as a trad route a top rope or a moderate high ball problem with the hardest moves happening in the 1st 15 feet.    Climb the crack and ramp system up and left to a stance where you can place good gear and execute the fun top out.    Video link: youtube.com/watch?v=dlBS72g…

name: Zeppelin
description: Stand start with two opposing crimps. Pull on to the wall and make a hard move up to the giant horn. From here, figure out a way onto the slab and venture up the highball, trend leftwards. The crux may or may not be the first move. Rehearsing the top on rope would not be a bad idea.

name: The Block Party
description: Sit start on the horizontal seam, make a long move up to the cool sloper/pinch hold, arrange your feet around and move you left hand up to the pod in the vertical seam, possibly using some small holds along the way. Then go for the top. The crux is opening move through establishing in the pod in the vertical crack.     The sloper/pinch hold is one of the coolest holds in Rumney bouldering. It feeling like gripping an oversized softball.

name: The Block Problem
description: Sit start low in a sort of ditch with a crimpy left hand and a slopey right hand, from here move up to another sloper then get in a stance and dyno for a shelf that as a decent lip, from here work up through easier holds to meet up with The Cock Block and top out there.

name: The Cock Block
description: Sit start just left of the The Block Problem (V9). Using a jug with your right hand and a sloper and a thumb catch with you left. Make a long move to a good hold straight up. Match then move way out right to a rail then top out. I found the key to this problem is having your feet in the right place think heels and back steps.    The route felt soft but it is listed in the guide book as V6 so I posted it as the book has it listed.    Up and right of the umbrella boulder.

name: Knock Your Block Off
description: The best line on the block. Squat start with both hands on a good jug  on the right side. Pick some feet out right and make a large move to the clam shell crimp. Heel hook by your hand and bump your right hand up a series of slopers until you are in a good position to float your feet to the left. Once settled make long move to the left arete and squeeze up to the top.

name: Ripping the Bull
description: Stand-start with a high small right hand sloping crimp to the left of the arete, and the left hand on a bad sloping left hand crimp lower and left on the face. Pull on with a large foothold and dyno to the lip of the boulder. Grab the slopers and topout easily.

name: Unblocked
description: Unblocked is a logical variation to the Block Problem, using as much of the Block as possible for a fun and natural feeling line that climbs great and is definitely not an eliminate. Climb the Block Problem into The Cock Block, and then finish as per Knock Your Block Off/The Block Problem. A right kneebar pad will go a long way in making the start feel reasonable.Could be pretty easy for a V7 as far as fingers go. It’s core intensive and sustained.

name: Under the Block
description: Start low with a right hand slot undercling under the roof and the left hand on a small mini pinch/ undercling on the lip. (It is used as a foothold in "Knock Your Block Off". Once you figure out where you want your left foot, the right hand start hold doesn't do much. (Think heel-toe cam!)    Figure out how to get off the ground and make a few hard moves up on good holds. Find what beta works for you and get established on the slab(Crux). From here take your time and reach up to a jug in a crack and match. Make one more committing lock off to a jug on the lip.

name: Fifty-five and a Brewski
description: This is a fun steep overhanging problem that suffers from an awkward start. Once established on the wall it climbs well though.  Start sitting on a small pedestal-like block under the overhang and figure out a way to pull on. The right hand starts low on a crimp and left hand slightly higher on another crimp. Pull on and make a few hard moves up crimps before tossing for some slopers on the lip. Don't punt the top.

name: Mr. Crawley
description: This route is a very short right slanting crack. It is comprised of only a few moves, but it is a lot of fun. sit start at the base and make one hand move up the crack then pop to the top.

name: Petroleum Jelly
description: Sit-start the steep overhang lip/ arete of the roof, climb up the arete to the apex and top out. Fun, friendly, dabby and awesome.

name: The Rift
description: Start low in the wide crack with good feet, work your way out of the crack jamming and laybacking to the crux move to the lip.

name: Vaseline
description: This one may be an all-time low. It may not get much tighter than this folks. If you thought sliding under the overhang for "Dab Control" was a bit much, you're going to be awestruck when you see this one.  Sit-start matched on a nice aesthetic zig-zagging rail on the steep 60 degree overhang. Figure out a way the positioning to pull on and make a hard unwind to a good hold found on the left arete/ lip of the roof. Stay tight and match the lip before continuing up a few more moves to top out at the apex where another arete comes down to meet the lip.  This problem suffers from a large slab behind it, but if that slab wasn't there, this climb would have had potential for one of the best that the Black Jacks have to offer.

name: A Fist Full of Silence
description: A rad core intensive one with some unorthodox foot movement!  Stack three or four pads and lay-down in order to get an "Adam Ondra toe-cam" on the large vertical rail. Stay tight and core-up to get off the pads. A full-span left foot hand match gains the large rail From here try hard not to punt the stand-start. There is campus beta and good heel beta, pick your poison!  An incredible line that may create a few giggles!

name: A Fist Full Stand
description: Stand start with a left hand vertical pinch on the lip and a right hand slot on the steep overhang. Find some feet and pull onto the wall. Figure out a sequence to match and eventually fire for the arete out left. Figure out a way to stand up and continue up the arete a few more moves then top out.

name: Beginners Layback
description: This route is a sit start but it is plagued by an often wet sit start, so unless you like sitting in mud, just start low and move the few moves up using the crack in the dihedral. This problem has a few face holds out to the right which can help somebody who is struggling, but a fun way to approach this problem is to use only the crack.    Not a great problem, it would be good if the sit start wasn't in mud and it was about ten feet higher.    But what the hell have fun on it.

name: Heartfelt Sorrow
description: This is a one move wonder that climbs the face just right of the B!&ch.    Stand start on some crimps then lunge for good holds right of the arete. Campusing seems to be the way to go

name: Heartless B!&ch
description: She can be tamed...    A powerful, technical line of slopers on clean solid rock with a good landing. Beginners may struggle with this one.    Start on an obvious "launch pad" grab some crimps and stand up onto a small edge. Now the fun begins, layback right onto slopers then swing under the overhang. Move right utilizing a range of techniques (Knee Bar), with few options for feet. Grab the arete get some feet then move around the arete. Reposition hands and feet, stand up then mantel up to the cleaned face above to top out.     ...But doesn't give it up easily!    Descend via Beginners Layback

name: Wide Crack
description: This crack is beautifully obvious, and amazingly fun. Stand start using the crack and some face holds to the right, but use the crack to full advantage by arm baring and putting your feet in the crack. When the left wall starts cutting into the crack move up and right to the top, be careful this can be sharp at the top. The crux of the route is pulling over the top, so be spotted well please.    This is a great problem for anyone at all levels and a great first boulder problem (it was mine).    Careful the top is sharp in places.

name: The Big Dill
description: Climb the pickle on the that shoots out from the top out the Short Trail Boulder, the route is on the right arete of the giant pickle, I have not gotten on this problem but it looks tough comprised of crimps and some slopey features.    Sketchy landing so be careful.

name: Despised Icon
description: This route traverses the back side of the boulder, starting on good underclings, and traversing right on a sloping ledge that gets better as you go when you get to the end of the ledge move up on good holds and top out. The crux is dependent on your climbing style. For me at 6 feet the crux is when going from the sloping rail to the jugs that lead to the top out. The feet are weird and the sloping rail is made tougher because it slopes slightly down hill.

name: I.P.A.
description: Sit start with a hand and a foot on either side of the sharp arete(the feet on the left side of the arete are really small)  pull up and establish yourself on the good shelf from here use the arete and face holds to move up and right topping out on a huge jug above a very dirty crack. You can get off the boulder on the backside of the boulder.

name: The Long Trail
description: On the face that faces the trail. There are two cracks that run parallel to each other use these crack and climb the very short problem anyway you would like, the sit start makes it harder. This face that this route is on is not a vertical face it is less than vertical but ultra fun. This is a great route for beginners or to play around on with friends making eliminate routes.

name: Multi Purpose Face
description: This is a fairly tall route that  has an weird boulder behind it that you do not want to fall onto. This route climbs the face up through the curl at the top without using the arete, the crux come half way up when you need to get really wide feet but once you have the wide feet it is a breeze    There are plenty of other cool variations on this face that can make it harder or easier.

name: PBR
description: Sit start on the arete and make powerful moves to the top. Crux is the first move, moving your left hand into the good slot. Although the rest of the moves are no gimme either.

name: Chocolate Chunk
description: Stand start eight - ten feet left of Hitting The Road on an obvious flake, work this flake until the arete starts trending right, while moving right on this arete there are small feet but the hand holds are big enough it is very possible to smear for this rightward traverse. There is no defined crux just easy fun climbing.    Good for beginners to get adjusted to the heights.

name: Hitting The Road
description: On the right side of this boulder just left of the tree, climb up on a technical face, it is straight forward just has small holds due to the nature of face climbing. Great top out. Very nice slab climbing. If you fall it may be wise to push out and left a little so you do not grind down the slab or fall into the tree.

name: Billie Jean
description: This route is fun easy route that climbs flakes to the top. These flakes may break so climb easy on them. Sit start on a good crimp one foot right of the tree and climb straight up, using the flakes and a fun undercling. The crux is either the start or the top out but the cruxes are not overly challenging.

name: Bobby's Arete
description: Start sitting below the arete with the right hand on a juggy shelf at 4 feet and the left hand on a small gaston crimp/edge. Work your way up the arete to a long move to a small pinch at mid height. Finish out with a few more longish moves on decent holds to a juggy hold at the lip and an easy top out.    Good movement on high quality rock!

name: Bobby's Problem
description: Sit start on left hand jug and a right hand crimp. Make a long move to a good pocket, move you feet around and get into the business. Move left hand to a crimp and move right hand up right to a three finger crimp. From here traverse left to the quartz jug in the crack and tackle the high but safe top out.

name: Dirty Diana
description: This route is dirty, well maybe thats an understatement...    Anyway it is a lot of fun on huge jugs. Start sitting on two huge rails and move up and right to the big holds. Keep moving up on big dirty holds. Top out straight up. The crux is the first move because even though the holds are big they are the smallest on the route.     I will try to clean this in the spring or sometime sooner if possible.

name: Entrance Arete
description: Avoiding the barn door will get you through this one.    Once off the ground less than obvious crux moves give way to an easy top out.

name: Offset Corner
description: When walking towards the Black Jack Boulders from telephone pole #37 this will be one of the first problems you see. It is identified as a dirty dihedral, the top is becoming overtaken by lichen again. This problem is nothing special, but as you climb you will find a few awkward moves but do not forget to stem, this will make you be able to run up this climb, it is not overly memorable but if you decided to do it have fun. And have a spotter because it is high at the top, don't let the height deter you.

name: Tallboy
