description: This problem is very tall and scary, many people have started this problem then backed off due to the height, myself included. This problem is face climbing directly across from Cavers Problem. This route gets neglected because it is tall and has some vegetation growing out of it. I have never topped out on this one, so if you are wondering how the top out is climb Offset Corner and investigate the top out. Also the fall is not good for two reasons 1. the height and 2. the rock that comes out of the ground by the base of this face.   Please be very careful.

name: Caver's Problem
description: Sit start in the narrow cave with your hands matched on a right facing blocky hold. Pick some feet and fire up to the large rail above. Surf the rail left for a few feet, before toping out via the obvious crimps.

name: Cavers Direct
description: Sit direct for Cavers problem. Start half way in cave on a small left sidepull and a tiny right crimp V10 (original way?), or right higher on a gaston V8, then make a hard move to rail, and finish Cavers problem. Top out in "the jungle".

name: Doppelganger
description: Sit start on the same hold as for Razor Blade Romance. Move right to the large jug on the rail of Cavers Problem and top out as you would for that problem. The first move is the crux because it is a big big reach to the jug. The top out is a little sketchy, so spot it well.

name: Razor Blade Romance
description: This route may be a new route, I have never seen any chalk or sign of climbing on it. If I am incorrect or you have any other information please let me know.    Sit start on the far left of the wall. The hold you start on always has chalk on it and has a loose piece of rock in it that wiggles but will not come out. Start here with your foot on the dagger like foot, stand up and grab the sharp crimp (the origins of the name). Once established here move your feet and go to the crimp up and right, then move your feet if you need to and go to the good top out. Once having your hands over the lip traverse right until you can rock over and top out.

name: Andrew's Problem
description: Sit start a few feet left of "Feldspar Arete" on a left hand gaston. Pull on and make a hard move out right to the horn on the arete. either hold the tension on the foot or take the footcut and avoid the dab. Finish up the arete.

name: Bumblebee Tuna
description: The crux of this one is getting off the ground and doing a long reach righty to a small micro-crimp. Squat starting it makes it a grade or two easier, but also makes it more fun.Sit start with both hands matched on a large diagonal rail. Pull on and figure out how to reach up to some micro crimps before heading right and up into the wave to topout. This problem and "Prairie Dog" share the same topout.

name: Feldspar Arete
description: Sit start low on the arete on the bad slopers. A singular desperate move gets you to a jug horn and then v1 territory. A handsfree kneebar is possible on the jug horn as well. Follow the arete up to its apex before topping out.

name: Prairie Dog
description: Sit start matched on the sloping arete/lip. Pull on with some smears, move out right to a good hold than press onto the slab. Venture up the slab into the scooping overhang on some large pinches and fin-like holds to an easy topout.

name: Quartz Adjourned
description: Sit start below the giant crystal blocks on a few small edges. Find the correct body positioning and make a long lock-off to another edge before gaining better holds in the quartz. From the quartz reach out right to the arete. Once on the arete traverse it out left and top out at the apex.

name: Quartz Administration
description: Sit-start matched on the super low good hold beneath the giant quartz protruding from the overhang. Find a tricky foot then pull on and hit a big hold out left then deadpoint up to a blind edge. From here work your way through the quartz and head out right to the arete. Once on the arete continue to the apex where it gets slopey and you can mantle.

name: Scoop Project
description: An aesthetic dihedral begging to be climbed. A low start on the prow will go with a mantle into the scoop, before finishing up the heady and balancy scoop. Needs a bit more cleaning at the lip and a little touch-up scrub on the face.

name: Silver Fin
description: Stand start the low block in order to get established on the pretty arete. A few moves up the sloping arete lets you reach to the lip. Mantle onto the slab or for some extra spice throw up a right heelhook. Problem is over before you know it. One of the shortest highballs in the park.

name: Tragic Inspiration
description: Sit start on the obvious horn jug, pick some feet and make long move up and left to a good sloper. With good foot beta this can be done static. Once you hit the sloper move right to the crack and work up over a tricky topout.

name: Child Prodigy
description: Both Firestarter and Child Prodigy can be found on the road-facing side of the Moat Boulder. Firestarter climbs the right side of the face on big holds and Child Prodigy starts as per Firestarter and breaks left.     Start on big holds that mark the start of Firestarter. Rather than going to a flake with your left hand, grab the crimp right below it and head left into an ill-defined inside corner. The crimps continue, some facing the wrong direction, until the lip where a hero-jug awaits. Topout up and right.

name: Codswallop
description: Sit start the lowest point of the low angled arete to the right of Firestarter. Traverse the lip up and left to the top out of Firestarter. This is a fun beginners problem or a good warm up. Surprisingly fun.

name: The Down Climb
description: Around the arete that the moat flake is on. This is a face climb that gets mainly used as a down climb hence the name, its very easy but little weird because of the height, but there isn't an overly hard move on the entire thing. I would reccomened climbing it up first before you climb down it just to know where the hands and feet are because they are not huge but they are certainly there, you will not feel like you will fall to your death at any point but it is high so be careful please.

name: The Fat Of The Land
description: Even though its a link-up, this climb gives you the full value of the boulder. It combines the difficulty(and then some) of Child Prodigy with the highball finish of Moat Flake.    Start as for Child Prodigy and then cut left at the large hollow flake in the middle of the face. Use a crystal covered knob and some unique body positioning to fire out and left to a large side pull. From here work your way up to the lip of The Moat Flake and then finish up the highball arête.

name: Fingerflake
description: This is a newly cleaned route, that I do not know the FA so if you have any info let me know. The climb gets the business of the route out of the way right away. Stand start on a good shelf below an obvious flake, mantle onto this ledge the make fun moves up the flake. Highball!!!!    I also down climbed this, finding it far easier than "The Down Climb" because the hands are bomber.

name: Fingerflake Sit
description: Sit start with both hands matched in the finger crack. Make a hard pull in order to get off the ground and then one-two clutch up to the large shelf above. Mantle this shelf then continue up the nice V0-1 finger crack to the top of the boulder.   I had to stack a pad.  The finger crack is also one of the safest and easiest downclimbs.

name: Firestarter
description: On the road-side of the Moat Boulder lies a steep, well-featured face. Firestarter climbs up the right side of this wall. Start sitting with good holds and make a big move up left to a flake and another big move to the lip.     This problem is one of those that just flows well...the kind that you find yourself doing everytime you are in the area.

name: Moat Crack
description: On the first of the moat boulders is a fun problem that is often out of commission because of the "pond" that forms underneath it. This is a great crack that trends from right to left at an upward angle. this problem is normally dirty because of the little action it sees but if you can get a dry day and don't mind a little dirt on your hands it's well worth the burn. Top out is high and a little nervous.

name: Moat Flake
description: Climb the obvious flake on the left side of the Firestarter face. Though the climbing is relatively simple (the flake is huge--not much beta indecision here), the height more than makes this problem interesting.

name: Authentic Flavor
description: An awesome traverse sit-starting in the crack used for "Right Train Tracks" and traversing rightwards past "Ricochet" and finishing up with the crux being "The Sword of Mercy". This problem has some very unique feet first climbing and some incredible moves.

name: B. Mills
description: Squat start on the chalked holds, pull on and move right to a good two finger crimp Then make the crux move up and left to an under-cling or crimp, depending on what you like most. Then enjoyable moves lead to the dirty top.    I plan on cleaning the top better soon.

name: Cilley Flake Sit
description: Sit start below the jug for Garden of Your Mind and Cilley Flakes on a left hand sidepull and the right hand in a finger lock (Both holds look like pockets). work out the feet and cross to a good hold, unwind the feet to gain the big jug. Finish on Cilley Flakes.  Personally I thought that this was harder than going into Garden of Your Mind because of the intimidating topout and the length of the route.

name: Cilley Flakes
description: Start in sort of a squat position and climb the large obvious flake. The crux is approaching the top out the holds turn from jugs to crimps then a sloper at the top out. If you figure your feet out it will be easier, maybe a little stiff at the grade.    On the smaller moat boulder.

name: Cilley Groove
description: Climb the dihedral that is slightly overhung, the beginning is tough but the real crux comes when it becomes overhung, the holds get much smaller and require good balance and core strength, this is ultra fun if you like crimpy moves, the top out is not too bad.

name: Cilley Old Man
description: Start on a sharp/jagged hold at about 6 feet. Get a right foot and then throw for a crimpy pocket above the starting hold. Get some feet and go for a sidepull left towards Cilley Flake. Drop knee your right leg to the left of the starting hold, grab a intermediate sidepull above the crimpy pocket and throw for a jug on the lip. Top out going right towards Cilley Groove with a heel.    I just cleaned the top out for this problem on 5/7/2014, it should be good to go!    I should add the route was named that because an old timer pointed the line out to me saying he wasn't sure if anyone had done it.

name: Cilley Puddle
description: The full line into the classic flakes. Slide on down into the small cave, sometimes it is flooded so get at it when you can.Sit start with some foot trickery and a sloping left hand pinch and a good 2-3 finger pocket for the right hand. Make a hard cross to another pocket-like hold in the crack and then make another hard move to a flat crimp rail. Figure out how to reach the jug, before turning on the kill switch and blasting your way through the rest of the flakes into a tricky top section.The second half of this climb is "Cilley Flakes". The first half is shared with "Mud Puddle of Your Mind".

name: Garden of Your Mind
description: Start on the same jug as for Cilley Flakes, instead of going out right to the large flakes work straight up over the bulge into the crack above. The crux is getting into the crack. Reach the crack using core tension, a sloppy crimp and a good side pull.

name: Garden of Your Mind Sit
description: Sit start below the jug for Garden of Your Mind and Cilley Flakes on a left hand sidepull and the right hand in a finger lock (Both holds look like pockets). work out the feet and cross to a good hold, unwind the feet to gain the big jug. Finish on Garden of your Mind.

name: Jerry's Traverse
description: Begin as for Ricochet traverse to the start of Left Train Track and finish up that problem, this route is hard and since the hard part of the route is a traverse it requires great core strength, the crux is stating low between the left and right train track. This rock is on the sharper side but it is fun none the less.    Located on the smaller boulder past The Moat Boulder

name: Land Shark
description: Start as for Jerry's Traverse but continue over to  Cilley Groove and top out there. This route includes the crux of Jerry's Traverse but that is not the crux of the route, the crux comes after the end of Jerry's Traverse, when the holds turn to hard crimps on slightly overhanging terrain. This section will challenge all of your climbing strengths and weaknesses and I promise when you are done with this route you will be pumped to the point where Cilley Groove will feel extra hard.    Located on the smaller boulder past The Moat Boulder.    I have not done this problem I just thought it should be added.

name: Left Train Track
description: Stand start on the chalked hold at chest height (Im 6 feet) make a long right hand move up to a crimp and bump it to the bigger hold. Move left hand to the crimp you previously had your right hand on, from here move your feet up and make another long move to a good crimp with your left hand up and left. Settle your feet and top out.    I feel this route either had holds break or is sandbagged, After doing it again I think it is closer to a hard V2 then a V1, but maybe I am just soft :).    Located on the smaller boulder past The Moat Boulder.

name: Miley Cilley
description: Squat start with the right hand on a good pinch/ crimp edge, and the left hand on a sloping crystal to the left. Pull on with difficulty and make a hard move up left hand then stab at a gaston with the right. From this position keep it together and bust out a few more big moves before topping out.This is a lower and full value start into "Cilley Old Man". The first two moves may be the hardest, but the top V5 section is not to be underestimated.

name: Mud Puddle of Your Mind
description: Sit-start in the mud puddle with left hand on a bad sloping rail and right hand in a tight two-finger pocket.  Figuring out how to get off the ground and generate movement with the left-hand dab-free is the first crux.  Once some beta is acquired, snag a pretty good slot and then a series of low moves gains some nice jugs. From these good holds head straight up "Garden of Your Mind" using a good left-hand sidepull and the crack which offers a variety of different holds. The topout is a bit insecure!

name: Pass the Ammunition
description: This is a route I cleaned off over the winter and is now finally climbable.    Start on jugs under the big slopey shelf and make a long move to the shelf. Rearrange your feet and fire to the crimp (crux). Once you stick the crimp, move your feet up, and go to the jug at the lip and make a really fun top out.    The bottom of this can be a little wet but I made a stick bridge to keep your pad out of the manky moss.

name: Powder Monkey
description: On the low overhanging face across from the Moat Boulder, start on the low far left jug, as for Pass the Ammunition, and traverse the seam right until  you get to the ledge. Step off or do an easy top out.   This is a good warm-up for the harder routes on the front face. The base suffers from wetness, so watch where you step or place your pads.

name: Ricochet
description: This problem climbs the right side of the slightly overhanging main wall that faces the road. Start from a sit start on a big flake, then move up to small crimps. Hit the crimps right or it becomes a hell of a lot harder. The crux is after you make the first move left and put a foot on the starting hold and rocking up with your right hand to the next series of crimps. The top out is mildly slopey, but you can easily bring a foot up because the right slide of this boulder slopes down, and it is a good foot.

name: Right Train Track
description: Start on obvious chalked jug and make a long Left hand move up to the obvious pocket then make right hand move to a good hold out right then top out on jusg. It doesnt look like a jug but go to it it is. The crux is the first move which requires funky feet I would recommend a back-step with you left foot and a high foot on the chalked hold out right with you right foot.    Located on the smaller boulder past the moat boulder.

name: The Sword of Mercy
description: Sit start on the huge jug on the right side of the face which faces the road. Pick from a few good feet for the right foot and a few bad smears for your left. Get some momentum and execute a huge deadpoint up to a good but really sharp hold way up and right. Core up and hold some gnarly tension! Once here, left-hand foot match and reach up to some good holds at the lip. Find a high foot and reach up right hand to a good hold. Figure out how to topout!

name: Wheel of Mercy
description: A tight low sit start on a a shitty flake underneath Left Train Track. Make a huge move to a jug, and then figure out how to climb through Jerry's Traverse backwards. After you're through that nonsense shake out on the jug of Right train Track, and climb through Authentic Flavor, which leads to the last crux, Sword of Mercy. If anyone finds a better way to start this rig it would be a four star instant classic.AND NO, you do not get to go up to the jugs above Jerry's Traverse and then downclimb Right Train Track. THIS IS BOULDERING AND THERE ARE RULES. Circumventing the Jerry's Traverse crux on this boulder is punishable by communal shame and the downgrading of your 8a.nu profile status. Route poster not liable for any ridicule, shame, or emotional burdens brought on by you climbing another silly traverse. Alteration of beta voids warranty, see restrictions where they apply.

name: Heir of Fire
description: Start sitting with two good holds and a high right heel. Pull up right hand to the angled crimp and move out to the lip out left. Top out up the arete.

name: Carranam
description: Start sitting with your left hand in the pod at the bottom of the crack and right hand on the good low sidepull around the arete. Compress up the crack and right arete to an easy topout.

name: Sick Man Says "Barf"
description: Start sitting just right of the arete on a good crimp, from there move up and pinch the arete just above a hold that is tempting, but the arete is better for the future moves. From here rock out to a small crimp with your right hand, then pop to the top, do not top out drop off.    It is over quick but packs a punch and the rock is sharp, the texture reminds me of P-way.

name: Sick Man Says "Deadpoint"
description: Sit Start- Dynamic Movement Right Hand to Remain on Rail Foot to remain on Start foot.    Right Hand: Rail Crimp    Left Hand: Undercling   Variation 1: Gaston First Crimp then Deadpoint/ Dyno    Variation 2: Gaston Second Crimp then Deadpoint/ Dyno     No Arete.

name: Bumbershoot Bonanza
description: This is a hard and friction dependent compression climb found on the right side of the boulder.  Stand start with a terribly slopey left hand sidepull found on the glassy false arete. Reach out right and grab a good right hand incut sidepull. Find some feet and hug your way onto the wall, trusting that there is enough friction to stay on the left hand. Figure out some tricky feet and smack up right hand to a nice openhand sloper pinch on the arete. A hard move to the seam for the left hand gains a positive hold, which is then followed by another right hand move to a pinch. From here, figure out a sequence to reach up to the giant horn four feet up. Continue up and left following positive holds on the arete to the jugs at the lip of the boulder. Topout a few feet off the deck on buckets!

name: Extendo Reacho
description: An interesting route with a hard first move.    Sit start low with a few options for holds and make a toss up and left to a good sloper (crux). Get you body position right and make fun moves leading to a dead-point to the huge jug. Get a quick rest then fire the top. All the holds at the top are good but the amount of lichen up there is less than inspiring.    The start can feel impossible until you get the positioning just right.

name: Satan on a Halfshell
description: A New England classic. Head straight up and out the overhang. Many different sequences will get you most of the way up the boulder, but the crux for most will be the last couple moves, when you can no longer keep your feet down low.    Apparently this was originally a v8 when Sherman sent it, using a blowtorch to dry the holds. The upper jug exfoliated, leaving the problem in its current state. Dave Graham got the first re-ascent.

name: Satan's Sister Sally
description: The direct start to Satan on a Halfshell. A superior problem in my opinion. Start to the left of Satan on a Halfshell with your left hand on an incut finger jug and your right hand on a sidepull. Throw up a right heel, utilizing two very small right hand crimps and a left hand slot that all take body tension and precision to stick. Getting your feet on the start holds, deadpoint up to a left hand crimp, hold the swing, and make one more crimpy move to the lip. Topout is cake...

name: Umbrella Project (Satanic Right)
description: The currently undone line of slopey crimps, sidepulls, and big moves. Start in the Umbrella Traverse holds about 3 ft right of Satan on a Halfshell on a pair of incuts below a big right-facing flake. There are a few edges that extend about 6' up from the start, then the ok holds run out and it's up to you to figure out how to use the microscopic flakes and slopey sidepulls to get to the topout.    The most probable sequence involves either a massive RH lockoff/LH bump sequence or a wild spring-loaded LH deadpoint to the crimp at the top of the seam (about a foot below the huge right-angled outcropping, where the seam goes from vertical to horizontal). From this hold, many options exist above for your right but the most obvious choice is to do a big dynamic move to the incredibly positive lip.

name: Umbrella Traverse Arete
description: Left side of Umbrella Boulder.

name: The Umbrella Traverse
description: Great Traverse.    Pumpy at the grade. The hands look fine, but once you've been on them for a while they get pumpy, especially if you are in a bouldering mindset.    Feet are key for this traverse, as they are polished and sparse in places. Use the good hands to traverse left or right and top out if you desire.   In my opinion, traversing right to left then following the arete to topout up by Satan On A Halfshell (V10) is the most classic of the variations on this line.    The right beta will make this climb seem V2, without that beta this climb might seem more like V3+

name: Day Flow
description: This is a fun compression and sloper line. Stand start with the left hand under the roof on a full pad rail and the right hand on the lip of the roof. Pull on and get a heel-hook before smacking up with the right hand to some slopers. figure out the balance point in order to come in for the match on the slopers. From here, a few more moves left and a big lock-off/ mantle up to the top of the boulder completes the climb.

name: Pulsating Core
description: A super steep classic overhang with large sloping pinches and rails.  Stand start with the right hand on a large horizontal rail and the left hand on the large sloping pinch found on the arete. Choose your jug foot wisely and make a few hard moves up to more sloping holds before taking a massive foot cut or figuring out some tricky beta. A huck for the lip gains a massive jug and an easy topout.

name: Slippery People
description: A cool sharp crimp climb with a toe hook. Start on the edges down low and go up left to a high half circle crimp then use a toe hook to get a right half circle crimp near it and hit the jug out left and traverse the lip right to finish.

name: Check the Technique
description: One of the best lowballs ever. Sit-start in the cave with a toe-cam-hand-match on a giant undercling horizontal break. Pull-on and either balance or fire for a good slot in another horizontal feature before hitting improving holds and exiting on a fun V1 arete to mantle.

name: Choss Patrol
description: Campus start on the chossy flake up to the lip and top out. Surprisingly sturdy and quite hard.

name: Daybreak on the Land
description: Stand start matched on a jug. Smear some feet below and mantle onto the slab then balance up the rest of the way with good feet and hand smears.

name: Daylight Cravings
description: Start laying down inside the cave with a small horn and a knob with a nice heelhook. Figure out where to go before smacking the lip of the roof. The lip encounter is quickly followed by struggling onto the low angled slab leading to the top of the large boulder.

name: F#@k the Technique
description: Sit start inside the cave down and left on the far side. Start with both hands inside the large off-width horizontal. Pull on and smear and bicep your way out right in order to join "Check the Technique".

name: Hatchet
description: A bit funky to start and brick-hard tension and grips. Stand-start high on the arete matched on an undercling feature. Pull-on and move up to a fin-pinch before figuring out how to get the other hand to the lip of the boulder.

name: Hatchet Sit
description: Sit-start the bulging base of the axe-head arete. Figure out some foot trickery and make a series of hard slaps and smacks on slopers and meatwraps until a large undercling feature can be reached. From here, hike the feet up and finish up the easiest V5 in the park.

name: Obsolete
description: Stand-start above the small pit with both hands on the sloping rail feature. Find some feet and get established onto the wall before following a series of sloping rails up or going big for the lip.

name: Opaque
description: Sit or squat start the far left-side of the sloping lip. Pull-on and make a series of difficult moves rightwards on the lip before a crux sequence to gain improving holds around the corner of the block before topping out.

name: Playing in the Band
description: Start in the small void created between to boulder and the ground matched on a large hold. Find some feet then pull onto the wall. The wall is overhanging at the start and the crux is to figure out how to utilize a large sloping shelf and mantle onto the slab. Once on the slab continue up and right of the crack or finish up and left for an easier finish.

name: Slimy Salamander
description: Sit-start the left side of the short arete/ lip of the boulder. Pull-on and make a series of fun moves traversing rightwards to the apex before topping out.

name: Toilet Bowl
description: Toilet Bowl is a long forgotten classic highball with a questionable landing located on one of the most unique features in the Black Jack Boulders. Start on some small holds at head height and do who knows what to get up to a toilet bowl jug at the lip. The difficulties don't end here, as the mantle is reportedly (and looks) very scary.   This one doesn't get done anymore, but with the resurgence of the upper boulders I think it makes sense to post this one up and try to get some communal stoke on it.

name: F.Y.G.
description: A hard aesthetic one move lock-off strength testpiece. start with a tight 3 finger slot for the left hand and an undercling sidepull mono for the right. Find the obvious foot before pulling on, staying tight and locking off to a sloper at the lip of the boulder. Match this sloper than work your way out right to rock over and grab the halo shaped tree root.   P.S. careful and watch the head dabs.

name: Incubating Incubus
description: Sit-start inside of the large, well-hidden cave with both hands just below the large shelf feature. Move up to a meathook on the shelf then out to a smooth right-facing sidepull. From here a big move gains a nice flat edge for the left hand. From this edge, lock it off to a sloper before piano-matching and executing an exciting and balancy big last move to a jug sidepull before topping out on positive holds.

name: Burger Bars and Bumper Cars
description: Sit start matched on the large sidepull undercling feature. Figure out some leg trickery and bust a massive move to the hole in the top part of the boulder. Figure out the no-hands knee-bar and float on to the top of the boulder.

name: Cheap Pair of Sneakers
description: A one mover starting on a pair of opposing sidepulls. The left hand is a bit of an undercling  and the right hand is the opposite located a few feet to the right. Pull-on and make a hard move to the arete lip then finish on jugs.

name: Life in the Time of COVID
description: Sit start with your left hand on a chip and right on a meathook undercling. Pull on and move left up to a good edge, power right out to the sloper and then top out on a series of good holds.

name: Panda Bear
description: Sit start with the left-hand low on the sloping arete and with the right hand on a large undercling feature a few feet right of the arete. Pull on to the wall and slap up the arete a few times before bumping the right hand to another undercling or sidepull. A few tenuous moves gains jugs at the lip of the boulder and an easy topout.   Hint: Think Thumb-catch.

name: Paperboy
description: This is a great compression climb that squeezes an arete and a few different sidepull features. Start sitting with the left hand on a bucket sidepull just inside the cave, and the right hand on a sidepull edge just below the arete. Pull-on and smack up lefty or righty to a positive hold before busting out left to a far sloping shelf. From here heel-hook and smack up some slopers with an exciting last move to a blind hold.

name: Vanilla Twilight
description: Start with the right hand on a low fat-pinch located on the arete, with the left hand a foot lower on a decent gaston also found on the arete. Find a toe and lock-off to some crimp rail features on the face. Come in with the other hand to the rail-feature before a cruxy move up to the sloping arete. Match the arete and figure out how to mantle.

name: Wafer
description: Jug feet, huge handholds, an easier less scary early exit or a taller more exciting exit. Take your pick. Start on the large shelf, move up and right to the apex before topping out, or rock onto the slab early.  Great for beginners and great for warming up in the tennis shoes or boots.

name: Chinese Connection
description: Sit-start the large sloping rail in the center of the face before pulling on and following a series of large holds leftwards to an exciting finish on slopers and a scary landing.

name: Deep Trouble
description: Excellent rock quality on a rad 60-degree overhang with some incredible quartz streaks. This problem starts sitting down inside the deep cave at the base of two vertical rail features. The left hand is fairly large and more of a false arete/ dihedral, while the right hand is a small sloping rail found on the steep overhang. Figure out some options for feet before squeezing your way up both vertical features on the 60-degree overhang. Hit the lip and figure out how to match while avoiding the rock slab behind and mantle onto the large shelf. Once on this large shelf, the climber has the option to climb up the 20-foot V0 slab or to wimp out and drop-off.

name: Pit Boss
description: This is a tall and proud one that hasn't been done in a long time. Sit start matched on the low rail in the middle of the tall face. Climb up some rails and make a few big moves up until the climber reaches a terribly slopey hold, then gain a high foot or dyno up to the slot. From here the holds get slightly better and then the slopey lip can be reached and mantled. Not sure if a hold has broken on this climb or not, but it is undoubtedly hard.

name: The Bootleg
description: Sit start the glorious 10-degree overhanging face on the obvious start hold. Pull-on and make a move left to a good crimp then work the side pulls and crimps to a long move to the lip. Top out on jugs.

name: Rail Rider
description: Start standing in the dihedral with a jug for the right hand and an okay hold for the left. Find a foot and move out left to a sweet two foot rail. Once here another move gains the giant 20 foot rail. Traverse the rail all the way left for a Crux transition into the arete. A few more smacks on slopey pinches and meat-hooks gains an easy topout.

name: Ratchet and Clank
description: This is a low left start to "Rip You a New One". Start with your left hand on a really bad small sidepull edge and right hand on a juggy undercling left of the Rip You start. Start with a high heel out right and pull on and either go left or right first. I found left first to be a harder single move but easier to link into Rip You and ultimately that was the way I did it.

name: Rip You a New One
description: Start with your left hand on a slopey pinch and right hand on a positive pistol grip pinch. Pull on with difficulty and make a blind smack up to a good but sharp crimp found on the face. Once here, moving out left to a funky sidepull  allows one to readjust the feet. Continue up the overhanging arete on some sharp crimps until you can rock over onto the face and punch for the jug at the top.

name: Speak-Kneezy
description: Start with your right hand on a dish on the sloper and your left under the roof on a side pull crimp. Pull on (think kneebar) and make the crux move up to the good hold on the arete. Roll right to a jug in the crack and then quest up the easier arete to the top.

name: Up Your Arsenal
description: Sit start with a good left hand hold, and a low right hand sloping gaston. Pull on and smack out the the arete before hitting a jug for the left hand. From here, figure out how to reach up to the lip of the boulder.

name: Eager Beaver
description: Start under the overhang on a giant right handhold. Pull-on with some poor feet and make a big move up to the next large feature. From here piece it together and figure out how to grab the sloping lip in order to topout.

name: Farm Fresh
description: Stand start the slab and venture up to some positive uncut holds and then jugs at the top.

name: From Good To Gourmet
description: This is an incredibly steep line that climbs out of a cave on an astonishing sloping rail feature.  Sit-start underneath the boulder matched on the sloping rail. Situate the feet before moving out left to a sloping gaston before encountering an improbable lip sequence on some extremely sloping holds. This section of the climb is then followed by an insecure and very balance oriented press onto a slab. The last execution of a hard barndoor move procures a large undercling feature. From here a few steps out left gains the climber some positive holds in a crack and an easy way to the top of the large boulder.

name: Mead Cannons
description: Sit start with a low left-hand meathook and a large right foothold. Pull onto the wall and make a big move up to a sloper before matching and figuring out how to mantle the beast.

name: Beta Box
description: Sit start matched on the large horizontal shelf. Pull on with difficulty and figure out some trickery then smack up to some bad slopers on the arete. From here latch a small sharp crimp and stand tall to a good hold at the lip before tipping out.

name: Limerance
description: An aesthetic sloping roof arete.Sit start matched low on the arete with a large foot feature. There is a large tree just to the left. Pull on and move up a series of pinches and slopers before making a hard move to a Gaston and a crux move to a good hold at the apex of the arete. Smack up some more meathooks and stand onto the slab and top it out.

name: 'Lil Peach of My Heart
description: Sit start matched on the large horizontal feature. Pull on and figure out a way to smash the sloping lip of the boulder. Once here go for the large horn and mantle. Short, sweet and peachy.

name: Victor for CEO
description: Erin's first first ascent. A classic. Sit start the right leaning left arete of the downhill side of the large block and make your way to the top. Tricky, delicate and somewhat powerful with a nice exposed topout.  The downclimb is located to the left of this arete.

name: 603 Special
description: The crux is the first move, which is high feet to an awkward pop move, this problem is fun and a good warm up for your body and head, because the problem feels taller than it is, stand start with hands about chest high (i am six feet) and go straight up. The moves at the start are fairly big, especially the first move, but don't let that deter you it is ultra fun and with a good spotter and pad it is very safe. Don't let the height scare you.

name: Opilio
description: Sit start under the overhanging scooped face with your left hand on a sidepull just below the arete and right hand on the large rail in the middle of the overhanging scoop. Pick some feet and pull up and move you right hand to the jug on the right side arete and work you way over the top.    It is very short but the moves are fun and strenuous due to positioning of the feet. If it went on for another 10 feet it would be a classic.

name: Trailside Crack
description: As walking to Waimea or Vader you will see this route to your left, it is fairly obvious. Stand start below the crack on good hold and move up using the crack, once your feet are on the good feet move up trying to use the and face holds and crack as best as you can, this is the crux because the crack becomes very tight and  hard to get any use out of it, the top out on this route is good so once you get past the crux section it is a breeze to the top on big holds.

name: Fragments of Time
description: Sit start matched on a large shelf found under the massive roof of the boulder. Pull on and make a series of hard moves through the roof crack in order to gain the large flake. Once on the giant flake, make a huge move to the lip and figure out how to pull off a tricky match. Once here, the large holds run out and the slopey nubs provide the climber with a crux top-out sequence. Some how make your way up to the large horizontal crack on the slab then continue up past a giant hands-free rail and eventually to the top of the giant boulder.  This climb would get more stars, but it is pretty lowball for a few of the roof moves. It is incredible that this climb actually is possible.

name: The Hills Have Eyes
description: Sit start on the right arete of the boulder on a series of positive shelves. Move up to a good left hand full pad crimp now figure out how to get to the jugs above, mantle and top out up path of least resistance to the left.

name: Home is for the Heartless
description: Sit start a foot or two left of The Hills Have Eyes on good holds. Move up to the crimp rail that is fairly obvious. The right hand crimp is better. From here settle your feet and make a long dead point or possibly a dyno if your are on the shorter side to a jug. mantle and top out the easy corner to your left.

name: Instant Crush
description: Sit start matched in the finger crack found on the roof of the block. the lefthand is a good jam while the right hand is a sloping pinch. Find a foot and make a huge right hand move to the large flake. Match, then make another huge move to the lip of the roof. Once here, figure out how to match, hit a pair of good nubbins, then get funky with it and believe you are going up to holds that are actually holdable.

name: Smoke 'Em If You Got 'Em
description: Sit Start and move left hand up to the only hold that isn't a jug on the route. Then bump your left hand up to a jug (crux). Once on the jug match and make fun-filled moves up to the top.

name: Abandon All Hope
description: Sit start on a nice high undercling with your left hand get your right hand on a crap crimp lift off the ground and get more crappy crimps to the top    The left starting was broken by Matt Wallace but it is still doable

name: Crocs
description: Climb huge holds up the arete. The holds are all large and flat. The route is a little mossy but it can still easily be done.     This can be used as a down climb, a way to get to the top of the boulder, or a fun climb in itself.

name: Dreamin' In Dog Years
description: Start on the juggs of Inverted Siberian Huskey (V5) that are just past the corner. Squat start of the jugs and make a long move to a crimp then move your other hand up to a crimp right next to it. Now you encounter the crux, mantle on small crimps and slopers to the top.    The crux is made difficult by the bulging nature of the climb.

name: Inverness
description: Stand start on obvious under-cling and move right following the overlap using another undercling. When the overlap ends, go straight up and mantle(crux) to the top out.    The underclings you use feel a little suspect but held me.

name: Inverted Siberian Husky
description: Sit start on a large jug and traverse left on the seam that gradually gets smaller and much more crimpy, the feet are all over the place in the seam below the seem and I have even seen someone use a foot above the seam but that never made much sense to me. If you leave the seam before it ends it reduces the grade drastically, the top out is slopey but if you inspect it before and find the right holds it will not be as difficult as a topout as it looks, but don't get me wrong it is defiantly a hard sustained route.

name: Light In August
description: The crux of this route is the top out which is nerve racking because you are at least 20 feet off the gorund. Stand start at obvious jugs the the middle of the face. Meander up the face with a slight rightward trend. Following the path of least resistence reach the top in a shallow v and top out.    This route is still dirty.

name: Press Release
description: Sit start at the opening jug for Inverted Siberian Huskey, but instead of traversing left as for that route climb up the short face on the trail.     This route is only 4 or 5 moves long but it packs a punch. Start in the jug and move out to a good crimp with your right hand. Situate your feet and cross left hand into the vertical crimp above your right hand (crux?). Then move your right hand up to the decent vertical crimp a bit above you left. Pick feet and make a long move to a sloper at the top out (crux?)

name: Assembly Lane
description: Squat start matched on the large shelf found on the roof of the boulder as for "Twilight Tour", but instead of climbing up the overhang compressing the sidepulls and the arete, smack out right to a sloper before getting a hand heel match on the starting shelf in order to gain a sloping knob found on the arete. Once here, figure out how to reach the large sloping hold several feet up. (Hint: there is a decent crimp intermediate) Once on this sloping hold, match and move up to improving holds on the lip of the boulder.

name: Nitro Fueled
description: Stand start the arete with a decent left hand edge and a right hand edge slightly lower. Find a foot and power out to the sloping lip of the overhang out right, figure out how to match and then top it out.

name: Twilight Tour
description: Squat start matched on the giant shelf hold found on the roof. Pull on and compress the arete with the right hand and some pinches out left for the other hand. A hard move to the lip gains a positive hold and then keep it together for a few smacks up to more positive holds for the topout.

name: Android Alley
description: This problem starts squatting with a poor left hand edge on the left side of the prow and a right hand sloping flake on the right side of the prow. Make a few hard moves up lefty in order to gain a large hold, and smack to some bad slopers for the right, keep moving leftwards on edges and make a few more hard moves in order to gain a positive hold on the leftside of the boulder's lip. Once here, smack up to another sloper and press it out.

name: Doctor Spazz
description: Sit-start the right side of the steep overhang with a high right hand pocket-like edge and a low left hand gaston edge. Pull on and move to the pocket out left. (This is the right hand pocket on "Fauteux Pocket Problem") Once here, a hard right hand cross move gains the next pocket. Next, toe down hard and move up to a  bad horizontal pinch and then the stellar finger bucket out right. From here, follow the good holds to the top of the boulder.

name: Fauteux Pocket Problem
description: Sit start (may have to stack a pad) under the steep overhang with a large left-hand sidepull and a small, sloping right-hand sidepull a few feet to the right. Pull onto the steep wall and move up to a good pocket-like hold for the right hand. From here figure out how to make your way up to the next pocket hold and then a good crimp or a sloping knob. Once here, a few more glorious moves on good holds over a no-fall-zone gain the top of the boulder.  This is a new classic that climbs very much like a gym-set or a Moonboard climb.

name: Naturally Sodomized
description: Sit start with left hand on a sloper and right hand on an edge and make a thrutchy move up to the perfect sloper rail. Mantle and get stood up on the slab. Poor line, amazing rock.

name: Neptune's Throne
description: Start in the cave with your left hand on a big slopey undercling like hold with your thumb in a pocket and right hand on the lower of the two holds on the lip. Pull-on and move your left to the other hold on the lip. Now use the pinches and crimps above to finish in the hueco. Drop off from here.

name: Puyo Pop
description: Sit start the right side of the steep wall with a right hand slopey pocket and a higher slightly better pocket for the left. Pull on to the wall and deadpoint to a hold around the lip before reaching up to a sloping rail. From this rail mantle straight up to the top or traverse out left into the jugs as for "Doctor Spazz" and "Fauteux Pocket Problem". (The original way this was done was the traverse.)  This problem is a higher start to "Spider Fighter" and was actually the first climb done on this wall.

name: Shadowbinder
description: Start under the roof on a pair of sloping rails. Choose from a few different foot options before pulling onto the wall and making a hard move to the jug lip. Topout on jugs. Figuring out the body positioning for the dyno and not dabbing on the swing is the crux.   Harder than Caver's Direct?

name: Spider Fighter
description: Sit start the right side of the steep overhang with a low right hand sloping quartz pocket a left hand gaston edge and some jug feet. Make a hard move up left hand to a slightly better pocket (This is the right hand starting hold for "Doctor Spazz") and then fire off a blind deadpoint to a decent pinch around the lip of the boulder. Match on a sloping rail then execute a fun mantle and reach up to the lip of the boulder. Or as an alternate exit at about the same difficulty, head out left to improving holds and topout as for "Doctor Spazz" and "Fauteux Pocket Problem".

name: Tranquil
description: Sit start matched on the arete/ lip of the boulder and traverse out right on slopers and positive holds and topout as for the lines on the steep wall. Easy climbing to help warm up for the steep wall.

name: Mo' Money Mo' Problems
description: Start on crimps with really good high feet move up the face using a good crimp and a real small side pull (crux) then move feet off of the good ledge to smaller feet then move to good hold near the top then top out.

name: Aurelion Sol
description: Sit start matched on a pocket-like mini-pinch found on the short overhang. (This is the same start as for "Soul Salvage".) Pull on and fire for the sloping lip, match, then traverse the sloping lip all the way right and top out on the apex as for "Blood Brothers".

name: Blood Brothers
description: This climbs the slightly overhung face just left of the right arete on the left of The Twin Boulders.Sit start on a good slightly sloped shelf and move up to the next similar shelf. Pick some feet and fire into the good but really sharp left side of the pinch/hueco. Then encounter the crux, the top out.The route is named because Tim Mijal and I both shed blood on this route on the hueco/pinch.

name: Cleaned on lead
description: crux at bottom and top...sit start ups the dificulty

name: Copperline
description: First off this route if fun and can be made much harder if you don't hold the holds right and you miss a key knee bar.     Sit start on two good hold and make a long move up to a left hand pinch on the arete, being careful not to cut your feet. Once you have the pinch move you right hand up to a sharp right hand just below your left then get your feet up and move to sloper-jug out left with you left hand. Knee-bar and move hands up to the top out. Hint for the top out don't just think straight up, left might be a good place to look.    The route is dirty on the top out and a few other patches of copper colored moss, for which the route was named (and because Copperline by James Taylor is a great song).    This is a new route but the rock is solid :)

name: Domino
description: Stand start on the clean blank face behind a small cluster of small trees on two good crimps with large feet. Move left hand up to a good rounded crimp, then move you feet up and reach for a cool quartz hold up high. This is the crux and will be harder for short climbers because the feet wont be as good. Top out into the forest :)

name: Grace Is Gone
description: This is a short little cave/overhang just around the corner from The Twin Boulders.     Sit start on an obvious jug and throw a heel up on the same rail system. Reach up to a good edge then bump the to jug at the lip and top out.    This route is short but it is extremely fun and a good intro to overhanging bouldering.

name: The Humble Truth
description: A powerful one-mover with a tricky top-out. Stand start with a left hand undercling and a right hand slopey edge to the right. Pull onto the wall with difficulty and smack up to a hold at the lip, match and get on top.

name: Moonlight Lady
description: This route is dirty but once clean will be a really fun route, I think it already is but I like an element of dirt and grime...    Sit start on a really sharp rail a foot right of the Copperline (V2) arete. Work up and right using a variety of holds. There are many different ways to do this but each way stays about the same grade. Trend up and right finishing in the rock that looks loose but is actually very solid.

name: Neon Moon
description: There are two cux's one which is getting off the ground and the other is the move to the top. Start start on large rail that makes the bottom of Cleaned on Lead and climb the right angling seam up and to the top.

name: The Noble Lie
description: Squat start with you left hand on the left arete and right on a crimp near the right arete. Throw up a left heel and squeeze up the two arete's using a variety of holds.     This problem climbs well, albeit a bit sharp in places. Not a super long route but a fun one to do.

name: Ol Man River
description: Start on an obvious crimp above head height with really good feet on the rock that curls out at the bottom. Once you have matched on this horizontal crimp move your preferred hand up to an angled crimp, move your feet up and go to the lip and top out.I stumbled across this problem and it had chalk on it already so I don't know the proper name or FA info, if anyone out there knows let me know and I will update accordingly.

name: One More Drink
description: Start laying down under the right side of the cave/overhang. Left hand on flake feature and right hand on little side pull pocket. Make a big move to the rail and traverse into the problem "Grace is Gone". Finish on "Grace is Gone".

name: The Pilfering
description: Sit start on the obvious jug and climb straight up. Not bad movement, just a bit tight between the large flake that was peeled off the wall and the boulder to the right.

name: Soul Salvage
description: Sit start under the short overhang with a right hand mini-pinch/ rail and left hand on a poor hold out left, or start matched on the right starting hold. Pull onto the wall and fire for the sloping lip of the overhang. Once here, wrestle your way up in order to stand on top of the block.

name: Spirit's Whim
description: Sit start with a sloping left hand pocket-like hold and right hand low on a positive pinch. Pull on with some low feet and lockoff to a good hold out right. From here smack into an awesome sloping pinch then fire for the lip. Once matched on the lip mantle direct or head out right and top out near the apex.

name: Two Thumbs Up!
description: This is the longest, most sustained, and in my opinion best route on this boulder.    Start on a shelf at the right side of the thumbs up boulder. Traverse left until your head is just above the ground, grab for the thumb, then move right to top out,

name: Big Body
description: Start low on a large flake jug.  Make a big move up and left to a good spot on the arete.  Easy finish on jugs, but be careful of a dinner plate jug that rattles.

name: Brand new Miura's
description: Sit start in the same good start as welcome to heartbreak, with a good foot out right. Instead of following the crack out left, continue straight up and slightly right, using under clings, side pulls, crimps and rounded slopers to top out.  All the time wishing you were wearing brand new Miuras instead of whatever is on your feet.

name: Brown Noise
description: This route is still dirty in the crack I need to get a brush to clean it out better but where I used the crack is clean.    Sit start on jugs with good but crumbly feet and move up to a left hand crimp then put your right hand into the crack below the bulge then jam above that with you left. From here move right hand to a jug and start the crux. Pull over the limp and make use of crimps and the crack get a high foot on the jug your right hand was on and pull over the top.     Like I mentioned before the crack is still a little dirty so be careful about that. The fall isn't great so have a spotter.

name: The Crescent
description: This is an aesthetic and technical line that follows a beautiful, arching flake up a tall, slabby face.    Start sitting at the bottom of the flake with your left hand on a good hidden sidepull and your right hand wherever you prefer on the obvious flake. Pull off the ground and angle rightwards via some technical foot moves to eventually reach the arete with your right hand. Continue bumping your right hand up the arete and doing whatever you can with your left to keep from barndooring. Clever footwork and strong body tension will allow you to reach a good crimp below the lip with your left hand. From there, locate some good top out holds and figure out a way to turn the lip. Done!    While this climb has not been previously documented, it's obvious that it has been climbed before. I met a guy named Pete (from NY) who used to live in the area and he said he climbed the problem 5-10 years ago and thought he might have done the first ascent, given how much cleaning he had to do. If anybody has any more history or information, feel free to share!

name: The Croissant
description: The direct version of the crescent, named for its... insecure and body tension based nature. Start with a low left underling and right on the obvious rail. With bad feet and a tight core move up, staying on the rail and avoiding baling to the arete. A really good addition to the field

name: Cutting Glass.
description: Start on the obvious quartz hold with really good feet. Make long (crux) move up with you right hand to a sharp crystal. Reach around the arete to a good crimp and work feet up and move up using progressive better holds to the casual top out.    This route is sharp, a little crumbly at the starting feet and the top could use a good cleaning. Once the cleaning is done it could get another star.

name: Good Head
description: Right most route through dirty rock and lichen (will be cleaned soon). Start on small undercling with sloppy feet rock up onto sloppy ledge using crimps on right side of arete. Stand on sloppy ledge and reach up to crimps and move feet up onto kind of sketchy feet reach out right and use undercling to gain the top. That is the crux because you need a strong head because directly below you is a sharp rock that would not feel good to fall on, hence the name of the route.

name: Little Weapon
description: Sit start with you right hand on a shallow under-cling formed by a flake and your left hand on the loose-looking flake below (it's actually solid). From here pick your feet and stand up and nab the slopey crimp, it is a long move. Then move your right hand up and right to another under-cling, then bump your left hand to a quartz crimp. From here move your feet up and work over the top.

name: Welcome To Heartbreak
description: The crack starts at a pocket which you match in get bad feet where ever you can pull up get two fingers in the next pocket get comfortable with your feet and then get your other two fingers into the same pocket get a far left foot grab a little crimp on the face then use the crack to switch hands and reach around the arete for another crimp bring your right foot over to a crappy hold then bump up to a decent sized crimp pull up for a good jug and top out     The crux is getting the two finger pocket to work out I would say and your feet it's mostly smearing     Very thin crack I would say if you follow the crack up it would make it maybe V5-V6

name: The Wood-Pile.
description: Start two feet right of Cutting Glass V0 with your left hand on a rounded nub and right hand in a shallow dish, both holds are located on a slopey rail. Traverse right up the rail to a dirty top out. The holds on the traverse are small but a kneebar helps with holding yourself on the rock.

name: 3 Speed on Vinyl
description: Stand start on the shelf and move right to an undercling the stand up to the crimp . from here get some high feet and throw up to the sidepull/jug. from he grab a small crimp and huck to the jugs above.    This is called Medicine Man in the Kemple guide and giving a rating of V3/V4 but, but this is the proper rating and name.

name: Dr. Quinn
description: This route starts on the sloping jug as for # Speed on Vinyl, but instead of going right go left heading for the juggy groove. To do this make a long span move (crux) to a crimp then bumping to the juggy groove. Then topping out.    The feet are good the span move is just really long it was my full span and I'm 6 feet tall with a +1 reach.

name: Fisher Fissure
description: Sit start with left hand on weird side-pull and right hand around the arete pull up to the rectangle hold that always has chalk on it, then work your way up to the top, using heel hooks and compression.    This route used to be a mediocre V3 but a couple winters ago the starting jugs exfoliated leaving it in it's current state. It was done from a sit start to the top last fall and is said to go as a classic V6.

name: From 'Down-Unda'
description: Start under the boulder, with a hand on the arete, from here you will want to pull up and pop to a ledge like feature, from here you will surmount the  bulge, onto the face that is fairly crimpy, but the hardest moves are certainly the first few moves. This route because it is overhung close to the ground at the start, it is often wet or dirty so i would suggest if you plan to do this route bring a brush, as it will make it more enjoyable.    This is another route that the starting hold has broken on which makes it harder, i have not done it since the hold broke so i cannot say how much harder, so if anyone has any info left me know.

name: Nala
description: Climb up the slab with the crux being in the bottom third, then a mental crux closer to the top. Using crimp, side pulls, smears and little nub make progress up the slab until you hit the easy top out.    The route could use a good cleaning but it still fun and doable in the condition it is in.

name: Revolution of the Youth
description: Do you like slab boulder problems that lead you pretty far off the deck? If so do this route.    Start on an easy ramp in the middle of the boulder  and work up right on the ramp. When the ramp ends make crux moves onto the face working straight up the face. At the bulge at the top Tim went left.    This route is a fairly dirty still, but I plan to clean this along with the route to the left.    My friend Tim, who is pictured, possibly did the FA, in the photos shown. I cannot confirm this so I didn't list it.

name: Up Into The Green Silence
description: This is basically the direct line of '3 Speed On Vinyl' (aka 'Medicine Man'). Start standing on the large chalked jug shelf (same start as '3 Speed'). Grab a sidepull crimp with your left hand, move your feet around and do a foot/hand match with your right heel on the starting hold. Rock up and reach high to a good right sidepull (crux). Bump left hand to another good edge. From here, the top out is relatively straight forward on good holds. This problem is more logical and less contrived than '3 Speed' and is definitely easier. The landing is flat, the movement is great and it's just high enough to add some excitement.     I'm not sure if this problem has been done before. If it has, feel free to let me know and I'll change the info to match that. Based on the condition of the top out holds, I would guess that if it has been climbed before, that hasn't happened in quite a while...

name: What's Left of Fissure
description: Sit start five feet left of Fisher Fissure V3 on odd angle jugs and awkward feet. Pull up and lay-back the OK side-pull in the crack, then do some fancy foot work and move right hand further up the crack. From here there is multiple ways to get to the top, either employing a small crimp or a lay-back, the top out is huge! Walk of the other side.

name: New Age
description: Stand start in the hole on the right of Peedunckle. Grab two large opposing sidepulls and climb to the top using the obvious crimps in the face. Make an easy top out on weird jugs.  If this stays clean it will become a staple of the Black Jack warm-up circuit.

name: Paleolithic Ways
description: This route is fun consisting of moves linking jugs. Sit Start on the arete with jugs then move straight up to the only non jug on the route. Then break left heading towards and obvious jug then top out.     The name refers to the dead tree we removed using a sharp rock and the fact that we had to pry a 200 pound diamond shaped piece of rock off. This was done after two of us had climbed it. We pulled the rock off then I resent it in its current state.

name: Peapod
description: In my opinion if this problem was taken back by lichen it would be no big loss. You sit start on the front rounded arete on a ledge with good hands and feet and move up to a gaston, or if you can all the way up into the undercling in the right trending overlap, then move feet up to the ledge you started with your hands on, make another move in the small right trending overlap then top out. The topout is mossy.

name: Peedunckle
description: Great problem for beginners to work finger crack moves. The only down side to this problem is you will wish it went another thousand feet. Here you will sit start on a good finger crack and OK feet, then simply climb the crack until you reach the top. The top out is mossy here as well.

name: 6B Crawford
description: Start on the good jugs on the right end of the overhang and traverse left topping out on the left arete. This route involves core tension and foot work to keep it at the grade.     The route could use a little better cleaning but it is a good climb and should be climbed.

name: Nowhere Man
description: Start standing, matched on the shelf about eight feet or so left of 'Spragueasorus'. The crux comes in the first couple of moves, first with a high step/heel onto the shelf and then using a tiny crimp (and possibly a smaller one below first) to set up for a committing move to a good hold. This move is the hardest physically and is made somewhat harder by the prospect of falling backwards onto the sloping boulder below. From there, the climbing ease somewhat in difficulty, but the last move to the upper lip is a committing one high off the deck over a very bad landing. Failing to latch the lip would not be good...     If you can get past all of that, and summon enough courage, this climb is defintely worth doing. It would be one of the best at the Blackjacks if not for the poor landing.    (descrpition by Christian Prellwitz)

name: Pyramid Power
description: There are a number of different ways to do this problem, and they are all pretty hard. Start sitting on the obvious crimp rail and head up and left. Some people use the small crimp in the horizontal crack, some people use a shallow undercling, and everybody uses the unusual pyramid shaped hold to eventually grab the jug on the arete and top out left. A great problem and one for which it may be beneficial to be a little shorter for a change.

name: Satan's Choice
description: From the crimp rail start of Pyramid Power, head up and right onto two small edges, then make a very powerful move to a sharp jug. Hold the swing, then celebrate because the finish is a stroll on great sculpted holds. This is a beautiful line on great rock that takes serious finger strength to pull off.

name: Spragueasorus
description: Ouch!   Crimp and power your way up this demanding face using deadpoints and precise feet.    The topout is huge (thank the goddess)    Way Hard for the grade(hence the V5+)

name: Summer Daze
description: A cool problem requiring good footwork and a bit of commitment. The crux revolves around a right hand crimp once you emerge from the cave. Sticking the crimp and pulling through may seem challenging at first, but it's not too bad with some good beta. Although the pit seems menacing, it is unlikely that you'll fall into it after you emerge.

name: Waiting for No One
description: Start standing just left of the right arete using a crimp and sidepull. Work up and right on crimps before topping out on good edges. Crux may be avoiding the slab behind you.

name: Bemis
description: This route is shot but has some fun moves. Start sitting with you left hand on a good hold about two feet off the ground and right had on the large rail. Pick your feet stand up and move you left hand up and left to a small, knob-ish hold, then comes the crux foot move. Move it up to a small positive edge then move right hand up to the top which in the wrong place could be considered slopey. Don't use the boulders on either side of you, they are off route. This route is fun but short if it was another ten feet tall it could be a classic, but with this said I still believe you should do it.

name: Diagonal
description: Stand start using underclings with very weird feet, either under the underclings or out to your left, make a few hard moves on underclings and weird holds until you reach the large right trending crack. Work up the crack using a variety of techniques including hand jams, fist jams, and others, until the end of the crack from there top out straight up.     Be careful of the boulder you must climb over it is large but a fall in the wrong spot could send you to the doctors with ankle injuries.

name: Diamond in the Muff
description: Start matched on the slopper left of the tree, make a big move up and right. Work right straddling the tree traversing on sloppers until you reach the obvious jug. From the jug go straight up and top out.

name: Drop The World
description: This is the definition of a low ball. Start laying under the boulder with your right hand on the arete and your left hand on a crimp. Heel hook with your right and flag your left out. Pull up and pop to the jug at the top. The crux of this route is not hitting the ground with any part of your body while making the toss to the top and topping out.    This route is short but it is the type of route that you enjoy and are not sure why, but you just cant walk away until you do it.

name: Good Morning Midnight
description: Start sitting a few feet to the right of Moose Tracks on a sloping left hand crimp and a very small right hand crimp, pick some feet and stand up to match the seam in two positive spots. Once established in the crack move your feet up and make a long move out right to a sloper. Establish on the sloper with your right hand and make a tension move to a jug up near the arete and top out.

name: Metallic
description: Metallic climbs the line of thin, slopey crimps just left of Zigzag Crack. Start with your hands on two crimps at about the seven foot mark. This is a perfect problem for a cold day because it's all about whatever friction you can get from the raspy starting holds. Place a foot on and toss to better holds. After establishing on the next set of crimps, the problem eases in difficulty. Top out just to the left of Zigzag in a little groove.

name: Moose Tracks
description: Locate the blunt prow on the left side of the Zig Zag Crack face. Moose Tracks starts as a sit and moves up through crimps to a relatively low top out.    The moves are interesting and the holds are positive, which makes Moose Tracks a good tick after Zig Zag Crack.

name: Scumbag Blues
description: This is a link-up of shorts, it doesnt have many independent moves but I thought it deserved its own route listing because it climbs different then the two routes it shares moves with.    Start as for Zig-Zag Crack (V1) and move up until the obvious triangle jug, once here move left with the seam into the top of Metallic (V7). The route meets up with Metallic (V7) post crux, in a short dihedral. Then top out, there is a good hold for the top out, it just isn't obvious from the dihedral.    The route could use a little cleaning on the top but the crux is very clean. The crux is the transfer between the two routes which can either be done with a long span move or using small crimps.     I dont know if this has been done before, I figure someone has done it at some point because it seems to be an obvious variation, so if anyone has a name or FA credit let me know.

name: The Truth
description: The crux is the sit start. Get a good right foot and a semi good left foot. Grab the tiny crimp for the right and the decent left hand crimp. Pull up and grab the good crimp and the crimp just to the left of that. Get some feet on okay holds. Reach left again to gain a good hold and jump for the top.    There is a V1 variation if you just stand start it with the good holds.

name: Zig Zag Crack
description: Zig Zag Crack is perhaps the best V1 boulder problem in all on New England if not in all of the country. Yes, that is high praise, but this problem lives up to the hype.    Locate the obvious crack on the Zig Zag Boulder and follow the crack using fingerlocks, laybacks, and high steps. The problem is about 15 feet high and would qualify as a highball if not for the perfect landing. A much harder variation (V9) starts as a sit to the right and climbs into the crack.

name: Zig-Zag Crack Variation
description: Start sitting at the only decent hold on the right-hand side of the face with the Zig-Zag crack, and traverse left into the crack on small sloping seams, using a shallow mono somewhere along the way. Finish up the crack.

name: La Fin Du Monde
description: La Fin Du Monde translates to The End of the World (It is also a delicious beer)    Sit start on the left end of the boulder with your hands in pockets, pull up to the good holds and work your way right up the hanging arete feature. The crux comes midway through, in the form of a right hand sidepull/undercling and a heel hook and crossing left hand into a good sloppy edge. From here make tension moves up to the groove at the lip.

name: Friend Of The Devil
description: Start on the large side pull and traverse left through the crux on crimps, until making a long dead-point to a good but awkwardly angled jug. From here settle your feet and make a long move up to a jug. The route stops here for now because of snow the top out could not be done but will easily go once the snow is gone. The crux of this route is from the ground to the dead-point. The moves through this section are fairly sustained and the feet leave something to be desired.

name: Highway To Hell
description: This route is very simple, it climbs the large flake that breaks this cliff ban in half. Stand or sit start and cruise up the flake to the top. There is no crux and each move is on jugs.     I do this route on cold days to get the blood flowing and to get my hands used to the cold. Up and down laps are always fun on it.

name: Question Mark
description: A fun little overhung route directly to the left of the trail walking up to The Meadows. A couple of painful moves out to the tip and the obvious flake and then a couple of moves back along the road facing side.

name: Renegade
description: The crux is the first move. Using a side-pull crimp with your left and and a good hold with your right, pick some feet out left and toss up and right to a sharp slopey hold. Picking the correct feet for the start will keep it at the grade. Hit the slopey jug and work your feet to the right and make use of a good heel-hook. Then move up and left to a series of really cool jugs to another hard move up to the final jug and drop off.     There is a harder start starting all the way in the back but I couldnt make the first move and the start I did seems more like the natural line, so i just left it like this.    This couldn't be topped out due to ice and snow but once it is melted and I give it a good cleaning, it may get another start.

name: Wallace's Roof
description: Sit start in the very back of the cave with a right hand hidden under-cling and left on top of the jug. Pull on and make a right hand move out to a 3 finger packet in the crack. From here move left hand out to a good but slightly slopey flake. Then encounter the crux. move to the lip using cool foot beta, once hit the lip make two moves up to a jug and drop off.    The first two moves will feel like the crux if you do not get the beta right think kneebar :)    The problem could not be topped out due to snow and ice but will be able to top out once the snow is gone and when that happens it will probably get another star and may be a bump up in grade.    There is a really hard looking variation that would come in from the left on a long horizontal roof and meet with this problem at the lip. Looks like it will be at least V8 any takers?

name: Sailors Beware
description: Start on the low flake with a lot of chalk on it can't miss it.  Bump up to a good hold with left hand then move right hand to a nice pinch pop up and grab another good hold with you left hand the next few holds are very sharp but awesome holds there are two ways to top out 1st is off to the right 2nd is over the very top of the boulder which is way more fun cause the last hold just feels awful but you can hold yourself there and get chalk if need be     Have fun it's a fun one  BE VERY CAREFUL ABOUT THE PLANTS KEEP AN EYE OPEN AND WORK ON STAYING ON THE THIN PATH WITHOUT STEPPING ON THE PLANTS.  PLEASE!!!

name: The Road Not Taken
description: A short overhanging arete that gets walked by, by everyone who parks in the main lot on busy summer days.  This is a line that I have looked at over the years and we finally climbed the other day.     Sit start on a crimp on the right side of the arete and one under the roof on the left side. Climb the arete using fun holds to a casual top out.

name: Caught in a Landslide
description: A great power endurance traverse with excellent movement, this line provides a good way to warm-up or burn-out on! Sit start the hanging arete on the right side of the large roof. Pull onto the wall and move left following the arete before continuing the leftward movement through a large sloping horizontal rail that acts as a lip for the roof. At the end of this sloping rail, there is a crux sequence that then leads to a fun section on large holds. Once at the left side of the boulder figure out how to mantle onto the slab for the top-out!

name: Choss is Reality
description: A fun roof problem on large reinforced holds. Sit start with a large jug shelf above the pit. Pull on and execute powerful moves along the shelf system. Avoid a dab near the end of the roof and commit to a good topout.

name: Dookie in the Ball Pit
description: Sit start below the finishing jug of Party Pooper on two compression holds that are about two or three inches below the holds you actually want to start with and a big right foot. Pull on and use a low left heel to bump up to the better holds, and finish towards Going Deeper. Grab the huge jug and step back down to the pad.

name: Easy Come, Easy Go
description: Sit start the suspended lip of the boulder and climb up and right along the arete/ lip on large but sharp holds to a somewhat easy topout. This climb is the first section of "Caught in a Landslide", but instead of following the horizontal shelf across the roof, stay on the lip a few more moves then mantle onto the slab.

name: Escape From Reality
description: This is the boulder problem hidden away in a cave just above the main parking lot. Start sitting way back in the cave and crimp your way to the large underclings 3/4 of the way out. Match the last undercling and use a tiny crimp intermediate to throw big for the lip of the cave, then keep tight and work up to the obvious finishing 'spike.' Unfortunately several holds have broken over the past few years and some of the moves (particularly at the start) aren't as nice as they used to be. Still a great endurance boulder problem, though - something like 18 moves long and horizontal the whole way.

name: Fighting the Flaws of Reality
description: An amazing climb outshone by rock straight from the bargain basement!   This boulder problem starts sitting inside the cave at the base of the crack on the right side of the pit. Right hand in a finger bucket and left hand on a smaller crimp. Pull onto the wall and move through the crack for a few moves before spinning around and moving diagonally out the roof. Hard rigid moves on stupendous roof features bring the climber to a crux lip encounter and a tough top out sequence! This climb follows the giant rail feature out of the roof while "Fighting the Laws of Gravity" starts the same but climbs following the finger crack out the middle of the roof.  Although the rock quality isn't the best, this route offers some excellent horizontal roof climbing on large positive features, providing climbers with an excellent spot to hone their skills.

name: Fighting the Laws of Gravity
description: This is an astonishing line that starts sitting in the back of the cave at the base of the crack! Start with the right hand on a good finger bucket, and the left hand on a crimp down and left. (From this positioning you will almost be facing towards the outside of the roof rather than staring at the back wall.)  Once oriented, pull on and follow a series of good holds found in the crack. Using a combination of strength and technique, make a series of difficult moves on finger-locks before having to make a crux foot-cut!
