Match the edge of the roof and make a few more hard moves up and left leading to a somewhat tricky top-out.

name: Going Deeper
description: A relatively normal boulder problem in an unlikely location. As fun as it is hilarious. Start with your hands and right heel on a giant rail feature on the right side of the cave (where the opening is), and traverse left on the feature to its terminus, making a final move or two to an obvious jug above. Drop off, or step off. Laugh and do it again.

name: Laws of Gravity
description: Stand start on a large shelf to the right of the ten-foot pit in the cave. With a hard sequence, move from finger jam to another finger jam before thugging out a hard foot cut. Reset and continue climbing up while trending leftwards using a variety of jugs, pockets and meathooks. A somewhat tricky topout will get you on top of the boulder.

name: Baby Mouse Buffet
description: Stand Start.   Start with your hands on some small holds below the mini roof-like bulge feature on the Mouse House boulder. Head up and left (or right, the grade stays about the same) to surmount the bulge. Mantle and top out.    A sit start would be potentially possible, but it would bring up the grade by a lot!

name: Environmental Destruction
description: Climb the dirtyish slab to the top, utilizing a variety of hand and foot options to get up it. The easiest way is V0, though it would be easy to make it far harder.

name: Mama Mouse Reads Bedtime Stories
description: Start low in the alcove with your hands on jugs. Using some interesting foot work, follow the seam to the right, and then head up on jugs pulling an interesting mid face mantle. Continue up the slab to top out.

name: Try This
description: Stand Start. Step up to the middle of the triangular face, and ascend the boulder via the most direct line. Starting on smaller spaced holds, and climbing up too big jugs for the top-out.

name: Scarred for Life
description: Sit Start on the left side of the boulder in the low jugs in the Horizontal Crack. Traverse the crack until thins into nothing, then use small feet and crimps to make your way to the top out on the small ledge at the end of the boulder. I did this by using very small holds and slapping the arete, topping out with a kind of side step mantle. This line will feel easier the smaller your fingers are.

name: The Sins of Omission
description: Start at the same start holds as for 'Scarred for Life' make one move to the right in the crack, pick some feet and make a long move to the lip. press out the casual top out.

name: Nature Boy
description: Start low sitting on a boulder in a group of three trees, and climb out the slightly overhanging face using crimps and then slopers; being sure  to take care to not dive down the embankment should you fall off this problem. When you hit the jugs, mantle onto the ledge to your right and claw your way up the low angle slab.    When you top out, howl at the moon. You're a nature boy now.

name: Axe Wound
description: The crux is the start, if I had to pick a crux. Start on jugs with good feet and work up the flake to smaller holds to the highest point of the boulder. No hard moves all relatively simple but fun moves.

name: Clam-a-Rama
description: The crux is pulling off the ground because of the slippery feet. Sit Start with left hand on arete and a okay right hand. Stand up and get a good crimp with your right hand and bump your left hand up the arete to an easy top out.    The base of this climb is often wet.

name: If Only I was Taller
description: This route is two moves and a top out...     Start sitting with you left hand on the arete and right hand on any of the small face holds. A good foot out left and a smear is what you will want to use for your feet. Pull of the ground and go right hand to the lip then move your left hand to the top and top out. (there is an intermediate crimp for right hand if the first move is too long).

name: Morbid Obesity
description: I cleaned this route out of moss not knowing what to expect and it is better than I though it would be...    This is a low traverse going right to left. The crux is keeping your weight on your feet. The hands are not great but the feet are HUGE.     Sit start on the low right arete and traverse left on small and weird holds to the left arete.

name: A Cheval
description: Angle up and left, up the slab, fun but could be a deadly fall. This problem is awesome with good feet and hands the entire way up. Climb the face and use the arete to its full advantage, it has great holds. An over all good problem that's worth doing, if you are comfortable with the height of the problem.

name: Ahab Calling
description: Sit start on a large slopey ledge,with a heel hook out right, fire up with left hand to a horizontal slot, then with you right hand go to a little knob below the two finger pocket then bump up to the two finger pocket then adjust your feet and top out.

name: Bad Ladder
description: Stand start on two crimps, one directly on the arete and the other to the right. Pull on and move up to a jug on the arete, then top out up and left. The top out is thin and tall but all there.

name: Barn Door
description: Start on the large chalked jug in the middle of the face. Move right and up using a big slopey undercling/sidepull and a variety of small crimps, to a fun and committing top out. Then follow easy ledges top the top of the boulder.

name: Barn Door Direct Direct
description: Stand start on the commonly used jug. Use the crimp rail to your left and a small crimp to work your way into a hard to hit thumb-dercling. Now find the tiny right hand crimp, adjust your feet and make a long move into the mail slot up and left. Once you grab the slot finish up on jugs to the top of the boulder.    The meat of the climb finishes at about the 12 foot mark but you top out well over 20 feet of the deck.

name: The Barn Ladder
description: This shares the start hold 'Barndoor' and splits left from he start and climbing into Bad Ladder.    Stand start on the chalked jug in the middle of the face, this chalked block is four feet off the ground, climb up and left to join Bad Ladder at the jug. To make the Jug from it the block you will test your core strength and finger strength. there are a couple ways to do this problem, it takes a little bit to find the one that feels V3.

name: Bucket Loader
description: A left sit start variation to Crimp Ladder. Start matched on a small crimp rail just right of the hemlock and pull up on decent feet to another small rounded crimp rail. Match and bob up to the higher starting hold of crimp ladder. Finish on crimp ladder. A little sharp, but a fun addition to the moderate circuit.

name: Captain Condor
description: I haven't done this route, I have worked on it though, I just think it should be included. Sit start on a huge side pull and undercling, pull up to side pull/gaston in vertical seem, top out up and right. This routes starting feet are desperately small which makes the first move in my opinion the crux, I also feel like to be short would be a distinct advantage at the start. This route is what could be defined as intricate because of the precise movements that are required, to send the route.

name: Crimp Ladder
description: start standing in the triangle shaped crack with good feet. Move right hand up to a crimp and then arrange your feet higher and make the crux reach out left to a decent side pull, then top out. the top out is high but it is easy and you should be safe with a pad and spotter.

name: Dog Tracks
description: On the barn door boulder on side that faces the road, just to the left of underdog traverse, two parallel cracks that run up the face. Follow either of the cracks. This route is fairly simple, with no defined crux, but it is intiminating because of the height and semi greasy holds from little use, but don't get me wrong it is a lot of fun, just don't fall because of the ledges below you, would surely break your legs if not more.    The two cracks climb differently, the left crack you climb with your hands in the crack and using the good feet it provides along with other feet once is starts arching to the left. The right crack however really doesn't get used much, there are a lot of good holds around the crack, so the right crack climbs more like a face climb.    A possible harder variation is possible if you climb the left crack until it starts trending left, from there move across the face right towards the other dog track...I haven't done it yet but it looks harder.

name: Easy Rollin'
description: Very straight forward. Stand start on the horizontal seam and blocks, and climb straight up, using the vertical crack that meets the horizontal, there is a clutch finger lock half way between the horizontal and the top out, the top out is not bad, just reach far and there are some better holds up there, a heel hook out right also helps on the top out.    Feet are low on this route so the move to the lip normally induces swing for me (I am 6 feet).     This route has a tendency to seep water and is very dirty at the top(I will try to clean it so).

name: Flyboy
description: Grab the good hold with your left and a slopey hold with your right about head height (I am 6 feet). Pick from some feet I would recommend a high right foot. pull on and throw to the sloping jug up and right, hit it hold on and top out.    I have not done this route but have tried it and come close, it is hard! This has all but been forgotten but I was flipping through the old Rumney guide book and this problem was in their so everyone go try it, its fun.

name: Gatsby
description: This route is a cool route on the tall slab face of the Barn Door Boulder. Start between the arete of A Cheval and the Crack of Pine Tree Crack.    Work you way up using a hard to find but positive crimp in a crack, then work your way up over the small overlap and continue straight up until you hit the arete of A Cheval then finish up that route.

name: Ginseng for Genius
description: The crux is the first move off of a bad left hand chip crimp and poor right hand sloper crimp. Pick some feet and toss up to the quartz starting holds of Pound for Pound.     I have not done this route, I have tried it, but I am adding it so people know it is out there.     There is rumor that this route is much harder than than v8 that it was originally given, not sure if something broke or the people who told me this and I have missed something.

name: Hemlock Crack
description: This route is much fun, sit start on a jug at the base of the crack just to the left of the crack, then move up with the obvious crack. this is a great place to work on different techniques, because the crack is so variable there are places for finger lock and I have even found one hand jam. The tree is off limits but of course if you are nervous about the heights, grab the tree, and have fun. This route fun to make eliminate problem on with your friends or even an outdoor game of add-on. The route can be down climbed if you don't want to jump off the step wall to the left of this route. Normally I jump off from right above Ahab Calling where the wall is the lowest, if you do decide to jump off I suggest placing a crash pad on the ground.    Also this crack could be used to teach about placing trad gear.

name: Horse Shoe Squares
description: Sit start on the same quartz as for Randy Moss, but instead of following the shallow arete out as for Randy Moss go straight up on the slab. This route is being taken over by moss at the moment and its really to bad, because its a fun route. The sit start is the crux, once established on the face it is an easy climb (as long as you remember to use your feet). Highball.

name: Lazy Man's Dyno
description: Start in the left most holds of Underdog in the horizontal, but instead of traversing the horizontal, get good feet and dyno (or static if tall enough I am at 6 feet) for the slightly slopey lip above you head. Pull over the lip making a semi awkward mantle. From here it is easy cruising up the arete to the top of the boulder.    The name from this route comes from the fact that after Tim's FA using dyno beta we realized the dyno could be avoided.

name: Ledge Line
description: Climb the large weakness to the top. The weakness a.k.a. line of least resistance doesn't go straight up so look around to find the easiest line. This line zig-zags from large ledge to large ledge hence the name. This can also be used as a down climb, but not my recommended way down.

name: Lost in Translation
description: Stand start with a left hand on a chip crimp and right hand on any of the crimps in the horizontal. Pull your feet onto the wall and dyno straight up to the quartz jug. Then top out through dirty rock with the all the holds you need cleaned off.

name: Minty Floss
description: The natural sit start of "Randy Moss" which makes avoiding the crimpy start holds of the mentioned climb possible.. Start on the giant sloper crystal ball down and left of the overhang. Make a hard move up use a left heel hook. From here make a move up to a crimp or do a big slap and move rightward on slopers. Keep traversing on slopers and edges. Hit a big sloper and chalk up for the crux finishing maneuver at the corner. It is far and feels like you won't be able to hold it. Once you commit to the big move you realize the hold is incredibly positive. Stick it and pull off a rad mantel!

name: The Oracle
description: This is the sit start to Easy Rollin'.    Start with your left hand on a sidepull jug down low and right hand on a small pinch in the crack at three feet. Pick some feet and toss up into the starting horizontal jugs of Easy Rollin'. Top out up that fun line.

name: Pine Tree Crack
description: This is a beautiful low angle finger crack, one of my favorite routes that I do almost every time I am out. The crux is about halfway up but its not a very defined crux.    This can be lead or toproped, but i suggest doing it without a rope if you are comfortable at this grade and with heights.

name: Pound for Pound
description: Grab the quartz holds above your head, hit the hold up and right pick some feet and throw. Classic problem, gets way easier the taller you are (felt V2 for me at 6ft, but guidebook gives it V4)    This is a great problem that makes you look like a stud when you grab the jug on the lip and swing out.

name: Randy Moss
description: This is a recently cleaned ('08) route the uphill side of the barn door boulder. I'm sure it has been done years back but this is a great new one to try. This thing is a slopers paradise.     Updated description from Matthew Wallace since holds changed - Sit start with the two crimps and move up to the next good crimp with your left, from there traverse out right using the slopers and the gaston crimp to reach a big positive sloper 2/3's up the arete. Now here is the crux, get your feet situated and match a little crimp, pull hard and stick the jug horn at the top, finish off the easy top out.

name: Reverse Underdog
description: Traverse  Underdog right to left starting on the crimp crux of the route by pulling into a high heel hook and heading towards the jugs on the left. When you’re at the jugs turn the Arete and climb easy jugs to the summit or just step off onto flat ground. It makes for a better warmup than underdog and lacks the punchy finishing move of the regular traverse.

name: Savak
description: This route might be a little contrived but it is fun.     On the face that faces the road sit start in a crack about 10 feet right of the chalked jug that marks the beginning of Barn Door (V2). From here make a tough move up to jugs, get you hands and feet situated and make a long move to a good crimp with your right hand. Get settled on the crimp and make a long left hand move to a crimp at the top of Barn Door (V2), then top out as for that problem.    No real defined crux, the sit start will be easier if your short but the following moves will be easier if you are tall.

name: Slabmaster
description: If you like slab I would highly recommend this route! This route is a slab climbers paradise with a few hand friction moves. The crux is committing to moving up when you feel like you could peel off at any moment.    Start half way between Slippery Corner and Pine Tree Crack. Work up on alright feet and a few good hands. Once  you are about 8-10 feet of the deck you hit the crux, the hands disappear and the feet become desperately small. Using friction with your palms trust your feet and move you feet up slowly, for a few move. You will eventually come across a good crimp that feels like a jug because you have been climbing on tiny holds. From here reach up to the jug and continue another 6 feet to the top on easy ground shared with Slippery Corner.    To do this route properly do not traverse left or right to the jugs of the neighboring routes.

name: Slippery Corner
description: Giant low angle corner to the right of Pine Tree Crack, it has been used as a decent more than one time. Not overly exciting, but worth it if you are working on getting used to heights. Only one move that will make you hesitate, often dirty. Finish how ever you are comfortable I suggest up the vertical face straight above the corner...enjoy.

name: Spicy House
description: Sit start on the large side pull and undercling like Captain Condor. Move up through the slot to the sharp loose hold, then move left through a crimp and good sloper to the lip jug used in Fly Boy. Pick your feet and top out straight up using small crimps above the lip. Traversing out left to the crystal crack is easier and reduces the grade.  A fun line and one with a lot of beta options.

name: Starboy
description: If you've done "Flyboy" and wished that there was a rad low start into it, look no further.  This variation is a great power endurance problem, with fun hard moves on a 45 degree wall.  Start down and left of "Flyboy", as for "The Oracle". Start with a low left-hand sidepull, and a right hand crimp in the vertical crack about 4 feet off the ground. Find a high foot and pull on with difficulty. Use your core and lock-off in order to snag the horizontal shelf. Match hands and use a lot of core and precise footwork to traverse the horizontal rightwards for a few moves and get into the start of "Flyboy". From here, get amped for the big move. Snag the lip and top out however you want!

name: Underdog
description: Start on the leftside of the crack and traverse to the right using percise feet and think heel hook for the end. the crux is the mantle onto the slab. If your foot blows off on this move it could result in a gash on you legs and an awkward fall onto your side (i bruised my elbow falling here).  An optional finish but a fun finish is up A Cheval. The holds can be sharp on this and a little crumbly. This is a fun traverse though.

name: Whale Calling Condor
description: This link up was shown to me by local John Myles and it is a lot of fun.    Start as for Whales Tail (V4+) and traverse left onto the slopey shelf that starts Ahab Calling (V3) then get your feet situated, move your right hand up to the obvious crimp and make a long left hand move up to a good crimp then make a long right hand move(crux) to the top of Captain Condor (V5).     Although it is a link up it climbs like an independent line so it deserves its own route in the database.

name: The Whale's Tail
description: A fantastic climb.    Start on the sloping ledge at waist height with good feet, make a hard move up and left and continue on the slopers until heading up and out left at the end for a heartbreaking move to the end jug and an easy top out.    A variation (unknown name) goes straight up and a bit harder V5? it makes excellent use on a undercling pinch hold that makes the sequence very doable.

name: Worse Ladder
description: Sit/crouch start to Bad Ladder. Sit below bad ladder with the right hand on a sloping foot hold and the left hand on a bad sloping crimp. Pick your choice of great feet and move up to a pocket, then cross up to the good starting hold of Bad Ladder. Finish on Bad Ladder.

name: The Arete
description: Climb the left side of the arete and find the crux nearer to the top than comfortable. HIGHBALL! This problem is tall and with the crux near the top I hope people do not get on this without being comfortable with the height. I haven't finished this problem due to a wet section at about the fifteen foot market, but I will be back to finish it.    On the EDCL Boulder.

name: The Corner
description: Start below the corner on the face. The start is the crux, once you hit the flake it gets easier. This problem had a variety of styles on it, the start is balance prone until you hit the giant flake, which has fairly positive holds and good feet.PLEASE DO NOT FALL.

name: Crystal Face
description: This route is in the middle of the slab, the start is the crux. Climb the face using crystal features, this is solid at the grade, not an overly fun problem in my opinion, but a good time none the less. The top out is fairly good, there is a good hold on the top about a foot and a half from the edge of the face, so reach for it. HIGHBALL!

name: EDCL
description: Start on the base of the finger crack that faces the road on a big jug. Climb the crack in full view of passersby, careful to not let your head get the better of you on this highball classic.

name: The Flakes
description: Climb above  an obvious "ankle breaker" block on some nice face climbing, past the halfway mark break right with the flake above your head on jugs. HIGHBALL!

name: Garnet Snatcher
description: Start low beneath the arete on a good jug out left, and a nice undercling for the right - the feet are obvious and nice. From there make moves staying left of the arete. The holds get worse as you slap your way up the arete until you reach a glorious jug that will help you mantle out right to finish on Standard.

name: High Voltage
description: Stand start and climb the finger crack on finger locks and face holds. The feet are mostly on the face but the crack does have some good feet especially on the bottom half. the crux on this route is very near the top where the crack becomes a little tighter and the feet are more awkward. Please if you get on this route be comfortable a grade or two above this, because the crux is so high. HIGHBALL!!!    There may be a couple placements for gear on the crack but I wouldn't suggest trusting many of the placements.

name: In The Fastlane
description: This route the crux is right off the ground. You start on two small sidepulls with very good feet, from here you move up and very slightly right, to a series of ledges the top one is the best. Pull over the lip and scramble up the easy rock to the top.    Watch for cars when doing this route, and watch out for the telephone line at the top, you wont get electrocuted but it will take you by surprise.

name: Sherman's March
description: This route is a traverse that starts on a jug on the arete and makes hard moves moving left until the arete next to the road. There area few hardmoves but the crux comes at the end of the traverse with a precise move to a crappy triangle pinch. This move is by far the hardest move on the route and is awkward to get out of.     Once at the left arete climb it up big holds to top out.

name: Standard
description: Climb the jugs on left arete, this route has a couples moves then a good rest in that pattern all the way up. This looks really easy but don't let it fool you there are a few difficult move on it and one is near the top, but for the most part the holds are gigantic and fun. Don't fall in the road. HIGHBALL!    Good first highball.

name: Tronic
description: Start as for EDCL on the jug, and as hard as it will be to not continue up the crack, break right making long moves to block like holds, until topping out, the feet are small and so are the hands but with good route finding skills you will be able to send this route no problem. It is fun, but under climbed because of the four star classic crack next to it, but this route should not be neglected. The top out isn't great but it isn't horrible either, and the crux is in the middle of the face on a particularly long move. Get on this problem but please do not fall into the road the end gets awfully close to the road, so please keep it safe and have a good spotter and don't climb while a car is coming.

name: Eye of the Storm
description: There are two little crimps one at about face height and one above your head if you're not like 7 ft. tall. On the right side of the little arete there is a very good but little foot hold. Power pop up off the ground and get your left foot in this little mossy hole in the rock right above the bottom lip reach up to grab a little side pull then bump up to a good left pinch then top out    This is a stand start stand in between the two little boulders and place your right foot first with the two good crimps    Very fun climb but it could be dangerous so be careful.

name: Katmai Disaster
description: Sit start on the start hold at the very bottom of the overhung traversing rock put your feet on good start holds and pull up a good two finger pocket then reach to a bad little dent in the rock bring your hand up for another two finger pocket when you reach the good jug holds you will be fine just keep traversing right until you can't anymore then go straight up for the finish    Awesome climb just dangerous yet again be careful of the sharp jagged rocks underneath you.

name: Where the Red Fern Grows
description: On the backside of the boulder, there is a face in the shape of a shallow V. This route climbs the right of the two seams. You start on the rock at the base, reach up to a small crimp then get a high foot, pull on, switch feet and work slightly left up to better holds, and a good top out.

name: Dancing Bears
description: The crux of this route is pulling off the ground. To do this you use a slopey arete with your left hand and a crimp that is at a weird angle with your right. Heel hook around the arete with your left foot  and with your right foot use the outside of your foot on a small hold just right of the arete. From this awkward feeling position stand up bringing your right hand to a small rounded crimp out right on the right face, then move your left hand up the arete to a good pinch, then adjust your feet and go to the huge topout.

name: Gary's Fortune
description: For a short route this route has a lot going on in it. Sit start with your right hand on the right arete, and left pinching the left arete. Heel hook on the jug by the tree with your right foot and left foot on a foot on the face. Pull up and make awkward moves surmounting the short overhung face, moving over to the less than vertical part is the crux. If this route went on for another ten feet it would be  classic but because of its shortness, it will never be.

name: B-Boy Stance
description: Start on a shelf to the left of the roof and go to a good sidepull. Get a heel on the shelf and make a big cross to a decent sloper. From here make an incredibly stretched out move to a bad gaston. Control the swing which is followed by more moves of similar nature until a crux move throwing your left hand over the lip with your right hand on a bad crimp. The rest of the moves to the top out are not easy but will feel like nothing if you can get there. Great boulder and definitely worth trying for anyone who can climb v12.    Jumping to the sloper to eliminate the shelf all together has been done and raises the grade to maybe v12/13 but feels very contrived.

name: Beware of the Blot
description: Stand start with a good left hand side pull and a small pinch with your right in a seam. Make a powerful move out right to the good edge, then left hand up to the big side pull. Now set your feet and toss to the lip.

name: The Birth of the Blot
description: This route has jugs, slopers, crimps, a finger lock and a heel hook, sound fun to you?     Its great!    Start with left hand on the jug with your right hand in the finger lock in the crack as for The Blot (V2). Move left through crimps below the bulge and slopers on the lip. I used a heel hook for these moves. The crux is fighting the barn door when removing the heel hook. Once removed the heel hook get your feet back under you and pull over the bulge on crimps to an easy less than vertical highball top out.    This problem climbs under and around the bulge that makes up the left wall of the dihedral of The Blot (V2).

name: The Blot
description: stand start on buldge and first finger pocket. follow the pockets in the crack (crux, really awkward. get up to the arete (using lowers the grade) and up to a good block at top of the corner. top outs pretty straight foward.

name: Hardman Dentist
description: Start as for Pound Crack but after one move exit the crack to the right working holds under the bulge. This is very scary because your body is horizontal for a number of moves, and at this point you are about eight to ten feet off the ground. The hard moves end when you reach over the bulge, to a jug. I personally haven't been on this route but I know several people who have and been there when they worked on it, for this route core strength is a must, along with strong fingers.

name: Limbic
description: Sit Start with you left hand on a flake and right hand on a sloper. There is a good left foot very near the ground, I actually dug some dirt away from it to make use of it. This problem will only feel V3 if you get the right foot beta correct.     Once you have picked you feet make a long move to an almost vertical edge and hold on (crux). Holding this hold requires good body position and tension. Once you latch the hold move youe feet and make a long move up and left to a large edge then top out.

name: Little Boy Stand
description: The stand start for the full line, it's worth doing in it's own right.    Start with a LH pinch on the arete (or a crimp around the corner if you can reach that far, you have other options too, use whatever you want really) and a RH high pinch. Find yer feet, pull on and bump LH up to a high sloper, bump RH to a jug sidepull/pinch. Bump LH again to a better sloper or just go all the way to the jug lip.

name: The Little Boy
description: And his Dream...    This problem is in the running for best v8 at the Pound.   Sit start with a good left hand crimp by the left arete, or use the arete. Grab an undercling with the right hand and figure out the body positioning in order to pull off of the ground. Squeeze the s**t out of the rock and make a burly move up left hand higher on the arete. From here do a little tricky footwork and move the right hand out from the undercling to the right arete. From here position your feet once more for a left hand bump, and then go big right hand to a good pinch higher on that side. Bump another time with the left or go big to another good edge on the arete. From here take a deep breath and make one more committing move to good holds and jugs for the top out.   Stand start around v4/5 and a right exit is also possible from the sit at around v6.

name: Loomit
description: This problem climbs out the roof on the left-hand side of the Pound Crack boulder. Start sitting with some funky pockety holds and make a powerful throw to the sloping rail (the kicker to the left is off-route, apparently). Use ingenious footwork and a lot of body tension to traverse right on the sloping rail until you can make a desperate throw to a decent hold. Keep your feet on or you'll be laying on the large flat rock that's now just below you. Make a couple more powerful, but easier moves on good holds to come around the corner and onto the face. For full value, proceed up the dirty 5.11 on the arete on which you are now established and top out. A good problem to work on in the winter, when the low sun beams in and the friction is good. Would be a classic in my book but for the eliminate start and the butt-dragging nature of the last couple of hard moves.

name: Odd Future
description: The route climbs a vertical seam that has a couple pods in it.     Sit start with left hand in the lowest pod and right hand on a sloper crimp, pick some feet and rock up and move left hand to a crimp in the seam just below the next pod, then lay-back and move your right hand into the pod. Walk your feet out left on the obvious rail and make a move out left to the obvious jug and then make a couple easy obvious moves to the top out.    When I found this route I broke several feet off below the lip for the sit start, I think everything that would come off under there has but just be warned. The amount of rock I peeled off leads me to believe that this has not been done before, or at least from a sit start, if it has and you have info for it let me know and I will update the info.

name: Pickles and Prune Juice
description: This is a possile new route... I did some scrubbing on this problem and there was no sign of anyone climbing on it, but if it has been done before give me the correct name and info and I will gladly change it.    Ok so the route is short comprising of only a few moves but the moves are relatively fun. Sit start in the middle of the face with a single pad crimp for your right hand and  another similar size crimp for your left, the left hand is kinda high. Using the good feet below your right hand pull yourself up moving to a good hold about two feet from the top, from here move your feet up and go to the top, the topout is awesome.

name: Plaque Face
description: This is directly across from The Blot. This is a fun problem to warm up the tendons because the first moves can be a little crimpy, and starts on OK feet, good fun and don't miss the giant hold out left, the top out is easy.

name: Pound Back
description: When you walk through the "cave" on your right will be two crimps that seem to be always chalked. This is how you locate the route, to start the route move back into the cave a little just past the rounded arete right of the crimps, here you will find a slopey feature use that and some fiction feet to stand up to the lower crimp with your left hand, then bump to the higher crimp, heel hook by your right hand then reach up with your right for a good hold just right of the arete. From here work your way over they top anyway possible (except using the boulder behind you). The top out is fairly good.

name: Pound Back SDS
description: This is a sit start to the broken Pound Back (the crimps on the face used to be much better).     Sit start with two low opposing underclings. Pull hard to get your butt off the ground and make a desperate RH throw to a great slopey jug. Work your LH up to the upper of the two slippery face crimps. Bump your RH up the sloper to make room for a very high right heel. Move RH up to perfect crimp around the corner. Get LH on the arete, bump it up to a great hold, then make a big committing move to the lip (it's a huge jug!).

name: Pound Crack
description: Don't let its height deter you from this one, it is as enjoyable, safe and wonderful to climb as it looks. Start on the obvious holds in the crack, use the block for feet and motor through the low crux to the jug, and a few hand jams later you'll be wishing that it went on for 100+ more feet and you had a rope on.

name: Power of One
description: Sit start below the over hang on two decent crimps, pick from the limited choices of feet and make a large move up and right to a jug at the lip.     One move wonder but a fun one at that.

name: The Return of The Blot
description: Start as for The Blot but move right to a flake near the lip. This route has small feet, but the feet are there, the holds are pretty good with a variety of different holds, this route will test your overall climbing skill by forcing you to use gastons, crimps, sidepulls. The top out is the giant quartz jug and the top out is easy.    V3 Variation: Stand start on the rounded sidepull at six feet and go straight up.

name: The Thwart
description: Just to the right of the starting jug of The Blot is a large left facing sidepull at about 6 feet. Grab this with your hands, pick some feet and toss for the quartz holds at the lip, then top out.    In the Kemple guide the topo for this route is miss labeled. After some discussion between myself and Christian Prellwitz this is how we both agreed the route actually climbed. If you have any info that contradicts this please let me know and I'll update the description

name: West End
description: Climb the obvious line above the block on the perfectly vertical face, the flakes look easy but if seen from the top the are not as good as they look. The holds are small but not tiny there are some long moves, but nothing huge. The route is just sustained, and none of the holds are as good as they look. It doesn't get a ton of activity because of the height of the problem, but it is a worthy problem. Be safe when one this route have plenty of spotters and pads.

name: Dr. Doom
description: This route is a low traverse that finishes with the same top out as for Prow Wow. Sit start in the same spot as for The Meek but insted of going up move right through the white streak to a large pocket, match that pocket and move right hand to a crimp in the white streak. From here get your feet situated and make a long move to a good hold shared with Prow Wow, settle your feet and top out with Prow Wow.    Using any of the higher holds, makes the route much easier....

name: The Meek
description: This route is a lot of fun for beginner climbers. It can be done from a stand start or a harder sit start. It is very straight forward climb up the left arete of the up hill side of the Prow Wow boulder (as if looking towards the road from behind the boulder). The crux if any is the top out because it is sharp and sort of painful, but much fun.    If you are out with someone new bring them to do this problem.

name: Prow Wow
description: This is a great 18+ move traverse. Sqat starts down and right of the obvious horn on a medium shelf. bump up to the jug on the top of the horn and start to work left around the front of the horn to slopers. This is where the feet start to go nuts on you. Keep switching feet from the staring hold, to the top of the horn, while moving hands across the lip on slopers (VERY cramped and awkward crux). Not much for feet below your hands so keep them on the horn and move up the small arete to a crappy crimp then to the topout on a square block. Very pumpy topout.    While none of the holds will push your limits, the endless sequence of 18+ moves (least amount ive been able to do it in) will push your problem solving skills and your forarms. Definatly super pumpy at the end and the top out.     Im sure i dont have the first ascent but ive never seen anyone on it, so we dubbed it Prow wow. Also thought it was about a low v3 but some guys iv done it with are calling it v4. If you know the real name and grade, your imput would be loved.

name: Short Layback
description: While this route is not on the Prow Wow Boulder it is on thirty feet to the right and a little down hill (If looking uphill).    Sit start on the arete on jugs and climb the arete on big holds to the top. Top out on good holds. This arete is short but is really enjoyable but over way to quickly.    There is a young tree very close to the top out of this route please do not rip it out!

name: Temptation
description: This route is a low traverse with the crux being the sit start. Start on the lowest part of the wall and traverse right and top out with The Meek (V0). This route is sharp and for the shorter climber the top out can prove to be difficult.     Putting your hands over the lip is not allowed :)

name: B-B-B-Beginner
description: On the uphill side of the Ships Prow boulder, on the obvious weakness in the middle of the face. Top out is huge. Really easy moves from a stand start will gain the top.    The route is a little dirty, but still fun.

name: Bang Boom
description: On the ships prow boulder, it is five fet left of the sharp arete by the tree. Sit start on the undercling and small crimp to the right bump left up to a "side" pull and right into smaller crimp, move feet up and make big move to slopper/crimp do some fancy moves to the top.

name: Kraken
description: Sit start as for Bang Boom (V2) then traverse left on under-clings, using tricky footwork. Once on double under-clings make a long move to a tricky dynamic top out.     Being short is a distinct disadvantage...    If this has been done before or have any different info let me know, I will be glad to fix it...

name: The Krystle Method
description: This route is defined by balance, short but intense, the holds are small. The top out can feel sketchy. Do it from a stand start. There is no real crux and no powerful moves, so remember your balance and move slowly. Start with your hand about head height with a hand out right and your left right in front of your body pull onto the rock and move your right hand up about two feet. Then stretch out left to a small hard to find hold, once in this position get situated and slowly move right hand above your head to a pretty good hold, match then top out.    There is an alternate sit start here as well maybe half a grade harder. This is on the small sharp flake that is fairly low, the start is cramped and hard, with awkward feet.

name: Pop Top
description: Short but fun route on the Ship's Prow Boulder. Stand start on the small shelves with a high foot, and pop to a bump on top of face, this bump is slopey but if caught just right it is fairly good. The crux comes after this and is actually a foot movement, move your right foot to a shelf, which is bomber but it is really high. Once your feet are on this ledge you can stand on it but the hard part is not over, you must still pull over the top, and besides the bump your right hand is on, the top is fairly blank, there are small indents on the top that must be used also a heel hook with the left foot is a good idea.

name: Port Face
description: Climb the central face starting on the slopey shelf. If you can reach the back of the shelf there is a small incut for your fingers. When starting put your feet on slippery feet and move up and right to a good hold, from here is the crux, mantle onto the slopey ledge and move left hand to a decent hold near the top, stand up completely and pull over the top, the top out couldn't be any better.    I found a sit start for this problem using one left foot and two small crimps way low making a big move to the shelf. The sit start is really low and left of shelf. I believe this move alone makes it V2.

name: Ship's Prow
description: The sharp arete on the Ship's Prow Boulder, is a great route but has potential for an awkward fall into the tree that is just to the left of it. You can climb this from a sit start or a stand start, on good holds. Most of the feet are there but it is a little weird because you are hugging the arete all the way to the top. I recommend this to everyone, it is a lot of fun, with a few weird moves but to keep some adventure in this route I am not going to describe these weird moves, just jump on the route and you will finish with a smile.

name: Thuggish Ancestory
description: Sit start as far left as you can go on left broken left face on a good shelf, from here move right using good feet, and alright hands until you reach the giant good sidepull. This can be done with small face crimps or a long move. Then keep traversing around the blunt arete and finish with pop top, the crux is the last move, in which you need to get high feet and rock over, it is a mantle-ish move.

name: Deacon Variation
description: This is what The Devastating Reverend Tom (V10) would be if the arete was not off...    Start on the two poor sidepulls as for Devastating, and make the first move, then instead of firing to the small ear make a big move out to the slopey jug on the arete. Then top out as for Skip and Sandy.

name: The Devastating Reverend Tom
description: Sit start with hands on sidepulls the right one being very small and with a decent foot, move your right hand first to a slopey crimp/sidepull with a small thumbcatch, then comes the crux move to what has been described as an ear, it is a two finger crimp or a horrible gaston so pick you poison. From there dyno up and right and finish with Skip and Sandy (V3).

name: Empire of Dirt
description: Sit start with hands on decent holds on either side of the arete and a good right foot on the arete. Pull off the ground and stick the sloper on the arete (crux). From here work up and slightly left on big holds and run up the short slab to the top.

name: Skip and Sandy
description: One of my personal favorite V3's. This route is compromised of technique and power moves. Sit start using the crack formed by the block, and progress up and left on a variety of holds including crimps, sidepulls, and gastons. The top crimps are hidden in a dark streak on the boulder so look hard. The top out holds are slopey but there are good feet. If you get scared at the top traverse to the right to gigantic holds, this is off the route but being safe is more important.    A piece of beta information is to use a small crimp two feet to the left of the top of the large block you start on, and cross over to the first rail with your right hand this puts you in a better position to continue the route.    With beta this grade makes sense, without beta it feels a lot harder.

name: Tweekers
description: Start on crimps with your right foot out to the right on a rail and your left foot on a small foot right in front of you at knee height (I am six feet). Then pop up to a triangle hole near the top that sticks out facing the road, then put your foot on one of the starting holds and move hands over the slopey top, hold on to the slopey top for dear life and pull over the top. This is a short problem but requires power so got at it if V2 is your limit this will be tough.    Awesome fun, I do this problem ever time I am there.

name: Under Wicked Skies
description: Start sitting with a left heel around the arete and hands crossed on the arete there is one good spot to do this, also pick a spot you like for your right foot. From here  move right hand to a crimp and adjust feet to bump and to a triangle pocket that looks much better than it is. Move left hand to crimp you just hand your right hand on. From here make sizable move to good hand for right, adjust yourself and make dead-point to a jugish hold up the arete rock over and top out.    The crux is getting off the ground and the dead-point at the end. This route has cool flow, and think heel hook whenever you are stuck and maybe a drop knee.     This route was shown to me by someone who originally told me they thought it would go at V7, well its not that hard, but the first move can be discouraging because it could take a while to get, one you get it, you will love the move.

name: Wicked Deacon
description: This is the right exit for Under Wicked Skies. From the start of under wicked skies, follow the arete/lip to the top of the boulder. This variation/exit makes the big deadpoint/dyno mandatory, and adds a bit of a compression move after. Finishing out the arete and mantling above skip and sandy proves to be pumpy and tall.

name: Novocain Stain
description: The sit start is the crux. Pull off the ground using an awkward large block sidepull with your left hand and right hand on a weird crimp. Pull up and rock onto the ledge/shelf, then make generic moves to the top out.    This route was showed to me by a friend a few years ago and I don't know the ascent history, my friend never did it he just thought something could go up it. I did it and it isn't anything special but it is something to do when you have done all the classic at the grade.

name: Smoke and Mirrors
description: Sit start in the "cave" with both hands left of the arete on crimps but with big feet. (There is also a really small crimp just right of the arete proper that I normally use because I feel it puts my body in position better.) Pull off the ground to match on the large slopey shelf. From here power up the arete using holds on either side of the arete. To obvious top out holds on the right side of the arete.    Foot work and sequence is key to sending this route. The kemple guide has it listed as only climbing the left side of the arete, however that is very contrived and making use of both sides of the arete flows better and still sustains the grade of V6.

name: Backstage Passes
description: The left trending weakness from the middle of the face. This route has plenty of big holds and feet and is a good problem for beginners or for someone who want to do a nice easy route. Also a good warm up because it can become harder, if you eliminate the big holds.     This can also be used as a down climb.

name: Closet Braiding Beads
description: Sit start on the left end of the nose and move up with the arete, I felt this may be easy for the grade, but I not going to say it for certain because every route is different for different people. Not an overly memorable route.

name: Cranium
description: Sit start as for Quincy Market But traverse right after the first move over the stone wall and top out on great holds. The moves over the stone wall are the crux because in your head all you can think about it not cracking your "cranium" off the wall below you. There is a hold with and X on it, just in case you don't know this means that this hold cannot be trusted to hold, it cannot be pulled out but if you have all your weight hanging on it there is potential it could pop out resulting in the dreaded "cranium" crash.    This route is named for the potential damage you can do to your cranium if you fall on the wall.

name: Front and Center
description: Stand Start on crimps and climb the awesome face up and right, the is a hold that looks like a really bad crimp to your left as high as you can reach, is in fact a bomber incut hold, which is a God send at this point, the route is a little harder if instead of breaking right to the jug, break left and top out with the seam, to a crimp then bump to a jug at the top.    There is also a sit start, which starts on the feet for the stand start, this is a hard one move added onto it. Myself and others who have done it feel it makes it (V2).

name: Opie
description: The crux is right at the beginning first two moves then you are good.    All the holds are very positive, nothing is bad.    Sit start on the little crimp with right hand and left hand on the down slanting crimp just above first hold. Toe hook under the little overhang just off the ground with the other foot back on the little ledge. Heel hook just above toe hook then make the first push up to the crux. Grab the jug and finish the climb up and over the top.    The decent. Either climb down the backside of the boulder or climb down backstage passes.

name: Quincy Market
description: Just on the other side of the stone wall as you enter the Pound, there are some jugs to your right, sit start and move up the slightly overhanging face on jugs, when get to the lip where there is a hidden jug just over the lip. So stand on the stone wall before you try it and locate this gem of a hold. Once in this hold move your feet up and reach to the obvious slopey slot, once in this slot move feet up again, then move hands over the top on more slopey holds, with your right hand bump to a good hold about six inches back. At this point you want to have the weight of yourself on your left foot so you can put your right foot into the hidden hold just over the lip. Once in this hold with you right foot the problem is a walk up from there. This is hard because you have to feel the holds for your feet because you cannot see them.    I feel this is harder than (vo).     Also be sure to have a spotter because of the nature of this route if you cut off at the wrong point you will land on your back and it hurts trust me I have taken this fall. Also have the spotter watch you from hitting the wall to the right, I have seen two people sprain their ankles from awkwardly landing on the wall.

name: Re-Fresh
description: Sit start on the ledge and climb straight up, crimpy near top. The start is super easy and the top is also easy, just need a little balance on the large ledge when reaching for the small crimps. Being tall is a distinct advantage, I feel like this route may actually be a grade harder if you are short. The top out is good.

name: Reflection Terminal
description: Sit start in the middle of the "nose" and top out straight up the face after pulling the first awkward moves. The rock that comes out of the ground by the sit start does not count, first move is really awkward, but incredibly fun. For this move use great hands but almost no feet, what must be done is heel hook by your hands with your left foot and use a small flake under the overhang for your right foot and crank hard off the ground to a good hold which is a fairly long move, from here the hard stuff is over, just cruise up the really easy slab to top out.

name: Stone Market
description: A fun and powerful route. Sit start on the triangle jug as for Stone Wall and move to the good crimps on the lip and traverse the lip right until you intercept Quincy Market then top out that problem.     Very fun route with powerful moves in the middle, if powerful isn't your strong point you can technique through it on slopers.

name: Stone Wall
description: Sit start on the triangle shaped flake on the left side on the wall. Pull up to slopers and top out, the route is fairly straight forward, but the slopers are really hard, they can actually be described better as a face with shallow rounded indents, to top out with. The slopers will shred the skin off your fingers, so if you can climb with tape on your fingers it may be a good decision, or else some blood may be shed.    Way hard for V2

name: Super Chalk
description: Sit start on the great hold on the right side of the "nose" and make a large move up to a jug, use a heel to keep your balance after this move. Then continue up the arete on easy holds until you have reached the height of the arete, then rock over onto the top of the rock and you are done. The top out of this route is at the same place as      Re-fresh.

name: Wicked Traverse
description: Start as for Quincy Market. Climb easily up to the lip then start the hard leftward traverse on slopers across the lip. Go around the arete and continue up progressively easier climbing to the high point of the boulder, this shares a finish with Re-fresh. This route is defined by slopers and fairly good feet, so avoid the pump and enjoy the route.

name: Agent Orange
description: The classic highball sharp righthand orange arete on the big boulder visible from the trail just a minute from the small parking lot.  There are two bolts over the top for a toprope, and I recommend that you TR it first.  The grade is accurate, but the beta is a bit cryptic and onsight will feel harder.      By the way, don't fall.

name: Climbing High?
description: Sit start with your hands on the side pull and the crimp pull up use your heel to stabilize yourself reach off to the left for another side pull bump up to another crimp type hold reach up for the last hold and top out     The top out is a bit sketchy because of the moss and pine needles.

name: McCandless
description: There is a big undercling for a starter hold feet are right under it pull up to a side pull on the left near the arete match hands on the side pull reach up diagonal to grab another side pull bang up to a flake to the left then reach up to the finish hold just above that

name: Shipyard
description: Sit start on shelf with a small seam and make a big move to a good incut up and to the left, from here pick some feet match hands and make another big move up to a good jug, then top out. (I did not do the top out because it was wet)

name: Stains of Time
description: Sit start with right hand in a large undercling and left hand in a good pocket. Move left hand up to a good side pull and get ready for the business. Making use of a odd pinch/sidepull, an undercling and a crimp work up to a good top out. For me the key to this route was where I placed my right foot.

name: Time Bandit
description: Start sitting as far under the twin aretes as possible. Then pull off the ground and slap up the sides on progressive better holds eventually making a long move to the top.    This route is very fun, I would highly recommend it!   The route is also very obvious and I am sure it has been climbed before, if anyone has info on it let me know.

name: Who Killed the Butler
description: This route is short and has some loose stuff on it but it is fun. Start with your hands on a bulge that sticks out from arete and pick any number of feet. Move left and to a good incut hold, then move right hand up a little higher to "slot" from here throw your foot up near where your starting hand was. Then rock up to a higher sharp pocket that is just up and right. Then rock further up and go to the top. The topout is huge.    Down climb where ever you feel comfortable, there are many options.

name: Allie's Route
description: Sit Start on two small crimps and make a deadpoint crux move up to a good full pad crimp with your right hand. After sticking that move bring your left hand up to a knob at the same height and then make a few more mellower moves to the easy top out.    The rock is still pretty sharp but it is a good way for beginners to learn how to deadpoint because the crimp you go to during the crux is thankfully smooth.

name: The Ballad of Mr. H
description: This route is short and sharp, and it is comprised only a few moves, but these moves are fun and pack a punch. Start on an excellent starting hold and excellent feet, stand up to a good gaston in the white quartz. From here move your feet up and move right hand to the sharp sloper right below the gaston. Get situated for the crux move, once comfortable make long move up to a small crimp up and right, sticking this crimp is the crux, once on the crimp get higher feet and move go to the good top out. Being short might be a distinct disadvantage on the crux move, but may help in moving your feet up before the move.

name: Corporal Charte
description: Sit Start at the start jug of The Ballad of Mr. H V2- and traverse left using small crimps and a sloper and end at the top out of Allie's Route V0.    This route has small crimps and the use of a heel hook will aid the fight to stop from barn dooring off the crux. The crux comes right after your left hand leaves the starting jug.     There will be different ways to do this problem depending on how tall you are and being short might be a disadvantage.

name: The Leftist
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Light Doses
description: Start this problem standing matched with some solid crimp underclings and some good feet on the slab below. The crux of this problem is pulling off the ground and establishing both feet on the wall and moving up to the sloper above. Once on the sloper, move up and left over the bulge and topout on decent holds.

name: Paradiddle
description: Starts the same as The Leftist. Left hand down low on a crimp by the left arete. Right hand on the slopey ball. Bump RH up to the trianglular crimp. Get a good heel toe cam and make a big move out right to a sloping jug. Use some body tension and possibly a knee bar to get your left hand on the starting right hand hold. Swing under the boulder and match the left hand to the sloper/crimp jug. Get some feet and toss up to a small crimp on the right side of the arete. Stand up and grab a left hand side pull in the crack. Top out on sloper jugs.

name: The Rightist
description: The other obvious climb on the boulder, The Rightest starts with both hands matched on the sloper ledge that's low and around the corner from the right arete.     Bury a good heal hook and work your way up the right arete. There's an awesome little crimp about 2/3rds of the way up the right arete that is essential in finishing the climb.

name: Magdalena
description: Start sitting at the base of the crack, put your left hand in the crack and right on a face crimp. Start with both feet in the crack, pull up moving you right hand up into the crack and work up the crack. Lift you left foot and heel hook the small rail just left of the crack, then pop up to better holds and finish up the crack. This part is extremely dirty and I will try to clean it up next time I am out there.

name: Pinot Noir
description: Sit Start below the face on good holds. Pull up and climb a mixture of jugs and good crimps to an easy top out.

name: Certain Frequency
description: This is a hard compression block with some really good movement. Sit start under the boulder with the left hand on the left arete and the right hand on a good sidepull. Pull on and make your way up both of the aretes using a variety of heelhooks and toehooks. Somehow figure out you can move to the textured hold on the face, from here power your way up to the lip before matching and mantling over onto the slab.

name: Dab Control
description: A short, steep and powerful compression line with a hard topout. The crux of this problem is avoiding the dab on the rock of which this problem climbs over. There is a lot of body tension involved to avoid the dab. This problem is a surprisingly fun line once you get over the dabbiness,  Slide down under the overhang with right hand on the arete and the lefthand on a low left sidepull. Pull on and move the right hand up to a crimp edge on the arete before moving the left hand up to another sidepull. Once here stay tight and make a difficult move to the lip. Match and figure out how to get over and onto the slab dab free.

name: Los Pollos Hermanos
description: Sit start with your hands match on the jug on the arete. Work up the arete using a crucial heel and a tough move to the lip. If it were taller it would get three stars for sure, super fun moves.    Really not sure where to put the grade on this on climb it and let me know!    Also the top needs to be cleaned soon. It will be done shortly.

name: New Freezer
description: Sit start low under the short steep wall with each hand compressing the two aretes. Pull on and make a few hard moves to the lip of the short boulder before a hard mantle onto the slab. This problem provides some powerful compression moves at the grade and a full value topout for a short boulder.

name: Pollo Campero
description: Sit start matched on the horizontal rail. The left hand is good, while the right hand is a bit slopey. Find your feet and deadpoint up to a good edge before hitting the lip and traversing on slopers and eventually jugs in order to top out.

name: S.F.
description: An excellent steep splitter crack! Start low in a fist jam and some foot cams, then pull up into the thinning crack and make your way to the lip. Turn the lip, jump back down and do it again. Pure jamming joy.

name: Things in the Woods
description: Among the jumble of rocks on the right side of Monsters hides this unlikely, and classic, problem. The problem climbs a beautiful steep face that is streaked with vertical quartz intrusions.     Start sitting. Use sidepulls, pinches, and drop knees to power and technique your way up the face. A heroic throw to the lip provides a fitting end to this amazing problem.

name: Twisted Sister
description: Start on a spike jug in the steep roof and power your way up through cryptic moves to a fun top out. This route feels impossible until you get the beta just right. My only hint is a kneepad :)    I originally heard this was a v7 but I have worked on it and a few of my friends have sent and we all agree its closer to v6.

name: Under The Bed
description: If compression is your thing I would highly suggest this short route that packs a punch. The crux of this climbing is the first 5 feet.     Start sitting with you right hand on the arete and left on a good sidepull. Slap your right hand up higher on the arete and with fancy foot work move your left hand to the jug at the lip. Then top out using good holds on the arete.

name: Supreme Clientele
description: A superb problem over an awkward and scary landing.     Stand start at the base of a good right trending flake system and follow the system up to it's apex at around 10-15 feet.    From here cross up to a slopey hold above you head and position your feet for a large unwind dynamic move up and out right to a large flat rail. Not committing or falling here could have severe consequences. Once the jug is latched, match and do a few more hard moves up to the lip of the boulder/cliff. The top of the rock is slopey and not as good as you'd like. Stay tight and figure out a way to mantle the beast.

name: The 5.8 Crack by the Road
description: Yes, that's right. It's called the 5.8 Crack by the Road, but it is in fact 5.7. I can't explain it.     However this is a really fun climb. I think it's the most fun moderate route at this crag. Very few people bring trad gear to Rumney, so on a busy day I like to bring a small selection of gear, and I can get on all kinds of fun routes while the strict sporty folk stand in line for the classics.     What can I say? It's a crack. Follow it and have fun. Mostly hand sized crack with some face holds.

name: Arm and Hammer
description: The business of Arm and Hammer is definitely crimps, however a the slabby exit moves will be memorable nonetheless. Some of the hardest moves are right off the ground, so stick clip that first bolt!

name: Asbury Park
description: One of the more fun moderate routes at the 5.8 Crag. You will find it on the far left end of the cliff. Follow the line of bolts wandering slightly up right following the blunt low-angle arete past crimpy and slabby moves to the top.     The crux is just past the first bolt and its a bit stout for 5.7. I feel like it's gotten harder with use. Very crimpy. A few more tricky parts but nothing nearly as hard as you finish. At the top, follow cracks to the clips.

name: Blueballs at Christmas
description: Blueballs is a super committing lead on very small gear for the first 40-50 feet. Most people toprope it, and it's probably a good thing because not everyone has the skills and cool head that is required to climb a hard R rated route like this. I worked it out on toprope first, then led it with one piece of gear (a purple TCU) and a few draws for the bolts at the top. I hear the TCU is bomber, but I don't wish to test it.     Starting to the right of the classic, Romancing the Stone (5.10c), climb the face on tiny crimps eventually meeting up with Romancing at its right trending traverse, at which point you will have some bolts to clip. Crimpy, crimpy, crimpy.

name: Bolt And Run
description: Climb up and over a few steep bulges trending left. Fun climbing leads to a confounding crux that most people solve by moving left and using a few holds on the corner. If you climb this section directly, it might bump up the grade a smidge. But it is more fun to do it at 5.9. The crux involves a big move to an incut crimp that is often tick-marked.     Being the only 5.9 at the crag, it is also the best 5.9 at the crag so make sure you climb it.

name: Chimney of Doom
description: Few people have bothered with this dirty, wet, mossy, ugly, cobweb infested, chimney. I've done it twice, haha. I like that sort of thing.     Out of respect for the average climber, I only gave it one star; however, if you are in to the kind of climbing described above you will love it.     Chimney up, passing a large chock stone and top out returning to the beautiful world above.

name: Granny's Route
description: This route right now would be described as chossy at best, Jim Shimberg cleaned this route a few years back for two reasons, an easier climb for beginners and an alternative to walking around the cliff to put up a top rope. This climb is fun even in the mossy conditions. Without the moss the holds can seem sharp because it is a newer route. There is no defined crux but as the route is now the crux would be dealing with the mossy holds. This route could be close to the same quality as A Week With Pete with just a little bit of love, I am going to try to clean this line once the ice melts off of it. The route itself goes straight up the slab on good moves, if you are the 5.8 Crag and don't mind some moss get on this route you will have some dirty fun.

name: License to Ill
description: License to Ill is one of the best climbs at the crag, move for move. The climbing is interesting and exciting, and the gear is good enough where you need it. I think it is more PG13 than R, but the guidebook says R due to a recorded ground fall, so I will too. It's not as scary as Blue Balls at Christmas.     So, you follow interesting moves up a flake and out left to a letter box slot (protect with TCU) climbing to the crux in the upper third of the route. A pretty big move to a good crimpy hold with a small(I use a #7 stopper I think) but solid nut at your waist. You can prolly get away with smaller crimpy moves too.     Climb it on TR first if you are not totally solid in the grade, because it is a little spicy.

name: Milksnake
description: Milksnake is a cool trad route that sees little traffic.      Start in the same techy corner as for Milktoast (5.10d) past 3 bolts and the crux of this route to the roof. As you get to the roof rather than going left as you would for that route break right up a crack/steep ramp (protects well with trad gear) that is more balancy and tricky than hard. Follow this system to the top of the cliff and the anchor.

name: Milktoast
description: A fun climb.  The bottom half is fairly technical with broad holds which lead up to a small roof.  Above the roof there is s striaght up fun crimp fest (.11a) or some friendlier (but not much) holds to the left.

name: Moe Pup Sensation
description: Nice face climbing for the first 2 bolts brings you into the slabby section. Make some committing moves for the next 2 bolts and you'll be rewarded with a great jug. After the last bolt there's a ramp of smooth rock with a couple good foot holds. This ramp looks like a ledge when looked at from the ground. Go up the ramp and you're at the anchor.

name: Only a Crow
description: A one move wonder on the far right end of the crag up the hill from Arm and Hammer (5.11b).     Start up easier rock to gain a stance, a few moves reach the crux (mostly crimps) to more moderate climbing. A few more tricky moves but for the most part the lower crux is the one to beat.     Not the best route of the grade, but on a busy day it is worth doing.

name: Pump Up the Volume
description: An appropriately named route, fighting the pump is the red point crux as each move tends to be easier than the last, but by the end of the climb, you could swear that the moves are getting harder. The route starts from a ledge that heads out left from the start of Sky Pilot (5.11b). Stick clip the first bolt and climb right in to the crux, a sequency series of tiny crimps and footwork leading to better holds and less technical climbing, but you will get pumped unless you are a tough girl (or boy).     It was one of my first 5.12b's, and I think it is a good first climb of the grade.

name: Raven
description: Raven is one of the more obscure routes in the area and does not see a lot of traffic.  The start is a little vegetated, but it's not too bad.  Climb the dirty corner past a couple of bolts and a pin (back up with a medium stopper).  From the pin, make some awkward moves up on to a large, flat ledge and clip the next bolt.  Continue straight up the slightly overhanging headwall.  The crux is clipping the bolt at the top of the headwall (if you blow the clip, you'll hit the ledge).  Mantle through a couple more awkward ledges and then work right to the anchors.  Strange climb, but worthwhile.

name: Romancing The Snake
description: Climb the first 4 bolts of Romancing the Stone then break left in to the upper crack of Milksnake (5.10c) and finish with trad gear. This finish is less pumpy and a little more direct than the right hand traverse on Romancing the Stone. Climb up to the Milksnake anchors (they are set back so extend them for lowering or toproping). This is a better choice of TR climb than the regular Romancing due to the more direct line so you don't have to bother with directionals and all that.

name: Romancing the Stone
description: Romancing the Stone is the most distinguishable climbs at 5.8 Crag, as is follows the first line you see as you approach the cliff. The first third of the climb is characterized by technical 5.10 face climbing that is punctuated by an exit move on the "romancing stone," an brick sized tooth that has been wobbly for as long as anyone can remember. In the immortal advice of Tenacious D, use this hold "gently." A rest of sorts can be found before launching into a pumpy traverse and jug haul to the chains.

name: Sky Pilot
description: Sequency 5.10 climbing up a featured crack leads to one or two dicey traverse moves that span between the end of the crack and a series of positive holds. The upper half of the is featured by a series of horiztonals that climb like a ladder.

name: Snake Skin Slab
description: Snake Skin Slab is one of the more difficult routes on the left side of the crag.  The crux is thin face climbing just past the first bolt (which is a little easier if you use holds off to the right of the bolt line).  Sustained climbing past three more bolts leads to the anchors.  There is a small runout between the last bolt and the anchors that can be protected with a small cam.

name: The Terrace
description: The Terrace is a slabby 5.8 climb with one or two awkwardly committing moves on small holds. While worthwhile, this is really the type of climb that you wire in hopes of skunking your friends.

name: Apocalypse Later
description: What a great climb. I can't get on it enough. If you are looking for a project at this grade or just looking to warm up before a day of hard projecting, this is a must do.     The route climbs the 45 degree overhang with killer huecos, then breaks right on to the vertical crimp fest.       Start up the short slab and on to the steep inverted hueco covered face. Move quickly and fight the pump, because you need to make a move to the right to gain a crimpy face and it can be a pumpy experience if you wear out your arms on the first section. On the top section, sequence is important so plan ahead.

name: Bad Seed
description: Bad Seed was originally rated 5.12a, but due to some unplanned hold exfoliation, it is now considered to be 5.12d. Climb the crimpy face to a low crux- a big move off an undercling of questionable size. Finesse, slope and undercling your way up for a few more moves and punch it to the chains.    Holds break off this thing like the plague...the beta changes faster than a runway model. In any case, get the tendons working and have at it!

name: Captain Fingers
description: Another awesome 5.11c not quite as perfect as its neighbor of the same grade, Apocalypse Later, but still not to be missed. "Holy crimpers" this thing will make you work your fingers (hence the name). The hardest moves are at the bottom, and it's just a matter of not pumping out your crimp muscles as pretty much every hold is crimpy. There is however a creative rest toward the top that will put the route in the bag for you, find it and love it.

name: Corporal Punishment
description: Corporal Punishment is steep and crimpy like the other routes at the crag, but not as memorable as the other 5.11's there in my humble opinion. It's definitely worth climbing; just make sure your fingers are all warmed up, because it is crimptastic.     Start from a ledge right of Captain Fingers and climb crimps that are pretty good to a crux just before the chains.

name: Good Earth
description: Crux is protected by the 3 hanging draws. Shares the start with Bad Seed but stays right. Shouldery moves with two decent rests followed by a hideously sharp finish when clipping the anchors

name: Kate's Arete
description: This is a great first lead for some one just learning the mechanics of sport climbing with comfortable stances to clip from and an opportunity to learn how to run the rope through the anchor to retrieve your draws. The route follows a series of steps up the arete to a few face moves at the top.     Great beginner fun. May be wet sometimes.

name: Serenity Now
description: Serenity Now is a great route to get on when folks are waiting in line for the "classic" 5.7s at the Meadows. You can normally get on this route on a busy day, and I'd say it's one of the best routes of the grade close to the parking lot.     You start up the same slab as Apocalypse Later (5.11c), but head left around the corner into the wet gully. Without wetting your feet, climb up on to the right hand wall of the gully and follow the bolts to the quick clips. The crux is on the upper part of the climb and is done in a few different ways, all of which give you your money's worth for the grade. Kinda tricky.     When lowering, keep the rope moving because the rope tends to run over some kinda sharp rock.

name: Supreme Onion Sacrifice
description: The far left route at the wall, just left of the left gully, Supreme Onion goes up the slightly over hanging often wet wall. There are a few tricky moves at about 2/3 of the way up the route, as the route heads right before going straight up to the top. A good rest can be gained near the crux.     People who don't figure out the beta say the route sucks. Those who figure it out say it's fun. Which one are you?    The only down side to this one in my mind is the wetness. Bummer.

name: They Come and They Go
description: Climb right side of off width by a tricky move up right that's not actually in the off width crack. After mounting ledge move further right to head back left to off width to do another tricky move to gain decent foot ledges. Above this is a small oak tree in the off width dirt now. Standing on the outside edges move up and clip tree. Go left onto knobby face and run it out to a bolt (5.4). At bolt moving left carefully on blocks is easiest way up here and awkward. Climb has gotten very lichen dirty now, move right up past bolt to small diagonal downward facing corner to move up to reach a 2 bolt belay. Climb filthy rock for 70ft with 2 protection anchors (5.2) to trees and rappel back to the bolt belay. Nice view and a very large, very dirty slab. There are fragrant ferns in this area that can be easily avoided.

name: The Anchovy Caper
description: Another nice recent addition to the area. The climbing on the slabby section is technical and thought provoking. The bottom is the crux for most (unless the trees are used for feet).    Start up the face between the trees on sidepulls and crimps till you can gain the lower angle face above. Continue following the bolts while you smear and layback your way past good flakes on the left to the top. This upper part is very fun if you like that kind of stuff.

name: Armed and Dangerous, and Off My Medication
description: A Rumney classic that deserves a spot on every 5.10 climbers tick list.
