The first time I climbed this route, I broke off what I though was a great flake-handhold climbing left of the bolt at the bulge, thus initiating what was only my 5th totally unexpected fall in 50+ years of climbing, but the rock is generally solid.  P4- Up the easy pegmatite rock directly above the belay to "white slab #2". Cross this on a left-diagonal, passing 2 bolts, to reach a stance at an overlap with a pine tree. [Optional belay here, highly recommended for those climbing on a 60m rope] Over the overlap [via the tree, easy...via rock-only, not so easy!] and continue up and left on slab (or thrash up the "forest" as per the FA) to a dbl bolt anchor. 210-215 ft (62-63m) 5.6  P5- The "Orgasmo Slab" pitch. There it is...climb it ! 130-140 ft, 5.7-5.8, 3 bolts plus gear.   Dbl-bolt, rap ring anchor on the grey pegmatite "headwall" about 10 ft below the trees.DESCENT - In the write-up in NEClimbs.com the FA party indicated they walked left through the trees "25 ft" (it's more like 100ft) to the top anchors of Oct. Sundae and rapped that route with double 60m ropes.  All anchors on Oct. Sundae are set for rapping, while those lower on Road North are NOT, although the top anchor and the anchor at the base of “orgasmo slab” do have rings (top) or quick links (base of "orgasmo slab"). It is also possible to rap with double 60m ropes in the following: 1) Down the Orgasmo slab to its anchors (135-140 ft), 2) a long (and a bit messy) diagonal rappel to get to October Sundae's rap station (the top of Oct Sunday's 3rd rap) 3) the long Rap over the Overhang, 4) the rap to the top of Oct Sun.'s P1, 5) the rap down to the  base.

name: Yowza
description: A nice fun route on the far left of the cliff. It's pure adventure climbing where you climb a pitch, bushwack through trees, getting to a new section, passing more trees and so on. You have no idea what will come up next! Most of the route is 5.5 terrain with some 5.7 moves on every pitch.Note: The route is rated 5.9 because of the fourth pitch. It does however have a new 5.7 variation, keeping the whole route at that grade!START- From the base of October Sundae bushwack left along the cliff till you get to a nice clean white slab on the far left side of the cliff. At the slab, scramble up on the left edge of the slab to a small dirt ledge. (See Photo of the correct slab to start on) P1. Follow the path of least resistance up the slab with some gear here and there up to a two bolt anchor. 170' 5.6-5.7P2. Here you have two options:* Climb up veering left over over a triangular right facing flake and continue up the slab to the trees. 120' 5.6* Traverse left with delicate moves past the bush to the slab behind and continue up through some fun moves to belay at the trees. 140' 5.6-5.7Move the belay 40 ft past the trees. 40'P3. Climb easier slab to steeper terrain and the headwall with a distinct diagonal crack. Surmount the headwall on the right of the crack for easier moves. For those looking for more interesting moves, use the crack or go left of it. Then continue on easier terrain to the trees. 195' 5.6-5.7Move the belay 50 ft past the trees. 50'P4. You have two options here:* When you get to the trees above, go right through the trees. When looking up you will see a steeper slab with a blue bolt. This is the crux of the route. Climb the slab and then veer right over easier featured terrain to the trees. 190' 5.9* To keep the route at 5.7 you can instead go straight up through the trees and you will see a head wall literally right where the trees end and the start of the pitch. Climb this head wall using underclings and fun moves. Then veer right (and you will see the blue bolt to your right from the 5.9 variation). Continue up and right through easier and featured terrain to the trees. 170' 5.7Move the belay 50 ft past the trees. 50'P5. Here you also have two options:* Climb the really nice slab straight up. Halfway up there's a small pocket for pro, but other wise not much else. Then veer right and traverse right all the way to the October Sundae top anchor. 170' 5.6* If you want more pro and featured terrain you can go up just right of the clean slab and when reaching the top veer right and traverse right all the way to the October Sundae top anchor. 170' 5.5

name: The Apron
description: A fun little climb with a nice arete on the first pitch. It's a little dirty and could use some cleaning.    P1. Climb short steeper section with some gear to the start of the arete. Beware of a loose hold. Follow the arete passing a bolt and some easier terrain to a tree ledge and a pine tree on the right. The original belay was at an old almost dead questionable pine tree more in the left/center, so we moved the anchor (and added new webbing) to a nicer tree on the right. 5.5 120'    P2. Move through the trees to the next part of the cliff and climb easier featured terrain. Gear belay at a crack. 5.4 160’    P3. Over the bump and easy slab to tree ledge with rap anchor. There was no rap ring and only an old torn buried in the moss webbing when we got there so we added more webbing and left a biner. 5.2 70'    Once at the top, you can bushwack uphill to the next climb, The Arete. An outstanding route and the main reason for doing this route.   Descent: Two raps. The first one just barely reach to next tree ledge with double 60m, but the terrain is easy and safe at that point. Then go through the trees and a second rappel to the ground on climbers left (where you started the climb). Not sure if you can get down to the bottom of the actual cliff.

name: The Arete
description: This is a fantastic climb in a beautiful setting. Especially if you are doing the direct variation, which has lots of delicate fun moves with good gear. The exposed arete higher up leads to a nice ledge and double bolt anchor.     P1. Start on the very left end of the cliff. Tricky first move leads to bolt and easier terrain. Gain the steeper arete with good gear and climb to the top and 2 bolt anchor. 5.7 120'   The Arete Direct   Don't know if anyone climbed this variation before, either way it's highly recommended.    P1. Start more directly (and slightly right) below the obvious high arete, where it’s a little steeper. Climb though flakes and underclings with delicate moves and decent gear. Veer slightly left and join the standard route just before the arete proper. 5.7+ 120’   Descent: Rappel from anchor. Bushwack back down to the top of the Apron and continue rappelling to the ground.

name: A Rope Runs Through It
description: Climb up to the short left facing corner/bulge system. Pull on top of it and slab up to a ledge with a right facing corner with a crack. Follow it up and right placing gear to a bolt anchor below the overhanging wall.

name: Anniversary Route
description: This is a great route with a sport first pitch and a trad second pitch that can be linked into one pitch with some long runners!    P1: Start under a larger roof. Work up the face with gear under a fin of rock to a high first bolt. Pull out the left side of the roof and then move back right across the lip. Pull onto a big ledge with a bolt anchor. 5.10c   P2: Move right of the anchor and gain a ledge. Follow the ramp left into the corner. Follow the fun corner to a bolt anchor at the top. 5.8+   Rap the route back to the ground with a 60m rope. It is best to have some follow to clean the route.

name: Arete Project
description: Climb A Rope Runs Through It and break left at the top to gain an anchor below the overhanging arete. Climb the arete on great rock to an anchor on top.

name: Blue Steel
description: The first bolted line where the approach trail meets the crag. A steep boulder start leads to the face and big holds. An optional #1 or #2 cam can be placed to protect the runout between bolts 3 and 4. Finish up the arete/corner feature to an anchor at the lip.

name: Flying Moose Arete
description: On the left end of the crag look for a sharp arete with bolts on the left. Climb the arete up to a bulge and move left to good holds. Pull the bulge and follow crack/seams to another bulge. Pull the bulge and slab up to the anchor. A short extension pitch leads past a few bolts to the top but most stop at the first anchor.

name: Fortune Cookies
description: This route is the extension to Meat and Cookies and can be done as one long pitch. Climb Meat and Cookies to the anchor. Move up to a ledge and climb the arete on the right face past bolts to a bolt anchor.

name: Lost Boys
description: The wide crack just left of Blue Steel. A large cam in the #6 range is needed to protect the start or smaller gear comes quickly. Climb the wide crack and pull through the roof on hand jams. Follow the crack to a big chockstone which looks scary but is solid. Gain the ledge and step right and finish up the last few bolts of Blue Steel.

name: Magnum
description: A high stick clip on the lip of the roof or a .75 cam will get you started. Start up a couple suspect flake/horns and gain a corner/roof. Pull through the roof up the shallow right facing corner (crux) and gain a foot ledge. Stay right of the final bolts and gain a ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: Mancation
description: Work your way up to a high first bolt. Pull the roof on huge jugs and continue up the face on a variety of holds. Finish at a bolt anchor on top.

name: Meat & Cookies
description: Start just right of a dirty tree filled gully. Climb the face on big holds all the way. Move up and left at the top to a bolt anchor.

name: Project
description: Climb Meat & Cookies to the anchor. Continue straight up off the anchor to a Vermont shaped wall. Climb the center of the face to a thin crux up high and a bolt anchor.

name: Roofies
description: Start up on some boulders at the base under a double tiered roof. Stickclip a high first bolt. Bolder up to a big undercling under the roof. Power through the second roof and gain a niche. Smooth sailing up and right on huge holds to an anchor on a ledge at the top.

name: Side Jobs
description: Climb Meat & Cookies to the anchor. Move up off the anchor to a ledge. Walk left up a ramp to a bolt. Climb the face with great holds past bolts to a foot ledge. Step left and gain a fist/hand crack. Follow the crack to a bolt anchor at the top.

name: The Stink
description: A super safe clip up on slopers! Balance your way up past bolts to a crux near the top. Pull onto a ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: South West Face
description: The neat thing about this climb is that you can combine a worthwhile hike with a technical rock climb and reach a real summit. Even though the overall difficulty is somewhat low the climbing is clean and entertaining. The views are some of the best in all the White Mountains and on a clear day can reach 50-100 miles in all directions. Do this climb for the pure experience of moving over wonderful rough granite in a superb location.  The cliff is at a uniform angle and difficultly the entire way with many locations for climbing protection in both vertical flakes and overlaps. The climbing varies from mostly 5.3 climbing to a few easy 5.4 sections and is always interesting and on attractive rock. The rock is very coarse, naturally clean granite that offers excellent friction. This is a perfect climb to do in your sticky rubber approach shoes. It is possible to climb anywhere on the face but the route described below links the best rock and the longest pitches on the slab.  Pitch 1: Start at the lowest point of rock. Climb straight up stepping over a few overlaps to a belay just down and right of the biggest overlap in the center of the face. 200  Pitch 2: Diagonal up and left under the center overlap eventually stepping over at a break. Follow flakes and cracks past cool holes in the rock up and left around the prominent bush island in the center of the slab. Belay 30 feet up and left of the island at a good overlap. 200  Pitch 3: Step right and climb straight up the beautiful clean rock past flakes and cracks till at the right side of another bush island. Belay here from a small spruce tree. 200  Pitch 4: Scramble easily to the top and move right to the trail. 100

name: 9 Dollar Boys
description: For a route "topo" see the photo posted to the main Outlook-Area page.    Topo may not follow exact route.    [via Barker's comments]   P1. Up the slabs with tricky gear heading towards a natural belay below the large roof on a ledge.  180 feet 5.7R   P2. Head up and left from the belay and gain the left slanting crack. Follow this through the roof on great gear up to another good ledge with a natural belay.  160 feet 5.7   P3. Scramble to the top of the dome.

name: Hand Over Hand
description: For a route "topo" see the photo posted to the main Outlook-Area page.       [via Woodman's comments]   P1. Climb 100' up to a roof, pull it awkwardly (crux, 5.7) and continue up on nice rock to the first anchor.  5.7,  160'   P2. Head up and left and pop onto a beautiful white slab. Jam up an absolutely gorgeous crack which starts at an inch and widens to off width as it curves right under the overlap. Broken cracks in blocks lead past a steeper headwall, the climb a small white dike to lower angle rock and the anchor.  5.6,   170'        P3. Scramble up to top.   5.0   120'

name: Sun and Games
description: For a route "topo" see the photo posted to the main Outlook-Area page.       [via Woodman's comments]   P1.  From a break on the tree ledge, climb straight up past featured slab and small corners, then step left and climb steeper rock up a beautiful face to the top. The crux is tiptoeing up a white slab to a small, loose looking block and crack. A really nice pitch.  5.7   190'   P2. Scramble up to top. 5.0 80'    [NOTE: We split P1 into two pitches. R Hall]

name: Sweet Success
description: For a route "topo" see the photo posted to the main Outlook-Area page.    Topo may not follow exact route.    [via Woodman's comments]   P1. Climb past flakes and small corners and overlaps most any way up to the anchor. The crux move is climbing a short white slab past a bolt. Dirty in spots. 5.6   160'   P2. Better climbing leads past more small features up to a break in some small overlaps, then past a block, and back to the tree island.  5.5   160'      The name is a play on the name of the mountain the Outlook is located on the side of Mt. Success.

name: Two Lost Guys
description: For a route "topo" see the photo posted to the main Outlook-Area page.       North Bald Cap, across the way, has it's "Lost Boys" area, so we called this "Two Lost Guys".     Acting on a recent post to MntPrjct we took gear and a printed copy of posted descriptions, along with some fairly high resolution photos I'd taken from No. Bald Cap a couple of years earlier, and went exploring. Outlook's submitter (Ron Birk) had sent me a link to a photo with routes, but I never clicked on it as I had assumed that the link was to the written descriptions in a public blog. (Yes, pretty dumb of me, eh?!)    After the grind to the top (1200 ft in 1.2 miles to the Outlook Junc.) we had many discussions on "Where, exactly, is this "tree island"? (Later I was to conclude it was on the very top of the cliff !)    We did find the double bolted anchor about 100-120 ft down the climber's-left skyline ridge. (photo)  We used this to rap down what you'd call the "west face" (190 ft rap, staying to rappeller's left and not dropping right over the overhangs) to a good tree ledge. (According to the photo on "smug-mug.com" there's another dbl bolt anchor about 30-40 ft right, and 10-20 ft higher than this ledge. On a 2nd trip to the Outlook we would find this station, see "Hand Over Hand")  A solid 5-inch diameter pine provided a 2nd anchor to rap down the "south face". We stopped about 150 ft down at a pine tree, about 30-40 ft from what looked to be the base. (Much scrub and many trees would have made for an unpleasant rap of this final 50 ft.)     P1 - Climb back to the pine tree ledge. For us, this pitch included climbing a fairly prominent, 25-30 ft high R-facing corner of more distinctly yellowish rock. (in photo of P1)  150 ft  5.3   Whether this pitch included any of "Hand Over Hand" is not known for sure. [Disclaimer: due to the weather, and the rope-mess that would have resulted in pulling the ropes into the trees and bushes, the "leader" top-rope soloed this pitch.]     P2 - Step right from the belay pine, then up the white-ish rock via a series of corners, flakes and faces, (photos) arriving at the dbl bolt anchor.  190 ft 5.4-5.5  It is now believed that this pitch is about 25-30 feet climber's left of the top pitch of "Hand Over Hand" This was a very nice pitch, and more interesting than it looked when we rapped down it. Whether it had been done before I have no idea. Can't believe it hadn't.     "P3" (as per "Hand Over Hand") - scramble 100-120 ft to the top trees. Class 3 to 5.0    After this climb we were still confused about where the already-established routes were, so one of us got lowered down 125-140 ft in two places on the main face of the cliff. We could not see any of the dbl bolt anchors that are supposed to be there, but given the mica embedded in the rock, this is perhaps not surprising, or perhaps we did not lower far enough.  (The first of our lowers is now known to have been only about 40-50 ft to climber's right of "Sweet Success")     The rock was generally quite climbable, and of a similar nature to the pegmatite section of Pine Mountain. Climbing back up from these "lower downs" was generally in the 5.3-5.5 range, including traversing under what had looked like a formidable overhang from our stance at the lower pine tree on "Two Lost Guys".

name: Sasha
description: Central crux.  Dig deep with the Fingers

name: The Edge
description: Start far left of the cliff,behind twin maple trees in a triangular crack system. Gear here to get into larger crack to the left and follow to the end. Getting off the slab here until getting back on at the 2nd bolt keeps grade at 5.7. Variation: Stay on the slab at the end of this crack and clip 1st bolt-5.10   There are 4 bolts on this pitch, which ends at 2 ring bolt  anchor (approximately 85')   2nd pitch goes up and left past 6 bolts to another 2 ring bolt anchor(approximately 120') 5.5   3rd pitch goes directly above anchor past 5 bolts to a tree anchor( approximately 60') 5.6

name: Harvest Moon
description: Start at the double birch tree growing against the cliff.    P1: Clip the first two bolts in the groove of Somebody’s Got To Do It and then move right to a third bolt on the face. (Back cleaning the second bolt is helpful). Go straight up to a flake that takes #1-3 cams. Step right and follow the bolts up the slab past flakes to a ring anchor at the top. 100’ 5.8+    P2: Move right to a crack and gain a bolt. Follow the bolt line up the slab to easier terrain and a ring anchor below a tree ledge which is shared with P2 of The Seven Dwarves. 65’ 5.10a

name: O-Town Browns
description: Start just right of Shine Your Helmet in the obvious left facing corner. Climb the corner past bolts to a stance at a left facing flake on the anchor ledge. Climb the flake right to a bolt. Continue up the face past bolts to a white quartz blob and an optional mid-sized cam before the last bolt. Finish up a flake to a foot ledge and a bolted ring anchor on the left.

name: Polish the Monkey (mid-cliff START)
description: This climb starts where "Somebody's Got to Do It" ends. History - According to Webster, (2nd Ed. 1986) the FA was made with one bolt just above the flake and stepped "right into a small depression" and then made "hard moves back left on a faint dike to the last bolt of [Helmet's] bolt ladder."  Presently above the flake there are 3 closely spaced bolts that lead directly up, sort of parallel to Helmet's bolt ladder and 15-20 ft right of it. Above these there's 2 or 3 more bolts) that lead to an independent 2 bolt anchor. I suspect these upper 3-5 bolts are the top of O-Town Brown's P1, the climb whose lower section climbs the bolted Left-facing corner between "Helmut" and "Polish".  P1 - From the Shine Your Helmet's P1 anchor [or top of "Somebody's Got To Do It"] , move to an obvious flake; up this to the small horizontal at its top. (Beware the blueberries which might totally hide the horizontal!  The vegitation further right may not be supported by rock!)  Clip the bolt and step right to the depression (now with some lichen) and then step back left and up past  bolts (5.9+ / 5.10a ? ).  Continue up and very slightly right passing 2-3 more bolts to a double bolt anchor. 120-125 ft from ground, 5.9+ / 5.10a? , the climb can just barely be TR'ed with a full-length 70m rope.

name: The Seven Dwarfs
description: Originally rated 5.5 in the 1986 (2nd ed.) Webster guide; the whole cliff was omitted from his 3rd edition (1996).  Classic example of "Old School" ratings. Most today give it between "solid 5.7+" and 5.8.    START: About 20-25 ft right of the "twin birch trees" of the "Somebody's Got to Do It" corner.    P1 -  Climb up mossy dike line, stepping back left  (5.6R?) to first bolt;  then up the short crack (#3 Camalot useful) passing a tree root.  Up, then reach left to clip the first bolt (which I think is actually on Harvest Moon), make a move up the corner, then a big step left onto the face. Head up the face, there's at least 1 more bolt. Continue a few feet beyond the pine tree to a 2 ring anchor.  110ft, 5.7+ / 5.8,   5.6R     P2-   Climb up to the overhang on the right, with the flake and crack, over this (gear) to a bolt.  Up the face (gear and 1-2 more bolts) trending left to a 2 bolt anchor.  80 ft 5.7  [see NOTE]   Webster (1986) lists a P3:  150 ft  5.3 that appears to not be very clean at present (2018) "Wander up broken slabs to a short headwall and left facing corner."   NOTE:  From the P1 belay, stepping left and going up the clean, white face with several bolts is P2 of Harvest Moon, 5.10a, to the same shared anchor with Seven Dwarves.

name: Somebody's Got to Do It
description: Listed as a Variation to "Shine Your Helmet" in Webster's 2nd edition.     Begin in the 3rd corner right of The Edge (about 50 ft right of that climb)  Corner has 2 trees at it's base and converts to an arching-left-flake-corner about 30 ft up.     P1 - Squeeze past the trees and start the corner ["hidden" bolt up and right, down very low]. A 2nd bolt [3/8" SS] protects the 5.6 / "5.6+" crux moves and then the flake provides further protection.    See Chinos COMMENT- The route now has its own double bolt anchor on the sloping ledge [thanks "guys"!]....or....(as we did before the anchor) continue up on "Polish the Monkey" variation [ 5.9 - 5.10 ]

name: Yet to Be Named
description: The furthest right cleaned line on the Main Slab, George cleaned and led the FA of this route, althought it seemed Mike helped on the last "bit" of cleaning !  (Sorry Mike, forgot your last name...drop me a line.)  Maybe 5.5, maybe 5.6..hard to say; what's not hard to say is that if you want a less "R-ish" route to the 2nd pitch of 7-Dwarves (or Harvest Moon's 2nd P ) then "this is your route"!  P1-  START About 20 ft right, and 15 ft above the start of "7-Dwarves"; a dirt-and-log "ledge" leads out to the start.  Climb cleaned rock past a fixed sling (on a tree root) and then on past 2 bolts (crux near 2nd), then easy rock just to the right of the "7-Dwarves" crack.  Move around the corner and onto some steep dirt climbing, past a 2nd fixed sling around a tree, and then (Var ?) step left onto the arete/flake and up to the pine tree and the dbl bolt anchor shared by 7-Dwarves and Harvest Moon. 100 +/- ft  5.5 / 5.6 / 5.6+ ?  If you place pro in the "7-Dwarves" crack, then think about back-cleaning it before starting up the dirt gully   Variation (?) I thought this "variation" was the main line until the second time I climbed the route and found George's fixed sling high in the "dirt corner".  It still might be the main line?      About 10 ft below the fixed sling, move out left to the arete on excellent footholds ( series of nearly horizontal cracks) but limited protection, and then climb the arete directly to the pine tree. 5.4 / 5.5 PG/R  (The last few feet are on 7Dwarves) You could always go up, clip the fixed sling and then go back down to the cracks.

name: Browns Corner
description: Clip a low bolt and move up the slab with gear options to a small blocky corner. Follow the jugs straight up into the large right facing corner. Follow the corner crack to a small roof. Pull the roof and follow flakes up and right to a ring anchor shared with Night Moves.

name: Honeymoon
description: Start above the large rock laying at the base. Climb past a bolt on the slab and pull into the steep corner. Follow the corner past several bolts with great movement. Exit the corner and pull onto the slab. More bolts lead to a bolt anchor.

name: Night Moves
description: Sling the stump at the start of the climb. Scramble up on good holds to a left facing corner. Layback up the corner with great gear to a ledge. Climb the headwall past bolts to an overlap with interesting moves. Escape the overlap and follow the bolts up the edge to a ring anchor.

name: The Corner
description: Start at the toe of "The Slab", climbing up past two bolts. Head up and right towards the obvious crack at the bottom of the left-facing corner. Trend up above any trees to avoid hellacious drag, placing pro as needed. Once you hit the corner, follow it up to the anchors any which way you please.We weren't there for the FA but that's the way we did it. If this is incorrect, please let me know and I can change it.

name: The Crack
description: START - A few feet up and left of the flat area in front of the tree.  Move up the slab, step left to the tree and into the crack (bolt, don't go too high), pass by a fixed sling in a "thread" and then onto either the tree anchor, or over to the double bolt anchor of "The Slab" and "The Corner".  (Take a double-length sling if planning to lower-off the dbl bolt anchor and TR "The Slab".)

name: The Slab Route
description: Although pretty much "sewn up" with bolts, I listed this as a "trad route" in that there's at least one placement (at the small overlap) that can supplement the bolts.   START: At a small flat area by a tree, about 50-60 ft up and right of the toe of the Main Slab.  From the tree, move up a few feet on the left (dirt) then step right onto the slab (bolt) and climb up the bolt line; a gold (#2) Camalot is useful at the small overlap about 50 ft up, although other sizes would work too.  Beware, the "texture" of the rock on the 2nd half of the climb is a bit less coarse than the first half, giving the climb its rating.  Above last bolt, step right to the dbl bolt ringed anchor. A double-length (6 ft) sling is advisable if lowering-off or TR'ing the climb.

name: Red Tail
description: Sit start under the prow/arete on the Hawk Block. Sit start and move out the face right on sharp crimps. Slap to the lip and top out.

name: Sidewinder
description: Start in the cave between the two boulders. Start in the back on the face to the left. Sit Start and traverse out left on crimps to a big jug/horn feature. Swing out of the cave and roll over onto the slab.

name: Tall Boy
description: This climb is located on the big block to the left of the Hawk Block. Start on the left hand side of the block below the obvious point at the top. Climb straight up the face and top out at the point

name: Tall Boy Traverse
description: Start on the right side of the Tall Boy Boulder. Traverse left across the low part of the boulder on good holds and finish up Tall Boy on the left arete. Keeping the feet higher will make it harder.

name: Talon
description: This problem is located on the Hawk Block. Sit start under the striking prow/arete. Work into a good right hand side pull and fire up and left to a decent jug (crux). Make another big move into a v-notch and top out with decent holds.

name: Arachnophobia
description: Start at the base of Raven Crack. Follow the slab with a wall on your left to a headwall. Move up and clip a bolt. Follow the gently overhanging corner left on flakes and cracks to an exciting exit. Continue up to the trees above.

name: Lone Ranger
description: Climb up the easy slab for about 25' to the base of the overhanging section. Climb up a short crack in the v-groove to the right. Angle left across sloping ramps and pull over the lip on the leftside of the overhang with great exposure. Continue up another 20' of easy terrain. Walk towards the trees. Rap or Walk off left.

name: Raven Crack
description: Look for a short orange wall with two distinct cracks. Climb the crack on the left. Start up the ramp and climb out the varied sized crack. Pull over the bulge on good holds. Continue up the slab for another 45' placing gear on 5.5ish climbing to the tree clump above.

name: Bio-Dome
description: Start the same as Sundown on the left side of The Dome. Climb up just left of Sundown. Stay left of the steep bulge and follow the slab on jugs. Go left or right of a large block/flake at half height and continue up easy jug slab to the top. Walk off left or rap.

name: Crack N' Groove
description: Start at the hand crack 15' left of Garlough's Groove. Climb the crack until it ends (crux) and continue up the face/groove above. Hard to describe it, all the features look the same. Finish at the trees on top.

name: Garlough's Groove
description: Scramble up a gully on the right side of the dome. Climb up the groove on the right edge of the dome placing gear when possible along the way. The climb is juggy and enjoyable. Finish at the trees on top.

name: Groove Child
description: Start on the face just right of the blocky overhanging section of the dome. Climb the face up to a right leaning groove at the top. Follow the groove and finish up to the trees above.

name: Sundown
description: Scramble left uphill on the left side of the dome to some blocky features with cracks. Climb up placing gear in the cracks and make some spooky moves over the crux bulge with your gear a ways below. Continue up the face on big holds up the arete/face to the trees above.

name: Big Ol' Crack
description: Climb up the short unprotected slab to a short overhang. Get gear and pull out the overhang into the large crack. Climb the crack until it ends. Finish up the series of headwalls to the trees at the top.

name: Bliss
description: Start up on the blocks below the crack lines. Move left to the slab with a large tree branch going across it down low. Shimmy behind the branch and stand on a large foot ledge on the right side. Continue up the slab on good holds to the tree ledge above. Find a good tree to rap from or walk off left.

name: Sunshine
description: Start on stacked blocks 5' left of Big Ol' Crack. Climb up cracks and jugs to the offwidth. Get in the wide crack at half height and move up being careful of blocks lodged in the crack. The are jugs throughout the climb if you feel around for them. Exit the crack to a tree ledge. Finish up another 15' section of rock to the trees above. Rap the route or walk off.

name: Corbie Corb
description: Start 15' right of the triangular cave at the base of the slab. Make the crux moves off the ground and follow the easy slab staying right of the tree clumps. Move into the corner on the right and follow it until it ends. Scramble to the trees above.

name: Ice Shoveler
description: Climb the easy slab staying in the large corner to an open book climb the book (crux) get to the top of the book and then climb left to the top.

name: Swami
description: Climb up an easy slab getting gear along the way. Move up to a large corner with a massive block wedged in it. Climb over the block onto the face and move up the groove. Finish up to the trees above.

name: Lost Slab
description: A nice slab with good holds. Start down in the gully at the toe of the slab. Run it out up the face to gear at 20-25'. Continue up the slab to a short corner. Climb up the right side to the trees above.

name: Touch N' Go
description: Start up the gully 15' right of Lost Slab. Climb the features straight up the slab and trend right on some flakes to a large pine. You could probably get some gear in. Rap from the tree.

name: Cloud 9
description: Climb the obvious striking corner up the center of the overhanging wall. Start up the moderate slab to the overhang at the base of the corner. Get small cams and fire over the bulge into the corner(crux). Continue up the corner placing gear onto a protruding blade of rock under a roof. Pull around the roof right and continue up the corner on big holds to a knifeblade. The corner ends and finish up another 30' of easy slab to the trees above.

name: Great White Buffalo
description: This is a cool 30ft face climb then it turns into 40ft of slab. The crux is the first 15ft of a balancey semi mantel.

name: Lucknow
description: Lucknow climbs the corner on the right side of the wall. Scramble up onto a ledge to the base of the corner. Climb the corner until it ends and exit onto a ledge. Step back left across the void with great exposure into another little groove. Continue up short headwalls to the trees above.

name: The Slot
description: This climb is not actually on the Overhanging Wall. It is located downhill and right on a small outcrop of rock. Squeeze through an offwidth and continue up the corner with a finger size crack in it. Top out when the crack ends and scramble down the gully to the left. It is possible to bail off the route to the left in a few spots.

name: Stoned
description: Start on the face 20' right of the Lucknow corner. Climb the face to a ledge. Continue up easy blocky terrain to the trees above.

name: White Out
description: White Out climbs the obvious white streak on the left side of the overhanging wall. This climb has a lot of movement for a short route, and it gets harder as you go. The crux is getting to the lip to clip the anchor. Climb past three bolts to a two bolt anchor at the lip.

name: Aerodrone
description: Sit start on the slightly overhanging section to the right of the tree.

name: Bipolar On Lithium
description: Sit start on a jug and crimp.  The crux is getting off the ground, now dyno or reach for the good left hand and top out.

name: Bungle
description: Decent climb with a couple neat holds. Start balanced on the left side of the arete on an undercling sidepull. Work right around the arete to a great righthand pocket and head straight up.

name: Chelsea Girls
description: Climb or run up.

name: Cosmic Gypsy
description: Short but fun.    Sit start on slopers with a good left foot that might be reachy if your short.  As long as you start on the slopers the grade stays the same. The crux is keeping your feet from flying out and sliding off the slopers.  Now get your right hand in the envelope slot, then left hand into a great hold and up to a jug. Top out and walk off.

name: F**k Tony Danza I'm the Boss
description: Sit start and up to easier climbing.  high topout on slab

name: The Faire Folk
description: Start on the small ledge and move up to the point.

name: The Fin Traverse
description: Traverse from low to high (right to left) on the trail side of the Fin boulder.

name: The Fin
description: If you like slopers like i do this is alot of fun.    Start on the obvious good hold and on a side sloper, get your left foot on a tiny nub and heel hook to keep it from popping off.   Slap up on side slopers to the next good hold and top out.

name: In The Court Of The Bear King
description: Start on a crimp and and a bad hold. Continue up on crimps to the point and topout. Really balancy and awesome.

name: Leaf House
description: Boulder right next to the road across from the swamp thats diamond shaped.

name: Love Is A Dog From Hell
description: Sit start on a small rock up to crimps over the bulge and top out.  Harder than it looks.

name: Lunatic Harness
description: Climb up the slightly left leaning and overhanging arete.

name: Missed The Boat
description: Climb on good holds and good feet.

name: New Mellow
description: Start on the horn just left of the tree, traverse left to the good match hold. Adjust your feet and push straight up/left. Start on the second hold for a nice warm-up.  Beta: https://youtu.be/qyclUVAxmgU

name: Poor Mans Hobbit
description: Sit-start in the hole with your right hand on a crimp and your left hand on a good hold.  Bump up to the right leaning crack and follow it right and up.

name: Project...
description: The slightly overhanging section to the left of Bear King on the blank face.

name: Secret Stairs
description: Climb just to the right of the tree.

name: Shark Attack
description: Start on some good crimps, then bump up to a good right edge. Now for the crux, make a big move to a great edge/jug. Find your feet, get the lip and top out.     This is a great little line. There could be a sit start to this that could possibly go but it would probably be much harder.

name: Televators
description: Start to the left of the small ledge on good holds and good feet.

name: Uncle Funky Pants
description: Climb just to the right of the tree and left of the arete.  Watch out for the pointed rock on the ground, it could be an ankle breaker.

name: What the Crack?
description: This spot needs some work...it's only ~25 feet off the road to the wall (down into the ravine / spillway), and there is a 5-10 foot wide section to approach the wall.  You'll see the first ledge to step onto (literally, a step).    From here, lots of slab work up, and don't use the gigantic horizontal crack.

name: Bridge Over Troubled Water
description: Bridge Over Troubled Water sits in my mind as one of the most unique climbs I have ever done, and I'm certain you will feel the same. It is distinctly sporty, but sound of Livermore Falls' unsettling churn below you adds a sense of adventure that you could otherwise only find on a big wall in a downpour. Expect moves like one of the many beta intensive boulder cruxes on the right side of Waimea. Wear a tight right knee bar pad, and don't expect to get it on the first go. The first bolt is positioned for the belayer to not get sucked out over the waterfall during falls.  Scramble up on to a ledge any way you please and clip the bolt on the face. Tiptoe down to the strange hanging corner feature. Creatively find your way into the corner using all manner of ninja kicks, knee bars, underclings, and butt scums. Finally exit left towards jugs via a perfect rail of crimps. Mantle into easier terrain and climb to the trees up top.

name: Dirty Old Man
description: Toughest moves up top.   Aptly named based on a couple dirty sections.    When nearing the top of the climb head straight to drop the grade or veer left under the roof for 5.6.

name: Becoming the Devil
description: This rarely done climb (often wet) is one of great vision. Start inside, at the back of the devils den cave. Climb out of the cave using the cracks at the top and sides for protection. Head for day light. Finish up the wall to the right of the cave entrance. Use tree at top to belay. (Headlamp Needed!)

name: Cave Corner
description: nice climb to start the day toping out is the hardest part

name: The Cave Wall Crack Left
description: These cracks are rarely climbed due to crumbly questionable rock. Follow the left hand crack up to bolts with hangers for anchors.

name: The Cave Wall Crack Right
description: These cracks are seldom done due to the crumbly questionable rock. Climb up past a bolt and follow a crack right placing gear until you reach a bolt anchor with hangers.

name: The Chimney
description: Climb the big obvious chimney in the middle of the wall by the cave. The climb takes good gear. Climb to trees at top.

name: Fallen Apart
description: Climb the series of crumbly broken up cracks to the left of the chimney. A tree sticks out mid way. Gear is sketchy. Not worth the risk.

name: Frozen Digits
description: Start at the arete to the right of the right cave crack. Climb past a pin to a bolt. Continue up to a ledge with gear. Climb up past another bolt and continue up to the trees or move left to the anchors of the right cave crack. This climb has some pretty good views out right as you climb.

name: Have Fun
description: The best easy climb in the den.The top mantel is the crux

name: Pucker Factor
description: short but sweet nice worm up for the slabs

name: Crystal Crimpin'
description: This boulder is located at the base of The Land of Overhangs. The route is on the back of the boulder. Its the obvious crimp line on the right side. Sit start on the lowest rail and work up to the lip. This route does not top out yet (really dirty).

name: Fools Gold
description: The moves up the bottom are a little tough, but finding the best holds helps a lot. Basically move straight up the crack/shallow corner system over here and when the crack runs out make some moves directly up the face to merge with the rounded arete on the right. Follow the arete to the horizontal crack right below the last headwall. From here follow the arete basically straight over the top.

name: Go-Go Gadget Arm
description: About 15 feet left of People Under the Stairs is a lone  bolt. This marks the start of the route. Climb up past the bolt and make moves up to a ledge placing gear. Clip a fixed draw out on the lip of the big roof overhead. Extend your arm way out over the roof to gain a flake and pull the roof. Continue up flakes placing gear on easier climbing to a tree anchor.

name: Here he comes, Rico Suave
description: Get up to short prow below texas flake, move up and go up left side of flake. At top of short corner make a thought provoking step right on a knob and mantle onto ledge. Climb up and slightly right to top out left of hole in the roof anchors. There's probably 3-4 sequences in the route at the grade, with a couple rests too.

name: Hole in the Roof
description: This climb starts just around the corner of the left end of the slab. It starts up an easy blocky section to a ledge. Continue up an easy groove to the obvious fist size hole in the top of the roof. Pull the roof and make a few crux moves through horizontals to bolt hangers.

name: Hysteria
description: Starting at small prow of rock below right of prominent flake pull on with a high hand. The route goes right up the stripe of lighter color rock between the routes on either side. A little sideways movement on this route unlocks sequences through the continuously sporty moves separated by some decent holds to catch your breath.

name: Master Exploder
description: One of two fully bolted route at The Land of Overhangs. Climb up past 2 bolts and gain a jug on the roof at the third bolt. Make the crux moves over the roof to gain the 4th bolt. Continue up to rap anchors. Nice rock and great moves.

name: People Under the Stairs
description: This is the route 20 ft left of Master Exploder. It starts up left leaning ramp to the short butt-crack. Place gear in a horizontal before working up a couple moves on a short slab under a roof to gain a bolt. Pull over the roof (crux) climbing past another bolt on knobs and crimps to a tree anchor at a small pine.

name: Sorry Joe
description: Start on a horizontal shelf-like thing and make a big move up to another horizontal shelf. From here up, follow the natural weakness that accepts decent gear. Merge onto Left Arete of slab/ Fools Gold, go up and finish as desired (left, middle, straight, all 5.9ish). This whole section is pretty sustained at 5.9 and the steep nature inflicts a pump.

name: Tree Crack
description: Start at the same bolt as Go-Go Gadget Arm. Climb straight up to the same ledge placing gear. Break left instead of pulling the gadget roof to a crack on top of a smaller roof. Follow the crack right and finish at the same tree anchor as Go-Go Gadget Arm.

name: Burn The Evidence
description: Start by moving up to horizontal crack pockets, make a big move to a slopey dish, stand up and mantle the insecure round top out.

name: Chino's Arete
description: The crux is at the first bolt.Clip the bolt low and pull up on a sloping crimp and shoot for a side pull up left.This route is a change of pace from the rest of the routes here because there are no flaring horizontals.The routes name came from the effort from the chino's.

name: Chinos' Warmup
description: Crouching match start on flat horizontal then throw for a good pocket. Now move to horizontal crack that runs the length of the traverse. Catch a small rest after about 20 ft then go for the crux section, about 20 ft of super pumpy moves before another good rest. Then finish up Dead Mans Drop.

name: Dead Mans Drop
description: Start with some pockets and move up past a couple horizontals to a thin top out. A fall could be scary.

name: Devil Man
description: The testpiece at The Outback. Climb up near vertical rock on thin technical moves. The crux is from bolt 2-4. Pull the small roof at the fourth bolt to rap anchors.

name: The Edge
description: Climb the route to the right of Secret Agent. Climb straight up past 3 bolts. Continue up placing a cam on mellow climbing or go right to the rap anchors. A great safe route to get a feel for the climbing in The Outback.

name: Hidden Treasure
description: The most righthand route on the cliff. Climb up on pockets to a bolt. Continue up making slab moves to a horizontal (place cam or tricam). Continue up past 2 more bolts to a rap anchor. The crux is at the top.

name: Pullin Pine Needles
description: Start with hands in the horizontal crack, move up to a dish, then up to a diagonaling flake/rail thing and top out.

name: Runnin with the Devil
description: Place gear down low in a horizontal break. Climb straight past 2 bolts to anchors. This climb has steep technical climbing on thin crimps, knobs, and horizontal breaks.

name: Secret Agent
description: At the far left end of the Outback Wall is Secret Agent. It starts just to the right of the ramp that leads to the top of the cliff. Climb up a thin technical section past 2 bolts. The climb gets easier the higher you go. Place gear in horizontal cracks and finish at a rap anchor.

name: Snus'in
description: Lower crux moves. Trust the feet. Work right past first bolt up to slopers, Trust the feet crank to the crimps. Super fun top.

name: Visual - Eyes
description: Start about 15' left of Chinos Arete. Clip a low first bolt and make boulder moves up onto the slopey ledge. Climb past two more bolts on great features and make a mantle that guards the two bolt chain anchor on the ledge.

Start in the same spot as the 12 b/c project at the outcrops. Follow the horizontal left under the roof and clip a bolt. Move up to a big flake and clip a bolt on the bulge. Make moves over the bulge (crux) and finish up and left to a bolt anchor.

name: Becky Route
description: The Becky Route is the last route along The Outcrops. The route starts 15'right of Chino's Arete on the Outback wall. Climb out of the steep cave area moving left along horizontals and mantle over the bulge to a small foot ledge. Make some committing slab moves to gain a tree ledge. Continue up broken walls with huge holds to the top.

name: Black Moonstone
description: This often looked-at line follows a series of pockets and flakes just left of the "Rat Cave."  Climb straight up behind and to the right of the tree to a moon shaped dish, then make a committing high step and rock-over move to overcome the crux bulge.  An easier but fun face leads to a pine tree belay.    Free soloed on the first ascent with an early evening moon rising in the East.   In India, moonstones are regarded as 'dream stones' which bring the wearer beautiful visions at night.

name: Booklet of Boobs
description: The only open corner on The Outcrops. Climb up the easy slab to a ledge at the base of the book. Climb up the corner placing gear. Clip a bolt and exit right out of the corner. Top out near a large pine.

name: Centerfold
description: This is a short route with a lot of fun moves.The crux move is getting to the anchors.

name: Corner Crack
description: Some fun crack climbing if you chose or climb the face or use the crack for a lay back what ever you chose.Climb to a dinner table size ledge,good rest before the crux then face climb to top out.I don't know about the top out because I toped roped it first time from some webbing around a big boulder at the top.

name: Cover Shot
description: Start at the bottom of the slab 20' left of the corner. Climb up 15' of great 5.8ish moves to a ledge. Climb directly out the overhang with a left hand flake and a right hand pocket to start. Finish at the bolt anchor.

name: The Devil Wears PraNa
description: This short hard bouldery route is located between the Land of Overhangs and The Outback. Look for a small wall a about 200 feet before The Outback. The route starts below a roof. stick clip the bolt over the roof. follow a short dyke over the roof and then it disappears. Go straight up on thin holds to the second part of the dyke. clip the anchors.

name: Dickson,Garlough route
description: the route consist of a small flake an a mantle move to top out. the crux being the top out.

name: Dirty Harry
description: Big fun moves up a mildly overhanging swell.  Named after a .357 Magnum casing found at the base of the route, and the fact that the key holds are a tad dirty, though adequate.  "Do you feel lucky? Well do ya, Punk?"

name: Field Goal
description: The top out is the crux.It is a dirty climb because of all the ledges

name: Honey Badger
description: Climb the route "24" past the crux and stand up above the second bolt.  Truck right on fun moves with great positioning to the dual anchors above the "Project" route.    This makes for a much more sustained and interesting finish to the route "24", keeping the moves consistant at the grade.  At present, only one of the two anchors atop the "Project" route  has a quick link to facilitate lowering or rapping off.

name: Little Deuce Coupe
description: Start about 20' right of the Way Out dyno. Climb up an easy short slab to a small crack/flake. Place gear in the crack and horizontal above. Make some nice moves over the small roof with good holds. Sling the pine tree and make a couple more moves up a short slab to the trees on top.

name: Rat Cave
description: This is a good route because it has only one 5.9 move on it and that's the start.There is a much easier start to it if you start five feet right.After the starts the route drops down in grade to about 5.5 and up you go.

name: Route 1A
description: Listed in the Chinos guide as a top rope, it appears that no one has lead this previously.  Right of Booklet of Boobs approximately 30 feet is a "Y" shaped beech tree growing out of a horizontal crack about 10 feet up.  Staying right of the beech tree, climb straight up through an overlap to a pine tree belay.  Get it?  Route 1A follows the beech...    A harder (5.9ish) version was top roped going up through the Y shaped brances, but the crux was avoiding the tree completely for progress.

name: Way-Out (DYNO)
description: This is a dyno at a small outcrop above The Land of Overhangs. Stick clip a high lone bolt or rap down to set it up. This can also be done ropeless, but dont roll down the hill. Start on a short wall and dyno out to a big block sticking out over your head. The further left you throw the harder it gets! This ranges from V0-V?.

name: Fish flake
description: the start is at the "fish flake" just around the corner from Animal. Climb the flake to gain a moderate face climb to a small roof where you can throw a good old knee bar and then you hit the crux, which is gaining the crimps/undercling finishing hold. use trees at top for anchor

name: Jedi Mind Tricks
description: This route is located on a big scoop just behind The Outback. Start up blocky rock to a stance. Clip a bolt and make the surprisingly hard crux moves up onto a block. Go straight up past another bolt to a right leaning crack. Place gear or run it out to the top on easier climbing. Places to build a trad anchor on top or rap of the trees.

name: Out of Retirement
description: This route climbs the right arete of The Scoop Wall. Climb up an obvious corner with an optional gear placement to a ledge with a Large birch tree. Clip a bolt and make hard moves up and left onto the face and clip a second bolt. (Help from the birch tree makes the route about 5.8 A0). Finish straight up with a small runout on easy terrain to a bolt anchor.

name: The Bugs Are Bad
description: Dirty start, but good climbing above.

name: Cloak + Dagger
description: Climb up horizontal cracks that will accept cams if you wish. Climb past five bolt to rap anchors. Bolts were placed due to some crumbly rock at the top.

name: Hellraiser
description: Start at the climb with the tree beside it[good reference point]Climb up steep slab past 3 bolts. At the forth bolt climb up the crux headwall .Clip the fifth bolt and Make a couple interesting moves to the anchor near the large hemlock tree.

name: Hunting Unicorns With Hand Grenades
description: A girdle of the slab. Something to try after doing everything else. Start by clipping the first two bolts on People of the Sun then move left and clip the third bolt on Stolen. Continue left to the fourth bolt on Hellraiser and continue to a high clip on Joyride then its all gear. Trend down a little after Joyride as you go across the wall. At the left end turn the corner and go to the Hole in the Roof anchors and top out.

name: Joy Ride
description: This route was probably a trad route at some time. It has been bolted due to questionable gear in the cracks (can still be done on trad for a rush!)Climb up horizontal cracks with opportunity for good finger sized cams, or run it out to the first bolt. Follow 5.6-7 climbing to the forth bolt. Pull the final crux mantle move (5.8+) to the chain anchors.

name: Left  Arete
description: As far left as you can get on the slab wall. Climb up just right of the arete placing gear in horizontals to the top. Crux at the top pulling the lip to the trees.

name: Left Arete variation finish
description: Climb the Left Arete route to the horizontal below the crux face at the top. Move left around the corner and pull up past a small flake and top out to the right of the Hole in the Roof anchors.

name: No Bolts Please
description: Climb up the center of the slab wall placing gear whenever possible. This is a bold and scary climb due to questionable gear. Climb up easier slab to the final horizontal. Plunk in as much gear as possible before pulling the crux moves over the lip to the trees.

name: People of the Sun
description: The first bolted line you come to. Slab up past three bolts. Crux at the third bolt. Sling trees for further protection or run it out to the tree at the top. [Its also worth noting that originally the line had only the first 2 bolts, but after taking a good size sideways fall ripping out jon's green alien and slamming into a small ledge feature we thought another bolt would probably bea good idea.]

name: Stolen
description: After failed attempts in the rain by Jon Garlough, Jay Denver nabbed the FA in the rain on this technical slab climb! Climb technical slab past four bolts with a crux after the first and fourth bolts. Finish at rap anchors.

name: Syd's Slab
description: This is a mixed climb on the left side of the slab. Slab up past bolts placing cams in the runout sections. Finish at an anchor.

name: Dirty Sanuk
description: Top out crux.

name: The Hamburgular
description: Sustained easy horizontal ladder climb. Commit to top out. Jug flake over top.

name: BWR
description: The route has one or two good move on it but that is it. Its kinda an adventure route because it has two dirt filled ledges on it. The crux is pulling up on the bolder on top. Its worth doing at least once.

name: Crescent Roof
description: Climb up a short low angle slab with optional gear to a pin. Gain the left arête of the headwall and clip a pin with gear for back-up. Make an awesome crux move to a bucket flake over the roof and continue on easy terrain to the top. Natural thread anchor to the right. The route will feel easier if you are tall.

name: Crescent Wrench
description: Start the same as Crescent Roof. Climb the slab past flakes and a pin to a ledge. Move back and climb out the small left facing corner/crack. Finish at the trees above. Watch for loose blocks near the top.

name: Tombstone Blues
description: Climb up a short wall to gain the obvious crack on the right side of the headwall. Follow the fun crack/face climbing to the natural thread anchor on top.

name: True Grit
description: Climb the center of the short slab to a ledge. Follow features up the center of the headwall placing gear to the natural thread anchor on top.

name: An Aztec Nightmare
description: Climb the start of "A Toltec Dream," the cleaned slab to a fixed pin and the shorter slab leading to a left facing corner.  At the top of the corner, move right to a ledge then straight up through the small overlap to the larger tree ledge.    Continue straight up past a short, mossy slab to a brief section of wide cracks and flakes to a single 8" diameter pine tree.  Climb the face just right of the tree (crux) and then straight up through broken rock and right angling cracks to the tree belay.

name: Begginer's Route
description: This climb is located just to the right of the descent gully on the left side of the cliff. Climb a short slab with horizontals and pine trees growing on it. Top out and walk off or rap from trees.

name: Comfortably Numb
description: This takes a pretty direct line in between Suicide Wall and Strychnine. Although some of the moves are close to Strychnine in the first 30 feet, it's a completely independent line. Pull on the wall with a somewhat stout start and connect the flake features that lead up the wall with some thin sections in betweeen. Pull over a bulge on big holds and crimp up the final slab that has a tiny dike running up it to the anchor.

name: Earth and Sky
description: Climb the dirty slab trending slightly right then back left to a short flake leading up to the first small overlap (pin).  Move straight up to the large overlap (pin) and traverse right (first crux, strenuous) on underclings to the inside corner leading to "Merrymeeting Ledge", a 5' deep ledge with trees.  Sling the largest tree up high and boulder straight up the steep friction slab/face (second crux) to an easy exit on good flakes.  Fixed webbing anchor with quick link.  A 60M rope will just get you down.

name: The Gloaming
description: P1.  Climb the low angle, blunt arête to a ledge 25' up with two small oak trees.  Follow the face behind the left oak past horizontals to a bulge with a fixed pin just over the lip.  Clip the pin, then move right and up (5.5), or left and up a short flake over the lip (variation, 5.8).  Belay directly above on a sloping ledge at a cluster of small maple trees.    P2.  Climb straight up a low angle slab to the crux overlap and bulge, staying 10' left of the obvious flake system on "Relic" and 20' right of the shallow arching corner of "The Wayback Machine."  Place pro at the lip of the overlap, then mantle over it and move up the steep slab (5.7+, crux) to horizontals and easier climbing.  Continue straight up and slightly left on short, discontinuous diagonal finger cracks to finish below a large overhanging boulder at the top of the cliff.  Move right to belay at the tree atop "Relic."    A fun, optional 5.7 finish moves up the 15' tall wide-hands crack that splits the boulder above the belay tree.

name: Hanta Yo
description: Hanta Yo (emphasis on the second syllable) is Lakota Sioux for "clear the way" which was necessary for the first ascent, and good advice for the spotter on the initial slab... The climb is located where the approach trail meets the base of the cliff. Climb up the 18 ft of unprotected slab to a tree ledge. Move up the corner and pull the roof on good flakes and holds to another tree ledge. Continue up and left placing gear when possible. Pull the final headwall to a large tree ledge. Move right to a big tree and rap.  --- Alternate Start: "The Variant" -a section has been cleared between Toltec Dream and Hanta Yo. There is now a horizontal and flake that can be protected down low to the left of the initial slab. Finish on small feet and rejoin the climb on the ledge -5.8. 2020, Jim Nupp, David Giampietro, J. Browher.

name: Islands
description: Start about 15' right of Relic. Scramble up some broken sections of rock. Move up a series of big ledges (5.4 R) then move left into a flake system. Continue up the slab to an overlap and headwall with horizontals. Finish up the horizontal headwall to the large pine tree anchor.

name: Lost Heroes
description: Look for the headwall with the striking crack. Climb up reasonably protected slabs and small corners to a tree ledge. Sling the small tree to the right and make the crux moves off the ledge on a technical slab to a horizontal with good gear. Continue straight up the slab to the headwall with a crack. Climb the crack over the lip and step left onto a slab and follow it to the large pine tree with an anchor.

name: Man Eater
description: To the right of Lost Heroes look for a large chimney halfway up the cliff, Terror Crack. Man Eater is an alternate  start to Terror Crack. Wander up the slab left of Velvet Underground placing gear when possible to a large ledge at the base of the chimney. Climb the chimney and finish at the trees above.

name: Midnight Direct
description: This is the direct and safer start to Midnight Special. Climb up the starting dike of Terror Crack to the ledge at 5-10 up. Follow three bolts up the slab and move right into the flake (gear). Pull over onto the ledge and finish up Midnight Special.

name: Midnight Special
description: About 60 right of Man Eater is a partially cleaned strip trending left to the golden face above.   P1: Climb up to a big flake. Get on the flake and traverse left to a large ledge. Continue up the wall with gear to a pin that protects the crux golden headwall. Climb the headwall to a large ledge with a two bolt anchor. 100  5.8 R   P2: Traverse up and right into a large corner. Climb up the corner to a ledge at half height. Step right making an airy move onto the slab face and continue up horizontals to the top. 55  5.7

name: Onslaught
description: Start on the left end of the cliff. Slab climb up a clean streak to the small headwall. Move left and pull over on big flakes and move up to the crux headwall. Pull the crux bulge to gain a large obvious flake. Climb the flake and continue up easier headwalls to the tree anchor above.  2020 NOTE: the old anchor tree at the top has fallen, and currently the webbing/rings have been moved to a tree further up.  A 70m rope will get you just down to the Tardis starting ledge (tie knots in ends to be safe); any shorter you'll want to walk off left around the cliff.   Until someone gets to it with a chainsaw, be prepared to negotiate the large fallen tree during ascent & rappel.

name: Orthanc
description: Orthanc climbs the obvious blocky left facing corner up the entire cliff. Start to the right of the massive corner and work your way up and left to the base of it. Climb the dangerous blocky corner past small trees to the top of the cliff and solid ground. I would not recommend this route for it is dangerous for the leader and belayer. 160'   5.8 R/X

name: Pirates of Longstack
description: Start next to the three birch trees and pull on past the right side of a small pine tree about 10' up. A few easy moves lead to a ledge below a dark wall with a thin, right facing flake. Make tricky moves (crux, pg-13) up to a horizontal crack and get some bomber gear. Next make some slab moves to the short, overhanging headwall. Pull over (2nd crux?) this on good holds, then a short bit of easy climbing leads to the anchor.

name: Raven Song
description: This route takes a direct line from the start of Midnight Special straight to the top of the cliff.  Similar climbing to Suicide Wall with interesting moves and decent gear, but at an easier grade.    Start as for Midnight Special, heading up to the hollow flakes and block (good pro in suspect rock, first crux), then straight up to a lone ponderosa pine on a 12" deep ledge.  Continue up the clean rock directly above the tree following the line of least resistance, passing a tricky move at a long reach to a short flake (second crux).       Fun climbing leads to the top of the steeper rock at a pine tree growing downwards along the face (possible finish here by traversing right 15-20' to reach the double bolts atop Suicide Wall).  For the Direct Finish, step over the pine to a short dike and easy slabs (5.3R) heading for the final overlaps.  Pull through just left of a clump of birch trees at a V shaped notch (5.8ish?) or step left then up to the anchor tree atop the route (5.5).

name: Rawhide
description: From the sloping belay above the 5" diameter pine tree, face climb up on easy but fun moves to a sloping slab under the headwall and overlap.  Make a long move past the overlap to a short diagonal crack and move right a few feet and up to a 5' deep tree ledge known as "Merrymeeting Ledge".  Continue straight up on easier ground passing a short flake, a bulge to a tree (stay left), and then diagonal up to tree belay.

name: Relic
description: The route was cleaned and an old pin near the top was found. We made the climb direct which could be different from the original line. Follow the slab and right facing corner to a ledge with a large oak tree. Sling the tree above the headwall and make the crux moves to a tree ledge. Continue up a slab to a large arching flake at the headwall. Move up and left on moderate terrain to a tree anchor on top.

name: Sacred Fire
description: Start below the obvious right facing flake on dirty slabs.  Climb the flake to it's top, then step slightly right and up to "Merrymeeting Ledge", the 5' deep ledge.  Sling the largest tree up high, then boulder up the 15' friction slab/face to better holds.  Place a couple of pieces of gear in a small crack, then negotiate the surprisingly tricky top out moves with a beached whale manoever, or if you're brave on the sharp end, press it out.

name: Spirit Guide
description: From the pine tree belay ledge located 20' above the base trail (same start as for "Rawhide"), step right to a left facing flake and climb strait up through several tiers of steep slab separated by lower angled ledges.  After 45', pull the 2' roof on big horizontals and continue straight up then step slightly right onto "Merrymeeting Ledge"' the large tree covered ledge that cuts across the left end.  Follow the upper section of "Rawhide" to the belay trees and rap from the anchors located climber's left.

name: Still Gettin' Booty
description: Start below the large chimney on Terror Crack. Climb the slab to a high black bolt. Gain a small tree ledge (bolt) and fire the crux slab to a flake. Follow the flake to the arete left of the chimney. Climb the juggy arete placing gear to a bolt anchor on top.

name: The Stroke
description: The Stroke shares a start and a tree anchor with Islands to the left. Start up Islands for about 25 and move right on a ledge to a lone bolt on a nice slab face. Pull the fun slab and continue up the headwall with horizontals for gear to the small birch clump. Move left to the large pine anchor. The protection bolt was placed free on the lead by hand.

name: Strychnine
description: P1: Start up a small dike behind a large oak tree to a bolt 10 up. Continue up the dike to the large flake/corner with gear. Continue up the face placing gear to a bolt. Continue over the bulge placing gear past another small headwall to a third bolt. Continue up the slab to a tree and walk left to the anchor on Suicide Wall. 100   P2: Walk right from the anchor along a ledge. Pull the bulge and follow the slab to a second head wall. Finish at the pine tree on top. 40'

name: Suicide Wall
description: This route starts in the vicinity of Midnight Special. P1: Climb up under the overlap and traverse right into a small right facing corner. Continue up changing corners to a blank slab. Move a bit left to a hidden flake and continue up and right to a bolt anchor. 100  5.8 PG-13   P2: Climb up the final headwall placing gear along the way to the top of the cliff. Climbing the face direct off the anchor is harder. Use a tree for an anchor. 50  5.8

name: Sweat Lodge
description: Start 20' right of Onslaught on a short slab with two small trees on the ledge above. Step right and follow the low angel slab with gear on climbers right of large pine tree on the ledge. Continue up the 5.8 slab (bolt) to gear under the overlap. Pull up on a large flake and clip a pin out right. Make the crux moves up the flake and seam to a stance (pin). Continue straight up on easier terrain to the pine tree anchor of Onslaught on the left. 115' 5.9+

name: Tardis
description: Climb up the slab start of Onslaught to the first little headwall. Traverse left to the second left facing corner. Pull the small corner and move up the slab to the bulge. Pull the bulge using the good horizontals on the left placing gear until the horizontals end. Run it out up the slab to the large oak tree with an anchor above.

name: Terror Crack
description: This is the original line of the chimney. Start the climb right on an easier dike feature just right of Velvet Underground. Climb the dike to a large ledge. Walk left across the ledge to the base of the chimney. Climb the chimney to trees above.

name: Toltec Dream
description: Start on a clean slab left of a large oak tree to a left facing corner. Traverse left across the lip of the roof to good holds and gear. Pull the headwall through a notch to a tree ledge. Continue up a featured slab to an overlap. Follow the flake/dike system to a tree anchor shared with the previous route.

name: Velvet Underground
description: Climb up easy flakes and rails past a pin to a brown streak with two bolts. Climb the crux slab past two bolts to a ledge. Continue up the face past two more bolts to a large ledge and a two bolt anchor. (You can bring a rack to #1 to supplement the bolts).

name: Way of the Peaceful Warrior
description: This route can be done as one long pitch.    P1: Start on a slab with two starts. The left start is hard 5.9 and the right start is 5.7. Climb the slabs to a set of overlaps. Follow the features through the overlaps to a tree ledge. 50 5.7   P2: Walk up a slightly left to slab. Follow the features up and right to an overlap with a bolt. Pull the crux overlap and finish to the tree anchor on the right. 50 5.9

name: The Wayback Machine
description: Start 15 right of Hanta Yo.   P1: Start on blocky terrain and continue up the fat crack system until it ends. Make the crux slab move with a pine tree growing off the cliff  to the tree ledge. Move up a slab to the right arching small corner. Climb the fun corner with  holds out left to the pine tree anchor. 90  5.9   P2: Climb straight up and left on flakes in a clean streak to the top. 35

name: Adventure Punks
description: This route climbs the left edge of The Big Wall section. Start the same as Chenoo. This is a serious climb on chossy rock and should not be taken lightly. The crux moves are bolt protected, but a fall anywhere on the route could lead to serious injury. Do not attempt this route if people are climbing in the area due to the potential for rock fall.   P1: Climb the slab of Chenoo past an overlap to a larger roof. Place gear and pull the roof to a ledge with a pine tree. 5.8  PG-13   50   P2: Move left from the tree to the chossy arête. Follow the left angling arête with corners and flakes placing gear along the way past two spaced bolts to the pine trees on top. 5.9  R  105

name: The Arete
description: The Arete is a second pitch variation to Layback Route. Climb the first pitch of Layback Route to the pin anchor. Continue up the second and move left under the roof. Take the open book corner with a hand crack to a stance ledge. Move right onto the super exposed arête plugging gear in horizontals. Pull the lip to a big ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: Chenoo
description: A good trad line up the Central Wall. Start at the top of the stairs just right of the blocky corner of Orthanc. Climb up the slab with good holds and a few gear options to a small roof. Pull the roof on good holds and continue up and sling the pine tree. Continue up the headwall pulling more overlaps and face climbing on good holds to an anchor on a foot ledge. 150   FA: Lincoln Tetherly and James Dickson climbed the route to the anchors on P1 of Riptide. Lincoln Teherly and Jonathan Garlough pushed the route to the top creating a nice long pitch up the Central Wall.

name: Graceful Tiers
description: Climb easily past a right leaning flake, a series of ledges, horizontals and mantels, passing 2 bolts to a shallow roof. Clip a third bolt, pull the first shallow roof (crux)to a second shallow roof. Pro at a horizontal (.3/ .4) and mantle around the roof to a slab and a bolt. Step up and left to a bolt shared with Happy Ending, finishing at a two bolt anchor also shared with Happy Ending.  Crux seems like it will be height dependent. Taller climbers will find the grade soft. Shorter climbers will find the grade stout.

name: Happy Ending
description: Climb up through an upside down v-notch in a flake.  Continue past rails and horizontals to a bolt below the roof.  Pull the roof (much easier than it looks from the ground, 5.8+, #3 camalot) to a stance and a second bolt.  Climb a  slab (crux) to another overlap, passing a shared bolt with Graceful Tiers to an anchor up and right (also shared with Graceful Tiers).

name: It's a Good Day to Die
description: Work up the left side of the amphitheater under the large roof on sharp cracks and underclings.  Tread lightly and pull through the obvious crack on the left end of the roof and straight up the slab and face above.  This climb would be worth two stars if it were longer.

name: Layback Route
description: The obvious corner system in the middle of the cliff.    P1: Climb the face with flakes and horizontals to a tree ledge below the big roof with a  three pin anchor in a left facing corner. 55   P2: Climb up under the roof and traverse left making moves into the corner. Follow the crack up the corner until the corner ends. Move right onto a ledge with a two bolt anchor. 50   P3: Climb straight up off the anchor and pull the crux overlap with a seam running up the face (5.10). The crux can be avoided by traversing right around the overlap (original finish, 5.8). Follow the bigger holds to the top. Walk off or rap from trees. 55

name: Locals Only
description: Start the same as Never Mind The Bollocks. The route was climbed as one long pitch on the first ascent.   P1: Climb the opening slab past two bolts to the tree ledge with the large pine. Move right and up a short block to gain the overlap (bolt). Make difficult moves to gain the large flake and a bolt. Climb the flake and continue up past another bolt to a ledge with a two bolt anchor. 90  5.10a    P2: Climb the flakes and face placing gear to a small pine below the roof. Move up some stacked blocks to a stance (bolt). Move right out the corner/arête on a mild run-out to a piece before you pull through the roof and onto a huge ledge (The Chinos Lounge). Move up one more tier to a two bolt anchor on the summit block. 80  5.10a PG

name: P.I. Dreams
description: This is a link up of Wet Lichen Dreams and Porno Poison Ivy.  The second pitch of PPI is slightly longer and a bit more challenging than that of WLD making for a more sustained overall climb.    P1.  Climb first pitch of Wet Lichen Dreams trending up and right after the crux roof to the bolted belay on top of P1 of Porno Poison Ivy.    P2.  Porno Poison Ivy.

name: Rampage
description: Rampage is a variation finish to Locals Only. It climbs direct out the large roof at the top of the cliff making for excellent exposure and views.     Climb Locals Only to the final bolt under the roof. Continue straight up under the roof and gain a horizontal and make a long clip to the fixed chain on the lip of the roof. Fire out the roof on big holds and finish at the Locals Only anchor.

name: Riptide
description: Start 15 to the left of Wet Lichen Dreams which has a bolt at 20 to help locate the start.    P1: Riptide climbs the arête of a short buttress of stacked blocks to a small tree ledge. Climb up the slab past a bolt to an overlap with gear. Pull the overlap and continue up the left facing corner on the left side of the roof. Clip a bolt and make the crux moves exiting the corner to a small foot ledge and another bolt. Move up and follow another left facing corner to a two bolt anchor below the overlap. 90   5.9+ PG   P2: Climb out left onto a large ledge and clip a bolt. Make the crux moves and continue up the fun and exposed face on big holds to a two bolt anchor on top. 70   5.8+

name: She's Out of Reach
description: An excellent climb with great variety.    Look for a little knoll with a tree just past The Arete (The Arete is one pitch up) and two bolts leading to a 3' roof with a third bolt just above it.     Use a flake to gain the first bolt at 15' and a stance.  One more sequence gains the second bolt.  Make a hard 5.10 face move past the second bolt to a slopey undercling (typically wet) at the third bolt.  Step right to a good hold and the crux.    A big move (crux) gains a horizontal break (has been done dynamically and statically).  Step up and right to a short, vertical crack.  Follow this to an easy but committing roof.  A few more face moves lead to a pinch with a thread anchor.    Stop here or..    She's Way Out of Reach....  5.10 A0 or 5.12+, FFA Jon Baldasarre 5/14    Continue up the steep face passing one more bolt (currently A0) and a horizontal.  Step right to a flake and stand up to a two bolt anchor.  The upper face is 5.10 if you pull on the bolt and is worth the effort -- or -- huck balls!!!  Nice work Baldy! Save a .4 for the horizontal. Lower or rap off with a 60, anything shorter and you're hosed.    NOTE:  To help reduce drag, clip the third bolt with an extendable draw but leave it short until you're at the stance after the big move.  You can reach down and extend it from here.

name: Steve Garvey Memorial Route
description: Pitch 1, 5.7R 50'. Climb up the face past loose flakes up to the right side of the roof. Continue up the right facing inside corner to its top. Walk 10' left and set up belay on comfortable ledge. Pitch 2, 5.10a, 5.8 pg-13, 80'. Climb up short slabs to a headwall. Step left and continue up and up to the first bolt in a blankish slab. Pull through crux (.10a) and continue over two more short headwalls until reaching a third one with a thin seam continuing up. Climb this and set up a gear belay. (Pitches 2&3 may be combined) Pitch 3, 5.11c, 40'. Put in gear under the roof, reach up and clip the bolt, then go for it. A couple of insecure moves on an overhanging wall lead to a bucket hold and then the top out.

name: Tree Hugger
description: Scramble up the gully just right of Graceful Tiers Move carefully around the blocks and up the corner until under the roof. Pull the roof on the right side and continue up to a small ledge with some birch trees. Follow the crux crack to a pine tree at its top. Hug the shit out of the pine to get around it.
