Continue up easy slab to a fun short left facing corner. Angle up and right and belay from the trees.

name: Wet Lichen Dreams
description: A nice two pitch route with varied climbing.   P1: Start up a moderate slab with gear to a bolt at 20. Continue up slabs past another bolt until under the large roof. Clip a bolt over the roof and crank the crux moves using a flake to surmount the roof. Keep cruising up the face with gear to a two bolt anchor on the ledge. 90   5.10 PG   P2: Climb the naturally well protected second pitch up a series of flakes and cracks to a two bolt anchor on top. 70   5.8

name: Adventures with Browdog
description: P1: Start about 30 feet to the right of Evening Blues. Climb up past the short slab to a ledge with two trees on it. Make a strange move to gain an undercling and a piece of gear under it. (This move is kinda hard?). Mantle onto the ledge and belay from the tree. (40) [NOTE: Check COMMENMTS below on rating of this pitch. R Hall, Admin.]   P2: Step left on the ledge to gear in a suspect flake. Keep moving up the clean streak of rock past slabs and horizontals for gear. Once on top walk back to a tree in the brush with an anchor on it. (90)  (Rap rings will be installed by Browdog)

name: Blackout
description: A natural line that follows flakes and horizontals past a pine tree below the overlap.    P1: Climb up big flakes and horizontals with gear and sling the pine. Pull the overlap to the tree anchor ledge. 80   5.9 PG-13   P2: Climb straight up on a great naturally protected pitch of jugs to the tree anchor on top. 60   5.4

name: The Browdog Indirect
description: A link-up of the first pitch of Evening Blues with the second pitch of Adventures with Browdog. From the start, climb up the slab and horizontals, then up a dike, past 2 pins.  Step right several feet onto a moderately sized ledge below a clean streak of rock to the right. Belay at the ledge with the tree, or continue up the clean streak, placing gear in horizontals, until you arrive at the top of the cliff. Belay off tree set back from the top. Rappel from the tree anchor atop Evening Blues. This link up avoids a more dirty and less aesthetic first pitch of Adventures with Browdog.

name: Cleaning up the Scraps
description: Move up a low angle corner then step back to the left on a flake on the edge of a roof. Rock up on this foot(crux) the some nice easy fun move to the top. Use care on the bottom of this route because there are a lot of loose flakes.

name: Coyote Rain
description: Takes a surprisingly easy line directly through the center of the large roof feature on the far right of the cliff. Should become a popular beginner route as it is now thoroughly cleaned, has great protection, and exciting moves on big holds.P1: From the beech tree at the start of Rona's Roof, face climb straight up (fixed pin on left) then passing climbers right of a small tree, then directly up to a stance under the large roof. Place pro and fire over the roof on huge holds to an easy, broken slab. Pine tree belay with fixed rap station. 70', 5.6P2: Continue straight up the broken slab to a shared 2-bolt anchor atop Trifecta. 50', 5.5

name: Coyote Ugly
description: A direct start variation to Coyote Rain.  Flake the rope & have your belayer stand next to the tree, where the original start is to Coyote Rain.Begin the climb to the left & below the original start, below a right-facing flake & directly underneath the pine tree way up that is growing underneath a detached triangular block.Climb the lower slabs, then the flake, then a series of ledges.  Clip the Chinos piton on the right, then continue up.  Protect next in a small crack on the right (small pieces might make you feel better), then fire a somewhat thought-provoking crux.  At the pine tree, go right. Do not sling the tree or climb the detached block - its integrity is questionable. Should be fine left alone.Continue right on jugs and up to the Coyote Rain roof. Fire the roof & continue up to the P1 tree anchor.A climb for those of you who want to combine the thrilling roof of Coyote Rain  with classic Longstack ledge-hopping. Can also be toproped after leading Coyote Rain P1. FA J. Browher, Z. Ross,  Jun 2020

name: Do You Want Your Pant Legs?
description: When you walk up the approach stairs to the Right Wall there are huge flakes. The climb is still cleaning up, so watch for loose stuff.   P1: The route starts up the right side of the flakes placing gear to a bolt at a protruding feature. Climb the feature to a small left arching crack that leads you to a ledge with a gear belay under the roof. 80    P2: Climb a short corner and transfer left to the cool arching flake to a bolt. Continue up the features to a tree anchor on top. 70

name: Evening Blues
description: P1: Follow up a slab feature trending slightly right to the short crux headwall. Make a big reach over the lip to good hands. Move up to the tree anchor. 55    5.7  PG   P2: Continue up and a bit right following easy slabs and jugs on enjoyable easy climbing. 70 5.5

name: Gentle Violence
description: Climb up a short unprotected slab to the bolt line. Clip a bolt from the ledge and move up to the right facing arch and make the second clip. (A small cam between bolts can help ease the mind for the second clip). Strenuous moves lead to the third clip and the crux moves on the blank slab. Gain a flake and another bolt and continue up past one more bolt on an easier face with a brief run-out to the bolt anchor on the roof.    A second pitch project pulls the roof to another bolt and joins Gold Lion to finish.

name: Gold Lion
description: Start 10 right of Gentle Violence near the tree.    P1: Climb up to the first bolt and make the crux move lunge to a rail and pocket (bolt). Move up into the left sweeping arch. Pull up the left side to a stance (bolt). Make tricky moves to gain a blind placement (.75 in the left side works good) in a horizontal. Pull onto the ledge and a two bolt anchor under the roof. 55   5.10+   P2: Clip a bolt over the roof (aid was used to pull the roof) and make hard moves to a ledge. Move up a series of headwalls placing gear to a two bolt anchor below the trees. 70  5.8 A0.

name: The Mighty Quinn
description: Start about 10 right of Gold Lion up a couple ledges to a small ramp/corner system (pin). Move right across the ramp and up the face placing gear to a sketchy flake/block with a bolt above it. Clip the bolt and gain a ledge. Use the two bolt anchor of Gold Lion.

name: Rona's Roof
description: The start of the climb is located uphill behind a beech tree. Climb a series of flakes placing gear to the crux overlap. Pull the overlap and move right to a tree anchor.

name: The Route Vultures
description: A worthwhile addition to the far right side of the Wonderland Wall, this route was named for the turkey vulture circling overhead as it was cleaned on rappel.  Longstack's carcass continues to get picked clean...    P1:  Amble up the easy but interesting face with good pro where you need it.  Head towards the middle of the thin roof up high, and pull through at the obvious small dike.  A short, quizzical crux leads to a step left and the Rona's Roof anchor.    P2:  From the tree anchor, climb up through a series of short clean walls separated by dirt covered ledges trending up and slightly left.  5.3

name: Short Stack
description: Short Stack is a variation to Weston's Syrup. Climb past three bolts on Weston's Syrup to the second roof. Traverse left into a left facing corner and follow the finger crack back right to the anchor on top.

name: Speck In My Eye
description: This is a long route that goes straight to the top of the cliff.  It was first climbed as a long single pitch using double ropes.  This route shares the beginning of Do You Want Your Pant Legs?  However, after clipping the first bolt on the big flake, continue straight up the headwall through some finger pockets and a system of cracks directly above.  Continue through a series of moderate slab bulges until you reach the crux, involving a bouldery move over a small but steep overhang.  Use double ropes for a single rappel from the trees, or walk off.

name: Trifecta
description: P1: Climb up flakes for 10 to a ledge and clip a bolt. Move up the corner/flake placing gear until under the roof. Move slightly left to the weakness and crux of the route. Exciting moves bring you over the roof to the tree anchor above. 80  5.9   P2: Climb straight up off the anchor climbing the clean streak on the right. A fun pitch of jug climbing with a brief slab crux leads to the tree anchor on top. 60   5.6

name: Weston's Syrup
description: The climb starts just right of the obvious flake system. Climb directly up the slab face past 2 bolts to a short easy corner with marginal gear. Move up to the overlap and clip a bolt. Make nice delicate moves up to a horizontal under the roof and clip a bolt above. Pull the fun roof to a ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: Winter Classic
description: P1: Start up a series of cleaned ledges 15 right of Mighty Quinn to a flake with gear. Climb past four bolts making interesting moves with good rests. Finish up through some blueberries to a tree anchor. 65  5.10a   P2: Continue straight up from the tree anchor on slabs and short headwalls placing gear when possible. A bolt anchor awaits on top. 70  5.8 PG

name: Wonderland
description: This route is a tribute to Loran Smith. Loran cleaned the route but was unable to climb it before moving west to Colorado. The route was set up by Garlough and Corbett the following day and climbed.     Loran spent his early years taking chances and climbing the dirty walls of Longstack on nuts and hexes. His love for the cliff was reignited in 2010 and he added many great lines at Longstack. He will be greatly missed by all the members of the Chinos Mountain Club.     This route starts to the left of Gentle Violence.     P1: Climb the short unprotected slab to a ledge (bolt). Follow flakes to a overlap (bolt) and pull over on the left edge to a short slab (bolt). Pull the small roof on big holds and continue up right of the pine tree to another small roof (bolt). Fire the crux on thin holds and continue straight up to a tree ledge with a three bolt anchor. 100'    P2: Climb straight up off the anchor on easy terrain to the trees on top. 50'    P2 Variation: Move right from the anchor and follow a clean streak to the top. 50'

name: Corner Crack
description: Just around the corner to the left of Ol Dirt Dogg is the obvious corner crack system. Climb up the corner/crack placing gear. When the corner ends move up the slab to the trees above. Rap from trees or walk off.

name: Desperado
description: Start 15' left of El Mariachi. Climb a cleaned slab up to the crux mantle at a shelf with a small tree. Continue up an easier slab to a ledge. Climb the steep headwall with a big pocket up to another ledge and continue up the face with big horizontal holds to a two bolt anchor

name: El Mariachi
description: Walk left about 50 yards away from the Satellite Wall down a short steep wall. This route is the first cleaned streak at the end of the short wall. Climb up a well featured slab placing gear and slinging trees along the way. Pull over the short headwall to a spacious ledge. Continue up the dirty slab to the trees above.

name: Ol' Dirt Dogg
description: About 100 left of Sandinista is another cleaned streak just before the Corner Crack. Climb up the unprotected slab to the headwall. Climb the headwall placing gear along the way. Belay and rap from the large tree at the top.

name: Perdido
description: This fun route starts 50' left of Sandinista and 25' right from Ol' Dirt Dog. Starts on a clean white streak in front of a standing dead tree, friction up to 2 horizontal cracks. Move right to the end of the cracks and up to a right leaning crack, at the end of where the crack stops going right proceed straight up to the large ledge.   (tricky gear placement to protect the move up to the large ledge, can be done with a red tri-cam and a stacked nut in a solution pocket)     Straight back on the large tree ledge proceed up the clean rock to a 2 bolt anchor.    Standard trad rack including tri-cams  up to a #2(gold) Camalot    FA: George Hurley, Jim Nupp & David Giampietro August 2016

name: Sandinista
description: Start 15' left of Desperado at a cleaned slab. Climb the slab up to a big tree ledge at about 35'. Follow the series of headwalls straight up to a two bolt anchor on a blueberry ledge.

name: The Arete
description: Climb the arête feature just to the right of Mollys Crack.  Place gear when possible on the way.

name: Cowboy's From Hell
description: Start 10 left of Daddys Day Out below another bolt line. Climb up the technical face past two bolts and finish up easier terrain to the trees at the top.

name: Daddy's Day Out
description: Start 10 Left of the previous route at a faint dike. Climb the faint dike up and left to a flake. Continue straight up the face to the top. A couple pieces of gear protect the route.

name: Flake Route
description: Start 15 to the left of Flakes and Dykes at a large left facing flake. Climb the flake until it ends and continue up the slab to the top.

name: Flakes and Dikes
description: Start 12 left of Cowboys. Climb a nice dike past two bolts. The climbing eases up as you finish to the trees above.

name: Killing Time in the Crystal City
description: The face between "Cowboys From Hell" and "Daddy's Day Out."  Begin immediately left of a beech tree, and climb straight up, then slightly left past a huge natural thread and a crystal filled pocket that gives the route it's name.  Really fun moves with a couple distinct mini cruxes.

name: Molly's Crack
description: The only crack line around. Climb the short but fun crack to the top placing gear along the way.

name: Shaman Moves
description: Move like a shaman as you highstep and dance back & forth across the blunt arete several times on the way to the top.  Don't blow the crux clip, or the shaman might rip your heart out.

name: Thanks to the Nubbins
description: The first route with bolts when walking left. Climb past two bolts on thin moves. Follow easier terrain to the top.

name: Bad Religion
description: Start at the base of the massive dike/gully. Climb up the unprotected lobster tail to the ledge at 20'. Clip a bolt with a quick link (Child's Play anchor). A four foot runner helps with rope drag. Pull out the roof using the dike past 2 pins. Clip a bolt over the final over lap and finish at a bolt/tree anchor.

name: Black Lips
description: This is an awesome little route that is unique for the area. Start in the same spot as Pump Up the Valuum. Climb up the short slab and traverse left across a massive flake to a bolt. Set up a belay here or clip a long runner. Climb up onto a ledge above the bolt. Step left to some big jugs. Fire straight up to the horizontal and escape right around the roof and pull into the corner. Continue up to a 2 bolt anchor.

name: Child's Play
description: Climb up the obvious dike/gully on really big holds to the ledge. Make another move and clip a single bolt with a quick link (anchor).

name: Psychic City
description: Start on the right side of the alcove area. Clip a bolt next to a flake/horizontal and pull over the overlap (crux). Climb up with gear opportunities and pull over onto a sloping ledge. Clip the second bolt on the bulge. Pull over the bulge/overlap on big holds and place more gear in the horizontals. Angle left to a tree anchor.

name: Pump Up the Valuum
description: Look for a large flake up high to locate the climb. Start up the slab corner for 25' placing gear. At the overhang fire straight up on great holds with excellent movement past 3 bolts. Take care when using the massive flake. 2 bolt anchor awaits at the top.

name: Rastafari Crack
description: Start the same as Psychic City. Climb past the first bolt to a small ledge. Traverse left and pull the bulge to gain the hand crack above an overlap. Follow the short dirty crack and step right to the tree anchor on Psychic City.

name: Transfusion
description: start at a foot legde in the gully. clip the first bolt out right. From there move out right on the face.climb straight up to the second bolt an follow the arete to a bolt under the roof. Exit the roof with wild moves!!!

name: Chinos Cafe
description: Start at a cleaned streak 25 left of Watch Owl. Climb up easy rock to a high first bolt with an optional gear placement down low. Continue up past three more bolts making a series of mantles to a large ledge. Run it out on easier slab to a bolt anchor.

name: Clash City Rockers
description: Start at the far right end of the cliff. Climb up discontinuous cracks with distinct pods placing gear to the roof. Gain the horizontal on top of the roof and hand traverse left onto the overhang and climb straight up the face past a couple of ledges and clip a bolt. Make a funky move up to clip the bolt anchor.

name: The Fin
description: Start the same as Metal Blade. Climb up 10 to a ledge. Climb up the crack and follow the big arching flake left until it ends (#2-3 cams). Climb straight up to a shelf and then trend up and right on dirty terrain to the trees above.

name: Metalblade
description: Start 20 to the left of Clash City Rockers. Climb up past two bolts in the corner. Make an airy move out onto the protruding blade of rock and clip the third bolt. Make a tough mantle to gain a bolt anchor.

name: Waiting For Arsenault
description: The route was originally cleaned for the new local Steve Arsenault. Steve never did make it out, so the local crew "The Chinos" nabbed the route!    This climb starts on the left side of the Right Wall. A lone bolt 25' up marks the start. Climb up under a overlap and follow a left facing flake to its end. Make the crux moves and clip a bolt. Continue straight up the face placing gear and slinging natural threads in horizontals. Surmount a small juggy roof to a large ledge with a chain anchor.

name: Watch Owl
description: Start about 20 left of the starting ledge for the previous routes. Climb the corner to the right of the big block of choss until under the thin roof. Place gear in a thin seam and pull directly over the overlap. Move left on the ledge and make the crux moves past 2 bolts. Continue up the steep face placing gear to a big spike of rock. Pull over the spike onto a belay ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: Westfalia
description: Start about 20 left of the starting ledge for The Fin. Climb the corner to the right of the big block of choss until under the thin roof. Place gear in a thin seam and pull directly over the overlap. Move left on the ledge and make the crux moves past 2 bolts. Continue up the steep face placing gear to a big spike of rock. Pull over the spike onto a belay ledge with a bolt anchor

name: Coney Island Baby
description: Start 15 uphill and left of Perfect Day. Climb direct up the face past two bolts and clip the forth bolt on Perfect Day. Finish at the same anchors as Perfect Day. Syd Howard did a line in this area on gear prior to the bolts. Maybe not the same?

name: Gunks Style
description: Start at the right side of the Satellite Wall. Climb up the face just left of the the roofs. When above the roof traverse right out to the arete. Finish up to the trees above.

name: Perfect Day
description: Start 15 to the left of Vicious. Climb up and left past four bolts. The crux is between bolts 2-3. Finish at a ring anchor up and left of the forth bolt.

name: Satellite of Love
description: A long traverse across the entire Satellite Wall from right to left. Start by climbing to the first bolt on Vicious. Move up to the next horizontal and traverse left to the first bolt on Perfect Day. Climb Perfect Day to the forth bolt. Move up to the next horizontal and traverse left. Follow the bolt line left past four more bolts to a ring anchor.

name: Vicious
description: Start at the right side of the wall. Climb up the face past two bolts and then trend slightly left and up past two more bolts to a double bolt anchor

name: Majestic Steeds
description: Majestic Steeds climbs the high quality orange face/arete in the center of the wall. Climb past 4 bolts on gently overhanging rock to a bolt anchor. Its not over til you clip the anchors!

name: Sputnik
description: Start in the alcove on the right side of the wall. Climb up the crack and move left to a bolt. Continue traversing left under an overlap to the second bolt. Pull the overlap and continue past a third bolt to a two bolt anchor above.

name: Black Mamba
description: Climb the black water stained streak (often wet) past 3 black bolts. Pull onto a ledge with optional gear. Climb up to the forth black bolt. Continue up with more gear in horizontals to a ring anchor.

name: Chicken Leg Landry
description: Start at the big chimney/off-width. Climb the series of ledges and cracks trending right. At a small tree ledge finish up the final off-width corner to trees above.

name: Chimney Route
description: Decent climbing that's a little bit clean but not really. Kind of good for a chimney I guess

name: Dogs of War
description: A nice thin face climb. Climb easier terrain to the halfway horizontal placing gear on the way. Get some good gear in the horizontal and then pull onto the final steep headwall. Place gear in shallow horizontal to and anchor at the top.

name: Dyke Route
description: Climb a nasty dyke up to a crack. Follow the crack and finish up blocky terrain to the top.

name: Eastern Cougar
description: Stick clip a high first bolt at the dyke route. Climb up the dyke to the bolt then trend right onto the face and continue past 2 more bolts to a horizontal that takes gear. Finish up easier terrain placing gear to trees above.

name: Fook Pig
description: Can you find the source of the name? Start the same as Chicken Leg Landry. Climb up the wide crack to the first ledge and then step left and undercling out to the high first bolt. Make the crux moves over the small overlap onto a small shelf and clip the second bolt. The blocks dirctly above the bolts look very suspect and I would recommend staying away from them. Climb up and left into an alcove and follow a small crack to the tree above.

name: The Great White Roof
description: Start at a small dead tree at the base. Climb up flakes and dykes past three bolts to a ledge below the roof. Climb up the crack and clip a fixed cord on a chockstone. Follow the fist to hand crack right under the roof and top out when the roof ends.

name: Howl Skank
description: Another roof system halfway up the cliff. Climb up the first part of Knights in White Spandex past 2 bolts and then traverse right over to the tree ledge (belay). Climb the big flake roof crack up and right and then continue up to trees at the top.

name: Knights in White Spandex
description: Climb up a small corner/flake to a high first bolt. At the second bolt traverse right along a shelf. Make a move up to another shelf and clip the third bolt. Climb through the crux to a horizontal that takes gear. Continue up the excellent face past a bolt to ring anchors just out of site over the bulge.

name: Mean Streak
description: Start 15' right of Black Mamba at a pocket. Climb up the slab placing gear past 2 bolts to an overlap. Pull the overlap using a big flake and continue up the face placing gear in horizontals to a ring anchor with a nice view!

name: Misled Youth
description: This route climbs the main buttress up the tallest part of the cliff. Climb up an easy slab to lone bolt. Continue up the slab with thin moves to gain a horizontal with a gear placement. Make moves up to a big flake and clip a bolt. Make the crux moves up to a jug and clip the third bolt. Make a hard mantle move to gain a ledge. Take a rest and then follow the arete past horizontals with gear to ring anchors at the top.

name: Mr. Bojangles
description: Climb the flake on the left end of the cliff. Pull over a small roof and continue up the face on big holds. The top has a new bolt anchor.

name: Project ...
description: Climb a thin flake with a bolt to a small roof. Clip the second bolt and make the crux moves over the roof on thin holds. Climb easier terrain past 2 more bolts to ring anchors.

name: Rigormortis
description: At the far right end of the crag start at a large oak tree and small cave. Climb up the cracks and ledges to a roof. Make the crux moves over the roof to a ledge. Finish up the final V-Groove to the tree above.

name: That Ain't Surette
description: A wild variation finish to The Great White Roof. Climb The Great White Roof until you are under the roof. Finish out directly over the roof and make a hard exciting mantle to the top with your last gear in the crack below the roof.

name: Arete Problem
description: Just to the left of the high ball is a cleaned off arete. Climb the arete on good holds to the top.

name: Aron A Aronson
description: Climb the arete to the top staying to the left side

name: Bass Eatin' Season
description: Ascends easy terrain past horizontals past the ledge to a left-facing, ear-like feature. Find the top, then finish up the center of the bow-like feature.Named as it was cleaned and climbed before & after the bass spawning season in NH

name: Bear Naked
description: Near the top it a push to get to a crimp but its big

name: Blood Diamond
description: Walk up the trail from the parking lot until the trail takes a sharp left at the base of the boulders. Walk right in the opposite direction of the trail for 150' to a pointed boulder. start on two small crimps with a good left foot of the arching rail. a one move wonder sticking the next crimp. top out at the point.

name: Boderline
description: About 10' right of Dike Steps is a cleaned section of horizontals leading between 2 small trees about halfway up, the finish is in a blocky section with 2 bolts- fun top out!

name: The Buddha
description: Make crux moves off the ground past the first bolt, then climb fun moves up to a second slabby crux around the second bolt.     Top out and belay from a tree, this route would be nice with a bolted anchor to eliminate the rope drag.

name: Casual Crack
description: Just around the corner follow another left leaning crack until it ends. Step right into a small crack and finish up the crux to trees.

name: Cave Direct
description: Sit start in the small cave area just left of a tree. Pull on the main crimp rail in the back to start. Move up on crimps and a big hold over the lip to the top.

name: Cave Traverse
description: Start on the far right side of the boulder. A series of big hands and heel hooks will bring you into the Cave Direct route. The crux is getting into the Cave Direct. Rocks at the base make it hard to get a pad in there without being in the way. Make a hard throw up to the hold over the lip and finish to top.

name: Cave Traverse Plus
description: Start as for Cave Traverse but follow the seam system around the corner instead of continuing up Cave Direct. Perform a full value mantle to establish on the slabby left side of the boulder.

name: Diagonal
description: Sit start the crux is getting off the ground.Climb the crack.

name: Dike Steps
description: There is no definite crux, its like climbing steps.

name: Dirty Bird
description: Climb up some easy moves to a few awkward and fun moves around the lone bolt. Once passed the single bolt climb up easy ground to the anchor.     The climbing is really enjoyable and a quality route. Having the anchor is convenient, a few more routes in the area could benefit from a fixed anchor.

name: Dirty Corner
description: starts just left of old route.start just left of the small roof about 3 feet off the ground reading for a nice fist sized pod. then climb the corner using pockets and horizontals placing solid gear the whole way. then climb the face straight up to the pine tree.    there is also a variation that is the direct start to the right up a small flaring left facing flake(5.7).

name: The Electric Rodeo
description: Ascend the ramp & horizontals to the top of the cliff, where you'll find nice jugs for handholds.  Find your feet, and top out.  This climb is named in honor of the one & only Electric Wrangler, who cut her teeth at Rines with the OSP. May the legend inspire generations of future new climbers & wearers of the Seattle Sombrero.  5.7 VARIATION: Rhinestone: Look for a small pocket to the right of the ramp.  Climb up, use the 2 pockets between the horizontals as feet, and join The Electric Rodeo.

name: Everything's Groovy
description: Climb the groove to the end, tree on the left. Move slightly left, up then back slightly right,several places for protection. Top out is spicy if you don't grab the root! Can top rope this from 2 ring tree  anchor

name: Fat Crack
description: A left leaning 4" crack. A few big pieces can protect the climb. Finish at trees.

name: Flake Route
description: Trad up a faint dike to a ledge. Continue up the flake and face to the trees above.

name: Flakes
description: Use the flakes for feet,then get your feet as high as you can....then mantle

name: Granite State
description: the same all the way to the top.more slab climbing then anything.

name: Have an Ort
description: Follow up cleaned rock,then slightly left to a pine just below the top of the cliff. There is a tree to belay from just back from the cliff.

name: High Ball
description: Walk left along the base of the cliff until you come to the large obvious boulder. Climb the clean face with bigger holds up the tallest part of the boulder. Walk off the fin/ramp to ground.

name: Just Visiting
description: Start squatting in two sloper/crimp pods with less that desirable feet. Cross right hand through to a big hold, then rearrange your feet and toss left hand to a hand slot above and top out on jugs.

name: Just Visiting SDS
description: Start sitting for Just Visiting with a left hand side pull and right hand in a sloping crimp slot.

name: K1,K2,K3,K4,K5
description: K1-slab to crack-5.3 K2-blocks to a corner-5.4 K3-slabby blocks-5.4 K4-lie-back,cracks and edge to top-5.8 K5-horizontals to a crack behind oak tree-5.8  [Note: R Hall added the photos of K1 - K 5  and their captions on 7/28/19 at the e-mail request of J. Nupp. ]

name: Layback Cracks
description: Climb the only crack on the face. Top out up a gully next to a big block.

name: Left Route
description: Start at the crack and move right along the rail to the first bolt. Climb straight up the face to another bolt with a optional gear placement in the hirizontal. Continue to tree above.

name: Middle Crack
description: The middle route of the three left leaning cracks. Follow the line to the top.

name: Moss Face
description: Climb up the mossy face in the amphitheatre area. Climb the big jugs and horizontals to the top.

name: Mr. Snuffleupagus
description: Stand start with hands on a flake then traverse right over a smaller boulder.Steming on the smaller boulder makes it easier.

name: No name
description: Its all just one motion

name: Nose squeeze
description: Start sitting on a sloper with left hand and a 2 finger shallow dish with the right. Figure out a way to pull off the ground and reach the crimp over the lip.

name: Old Route
description: The trail comes to the base of this climb. Climb the dyke past an bolt. Finish to trees.

name: Pedastal Dyno
description: This one is a little height dependant and hard to grade. Start sitting on the rock platform and pull on with the undercling and launch for the lip! Funner than it seems. Don't fall off the rock!

name: Right Ramp
description: A discontinous crack up the ramp in the corner. crack gets bigger at the top.

name: Right Route
description: Stick Clip the eye bolt on the right side of the wall. Make hard moves out of the alcove. Clip the third bolt on the traverse and continue up the left finish to the chain anchor.

name: The Scat Problem
description: Start sitting on slopers and pull into the slot. Make your way over the roof to a exposed mantle. Make sure you clean the top off first or you will understand the route name more!

name: Squeeze Box
description: At the base of the highball look right. A smaller boulder with an overhang is the climb. Start on crimps under the overhang. slap up left to the sloping lip. work right and move to a shelf. top out.

name: Standard Route
description: Climb the big obvious dyke up the wall and pick 1 of the 3 finishes. All vary a bit from 5.7 and protect different as well. Use your head and pick one.

name: Strong Johns Slopers
description: Start low on a sloping shelf with a good left foot. Pull on and figure out how to move to the right and top out.

name: Thin Little Dike
description: Sit start ,Pull on little crimp and then mantle to the top

name: Time for Funk
description: To the right of Two Cracks V0 is a good vertical rail on the face that leads up to the right of the cracks. Sit start on the rail and stand up into the cracks.

name: Trail Boulder
description: on the approach trail there is a large boulder. Climb the center of the boulder to a large pocket and top out. Sit starts make it harder.

name: Trail side traverse
description: Star at the right tree then climb to the crack and traverse left to a tree then back right

name: Traverse Route Left Finish
description: Start direct under the first bolt of the traverse. Make a hard move to gain the rail. Traverse right past 2 bolts and make a hard move up when the rail ends to a horizontal. Continue straight up past an eyebolt to a chain anchor.

name: Traverse Route Right Finish
description: Start at the crack on the left side and traverse the rail right past 3 bolts until the rail ends. Make a hard big move up to a hidden crimp to a large horizontal. Move up right past 2 bolts and a pin to the top.

name: Tree Slab
description: Just a fun little easy route

name: Two Cracks
description: Just climb the two crack you will see...

name: The Well
description: the grade is all dependent on hieght and being 5'8'' it runs about v5/v6 while for taller people in may be easier and dip down into V4.    start on a nice jug down low and make a move to the horizontal crack  where it starts to become slightly overhanging and work you feet up. then Dyno for the sloping lip. best place to land is on the sloping horn. then if you can hold on/ stick the dyno top out on eiser grounds.

name: The Yacht Rock
description: Climb easy terrain past horizontals to a ledge.  Move left to a smaller foot-ledge, then up hidden but good hands, and finish up the top of the prow-like feature.  Belay or top-rope off the tree.  Running a cord/rope with a loop for protection on the last move makes this G-rated.

name: Big Brother
description: Lay-back and stem the beautiful corner to the trees. This climb is really good, just in a bad location. The route is clean all but to top of the corner.

name: Little Brother
description: Lay-back and stem up the finger crack to the trees. Rappel from trees. 25 years ago I left slings and rings up there, cant see them now. This climb is pretty good but it is a bit dirty now, maybe it will get cleaned up next summer.

name: The Cock Bloc
description: Start on the finger jug/rail on the right side of this protruding horn, using any manner of heel and toe hooks to move under and around the block, to top out on the wall to the left. Tricky but fun. Transitioning to the wall may be the most difficult and least fun moves.

name: The Compression Problem
description: Start at the bottom of this arete, with feet on either side, and compressed on the lowest slopers of each side. Start bumping or slapping to top out a mere 3 feet above your head. Surprisingly fun for the distance!

name: The Clean Ascent
description: Just left of Down, Not Out (V0-), climb the clean face on holds and horizontals to an easy top out. Really enjoyable climbing!

name: Delirium's  Cure
description: The obvious line on the far left end of the steep wall. Start on a good right hand crimp, and a decent chip for the left. Move up through some tension based holds, up to the big move to the hold over the lip. It’s not actually over. Pull your way onto the slab, then keep it together for a few easy moves, and a somewhat hairy and high topout. Walk/scramble/shrub climb right to the ledge and down climb Down Not Out (V0-) or move directly up to top out and walk around the cliff line.

name: Down, Not Out
description: Ten feet right of the steep section of the wall, look at the obvious crack/flake system with a block (firmly) wedged into it. Follow the break to the top for a very easy mantle. Pull down, not out as the name suggests. Down climb, or take care to top out through some roots and shrubs.

name: Old Man Winter
description: Start out climbing a rather disgusting slab/finger crack for the first 10' before reaching the enjoyable crack system. Place gear and continue up and left following the cracks and topping out at the highest point on the cliff. Anchor from the trees far above. Not a bad route, but dirty until you reach the cracks. Lots of options for placements, this route was my first gear protected lead.

name: The Spice of Life
description: Find two opposing slanted side pulls in the middle of the wall. Start at the break below, and work your way onto these holds using low feet. Stick a righthand crimp flake, and shoot out to the jug at the lip. Pull onto the slab and delicately make your way to the top. Down climb Down Not Out (V0-) or pull on roots etc to top out the wall and walk right to eventually make it back below.

name: Two for One
description: Start in the break as for Spice of life, but move right from the side pulls, keeping your feet low and making interesting moves on crimps and a sharp tooth. Move into Whack-A-Bush to finish out the wall.

name: Whack-a-Bush
description: Start below and to the left of The Clean Ascent, also below and left of a crack system heading up the wall. Pull out of the break up to a right crimp and left gaston. Pump out to the jug rail at the lip, and continue up the crack to top out.

name: Beached Whale
description: Start on a small right crimp and good left hand on the arete. Pull towards the top, several ways are possible, but the most direct/interesting falls in the V2 range. Pull the sloping mantle for the full "beached whale" value!

name: Coffee and Cough Drops
description: (It's what I was subsisting on at the time of the FA)    Start on the flat, sloping shelf just right of Rustic Remnants. Pull straight up until it's possible to move left to top out.

name: Rustic Remnants
description: A fine route with a tough move through a sloping pocket/edge, and a sloping top-out on wavy schist. Start on the diamond-shaped gap (the missing piece should be around somewhere....), and pull out left to the sloping pocket. It looks easier to go right, but it's not, somehow...  vimeo.com/93535717    It's the last problem shown in this video (and the displayed picture).

name: The Shark's Fin
description: Find the very obvious feature and start on the right-most side of the ledgey hand feature. Traverse left until it's possible to top out. Really cool and fun feature.

name: Fault Lines
description: Sit start in a lower crack and move straight up to the higher crack, which you'll follow to topout. Nice fine-textured schist and good, friendly holds.

name: Flight School Project
description: Sit start as for Learning to Stand (V2), make the big move, then set up for a throw to the lip. There's an edge up there that's latch-able(?). I never got it anyway, could be harder but I suspect it's no easier than V6. It felt not possible when I was climbing the occasional V6 in Pawtuckaway.

name: Learning to Stand
description: Start almost sitting on the jug rail under the arete, make the big move before moving up and right to gain a sidepull that lets you stand up to the lip.

name: Beech Day
description: An okay, if sometimes wet, little route that starts just right of the namesake tree on an incut horn, with feet on the shelf below the rock. Drop into the horn and punch up into some crimps before performing an odd topout.

name: Drawing Lines
description: A line of perfectly cut schist edges starts with some funky beta to get off the ground. Begin on the left-facing gaston rail, somewhere around the middle. Properly placed feet make a tough starting move a little easier before trending up and right on great holds.

name: Flying grey squirrel
description: Start sitting on the v groove under the boulder made a move up to a good sloper and gain better holds over the top. A right exit may merritt a grade harder.

name: Mooers cave
description: Start sitting in the cave on a sloper. Make a big move out left to a good lip, the are more holds over the bulge. Figure out the sequence for the top.

name: Spring Again
description: Good rock, with the exception of the sharp crystals for the topout. The first line done here. A stiff move leads to several easy moves onto the lip, where an odd mantle solidifies the grade. Consider creative use of the feet to get off the ground...

name: Flicker
description: Mantle into the choss shelf, and be careful not to knock bits of rock down. There is a good (and solid!) crimp rail at the lip that will allow you to set up for a throw to a jug high up. The rock from here is solid, but the top out is committing and will likely require cleaning for future attempts.

name: Floating Point Precision
description: The overhanging, left leaning wall that trends up above Main Cliff. Start on the sloped landing under the feature on a small crimp rail. Pull hard to get a heel up and slap onto the arete. Continue moving left crimps and right hand arete holds to top out slightly up and left. Fun feature, surprising good rock, although somewhat fragile.

name: Barb
description: under cling, side pull, lie back, mantle

name: Barbor
description: crux is mantling the shelf   make your way up the V slot on the left

name: High Life
description: Sit start the flake and climb it to the top. Fun moves but over way to quickly.

name: Unknown
description: I don’t have any FA info/original route name or even if this is the standard route up this face, but it’s too good not to share. Start with your hands matched down and left of the face in a triangular hole.  Work your way up and right through thin holds to gain a great jug. Grab the lip and mantle over.

name: A Vulnerable Man
description: High quality moves with an awkward starting position.    Sit start with left hand on a good edge and right hand on a good knob with you feet awkwardly behind the rock you are sitting on. Make a big move up and right to an edge. Work your feet around and come left hand into a good gaston followed by a couple balance moves on crimp to a jug at the top.

name: Chernabog
description: Start on undercling and follow flake up to side pull/pinch at base of roof.  Slap up roof and don’t blow the mantle.  Decent holds on the slab.

name: The Dominion
description: Sit start with left hand on a cool pinched right hand on a good sidepull. Move left hand up to a big gaston and right into a pocket undercling. Work you feet around and crux left hand up to a good hold, then top out.

name: Forgetting Lasts So Long
description: Start crouching/sitting with the left hand on a small crimp on the left arete at around 4 feet and the right hand on an obvious crimp/sidepull at the same level, located about 4-5 feet right of the arete. The left hand starting hold is located a foot or so down from an obvious little bump on the arete. (See the photo of the starting holds below. The bump is the first chalked hold up from the starting left hand.) Make a hard first move to gain the small bump and then continue through a series of powerful compression moves to a crimp/edge rail at around 11 feet. From here, move left onto the slab and follow a line of good holds that angles left to reach the top of the boulder. Once established on the slab, the finishing moves are fairly easy but quite highball, topping out somewhere in the 20-25 foot range. A hard and sustained power endurance line that will likely test your fitness.  A brilliant and highly aesthetic line on flawless rock. Many repeaters have called this one of the best climbs in NH.  This was formerly known as 'The Alchemist Project'.

name: Lord of War
description: Start start on a big undercling with your right hand and a big right facing side pull with your left, now make crux move(s) up to the seam above. Establish yourself in the seam and move up to a cool hold below the lip, then topout straight up with a hidden jug over the lip.    For tall climbers the crux will feel a bit easier than the grade and it will feel harder for short climbers.

name: Native Rights
description: Sit start on jugs on the little boulder at the point of the boulder. Climb up with left hand on jugs to a fun lip encounter.

name: The Regulator
description: Sit start the same as 'Lord of War' on the big undercling and right facing sidepull and make the crux move up into the crack. Once in the crack traverse it right to the end of the boulder and topout.

name: Send Train, The
description: Starting on nice holds down low, moving up and right following the fingercrack/flake up to a tiny roof with an obvious hold under it that isn't as good as it looks. Choose whether to top out right onto slopers (tougher) or left with nice jugs.

name: The Troubadour
description: Start with good feet in the pit and matched on a good crimp rail. Move up to the crimps above your head and set up for the crux, a long move to a blind hold on the angling rail above. Match the rail and surf it to the jugs at the lip.

name: Anadromous
description: Squat start on the obvious jug, pull up to series of crimps out left before making the crux move to a good crimp back right, directly above the starting hold. One you have latched that crimp top out.

name: The Salty Dawg
description: Sit start the right-most arete matched on a crimp rail, make fun moves up the arete to a juggy shelf just before the top of the boulder, mantle onto the shelf and top out.
Sit start on the vertical seam, make a long pull up to the edge up and left. From there move left and match on the edge before moving to the lip and a hidden hold and then top out to the left.

name: Glass Ceiling
description: Sit start and climb the series of large flat holds that trend slightly left. This has not received a proper cleaning yet and may get another star when it does.

name: I Can't Breathe
description: You don't often get to do a foot jam, arm-bar, and finger lock on a boulder problem. Well you can on this one. Sit start and on the crimps at the bottom of the flared section of the crack and climb it straight up.   The top out may still be a little sandy but will get better over time.

name: Love Wins
description: Sit start with your left hand underclinging on the lowest rail and right hand on a pinch on the arete. Pull on with a kneebar and make a long move up to the sloper curved rail above, match it and then move up to the lip. Surf the lip to the high point of the boulder and top out.

name: Hunger of the Dog
description: Sit start left the arete on a divot. Climb the arete to an easy top out. No defined crux just sustained sloper arete climbing. If it was double the length it would be classic.

name: Rules of Engagement
description: Start standing with a right-hand crimp and a left-hand gaston on the arete. Move left hand up to a small crimp and drop right hand into the left starting hold. Fire to the apex of the boulder from here and top out on good holds.     None of the holds are terrible, there is just a distinct lack of feet.    There is also a sit start to be added, but it may actually bring the quality of the climb down.

name: Float Like a Butterfly
description: This is the obvious shelf running left to right on the boulder. Start sitting on the rock and make traversing moves up the shelf to a crux-y move at the 3/4 mark. Top out around the right arete on jugs.

name: Left Jab
description: Start with hands at the bend of the bottom crack (see photo). Start feet smeared on the slab. First move is a left hand to the horizontal crack above starting holds. Place a right foot on the tooth of the crack to flag up to the nice crimp to the right. Proper footwork and moving your right hip to the wall will help you undercling to a higher crack and stand up to reach the top with the left hand. After that, it is a simple top-out.

name: Overhand Right
description: Start with the hands hanging on right side of the crevice. Left foot starts on bottom-left jut of crevice. Right foot starts smeared on right slab of crevice. First move is a right hand up to the top of the right crevice. After a left foot placed by the starting handholds, the rest of the route involves traversing the crack to the left and to the top.    Until a proper beta is discovered, the difficulty is moving horizontally along the crack while smearing the feet along the slab because there aren't many options for footholds with the exception of a few notches, if you can call them that.

name: Sting Like a Bee
description: The right arete of the front face from a sit start.    Left hand starts on a good square crimp and right low on the arete, make tension moves up the arete on crimps. Top out on jugs.    Good foot work and core tension are the key for this one.

name: The Sickle
description: First off let me say that if I was awarding stars based strictly on movement this line would get at least 2 full stars, maybe a third. However, due to the friable rock it get bumped down to a single star.    Sit start on a flexing jug and pull up into the face above on crimps and gastons. Work your feet up to make a long move out left to a small intermediate crimp before bumping to a good but flexible crimp, climb lightly on this hold and hit the solid rock at the top out.

name: Asiago
description: The shortest and lowest quality route on the wall, but an obvious line and a decent warm-up. On the right side of the wall locate the good sloper, pull on and climb up incuts in the flake to jugs at the lip.  Beta Video: youtube.com/watch?v=v7MSYBJ…

name: Cider Is Not Beer
description: Start on the crimps at the six-foot mark, pull on and move up to the crimps above before manteling the top out.  This line climbs well but it is personally a bit of a disappointment. When I originally cleaned it, there was a single pad crimp rail that would have made it a good squat start with a hard move into the current starting hold, but it exploded off the wall...  Beta Video: youtube.com/watch?v=eTmgHpp…

name: Devil, Devil
description: Start on two opposing side pulls, the left in the crack and the right on the flake, below the shelves. Pull on and make your way up the good shelves, and into the corer above before topping out on jugs.

name: The Gambler
description: Good movement out the steep overhang that goes at a lower grade than originally anticipated for this steep line,due to good feet throughout the route.    Start on a triangle shape cutout with your right hand and a pyramid shaped hold with your left. Pull on the wall with the aid of a heel hook and grab the 1 inch thick rail(a really cool hold), now make a long move to a good in-cut and bump to a jug, move your feet around and top out.

name: In The Cloud
description: Sit start low on an obvious pocket, pull up to match on a sloper before entering the crux. Execute a unique sequence on crimps and slopers leading to the good edge on the arete, make a few more tension moves to a jug on the right side of the apex of the boulder and press out the top.

name: Vegan Propaganda
description: Start standing on a small shelf with a good left hand undercling and right hand jug. Move up and right to a pair of incut edges, and then left to a good sloper crimp. From here, make a long move up to a good side pull, and slap the lip. There is a decent pinch/sloper on the lip just above the final side pull, and a hidden jug above it.

name: The Dirigible
description: The sloping egg-like arete highball. Not really that high but higher than anything else in the area. couple little mini cruxes up high.

name: The Mooring
description: This can be found left of where the offwidth roof finishes. Start on the far left and follow the rail up to good ledge holds topping out using a sloper and reaching far for a crack.

name: Oh the Humanity
description: No specific crux. A bit pumpy. Pretty unique line.

name: The Slurry
description: Start sitting on the good sloper near the bottom of the arete, Surf up the arete on unique holds and good feet to an easy top out.

name: Spiderwebs
description: Start sitting on two obvious holds in the center of the face. Pull off the ground and hit the pocket to the right, then reach up to jugs and an easy top out.

name: Great Awakening
description: Great line on the left side of pulpit rock. Follows overlaps to the top.

name: Small Worlds
description: Sit start with left hand on the jug flake and right hand on the obvious undercling. Pull up to a slopey hold in the bulge before working your feet around and making a move up to a jug in the crack and top out from there.

name: Bad Boss Man
description: Start as for Working Man Blues and climb through the crux of that route to the jugs at the lip. From here move right through the sloper and up the arete using a big sidepull on the arete and top out easily in the notch.  Beta Video: youtube.com/watch?v=gxJoOW8…

name: Sweatshop
description: Start on the jug in the middle of the face (this is also the starting left hand for "Unionize"). Pull on and traverse the lip left to top out for Wage Slaves.  Beta Video: youtube.com/watch?v=K36UcPX…

name: Unionize
description: Start on the sharp quartz jug with your left and right in a pocket in the seam. Pick some feet, pull out right to a good crimp before tossing your hand up to a jug below the lip. Top out up and too the left.  Good movement, just too short.  Beta Video: youtube.com/watch?v=QDpxRzs…

name: Working Man Blues
description: A cool powerful line.  Start sitting down in the hole on the obvious huge jug rail. Now figure out how to hit the jugs on the lip before topping out with a long move to a good top to hold.  Beta video: youtube.com/watch?v=C6H2CEv…

name: Working Man Dyno
description: Start Matched on the left side of the big jug rail just to the right of the Arete. Gain a very high left heel (at or above hands), and pull straight to the jugs above. Significantly easier than it's neighbor, which utilizes a hold on the face to move up and right.

name: The Lupine
description: Sit start with your hands in pods in the seam. Pick some feet and toss up and right to the lip, top out on jugs. If you have a strong core you could probably keep your feet on, but the hold you are going to is good enough it seemed easier to cut my feet.    I always have a hard time grading dyno's, so please climb it and chime in on what you think!

name: Panini Centre
description: Start in the centre. Top out in the centre.

name: Panini Left
description: Starting on two jugs with your feet under the overhang, move up and right following the angle of the boulder. Tricky feet at the start is the crux.

name: Panini Right
description: Sit starting on the right side of the boulder trending up and left. Nice movement to the topout in the centre.

name: Ancient Highway
description: Sit start on the right side of the right face of the boulder on two crimps, pull up and traverse good incut crimps left towards the roof, traverse the lip of the roof on jugs and top out as for 'Streaked Roof'. There is no defined crux on this route, just many moves.

name: Last of the Wild
description: Stand start on a good side pull and a cool incut pocket right on the arete. Move up to twin crimps, then hit the jug on the lower lip, from the jug top out up and slightly left.    The landing is awkward do to the rounded boulder at the base of the line. However, with pads and spotters it is very safe.

name: The Mystic
description: Start sitting with your left hand on a good side pull and right on a good gaston. Pull up and make crux moves across slopers with help of a few holds out to the right before topping out on jugs.

name: Schism
description: Start sitting as for 'Ancient Highway" but climb straight up using the arete and a good face crimp, balancing your way up to the good hold at the top.

name: The Skeptic
description: Sit start on two opposing sidepulls just right of The Mystic, and reach up to a very small 3 finger crimp. Traverse with sequential feet right into the start of Sunday Funday. Top out as per that problem on fun giant holds.

name: Streaked Roof
description: Sit start on the jugs in the back corner, make a long move with big feet to the good crimps way out left, from here enter the crux. Pick some feet and grab the good crimp in the roof, work your feet around and turn the roof on good holds to massive jugs at the top of the boulder

name: Sunday Funday
description: Fun short route. Varied holds to an easy topout.

name: Brilliant Corners
description: The start is pumpy and bouldery, and can be protected with a #4 Friend. Pull over the small roof onto the slab above. Follow the finger crack in the huge corner until it ends. Step left to another , shorter finger crack (pin)to another roof. Protect, and get ready for the crux. Pull over the roof on the right into another corner (pin), very sequential. Head up and left to a two bolt anchor w/ rap rings.  Note 2020 COMMENT that states: "The flake feature off the ground, specifically the part with the obvious hold from which you place the big cam, is threatening to part ways with the cliff. Ditto for the huge left foot jug under the roof nearby. I would have attempted to trundle, but didn’t have the time."  R Hall NH Admin.

name: Count Down
description: The airy moves on the steep wall towards the top of this climb make it worthwhile.   Start in the alcove just to the right of "Straight, No Chaser."  Take the easiest route up (past a bolt) to a break at 2/3 height.  There are two big precarious blocks just sitting on this break.  Try as best you can not to touch them as you pull onto the final steep face.  Tricky face moves past a 3-4 bolts (crux) lead to the top of the cliff, and a big tree.

name: Fly Away
description: Interesting moves down low bring you past two bolts and up onto a sloping ledge. Move up the sloping ledge and start up great holds on the overhang. High third bolt. Don't pull too hard on the flakes. They are feeling pretty hollow.

name: Rootie Tootie
description: Start just left of Brilliant Corners. Climb up the overhanging crack placing gear to a high first bolt. Comtinue wandering up the face past two more bolts. Move to the left side of the overlap to a tree. Follow the flake up and right to the tree ledge.

name: Straight, No Chaser
description: One of the best 5.8s here.  Up the blunt arete past bolts and a pin to a small ledge.  You can either wimp right to a 5.6 chimney, or place some marginal gear (small alien and/or .75 camelot in a weird position) and keep heading up the arete on nice edges and rails.

name: Big Rock Candy Crack
description: The obvious offwidth. Makes for nice offwidth practice. There is a sling-able chockstone.

name: Limonade Crack
description: Right of the obvious offwidth.    Another obvious crack. Caution advised if bouldering.

name: Sunshine Crack
description: The furthest right crack on the halfway wall.

name: The Champ
description: One of my favorite routes at Sandwich Notch.  The left of the two bolted routes on the steep face.  Short, with a brutal crux (HINT: A secret move guards against an onsight).     Scramble up roots to the base of the route.  Technical footwork gains bigger holds at about mid route.  Tiny crimping and some difficult moves at the last bolt (crux) get you to the top.

name: The Contender
description: The right hand route on this wall, just as good as "The Champ."  Although listed as a sport climb, one may want to bring along either a #4 friend, or a simple shoulder length sling (natural thread) to protect a slight run out beneath the last bolt.     Scramble up roots until you can reach out and clip the first bolt.  Hard face moves (.10a) past 2 bolts lead to bigger holds, and then the final crux moves up and over a bulge (bolt) to the top.

name: JAG
description: I find this route to be a hard on sight, mostly because i didn't (boo hoo), but partly because it's very sequency.  Climb up a large flake on more than vertical rock past a couple bolts to a good hold.  You can shake out a little before tackling the even steeper top half of the climb on some hard to find holds that doesn't let up until you clip the free-hanging chains.  Short but pumpy.  This climb can stay relatively dry in wet weather due to the steepness.

name: Letting Go
description: If more of the climb was like the final moves, this would be a classic.  Climb up less than ideal rock with less than ideal protection (5.7ish) to the beautiful, clean, dihedral protected by two bolts(crux). Do a few tricky moves, and pull over the lip to the top of the cliff, and the usual good tree.

name: Old Boys
description: The route starts with an easy left-to-right ramp to a second bolt.  (The route is joined here by the direct start variation, Old Boys Club, 5.11a)).  Head straight up from here toward an overhang at the top through an easy, blocky section (5.6), and watch for loose and hollow flakes.  Traverse left under the overhang, and then, to surmount it, head back right.  The overhang gives the climb its 5.10 rating.

name: Old Boys Club
description: It's hard to believe that the dramatic overhang at the top of this route goes at 5.10c...but it does (you will have to work for it though).   There are two ways to do this.  You can start to the left (and avoid the 5.11a roof), which is the route "Old Boys" and goes at .10c.  OR you can do the "Old Boys Club" direct start (a one or two move 11a), which I feel is a cleaner line with better rock and moves. To do it, make some moderate moves up to the roof (a good hold), and the first bolt.  One or two .11a moves gets you past another bolt and onto 5.8ish climbing....but it ain't over.  climbing past a few spaced bolts up to the spectacular roof.  Pull through the roof on buckets and horizontals (.10c) and grunt onto the top of the cliff.  Take a deep breadth and a look at your scraped up forearms...wasn't that fun!!

name: Pretty Crack
description: Harder than it looks.  Climb the splitter finger crack up the center of the slab with increasing difficulty to the crux mantel move.  Continue more easily to big pine tree.

name: Quartz Crescendo
description: The dirty quartz dike found about stones throw right of the end of the highlander wall proper.

name: The Quickening
description: The poster girl climb on the wall.  The center most route, up the belly of Highlander Wall.  Scramble up easy, lower angled rock, to the first bolt. Climb up the steep corner (crux) gunning for the obvious break in the center of the cliff.  A rest can be gained here before tackling the upper half of the improbable-looking wall.  Climb up the overhanging wall directly above, finding hidden dishes and edges as you go.  If you're lucky, you will gain the lip of the top of the cliff.  Hand traverse right to a two bolt and chain anchor.

name: Sleeve of Wizard
description: Stiff moves out the overhang to the steep face above. Difficult clip at the lip.

name: Snafu
description: The left arete of the sunny buttress a stones throw from the end of the highlander wall proper. Starts right and moves up and left past two bolts and onto the left arete. Tough moves past the third bolt. A direct start is a good bit tougher.

name: Split Image
description: This is the obvious dihedral left of the Quickening. Climb up to a high first bolt, then tech (where did all the hold go??) past two more bolts in the dihedral (crux) before a final sting in the tail at the last bolt. Chain anchor. -Eric8

name: Hunger of the Pines
description: Work a couple balancy moves to gain a layback. Up the rail to the right angled flake. Follow the flake right to its end and head straight up, stemming, to join the crack near the top.

name: Left Diagnaling Hand Crack
description: The line that stands out the most at this area.  Good protection after the first 15', which is tricky climbing (thus the pg13 rating).  Carefully climb up to the start of the crack, then jam and layback to its end.  Crux is near the top.

name: Welcome to Slug City
description: Start of the ground at the base of the obvious left slanting crack. Instead of following the crack break right up the obvious shallow groove. Climb up cool jugs until about half height where you encounter the crux, then continue on interesting jugs. Top out and anchor off one of the live trees at the top.    The name I have used is just given by me because of all the slugs on the bottom half the day I climbed it. I do not know the real name and cannot find any information on it. If you have the info please let me know and I will happily correct it.

name: Death Wish in Paradise
description: From the tree, head up the left-leaning flaring crack until it runs out. Continue up the slabs to large pine tree that you can sling and belay from. Scramble to the top.   Super fun and exciting climbing on this route! Lichen isn't a problem, and the rock is mostly solid. After the initial steep slab, the grade mellows out pretty well and turns into about 5.6(+/-) friction climbing. The gear is not good after the crack, and placements are scarce. Be sure to bring your lead head, this route is a rewarding climb with a stunning view at the belay.

name: Stroll in Paradise
description: Head up sweet flakes on an unprotectable slab for 35' towards a nice corner. Place gear and keep heading up the slabs to the top. The climbing is fun and the rock is pretty solid, with some crumbly but not worrisome rock after the corner. Lichen is not a problem, and the climbing is fun! This route is a great intro to the area.

name: M.L.K. Jr. Memorial Route
description: The only dike on right side from the ground up or from a traverse half way up first pitch there is a ledge from the forest that almost reaches the dike. I climbed in this way avoiding the dike's lower section. It was almost to much friction to the dike (5-6). Follow dike up (5-4) until able to traverse left onto tree ledge. Above center of tree ledge climb excellent face move on bulges heading right to access hand crack (crux). Climb hand crack until it becomes a crack filled with brush hair organic matter, moss? Jams are still excellent regardless of the organic brush stuff adhered to the crack. Brush stuff made excellent foot holds very tough. Exit by holding onto pine boughs. Bushwhack very short distance to summit. Great climb and a great view but a lot of traffic by climbers would probably disturb this organic brush stuff ecology. I don't expect any traffic. Check on whether this is in the wilderness forest protection regulations or not before you do any nailing and power bolting.There used to be on the summit of Mt. Whiteface a memorial plaque to Martin Luther King mounted onto a boulder. Someone crowbarred the plaque off of the boulder in 1982. I named the route to reenforce M.L.K. Jr.'s chosen right to be here.

name: Flagrant Foul
description: Start sitting under the small overhang with another boulder behind you. Right and left hands on big jugs. Big move to hit the lip. Work up to the small crack up over the lip and top out. Sharp!!

name: The Jeff Smith Line
description: Sit start on the bad slopey rail and a sharp undercling on the left most side of the Slab Boulder. Move up and left to some left facing crimps and a left facing jug. I didn't use the arete proper but I don't think it would change the grade.

name: Slab Yourself
description: Fun slab route. Someone probably did it eons ago. I neglected to brush the slab much.

name: Jeff Smith's Traverse
description: Sit start with both hands down low on the slope rail. Traverse right onto the good pinch and finish by doing The Karate Kid.

name: Jeff’s Arete
description: Awkward sit. Sort of hidden rh start hold and a lh crimp.  Climb straight up.

name: The Karate Kid
description: Stand start with left hand on the great pinch used for "Who is Jeff Smith" and right hand up on the slopper rail. Work the slopper rail to the right to gain the biggest jug and bring up a high foot to pull a difficult mantel.

name: Who is Jeff Smith?
description: Stand start with your left hand on a good jug/side-pull and right hand on the side-pull rail. Head straight up the boulder using a great right hand pinch to some sloppers. Mantel the lip to an easy top-out.

name: Mosquito Bait
description: Crux is the start. Start with a left hand two finger undercling and right hand on a "ball/pinch" feature. Move up to the horizontal crack then continue up and left on easy ground.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start matched on the lip. Throw a heel and work the holds left to the top out for Overbite.

name: Amanita
description: Start as for Evil Beaver and link that into Mushroom Cap Crack. This is definitely a long pumpy route.

name: Ancient Futures
description: This route is named after the book Ancient Futures. The book discusses how globalization affects culture change throughout the world with emphasis on maintaining an ecological balance between humans and the environment.  Sit start on two crimps and make your way up to a gaston. From there, use a variety of holds to top out. There are multiple betas to gain the gaston. Either use an undercling, or use very sharp crimps. Your choice.

name: Angry Beaver
description: Start the same as "Overbite". Instead of trending up the arete, stay left and work the crimps on the face to the slopey topout.

name: Beaver Crack
description: Start at the base of the right arching crack on the backside of the boulder with "Bosquitos". There is a low start but I started standing and worked the crack to the top. See beta photo for start hold I used.

name: Bosquitos
description: Sit start with hands over head. Heel hook and move straight up to top out.

name: Chicken of the Woods
description: Start matched on the big undercling. Head up and left to the good crimp rail over the block. Up and over the small bulge on crimps. Forget about the landing and finish the crux mantle to the top.

name: Cutting your Teeth
description: Begin with sharp underclings, trend left to a decent if sharp hold.  Now work your way right, find the crimps and top out.

name: Dose
description: Climb the slab behind "Overdose". Easier moves lead to more excitement at the top! Stay to the right of the little tree growing in the center of the face. Avoid using the arete out right to bail. The climb goes straight up to the top.

name: Easy Beaver
description: Start on the lowest jug and head up the Arete on good holds. Serves as a good down climb or to get on the boulder to check out the top.

name: Evil Beaver
description: Would be better if the chockstone at the lip wasn’t there. I guess it also makes the route a bit spicier. Start sitting under the overhang left hand on the sloping feature and right hand on a crimp. Move up on great holds until you can reach the chockstone and pull the lip. Top is still a bit dirty.

name: Indian Pipes
description: Start just to the right of a small tree growing from the boulder. Follow the low angle face and crack to the top. Crux moves are low. Big holds up top makes this a secure climb. Tree is off.

name: Mushroom Cap Crack
description: Start standing on two flake jugs. Move up and right into the finger crack.  Follow the crack for a few moves until you can pull the lip.

name: Nice Beaver
description: Start sitting matched on a good jug under the overhang. Move up and left toping out as you would for Mushroom Cap Crack. Beware one flake is fragile, use the top right section or it might blow off.

name: Overbite
description: Sit start on the sloping rail filled with skin ripping quartz crystals, move up to a good jug and swing around to mantle up and top out. Stay true to the overhung arete for the true route.

name: Overdose
description: Start low in the wide crack. Good big jugs help you top out. Perhaps it could be protected with gear.

name: Porcupine Crack
description: Start as you would for Beaver Crack but head straight up the left crack instead of going right. Mossy and leafy up top. Highball.

name: Span the Gap
description: Sort of a stand start with Left hand up high on the top of the large flake between the two aretes. Right hand on the undercling/jug. Figure out the moves to span the large gap into "Evil Beaver (EB)". Finish as for "EB"

name: Upsurge
description: Sit start with right hand in the "hole" and left hand pinching the flake between the two aretes. Work your way straight up, between those same two aretes. Topout to the right of that tree. I just down climbed and jumped to the pad instead of going all the way up.

name: Warm Up Crack
description: Start on the left trending crack and top out is the same as for Easy Beaver. This serves as the best downclimb off of the second boulder.

name: The Worcester Mill
description: Start sitting on the boulder just below the arete. Match on the blocky jug and then move to a gaston right. Head straight up to the ledges. Top out by the sapling. Great holds, overhanging with a spicy topout!

name: Salty Mantle
description: Sit start as for the lip traverse. Head straight up and make a tough mantle move.

name: Salty traverse
description: Sit start at left side of lip. Traverse right to peak and topout around the corner a bit.

name: Dag
description: Start the same as "Norb", except instead of going straight up, traverse the lip to the right and then head up the arete. Easiest to stay left while topping out the arete.

name: Norb
description: Sit start with both hands matched on the large jug rail. Fire up left hand to a  good side-pull and top-out straight up and over the bulge.

name: One Move Wonder
description: To the right of the arete is a very short face climb. Looked easier then it was, which is why I am adding it. It is truly a one move wonder, if you can manage to get established at all.   Start with right hand on a small side-pull crimp and left hand where ever you want, step up to get onto the awkward start stance. Once you are established, make a dead-point move to a good jug towards the top of the arete. It takes a good bit of core tension to hold the jug. This actually ended up being a lot more fun that I thought too.

name: Barrel Roll
description: Start to the right of Slab Direct.  Step up to grab a small quartz crystal with your right hand.  Move upwards with some tricky footwork to the top.

name: Side Step
description: Start to the right of Slab Direct (same start as Barrel Roll).  Step up and grab a sharp quartz crystal with your right hand.  Then work your way left on smears and top out.

name: Slab Direct
description: The starting hold is the obvious frown line on the central part of the slab.  After an awkward mantle, balance your way up smears and small edges before trending right at the top.

name: Ascension
description: Sit start as for "Final Fantasy" but after the first few moves continue up and right to a big shelf, then finish direct and pull on to the slab to top out.

name: Final Fantasy
description: An awesome problem with big fun moves and good holds. Sit start with the left hand on a finger jug or a side pull ear slightly lower. Right hand on a left facing jug. Pull on and reach over with the left hand to a jug, then reach right hand to another good hold. From here climb up then make a big move left to an edge. Bring the right hand over and prep yourself for a big dead point move to a small crimp, or a big hold 6 inches higher. From here pull up and grab the arete and stand up on to the slab to top out.

name: Island in the Sun
description: This line traverses The Island Boulder from the start of "Final Fantasy" all the way left to top out the left arete. There are a lot of holds on this boulder making it a great warm up spot, and it is also 2 minutes from parking. Sit start and choose your choice of edges and crimps to make your way leftward to the other side of the boulder. Head up to a giant sloper shelf on the left arete or use good crimps instead to top out.    This boulder is almost like a gym wall. There are so many options, so I figured I'd add a few variations that have been done. This is definitely the spot to go before heading across the bridge/ spillway.

name: Lord of the Flies
description: Sit start at a high right hand crimp and a decent left hand hold. There are different options for foothold, although pulling off the ground is hard and committing. Reach up to a good edge and move left to more edges and then launch up to a big sloper shelf or a crimp rail slightly lower. Continue climbing up and right avoiding the tree and then top out.

name: Lord Of The Flies Direct
description: The tallest line on this bloc that heads straight up the overhang.     Start the same as for Lord Of The Flies, and makes the same first couple moves, but instead of making a big move out left this heads up to the left side of the ledge with the little tree. From here it continues straight up the face using another great edge and tops out at the very peak of the overhang.

name: The Most Dangerous Game
description: An eliminate/ variation linking "Final Fantasy" into "Lord of the Flies". Sit start as for "Final Fantasy" and make a long reach out left to a good horizontal edge that can also be used as a sidepull. The feet are good and you have to rock over the left toe and lunge for it while staying close to the wall. I hit the edge with two fingers. After snagging the good hold, hold the tension and move your feet in order to match. From here move up to two good crimps. Set the feet and make a jump move to a good shelf protruding from the face. This shelf has a small tree growing on it. From the shelf match and head direct on good holds to a fun topout. It gets kind of high off the deck, but the landing is decent, especially by Clough standards.    A very fun variation to do while warming up on this great boulder.

name: Boom Sauce
description: Stand stand on a jug located on the arete. Pull on and make moves up on good holds. Keep climbing up on good holds until you come to a scary topout! (Could use some cleaning!)

name: Changing Tides
description: A sloper power problem.    Sit start with a left hand undercling, a right hand sloper with a decent crimp seam in it, a left heel toe cam underneath the boulder and the pedestal. Wedge it in there good and use your right foot to press and gain opposition. From here pull off the ground with difficulty and reach up high left hand to a bad and sharp sloper. Latch it and grab the small thumb catch.    Take the toe cam out and get your right foot good, then with the left foot get a toe hook/ scum out left. From here pull in tight and grab another sloper with the right hand.    Release the toe scum and use a small edge for the left toe and dyno right hand to a poor hold.    From here match with difficulty and move the right hand right to edges and better holds.     Top out with ease and enjoy the flat boulder summit and the view of Clough!    There's the spray down, now you just have to get up to it and send it...   youtu.be/ma9DTF9yGxM

name: The Devil's Steps
