description: The finest of Clough thus far. This Mega classic lies above the large cave near Mammoth Rock.    Sit start way down inside the lair. There is a large flake right of a boulder inside the cave. Match hands and right heel hook. Pull on and make a few cool moves rightwards on good holds and slopers. Reach a good sidepull on the giant shelf and grab the next shelf. Match and make some hard moves pulling around the bulge using a crystal sloper pinch and a left hand undercling.    Snatch the lip and top out rightwards.  youtube.com/watch?v=8HTzi1u…

name: It Came From Beneath The Sink
description: A very cool looking over hang problem that is worth seeking out. Start matched down low on good incuts and move right toward more good holds. Make a big committing move toward a right hand side pull. Snag this and really crank down on it and move left hand to the seam on the lip. Continue right to good but perhaps dirty holds in the seams of the crack and top it out.    Avoiding the block down low for feet is really how I wanted to climb this originally but its very hard to ignore, so I used it for feet making this climb much easier than I expected...

name: Natural Flow
description: An extremely unique climb that traverses a large horizontal split in the boulder. Sit start in the crack out right and traverse it left on  good holds. Go around the corner and start climbing the overhang via good crimps and possibly a kneebar. Continue the leftward movement and press/ stem into the angle change and stay close to the wall. Make more moves in this position until you can reach up right hand to a hold below the lip. Stand up and match. Make a hard topout high off the deck over a not so great landing.    Jake and I were working this line trying to top out direct above the overhang, but the natural flow of the traverse sends you into the horizontal stemming sequence. The Line going up from the overhang seems like it will go, and will involves some hard compression moves off of a good undercling and the arete/ lip.    This line needs a lot of cleaning still, but it is definitely really unique and a fun problem. There is also some great potential for a hard slab climb going up from the start of this line.

name: The Root of Ethics
description: Sit start on a group of rad crimps. Pull on and bust a few technical moves up to a few slopey crimps and a few sharp ones. A few more moves gain a small left-hand hold and a cruxy move up right hand to a sidepull. Keep the tension and continue up to a sloper pinch on the lip. Bust out to a better hold and get on top!  This problem is one of the most technical and most difficult problems in the park. It climbs up a perfect 40-degree overhang and has a sick set of crimp moves that can rarely be set in the gym!

name: Satan's Alley
description: Start on right side of the face on two flakes. One of them is sideways. One foot on a rail the other pushing on a good foot out right. Make a move left to a sharp sideways flake and match.     Then go up to two more crimps, Use some foot work and get situated for a move to a sloping rail and then the crux going to a sharp crimp jug, which is better if you can get your fingers behind it and full crimp it.    From here get your feet up and make a few more moves to the top using crimps and slopers on the lip. You can only go one way on the top out, a hole where the boulder covering the caves ends, throw a left heel on a good rail and mantle up.

name: Sleigh Ride
description: Sit or squat start with a sweet left-hand blocky pinch and a right-hand press on a large low flat shelf. Pull on and dyno up the shelf. Match hands before busting out right to the arete and figuring out how to reach up to the lip. Fun moves on unique holds. A bit contrived, after matching the shelf, because the jug shelf continues out left to an easy topout.

name: Audacity
description: Sit start under the arete with a good sidepull and a good hold on the lip. Pull on and set a heelhook and traverse the sloping lip leftwards around the corner over a slanting landing. Once around the corner utilize some interesting meathooks and keep traversing till you reach buckets and can top out. A fun and pumpy traverse.

name: Frog Legs
description: Start on left side pull just below the left arête and right pinch or any crimp in the seam, find feet and work up the arête to the jug at the top.

name: Honky Tonking
description: Sit start on a good left side pull and small right crimp. Pull off the ground and then work up on good holds.

name: Paro
description: Middle problem on the 'Master of None' boulder. Sit start on a left sidepull and right on the big flat ledgey hold. Get feet and pull up to good holds. Up to the top.

name: Perry's Problem
description: A tricky problem with smooth slopers. Although short, it packs quite a few moves. The arete is smooth granite, which is friendly on your hands and atypical for Clough.    Start sitting with your hands below the lip in a pocket and on a sloper sidepull or hold right of the pocket. Figure out your feet and pull up. Traverse the slopey lip (it is bad!) until you can get to the left arete and throw to the peak of the boulder, or use some serious beta trickery (toehooks, heelhooks, leg-bars, and more toehooks) to get to the top.   youtube.com/watch?v=wxi4wOc…

name: The Sickening
description: Start on the arête with a left on a great jug and right on a good side pull. Get feet, move up and rock up onto the great ledgey foot and then go to the top. Short but fun.

name: Bulbasaur
description: This is a short powerful overhanging arete found on a nice looking boulder.   Sit-start crossed with both hands on the textured arete. Start with the right hand on a sidepull pinch, and the left hand about 8 inches lower on another pinch that feels pretty poor and friction dependent. Choose the footholds wisely and power up to the lip while keeping the legs engaged. Smack and latch the left-hand sloper before pulling up to improving holds for the right hand. Hit a bucket then figure out how to top out.  Short, powerful, core intensive, aesthetic and quite pure. The 3rd ascent is still up for grabs!

name: The Clementine Incident
description: Sit start the face of the roof with a good left hand edge and a hand-heel match out right in the horizontal slot. A less flexibility dependent right hand start hold is found slightly closer, this hold is a small poor crimp. Once oriented, pull on to the wall of the boulder and move up to a textured crimp, from here find a foot and smack out to the sloping arete before executing a powerful bump or right hand toss for the lip of the boulder. Top out on positive textured slopers.

name: Hypnotic Ditch-Hiker
description: Good rock quality, obvious starting rail,  and powerful moves to textured slopers on a rad suspended arete.  Sit or squat-start matched on a smooth flat rail under the boulder. Find some feet and pull on before tossing up to a good sloper. Figure out how to match and continue up on slopers and press it out to gain the top of the boulder.

name: Shiny Bulbasaur
description: This problem is a left exit to "Bulbasaur". It adds several challenging moves on slopers into the classic one-mover "Bulbasaur".  Sit-start with your hands crossed on the laser-cut overhanging arete. Find the body tension and smack up to the lip of the overhang. From here match and bust out left on some great Clough slopers! After a few moves, figure out some foot beta and press it out for the full value battle with not just Bulbasaur, but a special one, a Shiny one.

name: Red Hot Chilly Slopers
description: Sit-start the far left side of the lip. Make a few scrunchy moves at the beginning in order to reach the stand start jug and continue traversing right along the sloping lip of the boulder. A tricky end sequence revolving around a few crystals leads to a brick hard mantle/ lock-off to a pocket found on the slab.

name: Down With the Sickness
description: I don't give a lot of problems the bomb for star ratings, but this one brought me pretty close! This climb is actually surprisingly fun once you suck it up about the landing and dabbiness. If you are six feet tall, good luck on this one.  Sit start under the short roof on the right side of the boulder. a slider pad would most likely be best here. Reach over the lip with the right hand and find a right hand meathook seam. The left hand goes down low along the lip of the roof on an imaginary crystal pinch. Throw the left foot right under your left hand on the only obvious foothold. Once here, you are ready to pull hard in order to establish onto the wall.  Pull on and smack up to some textured slopers then bump up again before coming in righty. A tricky friction dependent shouldery sequence and a campus foot swap on the sloping foothold eventually leads to an ez-pz outtro and topout.  Fun to play on while the crew rages the rest of the boulder.

name: Enduring Duration
description: Sit-start with the left hand on the arete-like feature and right hand on the undercling out right. Pull on and move up the arete and a few sloping edges before encountering some barndoor tension and a smack for jugs at the lip.

name: New Disease
description: Sit start with a high right hand sloping edge and the left hand with a small sloping sidepull. Find a foot and do a big lock-off/ deadpoint to the sloping rail in the middle of the wall. match for a second then pop up to the jug at the lip.  Miles Galloway did a lower start matched on the undercling between these two starting holds, but quality and difficulty was not exactly added.

name: Smack at You With the Illness
description: A brick hard powerful one-move wonder.  Stand start with a large left-hand undercling and a sloping right hand undercling pinch 2 feet to the right. Pull on with difficulty and find a high foot before smacking up for the full span move to the right arete of the boulder. Latch it with difficulty then bring the feet up and match before topping out in easy terrain.  This problem was once the natural line on the right side of the block, but after the removal of some exfoliating flakes, a new hold appeared in the middle of the face before the arete. It is unsure if this hold would help for this problem or not, but the hold is considered "off" if you are trying to repeat the original powerful bicep test-piece.

name: Disclosure
description: Sit start with both hands on the arete. Start with the right hand on a low pocket-like hold, and the left hand slightly higher on a textured seam-pinch. Pull-on and make a few burly and shouldery moves out left on good feet before resorted to a series of strenuous right heelhooking while on some bad slopers. Smack out to a crystal hold and make a big lock-off for a mega bucket way up high and press it out. This climb tops out on the large bulging feature protruding from the lip of the block.

name: End of the Line
description: Sit start at the bottom of the arete with a low left foot and hands on arete. Continue left on smooth rock with great handholds, and heelhook/smear for feet. Grab the left sidepull, work your hands up to the shark tooth, and mantle over.    If you want, you could go up the 5.4 slab to the top of mammoth rock.

name: The Mammoth Dyno Project
description: Stand start with the left hand on a small crystal sidepull at about head height, and a good right hand undercling sidepull at waist height. Or use two undercling. Pull on with good feet and make a toss for the slopey lip. Get both hands up there and throw up a heel or toe and mantel it.

name: Remedy Project
description: The hardest line on the tall face of Mammoth Rock. This line starts in the middle of the wall. Left of "State of Fear" and right of "Timeline". Pull onto the great rock using small incut crimps, and make hard moves to blind holds in the smooth granite flake systems on the wall. This line is a direct and topout at the apex of the boulder about 25 feet off the deck. An early exit may be possible.

name: State of Fear
description: A stellar line on an amazing boulder! Start matched on the good incut flake and work your way into a good right hand undercling. Use your biceps and pull up into a left hand sloper sidepull. Shift your body weight around and lunge up to a thin seam. Get it good and make a desperate move up and left to a good hold. Keep it together and work your way toward the arete on good holds. Swing around the corner and celebrate.

name: State of Fear Sit
description: Sit or squat start on two sloping crimps and make a couple of hard, slightly shouldery moves out right to some incut crimps. From here a few more burly and fingery moves gets you into the stand start. From the incut jug move up into the undercling then continue up to a sloper crystal and a pair of gastons before a committing last move and fun top out. Awesome movement on some good rock!

name: Time Turner
description: Sit start on two opposing undercling sidepulls. Pull on with some smears and move up to a good sidepull out left from here crossover and continue climbing up and slightly left while holding a vast amount of tension another big move or two will get you to the juggy arete, and then a balancy rockover onto the slab finishes the problem.   This problem has some great movement on unique rock and some great incut holds.

name: Timeline
description: Whats not to like about this route. Awesome holds, cool movement and a juggy topout. Sit start on a good sidepull about 5 feet right of the tree and work your way up on good flakes. Getting your body position right and finding where the good holds are is key to sending this climb.    A great line on an amazing boulder.

name: Premeditated escape
description: This little problem shares the same start as 2 little piggies but it climbs to the left instead of right. You can ride the lip all the way to the same top out as piggies or mantle directly. The movement feels classic but the landing isn’t perfect, there are a couple small boulders and then a 6 foot drop where your spotter can stand to prevent you from rolling down if you blow the big move to the lip.

name: Two little piggies go to Clough
description: Sit start matched on an obvious incut rail on the face with a massive foot hold. Make a few easier moves trending up and right then it’s a crux big move to a right hand jug side pull. Once you stick this, stay tight and find a crystal intermediate before powering up lefty to the slopey lip. Ride the lip for a few moves and top out!

name: Undercover Brother
description: Start under the roof with a good incut pizza slice/ tongue feature. Left hand on the rail just below it. Pull on a bit awkwardly using the large pedestal for feet, then make a few core intensive move up before leaping off the pedestal and taking a gnarly swing on a pair of slopers. Get it together and figure out how to top out.  A sit-start on the pedestal adds a few funky and delicious moves into the established line.

name: Strikes Again
description: Sit start with the right hand on a low sidepull and the left hand on a sloper on the arete. Pull on and fire for the jug horn up and right or figure out some tricky foot beta like Jake Perry typically does.

name: Vital Slab
description: A classic slab with no holds and poor feet with a committing last move.

name: Vitality
description: Sit start with opposing sidepulls and make a big move left hand to a sloper. Move your feet and toe hook out left to setup for another throw to a right hand sloper. From here bump the right hand to a crimp and make a hard move up to a good horn above the lip. Get a high foot and rock up to a knob or a jug slightly further away. Great movement.

name: 2 Minutes To Midnight
description: This short little climb has more moves and is trickier than one would think. It was completely dark when it was done, hence the name from the Iron Maiden song.     Start matched in the crack, with some ok feet. Traverse to the left until you can find something good enough to top out on.     I'll get some pictures and update the description tomorrow, it's been a while since I've done it.

name: The Ax Palace
description: If you like crimpers, compression and hard snags, this one may be for you.  This problem is squeezed in between "Wolves Of Chernobyl" and "Tommy's Problem". Start low on two opposing sidepull crimps. Pull on and make a desperate right-hand latch to a sharp crimp sidepull. Stand up and throw out to a bad left-hand sidepull, then make another move or two before reaching the lip and topping out.  The grade is unconfirmed, but it is V-hard.

name: Bladerunner
description: This problem is a crimpy traverse which then leads to a good top out. It also has one of the few decent landings that Clough has to offer.     There is a project that starts way inside the tunnel and then it connects to the top out of this problem. Known as the Wormhole Project.

name: The Can Opener
description: A short problem that can be done as an arete, or one big deadpoint/dyno.     Start with left hand on a knob on the left arete, and right on the right arete down low. Find some feet and maybe a heel hook and either fire for the slot (way cooler) or bump your way up the arete until you can match and finish at the top.

name: Crystal Blight
description: Sit Sart with the left hand on a sidepull of crystals, and the right hand in a pocket formation in the crystals. pull off the ground and use small cystal crimps or make a big move up high to a rail, then a good crystal edge out left. Pull over with some slopers.

name: Darkness Awakens
description: This is a direct version of "Darkness Falls", which offers some excellent movement and could very well be the more natural line. Sit-start with a left hand gaston and a higher right hand on an incut crimp sidepull. Pull-on and move up lefty to ta slopey hold in the diagnol seam. From here pull out to a sidepull/ undercling pinch out right before standing tall to a sloping rail for the left hand. Once here, latch the arete and continue straight up.

name: Darkness Falls
description: This problem has evolved slightly over the years and the original stand start line that Troy did years ago no longer makes sense.  Sit-start under the twin crack/seam features with a high right hand incut crimp and a left hand gaston just below. Pull on and power out left to a positive pocket-like hold before making several more difficult moves up the features in order to gain the lip of the boulder before topping out.

name: The Darkside Project
description: The full line is going to be a sit start, but doing the stand start comes first. Grab a small undercling crimp flake system and find a foot to oppose off of. Pull off the ground with difficulty and deadpoint to a large sharp hold out left. Keep the tension, and fire up right hand to an awkward jug. Throw the feet back on the wall and grab the jugs and topout. Sit start looks to be around v10-11.

name: The Golden Boots
description: Sit start matched on the right arete with a hand on the giant foot platform and a hand on the arete. Get a high heel next to your hand and make a desperate move up right hand to a decent sloper on the arete. From here continue up the arete to the lip before topping out. FA was in the good'ole work boots.

name: The Golden Nikes
description: A fun traverse arete that can be done in even really broken and old sneakers (like mine).     Sit or stand start on the arete, get your feet up onto the obvious giant foothold out right, and then traverse all the way up the arete, using toehooks if you want. Traverse the lip out left a few more moves after the arete ends so you can get to a spot for an easier top out.

name: Guilded Fleece
description: Smooth friendly rock makes this climb one of the best in the park. Sit start with a couple sloper sidepulls and follow the dike like features up to the sloper arete. rock over on to the slab or follow the arete up and right.

name: Hot Rod
description: A fun arete with that can be climbed with a bunch of little move or a couple bigger moves.     Sit start down on the arete and head up to a better holds higher up on the arete, eventually hitting the lip of the boulder out right. Top it out, and jump down or down climb. Now do it again in one big jump like Rod Kimble.

name: Prometheus
description: Stand start with a good left hand hold at about five and a half feet and a pinch for the right hand slightly higher and to the right. Pull on and make a move out left to a good hold. Fire out right to a sidepull and then reach out to holds at the lip.    There is a sit start project that could be pretty difficult.

name: Prometheus Sit
description: Sit start at the base of the large vertical/ diagonal rail features. Find some feet and make a few desperate moves to gain improving holds on the vertical rails. Continue up the rails to top out on large holds.

name: Tommy's Problem
description: Stand start about five feet left of the arete on a pair of small sharp crimps about 5 feet off the ground. Pull on and bust a hard move up to a small crimp rail before gathering your mustard and dunking the lip. There are a few intermediate gastons if you can't dunk like Lebron. once on the lip, match hands and throw it behind you! Good eye Tommy!

name: Tooth Fairy
description: An eliminate that's pretty fun and a decent warm-up for your fingers. Start with left hand on a waaay low left flake and right hand up higher on a good edge (this same edge is used in Blade Runner). Find your feet and then bump your left hand to this crazy shark-tooth hold, don't try to crimp directly on the tooth or you'll cut yourself open, instead push against the back of the tooth and get a weird thumb pinch. Bump again to a good crimp right below the arete and then throw to the lip. The arete isn't used in the FA, but honestly it's not needed either as the high left crimp is really good and closer to you, it'd be a pretty big reach to use the arete.

name: Top Gun
description: A super fun warm up with some neat moves. Starts on the right side of the Darkness Falls boulder.     Start sitting on a strange feature sticking out of the wall. Compress your way up it, find a way to stand up and get the hidden sidepull, then work your way to the top. Top it out and do it again.

name: Wolves of Chernobyl
description: Stand start matched on an undercling sidepull right at about waist height. Pull off the ground with a good right foot and a good left foot. Reel in the undercling with your right bicep and stand tall to a crimper. From here reel in the undercling a bit more and bump to a far two finger gaston. Walk your feet and figure out how to get your right hand up to a small shelf. Once here, gather up all your mustard and blue cheese and go for the bucket at the lip!    Hard and great movement!

name: Frog and Toad
description: Squat Start with a left-hand crimp sidepull flake and a textured sloper for the right hand. Find a foot and make a hard lock-off up to a slopey horizontal just right of the bird's nest. From here figure out where to get your feet and your other hand before moving out left to a jug slot. From here reach up to encounter the slopey lip. Move left to improving holds or move back right.

name: High Noon Thresh
description: Squat start to the left of the large tree with a pair of textured slopers. Pull onto the wall and move up right hand to a nice positive slot in the horizontal. From here a tricky sequence gains a bad left-hand undercling which then leads to a powerful smack for the lip.

name: The Little Tree Frog Who Could
description: Stand start with a left hand sidepull undercling and a right hand gaston/ undercling pinch feature above your head. Pull into the shallow scoop and fall into a left hand rail before popping for the lip. A few moves right lead to buckets for a topout. A bit funky and a bit of a puzzle, but fun!

name: Millennium Traverse
description: Sit-start matched on the lip on the far left side of the boulder. Pull-on with some funky foot smears and head out right traversing the lip of the boulder. The handholds and footholds improve around the center of the boulder and then the jugs run out and are replaced with a series of bad slopers.  Continue the traverse on the slopers until you end up just left of a large tree. Throw up a high foot and lunge with the left hand for a large sidepull feature found on top of the boulder, from here roll over the lip to complete the long climb.

name: Tiny the Stone Giant
description: Sit-start with both hands in a low horizontal slot found in the middle of the boulder. Underneath the nose feature of the boulder. Pull-on with some good feet and move out left to a tricky hold before smacking with the right hand to a nice positive flat jug. From here make a long reach to the lip and top out on positive holds.

name: Unaccountable Bosh
description: Sit start matched on the low horizontal. Right hand is a decent slopey sidepull, lefthand is just left on a bad slimper. Smear some feet and make a hard lock-off up to a tres petite crystal before moving the feet and making a desperate lurp for a jug sidepull found near the top of the arete. Topout in easier terrain.

name: Man, Man-Cub
description: Stand start at the left side of the wall. Step up the slab below and start crossed with left hand on a sidepull and a right hand slightly lower. Pull onto the wall using a large foot and make a powerful move up to a large hold. Continue up and left then reach far back right to a large horn before topping out over the flat lip.

name: Tiger Stripes
description: Sit start on a small two finger edge for the right hand and a high jug left hand gaston. Pull on with some obvious footholds and power up into the awkward incut undercling. From here figure out how to reach up lefty to a jug and before following large rail features and finishing fairly high above a blocky slanted landing.

name: Dead south arete
description: Sit start with a right hand pinch on the arete and left on a decent crimp. Pull on and you’re immediately into the Crux, after a right hand bump on the arete make a pretty big floating move out and left to a jug, a few more easy moves and you’ll be topping her out.

name: Dead-birch slab
description: Stand start compressing the slab with a good left hand undercling and right hand side pull. Some trickery and balance a little higher off the deck makes this line a classic one in my eyes but the landing might deter some.

name: Quantum Mechanics
description: Sit start on two opposing sloper features. The right-hand hold is slightly better than the left. Pull onto the wall with some obscure feet and power up to the jug at the lip or figure out how to use some very small and sharp intermediates before a desperate bump to the same jug. Once on the jug figure out how to top out with ease.

name: The big Finnish
description: An amazing right to left arete climb on an aesthetically pleasing block. Stand start with right hand on the arete and left hand on the face on anything you’d like. Make some easy moves to get established, then make a couple tension moves along the finn before an exciting finish to a flat jug. Top out and enjoy the view! Really good landing but it feels larger than it is, highly recommend trying this if you’re in the area!

name: Finn-land bulge
description: Sit start with right hand on the arete and left hand on a crystal sidepull with a crucial thumb catch. Pull on and make a hard bump up the arete with your right hand to a patch of crystals. Pray you don’t dry fire and find some feet in order to surf out left to a good sidepull, crux is over but there’s still a little bit of balance to top it out!

name: Left Finn
description: A great left to right arete climb. Sit start with left hand on the arete and right hand on the face. Pull up and move out right to a seam on the face that allows you to compress the arete. Make a couple hard bumps up the arete and then some fancy footwork and tension will take you to a large crack jug. Rest up for a hot second and figure out your next path up the arete into the same finish as “the big Finnish”. Really good one!

name: Ivysaur
description: Sit start the aesthetic clean arete with a fat right-hand pinch on the arete and a super low left-hand undercling found on the face of the overhang. Find some feet and the body positioning and pull onto the wall before firing for an incut left-hand sidepull 6 feet up. From here a few more moves up the arete gains some nice slippery slopers for the top out!

name: Delcatty
description: Sit start on some rail features to the right of the tree. Pull on to the wall and make a few moves up before reaching over the angle change and holding some slopey holds on the slab. From here figure out how to balance your way onto the low angle slab before topping out in easier terrain.   Hint: There is a large hold behind the tree that looks useful, but wasn't needed or used for the problem.

name: Garleck's Mantle
description: Sit start under the short overhang. Pull onto the wall and mantle the lip feature.

name: Lunar Alteration
description: Stand start at the right arete with a few small crimp options for the left hand, and the other hand on the arete. Pull onto the wall and make a few fun technical moves up to improving holds before grabbing slopers and meathooks at the lip of the boulder and topping out.

name: Lunar Occulation
description: A fun boulder problem from a sit-start at the base of a vertical arete. Grab a very small left-hand crimp and a low hold on the arete for the right. Figure out how to pull on and surge up to a small index finger side-pinch. Once here figure out where to move your feet and how to balance your way up to improving holds before topping out in easier terrain.

name: Moonstone Arete
description: Originally done from a stand-start with the right hand on the face and the left hand on the sharp crystals on the arete. Pull onto the wall and make a few slabby balance moves while utilizing the arete and features found on the face. Continue moving up and rightwards following the slopey arete before reaching a good meathook at the right arete and topping out.  Doing a squat start down and left incorporates a few extra powerful, technical and friction dependent moves into the stand at a grade or so harder.

name: Colloidal Suspension
description: An awesome problem incorporating power, balance, tension and body positioning. Sit start eight feet to the right of the left arete on an obvious smooth triangular shaped hold for the left hand and a smooth sloper down and slightly right. Pull on and move up to a crystal deposit for the right hand before figuring out how to execute the hard lock-off/ lunge for the slopey crystalline lip of the boulder. Match the sloping lip then execute a slopey and powerful mantel over a slightly exposed landing.

name: Elfin
description: An aesthetic arete on smooth rock. This problem has a few slightly powerful and technical moves but is over far too quickly. Sit start on the arete with some feet above the small roof. Pull on and move up the arete on some slopey holds before doing a big move over the lip to a good hold and rocking over the slab to top out.

name: Little Hellions
description: Originally done as a fun v3 dyno until a certain Perry found the easier beta.   For the dyno, grab a smooth right-hand crimp in the seam at about chest height, and a 3 finger sloper crimp about a foot or so to the left for the other hand. Pull onto the wall with slightly awkward feet and lunge for the lip. The lip is slopey and requires a great bit of tension in order to not grate off of the crystals. Match hands and top out.   The easier beta requires starting with a high lefthand about a foot and a half higher than the seam used for the dyno. Start with the lefthand on a good incut gaston, pull on and bump lefthand to the lip, classic Perry.

name: Schistomatics
description: A few hard tension moves on unique angled rails lead to a fun top out on great rock. Sit start with the left hand on a large layback rail in the dihedral, and right hand down and slightly right. Find the body positioning and make a hard lock-off tension move and bring the right hand around and then left to the rail. From here continue up a few more moves before topping out some good and slopey holds.

name: Continental Drift
description: Sit start under the short roof with the right-hand low on the sloping arete and the left-hand in a crack feature on the overhang. Pull onto the wall and make a powerful right-hand bump move directly up to a sharp crystal crimp about a foot above the right starting hold. From here figure out how to power out from under the roof and go for the lip. Match the lip then top out on to the large flat platform of the boulder.  This problem is less dabby than its harder counterpart which potentially makes it the better line.

name: Seismic Project
description: Sit start with the left-hand in an incut crack on the steep overhang, and the right hand on a flat sloper on the arete. Pull onto the wall and make a hard right-hand move up the arete to a decent pinch with a good pocket thumb catch. Squeeze hard and get some higher feet before figuring out how to snag one of the sharp crimps on the roof with the left-hand. After the left-hand move to the crimp, make another powerful right-hand move up the arete. From here, reach for the jug lip with either hand and core up to prevent the almost inevitable dab.   A jump start from low under the roof with the pocket right-hand pinch to the lip jug has been done without dabbing the rock behind somehow. This leads me to believe that skipping the sharp left-hand crimps on the roof is potentially a possibility for a monster with incredible power and pinch strength and some serious core.

name: Pinkies Up
description: Climb up onto the decent sized boulder underneath The Big-Swirly. Reach up to an incut 3 finger right-hand sidepull and grab a small left-hand micro-crimp pinch and compress the two. Figure out where you want your feet and bust a huge jump start to the large shelf five feet up and over your head. Hold on tight and take an incredible swing over a nasty landing. Match the large shelf with some slight difficulty and figure out where the next good hold is. Continue up directly using good holds and press it out at the top above and exponentially downgrading landing.   An impressive and bold boulder problem. The next question is simply, how do you enjoy your tea?

name: Send or Surrender
description: A king line with a committing deadpoint to a sloping lip and a scary mantle. A punt on the topout could eject you 20 feet down a hill. Don't punt.  Stand start at the right side of the face on the pedestal. Climb up and leftwards on seams and edges utilizing a lot of core and some heel hooks. Fire for the lip and hold the swing with everything you've got before matching and beached whaling your way up unless you're a Galloway.

name: A Fistful of Moss
description: Sit or lay start with a good right hand and a decent crimp for the left. Using your choiceof footwork trickery, pull off and grab a diagnol arete-like feature. From here match or go big to a giant left hand sloper. Clamp down and reach up to other holds. get a foot on the sloper shelf and topout using a decent crimp knob.

name: Blue Jean
description: Lay-down start underneath the square-cut overhanging prow. Find the terrible right-hand divot starting hold and few options for feet. Find the compression necessary to pull on and then fire for a sloper out left. Latch this move then smack into a good meathook and figure out how to get on top.  Note: The detached and adjacent boulders are NOT used for this problem.

name: Faceful of Dirt
description: Sit or lay down start with the arete for the right hand and a crimp or side pull for the left. Pull on using some foot trickery and bump the right hand up the arete before moving to other holds with the left. Once established make a hard top out or move left to a small crimp knob and slopers.    Named after the heinous top out of the first ascent which left Jake with dirt all over his face.

name: Earth
description: Stand start beneath the arete. Place the right foot on the starting block and stand up to some good holds on the arete. From here waste energy trying to figure out where you want your feet or just go with the flow and campus the arete on good holds. You can pretty much mantel anywhere.

name: Earth, Wind, Mud and Fire
description: A fun traverse starting on "Earth" and topping out as for "Fire". Pull on to "Earth and traverse the lip into "Wind", where you can get a nice rest for the crux section. Traverse the lip a few more times then drop down to some crimps. Make it through the crimp section to gain increasingly better slopers and eventually jugs. Go around the "Water" arete and traverse a few more moves then topout!

name: Fire
description: This fun arete is full value, sit start, uses the arete and the crack on the face, interesting moves and a good topout to finish.     Sit start under the mini overhang/bulge with both hands in the crack. Figure out how to get off the ground (kinda tricky), make a hard slap to a sloper crimp around the bulge, grab the arete and a perfect edge, then figure out how to get up to the top using the crack out left and the arete, make a crux high bump on the arete then power to the lip, it's a flat jug.

name: Water
description: Stand start on a couple good sidepulls on the arete. Pull on and lockoff to a decent lefthand shelf, then come in right hand to a poor right hand crimp/ sloper. Campus up a foot and cross up to a mini pinch above your head. Roll into it and bump to a jug on the lip! a thriller with a sketchy landing, lots of body tension and fun movement!

name: Wind
description: Sit start with right hand on the arete and left hand doing nothing. Find a left foot outside edge smear and a right heelhook around the arete. Pull on and core up to a small crimper left of the arete. Snag this then make a right hand move to a giant shelf. Match hands then figure out how you are going to get to the lip. A huge lock-off, a big deadpoint, or mantel the shelf!

name: Xenon
description: Sit start with some nice textured rails and crimps  Pull onto the wall and reach up slowly to a right hand pinch with a crystal thumb catch. From here surf out to a mega-wide left-hand pinch before continuing up using a gaston in the crack. Once here figure out which crystals you want to grab and grab the bucket at the lip!

name: Coyote Killer
description: The alternative start for Coyotes. This line starts about as low in the crack as possible, makes a handful of very hard moves up the crack that get you pumped for the long traverse and heady topout.     Start as low in the crack as possible, traverse the crack to the arete, then finish up Coyotes.     The lower portion of this crack is often wet. It's also very fun to start one move further into the crack the from the start of this, as it gives you better feet. This way is probably v4/5.

name: Coyotes
description: Another great slopey traverse. Start down low on the left arete (to the left/below the crack) and traverse the lip, fight the pump because the crux comes at the top. Make a tough move to the top of the peak and pull a hard topout.

name: The Lone Wolf
description: The stand for Tears Of A Lone Wolf. This is a sick line on it's own though too.     On the right arete, start about halfway up the arete on some little nubbins about 6' up. Figure out how to get to the peak of the boulder using power and big moves, or small movement and lots of beta. Once you get to the peak, commit to a tough top out that'll get your blood pumping from the bad landing.

name: Tears Of A Lone Wolf
description: The mega-classic line of this boulder, and probably one of the best lines at Clough. Incredible movement and marginal holds finished with a tough mantle. This is the sit start to The Lone Wolf.     Start sitting low with fantastic heel toe cam, right hand on the bottom of the arete, left under you're heel and right foot smeared. Levitate up to the arete, make a tough match, then decipher the sequence you'll need to get to the top without being too pumped for the scary mantle. Top out and howl at the moon.

name: Young Pup
description: Sit start matched on a slightly diagonal undercling feature 3 feet off the ground. Make a hard pull on to the wall using good footholds and make a hard move or two up to larger holds before pulling up and over the angle change on to some smooth rock with some nice jugs for the slab top out.

name: Chihuahua
description: This is an okay little climb. With some more cleaning it will be better.     Start on a little sloper dish thing, then find some feet, get to the left arete and finish up on the left face.

name: Dragon's Lair
description: Sit start under the roof with a small crimp flake for the left and the arete for the right. Pull on and move the left hand out the arete. Throw up a heel hook and cross to an awesome pinch on the arete. Mantel over and grab a few holds. Don't dab and watch out for the rock to the left. Low and short on a unique rock and a nice arete.

name: Kaizen
description: Sit start in the center of the boulder with a hidden left hand undercling and a right hand slopey crystal crimp. Find a way to put weight on your left foot and make a couple hard left hand moves to gain a good sidepull flake. Move right hand up to another sidepull flake then make a big move up lefty onto the slab to a crystal nub and top her out.

name: Lichen It
description: This is a cool climb with a low crux and couple committing moves up high.     Start with jug left and low on the arete, and a crimp out right. Pull off the ground with difficulty and make a hard move to bump up the arete. Find your feet and get your right hand to some higher holds, then get your hand in a great, somewhat hidden hold in a crack/seam. Use some trickery to get from there to the arete up and right. From there make one more move to a jug on the lip and top 'er out, you'll be lichen it.

name: Slaps
description: This problem climbs using some big slaps up an arete and some crimps.    Start using either of two left hand crimps, one is bigger but further away, and a right hand as low as you can (or want to) on the right arete. Bump up to a really good hold on the arete, then make a big slap up the arete the an awesome hold that has a perfect little divot-oval cut out that fits 4 fingers. From here figure out how to get a slopey jug up high and work up and left and top at as for Lichen It.     This climb is kinda morpho, as Brad couldn't span where I started, so people with shorter spans might have to just start matched on the arete, or higher up on the arete. I think the best option would be to climb it as a jump start, left on the crimp then jump up and catch right on the arete up high.

name: Brass Monkey
description: Sit start with hands matched on a good rail. The left hand should be in a crystal pocket. Make a big move out right to another rail. Match or go straight to a crimp up and left. Hit a sloper for the right hand, then get a higher foot and rock over, staying tight and balanced reach out left to small holds and swap feet and move up the slab. Top out with invisible holds and walk it off.

name: Chip Off The 'Ole Block
description: A fun climb with big easy moves on big holds leading to a crux mantle on a shelf.     Start down low on a jug, follow a big holds up leading to an obvious shelf, and mantle that.

name: Monkey Wins Big at the Slots
description: This is a fun traverse starting at the right side of the downhill face. Sit start with a right hand sidepull and a left hand slot. Pull on and stand up to a rail on the lip of the boulder. From here make your way leftwards with a few tricky moves to get past "Slot Machine". From the crack, reach far left to the rail on "Brass Monkey", and with difficulty join that line before continuing around the bulbous corner for a cruxy mantel-like exit on to the slab. From here continue left and up to topout! A fun traverse with some unique movement and lots of moves!

name: Slot Machine
description: Squat start at the horizontal slot and move up and left to good holds. Get a handjam and reach up and left to a sloper in the crack. Get a heel and pull too reach a pocket up and out right. Stay right and trust a blind toe in the crack    Work some magic and stand up.

name: Another One Bites The Dust
description: There is a squat start and a lay-down start, both starts are about the same grade. For lay-down, start matched on a side-pull and a heel in the triangular flake for the start of "The Dungeon". Throw out left to the bottom of the arete, there is a small crimp. (this is where your left hand is for the squat/ sit start) Toss right hand up higher on the arete and bring your left hand up to sloper. get right hand established on sloping rail and grab a jug to the left and top it out.

name: Dragon's Back
description: This is a great climb that has some tough moves that flow well on cool holds.    This starts with good left hand crimp and a sweet right hand sloper pocket with some good feet. Get an awesome right hand sloper pinch, figure out your feet and one of a number of possible left hand holds then fire for a jug. Top out. Downclimb using the tree, go down the back of the boulder, or just hop down.    There is a variation that adds one move. It starts with the right hand instead on the big undercling/sidepull thing that's closer to the left hand start hold. This way makes pulling off the ground harder and adds a crux first move, making it probably V4+. It's not as good as the normal line.

name: The Dungeon
description: This route starts in a lay down position, both hands matched on a triangular flake. Left foot on rail and right foot flagging left. make a move to a right crimp, then go for the rail at the lip. Topout the slab using a heel/toe and some holds out left.   A good warm up and relatively close to the gazebo make this a great line for climbers getting familiar with the area.

name: Here There Be Dragons
description: This is a pumpy traverse that goes across the whole lip of the boulder with a crux at the end. Sit Start on left arete as for Another One Bites The Dust. Do the first two moves of that line and then begin traversing the good lip rail out right, all the way to the finish jug for Dragon’s Back and topping out as for that line. The good lip rail runs out about halfway through the boulder, between The Dungeon and White Fire. From the end of the rail begins a tricky and hard section that just keeps getting harder until you finally match the jug. Proper sequencing and grabbing the right slopers is crucial for not pumping out on the finishing match.

name: White Fire
description: Are you finding that you just have too much skin lately? Feeling like you want to clench your teeth from sharp holds? Want to test you pain tolerance? Then give this problem a try!    In the middle of the boulder, start sitting with your left hand on a friendly, but small sidepull crimp and right hand out on the obvious sidepull out right. Figure out the best spots you wanna the starting holds on and think hard about the feet you wanna use.     Squeeze hard, pull up, and make a crux throw to a 1/2 pad crimp. Dig as deep as you can to hold on through the pain and keep your core tight so your feet don't cut. Now using an option of slopers and divots (the jugs way to the right on Dragon's Back are sucker holds), work out how to get your way on to the slab. From here, press hard and pull the second crux, the top out. Run up to the top and check your skin. If you don't have any cuts you didn't do it right.    EDIT: Went back to this the other day and turns out the 1/2 pad crimp isn't all that sharp, you definitely don't want to be dry firing on it a bunch of times though.

name: Ambitious and Disordered
description: Sit start as for Clever and Devoted, but once on the sloper shelf, bring right hand up to the diagnol slopey right arete, and left hand up the left arete. Compress your way up until you can lunge for the fin shaped lip, then topout.

name: Clever and Devoted
description: Sit start with left hand on a knob on the arete, and the right hand on a low sloper with some divots and crystals. Find bad feet and pull on and hit the sloper shelf, or spin around and bat hang the sloper shelf to get off the ground. From the sloper shelf move left around the arete to a thin crack and good diagnol holds with difficulty. From these sidepulls climb straight up and top out.

name: Dance of the Toadstools
description: Start on the right side of the boulder in a squat-start with a hand on either side of the arete. Move out and hand traverse left along the lips with good holds, a couple of nice heels in the middle of the face. Then make  a big move and figure out how to pull around the left end and top out.

name: Full Tilt
description: A super sweet traverse problem that uses multiple boulders and a crazy roof. Double kneebars, toe hooks, heel hooks, and crosses oh my!    Start matched on the bottom of the roof with a double kneebar and little rock for feet. Traverse your way around using the roof and the next two boulders to eventually top out on the roof. The big boulder to the left of the roof is not used.    It might be a good idea to brush holds of before you climb on them as it can get pretty dusty in this cave.     This video is really helpful for understanding this route since not many problems out there use multiple boulders.    youtube.com/watch?v=usqlDI_…

name: Lower Jaw
description: Squat start matched on the jug in the horizontal split, and lunge direct to a good edge at the lip.

name: Music For The Tilted Generation
description: A tough traverse across the Full Tilt boulders.     Start the same as for Full Tilt, and make the same first few moves, but instead of breaking up and left to top out on the boulder that forms the roof, continues heading right on the seam/crack. Traverse all the way across the boulder until you reach the right arete, finish up on that arete.

name: Walk Off
description: This is the traditional way to get back up when you are swimming here... If so many drunk people have done it over the years it's gotta be pretty cruser...

name: Angler
description: Right of the Training Wall look for a right angling dike feature on a less than vertical wall... climb this feature to the top...     I really forget how hard this is but they wont let me put "i dont know" for a grade...

name: Escapist
description: If you jump off the Training Wall and can't make it up those problems this can be a good option... Climb out of the water as for the Training Wall Right but break to the right up an easy ramp and an easy mantle move... Then rest up and hit the training Wall again...

name: Get Shorty
description: I really don't remember the exact grade but its steep and short with a cooll move or two...    Climb out of the water on crimps and hit a lay back move then climb on up...

name: Hangover
description: This is a neat little climb... Getting out of the water is pretty moderate since there is a little ledge above water... Then you are face with a small powerful roof with small holds up to a mantle move top out...     Not sure on the grade... Feed back would be great if you go climb it... The name is dedicated to generations of drunken party goers that have incidentally made this pretty spot pretty ugly

name: They Swim All Over You
description: This is the main jumping spot so be careful as you aproach so you don't get hit... Climb as directly as you can up to the "Diving board" you will have to break a little right as you go... cool crimpy moves and foot work are the name of this game...     If you know The Little Mermaid you might get the name...

name: Training Wall Left
description: Climb out of the water on sloping edges and work up to a corner and a funky topout...     Starting can be tough since you can't see your feet and its pretty slimmy down there...

name: Training Wall Right
description: Climb out of the water with slimmy hard to find feet and sloping edges... A big reach to a slot gets your hands to the top and most find topping out to be the crux...    My favorite line at this quarry...

name: ANDY'S ROUTE
description: The most obviously line a little bit right of middle of Andy's Cliff.  It is a break in the wall that goes all the way up to a pine tree at the top that zig-zags a little and set back from the left face.  Climb the face or walk up the ramp to the block.   Lay back on the block to get up on it.   Go up and right with the crux coming at the end of the right traverse.   Cut back left and finish at the pine tree.  Good pro all the way makes for a fun first lead.

name: Broken Toe (Walk On The Wildside Variation)
description: This is the face climbing variation to "Walk On The Wildside".   Start at the same unmistakable right trending crack.  The crack jams real well and feels easy 5.7.  A few feet before the arete there will be slanted horizontals above you at which point you'll start going straight up.  Have faith climbing the face as unique for New England "eyebrow" cracks appear exactly where you need them.   Place pro carefully about 1/2 way up the face as the eyebrow cracks are just flared enough to make placement tricky.   Good pro can be had 4 feet above the tricky placement.  I cleaned the exit crack pretty well so it is a straight 5.6 move and not a manky, dirty, scary mantle move on rock with lichen.  To make it even more mellow, you can place pro to protect the top out.

name: Cross The Reaper
description: Probably the best route on the Main Wall.   Start basically right below the pine tree at a right facing crack with a few blueberry bushes growing out of it.   Climb straight up to the two  big diagonal cracks that slants up right. Zig (go left)  just a little bit to go above the diagonals and zag (trend right) back more or less going towards and mantle exit right under the pine tree at top.  Mantle up and walk to the tree to finish the route.  Plenty of good pro is to be had on the route if you look carefully.    I'm not sure if it's a 1st ascent, but I'm pretty sure the pine tree probably was much smaller 38 or so years ago.   It is not documented in the old guidebook and crosses "The Reaper", "Whip It" and "George's Route", hence I am calling it "Cross the Reaper".   If there is some info on the 1st ascent let me know and I'll correct it.

name: Dihedral
description: DIHEDRAL( 5.5+ )-Follow the lower cracks of Georges route to their end then go up past a birch tree to bulge then over.(F.A. A.Kling summer '79)   (Variation on DIHEDRAL)(5.8-)-Face directly around corner of bulge.

name: Georges Route
description: GEORGE'S R0UTE(5.6+)-Traverse the two large cracks until you come to a small crack system. Follow this to the top finishing in the wedge at the top ten feet to the left of the cave. The main Cliff hosts many bee's nests in the summer months..So keep an eye out.

name: Georgiana
description: A nice alternate to George's. Climb the right facing flake to a shelf. Traverse right to a small broken face within the gully, then climb the broken face to a stance just below a small open book (this is the George's finish). Traverse right along a face on a narrow shelf (currently occupied by a tiny but inconvenient black birch) with good holds for about 10 feet, then up a vertical crack (crux) to a rounded but easy topout with decent hands and feet (though it is not a jughaul). Careful rope management is needed to minimize rope drag.

name: Goofer's Roof Right
description: See beta picture. Start on the left crack and climb it as it goes right. Powerful movement will get you off the ground, small gear protects till it tapers off, then it's a committing move straight up to the roof crack and continue up the roof crack right with little feet and a committing mantle to top out. The old guidebook says use the tree for anchor but you can set up a very good anchor at the lunch ledge.  So ALL the cracks flares in one way or another, so please be a solid trad leader for this one.

name: Hooterville (most obvious version)
description: This is my version of the route as there are many variations you can take on the face.   It has a nice juggy dead vertical section-not bad for a 5.5 in New England!   Too bad it only lasts about 5 feet!  We started on the right-trending crack on the left of the small alcove that is the start of the "Standard Route" (which goes right from the alcove).  Follow the crack up to the ramp, then go right from the ramp to the small tree/bush and then go straight up (low angle 5th class)  to the top of the cliff.   See pics.

name: Hungarys Burnt (a.k.a. the Dogs Face Crack)
description: HUNGRY'S BURNT(5.8+)Good free climb. Starts on the right crack, few tough moves off ground to a balance move on face, gain roof and follow it to right end of roof and finish out end.

name: I'll Tell You What You Missed
description: On the Lower Right Side of Andy's Wall start on the diagonal rail on the right of the water streak, climb up edges and pockets right then left with some big reaches to a good hand jam in a horizontal.  Do some cool moves and make it to the ledge.  Celebrate your victory with a big fist pump in the air and exclaim "Yeah!"  This route crosses the big water streak so may not be good in wet times.

name: That is That
description: Down and right from "This is This" on Andy's Wall, this route starts on the bulge on nice diagonal edges and a horizontal full of quartz and climbs straight up to a small ledge and on up through some cracks to diagonal cracks to finish on a ledge.  Top Rope from the large pine tree.  Good pro but you may need to hunt for some of it.  *I did some major cleaning on this route.  It will continue to improve with traffic.  Climb it!

name: This Is This
description: The first moves are between a right-tending crack (to the left) and a lower, left-facing flake (to the right).  Work you way up to a pocket alcove, then tiptoe left to the left-facing flake.  Work your way straight up to a reachy, small jug/ledge (crux); this gets you to the arete. Follow the arete and exit early, or you can continue left to the bolted anchor for the 5.11a sport route.

name: Unknown
description: This route is on what is known as Porcupine cliff as there has been a Porcupine occupying the cave for as long as I can remember. Approach the roof as seems fit. Make tricky moves up the finger crack gaining the nose. Pull up and over.

name: Unknown
description: This balancy route holds your attention as you follow 2 bolts on the right side of Andy's cliff. To make it safe you should carry a mid size cam to place in a seam before the 2 bolt anchor.

name: Walk on the Wild Side
description: WALK ON THE WILD SIDE(5.7)-Large right diagonaling crack. Follow the crack to the left side of the overhang, You can head up on some unusual horizontals that take cams.

name: You Tell Me What You Saw
description: Climb the face between the two brown water streaks on diagonal sloping cracks to a horizontal finger crack midway up the wall, continue up through face holds and thin cracks to a ledge at the top and a pile of possibly disconnected rocks.  Top Rope from the large pine with a directional on the oak (or was it a maple?) tree on the right of the ledge.  Will accept some good gear but the bottom half will be tricky.    *I named this route but correct me if I'm wrong

name: Ein
description: the route is a traverse following the crack till the route is interrupted by the tree.

name: The Big Boulder
description: Bypass the roof and climb the boulders right face.

name: Leech Therapy
description: Locate the undercling in the middle of the face. Stand start off of two bomber lower feet and the under cling. Climb to the highest point on the boulder using crimps and the arete.

name: Twerk
description: Just left of leech therapy is an undercut wall below an arête.  Grab a weird flake left and a crimp right and from the stand pull up and make some weird balance moves till you can establish on the face.  Finish as LT.

name: Bruisemaster
description: A flared crack going up the roof

name: localmotion
description: The line follows a crack in an obvious groove.  Start beneath a large flake, climb the left side.  Move up and left clipping a pin and climbing the groove proper.  Top out beneath the small tree on top.  (don't use the tree! It's only 5'6...)

name: Unknown
description: Climb the top of the blocks that form upper and lower horizontal crack and do an fun hand traverse followed by an easy scramble.

name: Womb with a View
description: Guidebook Description:  Surmount the left edge of the block, starting on the left side and traversing to an overhanging mantle.    My Description:  Start on on a large bulge under the far left side of the Bruisemaster roof.  Make a long move to the edge and work left to a flake and stance.  Move back right and up the arête to protection and climb easy slab to the top.

name: The Hang
description: Good little route.  Start up blocky crack 5' to the right of The Killer Flake.  Move up protect and pull onto the slab and set up below a small roof.  Move up and over the left side of the roof on good holds.  The anchor is just above the flake.    Variation:  5.7   Climb under the flake to the right and avoid pulling the roof.

name: Stone Zoo
description: Climb the obvious finger crack, sustained

name: Brachiotomy
description: Start on the left side of the boulder and hand traverse under the route.

name: Dumplington Hammer
description: Sit start on the face to the left of the arete for Dumplington Spike. Low foot, left hand on a small crimp, right hand on the arete. Work up the face and finish up Dumplinton Spike.

name: Dumplington Spike
description: Sit start the right arete, low foot, both hands on the arete or your right on the arete and your left hand underclinging the block. Work your way up the arete and follow it around the horn until you can rock over on to the arete top out.

name: Horizontal Thrutch
description: Start at the tree growing out of right to left low angle diagonal off width crack, ending at the chimney on Krazy Krack.    You can either wedge yourself inside the crack (5.5), walk along the crack (5.7) or Hand traverse the lip and mantle into the chimney (5.9)    Just a super fun and silly problem.

name: Krazy Krack
description: Climb the obvious wide crack out the roof to a horizontal, mantle into the chimney and top out.

name: Krazy Krystal
description: Climb the spicy, crystally slab dike to the top.

name: Bagels and Locks
description: Climb the obvious left leaning thin finger crack

name: Block-Out
description: Climb the obvious dirty chimney, passing a loose block.

name: Endo
description: Start on two small underclings for hands, a low ledge for feet. fire up to a thin rail, mantle, slap lip and small crystal, top out.    The start might be height dependent

name: Flight Line
description: Start on the crack just left of Vector and just right of a birds nest.  Move up to a large hold and make a series of thin moves in horizontal seams to a balance top out on a great edge

name: Good Godfrey
description: Climb the obvious layback flake

name: Numb Knees
description: Climb the right chimney

name: The Something Seam
description: Climb the slab below the The Nothing Seam and finish up The Nothing Seam.

name: Tartor Sauce
description: Climb the large boulder that lies at the start of Bagel and Locks. Under cling the crack and smear your way to the top.    Alternative start to Tarter Sauce, Start behind the boulder at the base of the problem and stem/layback the corner till you can gain the underclings.

name: Unknown v2
description: Start under a small roof either matched on an undercling or squeezing the block.  Move up the blocky section, out to a crimp, and mantle the topout

name: Vector
description: Climb up awesome edges and crimps till you can move right and top out.

name: 2 in the Bush
description: Delicate climbing off a block, move staright up to the pocket/flake.  Pinch and undercling and make a hard move to the flat edge on top.

name: 5th of November
description: Climb the chimney placing gear in the crack in the back.   Climb to a stance, protect and climb spooky/fun traverse left until you reach top of the pinnacle.  Protect and make tricky face moves to reach the top.    Guidebook:  Up the right chimney, then climb the center of the upper face.

name: Access Route
description: Climb the broken dike to the top.  Good access for the TR anchors.

name: Sky Flake
description: Climb the left side of the pinnacle to a slanting feature, then make hard moves right to a good flake crack. Finish up horizontals above the top of the pillar.  You can finish on either Squeeze Box or 5th of November  "This line has scruffy trad trickery. It was cleaned on rappel but not toproped. I shinnied up the tree and left gully and girth-hitched a sling above where it touches the rock (tree was smaller 30+ years ago duh). The left rope protected the crux past the slanting feature to the bottomless crack, then a couple of cams pro-ed that to the top of the block. It needs another scrub & dig, as do many routes at minor crags.  It climbs like some British gritstone weirdness. You could rate it E3 5c----figure that one out! " Mack Johnson

name: Squeeze Box
description: Climb the first chimney you'll see when leaving The Roofs. Climb the chimney until you can't climb anymore, traverse left and finish up Ledgeland.

name: Fretful Porpentine
description: Climbing the ugly right hand crack located in a shallow groove-corner.   Crux protection is behind a loose block.

name: Ledgeland
description: This is one of the easiest routes in The Roofs/Main Cliff Area. Climb onto the ledge, walk right and finish up cracks and holds on the left-facing wall.

name: Power Ladder
description: Climb up edges to a tough mantle.  Sramble off right and up or jump down.

name: Riplash
description: Climb the wild fist jam crack.

name: Shoot the Moon
description: This is the first crack that you'll come across when you enter this section of the Main Cliff Roofs Area.   Ascend the left most handjam crack out a right-facing dihedral

name: Quarryman
description: From a stand start on great holds and make a long move left to another great edge.  Continue up on good edges to the top.  Don't be ashamed to use the tree.

name: Thomas the Train
description: Climb the groove to crack and make a tricky top out.  Scramble off left and down climb.

name: Todd's Crack
description: Climb the easy left leaning fist crack.

name: Chickadee
description: Sit start to the right of the blank area, as with Penguin. Travel up some loose finger cracks and traverse across to the corner, then up to a small ledge and topout.     Was originally V1 until a bird freaked me out, making me lean back, removing a loose chunk and making the route way easier.

name: Falcon
description: Start out on the crux where you're squeezing a depression in the roof and the side of the crack. Work your way up into the crack, top out is dirty and loose but fun.

name: Penguin
description: Traverse from the small footholds as in the beta picture for Birdcage across a blank section in the rock. Finish up the offwidth crack, top out is the same as Falcon.

name: The Adorable Miss Granger
description: The start is pretty much the same as Ginny's Secret but instead of climbing the easy groove you climb straight up the wall above... The rock is slick and the gear a little funky in spots but its safe and fun...     This was the first line we climbed when we discovered the cliff...

name: Aragog's Lair
description: Cool steep climbing... Mega crimpy in the crux with cool fun moves the whole way... Recomended!    Climb up to the steep wall and get a piece in a crystal pocket... Micro crimp your way up then dyno (well above your gear) to a really good jug and some more gear... Climb up to a good rest and pull straight over one more bulge at 5.11ish... Belay from trees... Described for the lead but toprope recommended first unless you really rock...

name: Beyond the Veil
description: This is the best route under 5.8 at the cliff...    Very cool moves off the ground following the arete... you get a rest on a ledge after the crux beginning Pretty much contunue on the arete to the top staying left of the wide crack at the top of Fawkes...

name: The Boy Who Lived
description: A really fun climb and one of the easiest to spot due to the crack at the base and one up high...Pretty well protected but a couple loose rocks getting in to it...     On the right side of the wall look for an obvious corner... Climb up a wide crack/flake to a stance below the corner... Pull out an overhang and in to the corner with a crack... Climb the corner to the top... Belay from trees...

name: The Burrow
description: Short but sweet... Fun, interesting moves on solid rock...     From a ledge on the left side of the cliff step out right and climb the thin face holds and cracks up a short wall to the top at the trees...

name: Diffindo
description: On the far right locate a crack in the bulge above... Climb up to it and over the top to a crack in the slab... Climb moderate rock to the top... this line is longer and more fun than it looks...    There is some loose stuff on this one... If you lead it be careful where you place things as the loose rocks could shift and ruin your day...

name: Fawkes From the Ashes
description: Maybe the most obvious route here... Fun climbing but its normally wet, and loose in spots...     Climb the deep corner to the right of the steep wall stemming most of the way and following a wide crack/groove to the top...

name: Flight of the Phoenix
description: Maybe my favorite route here so far... Fun technical climbing on steep rock with good but funky, spicy gear...    With some good gear craft this one can be safe but the pro can be very tricky and small... I worked it out on TR first...  Start to the right of the tree near the base of the steep wall and climb up and a little left past funky holds and a pocket or 2 before trending back right and up to the top... Belay from the trees...

name: Ginny's Secret
description: On the left side of the cliff is a lower angle section with fun moderate routes side by side... This is the left most one on this section...     Climb up to a ledge left of a low pine tree follow the groove up and a little left to the top... Fun climbing...

name: Parting of the Ways
description: Another fun way to utilize this uverhanging playground... Mostly big moves to good holds with a couple killer crimps near the top...    Climb the steep wall between Flight of the Phoenix and the Boy Who Lived... Start with a boulder problem to a ledge rest then a little loose rock to a solid steep wall that could be a bit harder for short climbers... Only a couple good pieces of gear... One at half height and a small nut up hight...

name: The Secret Keeper
description: Make interesting moves up the first steep section to a ledge rest... Climb straight up the wall above following some cracks and interesting (sometimes secret) holds to the top...     These routes are close together but all offer something different and really do have there own lines...

name: Hass Crack
description: Climb the left sloping crack to a scary but easy top out. Watch out for the tree behind you!

name: Hot Potato
description: Start with a high right hand, and a left hand down low. Work your way up on crimps and mantle over.

name: Slow and Steady
description: Start on a good left handed crack and a right handed sloper. Bump up to a small crimp and swing your legs left. Traverse and top out.

name: Butter fingers
description: Start with left hand on a slight creator and right hand is sort of just smearing. Foot hand match the left hand hold. It is delicate to stand up on but good once you are up and can smear it. Once you've gotten this move and your standing use tiny features and smearing your feet too work right. And up to the top. Hardest part is standing up off of the foot hand match

name: Poop diamonds
description: On the left side of the black diamond boulder is a slab problem. Not amazing but very thin feeling. A hard start low on the boulder to just get grip. Then foot too hand match stand up using balance on a tiny chip to a few dimples too work your way up tend too the right side as the left is alot easier

name: Undersit
description: Start sitting with a great left hand jug and a vertical crimp. Pull up and follow the arete up to the crack and topout.

name: Understand
description: Start standing. Find the crimps on the upside down rail. Work your way up and right to the big jug. Arete is off.

name: Crunching numbers
description: Sit start RH on a crimp high up LH on a low slot. pull up work your way up and right through good edges.

name: Gypsy tears
description: Start on an obvious crimp rail same as spread em but use different feet and got straight up using a weird gaston then try to grab the jug without dabbing the tree.

name: Introdyno
description: There's two nice jugs to start on. Use a high left toe and launch up to the top lip. Traverse left or right to top out or press it out to make it a little more difficult.  Nice fun easy problem.

name: its in the bone
description: Start super low on a jug do a big lock off to an awful two finger crystal crimp (sharp) then trust a bad foot and hope it doesn't pop or your shin is going to be hurting hence the name.    went there today and the crimp felt like its going to break.

name: Nest Arete
description: This problem (and boulder) Is a bit chossy. Head straight up the flake on the arete to the bomber handle up by the sapling. The feet at first aren’t great.

name: Spread Em
description: start matched on an obvious rail with a left toe hook, work your way left through good holds and tricky foot beta, find a crimp and either dyno to the finish or use the arete. The dyno from the crimp makes it a grade harder.

name: Start at the Slug
description: Start almost from a sit at the very bottom of the arête. Find some good holds and pull on. Move right along the lip and top out at the peak.

name: Wabi-sabi
description: Same start as "It's in the Bone" on the low jug. Big move out to the tip of the arete and either continue around the corner (left) and then top-out or continue up the arete and slightly right for an earlier exit. Felt the same grade either way. I enjoyed the left exit better, as it flowed nicely. Careful of some loose rock on this section of the boulder.

name: Circus Freak
description: Follow beta from Roadside Attraction but once you are on the small pocket head left to the arete instead of right to finish up.  Super slab and bad feet. Have fun.

name: Dazed & Amused
description: Start low right side with heel hook and both hands on a protruding flake. Follow roof left using slopers, crimps, heel hooks, and few good feet under roof. Gain furthest left arete and mantle this fun lowball.

name: Elephunk
description: Start sitting and move up to a good jug flake, Move left to a flake and then make a long love to the pockt and top out striaght up

name: Heartless
description: Same start at Summercamp Massacre but instead of heading up the vertical crack to the top, find the undercling below the prow. From there make a big move directly to the apex of the prow. Top out.

name: high ball roadside attraction
description: walk down the hill from the over hanging large boulder and the one in the corner and walk down a path to the back side of a seemingly small boulder... the otherside holds a 15 foot highball boulder with a tree about two feet from the right side...  the boulder is relitivly clean and slabby right off the bat you should see a two finger pocket pretty close to the center work your way from the left side with a terrible crimp with a thumb catch and a opposing side pull up to a left hand juggy pocket from there move your right hand up to another side pull move your right hand into the centered two finger pocket then switch hands to your left hand in that same pocket... move right using shisty foot holds to a dyno righ to anothe sidepull crimp... get you right foot up and the crux and the sketchy ascent begin as you move your left hand up to a slopy ledge up high and use arete up with your right until you can dyno to the nice finish ...

name: Lakeside warmup
description: A nice warmup for the other routes on these two boulders. Start sitting/crouching, left hand in the crack, right on a decent sidepull and move up into the flake and top out straight up

name: Machete Man
description: Start on the block with your feet and hands on the rail and crimps to traverse to the good hold. Finish up on the moves to SummerCAmp Massacre.

name: Pauls Bunion
description: Start low on two jugs, left hand has 3 slopers/crimps to choose and bump on while right follows big flake. The crux is gaining the next two crimps and reaching the flake above to freedom.    Fun fun fun problem thats begs to be climbed. Not sure if it's been sent before or not. Cleaned fair amount of linchen off around arete and up top.

name: Stoop kid
description: Start on big flake (Lakeside Warmup) then dyno straight up to large sloper for top out. Fun and easy dyno.

name: Summer Camp
description: Start with hands on the seam and a bad left foot. Pull up make a few moves to the flared horizontal and continue up to the tallest point. The start is the crux with a "fun" topout

name: Summercamp Massacre
description: Start the same as Sleeping Giant, Once you move left to the flake continue up and left under the prow. Make a long move onto the face above on good holds and keep a cool head for the top out.

name: Super Camp Traverse
description: Start on the left side of the prow and traverse right. Climb through the corner and top out for Summer Camp. A link up of Supermoon into Summer Camp.

name: Supermoon
description: a fun traverse from the left side of the boulder and finishing with the problem "sunset traverse" at the right of the boulder

name: Tricky Biscuits
description: ground start with a match on the only crystal hold, slowly stand on a tiny nub with your left foot into the corner, reach for a rough pinch with a tiny thumb catch, left hand to frictiony hold, dance feet to left for a toe hook, left hand to hold under supercamp massacre jug, right hand to crappy side pull under supuercamp massacre flake, move to toe hook on the right, high reach with right for crappy two finger hold, left hand on jug just above, finish the top of supuercamp massacreNOTE In Sept 2020 the original submitter of this route requested it be deleted, but agreed to have his name removed and for the route to be "reassigned", whereupon I "took it on".  R Hall NH Admin.

name: Ashy Larry
description: Start on same blocky jug as Draw Backwards. Move to the vertical crimps to the left. There are about 4-5 holds along the seam. Once on the ledge finish the same as Draw Backwards.

name: Draw Backwards
description: Match on a blocky jug to start.  Move up with your left hand to a crimpy side pull and hit the next crimp with your right.  Adjust feet and move to a matching crimp.  Reach up to nice ledge.  Fat left hand pinch and hit a good crimp up right.  Sit heavy on the crimp and pull up to decent jug left.  Top out using good jug. You can traverse left or right if you're sketched about topping out.  Crux seems to be the crimpy side pulls at the beginning.

name: Half On
