description: Start matching on a nice small rail. Move up to a crimp both left and right. There's a crimp midway if you need to bump. Stay real tight and get up to the crack. Feet up and hit the lip. Easy press to top out. There's a crimp over the lip on the next ledge to help finish but I found I didn't need it.

name: Moose Maple
description: Start on a blocky jug and sit low. Move straight up through some crimps and a cool triangle hold. Gain the small ledge and top out.

name: Party time
description: (From the FA-er) Fun traverse line with a nice topout. The landing is okay but don’t roll too far or you’ll take a tumble off the cliff. Roof is above the quarry so you’ll have to hike around to find it. Good luck. You’ll be happy you searched this one out.

name: Crack W****Traverse
description: This line is a bit contrived but what do you want from me, i love cracks...    Sit at a hand crack on the far right side of the left most boulder... Climb this crack to a left angling crack that leads you to the topout of the previous problems...    Fun times but not classic...

name: Hannah's shorts
description: The first time I got on it was with a friend of mine named Jakob and we were determined to get the first ascent so much that we camped out at the boulder until 2am only to not send it. Almost a year later we went back with my other friend Hannah and she sent it first go. We were all very impressed until we had found out she had sent the problem 3 weeks before and neglected to tell us.    Any ways this is a great problem. You sit start on the right side of a small roof on really small crimps. After heal hooking the edge of the boulder you throw out to a block to the left and traverse left on the small roof making sure not to dab your feet! After you have gone out of the roof section head up to the top and celebrate!

name: High and Mighty
description: The nicest route here to date... Required no cleaning and just begged to be climbed... Also the tallest problem with a nice easy top out...    Sit at the base of the nice quartzy line and climb pretty nice holds the whole way to a killer jug at the top...

name: Mud Sundae
description: The best line on this boulder...    Sit to the right of Weekday Warrior in the middle of the boulder at a perfect start hold... Climb jugs straight up and top out the roof to mantel using a horizontal crack...

name: One Move Wonder
description: Sit a few feet to the right of High and Mighty on a couple of hard holds... Pull your ass off the ground (crux) and make a quick move to a good hold... The rest of the route is easier... Angle left to meet the top out of High and Mighty...    A fun route but the real fun on this boulder is to the right on a steep face yet to be cleaned and climbed but its gonna be cool...

name: Rusty van
description: Start on a side pull and a high crimp, get a high foot and fire up to another crimp then bump your right hand in to a sloped edge, then make a big cross with your right hand to the jug. Top out on jugs. Using the tree at the top gives it v8- but if you don't use the tree solid v8. Crux is the start two moves.

name: Stand and be Counted
description: When I first found The Dugout this is the line that popped out at me... Well, kinda... Actually the part that looked so good was the sit start under a 45 degree wall that led to an intersting top out about 10 feet up... This problem as it is, is just the stand start leading to the top out which on its own is the best problem here...    I really hope the sit start goes (it looks about V7-ish), but the rock quality on the first half is kinda junky and so far many holds have broken... I plan to try again at some point but till then here is the problem's stand start...    Stand to the right of the steep wall with one hand on the nice granite out right and one on the crappy rock on the left... Get your feet on and slap your right up to some ok holds... Big move left gets you to a rad solid crimp right above the 45 wall... From here I kept going up and left to the sloping top and slapped my left hand up to the top over my head then manteled... Fun times and the rock is solid and sweet unlike much of the Dugout...

name: Wasted Wilderness
description: Up and to the right of the Weekday Warrior boulder is a low wide boulder... sit start on the far right and traverse to the left as far as you can and top it out...    I had to dig this one out of a lot of moss and lichen thinking it was gonna be rad and it only ended up being ok... Thats what inspired the name cause i though it was a waste to kill all those plants...    so climb it and it wont be wasted...

name: Weekday Warrior
description: On the boulder to the far left you will see a big broken overhang... Sit down and left at a nice big jug and climmb straight up to a pull over the small roof and mantel to the top...

name: Cracks
description: Nice cracks to the top. Start on the right leaning crack into the "horizontal" and up to nice holds up top.

name: Face to Crack
description: Climb the easy face to crack going up. Alittle dirty but very easy.

name: Fish and chips
description: Climb the thin face to the large jug/bucket hold on top

name: One Step Back
description: Sit-start far right on the main face on the knob and jug to the right. Traverse to the top of Fish and Chips.

name: Small Face
description: Climb the very easy face

name: Center overhang
description: Climb up and over the center overhang on good holds.

name: Layback
description: Layback the crack on the right side of the overhang

name: Falcor
description: The farthest left usable rock forms a corner with a big loose block on one wall that looks a bit spooky to stand under. this line climbs left of the corner on a slightly dirty looking but fun wall with interesting holds. Sit start low and tech your way up. fun moves all the way.

name: Moonchild
description: This one gets fun points for sure!   Start sitting under the middle of a steep wall.   Pull up in to a big undercling with fun footwork make a big reach to the lip on slopy holds. Get situated find a better hold and pull the mantel. There is a nice crack hold as you pull the last move.

name: Birds Nest
description: Locate the low overhang/Bulge in center of cliff. Usually a Swallows bird nest marks the start. **Please do not disturb in the spring, if possible**    Make a crimp move (also a small TCU) and pull over lip to a large hold. Continue up horizontals to a tree. Usually dirty but becomes better in late season. Protects well.

name: Learning Curve
description: Follow the large prominent arch in the center of the cliff to a few face moves then follow the short crack out the bulge to the right.   This route was 5.7 and I have upgraded it to 5.8 as a hold broke and getting up to the arch is a little tough.

name: Peters Pulpit
description: Climb the awkward crystal pocket right of Learning Curve. Placing protection here could take your good holds. Put together the sequence to stand tall and exit to a good hold and another arch. Place pro and climb to the top of cliff.

name: Unknown Crack
description: This is one of the furthest right climbs on the main face. Climb up a broken corner/ steps to a left to right facing 15' hand/finger crack. Place your pro and step left out on the face. Make some great moves and top out. Sometimes dirty.

name: Y-Me
description: Climb the break in the right side of the slab on to a bulge. Place tricky gear recite the route name (Y-Me) and follow path of least resistance to an over hang with a crack. Pull up through the crack using large hand holds.

name: The Batman
description: Start the climb in a bat hang and from there work your way up and to the right. Some really nice movement here and the start is fun. Of course, if you’re feeling strong you could just campus the star but where’s the fun in that? As of right now the top out still needs some cleaning but as of right now the route ends just short of the top out

name: Sasquatch
description: Start standing left hand on good crimp and right up on the jug. Pull up and squeeze you feet around the arete. Use the crack to gain high feet Gain the sloper up above the lip and get your feet up. Pull on some crystally crimp rails on the slab to finish out.  Slab portion can be heady as you search for gold holds. Looking to add a sit start which may go at a V4.

name: Sasquatch SDS
description: The sit to Sasquatch. High left hand on a decent hold and pinch with your right. A super low foot makes the sit kind of awkward.

name: sLaBsquatch
description: Start with high hands and small feet. Work over the little bulge onto the upper slab section and top-out the boulder.

name: Squatch Crack
description: Same start as Sasquatch but gain the crack and follow good crimps along it left. Top out on the upper slab portion which has a nice two/three finger pinch on a crystal. Fun problem!

name: Grilled-Cheese Crack
description: Top out the boulder using only the crack (hands and feet) till you reach the top. Tops out at the upper corner.

name: Moose Rub
description: Undercling crack/split and find a high right crimp. Step up and pull on jug to top out.

name: Mossy Bloke
description: Start using big juggy undercling left and a chossy right hand hold.  Smear left foot and get a good right foot. Hit the lip and press out to top. I'd avoid the rock at the top as it is not attached.

name: Quick and Easy
description: Start on the corner with the overhang. Make a few static moves or one big dynamic move and top out.

name: Signpost Cedar
description: Start on the blunt arete low. Work your way up with some smearing feet and a couple decent foot placements. Body position is key not to pop off. Use the slopey tip of the boulder to top out or make a small dynamic move to the nice hold just past the tip.

name: Upper Boulder Direct
description: Start at the face and work your way straight up. Avoid using feet on the left arete.

name: Death Star
description: Start with a good left foot on little rail and work your way up the slab to the top. Stay to the right of "Rookie Wookie" the entire way to the top. Do not use huge jug.

name: The Force
description: The crux start involves finding a right mono-finger crimp, left thumb catch, right foot (toe) on a tiny crystal and left foot out to a small cluster of crystals. Use THE FORCE to find your balance and work your way up the slab. Avoid using the huge jug found on "Rookie Wookie".

name: Rookie Wookie
description: Start on some feldspar crystals just below the only obvious jug. Work straight up towards the jug. Hit the monster jug handle and top out.

name: Beaver Spotting
description: Sit start on the right side arete up on a ledge. Move up and right to a funky fun topout.

name: Cobble Maker
description: Sit start the short arete matched on obvious crimp rail. Crank up hard and stand up to top out. Painfully short route, wish it was longer.  Cool boulder that was being cracked into cobbles.

name: Drill Top Cafe
description: Stand start. Pull on using the big wedge. Climb straight up on good hold horizontals. Drilled hole on top helps pull over.

name: London Fog
description: Stand start right of small maple. Climb up the mossy and lichen face and top out over the piece that pokes out over the edge. Could use a bit of cleaning but everything needed was clean enough. Perhaps you’ll find different beta.

name: Scabulous
description: Stand start the arete climb up to the hollow blocks. Top out right of London Fog and left of two black birch trees. Go easy on the blocks. Mellow climbing. Probably a 5.6 but gave e a v0 grade for height.

name: Bombs Away
description: Start on the arete left and right on a crystal undercling. Move up to jug right and work the arete left. Sit into a layback and walk your feet up the arete. Easy top out.

name: Sporadic
description: Start on low hand rail and ring lock with your left. Head straight up using good holds to top out over the mini roof.

name: Geosmin
description: Sit start (basically a lay down) on the big prominent shelf. Good crimp and a throw to the sloped top. Mantle.

name: Ice Crack
description: Start as for Invasive Species except traverse the seam below the roof into the top out for Night Fall.

name: Invasive Species
description: Start sitting on the left side of the boulder. A couple moves through the crack on friendly holds allows you to pop to the lip and eventually mantle to top out.

name: Night fall
description: Sit/crouch start with hands matched on slopping jug. Fire up to good crack hold. Traverse a bit right and head straight up on nubs and sloppers from there.

name: Palmer’s Crack
description: Start sitting at the base of the crack. Head up and top out to the right of the black birch growing from the top. Not using that birch as a hold proved to be the crux.

name: Attack Dog
description: Definitely a bit contrived. The crux of this route is getting established on the start. Start with a good big left side pull, right hand also on a decent jug. Press away from the corner with a good left foot and go for the right hand sloper. Move right foot up, after it is established, go for the next bump up with another right handed sloper. Find your balance and hit a good left hand hold. Lay-back moves to finish the tricky upper part and then its about 5-10 feet of easy slab to the very top!  Get down by down climbing "Left side Arete" or jumping down from the top of "Left Side Arete", onto a pad!

name: Don't Drink the Hemlock
description: Start matching on the blunt arête. Move straight up on some good holds to a decent topout.

name: Get Lost Arete
description: Start on the right arete of the clean slab side. Layback off the arete and smear both feet. Work your way up to the prow for the same mantel finish as "Get Lost Slab".  To get down either down climb "Left side arete" or jump down from the top of "Left side arete".

name: Get Lost Slab
description: Start at the bottom middle of the clean slab side wall. Use a decent right foot (smeared) and pinching some crystals with each hand. Progress upward and right towards the top-out prow. Mantel over the prow to finish.    To get down either down climb "Left side arete" or jump down from the top of "Left side arete".

name: Left side arete
description: This is a two-three move problem. Likely a good quick warm-up before getting on anything else. Start with a right hand around the arete on a good jug, left hand on a sloper and smear both feet. Press off both feet to hit the bigger jug over the bulge and pull up and over.

name: "F**k on"
description: Sit start matched on the crimp rail at the lip. (might need two pads to reach it if you're shorter) Figure out how to pull on with limited foot options. Top out basically straight up using slopey rail features. As well as a couple good holds in the crack, that are good holds but were hard to use with available foot options. Not sure if this is new or not but was a fun and on nice rock.

name: Alexander the Great
description: Probably the most striking route at the swamp. It climbs a thin vertical finger tip crack that has a horizontal sloping crack at ten feet. Start on the huge obvious flake and climb directly up pulling the bulge.

name: Anthropology
description: Start on two obvious chalked holds and your feet out right. Go up and slightly to the left. Topout

name: Bologna Skins
description: Start on two very small crimps. Find an okay right foot and pull on. Move through a series of crimps and slopers to get to the top. Delicate.

name: Cheat Code Left
description: Sit start on a big jug on the left arete. Move up on some good holds heading onto the left face. Mantle top out. Needs a bit more cleaning as things were frozen.

name: Cheat Code Right
description: Sit start left corner on a big jug. Move up and right to a nice fin. Top out on the slopers.

name: Cowabunga
description: Start the same as Tree House/Humunga but traverse across the slopey face to the right side arete. You could also start at Feathered and Wedged and traverse the whole boulder. Delicate and friction based. Fun for an easy one.

name: Crypt Keeper
description: Sit start the same as for Tales From The Cryptic. Move straight up using a sloper and the large hold out left. You can easily escape left but stay more on a straight line if you want more difficulty.

name: Deviled Egg
description: Stand start matched in the large egg shaped dish. Work the sloper arete to the top.

name: Disappearing Act
description: A slightly overhanging sloper arete. Start from a sit on the far right end and work left. The top out was less than stellar but the arete moves were good.

name: Dishes
description: Short problem on a visually pleasing boulder. Start right hand on arete near “slide”. Left hand goes real low on lip by ground. Heel hook right. Move along keeping heel until you can get into the dish. Top out at the drill hole. Contrived.    Alternatively start matched on arete and move up until you can top at the drill hole. V0.

name: Early Exit
description: Start at left end of crack system. Left hand on big jug and right hand in the crack. Work your way up the crack system and top out whenever you cannot continue up the crack any further.There is a problem that works the entire length of the crack, with hands only in the crack-system to the very end. It has been sent. Not sure on the grade.

name: F**k That Tree
description: Would be much better, if it wasn't for the tree. It is still climbable and enjoyable, so I figured I would post it. Start at the far right side with hands in the crack and traverse the crack from right to left. Crux is getting around that tree without dabbing it. Top out after you get around the tree.

name: Feather and Wedged
description: Start standing. Left hand will be by one of the drill holes. Right hand catches friction on a sloper (sort of).  If you don’t start in a specific way this may seem way harder than it actually is. Find your way up to micro crimps that help you gain the jug. The starting hold for Tree House is off but the left arete is on. Go straight up. Crux moves are low, the rest is a scramble.

name: The Fridge
description: Cool looking boulder that looks like a refrigerator except the top isn’t square... Start as low as you can on either arête and work your way to the top. I found myself bumping right a couple times before moving my left. There’s a nice jug that’s a little blind that helps you pull up and over.

name: Humunga
description: Start on the same hold as Treehouse but instead of hitting the big flake/jug trend right up the slab to the very top ridge. Tall but very mellow.

name: Hunting Blind
description: Start sitting using the super cool underclings. Head straight up over the lip using some crimps and slopers. Detached block is on as it still seems like part of the boulder.

name: Joey Bag O’ Donuts
description: Start low matching on huge jug. Move up to big sloper rail. Follow the thin crack up and right using crimp(s). Sloper top out is the crux.

name: Kid Chameleon
description: Start matched on low jug with some good feet. Move up and left and follow arete to peak. You can exit early.

name: No Longer Numb
description: Sit start the crimp rail. Find the good jug at the arete, hold the swing and finish up on Novocain.

name: Novocain
description: Start matching on a good jug. Pull up from sit and work up on good holds to the scoop/dish like lip. Pull over the top. Way fun boulder problem that climbs super smooth.

name: Obey Alexander
description: Stand start at the big flake with great holds. Gaston the thin vertical crack to gain the slopey horizontal feature. Move a bit right onto some crimps and top out.

name: Ornithology
description: A rad and logical line. Start on the obvious sloper shelf, move directly up via crystals and a hard mantle move.

name: Pupil
description: Start matched on the shelf. Move up through crimps trending left to a slopey top out. Commiting top makes it feel spicy.

name: Raby Soldier
description: Start low on right arete using jugs in the crack. Move up the arête using nice holds. Top out can either be on the face to the left or right through the big crack. Going left may be a bit harder. Good for warming up for the rest of the swamp routes.

name: Rest Day
description: Start sitting directly below the water runoff. Move straight up to a tough mantle move. Finish the scramble up the gully.

name: Rhinothology
description: Short and sweet! Start matched on the same jug as for "Swamp Gas" but instead of heading right, go straight up.

name: Rock Garden
description: Start matched on the flake on the overhang. Move up with some nice holds to the lip. Move right to top out on good jugs. The flake is a bit chossy but seemed to be holding me pulling on it well. The rest of the route is on good holds.

name: Salt Lick
description: Sit start on a good hold and climb up and a bit left.

name: Sassafras
description: Sit start on the good low jug. Work straight up the crack and top out.

name: Short Crack
description: Climb the short crack to the right of the Tongue. If it were taller it would be more worthwhile.

name: Slab from the Black Lagoon
description: Climb slab section of boulder to the left of the big crack. The crack/arête is off.  Using small crimps get to the top. Super quality rock and nice holds.

name: Solomon’s Seal High
description: Same start as Solomon Seal Low but use the dish instead of the low fist jam.

name: Solomon’s Seal Low
description: Same start as Zoidberg on the low shelf. Move up to second shelf and then right to the hole. Head straight up to the right of the big dish. Top out.

name: Swamp Crack
description: This boulder can only be climbed in winter when the swamp freezes over. Climb the fist sized crack. Over before you know it. Okay only cause it looks cool.

name: Swamp Gas
description: Stand start at the big jug above your head. Move right to the peak of the boulder and top out.

name: Swamp Man(tle)
description: Start somewhere sitting on the right end of the crack and head straight up to a mantle finish.

name: Swamp Thing
description: Start left hand in ledgey jug and right on crimp inside of the crack. Find your feet. Throw a tall right hand up and to the lip. Work your way through some jugs to top out.

name: Tales From the Cryptic
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder with a great left hand jug and right hand pod in the crack. Head out right to a series of decent holds then head up left along the sloped arete until you can get into the gully.

name: Teaberry Arete
description: Sit start on a nice pocket and whatever else feels good (there’s some options). Small ramp to left is off for feet. Head up the arete and top out to the right of the sapling.

name: The Tongue
description: Climb the tongue shaped feature. Serves as a good down climb as well.

name: Tree House
description: Starts matching on small crimp rail. Smear some feet and get up to next crimp rail. Hand foot match. Stand up to flake/crack.

name: Vernal Equinox
description: Sit start at the base of the "Shark Tooth", with both hands on the rail. Move up from there and top-out.

name: Warped Slab
description: Start right side of "Warped Wall". Static problem working seams to the top-out of this slabby boulder.

name: Warped Wall
description: Some might say this isn’t a boulder problem...  Nay I say to them!!  Unconventional but wicked fun. You must try this problem if you’re here. No reason not to. Get a running start and run up the big satellite dish shaped depression in the boulder.  Get as many steps in as you can before you slap some slopers and friction your way to the very top of the boulder. You’ll probably come sliding down the first couple trys. Looks easier than it is. Threw a v-easy grade on it but it could actually be harder...

name: Zoidberg
description: Sit start on the lowest shelf. Move through shelves to Zoidberg’s undercling tentacles out left.  Instead of bailing out left to the crack move straight up along the arete and top out. Top is a little dirty but doable. Cool features. Exit off to the right.

name: Pac-Man
description: Start left hand on crack under roof. Right hand up higher.  Move your feet along ramp and work your way up some slopey holds to gain the topout.

name: Pac-Man Crack
description: Start at the far right side of the obvious crack line. Work your way across the boulder using only the crack for hands. There is one good jug part of the crack that makes for an easy transition. The hardest part about this climb is finding the feet. Top-out the same at Pacman.

name: Another Little Piece
description: Start on the Big shelf 10 feet right of the center crack. (sit start possible?)  Climb straight up on crimps to a slopey topout.

name: Cross My Heart
description: Hang on the good shelf all the way to left side of the main face of The Broken Heart Boulder.  Pull right to the start of the V0 "Heart Burn." (try to avoid the rock near your feet) I originally started here and added the longer start right after I did it once.  Cross the shelves.  Make a hard couple moves across the fairly blank white stripe to gain the next shelf (crux, awesome!)  Finish up the V1 "Another Little Piece."    Could be a reeeeally hard dyno above the crux on this.  If thats something your into have at it.  Looks easier than Blaow but not by a whole lot.

name: Flatline
description: Far right side of the boulder.  A little slabby fun!  Start one hand on the "Smile" and one low on a shelf.  Or both low, maybe a little easier, or both on the Smile, a lot harder.  Make a hard leap move to a flake, move feet around(crux). Finish up the real slabby top, super fun!

name: Heart Burn
description: Stand start on the huge shelf in the main crack of the Broken Heart, feet on the slopers.  Go straight up the crack on some interesting holds, top out.

name: Heart Rate
description: Easy route. Start with feet on a small shelf and hands on the first major hold above it. Make your way across and up the crack. Topping out can be sketchy with all the debris from trees above since it’s at a downward angle. Just keep that in mind.

name: Left Ventricle of Power
description: Start on the far left of the Broken Heart Boulder on a low shelf.  Traverse right on jugs into the blunt arete. Get a good left and stand tall to a small right hand crimp.  Get a high foot and reach high with the left to a mono sidepull, crux.  Go right to a good sidepull crimp, balance, feet up, get the top.

name: Pass the EKG
description: Start at the Left hand shelf (same as for Cross My Heart)  Instead of finishing the Cross traverse, finish up the main crack (Heart Burn), makes the V0 much more interesting.  A real fun first few moves.

name: Quadruple By-pass
description: Are you taller than me? 5'7".  Then it's probably a V1-, shorter? A V2.  Start on the left hand shelf and instead of going right, go straight up on crimps, two little ones for us shorter folks, or a little and a big for you tall folk.  Top out straight up next to the main crack.  Look for a cool hold on the top you can't see from below.

name: Ride the Lipoproteins
description: Climb the wide crack all the way right, past the tree.  Thought it looked like a fat, short Ride The Lightning...well... it sort of has the same shape, sorta. Anyway it's fun in flip flops that don't fit really well!  I'll get a pic so I can be laughed at.

name: S.E.B. Arete
description: Really good climb!  Sit start on the overhanging side of the arete with hands on a good sidepull, left foot arete, right foot on the huge block.  Pull up to a crimp on the opposite face, (try to avoid the real hollow flake, it's gonna blow soon, I purposely didn't use it) move some feet.  Hit the dish on the edge of the arete, grab the real cool undercling/sidepull (great move)reach for the top.  I topped out over the overhanging side, made more sense, but you could probably go up the other side, might be a little easier.  Walk off.  Watch the branches!

name: The Eye of Horus
description: Start low on arete and work up to the peak.

name: Oracle
description: What a superb line!! Start low on crimp rail and feet on nice pedestal. Move up and left along the crimp rail. Use good feet to lock in. Find the sequence to hit the horn.  Top out.

name: Oracle SDS
description: Oracle with a sit down start. Start on the lower rail to the right of the start on "Oracle". Move left into Oracle and top it out.

name: Soothsayer
description: Start low on crimp rail and feet on a nice pedestal. Move up right to the fragile crimps. End up standing on start holds and use undercling flake up top to finish up left. I’m sure a straight up top is possible too. Good holds are out left though.

name: Mercutio
description: Sit start left on very low potato chip crimp. Right around the arete. Feet matched on nice low pedestal. Stand up to slopey hold. Find the crystals near the lip and pull up and on top.

name: Tybalt
description: Sit start. Match on lowest bulbous jug. Find hidden toe underneath. Pull up to next big hold. Use the arete then hit the top. Kinda tricky for a short problem.

name: JOY
description: This is likely going to go down as a classic climb at Purgatory Falls. Start low in the scoop. Both hands matched to a big jug, feet smeared in the bottom of the scoop. Move out of the scoop and work your way over the roof using crimps/rails. Make a big move to the top and match hands. Mantel move gains the top-out.

name: Phive6
description: Start the same as you would for JOY (low and left side of scoop) but move right through the scoop to the bomber pinch and then top out straight up from the Phive6 graffiti.

name: Armpits
description: The first half of this route hosts the nicest crack on the cliff in my opinion... You will see the crack 15 feet up on a slab, a small pine tree growing at its top...     Climb up easy ground to the right and make a traverse to gain the base of the beautiful (but a little too short) crack... Jam and lock your way up the crack to  the small tree and a nice ledge... Climb the grove above to the base of the overhang with cracks in it... Optional belay here... Climb the right hand of the two cracks in the overhang with a few strenuous moves that lead to easier climbing to the top....

name: Catwalk
description: Catwalk is one of those oldschool "classics" dirty, awkward, and hard in the grade...    An easy line to locate... Look for the big right slanting chimney/crack starting just right of Armpits (5.7) that makes for a moderate line up this blocky section of the cliff... Face climb up 20 feet and get in to the chimney... Make your way up the chimney (harder for big folks) until you can break right on to a face and up to where catwalk meets Heave Ho (5.5).... This is achived be traversing right under a bulge then up cracks to a stance... to gain the summit climb a moderate corner to the top...     Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: The Devil
description: One of the better not too moderate routes on the cliff... Unfortunately the best part of the climb is over quickly...     Climb an easy face to a ledge with a big tree to belay from or keep climbing and do it in one big pitch... Either climb the face directly or move right up more moderate climbing and back left under and overlap... Climb a steep corner to gain the meat of the climb a huge right facing flake that looks fun from the ground and looks even better up close... Make fun moves up the flake past a bolt and to its top... Move left and up to the top...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Face to Face
description: The somewhat blank face in the middle of the cliff.... Start at the too perfect, crescent-shaped, start hold.... Find your choice of slippery feet and make a big move to a crimp and a few more delicate moves to better holds.... Once you can stand on the start hold, you are pretty much done...but it is pretty high, and there is a ton of glass here so care is needed topping out on to the ledge....    Scramble off to the left and down a groove....

name: Heave-Ho
description: A good moderate option up the middle of the cliff with good protection... Unfortunately it can be a little dirty...    20 feet to the right of Catwalk 5.5+ there is an obvious left angling crack that meets up with cat walk halfway up the cliff... Climb the crack and finish on Catwalk when the two routes meet...     I like Catwalk a little more but the wide part on that route can scare beginning leaders a little, this route is the answer...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: The Lonely Bolt
description: A good face climb with slippery feet and small hand holds and crystals...     Start as for Armpits and as you gain the really sweet crack break right to a lone bolt on the blankish face... connect a couple of good holds with a little fancy foot work and tiny crimps as you head straight up and to the right of the small pine tree growing out of the top of the crack... You could protect in the top of the crack and stay right for more face fun or just top it out and celebrate...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Persperation
description: A serious climb for 5.8... be ready...    Climb the first half of Armpits to the ledge below the overhang with cracks in it...    Climb the left hand crack to a very challenging top out on to the ledge at the pine tree... Stay left of Armpits (5.7) up the slab after the pine tree and pull one more moderate overhang to the top...

name: Ultimo, Ultimo
description: Perhaps a little contrived but fun none the less...    Basicly climb Lonely Bolt (5.10) to the bolt but I think you do the start a little more direct rather than going all the way in to the Armpits crack... Continue right from the bolt to a black streak where you can stand on the jug on Minute Man (5.12)... From Here climb straight up to a wide crack (fist jam and #3 cam placement) climb the crack then angle left to the ledge half way up the cliff...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Beehive Crack
description: A fun climb that looks a bit intimidating but interesting from the ground... Not really as much of a crack as the name implies but there are are enough cracks to make it pretty much well protected... With the exception of one move up top which is easily avoided by taking an alternate finish...     Start by climbing up the easy buttress below the right end of the Beehive Overhang to a ledge at the right edge of the overhang... Place some gear and make moves up and slightly left to a stance below a piton, clip it and move up the steep wall to another pin (half driven junk, i didn't bother with it) one or two moves after the pin there is a jug and a nice crack for a cam (conserve your yellow camalot if you do the finish i describe)... Climb up easy lower angle rock to a left facing horn/flake below a steep blankish wall... Start left and climb up and right (PG13) on a horizontal crack, pull up to place a piece(yellow camalot)... Continue up right with a high foot mantel move... Easy slab to the top and a tree to belay... The route is a nice straight shot up the cliff...

name: Beginners Direct
description: A bit scary to look at, it's just dark and big and spooky it climbs ok though...    Just climb up in to the wide crack and thrutch your way up to the tree... Not much else to be said other than the fact that it is often wet when things are wet... From the top of the crack climb up the groove above to its top... Step right and face climb up steep rock with a few mantel moves... and finally make hard sloper moves to the summit...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Beginners Route
description: Another fun moderate right here in Manch...    Start under the intimidating looking black overhang climb up to the overhang and just when you are about to do something absolutely  amazing to get over the roof you change your mind and traverse left in a horizontal crack toward the big tree on a ledge leaving the world to wonder... From the tree climb the groove above you till you get to a steep wall that looks hard to climb straight up... This time move right up a cracked corner to a nice ledge... The top is near, just make a few moves up on ledges and you will find trees to belay from...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Creatures Creation
description: A local favorite for sure... At the left end of the cliff before you get to the slab look for a nice big flake near the top of the cliff on a white face... That is the key feature on Creatures Creation...    Start as for Powder Puff up the layback corner 10 feet right of Little Overhang... Climb the slab above heading for the white face and the nice flake... Mantle a 2" wide ledge and gain the left facing flake... Climb the flake and mantel to a slightly better stance on a small ledge... Climb up and left to meet Tippy Toe Slab and on to the Top...    Some times i pick a route just by looking at one feature on the climb and saying i want to touch that... The big flake on Creatures is like that, you can see it from the ground and you just want to grab it...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Little Overhang
description: There are endless variations to this problem...    start in the corner and climb out the roof gaining a good hold, then a tough mantel and a scramble down... A fun warm up...or project.... There are variations heading out left and out right at the roof but straight up and over is the most popular and fun....    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: The Mangler
description: This is the route that climbs the Black Overhang directly up on to the slab above via cracks and incut holds slightly right of center...    Climb up to the overhang and possision your self just below the crack at the lip of the overhang... Climb nice incuts (that might be reachy for smaller folks) to the lip where you can jam a good crack place some gear and do a sidepull move to gain the slab... From here climb the slab until you can join Standard route climb that to the top with a slightly direct variation at the top at about 5.7...    This route unlike most Rimmon routes doesnt feel like a sandbag... Maybe i did it wrong and all the good holds are "off route" haha...

name: Powder Puff
description: This is my favorite route at Rimmon to solo cause it looks pretty serious but the holds are really good on the steep part... The moves are super fun and there are many places to just sit and chill... On a rope you can do it in one pitch or two depending on what you are looking for...    Start in the corner crack 10 feet right of the little overhang.... Climb the corner to a small pine tree on a nice big ledge... Continue on easy ground up and right to a roof with a ledge and a very small pine tree on it... Climb over the roof and on to the ledge to left of the little tree... Sit on the tree ledge with your feet hanging off, trust me it is a really nice spot... After taking it all in step behind the tree and up on good holds to the top... Belay from a tree or anchors to the left...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: The Washbowl
description: Not a bad way to get your hands in a crack with out having to go too far (if you live near by)...  Climb a series of ledges for 10 feet till you can reach the crack... Jam the nice crack to a slab then up a groove along a crack... At the headwall continue up the crack system just to the left side of an overhang... Mantle a ledge above the overhang and continue up the crack to a slab and on to the top...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Zig Zag
description: This is a cool climb that zigs and zags through the middle of the 100 foot wall following the path of least resistance with a few options...    To start locate the black overhang just right of a big pine tree on a ledge 25 feet off the ground... Step to the right till you see a really moderate grove... Follow the grove to an overhang and traverse left and up the slab laying back and jamming cracks ... There are a few options here you will break right either before or after a roof... The traditional way is to go right before the roof (about 5.6 by modern standards) and up some interesting climbing... If you keep heading up the corner past the roof you break right up a grove to a series of ledges and the top (this is the finish of beginners route 5.5)...    The route can be broken in to a few pitches or done in one...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Angel Left
description: Start at the base of the right hand wall looking up a slab and a right-facing corner.... Follow the corner up till the wall gets steep.... At this point, you can protect well and step right and following the path of least resistance back left and to the top of the cliff.... The  holds reveal themselves as you climb and most of them are jugs of high quality....    The coolest thing is that you can't see what your next move or piece is until it's in your face, so it's a fun onsight....    I once climbed up this route to find 3 teenagers that were so stoned they were having trouble understanding where I had come from...So I told them that I just appeared....    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Angel right
description: Just a variation to Angel but it has a very different feel for sure other than being a little harder..    Climb Angel until you step left near the bottom of the head wall... After the step left head straight up the wall on good holds with a little balancy beta to get from hold to hold... A bit of a hair-raising mantel the way i did it... Fun...    There are supposed to be two routes here at about the same grade only a few feet apart, I cant figure one from the other so just head straight up and climb what looks cool and enjoy...    Photo link: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Angel: On the Stairway to Heaven
description: Another variation to Angel... I swear its the last one i'll post (there are tons) but this one is fun and a major deviation from the other lines I've posted...    As with the other angel routes, climb the low angle start and up the steep bulge corner to a stance to the left... You can go straight up here which is sketchy to lead and a little harder than 5.8 but a fun way to get in to this route... Or do the traverse left and then straight up as for Angel Right but you will quickly find a right trending traverse which you will follow for a good bit till you find a nice exit straight up... Again there are variations that i wont get in to just find the top out that looks fun for you...    Photo link: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Butterfly
description: Another nice moderate up the steep right side of the cliff... This route ascends 20-30 feet to the right of Angel up a nice weakness in quality rock...     Climb a corner leading up to a crack in the relatively low angle rock... Climb this crack up till you are below the intimidating overhanging wall... Traverse right (10-15 feet) to a break in the headwall...Just right of the break Use underclings to gain good holds above and climb straight up... you will see a pine tree at the sky line above... Aim for the tree and pull a tough mantle at the top... fun stuff...     Map:   mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Little Plum
description: A killer fun time... 5.9 by modern standards but who am I to blow against the wind...    Before I ever saw a guide to Rimmon I spotted the pretty right leaning crack near the top with binocs from the parking lot and i was sucked in... On a 100 degree day i went up to find may way up to it... That is a fun way to climb just pick the line and go for it... It was a really good way to spend a couple hours on a hot summer day...    Hike up so you are below the nice crack and climb 15 feet of clean rock to a comfortable ledge... the middle part is a bit wandering but you are following the path of least resistance toward the right leaning crack... Zig zag through the fun jugs and cracks and eventually jam the hell out of the right leaning plum past a small tree growing out of it and up an easy slab to the final steep wall... Climb right through the steep wall on a crack and some holds and mantel the top... Belay from the trees... You can avoid the final hard moves by walking around to the right on the slab...

name: Zero for Conduct
description: Originally an aid line ('The Bolt Ladder' 5.7 C2), this climb was freed by Dave Jacobson.    Easier climbing up cracks, underclings, and edges leads to a stance to the right of a small, hunched over birch just below a lighter gold band running straight up the steep headwall. This spot has been called the 'Hollywood and Vine stance'. The climb follows the gold streak up passing a series of suspect bolts and hangers.    Standing up tall with an undercling (or using the edges on the bulge above) will let you clip the first hanger. A short boulder problem gives way to a thank-you jug and your next piece to clip. It's about to get real. Continue up the overhanging face on small crimps and sloping edges, starting on the right side of the bolt line moving up and to the left side. A few decent holds at the bottom of the dark gold spot below the small roof will let you clip the 5th hanger.  Continue right and then up and to the lip, gathering yourself to make the final tough mantle. A jug above the lip, set back and out left, makes this possible. Up on the slabby edge of the cliff is a set of eye bolts. About 15ft above, another set of anchors and an escape to the top of the Rimmon.    An older guidebook mentions that "this can be climbed with slings and biners (5.9, C2) or a Chouinard hook (5.7, C2)".

name: Gravy Train
description: A great solo/scramble on the left side of the slabs... This would be a much better option for the local kids to solo in there sneakers as it is easy for most anyone... Also a good route to bring super beginners to get them used to the systems and to gain confidence...    Easy to find and easy to climb... Locate the crack on the left side of the slab... Jam the crack or just stuff your feet in and walk up it...    Great rock...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Gripped
description: This line climbs the arete that marks the right edge of the Tipppy Toe slab... A fun route but the top is a little contrived... Of course you can finish however you wish and link it up to your favorite finish in the area...    Start at the right side of the slab on the arete passing flakes to a ledge about 40 feet up... Move right on the ledge then climb to the top with hands on the arete and feet on the face (i like to do variations of this part, choose yor own adventure)...

name: Tippy Toe
description: There are a ton of variations to this "route" because this is the name of the whole slab and it is not broken up in to different lines... All variations are R rated on the lead but there are convenient TR anchors at the top...    My favorite way up the slabs is to start near the middle and climb easy chicken heads trending right tward a left leaning crack above... The chicken heads get smaller as you go... Gain the base of the crack and layback and jam your way to the top...    If you like real friction climbing start in the middle and head straight up to the top... There are fewer holds this way and you can test your rubber...    No matter what variation you are on if you spend some time here you will end up rescuing some unprepared novice or local punk who was suckerd in by the super easy climbing down low...    Map: mountainproject.com/v/new_h…

name: Cold in the Shadows
description: funky and short, this route will leave you cold in the shadows if you mistake a lake spider for a killer jug

name: Grab My Knob
description: with wet shoes squeaking on the rock, the knob is best served with a cold beer

name: Beer Me
description: Left hands starts on slight uneven crimp and right on an incut flake. Just ride the crimps to top out.

name: Bwobnarg
description: Start with both hands in vertical crack, bump to a pinch, then 2 fun slopers to the top.

name: The Native
description: Start hugging arete, lay back and get your weight around as you climb up nice edges to a massive flake.

name: Project
description: Open project.    Not sure of the grade or if even possible.

name: Simond Says
description: Stand start with left hand in 2 finger hole and right on crimp hugging arete, bump to a pinch then bump again to sloper. Gain the jug above and send to the top.

name: Simond Says Sit
description: Sit start version of Simon Says    Left hand starts on nice in-cut crimp and right on pinch, balance up and then follow Simond Said up the arete to topout.

name: Mable and Whiskey
description: Stand start, about 5-6 moves. A bad left hand crimp and good feet launch you to the top jug and mantle to finish. Fun problem but rock is a little chossy. Significant lichen on the west face.  Possible sit start that could go at V5-6

name: Almost Alpine
description: Relatively short climb beneath a large arette on the climber's left. Begin at a somewhat blank section and climb beneath the arette. Crux section may be getting of the deck with another interesting move about halfway up.

name: Bat Cave
description: Five feet to the right of the start of Layback is a nice finger crack that starts ten feet up the cliff climb this to a wide crack/flake. At the end of the crack climb the face past horizontals to the top of the cliff. Excellent route!

name: Inside Straight
description: Toward the right end of the cliff look for the large corner system with a couple roofs in it that starts at a bottomless corner. Gaining the corner at the start was definitely the crux and definitely harder than 5.6. Climb crack to a mantle then up to final roof. Make an exciting move around the roof at a wide crack then follow dirty low-angle corner to the top. Two bolt anchor.

name: Layback
description: Excellent single pitch trad route in the center of the main face. Layback a right facing corner (crux) to a roof then transition to a very nice arching finger crack. At the end of the crack work up and right on the face past horizontals to the top of the cliff.

name: Sunny Slab Left
description: Left of the two bolted routes on the sunny slab. Crux at the second bolt with some thin moves. Some exposure due to the location makes you feel like the route is longer than it is. Optional .4 cam to protect top.

name: Sunny Slab Right
description: Right bolt line on the Sunny Slab. Fun mellow climbing past two bolts to a crack (small cams).

name: Unknown Corner
description: Short and sweet! Climb straight up to the open book, and then climb the corner. Crux is either getting off the ground or exiting the chimney. Climb left or right past the twin birches and then up a dirty, mossy, and blocky groove to the anchor.

name: The Bridge
description: Extremely morpho. Start with right on the arete and left on a small left facing edge. Pull on and compress, slap to a good right hand and move left to a jug. Top out direct.

name: Floralia
description: Start on a good ledge under the roof. Make a big move to gain the shelf. Work up and right through the sloped lip to a jug at the apex of the block. Gorgeous rock but a bit sandy. Still fun to be part of the landscape nonetheless.

name: Panther Mode
description: Start matched on an obvious block. Use a seam crimp on the face to move into top notch compression moves on the arete. Work all the way up the arete to a tricky top out on gritty rock.

name: Party Fowl
description: Climb obvious series of huge edges to the lip. Many variations exist.

name: Ride The Wild Turkey
description: Start standing with left on a good side pull and right on a rounded jug. Pull on perhaps using a heel to dead point to a right handed side pull. Continue up and right on slopers to a big lock off at the lip. Best climb in the area.    The sit start is an obvious project. Start sitting on an edge and use a tiny crimp to navigate into the left start of Turkey. Hard.

name: The American Dream
description: Just left of "Wrapped in the Flag." Start with left on a side pull rail, right on a good edge under the roof, left heel. Pull on and throw for a right pinch on the arete. Make a big move left to a good side pull and establish on the face. Fantastic compression moves.

name: Flying Colors
description: Start in the hueco feature just right of the arete. Pull on and make a long move up and left to a huge sloper. Directly to the top from there.

name: Free Sandwich
description: Squeezed between "Hessions" and "Sons of Freedom"... Start matched on the left sloper of "Sons of Freedom," dyno left to slot jug below lip.

name: Hessians!
description: Stand starting on a right hand rounded side pull and a slimper. Pull on and lunge to a sloped shelf.

name: Plaque of Our Fathers
description: Start just below the plaque on the boulder left of "Taxed." Right hand side pull around the arete and left on a large side pull. Pull on and work your way over  the low bulge using a left handed sloper rail and right handed pinch. Top out direct.

name: The Price of Liberty
description: Start sitting in a perfect mail slot. Pull off the ground into a right hand undercling/sidepull. Work directly up through veritcal compression features and a right handed slot to gain the lip.

name: Revolutionary Prow
description: Under the obvious huge prow on the backside of the boulder, start matched on two half pad crimps. Make a long move to a big sloper with the right hand. Catch a good left hand around the other side of the prow and go straight up to a tricky mantle.

name: Revolutionary Prow Direct (Jon's Variation)
description: Start as for Revolutionary Prow but match the slower and continue directly out the prow to a mantle at the apex of the overhang.

name: Revolutionary Prow Left (Pat’s Variation)
description: An alternate version of The Revolutionary Prow. Less pumpy, but adds a few moves. Start with left hand on the larger crimp to the left of the standard start and right hand the same as the standard start. Bump up and left to the rail and then bring your left foot up onto the jug below the rail. From here you can bump right to the good crimp above the right hand sloper and finish as you would the normal route.

name: Rob's Grunge Crack
description: Climb the obvious Z crack from a sit.

name: Scooped Up
description: Stand start on the edge/jug that you dyno to on "Wrapped in the Flag." Move right to a side pull and make a long move into a a scoop at the lip. Mantle it out.

name: Sons of Freedom
description: Squat starting with left on a crimp and right on a very low undercling side pull. Pull on and grab two perfect slopers. Jump to the lip. Fun. An easier, indirect variation exists if you move right into the giant flake feature and up.

name: Sons of Hessians
description: Start for Sons of Freedom and finish on Hessians

name: Taxed
description: Start on a low edge and climb straight up through large undercling features to a tall mantle.

name: Taxed Right
description: Start on the slimper rail right of "Taxed." Move up right handed to a gaston (second hold on Price of Liberty) and high step to get a left gaston. Move left out of the double gaston into "Taxed" an finish straight up.

name: Vigilance
description: Same start as "Flying Colors," except make a large shouldery move right to a flat ledge. Level up and go to a left handed slimper and slap for the shelf. Fun moves.

name: Vigilance sit
description: start on two crimps lower than the large hueco with left hand a right hand below the large rail cross to the rail and go straight up using the side pull sloper and a crimp to the large jug and top out.

name: Wrapped in the Flag
description: Start sitting with right hand on a very bad slimper and left on the arete. Use a heel to pull up into a good left handed edge. Reposition yourself and dyno to the huge edge on the face. Go straight up to a fun exit.     A stand start can be done at v7/8. Start standing with left on the good edge on the arete and right on the slimper or sharp micro edge. Complete the dyno and climb the rest of it.

name: Illuminati
description: Super fun face climb on the right side of the main face.  When the river is high your basically over the water. Stay right and work up on crimps and finger jams to the top.

name: Chickadee SDS
description: Sit start on high left crimp and right on smile crimp. Make an awkward pull up to good side pulls. Use a dirty finger slot and traverse the lip left to top out as for Nuthatch Chatter.

name: Loon Crack
description: Sit start the crack low amd right. Climb up and left until you can top out through the ferns/polypody (not super fun) or as a better variation climb the face mid way through the crack to top out.

name: Loon Direct
description: Sit start on the edge of the road matched on a big jug. Watch for traffic as you are directly roadside. Climb straight up and finish as for Loon Crack.

name: Nuthatch Chatter
description: Sit start center face of the boulder. Climb straight up. Watch the top out jug. Felt a bit cossy and loose.

name: Pullogna
description: Short. Sit start the arete. Left on great crimp and right on small chip crimp. Make one awkwardish long move to a good arete hold. Top out.

name: Stacked Slab
description: Stand start the mossy slab face using crimps just above waist height.

name: Small Axe
description: Fun compression climbing on abrasive rock. Start sitting with left hand on a bulge in the face and right on a sharp in-cut under the roof. Make a long move out right to gain the arete. Compress your way to a fun mantle.

name: Choss Aside
description: Sit start with both hands on a horizontal on some crimps in the seam. Toss for the lip of the boulder then topout.

name: Destructive Creation
description: Start low on the left side of the boulder on a left facing incut and a barely there right hand crimp. Use a big left foot to pull on and stab for a precise, flat full pad edge. Climb straight up on edges. Best line Willard has to offer.

name: Destructive Creation (Stand)
description: Stand start to Destructive Creation. Start standing or partially seated on a small boulder. Start right handed on a flat edge and left matched on a thin hold next to it. Pull on and grab a sharp sloped side pull and make a very long move to a good but precise slot. Find a way to unwind from that position and climb straight up.UPDATE FALL 2020: With the start hold to the Destructive Creation (sit) now quite a bit bigger than it originally was, the stand is really not materially harder than the full climb.

name: Easiest Way Out
description: Start on a huge ledge on the far right side of the wall. Climb up sharp edges to an easy mantle. May suffice for a warm up... kind of

name: Goosebump
description: Start with left hand around the arete on a rounded edge, right on a terrible non-existent crimp. Pull on using some feet options to a left facing crimp and bump to a large slot jug (right). Cross under/match to connect with face holds and climb the arete to the lip. A super low start also appears possible but would be less cool.   A left variation staying on the left face of the boulder after the bump also exists at a similar grade - see "Goosebump Left" ~v8ish.

name: Goosebump Left
description: Direct version of Goosebump. Start as for Goosebump but continue straight up from the bump move on crimps and slots to an easy exit.

name: Heaven or Las Vegas
description: Start with your left hand on a good flat edge (same edge that you use with your right on destructive creation) and right on a rounded edge slightly below it. Pull on and dyno to the block in the middle of the face. Exit up and slightly right on incut crimps.   You can also exit via the big edge on Tabernacle which lowers the overall quality of the climb but doesn't change the grade.

name: Heaven or Las Vegas Sit
description: Start as for Destructive Creation and climb into Heaven or Las Vegas

name: Heavenly Destruction
description: Start as for Las Vegas, stick the dyno then finish left through Destructive Creation.

name: Painted Like a Warrior
description: Start as for Tabernacle but move right handed to the (far left) slot on tabernacle and then a huge big left-handed jump (power glide!) from slots to jug block. Continue left and exit as for Destructive Creation. Epic line that covers the entire face of the overhang.

name: Tabernacle
description: Start on good slots with a large ledge for your feet. Move up and right to match the next seam and make a long move to a sloped edge. Continue straight up to a big left facing edge and exit directly.

name: Get 'Munked
description: Stand start with low left hand in the crack, a high right hand on a sloper crimp on the lip, and obvious feet at the bottom. Work your hands up the edges and gain a small foot on the face. Throw a heel and press for a good top out. The detached block out left is off for this climb.Nice flat landing and beautiful climb or warmup. There is a possible sit start with low feet and hands on the lower right crimp rail that may add a couple grades. Enjoy the climb and the multitude of chipmunk friends you'll find at this boulder!

name: Forgotten Man
description: Start right hand on a good 3 finger edge and left on a lower sloped edge. Pull on and grab a horrible and sharp left crimp. Jump to a prickly pinch and head straight up the face from there to a deceptively tricky top out.

name: Lost and Found
description: Start with your right hand on the right arete of the block and left on the edge that marks the start of "Forgotten Man." Use a heel or a toe to pull leftward and make a large span (yes it's morpho). Exist as for "Forgotten Man."  It's something else to do on the same boulder..

name: The Mantle Problem
description: Start on a big edge just right of the quartz on polyhedron. Use sharp pebbly rock to mantle and climb the face.

name: Polyhedron
description: Start low in the spattering of quartz with your right in a large quartz slot and left on a big blocky edge. Move left to a lone quartz edge (super unique hold) and move straight up the maze of quartz to a delicate lip encounter.

name: Razorback
description: Start seated with hands matched on a good shelf, move up to slopers and jugs before gaining the lip. Move left and mantle at the apex of the lip on slopers.   Sharp holds but otherwise fun climbing.

name: "Wide Ride"
description: Wide crack. Layback or offwidth grovel to some good jugs at about 10 feet up. Top out on good holds.

name: The Arete
description: Climb the arete on the backside of the boulder from a sit start. Low crux but pretty tricky at the topout.

name: Check Your Pants
description: Climb straight up the crack on the left of the prow.

name: Chockstone Crack
description: Climb's the obvious crack on the left side of the north face of the boulder. Climb past a juggy chockstone and finish with jams or lieback onto the top.

name: Climber's Crack
description: Climb up the large crack in the middle of the boulder. This is the easiest way to get off of the boulder.

name: Comatose
description: Start as for "The Arete" and then move left on bad holds into "Sloper Crimp".

name: Confidence
description: Climb underneath the overhang left of Climber's Crack, then up onto the slab.

name: Deer Proof
description: Climbs the crack and face to the right of "Wide Ride". Start up the finger crack on the arete and move left to good face holds and edges to the top.

name: Dolph
description: Climbs the right arete and lip of the east (overhanging) face of the boulder. Climb up the left side of the flake on the arete and move left along the lip on slopers to the jug of "Jackknife".

name: el espectro rojo
description: Climb up slopers on the right side of the prow, then proceed up and to the right on small edges. A hidden jug at the top will be a relief.

name: Eliminator
description: Sit start the left facing sidepull/rail between Zap Cracks and Climber's Crack. Pull onto the slab above and join Climber's Crack to the top.

name: The Exeter Project
description: This route which stands at about 16-20 feet tall is the hardest route on the boulder and the main route Exeter Boulder is known for. It has never been sent, so an accurate grading cannot yet be provided and the FA is up for grabs for anyone who is up to the challenge.  Start with both hands on the obvious sloper sidepull marked with chalk and climb straight up the prow.

name: The Exetonian
description: Number 12 on the Exeter Boulder topo. The first few moves off the ground make up the definite crux with the climbing getting progressivly easier. This problem has good movement, mostly comfortable holds, and a good landing. One of the better problems on the boulder.

name: Pick Pocket
description: Moderately challenging slab climb. Start on the sloped shelves just left of the pine tree.

name: Poof
description: A few crux moves off the ground on sidepull slopers to a slab top out. The direct slab topout seems to collect a lot of dirt / pine needles. You can move a bit left and go up a secure right angling crack to avoid the slab moves.

name: Puddle of Blood
description: Begin at the crack holds on the arete (same start as Deer Proof). Head straight up the shallow dihedral above on insecure holds to the top.

name: Railroad
description: Great slab climb with a slightly challenging start, then a couple of balancing moves until you can escape up and to the left via a medium-sized crack. The right arête is off limits.

name: Ripples
description: Climbs the flake and face just right of the arete on the back side of the boulder. Start up the right side of the flake of the juggy flake. Make a long reach to a good hold below the lip and then transition onto the slab above climbing a series of cool "ripples" in the rock.

name: Sloper Crimp
description: Is it a sloper or is it a crimp? Sit start left of the arete at a miserable sloper/crimp hold. Bump up to better edges then easier climbing to the top. #18 on the map

name: Tango
description: Start as for Climber's Crack and Confidence but at the overhang, move left into the finish of the Exetonian.

name: Tip Ripper
description: Sit start from the small rock and use the crimps to top out at the hidden jug.

name: Tip-Toe
description: Tip-Toe is a classic V2+ which starts at the sloper sidepull, proceeds left across a slab section under the prow (watch out for the big rock), and finally climbs up using the same crack used for "Check Your Pants".

name: Zap Cracks
description: Sit start below two parallel vertical cracks. Bump to the juggy horizontal crack then work your way up the two vertical crags on the slab above.

name: Boardwalk
description: Start at the undercling. Move up good holds to the top.

name: Off Road
description: Ride the arete to the top.

name: Black Axe
description: Sit start at a finger crack and an ok right hand. Move through positive holds to the lip. Make a big reach to a crimp on the upper slab. Mantle onto the top.

name: FUBAR
description: A funky flake and off-width crack. Sit start the detached flake. Undercling your way out the flake utilizing a good kneebar to transition into the widest part of the crack. Push your way up onto the top.

name: Pixie
description: Start low at a nice horizontal crack. Bump up through great holds to slopers at the lip. Grope your way up to a good left hand hold and pull onto the top.

name: Tangent
description: Climbs the face with the horizontal seams. A thin topout. Sit start in the vertical seam then follow great horizontal edges up to a good hold on the lip. Grab an ok edge, get your feet up and mantle onto the top.

name: Burger and Fries
description: Climb the crack to the top.

name: Extra Pickles
description: Climb edges up the left side of the boulder.

name: Broken Tire
description: Sit start the left end of the boulder at a sharp incut rail and bad feet. Move up increasingly positive holds to the top.

name: Heat Lightning
description: Climbs the obvious left rising crack in the center of the boulder. Sit start low ledge near the base of the slope. Move up to finger crack and then left as the crack turns into a sloping rail. Finish up good holds near the left side of the boulder.

name: Water Wheel
description: Start at the low ledge near the base of the slope (as for Heat Lightning). Establish in the crack then use a nice layback hold to get to the lip of the boulder. Mantle onto the slab above.

name: Filo
description: Climbs the face on the left side of the trailside arete. Easy climbing to a very thin top. Start at the jug/ledge below the arete. Move left along good crack holds. Get your feet up high and reach up to thin holds at the top. Grope up the rails onto the top.

name: Puff
description: Climbs the trailside arete and face to the right. Start below the arete at the big jug/ledge hold. Climb to a sharp hold on the arete, get your foot up and pull up to a nice layback hold on the right face of the boulder. Pull to the top.

name: Shortcrust
description: Climbs great juggy crack holds up the left side of the boulder.

name: Body Slam
description: Mantle the lip!

name: Big Boy Crack
description: Perfect splitter finger crack! Jam the finger crack to the top. Great!

name: Deep State
description: Reach deep for those good jams! Great splitter up the shorter side of the boulder. The crack starts wide (fists) and narrows to hands. Jam to the lip and mantle. Good fun!

name: Beanstalk
description: Climbs the tallest feature here (the "giants feet"). Ascend the gently overhanging face via a layback crack to a finger crack to a juggy ledge. Pull to the lip and mantle onto the sloping summit. Easy climbing to a committing topout!

name: Giant's Toe
description: Climbs sloping shelves up the side of the "giant's feet".

name: Golden Hen
description: Climbs the middle of the "giants belly". Use ok sidepulls to get your feet up and reach for a jug in the horizontal crack. Pull to the juggy lip and mantle.

name: Magic Beans
description: Sit start the great undercling jug. Crank to an ok hold on the lip and then move into the big jug. Get your feet up and pull to the top.

name: Pie Grande
description: Climb the less-than-vertical face and arete on the left side of the Giant's Foot. Smear up the face along the arete to a great horizontal edge. Get your feet up and go to the lip. Don't mess up, the landing is terrible.

name: King Ghidora
description: Fun little corner crack up the front of the boulder.

name: Rodan
description: A one-move wonder. From the sloping shelf, pull to the lip.

name: Green Machine
description: If you like a good (i.e. - painful) heel-toe cam, you'll love this boulder. Sit start off the detached flake. Utilize a sharp sidepull/undercling hold to grope up to bad holds at the lip. Find sharp edges in the thin crack and reach to the top.

name: The Mailslot
description: Fun face climb. Start in the "mailslot" pocket and move left and up a blunt arete to the top.

name: Natural Selection
description: Sit start at the thin edges of the flake. Move up and right along the arete using a jug on the face out right to get up to the top arete.

name: Butter Boy
description: Start at the sloping rail. Smear your feet, bump up the rail and pop to a jug just below the lip. Mantle onto the top.

name: Dutch Baby
description: Good edge to horizontal crack to the lip. Short and sweet.

name: Pancake
description: Good holds up the arete just right of the big pine tree.

name: Shimmie Sham
description: Sharp edges and bad feet take you to the top of this boulder. Start at crimp rail at head height. Move through several more bad edges to the lip.

name: Judge and Jury
description: Climb the tall slab. The taller you are, the better.

name: Slice of Life
description: On the right side of the boulder is an overhanging face with an obvious layback crack. Enjoyable laybacking up the crack to the top.

name: The Tooth
description: Sit start the left side of the face at the edge of the overhang. A big pull to the gaston then move into jugs in the crack to the top.

name: The Tounge
description: A one-move wonder mantling the lip of the short overhang.

name: Candy Slide
description: Sit start at the overhang. Pull into the horizontal crack and crank up and right to a crimp. Pull to the lip and find the small pocket. A tough mantle gets you onto the slab and the top.

name: Trailside
description: A great boulder up through the obvious horizontal crack. Sit start on the low shelf at the overhang. Pull into the horizontal and take it leftwards. Move up through a crimp to slopers at the top. Fun!

name: Tropius
description: Ride the sloping arete up and left to the top of the boulder.

name: Birds of a Feather
description: Finger crack to face holds to a hand jam. This is the boulder problem you can see from the boardwalk and is the first boulder you come to from the trail. Sit start the thin finger crack. Bump out to good face holds then transition into the widening crack above using a nice hand jam to escape to the top.

name: Finger Puppet
description: Climbs the slightly overhanging finger crack on the upper ledge above the swamp. Sit start off the nice ledge about five feet up. Tough jams get you to a good face hold at the lip. Get your feet up and reach up and right to find a good pinch hold. Use this to get your foot up over the lip. Finish with a great hand jam to get you to the top. Terrible landing. Do not fail once your past the lip!

name: Scavenger
description: A nice arete climb up the large boulder at the base of the hill. Layback up the arete to a good jug at the angle change. From the jug transition onto the left side of the arete and follow it using a nice rail to the horn at the very top of the boulder.

name: The Itch
description: Climb the right facing rails to the top.

name: Lichen It
description: Sit start the arete and ride it rightwards to the top.

name: Too Close for Comfort
description: Climb the face and arete on the back of the boulder.

name: Wilson
description: Climb the middle of the rippled face.

name: Wilson's Crack
description: Climb the crack on the left side of the rippled face.

name: Black Magic
description: Sit start under the overhang at a great side-pull horn. Big move to jugs at the lip. Make a tough mantle onto the top.

name: Rambo
description: Sit start the arete. Bumping and bad holds get you to a nice jug under the lip. Slopers to the top.

name: Splits
description: Sit start the blocky face on the uphill side. One move wonder then top out.

name: The Camel Toe
description: The obvious hand crack up the main face of the boulder. Some mandatory jamming gets you established on the easy slab up top. For added challenge, sit start down and left.

name: Dromedary
description: Layback up the crack in the corner to the top.

name: Camel Top
description: Sit start the thin flake. Pull to ok holds and the top.

name: Cow Pie
description: Sit start the pocket in the dihedral. Pull to the crack/seam at the lip. Get your feet high and pull onto the slab above.

name: Cow Tipper
description: Start low on thin flake edges and move up and left to a good hold at the lip. Move left into Cow Pie and finish.

name: Escalator
description: Ride that escalator to the top! Start low and undercling up the slab to good holds on the face above.

name: Milk Maid
description: Short little boulder problem off to the left side of the boulder. Start low and mantle over the lip.

name: Quarter Pounder
description: Start low off the shelf. Grab thin crimps over the lip and mantle to the horizontal crack at the top.

name: Cephalapod Love
description: Balance on the low slab. Grab small finger pockets and pull to hidden jug at the lip.

name: Cosmic Monsters
description: Sit start as for Twisted Tentacle at a good rail. Move up and left to a ledge and mantle.

name: Cthulhu
description: Climb the face through the white band of rock (fingery pocket/crimps) with a big move to the horizontal crack near the top. Mantle over the lip.

name: El Matador
description: Start on blocky sidepulls and squeeze your way up the rounded arete to slopers at the top. Short and burly.

name: The Hydra
description: Climb's ledge holds, jugs and a horizontal crack to the top. One of the easier ways up or down.

name: Klingon
description: Sit start at the left facing layback flake. Pull up into the jug and climb edges to the top.

name: Shoe Goblin
description: Start at bad holds in the quartz vein. Pop to the big ledge hold and then either do a huge lockoff move up to the jugs near the top or commit to intermediate slopers.

name: The Step
description: High step onto the ledge at the base of the shallow dihedral. Press and pull to the top.

name: Twisted Tentacle
description: Sit start as for Cosmic Monsters on a good rail, but climb up and right along slopers. Don't bail rightwards into The Hydra. A bit contrived.

name: Wink and Nod
description: A hard sit start to a terrible sidepull lead to better holds and the top.

name: Beer Belly
description: Start at ok edges and climb up and left to finish at the left arete at the top.

name: Call of Cthulhu
description: Climb the great hand crack to the top!

name: Cultist
description: From the undercling and sidepull slap to the slopers on the lip of the slab. Transition rightwards into ok holds then move to jugs and finish easily up the low angle slab.

name: Cultist Direct
description: A direct alternative the the Cultist. Begin at the undercling and sidepull and slap to the lip of the slab. Mantle with difficulty straight up to good holds. Finish up the low angle slab to the top.

name: Eye of Cthulhu
description: Sit start low in the mini-cave on the right end of the overhang. A hard pull to an ok hold leads to jugs and an easy finish up the low-angle slab.

name: Little Cthulhu
description: Climb up the arete on slopers along the lip of the vertical face. Mantle onto the slab to the top.

name: The Goat
description: Jump to the big pocket jug in the middle of the face. Get your foot in the pocket and make a huge mantle move to the lip or move right to the arete into the top half of the Lion.

name: Holy Roller
description: Climb the arete next to the slab.

name: The Lion
description: Climb the arete left of the slab. A hard start to get established on the arete leads to easier climbing above.

name: Razor Blade
description: Climb sharp crimps at the left end of the boulder.

name: Scoop
description: Climb the scoop feature. A thin layback crack, and good edges give you options to get to the lip at the top.

name: Super Slab
description: A bit contrived. Follow the left-diagonaling features up the middle of the slab while staying off the left and right aretes.

name: Touchdown
description: Climb straight up from the "alley". Start high on sloping holds. Move up into the thin crack to slopers and the top.

name: Deer Hunter
description: Climbs the tallest face of the boulder. Start on ok crimps on the right side of the slab. Move up into the horizontal crack, get your feet up, grab the arete and pull to the top.

name: Blinn's Shin
description: Thin climbing up the center of the face past a thin crack/seam to the top.

name: Fin of Blinn
description: Sit start the arete. Slap and squeeze your way to the top.

name: Magic Dragon
description: Sit start at a low shelf. Work your way up the sharp left arete to a mantle at the top.

name: Black Powder
description: Sit start on good edges. Move up and right through smallish holds to the lip.

name: Cannon Fodder
description: Sit start on good edges then up and left to the arete. Grab the cool undercling and make a long move to a sloping shelf then jugs at the top.

name: Juicer
description: Climb the double aretes to the top.

name: Major General
