description: Sit start in the cave. Climb out the cave and up the double aretes until you can transition to easier terrain on the left arete to the top.

name: Out of the Fire
description: Hard undercling move to a jug. Move up to the lip and mantle.

name: Water Slide
description: Fun squeezing up the unique groove feature. Sit start the double arete and slap/squeeze your way up with some bad feet.

name: Wave Rider
description: Sit start low below the slab at a good right hand sidepull and a small sharp crimp for the left hand. Bump to the jug on the arete. Match, bring your feet around the arete and transition on to slopers on the arete. Mantle onto the slab above.

name: Hemlock
description: Layback up the face next to the hemlock tree.

name: Pine
description: Climbs face holds just left of the big pine tree.

name: Super Sloper
description: Climb out the small cave with bad holds to the top.

name: Bad Demeanor
description: Climbs just left of the arete. Sit start at horizontal edge and climb to the top.

name: The Leaner
description: Climb the right side of the arete. Fun moves working up the sharp arete. Sit start with the arete for the left hand and a bad sloper/pinch for the right. Bump up the arete to good holds near the top. Get your feet up and mantle onto the top.

name: Mr. Meaner
description: Climbs the face just right of the tree.

name: The Girlfriend Problem
description: Good horizontals up the middle of the face to a big lock-off move to the top.

name: No Huevos
description: Sit start below the left arete and layback your way up to the top.

name: Whine and Dine
description: Splits off from The Girlfriend Problem rightwards along a crimp rail to the arete.

name: Dime Bag
description: Sit start the crack. Layback up the crack and move left on the juggy lip to the arete.

name: Hallucinogenic Lichen
description: Start low on good holds right of the crack. Move up and right on good holds to the lip and mantle.

name: Earn Your Stripes
description: Climbs crimps and horizontal cracks to the top of the boulder.

name: Back Door
description: Layback up the crack to the top.

name: Creek Tweak
description: Start low on the left arete. Bump up to the lip and mantle over the top.

name: Dirty Dog
description: Sit start a cool flake feature on the right side of the gently overhanging face. Move to great horizontal ledge holds then pop to a hidden pocket over the lip. Mantle onto the top.

name: The Hum
description: Climbs the right side of the boulder. Start as for Industry but move right to a cool layback hold and up to the top.

name: Industry
description: Fun moves up the right side of the shorter boulder. Sit start at undercling crack. Grab hidden crack/pocket and fun features to the top.

name: Mr. Clean
description: Sit start in the low cave on a big jug. Climb up and left along jug rail then mantle to the top. Short but sweet!

name: Mr. Green
description: Climbs decent holds up the blunt arete facing the trail on the taller boulder.

name: My-hedral
description: Start low at pockets at the base of the slabby dihedral. Climb up and left along the dihedral to the top.

name: The Stick
description: Sit start at a big jug (as for Mr. Clean) then move up and right to a shallow pocket on the slab.

name: Task Master
description: Climbs shallow holds left of the blunt arete of Mr. Green.

name: Toxic
description: Cool one-move wonder on the shorter boulder. Sit start in the middle of the boulder at a small one/two finger pocket. Big move to jugs then mantle onto the top.

name: Introduction
description: Fun climbing up the arete. Sit start at a good hold. Make a big reach to the arete and transition into amazing grips on the upper arete.

name: Passing Thoughts
description: Climb from the sloper and crimp up bad slopers and balance moves to the top.

name: Sail Away
description: Mantle onto the slab and then follow crack and arete to the top.

name: Skin Doctor
description: Sit start at sharp crimps below the slab. Hard move to the lip of the slab, mantle then continue directly up the tall slab to the top. High!

name: The Sword
description: Climb rails and hollow flakes to a spooky slab move at the top.

name: 100 Lumens
description: Climbs the vertical finger crack between Lime Light and Light Bulb.Sit start as for Lime Light and follow the juggy crack (Black Light) rightwards until you can reach up into the finger crack. Gaston or layback the crack to a very thin topout.

name: Black Light
description: Climbs the right diagonaling crack on the back of the boulder. Sit start at the arete to the right of Green Lantern (as for Lime Light) move up and right along the juggy crack until it ends at a vertical crack (Light Bulb). Layback up the vertical crack to the slab on top.

name: Flash Light
description: This is also the down-climb. Climb the crack and ledge to the top.

name: Green Lantern
description: One of Exeter's classic boulder problems! Sit start to good edges. Use the obvious undercling to make a heroic reach to slopers at the lip. The landing zone goes under water when the brook floods after heavy rains and during spring snow melt.

name: Hat Trick
description: Climbs up the hanging slice of rock. Begin on the hanging rock at a pocket and the arete. Utilize a cool stem to move through the bad sidepull and access some terrible crimps. Bump out left to a good edge and finish up easier terrain to the top.

name: Illuminator Project
description: V8? Start as for Green Lantern. From the good edge below the underclings, move left to a bad crimp. Grab the sidepull with your right hand, get your feet up and pop to the lip. Base is often wet below the crux so plan on attempting this in dry weather when the creek dries up.

name: Jack-O-Lantern
description: Climbs the slabby arete on the back side of the boulder.

name: Light Bulb
description: Climbs up through the big pocket on the back side of the boulder into a vertical crack leading to the slab on top of the boulder.

name: Lime Light
description: Climbs the arete to the right of Green Lantern. Sit start under the overhang on good holds. Move up into a chockstone jug then left along the arete. Thin holds at the top make for an exciting finish.

name: The Warrior
description: A unique journey requiring some burl and some jamming skills. Climb out the low, v-groove roof feature over the water. Exit the roof and gain access to the sweeping crack that takes you to the top of the boulder. Don't fall in the brook! The landing is almost always wet except during extremely dry summers (when Norris Brook completely dries up).

name: Libertine
description: Climbs past the crystaly ledge on nice edges to a nice undercling to the lip.

name: Wholesome DNA
description: Sit start at nice flake holds. Move up and layback (or jam - sharp!) the finger crack for a few moves then move up and right to good edges. Finish up a cool fin to the top.

name: A-Crack
description: Climb the 6" wide crack up and left to the top.

name: Blubber
description: Climb the left side of the boulder. Use sidepull and undercling to hit the lip. Bump to awesome jug.

name: Slick Willy
description: Horrible thin holds up the middle of the face to nice holds at the lip.

name: Crystal Crack
description: Climbs the crack on the right end of the face. Starts with locker fingers!

name: Dark Crystal
description: From the good horizontal edge, move up and left to layback up past the finger tip crack to slopers at the lip. Mantle onto the slab above.

name: Three Ribs
description: Start at the good horizontal edge and follow the groove up and right to the top.

name: Mid Point
description: Start low on the arete at slopers and move up and left to the top.

name: Deer Hunter
description: Sit start at the triangular pinch and move left into the little v-notch.

name: Duck Hunter
description: Sit start the right arete. Grab a little finger crack and top out.

name: No Hunting
description: Sit start the triangular pinch. Move up and right to the arete.

name: Abductor
description: From the low shelf below the arete move up and left into the bad finger pocket. Power up to the finger crack and the lip.

name: Alien Butter
description: Sit start at the jug. Heel hook and mantle up and left into good face holds to the top.

name: Alien Nectar
description: A bit contrived. Sit start at the jug and move up and right along slopers up the rounded arete to a tough finish.

name: Another Betty
description: Sit start at good holds and make a hard pull to the lip.

name: Conehead
description: Sit start overhang. Move up and right to finish.

name: PAAF
description: Sit start at the good shelf in the middle of the face. Up ok holds to the top.

name: Phenomena
description: Climb the layback crack to the top.

name: Tractor Beam
description: Climb the right leaning crack.

name: UFO
description: Short but sweet. Climb the series of sloping rails to the top. Bad feet.

name: X-File
description: Easy jugs up to the top. An easy downclimb.

name: Lithium
description: Follow the crack feature to the top.

name: Empty Chair
description: Climb the arete.

name: Lazer Wire
description: Climb the crack to the top.

name: Tramp King
description: Layback in the corner to the lip and mantle.

name: Apples & Oranges
description: Sit start as for The Orange Peel at a right-facing seam. Move up and right to jugs at the lip. Mantle onto the top.

name: The Orange Peel
description: Sit start at the right-facing seam. Cross right hand into the sharp pocket and work way out left into the "orange peel" flake to a sloper finish. Burly!

name: Pants
description: Climb up into the crack and layback your way to the top.

name: The Pocket Problem
description: Start on comfy pockets. Step high and reach for the big ol' pocket near the top of the boulder.

name: Goose Eye
description: Sit start at a crimpy rail. Up sharp crimps to the lip. Ouch.

name: Hungry Dog
description: Sit start low at crimps. Move left to big move to sidepulls then to the top.

name: Pond Scum
description: Sit start at good holds and climb up along the arete to the top.

name: Ri's Arete
description: Climb's the arete on positive holds to the top. Stand start.

name: Vortex
description: Sit start at the sloping shelf under the overhang. Move up into the nice finger crack above.

name: Beech Nut
description: Climbs the arete on the tallest part of the boulder. Sit start on great holds below the arete. Transition onto the arete and balance to the top.

name: Log Toss
description: Start at the good rail on the slab. Move up sloping edges to meet up with The Quarryman.

name: Quarry Drop
description: A little contrived. Climb directly up the slab avoiding the aretes.

name: The Quarryman
description: Begins at great holds just below the arete. Climb/balance up the attractive scoop feature left of the arete.

name: Tip Trip
description: Start on jugs in the slight overhang. Climb to the lip of the slab then use the thin crack/seam to pull over onto the slab to join Quarry Drop.

name: Band-aid
description: Climbs out the overhang onto the slopey arete.

name: Bandit
description: Climbs from the low ledge under the overhang up through the white band to the top.

name: Bandstand
description: Nice arete features to the top of the boulder.

name: Go for Broke
description: Sit start at the layback crack, bump to the sloping ledge, move into the good horizontal, gain the arete and finish with a mantle over the top edge.

name: Good Vibrations
description: Climbs the quartzy face to the top. From the sit, squeeze and bump your way to the jug. Then pull through some upper pinches to the top.

name: The Gift
description: Fun arete climb with some good heel-hooking action. Sit start at obvious right-facing layback. Squeezing and crimping gets you onto the upper arete.

name: Anything's Possible
description: Awkwardly sit start the arete left of the Impossible Problem. Traverse right into the slot hold at the end of the v-groove and finish on thin face holds above.

name: Bent Wheel
description: Low start at good edge. Work up layback holds out right then up to slopers on the arete. Good holds from there up to the top. Tall!

name: Classic Crack
description: Layback up the arete to access the finger crack. Perfect jams up over the bulge onto the slab above.

name: The Elf
description: Sit start at the flake. Pull over onto the easy slab above.

name: Gridlock
description: Prepare to shred some knuckles! Sit start left side of overhang below the thin, left-angling, crack. Slap left to slopers then jam the crack to the easy slab above.

name: The Impossible Problem
description: V10? V-Impossible? Who knows? Project! This is the crazy overhanging v-groove. Sit start and muscle out the v-groove to an ok slot-hold at the end of the groove. Finish on thin face moves above to get onto the easy slab at the top.

name: Mission Impossible
description: Sit start in the overhang on a pinch and a sloper or bad crimp. Move up and right to the gaston rail then up left to slopers and finish. For an easier finish, bail right at the rail into often wet crack holds.

name: Scratch
description: Sit start to the right of the detached block squeezing the two aretes.  Follow the finger crack and face holds up and right to the top.

name: Silly Sister
description: Harder moves from the sit lead to better holds over the bulge. From the sit, work through the sidepulls and some sharp crystals to good holds over the bulge. Reach to the jug and mantle onto the top.

name: Whine and Dine
description: Climbs the face below the small tree growing out of the crack. From the sit move into pockets and mantle to reach good holds next to the tree.

name: Turkey Twerk
description: Sit start the right arete. Move to sharp crimps and mantle up the arete on the slab.

name: Wild Life
description: Hard move from the sit to the lip. Hold on through sharp slopers up and right and top out.

name: Left Field
description: From holds on the left arete bump up to the top and mantle.

name: Short Stop
description: From a sit, work up the arete to the top and mantle.

name: Thing 1
description: A low, mantle problem. Sit start at the little flake crack. Heel-hook the lip of the boulder and mantle.

name: Barad-dur
description: A bit contrived. Avoids the left arete. Climb straight up the middle of the face off the sloping shelf at head height. Gaston the sharp crimp rail and push to the good hold up and right below the lip.

name: Orthanc
description: Climb the left arete. Start at a juggy shelf move right into a vertical crimp rail. Squeeze the arete, get your feet up and reach to the lip.

name: Ripple
description: Climb the face and arete to the top. Easier the longer you can reach.

name: Tower Crack
description: Layback up the wide crack.
Start at a seam and climb the arete to the top.

name: Air Horn
description: Start low on a good pinch grip. Move right to the arete and finish up to the top.

name: Kid's Corner
description: Layback and stem up this perfect dihedral.

name: Rush Hour
description: Start low at the good edge on the face below the arete. Move up and left to the arete and follow it to the top.

name: Tunnel Slab
description: Climb the low angle slab and crack to the top.

name: 98% Biodegradable
description: Start low and left on two decent sized holds with your feet wherever they're comfortable, toss out right and continue to traverse in that direction using a slew of tricky footwork, including and illusive toe-hook. At the end of the traverse, head straight up the face with a set of technical high steps off of decent holds. Take it to the top, and take care on the committing top out. Pulling on the small tree to the right is definitely cheating.

name: Almost Compost
description: This problem is the finish to 98% Biodegradable, by skipping the tricky traverse the grade is more manageable and the climbing is still enjoyable.   Start with your right hand on a good in-cut crimp, and your left on a side pull. Climb up the face using committing high steps and small holds. Finish as per 98% Biodegradable.

name: Fracking Crack
description: Sit start awkwardly with your hands matched jamming in the crack and your feet anywhere they fit. Stem and jam upward to an easy exit. This is probably a good route to learn how to jam on as the crack is irregularly sized, and finding the perfect jams can prove to be challenging.

name: Hydrocrag
description: Relatively easy climb but fun warm up. Far right side of main boulder in gorge. Large holds with an amazing juggy ledge at the top left. Stay left of crack and fern in picture.

name: Hydroelectric
description: Located almost over the water, with enjoyable big moves between big holds. Start low on a massive jug rail, set your feet and throw up and right to a large side pull, then progress leftward on jugs topping out almost over the water. This route is one of the best in the area, and its exciting setting is not to be missed.   youtube.com/watch?v=ioCGrfv…

name: Man Hands
description: Start with the glorious underhold at waist level amd reach up to the two jugs about 2 feet up from the start. Work your way to the crack, but this is not a crack line so use the crack as a left hand hold only. There is an obvious foothold to the left of the crack. From there, reach up to the jug thats about 6 feet up (this is the crux move), and hop your foot to the wall. Theres a small divot where you can smear while you reach up to the upper jug. The amount of handholds at the top make the finish rather easy.

name: Organic Contaminants
description: Start standing and get your hand into a very flared jam, set high feet and continue up the incipient crack in the slab to the top. Don't fall!

name: Pilot
description: Start sideways on the edge with two jands on the edge, smear the adjacent wall to get your left foot up. Ride the edge u til you near the top. Theres a fingerhold on the upper left where two edges meet and theres a sweet jug on the upper right. They are about a wingspans width from each other. Use these to pry yourself up, then grab the top handhold. Your left foot will use the prior left fingerhold as the final step in the route.

name: Rubbish
description: Start with your hands on two less than great sloping holds, lift your feet off the ground and campus to a massive jug rail on the right (which can be reached from the ground so the route is kind of contrived but I'm too weak to do the full sit start which is probably harder than V6, someone get after it). Throw a heel over the lip and rock over.

name: Slippery when wet
description: Back side of main boulder next to falls. See vertical shelf. Only accessible when water is VERY low. Late spring through summer

name: The Virgin
description: Nice easy ladder to warm up on. Nothing too fancy.

name: A fear of spiders
description: On the far end of the right side of the corridor there starting in the little cave maybe 50-60 feet from the trail, just before the trail forks.

name: Anarchy traverse
description: Start on the same big hold as "In spite of Authority" and traverse left following the horizontal crack on good holds until you hit the junky crack-ish area behind the small pine tree. Topping out is dirty.

name: In Spite of Authority
description: Sit start on the far right with good hands on the horizontal crack and bad feet, move left to a really good hold, set your feet and make a big move up to the slopey jug finish straight up with a questionable and dirty top out.

name: Keep it tight
description: Start all the way left with a right hand on the low ledge and a right hand on the only obvious place to put it. Move right with low feet behind/under the tree to the good slopers and then finish straight up or go to the big lip on the right side next to the huge crack. Do not use the big flake down low as it will likely break off. The top is dirty, bring a brush

name: Pop on Hop
description: Very Dirty, big holds, and kinda tall. head straight up the left end of the wall

name: There's good, there's bad and there's just plain ugly
description: Start just right of the tree growing against the rock on the slopers just above head height. Go straight up. The top, like everything else needs some love and is currently pretty dirty.

name: Tipping Good Time
description: Sit start with fingers in crack, an awkward foot. crank to the top, mantle over the top.

name: Tweety bird's nest
description: Direct up the aerte at the end of "A fear of Spiders" good jug with the left hand and a decent jug/ side pull with the right. Go straight up to finish.

name: Shark Fin Soup
description: Sit start at the left hand of the small roof, tricky moves at start gives way to easier ground

name: And Eeyore
description: sit start on the face to the right of The Tao of Piglet face.    Left hand on the arete and right hand in a side pull. Stand and climb up the sharp crystal face.

name: The Tao of Piglet
description: Sit start as for The Tao of Pooh but crank out right around the arete and up the center of the semi blank face.

name: The Tao Of Pooh
description: Sit start on the obvious jug, on the left side of the arete. Climb straight up the left side of hte arete.

name: Man Overboard, Left
description: Start on the far left side of the boulder, traverse left on good holds, finish as for Man Overboard, Right.

name: Man Overboard, Right
description: Sit start to the right of the roof, on crimps and jugs, move left until almost under the roof and work your way up the weakness.

name: Wing & a Paryer
description: Start as for Man Overboard, Right, once at the roof traverse under it and mantle out on top.

name: Lichen Corner
description: Climb the dirty inside Corner just right of the lichen field until you can't anymore and are forced left into the lichen field.

name: One Crona afternoon
description: Start on the big flake to the right. traverse up and left to the obvious topout. The direct exit is much easier.

name: Overboard, Sit Start
description: Sit start hug the Arete and crank up in to the slab.

name: Overboard, Stand start
description: Stand start the arete and crank up to the slab for a spice finish

name: Slimer
description: Climb the dirty moss cover slab.

name: tic tac
description: Sit start on the obvious jug in the middle of the wall and tic tac you way to the top on a mixes of crimps and jugs.

name: Unnamed Arete
description: Just right of the Arete, start on two crimps, one good foot and crank your way to the top. You can finish at the first ledge or keep going to the top of the cliff.

name: Flee the Hephalump
description: THE LOWER SHELF FEATURES ARE NOT PART OF THIS ROUTE-- if they are used the climb is far easier.    Start just to the left of the big crack that marks the left side of Pooh's roof (pooh's roof is over top of the jars and pans that are out there for kids to play with). Make a move to the obvious sloping feature at about waist hight. move left to the two crimps and then up and left to exit with a few big moves at the top.

name: Rising Tide
description: The right problem.  Start In a cool unique hueco and move right till you can grab a short thin finger crack and climb out.

name: Image Problem
description: Start with a high right heel or toe and a left foot scum. Left hand on a sloper side pull, right on a good crimp.     Make either a big move out left and then switch up the feet, bump up the arete, or make a bigger/harder move to the top (not as fun).

name: A Deja Vu That Lasts
description: Start down on the left corner of the boulder (side facing the river) where the crack begins. Traverse the crack using your heels well before topping out on the right side.     Fun little problem, not sure if it's been done before.

name: Peace Train Traverse
description: Sit start on the far left side of the boulder so that the river is to your back. Traverse right on small rails and side pulls to gain sloper(avoid bumping into the tree), keep traversing around buldge and onto face climb on other side topping out on right side of highest part of boulder. Nice little gem

name: Admiral Nelson
description: A warm-up climb with 2 blocks to climb up to, then an interesting top out.

name: Arête
description: Climb the beautiful arête

name: Height Dependent
description: Start in the middle of the face on a large high jug, choke up and toss for the horizontal below the roof.  A couple thin moves on suspect flakes gets you over the roof.  You can break right at the hard stuff and traverse back in too, v1

name: Linus
description: Stand start on two small crimps about chest height. There is a nice shelf for the left foot, and a small pocket for right toe. from here work directly up and over. The crux in in the first move from the crimps. Finishes really clean. Very fun warm up or beginner climb.

name: Spider Eggs
description: This is a fun problem on some old crumbling granite. It starts sitting with feet on a low rail, a left hand side pull, and a right hand 2 pad crimp. you travel up to a sharp crimp, then traverse left to a sloped pitch. Follow that up and right to the top-out.

name: Fun guy
description: Obvious Slightly off-width crack.

name: Moss Top
description: Good finger locks on the vertical face to a mossy slab topout. Crux is pulling up on the slab. You can move right at the start of the slab and it is a bit easier.

name: Arete
description: Climb the slabby blunt arete to a block on top.

name: Broken Wing
description: Start in the steep crack on the left side of the little cave, climb up till you can reach the 'the wing'.  Now the fight begins, struggle your way over to and onto the wing.  Seems to be low and high beta, thrutchy in either case.

name: Done Before
description: Climb the beautiful steep slab left of the wing and facing the trail.

name: Mossy Crimps
description: Climb the face via some cool crimps, but then move to a potentially loose block.

name: Bulbous Punch
description: Start on the right-side bottom and kick left foot out to a step created at the bottom of a flake. Get body up and work left and up the hump on the left side of the photo. Not many good holds (or I couldn't find any) and tricky foot movements/reaches.

name: Hump Slide
description: Start with a foot on the bottom on the small ledge that juts out above the pine needles. Figure the rest out. Stay on the rock side of the tree up the hump.

name: Riverside Crack
description: Starts on the small ledge just above the high water line of the river and climbs easy slab to an overlap. Get above the overlap and climb the crack to the top. There are some decent face holds next to the crack as well.

name: Emmy-lou
description: Techy face climb....more reliant on footwork than anything else. Spicy top out...watch out for those ferns!

name: Thursday
description: Climb the obvious crack. Great problem to learn hand jamming on!

name: (unnamed)
description: Sit start on good holds follow the blocky holds up to a good lip, work your hands left and either pop a heel or a high toe and mantle up.

name: Dolly Parton
description: Sit start with your right hand on a crimp and your left hand on a slopey sidepull. Compress up the left arete to achieve the  big move to slopey jug.

name: Elvis
description: Sit start with good feet, a right hand crimp on the arête and a high left hand sidepull, if you cant reach the side pull a bad crimp can be used below it, making the start a little harder. Work your way up using the larger sidepull and holds on the arête to a good top out.

name: Laid Back
description: Sit start with good feet and your hands on a fat jug, pop up for the first massive sidepull. Work your feet up and lay back the other massive sidepull to a mellow top out.

name: Laid Back Elvis
description: Same start as Elvis, then traverse left using the great side pulls on the face then top out same as Laid Back. Its all about the foot work.

name: Laid Back Mantle
description: Same start as Laid back except once you hit the first side pull move your feet up and either match the sidepull or use an intermediate crimp to make the move to the ledge, mantle the ledge and top out directly over, do not work left or right.

name: Not So Laid Back(Split a Tip)
description: Sit start with one hand on the triangle shaped jug that is the start of the Laid back and the other on a crimp out left . With good feet go up to the crimps next to the good side pull. Side pull is off. Another tricky move to a crimp out right then throw to the lip. Top it out.

name: Pickin Apples
description: Start with a left and on a deep side pull and right hand on a rail. Grab a large pinch and stretch for the perfect sidepull crimp, top it out from there.

name: Saw Blades
description: Stand start with a small sidepull for your right hand, a Gaston for your left hand and a high right toe move up and right with small feet and interesting hand holds. Fun move to the good lip out right, get a heel up and mantle the slopey lip to top out.

name: And Partner Direct
description: Surprisingly fun moves and continuous climbing that is in character with the other routes on the wall. Start slightly right of the first bolt in a short diagonal groove. Move left up the groove and then straight up the face to a rest in the bottom of the crack of Flying Squirrel. From there, continue up to a horizontal and then slightly right up face holds to a short deadpoint crux and another horizontal. The final few moves are easier but not a giveaway.

name: Bald Man In A Boat
description: Fantastic thin face climb.

name: Barrington Hot Pocket
description: Climbs steep edges and pockets to join the last two bolts on Luna. Sustained.

name: The BBB route
description: Locate a bolt about twenty feet up, strategically placed below the beginning of a thin seam. The climbing here is solid 9- but requires a cool head. There is a piton just right of the climbing at head height from the ground but it would do very little for you if you fell above it trying to clip the bolt. After clipping the first bolt, thin fingers lead to a boulder problem crux and a marginal rest on a sloping ledge. From here you can escape left at 8+ or plug gear in a horizontal, step up to a lone bolt and launch into a pumpy thin fight to the chains.

name: The Day After My Birthday ( is not my birthday mum)
description: Climbs the first 3 bolts of Sicilian then heads right to the overhang. Pull the roof crux then up the steep face to rejoin Sicilian at the top.

name: Desperation
description: This route was recently retro bolted and its a situation where it was well warranted. I've climbed this route pre and post bolts and having solid fixed protection does not detract from the climbing.   Start left of the BBB and climb 10 feet up to the first bolt, move up and left on thin edges and slopers to a ledge, traverse slightly left then back right on steep slopers and jugs to a strange v slot at a roof, layback around the v slot getting your feet on a small ledge below the slot, rest then move up on less than inspiring rock to the chains.

name: Donny You’re Outta Your Element
description: The left most route on the Don Wall.Easy slab to steep face. I heard that John Goodman soloed this in work boots and a vest.

name: Down By Law
description: This is a  clean slab route with a desperately slippery crux. Wait for cool temps or prepare ye to slide. Bolts are a little spaced due to the scarcity of good clipping stances.

name: Flying Squirrel aka The Diagonal
description: Locate a bolt just above small triangular roof at the base of the cliff. Pass the bolt on moderate 10- to thin cracks up to the main diagonal crack. Follow the crack switching to the higher crack mid route. The climbing here is sustained with a show stopper bouldery crux just below the last bolt.

name: Geezer Pleaser
description: Great climbing and one of the most difficult all gear protected routes in New England. The meat of the climb is a V9ish  boulder problem at mid height  involving a series of very powerful opposing side pulls to either a long low percentage dyno ( Will C) or several more difficult face moves (Joe T) to the horizontal.  Blow the last bit before the horizontal and you'll take  a 25' - 30' lob. If the small cam pulls, a bomber offset nut will keep you off the ground.     The route tops out so the anchors are set back from the edge. Bring 6' slings if intending to TR.

name: Hymie's Last Stand aka  Karin's Route
description: This is a really enjoyable face climb on  positive holds.

name: Joke Book
description: Start up the wide crack (wide gear not needed)in the right facing corner into a great finger crack.  Turn the lip at the top and run it a ways up a low angle corner system and easy slabs to the top.  Easier to belay someone or set a gear TR above the vertical corner.

name: Luna
description: Sustained  crimps and slopers, long reaches and multiple cruxes. Decent rest at the undercling. Originally rated 12a in 1992, consensus seems to be 2 or 3 letter grades higher.    My apology to those sandbagged.

name: Moe Howard Died For Our Sins
description: Great rock and  wonderful varied climbing  easily make this one of the best of the harder lines at Stonehouse. The route starts with a difficult  sequence of underclings and crimps  past 1 pin and 3 bolts to a sit down rest . Above, climb smooth marble like stone on good edges.

name: The Nose
description: The obvious rounded arete that forms the center divider for the cliff.     Mostly if not all fixed gear (bolts and pins)

name: The Roost
description: The right facing corner in the middle of Stonehouse's main face.    Well protected laybacking up the full length of the corner. Starts at the base of the corner, follow up on laybacks and face holds behind and above you. Belay from a tree further back, or hand sized cams just below the top.    A variation goes from near the top of the corner, but traverses right after the vertical step. Makes for really fun, airy moves out right on good feet, with hands in a horizontal. Good gear, good hands, and an airy feeling. Great climbing, finish as for The Nose (5.8).

name: Shut The F**k Up, Donny
description: Easy slab to fun face climbing just right of the arching crack.

name: Sicilian Olympics
description: Probably the best route on the Luna wall. The route originally climbed right at the 4th bolt into the shallow dihedral,12d. Going straight up here keeps the grade at about 12b and is more consistent with the rest of the route.

name: Son of Snake
description: Just to the right of The Roost there is a bulge, climb over that  with no pro stopping you from hitting the ground, though you can place a cam so that you don't pull you and your belay off the ledge. Continue straight up the slab to the top of the cliff.

name: Swiss Movement
description: Climb straight up thin face holds up to some bigger ledges above.

name: Unknown Route
description: Thin sustained climbing around the corner from the roost and the nose. Great protection once you are on the route, a runout scramble from climber's left to reach the first bolt. Thin hands and feet until you reach the crux about 2/3 of the way up, where feet get even thinner.  Dirty last couple of moves to the anchor.

name: Stinky Crimps
description: High ball boulder with an iffy landing in a beautiful location. Start at the horizontal jug crack and move up and to the right to the first stinky crimp. Long reach to the flake. More stinky crimps to the top. Crimps are brittle and sharp. Don't end up in the soup.

name: Bloody Fingers
description: Sit start on the crack leading up to the crack. Use a few nice (sharp) holds to get your left hand high into the crack. Slowly work your way up the crack and top out

name: The Abyss
description: Climb just the left arete of The Dark Slot to the top for an exciting top out.

name: Black Magic
description: Start the same way you would for White Magic. Instead of going straight up head out right towards a crack, and continue up that to the top.

name: Black Magic right
description: This variation adds a few great moves to Black Magic and tops out around the corner on the tallest point of the boulder, making an already-excellent problem truly superb.    Start as for White/Black Magic, work right past the crack to a rail just above the lip of the roof, then continue rightward to holds at the lip and feet on tiny edges. Gaston or cross into a layback on the left-facing crack, then reach around the prow to the right facing crack. Work your feet up, make a big move to the lip of the boulder, and float the chill but high topout.    Feels about as hard as Magician, which to me is solid V6. Both of these problems would be sought-after classics if they were at Pawtuckaway.

name: Captain No-hands
description: This is the left most climb worth pointing out on the boulder.

name: The Crack
description: Fun if you like wide cracks! Securely wiggle your way up the big crack in the alcove.

name: The Dark Slot
description: Crawl into the wide crack next to Dolph's Traverse (to the left) and Palm Reader ( to the right), then utilize squeeze chimney or off-width techniques to huff and puff your way to the top.

name: Dolph's Traverse
description: Begin this climb in down in the ditch in front of the main boulder. Climb the left side of the wide crack with some lie-back moves working up to a solid   hold near to top deep in the crack. From here work your way left out of the crack and over the rock below in front of the boulder to some good jug holds. Slap/mantle out up and over for the top out.

name: Fireball
description: Stand start up a left hand side pull.

name: Friction Fiction
description: Sit start to the right of Fireball on a small right facing flake and head up to the top of the boulder on what little you find for holds.

name: Fun Ladder
description: A super fun V0! Style your way up the right side of the wide crack that is "The Crack". While the climbing is not particularly interesting, there is a definite feeling of joy that comes with doing this problem.

name: Lunch or Plunger
description: Climb from The Wiz, into Lunge or Plunge. Adds some length to Lunge or Plunge, and seemingly ups the difficulty.

name: Lunge or Plunge
description: This super awesome route takes a hard line up the face to the right of the Wiz (left of Fun Ladder). Start sitting (you'll probably be sitting on the knee-height block) and utilize some funky crimps to reach a couple of decent edges before you set your feet high and try to catch the elusive lip of the boulder. Hard and fun problem for sure!

name: Magic Carpet Ride
description: Start low and right of Shorty, slap up the lip on sloping holds until you reach Shorty, then top out.

name: Magician
description: Starting just to the right of Fun Ladder, use a pinch with the left hand to gain some awful feet and a high gaston continue up and right into a scoop for an exciting finish

name: Man Handle
description: Sit start atop a boulder. Grab the sloping rail and continue up on progressively more positive holds, shuffling your feet up for an exciting mantle at the end.

name: Palm Reader
description: Start on a good sidepull just right of the Dark Slot, mellower moves will lead into a hard sloping top out.

name: Pimp My Ride
description: Sit start to the right of Palm Reader, and cruise up the arete.

name: Redemption
description: Someone, please correct me if this is already a route, but you start to the left of Man Handle with left hand on a side pull crimp and right hand on a nice jug with a standing start (I also use a toe hook for my right foot). then traverse right and up for a tricky top out similar to Man Handle. The start is a bit sketchy but altogether a very fun route.

name: Redemption Arc
description: Start same as Redemption, but travel right to the feature and around into the corner to a crimp that is right above the crack. Getting into the crack with the right beta is not bad but with bad beta, this could be the crux and is where the landing is the worse. From here go down the large crack and out right onto some good side pulls. Get higher feet and throw for a sloper and match to completer the route (crux). If you top out add at least 1 grade maybe 2.

name: Shorty
description: Start low on the arete to the right of Friction fiction and make one pop move to the top of the boulder.

name: Slope Dope
description: Stand start on great feet and a solid left hand. find some friction with your right hand and work up the obvious line diagonal right to a solid jug. Next move is the top out.

name: Sloppy Seconds
description: A very cool route on the main boulder at the Thompson Farm. Start on a pretty juggy sloping hold and throw up left to another jug, from here match your heel to your right hand on the sloper and rock over to some side pulls out to the right.  Easy top out, and a super fun problem!

name: Warm
description: Left side of the arête.

name: Warmer
description: This stand start takes you up the right side of the arête

name: Wet Willy
description: Starts on the large edge of the arête, up to a top right sloper and a high up left edge over the top.

name: White Magic
description: Make a high step onto a rail on the slab, and continue up to the top on some very small edges. This climb is great practice for slab anywhere!

name: The Wiz Kid
description: Same start as The Wiz, but continue out to the left and up on good edges.

name: The Wiz
description: Sit start to the left of the arete near the alcove that harbors Fun Ladder. Climb into the finger crack and top out.

name: Fool's For A Day
description: A good antidote to Reelin'. Straight up the main slab past 7 bolts, a bit run out to the first. Excellent climbing. See the COMMENTs for Beta on the differences between this and "Reelin' in the Fears".

name: Gemini Dreamin'
description: Classic NH 9+, there are 3 sections of 5.10. Boulder up a face to a thin crack, angle right to a ledge then up a finger crack to tree belay

name: Reelin' In the Fears
description: A true death route, I only list it because the climbing is good and on great rock. This line can be tr'd easily, especially after doing Fool's.The crux is 15' from the top and your last gear is literally out of sight.   I was reeled in hand over hand after falling from the last move and only fell 70' instead of a 100'crater. Thanks guys !    See the COMMENTs to "Fools for a Day" for Beta on (slight) differences between the two routes.

name: Standard and Poors
description: It appears the three (3) 35-yr-old 1/4" bolts have been replaced with 3/8-inch Stainless. Not to say this isn't a "bit run out" (since the originals were hand-drilled on the lead from "stances") but at least what pro there is seems solid. With a directional or two it can be Top Roped using 2 ropes from the "Reelin'" Dbl Bolt anchor.Pretty sustained climbing on excellent rock.START: About 20 ft left of "Tao of Dow" on a slab with an arching overlap above. Up the slab and over the overlap, then up diagonally left 20-30 ft (coming within 10 ft or so of "Reelin' ") to a small stance (bolt) then straight up to a steeper swell (bolt), climb over and up the steep slab above (crux?) finally diagonalling left to the dbl bolt (3/8") anchor of "Reelin'".

name: The Tao of Dow
description: A pretty good climb at a moderate grade. Ascends a nice slab with fair-to-good pro, though a little run out at the top.    START: On the slab below, and a little right of, the tree growing from a crack about 20-25ft up. [Var]  Climb the slab, passing to the right of the tree, and climb the slab above (tri-cams and TCU's) to a very shallow flake/left-facing-corner (natural thread possible). Up this and on to a stance (with 1/4" bolt). Now step right and make smearing moves (crux) to the slab above. Move up and left (TCU and/or nut for possible belay and/or directional) and then up along a dike. Continue to the dbl bolt (3/8") anchor of "Fools / Reelin'" ....or, about 10-12 feet before reaching that anchor, step up right and out of the dike to the slab and trees above.  140 +/- ft,  5.8+  PG-13 to R (for the old 1/4" bolt)    Variation: It is possible to start on "Standard and Poors" and move right up the slab to intercept the described route below the flake/corner.  This variation is less well protected and you have to fight the tree's branches.

name: Fight (undone)
description: Start as for Flight, go to second hold of Flight then up and left to a decent rail. From there go out left to arete. From there, this is uncleaned. There are probably two ways to proceed, one being to pull yourself around the arete and top out a slopey ramp. The other would be to keep working your left hand up the arete and then getting your feet high enough to deadpoint/dyno to the lip with your right. Then mantle the lip to top out. Both variations need a bit of cleaning. My guess is the first variation is around V4 and maybe the second V5/6, although it really depends on how good the arete feels once cleaned.

name: Flight
description: One of the purest lines on the boulder (the arete to the right needs to be cleaned and might be better). Grab the kind of poor crimps to start, find a little bump on the wall for a foot and move right to a good rail. Get matched on the rail, set your feet on a couple of smears and go up to the sloping ledge. There is a sweet spot in the back you may have to feel around for. Bring your right hand up to a hornlike feature created by the end of the sloping edge and make a deadpoint move to the lip. The mantle is pretty easy but scary, make sure its clean first.

name: [Redacted]
description: This is the first climb you come to if you follow the traditional approach trail.  3 bolts in a shallow groove mark the climb.  Climb the groove to a ledge .10a.  Then follow a beautiful hand crack out a flare .7 to the top.

name: Bandit
description: This is one of the better single pitch jamcracks of its grade in the Mount Washingtom Valley. Continuous hand-jamming up a round edged crack in a big left-facing dihedral. Exit left to a ledge before the top of the cliff, where you can rap off a tree with one rope, or continue to the top and bushwhack right to walk off.

name: Black Streak
description: Good Barber Wall style face climbing. Sunny! Good early season and late season.

name: Butcher Block
description: This route is directly above OVER DONE. It is the finger crack on the overhanging block with a giant roof. There is an old peg at the bottom.

name: Finally Dunn
description: The route follows the awkward center crack. This route is togher than it looks. The crux is at the top.

name: Heavy Weather Sailing
description: Well, I am surprised no one have posted up this classic. An absolute kicker climb. Powerful and technical.

name: Hercules
description: Climb the overhanging wall past four bolts to a chain anchor. The route is just to the left of Over Done.

name: If Dogs Run Free
description: One of the 10 best routes in NH. Just awesome climbing-technical, good gear with work and strenno.

name: Jungle Work
description: Formerly the hardest 5.10 in NH- brian was way strong. The steep crack(thin and thin -hands) right of Malt Therapy. Pretty hard and watch out for bee's

name: Machina Ex Deus
description: A tough one ! Nice groovy slabbing leads to a hard finger to fist crack up a steep wall. The initial 5.10 groove can be done on it's own with a belay to the left.

name: Malt Therapy
description: A short but worthwhile route. Athin layback crux and good anchors. Bring some brews if it's warm.

name: Over Done
description: A thin steep crack with a few flexible and wafer thin face holds. Tread lightly. A tricky and possibly spooky start protected by a small nut, followed by fun overhanging face climbing and maybe a layback or two leads to a beautiful mantle move from a small left facing corner onto the sloping ledge; though bomber gear is at the climber's hip, a tall climber could hang a draw on the chains above from a jug for the security of a TR on the last moves. The X marked flake, though helpful for a solid left hand, is Unstable and moves when pressure is applied.

name: Standard Route
description: The route starts on the left side of the center amphitheater.  Follow an easy rotten groove till you see a bolt on the slab below nightflyer.  second pitch goes up the often wet painfully obvious gully above you.  Be careful of loose rock and munge.

name: The Understatement
description: At the far left end of the cliff are three vertical jam cracks. This is the route on the right in the corner.

name: Unknown Left of Hercules
description: This route is just to the left of Hercules. Start on the left side of the wall and climb past 2 bolts to an anchor.

name: Way Radical
description: Think you climb 9+ / try this one. Super wild stuff.

name: Carter Ledge Direct
description: P1  Climb up and left to protection at a pine tree 40 feet up. Climb the slab right of a right facing corner with a few trees in it at the start to a left curving arch. Step up then follow the arch left 15ft to a step over to the slab above. (at an intrusion of quartz) Climb to the next overlap with a small pine bush above, pull this and belay at an oblivious 20ft tall thin pine tree in the center of the face below a beautiful white slab. This lonely belay tree can clearly be seen from the base on the horizon. 5.5 150ft [see COMMENT]       P2  Climb the clean featured slab with no protection for 40 feet to a shallow curving arch on the left. Step up to a left facing flake for gear. Climb up and slightly right to a small flake/handhold (crux) then up to the crest of the swell at a small bush that has a fixed piton in a hole above. Climb straight up the shallow dike joining Living the Dream with many tri-cam pockets to a low angled sloping ledge below the sweeping headwall. Belay at the start of the lower angled slab near a small bush with a 20 inch slot that has a natural thread and cam placements. 5.5/6 PG 13 200ft [see COMMENT]      P3  Climb the headwall on pockets of all sizes (Cool Climbing) and continue on passing a few small Jack Pines to the summit of the Ledge. 5.3/4 150ft    Variation: On pitch two you can climb up slightly right (this has better protection) in cracks and flakes climbing just left of Living the dream to the same fixed piton at the base of the shallow dike. Continue up the dike to the same belay at a slot. 5.5 200ft    Walk 30-40 feet back and right and you will cross the hiking trail. Turn right/ down, soon re-tracing your hike in., about 2.5 miles back to your car.   Gear: Light Standard Rack with Tri-cams for the upper pockets is adequate. #2 (gold) Camalot-sized for belay at thread, end of P2 and for "Quartz move" on P1.     FA: Unknown but years ago. (Old pin) Route description as climbed by Brad White and Paul Segal. Sept 2012

name: Living the Dream
description: P1  Start eight feet up on a flat ledge at a small tree 70 feet left of the right end of the base of the slab. Step left then back right to a higher ledge then climb up 30 feet to a short left facing corner with a small pine branch growing out of the top. Climb the corner and then the slab above to a small tree belay on the left.  80 5.5    P2  Climb slightly left and up thru flakes and cracks in a short headwall. Climb straight up the slab above passing a block and thin corners to a belay at three large pockets.  The right pocket is a good thread. 150 5.5    P3  Step left and follow a thin dike feature with pockets up the center of the slab and over a cool wave. Belay at a tree 30 feet higher. 200 5.4 [RHall NOTE: See COMMENT below about length of this pitch.]    P4  Scramble 70 to the top. Walk 30-40 feet back and right and you will cross the hiking trail. Turn right/ down, soon re-tracing your hike in., about 2.5 miles back to your car.     Gear: Light Standard Rack with Tri-cams for the upper pockets is adequate.

name: Sachem
description: Sachem- A paramount chief amoung the Algonquian tribes.   The name was chosen as a historical reference to the Indian Sachems that were known by settlers around the area.  Powerful Sachems included Chocorua, Pagus and Passaconaway, of which the nearby mountains are named after.    This route climbs the right side of the main slab through the obvious headwalls.     P1: start up the featured slab passing a couple small birch trees. Continue up the slab to the left arching corner. Get great gear and pull onto the headwall following a trail of pockets. Pull the crux rock over move onto a lower angle slab and continue up the a headwall with a horizontal crack. Traverse right and belay from the tree. 150' 5.7 R     P2: Pull through the headwall at the crack in front of the belay tree onto the low angle slab (crux). Traverse left passing an often wet crack to the far left of the second headwall. Pull into a left facing corner (second crux) and then trend up and right to a tree ledge with a boulder and belay. 5.9. 130'     P3: Continue up the brown water groove to the top of the cliff and trees above. 5.4 PG-13. 110'    Walk back and right to the hiking trail.     -additional description by Jonathan Garlough

name: Wandering I
description: P1  Climb 40 ft up to a small overlap in the left center of the slab. Start moving up and right to a small bush (hidden yellow #2 Camalot crack) then up a shallow left facing flake near the right edge of the slab. Move up then right over the top of the tree island using the occasional tree for protection. Belay at a small pine tree with gear backup 40 feet below the obvious corner/overlap.  200 ft 5.5 PG 13    P-2  Friction straight up to the right slanting corner crack, (the eye), good protection can be found in the crack as you move up and right.  Layback over a steep swell (crux , # four Camalot) and up the corner above another fifteen feet. Pull left over the corner 10 feet before its blocky end on big holds to a tree belay above. 5.6 80 ft    P-3  Scramble up a low angle right facing corner to a second tree. Above the second tree climb a right curving groove to protection pockets at its top. Move left and up the clean white headwall above that is 30 feet left of the pocketed dike finish of Living the Dream. There are 2 hidden protection pockets (red Tri-cam or sideways nut) in the center of the headwall. Climb straight up the slab above to the highest Jack Pine the rope will reach. 200 ft 5.6 PG 13    P-4 - Scramble to the top. 4th class.    Walk 30-40 feet back and right and you will cross the hiking trail. Turn right/ down, soon re-tracing your hike in., about 2.5 miles back to your car.

name: Blister in the Sun
description: Start the same as Chasing the Sun. Climb up to the small overlap. Pull the blocky overlap and move left to a bolt (bolts right are Chasing the Sun). Continue straight up past a second bolt and gain a right facing flake. Follow the flakes and slab to the left of the pine on the cliff to the trees on top. Belay from trees.

name: Chasing the Sun
description: Climb a cleaned rib on the left to small ledges. Climb up and right crossing a slab (bolt) to a good crack up and right of a small bushy ledge. Step right and climb beautiful 5.8 face (crux) straight up passing two bolts to where the angle eases off before a 6 diameter spruce tree in the center of the face. Climb slightly left up shallow corners to the top (5.4). Belay at a small clump of maple trees at the top of the face.

name: High Voltage
description: This climb is located in an alcove on the far right side of the East Buttress. Walk right around the corner from Out of the Forest to the obvious alcove with short overhanging walls. High Voltage climbs the obvious corner in the center of the alcove.     Make thin moves up the corner to a small roof. Make a funky and hard mantle onto the sloping ledge . Pull the next small roof with another funky mantle. Fire out the top crux moves to bigger holds and end at the ring anchor at the top of the corner.    This climb is short but packs a punch! Lots of movement of various styles!

name: Men in Bright Lycra
description: Start as the same as Out of the Forest, climb the crystals until youre on top of a ledge then break right until you are under a brown slab. Place gear and climb up on the brown slab and run it out until you are under a twin roof (crux).  Traverse right under the roof to gain a finger crack and then surmount the roof. Climb up to a large low angle slab then traverse way left and finish up a blocky arête. There is a strait up version at the top but it was done ground up and didnt have time to clean it on the lead, but it will be done.

name: Out of the Forest
description: Climb 10 to the top of the block under a small spruce tree. Step up and right to a big ledge and you are out of the forest. Step right and mantle (crux? well protected) to a second smaller ledge. Move left and up into the right facing corner that runs up into the center of the face. Climb the corner to where the angle of the face eases off. Continue straight to the top (5.4) staying just right of two small dwarf pine trees. Belay at the big Pine tree on the right.

name: Shisha
description: Start at a large left angling crack in a slab about 15' left of the corner start to Out of the Forest.    Climb the large crack to the tree ledge. Move left to the arete next to a maple tree clump. Climb the face/arete placing gear into a small right facing corner. Clip a bolt and exit the corner onto a foot ledge. Continue up the slab past a second bolt and a mild runout on easier terrain. Finish up a quartz dike in the headwall and finish at the pine tree (shared with Out of the Forest).

name: The Waco Kid
description: P1. Climb a rather run out slab slinging trees for protection where available. Belay from a clump of trees 5.3 60 Feet.    P2. Continue up the slabs through some overlaps and flakes until you get to the head wall. Pull the mantle(Crux. Going left may be easier but dirty).....Now stay "Steady as a Rock" and climb the slab past 4 more bolts to the anchors 5.9 90 Feet

name: 5.7 Link Up
description: 5.7 link up    P1 -Trail of Tears or Go West Young man to bolted anchor. 5.7 120   P2  Trail of Tears or 5.7 PG 13 left variation to bolted anchor. 5.7 115   P3  Climb straight up the slab above the anchor till a left slanting dike is reached. Climb the leftwards leaning dike past a small group of trees until you reach the short center crack (just before the overhanging corner crack) in the left facing wall of the Manifest Destiny corner. Climb the short crack to the arête and follow this to the gear anchor at the flat ledge. This gear anchor takes perfect #2 (Yellow) Camalot size pieces and also a #1 (Red) so I would recommend bringing doubles in both cams and saving both of the #2s for the belay. 5.7 120   P4  Climb the left facing corner to easy slabs above. 5.4 115   This could be one of the original climbs on the cliff and makes it possible to climb the entire center height of White Ledge at 5.7.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start 30 feet up and right of the toe of rock on a small ledge. This ledge can be accessed by hiking up and around a large White Ash tree on the right and then walking back left.     P1  Off the left edge of the ledge climb a short slab to the next small tree ledge. Climb up on a left leaning ramp behind a small clump of trees to a bulge below a slab (bolt). Climb straight up the slab stepping left into a large right facing corner caped by a small roof. Climb the corner and roof, then continue up the slab above (bolt) to a comfortable ledge with a two bolt belay shared with Go West Young Man. 5.7 120    P2  Climb 15 feet up the left facing corner till a step right around a nice arête can be made. Climb the shallow cracks in the slab to a short bulge/headwall. Climb straight over this to a flat ledge then continue straight up and over the overlap just before its right most end to a 2 bolt anchor on the slab above. 5.7 115.     Alternate pitch 2; Climb up and left following corners and flakes around a clump of bushes joining Illusion of Prosperity for 40 then back right to the flat ledge. Move right and up, pulling the large overlap just before its right most end to the same two bolt anchor on the slab above. 5.7 125     P3  Climb straight up the slab above the belay for 20 till above the bush island. Trend up and right over a small dike and shallow left facing corner/step to the first of four significant overlaps with bolts on the second and third. After the third polished overlap (crux) climb up into a small alcove below the spectacular brown headwall. Exit the overhanging alcove on the left using a slanting finger crack. Climb the headwall to a two bolt belay at a small ledge at its crest. 5.9 115    P4  Climb straight to the top past one thin move above the belay (bolt). 5.5 100    This climb can be rappelled with a single 70 meter rope. If you have a 60 meter or less you will need to bring a second rope or walk off. The first rappel is from the pine tree at the top of the cliff and then follows the ring bolt anchors to the ground at the starting ledge. With a single 70 meter rope the third rappel just makes the ledge so tie knots in the ends of you rope and make sure it is centered!  The middle area of left facing corners was climbed before possibly exiting up the slanting dike to the hanging corner of what is now Manifest Destiny. Parts of this climb were most likely one of the original climbs on the cliff. FRA as described; Brad White and Matt Peer Summer 2012

name: Eminent Domain
description: P1  Start at the toe of rock. Climb the left clean streak straight up using small trees on the left for protection to a small thin left diagonaling flake. Protect in the flake (protection difficult) with small cams (Yellow C-3 #2) and small nuts. Layback the flake and then follow just right of the arête of the Old Route groove until you can step left to a two bolt anchor on the left side of a large white flake system. 80 5.8 PG 13     Var. Climb the first pitch of Old Route 5.4 to the same anchor.    P2  Step left and follow seven bolts (crux near 2nd bolt) to a right facing flake (gear) that passes through the break in the large overlap. Step left to a small stance with a two bolt anchor. 5.9 110     P3  Climb the large left facing groove on the right to its top at short twin finger cracks. Climb the left finger crack, then straight up through small overlaps for 40 curving right to the large pine tree belay 5.5 110    P4  Climb straight up directly behind the pine tree past a troublesome overlap at 25 to a small tree clump.  Belay at a two bolt anchor on the left side of the ledge. 5.9 60    FRA - Brad White and Matt Peer Summer 2011

name: Go West Young Man
description: P1  Same start as Manifest Destiny. Start at the toe of rock. Climb the slab via the center clean streak to a bolt at 25. Climb slightly right to a short headwall, joining Illusion of Prosperity at a ledge. Climb flakes and thin cracks up and then left to a tricky step over at the left edge of the headwall onto a slab. Climb the easy slab to the right tree on the big ledge. Continue up the left facing corners above the tree moving slightly right to a two bolt anchor on a nice wide ledge. 5.7 140     P2  Follow the thin finger crack up and left across the entire face till the crack fades out at the top of a large low angle left facing groove under short twin finger cracks, belay here on gear.  Bring many very small nuts and cams. 5.7 120'                                              P3 - Climb the right hand finger crack to small overlaps. Move right through overlaps and then straight up a slab to large pine tree belay. 5.6 60    P4 Step up right from the pine tree belay to two small trees on the same ledge. Squeeze behind the trees to step up and right onto the rock. Climb up 25 to a short wall/overlap. Pull this on good edges below a short flake (good gear) on the top. Wander up the slab aiming for a prominent right facing thin flake in the overlaps. Layback a move up the thin flake then step left to good holds pulling two overlaps to the blocky white arête.  Follow the arête to the woods. It is possible to finish from here by climbing out right and joining the easy slab to the top of the ledge on Manifest Destiny or just scramble up thru the woods to the top. You can also move left and do a short rappel from trees to the anchors on Old Route then linking anchors to the ground in four more single 70m rope rappels. 80 5.7

name: Illusion of Prosperity
description: P1  Start at the toe of Rock ten feet right of the center (Manifest Destinys) clean streak. Climb 35 feet up a thin strip of clean rock (cam at 20) to a flat ledge below the steeper rock. Climb flakes and thin cracks up and then left to a tricky step over at the left edge of the headwall onto a slab. Climb the easy slab to the right tree on the big ledge. 5.7 70    P2  Climb up and slightly left to a bolt on a steep swell. Make 5.9 moves past the bolt to a horizontal shelf with a thin horizontal crack. Move right up steep slab to a hole with a bolt above. Climb left then straight up the center of the slab above getting protection on the right edge in scoops and cracks till a large double overlap with a small right facing corner above is reached. Pull the center of the two tiered overlap with good protection (crux 5.10) then move up and right 10 to the 2 bolt belay on Trail of tears. 5.10 (5.8 PG13) 140    P3  This pitch wanders a bit but picks up some good climbing on the way. Bring a lot of long slings if you are leading with a single rope to eliminate rope drag. The big overlap with the wide crack underneath can suffer from seepage after a lot of rain. Climb up and left for 35 crossing Manifest Destinys slab to a short smooth step. Pull the step at a nose of rock with a tiny one finger pocket on the left (crux, bolt). Climb the slab to the wide crack under the center overlap. Even though the crack is four to six inches wide smaller gear can be found up inside and to the left. Move left for 15or so till a step up on edges can be made to the next shelf. Move straight up the slab crossing a very thin horizontal crack to the next vertical wall. Protect, and then step right into a shallow right facing corner system. Climb this then move right crossing Manifest Destiny again to the steep crack in the center of the left facing wall of the dihedral. Climb the short crack (only 5.6!) to the arête and follow this to the gear anchor at the flat ledge on Manifest Destiny. This gear anchor takes perfect #2 (Yellow) Camalot size pieces and also a #1 (Red) so I would recommend bringing doubles in both cams and saving both of the #2s for the belay. 5.10a 130    P4  Finish straight up on Manifest Destinys 5.4 corner to slab. 115 5.4

name: Manifest Destiny
description: P1  Start at the toe of rock. Climb the slab via the center clean streak to a bolt at 25. Climb to a short headwall, up this (bolt/crux), then left and up to another bolt and a small tree clump belay. 70 5.8    P2  Climb the right side of the large flake to its top at a left curving crack. Step up right to a clean white face with 2 bolts (crux). Climb straight up past a horizontal finger crack and a small black tri-cam pocket to a triangular block. Climb right around the block and up slab above past a bolt to a gear belay at the left end of the large overlap. 140 5.8 Medium cams for the belay.     P3  Stem up above the belay and clip a bolt on the left side of the big overlap. Step left and climb up the slab moving slightly right to the next small overlap. Step over this and continue moving up and right on the slab under the bigger overlap above till 10 feet left of a small clump of trees. Climb straight up over the bulge on white rock (left of an upside-down v-slot) crossing over a thin horizontal crack to join the left slanting dike. Follow the dike left to a spectacular overhanging corner. Layback the corner, (crux 5.8) to a gear belay on the right at a left facing flake. 135 5.8 (medium cams for belay)      P4 - Climb straight up the left facing corner above the belay to low angle slabs that are followed to the top of the cliff. 115 5.4

name: Old Route
description: Start about 20-25 ft left, and 30-35 ft above the toe of rock. (many variations)    [Admin's note- June 2016: Was up on "Tears" 6-24-16 and saw 3 gals who had mistaken the start of "The Waco Kid" (on the "Left Wing" AREA) for the start of "Old Route".  I think the leader got to the 5.9 move on "Waco's P2" and then backed off, sounded like she downclimbed it. (Good for her!) But don't make the same mistake and go too far left. If you are near/at the correct START, you should be able to see the white slab and bolt(s) of Manifest Destiny at about your level and 20-25 ft to the right. R. Hall ]      P1  Climb 25 up a short slab to a tree ledge and follow a vegetated groove to a two bolt anchor on the left side of a large white flake system. 50 5.4    P2  Step right from the belay and layback the entire left side of the flake to a shallow corner. (Great Climbing!) Climb the open corner till a small finger crack crosses it. Follow the fingercrack up and left for 25 then back right to a gear belay in a thin left facing flake. 115 5.7 (medium sized gear for belay)     (Var. #1) Climb up right side of the big white flake above small trees for 15 and cross over left to a fixed pin in the center. Step left into the layback flake and climb straight up to the shallow left facing corner.     (Var. #2) 5.8 PG 13, Layback and climb straight up to the fixed angle piton, then face climb up the left arête of the flake. When you come to where the finger crack crosses the corner continue straight up to protection on the left side of the triangular block and then up and left to the belay flake.    (Var. #3) Climb entire right side of flake as for Manifest Destiny and cross over at the left slanting crack. This is the easiest way to get to the open corner above.     P3  Climb up slightly right 20 to a white jug below a shallow groove with a hidden red tri-cam pocket. From the pocket, slab climb up and left to a small overlap then straight up white face above to a large flake that is followed left to the large pine tree. 60 5.5    P4  Climb up low angle ramp on left for 30 to an open corner. Climb right side of corner up through overlaps to a two bolt ring anchor. 70 5.5 PG 13    FA: Unknown, but a fixed pin and pin scars say long ago. Pitch two and three can be combined with a 70 meter rope and lots of long slings. Route description and P1 and P4 anchors are from Brad White and Matt Peer Summer 2011.

name: Rusty Bolt
description: P2  Start at the first belay of Old Route. Step left and climb smooth 5.9ish slab to a small stance at an old ¼ inch bolt. Climb up and right to a slight rib (crux), and then make a long runout slightly left (5.8) into ground out territory to reach small flakes for protection. Climb up and make a long leftwards traverse under the big overlap following shallow flakes and ripples till you can join Eminent Domain at the two bolt anchor. 5.9+ R/X    Another possible finish is to climb straight up to the small shallow rooted tree. Behind the tree climb over the overlap on the right running it out up the blank slab till the slanting finger crack of Go West Young Man is reached. Move right and up to the gear belay of old route. Finish as desired. FA: Unknown: Have at it!

name: White Riot
description: This is the sporty route on the steep buttress. From the P1 bolt anchor on Trail of Tears move right to the bolted headwall. Start up on crimps with the crux at the second bolt. Continue up the large flakes past a third bolt and pull the lip on jugs. Finish up the moderate slab with gear options for 30 to a tree anchor. 60

name: A Walk on the White Side
description: This route climbs the ramp on the right side of the upper headwall. It climbs to the right of  the final pitches of Trail of Tears.     Start on the halfway tree ledge. Scramble up and left to a small tree ledge below an overlap or start up White Boys, clip the bolt and traverse left to the small tree ledge.    From the small ledge (will have a tree anchor on a pine soon) climb up over an overlap (bolt coming soon) and gain a large flake/crack. Follow the crack to the ramp system that breaks left. Move left onto the face and clip a bolt. Pull over onto the slab and continue past a bolt to a small foot ledge with gear. Pull onto the last slab ramp placing gear past another bolt to ledge and finish up Trail of Tears to the tree anchor.

name: Chinos Brigade
description: Start on the left side of the halfway tree ledge.  Start the same as White Boys. Clip the first bolt on White Boys and move left under the roof to a bolt. Make the crux moves over the roof and continue on the left side of a maple tree up a slab with two bolts. Continue up flakes to a small bulge (bolt) near a dying pine tree. Pull the bulge and continue up the small headwalls placing gear to the trees on top. 195'

name: Heart Attack Man
description: This route starts the same as the second pitch of White Wonder on the halfway tree ledge.     Climb up the white streak to a bolt at 20. (Same as P2 of White Wonder) Move up to the small overlap with gear under it and gain a small tree ledge. Follow the crack system trending right to the base of a large left angling crack. Climb the crack until it ends and then face climb up and left with no pro to the tree anchor on P2 of White Wonder. 100

name: White Boys
description: From the halfway tree ledge locate a bolt on the left a couple moves off the ground. (Also can be used to access A Walk on the White Side, recommended).     Climb past the bolt to a small roof under a maple tree. Clip a bolt and pull the roof (crux) climbing up on the right side of the maple tree. Continue up a moderate slab past a third bolt which leads to a headwall. Climb the left side of the headwall/arête placing gear in flakes. Finish up the slab and flakes to the tree anchor on top of White Wonder. 170'

name: White Wonder
description: This is a full length climb up the right side of the cliff. From the Main Wall at the base of the cliff walk right and uphill to a small alcove with stacked blocks.     P1: Climb the right facing corner on the left side of the alcove to a small roof with a crack. Pull the roof crack and follow the flakes to a final slab with a bolt. Move up to a tree anchor on the halfway tree ledge. 5.9    95       P2: From the halfway tree ledge climb up a white streak in the slab above the P1 anchor to a bolt at 20. Move up to a bushy ledge with gear under the overlap. Climb straight up to a crack and follow the flakes on the left to a small ledge with gear in a horizontal. Step right and pull a steep slab to the large flake system on the right. Follow the flake into the corner system at the headwall and finish at a tree anchor. 5.7    100    P3: Step right to a large ledge. Climb straight up the broken slab with a few gear options to a large pine tree anchor on top.  5.5   60

name: Crash Course
description: This climb is located between Goldrush and Freakers Ball. Climb the thin seam placing gear past a pin and a bomber nut. Join Freakers Ball at the top (bolt) and finish at the bolt anchor.

name: Exclusiva
description: The climb is located in the corner/ face system on the left edge of the overhanging wall on the right end of the Atta-Scrap Wall. Climb the corner/face with increasing difficulty past four bolts to a ledge and a ring anchor.

name: Freakers Ball
description: Freakers Ball climbs the shallow left facing corner to the left of the large corner of Goldrush. Climb up to a bolt then follow the corner angling right and placing gear to a small foot ledge. Reach out right and clip the bolt at the top of Goldrush. Finish up to the bolt anchor above.

name: Goldrush
description: Goldrush climbs the big left facing corner on the Atta-Scrap Wall. The climb looks like a mini version of crack in the woods. Climb the corner up to the roof. Traverse left out the roof and make a hard semi blind placement (#1 worked). Move up and clip a bolt that protects the exciting finish. A bolt anchor awaits on top.

name: Hot Fortuna
description: The climb is located about 50' right of obvious corner of Goldrush. Climb the sustained near vertical face past four bolts to a small ledge. Sling the birch and finish up 40' of low angle super fun 5.5ish arete/crack climbing to the top.

name: Mantis
description: The climb starts left of the other bolted line, Hot Fortuna near the center of the cliff. Climb the shallow groove following a flake to a bulge. Make the crux moves over the bulge on thin crimps and top out. Rap from the tree.

name: Misfit
description: Start in the giant right angling ramp/corner system passing 3 bolts to a ledge stance. Clip a bolt and fight the offwidth to gain a finger lock, slopers, and eventually a jug! Place gear and finish easily to a ring anchor.

name: Rum Diaries
description: The climb is located on the far right side of the Atta-Scrap Wall. Climb the steep wall past 4 bolts on gold holds to a crux at the top. Finish at a two bolt anchor on top.

name: Scetchy
description: The name says it all. This would have more stars but at the crux there is a big loose flake that will eventually rip off. Climb up the blocky start then into the bottom of the flake. Reach high up to the right and grab the top of the flake below the 3rd bolt. Then mantle over the bulge and up to the top.

name: A Bolt Too Far
description: Thin, delicate, face/slab climbing up past 8 bolts.  The bolts gradually peter out as you reach an odd quartz vein that can be followed easily but a little iffily to the top.  Very fun climb some call 5.10, some call sustained 5.9 without true crux.

name: Alice's Ballroom
description: go up a slab past a small diagonal bulge to gain the bottom of a short steep wall and a right-facing corner. Climb the corner and the face to its right.

name: Bear
description: Fun climbing straight up the slab just right of the presently heavy lichened Bear Crossing. The 4 bolts above the dike seem a little left of the best holds and the natural line so the clips maybe a little awkward. If you lead the route straight up by the bolts it feels 5.9, if you use the better holds to the right it's 5.8.

name: Bear Crossing
description: Start directly in front of the large oak tree, about 15 ft Left of "Bear" and 10-12 ft Right of "Golden Slippers".  The current guidebook designates this a "trad" climb...perhaps the bolts are too far apart to qualify as "sport". The book also lists it as "5.8". I thought a bit harder and posted it as such. We'll let "consensus" determine the grade.  Climb up the bolted line (holds brushed 2015), passing the place where a flake broke off (before or after the grade of 5.8, per guidebook, was established?) cross over "Bear" and finish in the "groove".  2018 update - currently the abundance of oak sap from the huge tree has given the lichen plenty of food and the climb is in need of another brushing, although the holds are cleaner than the surrounding rock.

name: Choo choo
description: This is the first climb encountered and maybe the easiest on the cliff.  Head straight up the slab following an obvious line of 4 bolts.  Straying into the off-width on the right probably lowers the grade a bit.     You'll understand the name if climb there long enough in the summer months.

name: Contentment
