I've never ventured higher, though to me it looks like worthwhile crack climbing.    This is an exceptionally fun pitch that is marred only by the condition of the 2nd pitch. I hope some cleaning will yield more fun to complete the Rough Boys experience.

name: Sewer Rat
description: Free climb or hooks off the ground treding right into a right facing corner.  A couple of tricky moves moves and a huge gut busting reach to a suspect pin gets you into the roof proper.  Easy aid gets you to bolted anchors under the roof.  A second pitch is easily possible.

name: Shadowline
description: A real ass-kicker. The original grade was 11B. A hard start and sustained thin fingers up a steep wall. Don't be shocked if this one takes few tries (at least).

name: She's Crafty
description: This route is under the huge left roof and is always dry. It is just to the left of The Argonaut. I believe the first bolt is missing. Climb past 3 or 4 bolts to an anchor. Thin face climbing leads to a v-groove.

name: Stiletto
description: Chimney behind the detached pinacle to the top and climb loose groove to the top of the cliff.

name: Summer Teeth
description: Look for the corner of toothless grin take it all the way out through the roof.

name: Sundog Delight
description: Climb all of Eyeless in Gaza above the anchors to a horizontal crack. Rest in the crack then traverse right to the Mithras anchors. Clip the anchors for Mithras, then continue climbing right finishing on Confederacy of Dunces. Finish at its double bolt anchor.

name: Tar and Feather
description: A very demanding and hard to protect line. HARD fingertip jamming on a slightly overhanging wall.   A hard crack is good to find.

name: Tits Out for the Lads
description: This climb is generally done as the start of Confederacy of Dunces, but the climb is a lot of fun on its own and is a great way to set TR for Mithras or just to do something sub 5.12 at Sundown.    Climb the initial corner with trad gear then move into thinner moves with bolt protection. Exit left out the roof to a hand rail that leads to the Mithras anchors.

name: Toothless Grin
description: Climb an arete into a small corner onto  another face into the bottom of an intimidating looking overhanging corner. Use your stemming prowess to gain a usually damp jug for a quick shake before the crux section. From the jug use  blacks magic to reach a gigantic undercling with extremely poor feet. Lean right into a tips crack or if you have sausage fingers make a heroic huck to the finish.... Then whip while trying to clip the anchor and puke from exhaustion.

name: Vanishing Point
description: There is a bolted line immediately left of Toothless Grin. This route starts on the first two bolts of Toothless Grin and heads left, following a horizontal crack above a big roof. Then the climb veers sharply up, and climbs past numerous bolts to an anchor above the upper roof system.    The climbing on this route is certainly unique, from the pumpy crack traverse, to the technical slab (we used a slab-dyno), to the big tenuous moves before the anchor. Though this route may not be considered classic by everyone, I am aware that there is a small, but somewhat askew, following.

name: Vultures
description: Vultures is the striking thin finger crack that splits a blank wall to the left of the obvious roofs. If you aren't into sport climbing or you want a warm up before the harder stuff, Vultures is probably the route you came here to do.     It doesn't look that bad, really, as the wall is a bit undervertical and there seems to be many options for your feet. The crack is splitter, and it looks like it offers some good fingerlocks. You might think to yourself that Vultures could be a quick tick, that it's massive reputation as one of the harder 5.10s in New Hampshire is a bit overblown.    I thought these things, that is, until I found myself ten feet up, with one gray TCU in, blindly groping at the crack that most decidedly would not accept my fingers. And those footholds that looked so great were just bad small enough, or polished enough, or something, that they did not inspire confidence at all. In a word, I underestimated the crack.    This is what I think Vultures really is: a standing testament to the climbing skill of its first ascentionists and a testpiece that is sure to test climbers from any era.     Yeah, so climb the thin crack to bolt anchors. It doesn't look too bad, does it?

name: Yellow Matter Custard
description: Yellow Matter Custard is yet another perfect sport route on Sundown's Main Cliff. While Yellow Matter Custard retains a reputation for fingery, sharp climbing, the route still requires more than just finger strength. All of those crimps lead to a pretty sizable pump, and the redpoint crux might be managing whatever fatigue you sustained on the lower, crimpy crux.      Start just left of the popular Romper Room, and climb up a series of stacked blocks. Pre-clipping the first bolt is a good idea. At the first bolt, the rock changes to the best Sundown has to offer: fine grained with crisp, good edges. From here, the climb follows a shallow groove with increasingly hard moves that culminate with a sequential crux. The crux ends with a big lock off to a perfect rail.     The climbing to the anchor, while definitely heroic in feel, keeps the send in question until the final moment. It amazes me that this climb was bolted and sent in the 1980's. Despite the lycra tights and the high-top boots, those guys knew a good sport route when they saw one.

name: Counter Culture
description: Just to the left of Phantom there is a crack system that goes through a small overlap at mid height.  Continue up flakes and cracks till you are able to pull a larger overlap top the left of Phantom.  Pull this and establish yourself below a lone bolt on a smooth slab.  Climb the slab to the top.  Hard moves.

name: Hyperspace
description: From the oak tree, up a mossy slab to broken rock, protect and move left.  Climb up short sparsely protect slab to a small roof that has a questionable fixed nut, back this up then move left up a groove and mantle onto ledges and to the anchor.  There is tons of poison ivy on this ledge.  Move up and left from the belay into a v-groove (hard)that's capped by a roof. Pass this into another slot/chimney (awkward) with another roof.  Mantle this then climb more easily up ledgey rock to the top.

name: L-Whop
description: good rock, crimps all the way up a vertical face.

name: Love Crack
description: Climb the right leaning crack on amazing and fun jams to crack's end. Start as low as possible down there. When the crack ends face climb straight up (crux) to a bolt around the corner. Two options exist from here, climb the left face up to the top or continue up the right face and cracks to a shallow tip layback corner and a thin face moves. Lot's of great climbing! Pine tree anchor. I didn't see a bolt anchor.

name: The Object of Great Desire
description: Climb up below the roof on flakes. Follow dihedral and crack to top.

name: Parallel Worlds
description: Recently scrubbed up nicely and in my opinion the better climb at the crag.climbs the left of the two corner systems. we climbed this pitch differently than Handren's book described it and seemed to protect much better. Climb the left facing corner to its near top, finish with a few layback moves and instead of stepping out right onto the face (no gear from what i could tell) we stepped left to a comfortable stance, then continued up to horizontal cracks and good gear placements which lead up and right to the big layback flake feature. another fifteen feet gets you to a two bolt belay. CLIMB THIS ROUTE!!

name: Phantom of the Woods
description: Climb up the center of the groove groove for 40' to a small overlap.  Make a tricky mantel like move to a ledge on the right (5.9).  Make a couple reachy moves on good holds staight up till you are able to traverse easily off right on ledges (5.4 DFU).

name: The Potato Peels
description: This route starts by climbs a number of blocky steps while making use of a few horizontal cracks and medium sized crimps for hand. The crux is the first twelve to fourteen feet as one works up to a clean and deep horizontal crack. This crack is the first opportunity for good gear placement. The reminder of the route is still fairly sustained, but slightly easer that the initial crux moves. The top out is at a significantly sized tree that can be used for a top rope anchor or to rappel from.

name: The Raptor Roof
description: Climb the dike to the base of the roof sporting a 4 inch jam crack. The start is a little mungy but should clean up. Hand jam, fist jam, scum, stack, and whatever else you feel like doing out the off set crack. A nice ledge and a fixed anchor awaits after you pull the lip. You can walk/scramble to and fro this ledge.

name: Repeat Offender
description: It's a variation finish to the first pitch climb "repeat performance" which climbs the right of the two corners.climb the corner to the roof, undercling cool featured holds and hand jambs out left, crank over the roof on great edges (crux), continue on up in to the final corner with attention grabbing moves.Two bolt lower off.

name: Tears in the Rain
description: Start on Suspended Sentence for 15ft and move right. .75 cam protects this part, the rest is bolted. Climb slab to roof, boulder through the roof and climb arete!

name: Gecko
description: Sit start on the nice platform.  Compress both sides of the boulder and smear your feet. Slap up the sides of the boulder like a gecko and top out on the prominent feature.

name: ...Love the Dead
description: Climb the right of two seams with the help of the Arete. Watch out for the tree behind you if you pitch off.*Named after a Misfits song in honor of the NH State bird

name: 2 Pop (on Lichen Slab Bldr)
description: This has probably been done before, but I thought it was a great problem worth sharing.Start matched on the undercling and pop to a good right hand crimp. Use a small left hand pocket and pop right hand to the arete. Topout has not been cleaned, but it is not very difficult.

name: Balls to The Wall (on Balls to walls boulder)
description: Starts matched on lower sloper, with your heel on lower left flake. Pull up and shift your weight onto the heel. Go left handed to the crimp left of the sloper (can be grabbed upside-down if you want to pinch). Then throw the right hand out around the arete, there is a slight dish on the arete. Then go left hand around the other side, foot on the start hold and top out.

name: Bishup Bolder (on Bishup Boulder)
description: Stand starting on two crimps. Make a big move up to another crimp.  Finally, wrestle the slopers and the blunt arete to gain the top out.

name: Blundercling (on Blundercling Boulder)
description: Start on a left hand crimp and a slopey right hand.  Move into the obvious undercling and work your right hand up the arete.

name: Butterfingers    (Butterknife Boulder)
description: Start matched with your hands in a horizontal seam.  Get high feet (it's not Lynn Woods so the separate boulder is not "in") and throw to the lip. Mantel and top out.

name: The Butterknife (Butterknife Bldr)
description: I found some chalk and cleaned boulders in this area, but I don't know how they missed this gem!  It was completely covered in lichen when I found it and quite unclimbable.  After a bunch of cleaning it turned into a great line.    Start standing with your hands on either side.  Then desperately muscle your way up the arete.    A lower start is probably possible and much harder.

name: Extra Warm (Warm-Up boulder)
description: Sit start where the normal “warm-up“ problem is. Instead of going straight up, traverse left on flakes and edges and top out up the far left arete.

name: Face Value
description: Stand start on crimps and climb straight up the face.

name: Hate the Living...
description: Climb the left of the two seams on wall between Tier 1 and 2. Landing is pretty good and the top out is fun.

name: Hook and Jump (Butterknife Bldr)
description: Start with hands matched on a good crimp and a left heel hook.  Make a big move up the arete and match again.  Work your way up the arete to top out.

name: Lichen Slab (on Lichen Slab boulder)
description: Stand stand and work your way up the tips crack.    A sit start is possible and considerably harder (at least V5).

name: Northdivison Memorial Problem  (on Blundercling Boulder)
description: Break out your Send pads and strap them on for a wild ride! Sit start in the small cave and use an excellent kneebar to get off the ground while matched on the undercling.  Establish into the crack out right and find the second kneebar! Follow the crack to the top and mantel out.Word on the street Northdivison only sends with a kneebar pad on.

name: PPE (DGB boulder)
description: If you like crimps, then this is the boulder for you. Stand start with your fingers in the horizontal seam.  Throw big to a crimp.  Bump again to another crimp (depending on your height) and then slap out to the arete to top out.

name: Short and Sharp (on Balls to Walls Bldr)
description: Not sure of the FA. I cleaned the key holds, but further cleaning may be helpful.Sit start on a small left hand crimp, and a right hand pinch/crimp with a good left foot. Pull up left to a sharp crimp, and throw out right to a good pinch. Rock-over and top out.

name: The Trunk (on Bishup Boulder)
description: Pretty sure this is “the trunk” in the Parking Lot boulders section. Sit start on the the steep sloping aretè. Work up and right to the vertical aretè. Figure out how to turn the corner and move straight up. Hard!

name: Warm-Up Boulder
description: The name pretty much says it all.

name: Compression session
description: Sit start at the base with a low left hand hold and an upper right hand in the crescent arc. Figure out the feet, squeeze your brains out and throw up left to a positive rail.  Control your swing and make another big move to the lip of the boulder.  Top out and then go take a nap.

name: Crescent Moon (on Moon Boulder)
description: Start matched on the lower right of the crescent moon feature.  Slap up and right on the blunt arete until you can build your feet high and launch up left to top out.

name: Crescent Moon Dyno (on Moon Boulder)
description: Start matched on the upper part of the “Crescent Moon” with poor and limited feet, and lunge up to the jug up left. Right arete is off.Hard to put a grade on this one since it’s only one move and may vary for climbers of different height, but V6 still makes sense in my opinion, even though Crimp Ladder felt impossible for me.

name: Crimp Ladder
description: Start using a small pinch crimp for your right and a sloping left handed crimp. Figure out your feet and shoot up to small crimps and into a gaston.  Continue through more crimps up and left to top out the boulder.

name: Red Hot Moon (on Moon Boulder)
description: Sit start the warm-up arete. Climb up to the horizontal flake and traverse right on bad feet. At the end, make a huge move right and top out crescent moon.

name: Slippery Corner
description: Has probably been done before since it was cleaned when I got there, but not sure of the FA. Start squatting with both hands on the arete, and  a good right foot. Use very technical feet and balance-y moves all the way up. Felt hard for me, but in cooler temps this is definitely easier, and with perfect foot beta it could go at around V5.

name: Warm Up Arete (on Moon Boulder)
description: Start at the bottom of the arete on good jugs.  Work your way upwards with a variety of holds to choose from.  You can traverse left to exit out on slabs for an alternative.

name: Changing Corners
description: Start down low in the talus hole and start matched on the arete.  With high feet, work up to the sloping block feature and figure out how to change directions and finish by climbing up the opposite facing rail above to top out.  This is a fantastic climb with great movement and makes you think.

name: Crunch Time
description: Stand start matched on the diamond feature at head height. Pull on and traverse left into extra credit. Finish straight up.

name: Entrance Exam (on TG Boulder)
description: Stand starting matched on an undercling jug.  Throw to the right Gaston and use the left side pull to build feet and throw to the lip of the boulder to top out.

name: Extra Credit
description: Sit start on a low rail with a pinch and a sloper, bad feet. Make a move up to good holds then top out on jugs. Really fun!

name: Fingers for Breakfast
description: Slightly overhung vertical face with solid crimping all the way to the top.

name: Maverick  (TG Boulder)
description: Sit start for entrance exam.  Start matched on the incut edge at the end of the sloping rail. Pop up into a gaston on the starting hold of entrance exam. Set the heel and match.  Now climb entrance exam to the lip.

name: Scraps (TG Boulder)
description: Sit start with your feet low under the boulder using a left hand pinch and a right hand side pull. Set your heel and fire up to a crimp on the right of the arete. Use good side pulls to work up and left to the lip to top out.

name: Tsunami (Tsunami Boudler)
description: Fantastic looking boulder that climbs just as well.  Start matched low on an uncut jug on the lip under the wave.  Climb up right and figure out how to get over the bulge and ride the wave  to the top!  A spotter would be handy for the top out due to the tiered landing.Looks like a full sit starting low under the cave would go, adding around 5+ moves into the stand and would be incredibly awesome

name: Tsunami Sit (Tsunami Boulder)
description: And the sit goes! Start low in the cave using the block in the roof for the right and your left on the lowest good spot on the rail.  The next moves are powerful slaps out to the lip using heels and toes to get to the start of Tsunami stand.  Climb to the top.

name: PHOTOS of Boulders in "Tier 1 Right Side of Trail"
description: These are photos of boulders on the right of the hiking trail, before you get to Campground's "Landmark" boulder.Note- In some instances two, or more, different faces of the same boulder may be pictured.

name: Campsite #4
description: Start on the lowest positive rail with good feet.  Work your way up to the lip using rails. Top out.

name: Campsite Crusher
description: This boulder is probably too close to a campsite at the Covered Bridge Campground... unless you're the one camping there.    Start sitting on the arete and burl up on edges and slopers to reach the top out.

name: Campsite Warmup (Camp Boulder)
description: This boulder is a great area to warm up and has many options on how to get to the top.

name: Creakin'
description: Stand start on the obvious flake with some smears, move up to the jug in the crack and make a couple more mellow moves to the top.

name: Flake n Bake (Camp Boulder)
description: Start low on the big flake. Make big moves to reach the finish.  July 2020 Update - The "Flake and Bake" boulder seems to have all 4 sides cleaned (see photos), thus it is assumed there are at least 3 other problems on this boulder. Please make a COMMENT if you have info on these: 1) Location (which face) & description, 2) Grade, 3) Name, 4) FA-er(s) and maybe date of FA.

name: Hypalon (on Stop In French Bldr)
description: Heel hooks, crimps, slopers? What more could you ask for.  This route has it all and then some. Start with your left hand on a side pull on the left face and your right on a side pull in the shallow cave.  Move up and right to a nice half crimp while bumping the left.  Figure out your heel beta and slap up to a small crimp.  Throw around the corner to slopers and work your way to the top of the boulder.

name: Ledge Fund
description: This climb follows the obvious left-facing ledge.  NOTE: The Ledge Fund Boulder is marked "Boulder #2" on the sketch map.

name: Lurp
description: Start on jugs. Make a pretty big move to gain the lip.

name: Measuring Contest (Camp Boulder)
description: Sit start on the right side of the boulder using a small left side pull and right hand on a sloper.  Work your hands up the arete, and figure out how to make the large move to the side pull on the featured face.  Once you're stretched out, slap up to the top of the boulder and top out.

name: No Slopes
description: Start on two good crimps while ignoring the big sloper (unless you want to use it). Pull pon with high feet into the two crimps straight above then move up and right to the lip to top out.

name: Photos of Unknown, Cleaned Bldrs
description: This "climb" is just a holding place for photos of cleaned boulders (or boulders that are naturally clean) that are presently "unknown" as to 1) Grade, 2) Name (of boulder or problem) 3) FA-er(s) , 4) any other data.  [Note, in creating this "route" I HAD to put a grade in, so I put in Vo. By no means do I think the problems in these photos are Vo.  Same thing with the # of stars, HAD to put in something. ]   Please, if you have any of the info above (even if it's just "Grade" because you've done it) leave a COMMENT to this "route" with the info.  Admins get a notice when comments are posted and then the info can be converted to a real "route".

name: Slab Dyno
description: This climb is almost a joke, but I thought it was fun enough to warrant its own page.      Stand up on the slab and jump to the top.

name: Sourdough Starter
description: Start matched on a rail with your feet out left. Work your way up and right to top out.A fun short problem!

name: Stop In French
description: Start on a left hand crimp and the arete. Move up the arete to reach jugs. Top out.

name: Tallboy
description: I did a stand-start, but a lower start or a sit-start could make this one substantially harder. It iss barely less than vertical and is pretty sustained slab climbing the whole way up. It is a little tall, but has a great landing.  NOTE: This boulder and the "Stop in French" boulder are adjacent to each other. R Hall NH Admin 7/17/20

name: Boulder #6 (and "Tipsy")
description: Continuing on the trail past The Prow, you'll come to a notch with stone steps, as you go through the notch a huge boulder is overhead. A few more steps and you're on the East side of the boulder, which is a large as several SUVs and looks as if it might tip with the least provocation. Boulder #6 is located about 40 ft southwest of "Tipsy" (photo, sketch map).  It is sort of a "double boulder" with another boulder leaning against it. Again I've entered Vo because I have to enter something. Please COMMENT with any info on routes.

name: Closer to the Sun (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Sit start the arete facing the trail. Right hand on a side pull on the right side. Left hand on an undercling. Make a weird pull and climb straight up.

name: Cutlass Crack (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Stand start on the sloping ledge at head height. Climb the thin crack straight up.

name: Emerald
description: Sit start the steep face and arête. Begin with a left hand crimpy side pull and a right side pull and a good semi-circle foot bar. Move up to two crimps and the pop to the arête and move up and top out.

name: Field Loss (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Same start as “Phase Loss” but goes straight up on slopers and pinches.

name: In the Black
description: Squat start matched on a decent crimpy edge. Pop up and right to a small crimp. Move feet up and shoot for the good hold above the crimp.

name: Innies & Outies (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Really varied climbing, to pumpy finish. Sit start on Over Current. Move up and right to get feet on the small ramp (Awkward!). Traverse right to the next sloping hand ledge. Hand traverse the sloping ledge on bad feet to the crack. Traverse the crack to arete and top out. Interesting problem.

name: Lion King on Ice (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Would be a great problem until you’re forced to use a scary flake at the crux. Sit start in the small right facing corner on crimps. Climb up and slight right to a sloping ledge. Move left from here, using a scary flake that may or may not explode in your face. Move up to the lip.

name: Man of Fire (On Pelton Boulder)
description: This begins with the same start as Phase Loss, but instead of moving up the seams it traverses into Marmaduke using the lowest seam and good feet. Small crimps or a big move with get you across and finishing up Marmaduke.

name: Marmaduke (On Pelton Bldr)
description: Sit start the flake and climb to the horn. Needs to see more traffic. Classic!

name: Moose Ball Arête (on the Prow)
description: This is far and away the best line at Sundown.  Unfortunately, I was not able to send.  In fact, I'm not sure this line has ever been sent. The landing isn't ideal, its pretty tall, and not exactly clean at the top. A physical and mental test-piece for sure.    There's the potential for about 3 lines on this face.  One that goes up the right arete, one that goes up the left, and one that goes from right to left.

name: More Photos of The Prow
description: I've put photos of the other sides of The Prow in here. Leave a COMMENT if you know a climb's name or rating. I MUST put in a rating, so I've used Vo.

name: Over Current (on Pelton Bldr)
description: Big easy moves to a scary sloper top out. Sit start on sloping ledge. Climb straight up to a sloper lip on the arete. Don’t bail right!

name: Phase Loss (On Pelton Bldr)
description: Sit start on the broad arete, left had on a small flake, right on an ok edge. Move up into the crack and move left to the jug. Find some feet and throw up to a good incut rail. Match and resist the urge to keep going left. Get a high right foot and go straight up the face on edges to the lip.

name: Photo(s) of Boulder # 3
description: Again...just photo(s),   I MUST put in a rating, so I used Vo.

name: Photos of "Pelton Boulder" (Boulder #5)
description: Mountain Project contrbutor "Apelton" writes that he cleaned the climbs on this boulder and always called it " this is my favorite boulder in the area" and has "8 established problems on it". He has added these as individual climbs. THANKS !

name: Photos of Boulder # 4
description: Boulder #4 Photos - as usual, "Vo" was entered, no idea of routes or grades please COMMENT with any info you have.This boulder is actually two, since it is split down the middle with a huge crack, but you won't see this from the trail unless you circumnavigate the whole boulder.

name: Photos of Boulders # 1 & 2
description: Again, Photos ONLY, but I MUST enter a grade so it was "Vo".

name: Short Circuit (on the Prow)
description: Start on good crimps at the bottom left of the boulder.  Work up through small crimps to a good ledge.  Figure out how to work through the upper crack section and top out.

name: Triangle Face
description: Start on a right leaning flake to gain a huge jug half-way up.  Finish to the left and top out.

name: Green with Envy
description: Sit start the left arete on marginal feet and hands.Powerful.

name: Lost and Found
description: Sit start the left trending arete.

name: Needle in a Haystack
description: Sit start the face and move right then back left

name: The Nose
description: Sit start and traverse right to a slopey topout

name: Pomp & Circumstance
description: Sit start the face on small crimps and gain the slopey arete and top out.

name: The Trunk
description: Sit start the steep arete and traverse right to join another arete on great granite.

name: Union Man
description: Sit start the steep right arete

name: Right Tree
description: Climb the crack up until it takes a turn left horizontally, then turns again back up to the top.Moving left is the crux because it is surprisingly slopey in the horizontal crack.

name: Decimator Protocols
description: Face moves to pull over a roof. Favors the tall.  Negotiate small hanging arete to upper face. 2 bolt anchor.

name: Aspiring
description: Climb up the obvious inside corner clipping a few pins till under the roof.  Protect and power undercling out right till you can reach out and grab the jugs/exit crack.  Terrible feet under the roof

name: THE MISSION
description: From a 15 foot high V groove climb a thin crack to a bolt and very thin steep face with a ring bolts and black water streaks that look like the ones on a more popular 5.13b on Cathedral. After clipping the last bolt angle left on  another crack to a two bolt anchor.

name: Roger's Arete
description: The left side of the Caterpillar Wall is marked by a huge leaning pillar that becomes a detached spire at its top.  Roger's Arete diagonals up the obvious arete on the right side of the pillar, passes a ledge, and continues up the lower-angle arete to the top of the spire.  Only the lower section is bolted, and a semi-detached block leans out from the steepest part of the lower arete.  Getting off that block felt awkward.  It is probably easier if you are tall. Handren reported 5 bolts; I remember only 3.  After the bolts and a ledge, easy climbing leads to the spire's upper face and arete (5.9).  There are shallow cracks on the face, but you may need to stem from the arete to the main wall in order to place pro in a vertical crack inside the chimney.  At the top of the pillar is a large block, possibly detached, slung with much tat.  Belay here or continue up Aspiring.

name: Roger's Spire
description: Climb up a blocky corner till you are able to crawl inside of the chimney proper.  Climb until you reach the tangle of anchor webbing, clip it and top out the pillar.  I find it easier to be lowered off and have you second TR it to clean the gear.

name: Steamroller
description: Classic!    Undercling and Jam up an overhanging and strenuous left arching crack to an exciting move into a left facing corner's above the head single pad undercling and a side pull chicken wing "rest" before moving left again to more pumpy moves and a stopper crux using a few potential sets of beta to a piton and a heroic rock over mantle and a bolt anchor.  Pitch two is dirty but angles left on the Bucket Loader finger crack to the trees. Step right to a piton and clip the lichen as protection up a left slanting crack.

name: Winged Eel Fingerling
description: Climb to the top of flake. Move up to thin horizontal and traverse right 3 bolts to reach a beautiful thin crack which widens from tips to hands and leads to an anchor.

name: Zero Gully
description: Entered more as the "dividing line" between Caterpillar Wall and Diamond Wall than for any other reason.

name: Diamond Edge
description: Climb the face to the right of the arete,past a couple of pitons to a nice little ledge at a  handcrack in a alightly overhanging corner. Stem ans jam up the crack and corner to a piton. Step left and climb non-descriptly to a cluster of Oaks?

name: Judgement Day
description: Judgement Day is pretty bad ass for the grade.  Although following cracks it climbs more like a sustained face climb.  There is no real crux but the climbing is pretty sustained especially through the middle section.  It protect pretty well with a decent amount fixed pro supplemented with gear.     This route follows a incipient system of cracks and flakes that trend diagonally from the the center of the wall to the upper left corner.   Start at the base of the right facing flake/roof just right of center at the base of wall.  Climb this out to a pin and then head up into a left leaning crack where you will eventually find another pin.  From there continue trending left across an overlap to a bolt.  From the bolt move up into to the base of a large left facing flake (pin) then traverse the small orange colored wall at the top into another left flake system which you follow up and over.

name: Terminator
description: The Diamond Wall is overlapped, overhung, and riddled with elegant diagonal seams and cracks perfect for side pulling through high step face moves to the key hold above. A truly adventurous yet sporty feel. The gear is fun to fiddle with, the rock is high quality yet engaging, there are some creaky flakes so use caution. Save some juice and commit to the fierce last moves of the route which are protected by a couple of solid looking LA's.    Onsighters will be well rewarded by managing the rope drag properly, and bringing their GPS-like route finding skills.    This route has it all, technical face, underclings, a few jams, tricky gear, and adventure. A magnificent climb in a perfect setting.    To descend... scramble down the gully on the right after topping out  OR rappel the route with two ropes.

name: Kampala
description: Climb the left one of a pair of conspicuous cracks.  This one starts in a right-facing corner and passes several trees you can sling.  Apart from these trees, finding pro may require some searching.

name: Pleistocene
description: The Root of All Evil and Pleistocene have the same first pitch. There are some spots on this route that require carful movement due to loose rock. Also, it doesn't appear to get much traffic, so the lichen up at the cracks was...distracting...  Normal rack, on the small side up to hands. Mostly finger sized. The crux isn't really protected for the second, so make sure they are confident at the grade and/or has some gear to ascend the rope in the event of a fall.  P1: To the right of Deadline there is a blocky buttress. On the right side of the blocky buttress, about 30' to the right of the Deadline corner, there is a blocky chimney/notch. Climb up the chimney to the top of the buttress or a bit further to the base of the slab on the second pitch. There is a tree belay at both spots. 80'-100'. 5.7  P2: Surmount the blocks to get to the base of the slab with a single bolt in it if you not already there. Make careful moves to a good stance for clipping the bolt (the moves to the bolt can be protected via a nut in the crack to the right; however, you may want to retrieve this piece after clipping the bolt). Traverse up and left (crux) past the bolt to a weakness in the overlap. Continue up and left following a series of cracks with terrific exposure. Gain the notch above. We set a belay anchor in the notch, but most parties probably belay from the top. 140'. 5.10c  Decent: We rapped down from an existing rap station about 50' to climbers left of the top out using a 70m rope. That took us to a ledge that we down-climbed a bit to another rap station that brought us down over Sledgehammer. Doubles would have helped with the rap.

name: Sledgehammer
description: A beautiful little trad climb on top of an awesome  steep sport climb. Stick clip the first bolt and climb the overhanging corner and arete on spaced buckets and great rock past bolts and a piton inside the corner. Then step left into a nice fingercrack and a two bolt anchor.

name: Stone Free
description: The crux is free climbed now at (5-11b). F.F.A. Brad. White ( not me) and friends, 1988. Climb up the central dike to reach the traverse ceiling moves left or west. There was a tremendous amount of loose rock in this section. I was leading it and the rocks had to be rid of first, before progress could be made. Ted was belaying at the large oak tree below the dike. When he was ready behind this tree. I pulled out the bottom rock and dozens more flew out, ricocheting all over the place, off of the high branches of the tree. After that event I was able do the (5-9) mantle onto the spike below the crux. I nailed the crack above the roof (A2) and traversed right or east onto the left diagonal upward sidewalk to belay. Ted led second pitch up sidewalk until it ends and then face climbed right directly up (5-6) to summit.    For decades people have wondered who did this climb? The wonderment is over now.     There are three variations to second pitch. The easiest being (5-4) by going up the alcove corner above the sidewalk, the (5-8) directly up from the first pitch belay and the hardest (5-10d) keep moving left 10ft to a slanting crack and head up it to crux face climbing to the summit. The namesake of the route is in homage to Jimi Hendrix.

name: Zanzibar
description: Start in a slightly vegatated corner, easy climbing will bring you past a fixed tree anchor for an adjacent climb, continue on easy rock to the top of the butress.  Second pitch follows the same crack system to the top.  Starts low angle then some of the steepest 5.6 this side of High E.  Continue past the steep rock to a tree anchor.

name: Ace of Spades
description: This fun, steep climb follows a crack system a few feet left of Zonked Out.  Jam and stem your way up a chimney/groove to a good ledge on the left.  Be warned, this is Henry Barber "5.9+"!

name: Circus Time
description: Start just right of SYZ. Climb obvious left-facing corner to an offwidth. Traverse right to anchor. 10d if you climb the offwidth.

name: Firebird
description: Good vertical crack climbing fun and recently cleaned, Firebird climbs a friendly crack system on the left side of the Zonkers wall.  P1 5.6+ 80 Climb a short hand crack step left, follow the crack system up to a large ledge with some oak trees.  P2 5.7+ 45 Start on the left side of the ledge, Face climb up to a 6in wide crack leading to the top.  The second pitch has not been cleaned but could use it. From the first belay you can walk right along a ledge that provides access to some of the upper routes/pitches or just for the view.

name: Queen of Hearts
description: Begins in a rather ominous looking chimney with many stacked flakes. Good "full-body" climbing skills and prudent gear section lead to a deceptively pumpy and powerful sequence through the small roof. An excellent warmup for the real reason you came to the Zonkers wall just a few feet to the right!

name: Screaming Yellow Zonkers Crack
description: This is one of the best pitches in the northeast! Don't follow the crowds. Come climb this materpiece! Spectacular overhanging finger crack climbing to pumpy and technical crux. Jaw dropping!    Some history from the Ed Webster guidebook: "Joe Cote and Bruce Kumph aided the first ascent of the route on June 15, 1975. The first free ascent was a significant climb of the times when it was done by Jim Dunn in October of 1975."     Trust me, onsighting this crack is gonna feel significant in 2024.

name: Unknow
description: Start from obvious corner system, Circus Times just right of SYZ, and climb right into right facing corner, onto the arete.

name: Zonked and Screaming
description: Climb Zonked Out and after the crux there is a horizontal crack that leads over to the last 15 feet of Screaming Yellow Zonkers.

name: Zonked Out
description: Zonked Out was the first 5.12 in New Hampshire and it remains one of the best 5.12 trad leads. It's the thin crack to the left of the classic Screaming Yellow Zonkers.    Zonked Out is a study in technical laybacking and thin jamming. The moves are engaging, and the pro is pretty good.

name: Easy Street
description: Climb the right-facing two-tiered corner on the rightmost side of the playground.

name: Gemini
description: Twin hand cracks to groovy crux finish. Free soloed and rope climbed with Bill Hardigen in 1982. Bill with his long arms skipped the crux by reaching past it. Howard Peterson, Brad White, Babara Knight climbed it 1988 and called it Gemini.    I'll let the name remain the same but I'm not a Gemini. I'm an Aquarius, Hah!

name: Zig Zag Crack
description: Fun little climb at the Playground.

name: Irish Potato
description: Sit start the overlap and move up to a good hold and top out.

name: Aging Backwards
description: Sit start the steep headwall using a slopey shelf with a decent knob. Move left to a crimp and the right hand to a high, small crimpy sidepull and then launch left to match on an edge and the traverse all the way left to the same top out as the problem The Pearl.

name: Cement Shoes
description: Problem starts from the lowest sit start possible (right hand low on arête below the rock that leans against the arête) and moves up the arête and tops out.

name: Code of Life
description: Code of Life shares the start of Aging Backwards but instead of moving left toward the jug rail this problem goes directly up the center of the face then traverses right on the slopey lip and tops out as for Only Getting Younger. I thought it was just as good as its neighbor and slightly harder.  From the starting shelf grab a right hand tooth crimp then hit a left hand gaston. Match the crimpy seam above then hit the slopey but very textured lip. Traverse the lip right a bit and top out.

name: Only Getting Younger
description: The obvious well featured line of wrinkled seams on the right side of the face. Stand start on good holds then move through a crimpy crux to gain a high jug. Grab a nice right hand pinch block then swing a foot onto the lip out left and top out.  It is likely this line has been done before because it is so obvious and the holds were clean. I did have to clean the lip to the left which was covered in moss. I will change the name/FA if anyone else reports they did it.

name: The Pearl
description: Sit start the right trending arête and top out.

name: Front Porch Safari
description: Sit start on obvious feature at waist level. (Same start as for the problem Wolverine.) Instead of moving straight up move right on a series of crimps and bad foot smears and then top out.

name: Honey Badger
description: This is a fun little problem that climbs an undercut arete just past the Alcove Boulder. The holds are friendly so this could be a nice warm up for harder climbs on the Alcove or DNA boulder.  Sit start under the arete on the furthest right rail. Gain the arete and crank up to a good hold on the upper face then top out. Downclimb the other side of the boulder using a jug at the top of a crack.

name: Wolverine
description: Sit start the sheer headwall using the obvious feature at waist height. Move right to a high, distant crimp and the trend slightly left to top out at the high point of the boulder.

name: The Death of Denim
description: Sit start roughly the center of the vertical side of the boulder that faces the Lower Primate Wall.

name: Hourglass
description: Sit start the far right arête.

name: Diamond Cutter
description: Sit start with left hand low on a funky sidepull/undercling under the roof and your right hand on a crappy ball sloper and power pretty much straight up and top out.

name: The Rising
description: Really low sit start on the hanging cylinder arête. Starts as low as possible and busts up the cool prow.

name: Praying Mantis
description: Sit start the obvious undercut right side of the cave and move up and top out.

name: Forged from Fire
description: Sit start the steep left arête and move right and up to top out.

name: Oracle
description: Sit start the slopey arête and top out.

name: Scrambled Eggs
description: Sit start the egg on decent crimps and head up and top out.

name: Vapor Trail
description: Sit start the steep prow and top out.

name: In God's Country
description: Sit start the nice, tall right trending arête and top out.

name: Search Warrant
description: Sit start the cool featured boulder and top out.

name: Collision Course
description: Sit start roughly in the center of the face and move left to the marginal arête and then top out.

name: Crocodile Tears
description: Sit start the steep, undercut right arête and move up the face and arête and top out.

name: Extended Warranty
description: Sit start the arête and top out

name: Nightcrawler
description: Sit start the face and traverse right on crimps to the lip and surf the arête left and top out.

name: Straight Jacket
description: Sit start the steep, grey, left prow and top out.

name: Breaking Down Silos
description: Sit start the steep boulder with left hand on feature obvious low feature and right hand low on the arete and move up and right to a slopey top out.

name: The Untold Story
description: Sit start the really steep nose and top out.

name: Australopithicus
description: A fun climb up the tallest cliff in Kinsman Notch.  This route can have two grades depending on which final pitch you climb, it will either be 5.10a or 5.8+ (5.6 R)  P1 - Starting at the toe of rock, climb the slab up past a pin in a shallow corner, between the two trees and over a small overlap to a bolted belay. Protection is typical for a slab, a bit run out but if you work for it, it can be made relatively safe. 150 ft, 5.6 PG-13  P2 - From the belay, climb left along a faint dike clipping a pin and a bolt to a short headwall. Pull the headwall and enjoy fun climbing past natural gear and bolts up to a low angle slab. Scamper up the slab to a bolt and a final bulge, mantle the bulge and end at the bolted belay. 150 ft, 5.8+  Original P3 - (I did not climb this) From the belay head up and right on poorly protected rock,  eventually heading straight up at a cleaner (not clean just cleaner than whats on either side of it) section of rock passing a bolt 2/3 of the way up to a bolted anchor. 80 ft, 5.6 R  Variation P3 - Head up and left from the belay through a bit of crumbly rock to a high and oddly placed first bolt (this bolt should probably be 4 feet to the right). After clipping the bolt climb right in the corner on good holds pulling onto the face at the second bolt. From here follow the bolt line up and left to the top of the cliff. This climbing would be spectacular if the route was clean, in its current state (a thick sea of lichen) it becomes low quality. There is a bolted anchor off to the right from the top of this pitch. 80 ft, 5.10a  In its current state, a decent outing, with the second pitch being quite nice. If the third pitch .10a got cleaned up, this would go from a 1.5/2 star route to a 3-star route and would be highly recommended.

name: Elf Crack
description: Starts as 4 inch crack and narrows as you climb. Pull up onto easy slab after 30 to 35 feet or so and climb up to fixed anchor (block slung with cord).  Best route at this little crag, in my opinion (So good I climbed it twice!)

name: Gargoyle
description: Climb the crack/flake in the shallow left facing corner. Starts as hand size and then gets thin for a few moves. Crack then widens out again and arches left, forming a nice little roof to pull at the end (at about 30 feet). Follow the large flake up easy slab to bolted anchor (same anchor as for Troll).

name: Interloper
description: Dirty cracks to slab with 2 bolts. Current crux is lichen on the slab.

name: Ogre
description: Another great, short crack climb. Climb up the obvious offwidth. Some nice feet on the face and a great jug make this not as much of a struggle as most 5.9 offwidths. The difficulties are over after about 25 feet and then finish up some easy rock and the slab to a fixed anchor (same anchor as for Elf Crack).

name: Pimping Pinksky
description: Short sport climb left of the obvious Elf Crack. Cracks/crimps to a few loose-feeling flakes up higher.

name: Troll
description: Crack in the obvious left facing corner. Starts as fingers and hands and widens to some flaring offwidth and then chimney. Crack goes for about 30 feet, then climb easy slab up to bolted anchor.

name: Irene the Bully ( aka No Bull ?)
description: The "Irene" is hurricane Irene, which devastated western NH and eastern VT in early Sept. 2011.   START- in the center of the slab at the "toe". Climb cracks and shallow corners, then up a face to the headwall. Finish at a 2 bolt anchor.  Variation - From just right of the START, climb up right, then back left along a crack-ramp to rejoin the route about 1/3 - 2/5ths of the way up.

name: Little Matador
description: START- at the toe of the slab, climb the lichen-y face on the left to a 2 bolt anchor.  PG-13 /R due to limited protection.

name: Brown Eyed Russian Brushing
description: This is an awesome route, stellar rock quality and fun dynamic movement. Very unique as far as granite goes. Only thing keeping this from being 4 stars is the length, if your in the area it would be a shame not to get on this. Crux is in-between first and third bolt. There are some other cool looking sport climbs in the area, if you wanna learn more about them buy The Notches by Jon Sykes as it documents Kinsman notch very well.

name: A New Jon Sykes Route
description: This is a new Jon Sykes route that has recently been added to the crag, (2019/2020). Its the bolt line just right of BT. Very thin holds and delicate movement with great flow, a classic addition to the crag! I had climbed this route thinking it was the 5.7 to the right called Patina (silly me). I bumped into Jon at IME and asked him about it, he told me he had put it up pretty recently and it goes at 5.9, his wife Laura thought 10a. This was great news as I thought 5.7 was a tad rugged haha. If anyone knows the proper name for this route please edit this listing! Jon told me he couldn't remember what he named it. Also as per Jon Sykes style, drilled on lead...

name: Black Tourmaline
description: A wonderful climb on rock with a unique patina, and some fun crack climbing at the grade (and a lot of fun face climbing). Pitch 1 and 3 are very fun, but P2 is a little bit dirty, but worth it for pitch 3. This route was found in Jon Sykes book The Notches (which I recommend you get because it has a lot more detail, pictures and adventures in it), and I think it is a fun route which needs a little bit of love to clean it up and make it classic.  P1 (5.7+): Climb up "past 2 right-facing flakes, then past a bolt", go up and to your left into an alcove with a tree (it wouldn't be New England without some tree action), climb out of the alcove and follow a crack with some beautiful patina up and to the right, face climb to a "right-facing corner" and finish at a 2-bolt belay. Spectacular, has a little bit of a Red Rocks, NV feel to it.  P2 (5.6 PG-13?): [According to Rob Albert P2 and P3 are inaccessible] From the P1 belay go up and left through the trees to get you to a slab. Go up the run out slab and traverse left at a logical point and climb up to a 2 bolt-anchor. This pitch is a bit a bit dirty, and a little bit run out.  P3 (5.7): Climb up the to the arching corner system, clipping a bolt (spooky). Continue up the slab past 3 more bolts to a golden left-facing dihedral (if the corner crack were a little cleaner this would be as good as P1). Belay at a 2-bolt anchor.  Descent: Rap with 2 60m ropes to the base of Russian Arena OR according to Sykes "Rappel with one 60-meter rope down into the Russian Arena in 2 rappels"

name: Cheetos Direct
description: This steep dynamic route route is quite tenacious for its size, but protects well  and falls are clean. Start under the overhang and climb up into the awkward corner. Clip the bolt and make a big  move to a good hold. Protect the crux move in the horizontal with a big stopper. Make powerful moves  over blocky bulges to a finger sized crack. This is where this route comes into the crux "Assbone Arete" a 5.9 done by John Bain and John Sykes. Follow crack to a two bolt anchor.    Story Time- After a day or working the crux and getting further every try, we decided to come back another day. The next day rested i got the route first try. After a few tries and no luck, Isaiah ate a bag of cheetos and the cheese dust was just what he needed to get him up the route.

name: Patina
description: Climb up on nice edges to a bolt. Follow 2 more bolts to an overlap (can be wet after rain). Pull the overlap and clip another bolt. Continue up and to the right of Black Tourmaline, use the same 2-bolt anchor as for P1 for Black Tourmaline, rap or continue up Black Tourmaline for a nice link-up.    There is gear in between some of the bolts and after the last bolt.    For more route information see Jon Sykes guidebook, The Notches

name: PowerHead
description: START: A few feet right of the boulder on the dirt ledge, directly below a piton about 8 feet up. In 2019 there was one flat rock to stand on at the start.  NOTE: Listed as a "R/X" in the Sykes guidebook, the route was recently retro-bolted by the FA party.   P1 - Climb up to the pin (behind a hollow-sounding flake) , place optional gear just above and then move up and slightly leftish to the first bolt. Follow 2 more bolts to the (new-looking) chains.

name: Tuolumne Two Step
description: Climb up past bolts over some fun low angled face climbing, into a right leaning crack and then into a wider crack. Follow this up into a corner, pull around an overlap/corner and then head to the 2 bolt anchor.    Rap

name: Ant Phobia
description: Climb cracks with a little bit of face climbing straight up for 70 feet. Finish at bolted anchor.   I thought this climb was fun and well protected.  I climbed this in the fall before the fires, so please be aware that bolts could have been affected by the fire.

name: Indian Summer
description: This climb takes you over some beautiful rock with a unique patina for the NE. The route still needs a little love, but the rock is awesome and the views are great too. It has been one of my favourite discoveries in Jon Sykes' guidebook, "The Notches". Sykes does say the "Runout between protection makes this route a real thinker", but while the runout is there the gear was present where it was needed. Solid, exciting and beautiful face climbing.  Start below a partially detached block/boulder with a tree growing out of climb up the right side of the boulder using the left facing corner. After this you will climb up to a diagonal seam using the face and crack to get towards the first of 4 bolts. Follow the bolts (gear in between) up to a flake, then pull up to the anchors.  The climb is almost 60m long and will require 2 ropes to rappel. There are no good trees, or intermediate anchors to use, so if you only bring 1 rope you will have to be innovative.

name: Nuttin But Nuttin
description: Climb the obvious finger crack. The first few moves stepping off the ledge and getting in the crack are a little spicy, but then it is very well protected. Follow the crack to it's end, and then move up and left (I thought this was the crux) to the bolted anchor for Ant Phobia.   I climbed this in the fall before the fires, so be aware that bolts could have been affected.

name: Rib Rider
description: P1: Climb up the obvious rib of rock. Clip a couple of bolts on the way as well as a gear placement or 2. I think I remember a bolted anchor here, but I could be wrong. Looking back at the book it says to belay at a tree. 90 feet.    P2: Continue climbing up the rib. I thought the crux of the climb was at the beginning of this pitch. Belay at two bolt anchor at the top. 110 feet.  I climbed this last fall, so I have not been back since the fires. Be aware that any fixed protection may not be good.

name: Bangarang
description: The first route you see when the trail comes to the cliff. Follow bolts up the slab to a stance 25  feet up. Go off the stance to the left following bolts and aiming for the left end of the big roof. Pull around the left side of the roof and follow slab into the low angle to the corner to the anchor above.

name: I've Gotta Crow!
description: To the right of Tinkerbell Hell are two bolt lines. I've gotta Crow is the left one. A fun slabby route capped by a cool overhanging alcove feature. It is helpful to clip the bolt at the base of the alcove with a long draw.

name: Lost Boys Go Bolting
description: This route climbs the big left facing corner on the right side of the crag. Climb the slab to a small overlap, protect and pull into the corner. Clip some bolts and place some gear climbing the corner till the overlap is reached. Clip bolt and pull over overlap to the right. Slab up and pull through another overlap with a grove in it. Climb the thin slab with bolts and gear to anchor.

name: Mr Smee's 5.8
description: start with a mantle, and climb the finger crack to the right. climb the hand crack above the finger crack and then slab your way to the anchor.

name: Mr Smee's right
description: Same start as Mr Smee's 5.8. Mantle off the ground and climb the finger crack right. Instead of climbing the hand crack above keep right and climb the right facing dihedral to the shared anchor.

name: Tick Tock
description: A fun bolt line with thought provoking moves, following the blunt arete. Follow the bolts up the arete, till a overlap is encountered. Pull the overlap doing some tricky moves. Climb the slab aiming for another overlap with the "sharks fin". Pull over the overlap to the right of the fin to the anchor.

name: Tinkerbell Hell
description: A wandering route in the middle of the cliff. start at the height of the land clipping a fixed pin. Follow the zig zagging bolts till your under the roof. Traverse under the roof clipping these bolts with long draws to prevent heinous rope drag. Traverse right till in the left facing corner, clip the hidden bolt inside the "crack". Climb the corner and right wall, pull over to the anchor.

name: Bury the Hatchet
description: An excellent "bolter problem" up a steep arete. From the belay stick clip and scamper up a slab to reach a left trending line of crimps that take you to the arete. Do a powerful and tricky crux sequence and clip the last bolt, then keep it together through jugs on your way to the top. When you get to the anchor find a comfy rest position to clip, then finish off by mantling over the lip. It ain't over til it's over.

name: Bury the Hatchet Direct (open project)
description: The arete of Bury the Hatchet has an obvious direct start. It goes from some obvious decent holds to a terrible sloper and then somehow into the holds that mark the start of crux for Bury the Hatchet. It could be V7 and I'm missing something, it could be V12 and I just don't stand a chance. The stud for this project needs a bolt hanger, anyone is free to give it a try.

name: Crag Dweller
description: Burly, primarily awkward sport climb at the bottom of the Waternomee climbing area.  Towards the top of the steep path heading to the wall, you see a shorter wall with an overhanging face.  On the left of this is a short arete and upper face that Jon Sykes bolted and apparently climbed. You kind of grab the arete, step on it where possible, but generally the lower 20 feet of this line is dominated by your body getting sucked down and right into the overhang where there are very limited right foot opportunities, and then grappling with the strange broken cleft above the overhang to find good enough hand holds.  All the while your left foot and leg is clawing at the arete to gain some stability.   Long story short, it's a sandbag at the 5.8 grade in the guidebook and perhaps even stiff at the 5.9 I am giving it here.   Not a bad climb but also not a "warmup" unless you already did gymnastics at home before coming to the crag.

name: Danen Direct
description: The Eyeless in Gaza of Kinsman Notch, this route will be on you to the very end. Climb the slightly overhanging bolt line through pumpy edges to a distinct low crux that ends at a nice resting jug. From the resting jug follow the original line rightward through a technical boulder problem that yields to good beta and well timed rest.

name: Danenome
description: Start on Danen Direct and climb through the easier low crux to the nice resting jug, from the jug make one move up and transition to the last bolt of The Spirit of Waternomee. This link-up follows the path of least resistance for Danen Direct's finish, however it skips the hard crux at the end making for a pumpy but friendly 5.12a. A great choice if you can't quite figure out the last bit of beta for Danen Direct, or are just looking for something with a little less sting in it.

name: Devil's Diagonal
description: Climb gigantic loose looking blocks up a wide corner towards a steep feature at the top. Bring long slings and climb with care. Having not climbed this one but others in the area before they were clean, I'd hesitate to say this one is going to feel like sport climbing.

name: Lone Wolf
description: Locate the overhanging corner on the right side of Waternomee, make weird moves past a few bolts up to an interesting mantle to the anchor.

name: Paleface Arete
description: Unique and high quality sport route that carves across the top of the Waternomee amphitheater.  Not your everyday climb. Ride the arete, try to stay in rhythm, drop your feet below the lip if you dare. Save some fuel for a tricky section at the top. 9 bolts.    Gets 3 stars in the Sykes book; I don't disagree but for MP I gave it 3 out of 4. The 10a rating felt spot-on. Tricky for an onsight because it's so weird, but ultimately the moves are on grade.  Note: This sucker goes way the hell right from the start, so cleaning on the lower would be impossible.

name: Spirit of Pete
description: A silly but fun link up. Use long slings to climb the first five or six (depending on drag) bolts of The Spirit of Waternomee, and transition to the resting jug that marks the rest on Danen Direct. From the jug execute the final boulder problem of Danen Direct and finish on that anchor.  Its a fun route, but probably only do this one if you've run out of stuff in the area.

name: Spirit of Waternomee
description: A 60 foot flake that overhangs slightly the whole way. Grab a jug, layback to the next jug, rinse, repeat. If this route was located in Rumney it would be a contender for one of the best 10d's there, and you would have to wait in line for it even on weekdays. On its own it is an amazing route, and better still is its proximity to the crag's classic 5.12. If you head up this with 16 or so draws you can also hang draws on "Danen Direct" on your way down making it the perfect warmup.

name: Bee in Your Bonnet
description: Stick clip the first bolt. Start on a flake jug above your head and move through crimpy holds and powerful but precise moves toward a little lower angle terrain and a big rest ledge. After hanging out on the rest ledge, do big moves through another bouldery section to an anchor below the lip of the wall.  Jon Sykes and Larry Boehmler aided this seam during the winter, and called it Seam's Cold 5.7 A3.(guidebook, pg 306, RHall NOTE) At the ledge they traversed to the left toward 5.7 terrain, but if you look carefully near the second bolt you can see an obvious drilled bathook hole from the initial ascent.

name: Honeypot
description: Honeypot was called open project in the Notches guidebook (pg 306), bolted by Pete Danen in the early 2000s. The bottom of this route can seep badly in the spring and feel strangely gooey, but if you catch it on a dry day you'll be one busy bee! Climb up to a jug and navigate through a horizontal filled with holds that could be better. Head straight up on bad holds through a wildly powerful move to a sloping jug, and then another very powerful move to a good hold and a rest ledge. Hang out for as long as needed, then trend right out a prow through one final boulder problem and a juggy finish.

name: Little Stinger
description: A short route going up into a corner. A mantle at the top lets you clip the anchors from a casual stance. Stick clip recommended. Once you know the moves well it makes for a good warmup for the harder routes at the crag. Be careful to pull your rope out of the rope eating flake before you lower off this one.

name: Murder Hornet
description: Clip the first bolt of Stung, but trend right on jugs and slopers to a horn shaped jug by the 4th bolt. Shake out and do one hard move to the lip, then sink an excellent knee bar for a needed rest. Climb left along the lip to the mantle and anchor of Stung.

name: Stung
description: Stung is a good little 12a with a very powerful crux for the grade. Climb up the ledge into the cave and take a bolt line up a steep arete feature out to the lip. Mantle up and clip the chains.

name: Yellow Jacket
description: This is a fun route that looks harder from the ground than it is.  I wouldn't hike in just for this little crag but if you are coming down from the upper crags it is worth a stop to do this route.

name: Three Amigos
description: This route is an absolute gem, stellar steep climbing on big holds to a heroic move to gain the lip. This route would for sure stand out at Rumney (IMO).

name: Bear Den Direct
description: A sport route that climbs like a trad line.  It's a winding, blocky adventure up and over the Bear's Den roof, a fun romp with alpine-y movement and some suspect rock to navigate.  You end up way "under", then come "out and up" moving to the left on big features.  You'll pull the roof and find the anchor, with a bit of exposure taboot!  Speaking of trad, you may want to place one piece, and maybe two.  As a ground-up route, the bolting was not intended to comply with sport climbing norms.  If MP had "mixed" as one of the choices, I would have chosen that for this upload.

name: Bearly Got It
description: Sport route that takes on the Bear's Den roof in dramatic fashion.  A demanding crux sequence that requires two hand-matches, while cutting left across the underside of the roof.  If you get it right, and find some footing, you'll mount the lip of the roof and find the escape holds.   Like a boss!  It should be noted, this route was established ground-up, and as such it may or may not have a bolting sequence that matches the normal expectations of a sport-route.  In other words, there's a significant gap before getting clipped into the key roof bolt.  You'll be exposed above a ledge with your previous bolt at/below your feet.  A cam or passive could be used to mitigate this difficult sequence.  Retro-bolting this section is a possibility.

name: Black Bear
description: Pretty nice sport route with a tricky crux sequence.  Feels awesome when you nail it.  Holds are good and perseverance is rewarded!    Find a bolt just over the bottom overlap, avoid the slime near the ground.  Engaging moves to the second overlap. Clip the right-hand bolt under the overlap to get stable, then reach left to clip the other bolt. Remove the one underneath and keep going.  You'll hit the big roof after negotiating a third overlap.  A neat and pumpy bouldering sequence will take you over the roof, where a final bolt protects the run to the two-bolt anchor.    High quality climb, and totally do-able!

name: I'll Lead That
description: An engaging line up the right side of the Snake Skins wall.  This cliff looks good to the eye, and is even better once you start climbing it.  The rock quality and varied features makes for a great, long romp.    Ascend about 30 feet of 5.3 climbing, and trend right towards a bolt which guards a seam and crack system.  You'll head up and over the cliff's bulge, encountering pockets, cracks, face holds, and slabby feet.  Plug some gear when you see it, because at one key point the protection's finicky.  Fun sequences on amazing rock will take you to a two-bolt anchor which is hidden atop the final little headwall.  A 70 meter rope will not get you down.

name: The Wolfgang Marten
description: A fun and direct line up the left side of the Snakeskins Wall, taking you to a proud perch at the top of the cliff where only the Peregrines dare to dwell. From the shady base camp area where the trail comes up, look for a ledge/alcove about 80 feet up beneath the steep headwall that guards the clifftop.  The alcove has vegetation (and a tree stump) and is noteworthy also because there is a broken blocky roof feature you'll be climbing, followed by crack system up to a two-bolt anchor.  The Wolfgang Marten ascends the lower faces of the cliff on slopey horizontals and a few deep definite incuts, passing a couple of bolts and a few gear placements.  The route passes through said tree-stump alcove and up through the notch where there is this neat triangular wedged chockstone and a finger crack.  You'll love the position hanging from that anchor, looking left and right across the wide expanse of spectacular Kinsman Notch!   A single 70 gets you down, pretty close, with stretch and a small down climb, or take your 60m rap to a midway belay station a little to climber's left.

name: Anal Volcano
description: This route mounts the crest of the Tsumani Wall on the left side, joining a nice crack that leads left past a sappy pine tree to the base of a separate buttress. This new face is followed all the way to the top which is much higher than you would think.  It's a very nice long moderate climb, with great position, and lots of superb moves on killer rock.  The gear can feel a bit tricky at some key moments.  Getting to the crack is a little hairball for the grade!

name: Lonesome Crack Climber
description: "After all this kind of fanfare, and even more, I came to a point where I needed solitude and just stop the machine of "thinking" and "enjoying" what they call "living", I just wanted to lie in the grass and look at the clouds"  -- Jack Kerouac  A gorgeous climb in a very special locale.  The plumb line right up the middle of Tsunami Wall, offering classic movement on amazing stone.  Navigate the subtle crack system over the crest of the wave, and bullet-hard incuts up and across the steep face to a two-bolt anchor.  Passive pro works well, maybe a couple of cams.  A few bolts help you along the way, but really it's just you and your thoughts up there.  Find your silence!

name: Maverick
description: Starts like a sport climb, taking on the overhung scoop on the right side of the Tsunami Wall.  Killer crimps, strange grabs, and the right beta take you past three bolts over the lip onto the main face, where a bunch of tenuous 9+ face climbing awaits.  Flow through tricky gear and balancey moves up and slightly left to the two-bolt anchor.   A bit of a sandbag!

name: Blueberry Crack
description: Just a really nice crack.     Climb straight up the slab gaining the vertical crack. The crux comes as the angle lessens but the crack seems out. Step left placing a #1 camalot then make your way to the trees.     Lower or rap off a tree anchor.

name: Diagonal
description: This is the most obvious line on the cliff. Start at the base of the obvious large Diagonal crack. The crux comes when passing a cluster of bushes that stick out of the crack. This route is interesting because the feet are small your legs will actually get pumped.     The route could use a bit of a cleaning, it has some lichen on some of the feet. If it got a nice cleaning it would deserve another star of sure.

name: Easy Morning
description: Climbing doesn't always have to be hard.     Start up a a quartz dike with no pro (5.2), climb the crack to a ledge then a couple of short walls lead to a tree anchor.     Maybe bring some webbing to back up the chord anchor. Or step left to blueberry crack. Rap or lower off.

name: Hand Crack
description: Climb the slightly left arching hand size crack to the blocky left faceing corner and tree anchor. Pretty fun climb if your at Bryant and worth doing. The gear is good and plentiful thought the route. Still needs some cleaning as there is vegetation growing in the crack, but easy to avoid.

name: Left Out
description: Climb a right slanting crack to a stance. Follow a short flaring  vertical crack placing a finger sized cam in a pocket at its top then make a thin move left to the tree anchor.

name: Millenium Falcon
description: This route is quite good but not a good intro to 5.9 trad climbing. Start on the route Diagonal 5.6 and follow that crack for about ten feet, from here balance and technique up the face above using obvious seems for protection. (In one vertical seam there is a perfect .75 pod that shows itself when it looks like it will take no more gear.) The crux of this route is the 15 feet of climbing after leaving Diagonal 5.6, with the hardest move being a awkward step left onto a small foot.    The route could use a good cleaning and might actually make it better and possibly a little easier.

name: Right On
description: Start up the left side of the alcove, climb to the crack with no pro, follow it left stepping left to the tree anchor.    Alternately, climb past the tree and follow an easy crack/ramp back right to the blueberry crack anchor (100')

name: Seaming
description: To the left of "Hand Crack" is a crack/seam that runs to the tree cluster of "Hand Cracks" anchor.Climb to the start of "Hand Crack" and traverse left 15 feet to the start of the slabby seam. Honestly I thought it was a really fun route but have your head on tight because the gear is mostly really bad or non existent. It's really easy to set up a TR from the top of Hand Crack.

name: Trees-a-crowd
description: An historic route, this one had an old cloth belt for an anchor. It's been upgraded.     Climb the crack. The crux is being crowded by the small trees.

name: The Body Electric
description: This climb took me two tries and is a great way to fool around on the rock during a hot summer in New Hampshire. The crux comes close to the top about 20' off the water. The topout is solid and pretty secure although the time I fell was in the top lieback crack/arete.     I've been told the water is too deep to ever touch bottom but always be aware of your fall zone and scope it out before trying it.

name: Warhammer
description: This route shares the same middle section as the route "The Body Electric". Route was done traversing in from the left side along the scoop at the base of the wall which can only be done at lower (summer) water. Follow the ledges up for a few moves and then break left onto the finishing panel of rock.

name: Hunchback Crack
description: Good hand/finger crack for 30 ft with great pro, then make a move onto the lower angle rock and make your way to the top. the book suggests there is a bolt, but no such bolt existed which makes the top a little run out.

name: Ninety Degrees in the Shade
description: Climb the dirty slab past 3 bolts (hard to see all 3 from ground) heading toward left facing corner. Climb the cleaner corner on good pro. Trend slightly left above for fixed anchor or belay from a tree.     Note: A fixed anchor is mentioned in guidebook, I did not see it and ended up belaying from a tree

name: Octoberfest
description: Start of a block and step right to get into the flake (optional cam placement). Traverse the flake right for a couple feet until you can clip the bolt over your head. Now enter the crux, make fun moves on sloper holds to a slopey ledge. Then tackle the upper bulge on more slopey jugs, to an easy low angle finish.     The easiest line wanders a little bit at the start.

name: Race Day
description: Climb the fun but short corner (crux) until under a bolt. Clip the bolt and pull up over onto the slab. Climb easily to the tree and make an anchor there.     If the corner went on for another 40 feet it would be a classic, unfortunately it does not.

name: Schoolhouse Rock
description: Start up the obvious right leaning crack just to the right of the headwall that makes up Black Fly Festival 5.12a. Make fun crack moves up to an smaller overlap (crux). Once over the overlap follow the crack to the top of the arete and make a balancy move to establish yourself on big ledge and up a short corner to trees at the top. Again there is an existing anchor up there but I dont know if I would trust it. Rappel the route when finished.

name: Start Me Up
description: The crux is right of the ground through the second bolt. So I suggest a stick clip. Make bouldery moves on slippery holds trending from right to left. When the angle of the rock becomes slab clip the bolt on your left and make easy moves to a hidden two bolt anchor.

name: Tripoli Crack
description: find and climb the finger crack. It'll have some dirt in it that will have to be cleaned out for stopper placements on the lead. Rock is good for the feet while you work at keeping yourself safe.

name: The Haunting
description: Start 5' right of Stone Cold and just left of the large corner. This route follows the line of bolts on the face/arête. Make hard balance moves off the ground that lead to a thin crux a mid height. Finish at a bolt anchor shared with Stone Cold to the left.

name: Stone Cold
description: A pretty good route when clean. Follow the line of bolts on the far left side of the crag 15' left of a big corner. Interesting moves on good rock lead to a bolt anchor on top.

name: Anniversary
description: Start on the left side of the ledge by a good size flake. Climb the slab to the right of the flake past two bolts to just under a nose. Climb out right of the nose untill your feet are even with the bottom of the nose then clip a bolt then step out onto it. Climb up esay slab to the top. You can all so pull strait onto the nose at a little bit of a harder grade. The route says trad in the guide book but you can do it as sport if you run it out a bit.

name: Around the Corner
description: The route consists of a slab to a nicely featured face and then finishes up a steep corner. Dave Penny discovered the route when he bailed right around a corner from a 5.12 project. Under heavy lichen he found nicely featured rock, which he used to climb up and retrieve his top rope anchor.        Pitch 1: Step up on nice rock to clip the first bolt. Step onto the ledge and lay the crack back to the right (protected by cams). When the crack ends, step left onto the face with nicely featured rock protected by bolts. Surmount the face onto a ledge. Follow the corner up past three bolts ( crux) to join the last bolt and anchor on Tree Keys.

name: As Easy as Instant Pudding Pie
description: Climb up past 3 bolts to a 2 bolt ring anchors, the name says it all.

name: As Easy as Instant Pudding Pie (pitch 2)
description: Climb corner/crack on gear and fun moves. Then continue up the flatiron/buttress on the left side, to ledge. This part is shared with ""Let Them Eat Cake". Stop at ledge and belay at 2 bolt anchor (of "Retread") or continue up until tree anchor of "Cakewalk".  Direct variation:  From anchor it goes at 5.10 with an enjoyable upper section. There are a couple bolt heads at the crux (without hangers).  Descent: From 2-bolt anchor, 60m rope just reaches bottom.  (Wrote up as separate route as the first pitch is a nice easy 5.4 sport. The second pitch was added a few years later.)

name: Autumn Tears
description: Climb up the face to first bolt, optionally placing a nut on the way. It's easier going on the right and then traverse left to the first bolt. Then passing two more bolts straight up. Now the terrain gets easier and more slabby but without any more protection until the head wall. A 2 bolt anchor is set rather high so an extra move or two is requires to reach it.  Second pitch is 5.9 trad and described separately.

name: Autumn Tears (pitch 2)
description: Climb straight up the head wall passing two bolts. Continue using some gear to rope anchor at tree.  Descent: 60m should reach the bottom  (Wrote up as separate route as the first pitch is a nice 5.6 sport that should not be overlooked. The second pitch was added a couple of weeks later.)

name: The Badlands
description: Climb the steppy face up to the headwall. Pass it on the right side and back left. Continue up via some maples to the top and belay tree.

name: Cold Feet
description: A gear protected variation to Anniversary.      Climb the flake just left of Anniversary, pull the roof and join Anniversary at it's last bolt.    Easier 5.10 if you pull the roof left trending, harder 5.10 if you pull it straight on.    The crux gear is extremely marginal.  Could improve with traffic.

name: Cornered
