I would argue no moves are harder than 5.9. Traverse 12 feet right into a flared chimney, with great relief, place gear, and climb straight up the corner under a huge roof. The book recommends belaying under the roof, but I recommend continuing another 10 feet on a finger / hand traverse out right to a nice ledge on the next arete. This gives the belayer a good view of the previous pitch, and the next. 80' 10a R  P5: Traverse directly right on a crack reminiscent of the Fairy Tale Traverse. Belay at the obvious ledge 50' 5.8  P6: Downclimb the face below and to the right keeping just above the overhang. Move right to the base of a nice, obvious finger crack. 50' 5.8  P7: Climb the finger crack up and right until it starts to break up. Climb the broken cracks staying just left of a dirty groove. Climb over a small bulge at a curved flake. Belay at the base of a corner with small roof at the top of it. (the last crux of the route) 120' 5.9  P8: Climb the corner up to the roof. Surmount the right side of the roof (10b) then climb up and right choosing the path of least resistance on the final face of the buttress. Finish at the lip. 100' 5.10b  Descent: Follow the ridge, hike 200 yards up the loose talus to the alpine garden trail. Descend either the Huntington ravine trail, or lions head trail.

name: Psychedelic Soul
description: A long, varied pitch with lots of 5.11 climbing and a wild 5.12 crux.  A great line in an incredible setting.  Full value.Stem across the stream and begin by climbing the initial corner of Mechanics' Route.  Step right after 35' to a line of bolts that follow a technical arête and lead to a 2-bolt anchor beneath a square roof (5.11d to here, and fully worthy in its own right).  Continue climbing past the anchor and wrestle your way into the crux - a cryptic, holdless corner.  Work your Houdini magic and will yourself to stay in there, then keep fighting to reach a well-earned rest.  Boulder up and right to gain easier ground and continue to a 2-bolt anchor on a fantastic perch.Descent:  A 70m rope doesn't quite reach, at least not without some minor shenanigans...  It's best to lower to the mid-anchor and descend again.

name: Blockheads
description: Climb on good positive holds to a long reach to an horizontal between the first and second (missing) bolt. Put a good cam in the horizontal and fire a tricky sequence on really small crimps to the third bolt. From there go more or less straight to the arete on much better holds and finish on Thriller Arete.

name: The Chimney
description: Right of Thriller Arete, One will find an obvious chimney that slowly constricts all the way to the top. Scramble up to the base where face holds and a handcrack on the left provide easy climbing to the 5.5 crux near the top. Though slightly slabby in nature, The Chimney will bestow you with a hefty payload of positive feet and hands. Makes for a great first trad lead- will take pretty much any protection all the way to the top.

name: Joe's Place
description: Admin's NOTE: I'm not sure where the "somewhat vegetated" crack is on the description (as posted) below, but this climb takes the right-most line on the main face, at times even using the arete as a handhold. Done in this manner, the route is at least equivalent in quality to the Standard Route and The Prize. The crux is getting off the ground, especially if you are short, although there is some 5.4-5.5 climbing up by the upper crack(s).      Joe's Place is an unlikely route up the far right hand side of the main face. Starting at the overhang between the Standard Route start and Thriller, pull out left towards an arete on good holds until it is possible to move around the corner onto a slab. You now face a somewhat vegetated, slightly overhanging crack that appears to be much harder than 5.6. Using some hidden face holds, make strenuous moves past the crack and an inconvenient bush. Continue more easily along discontinuous cracks with ample face holds, right along the top of the spectacular, arcing Thriller Arete. Finish towards the top of Standard Route.    This route is of a much lower quality than Standard Route. The moves are less fluid, the line less obvious, and some parts are dirty. However, the cruise along the top of Thriller is spectacular, and it might even be possible to set up a toprope for it from a point on Joe's.

name: Practice Session
description: Practice Session is the farthest right climb at Square Ledge, and is often toproped. It climbs the obvious handcrack up and left to a stemming roof. Makes a good introduction to basic crack climbing.

name: The Prize
description: History: The FA was made in 1944 by Brooks Dodge and Mary Backus.    The Prize ascends the far left side of the main face, about 20 feet left of Standard Route. Following a thin crack system most of the way, the climbing is a little less fun and varied than that on Standard Route. However, this climb is still worthwhile, especially given it's ideal position above scenic Pinkham Notch.    Begin climbing at the base of the buttress, right where the hiking trail hits the rock. Navigate easy terrain around a bush. Continue with more difficulty up the discontinuous crack system, but using mainly face holds. Either establish an awkward belay at half height or keep going. The crux is a slight bulge in the slab as the climber nears the top. Move up this steeper section with scant protection making easy but balancy moves. Alternatively, break right into Standard Route at around 80 feet. Gear and tree anchor at top.

name: Standard Route
description: HISTORY: The FA of this route was done in 1943 by Bill ("William Lowell") Putnam and Brooks Dodge in 1943. (Brooks was the son of Joe Dodge, who ran the AMC's Pinkam Notch camp from its inception in 1922 to 1959 [1928-1959 as Manager of the Hut system]), probably (?) just before Bill went to Camp Hale, Colorado to train the 10th Mt Division. Bill would later take part (as a Pvt.) in "removing" the Japanese from Kiska Island (Alaska) the only US territory Japan occupied during WWII.  Here his climb to the volcanic high point of the island took a bit longer than anticipated and resulted in AWOL, the "punishment" for which was to lead the entire company up as a training exercise the next day. During action in Italy in 1945 with 10th Mt. Division he took shrapnel to the chest (lungs) and missed the action at Riva Ridge and Mt Belvedere, but (now as a First Lieutenant) took part in the final push into northern Italy. After the war he would make the 2nd ascent of Mt St Elias in Alaska, lead many trips to the Adamant-Austerity range in the Selkirks of British Columbia, and serve as both President and Honorary President of the American Alpine Club.         Climbing up the middle of three cracks on the main face, Standard Route is a classic. Though it can be done in one push, most prefer to break it up into 2 pitches. The first belay is usually about 2/3 of the way up the face on a small ledge. This allows the belayer to always be within sight of their leader.     One can choose to either follow the crack system to the summit, or use the massive face holds. Either way, engaging climbing awaits all the way to the summit- just play it to your strengths.

name: Thriller Arete
description: This prominent arete is certainly the most photogenic climb in the area, with terrific views of Mount Washington in the distance. About 60 Feet to the right of Standard Route, Thriller climbs the intimidating overhanging arete, following it up and right. Start on the right side of the arete, eventually making your way around the corner to holds the left. Eventually a jug can be reached near the top where you can shake out and consider the top out. Breaking left from this jug is a variation of the original route, and clocks in at 5.10a. Either way, the climbing is pumpy and sequential all the way to the jug.

name: The Tumor
description: Left of The Brain is a roofed corner that is the start for both The Tumor and The Nose. Pull up and out the left side of the roof and into the vertical groove. Follow the groove up and left of the arete to the top. A lot of the holds after the roof are good (but kind of slippery) quartz crimps.

name: Unknown (Left of Practice Session  Right of The Brain)
description: This climb is just left of Practice Session and and right of the Brain. It is a not so obvious fissure\finger crack that is not listed in the Guide book.    Finger lock and face climb your way to the top. Can walk off the cliff from the top or set up a TR anchor (Can't remember if it is gear or small trees), lower and belay the second.

name: Unnamed finger crack
description: Climb the easy first half of "The Chimney" then break left following a nice finger crack. At the end of the crack, reach for the nearby arete and finish the last bit of "Thriller Arete". The finger crack has good locks and protects very well with small cams and nuts.

name: Blue Line
description: Good climbing. On the right side of the crag climb 20' up to the roof. Turn the roof on it's right side then up the face toward the juggy arete.

name: Hop High
description: Up the face 20' to a large ledge. Traverse left and pull the roof on good hands (good luck with your feet) and continue up the well featured face.

name: Pinkham's Magic
description: Start up the same face as Hop High to a ledge. Go right over a short steep wall, nice moves, onto the upper face.. Continue up and right to a left-slanting crack. At the top of the crack exit left back onto the face. When you reach the top block and small horizontal crack go right and up to the anchor. Good rock, moves, and pro.The Cure Var. 5.7+ PG13   This variation to TMOP  follows thinner climbing and pro.Climb Pinkham's Magic until the 4th bolt. Instead of going right to a crack, go straight up through thinner moves to rejoin TMOP at a higher bolt.  At the top block go left to a steep beautiful hand crack finish.

name: The Creature Within
description: Climb up a steep face passing 3 bolts then right to a ramp and another bolt. Follow the ramp to a right facing corner. At the top of the corner 2 bolts protect the upper face.

name: Submariners Can't Get Me
description: Up face moves to a finger crack.  Trending a little left, head up the highly featured face to the upper block where you can reach for a bolt.  Leftward moves up the block top you out.  Rap rings are set back a little.

name: Theo
description: Excellent and interesting climbing. Climb a left facing corner/crack exiting right to the top of a pedestal. Climb left into a beautiful circle feature and up a steep face passing 2 bolts to the anchor.This climb was originally named Ski Baby after my grandson's womb name. He has since hatched!

name: Windfall Crack
description: A left leaning crack up the prominent face.  A couple face moves, then up the crack utilizing jugs and jams.  Step up onto the pedestal when the crack ends and finish up the Ski Baby face directly above.

name: Polecat
description: Climb a block that leads up onto a ledge at the north side of the C Lot area. There is a face above, broken up by two horizontal/diagonal cracks running across it.  A bolt protects a tricky move to gain the lowest crack.  Climb through the cracks to the upper section, also protected by a second bolt for the top out moves.  Belay/rappel from rap rings.

name: Sam Stone
description: Great horizontal cracks get you past a small roof and a short steep face to the top of a block. Easier climbing leads to a view and belay ledge.Go up a short right trending ramp to clip a bolt under the roof. Reach around the roof to clip another bolt. Pull the roof/crux and up a short steep face using 'thank you' horizontal cracks to the top of a large block (great cam placements at the bottom and top of the block). 2 more bolts up a moderate face brings you to the anchor/view. A hidden cam placement was unearthed after the bolts went in so the finish is over protected.John Prine was a great singer/songwriter. He passed from COVID19 in April 2020. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rtrALjg0-xQ

name: Spanish Pipedream
description: Some good moves. Start at the toe of the slab and go straight up the center. Crux is passing the first bolt. If you enter from or use the sides of the slab it goes at 5.6.John Prine 1946-2020"I knew that topless lady, had something up her sleeve"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DWmG9wCE440&list=RDDWmG9wCE440&start_radio=1

name: Tess’s Skulduggery
description: Fun well protected face climb. Crux‘s are at the second / third bolts, thin face moves, and final bolt at top opposite rock of repel ring (V Groove)

name: Albert
description: Great hand jams to a nice sequence over the roof (bolt) and finish up a well featured face (small wire).

name: Decker Face
description: A variation to the lower half of Rolf's Amazing Journey.  Start at the bottom of the buttress, twenty five feet right of Rolf's. Climb up the face, passing two bolts and a tricky cam or nut placement, and onto a large ledge.  Pass a third bolt and protect in the horizontal, then move left into the Rolf's crack, and up to the hidden ring anchors under the roof.

name: Raven Corner
description: The deep V corner straight up the crag.  Climb the right leaning, right facing crack right of the birch tree.  Up a ramp to the V corner.  Climb the overlap into the corner then enjoy great stemming moves to the top.Raven Face variation:  Step right, out of the corner, and up the face.  A fun position above the large central roof.  Climb trending right, staying just right of two bolts.  A third bolt is hidden above, and appears as you crest the face, to protect the upper moves to rappel rings.  (August 18, 2020)

name: Raven Face
description: This is a variation on Raven Corner.  Climb up into Raven corner, then step right onto the face.  A fun position above the large central roof.  Climb trending right, staying just right of two bolts.  A third bolt is hidden above, and appears as you crest the face, to protect the upper moves to rappel rings.

name: Rolf's Amazing Journey
description: A really fun route that protects easily.P.1 Follow a beautiful right facing corner to a ledge on the left (2 bolt ss rap anchor, hidden from below- RH Note). P.2 Go right under the roof with plenty of air below you and finish up a crack to another 2 bolt ss rap anchor.  1 rap down with a 60m. Can be done in 1 or 2 pitches.

name: Contact
description: START - About 30-40 ft right of the "toe" of the slab, at a clean slab with a L-facing corner (photo) on the right (with lichen on the part of the slab that is next to the corner).     To the left of this clean slab a line of trees and bushes runs up the cliff 15 +/- feet and provides what might be an alternate start*.    P1 - Climb the clean slab ( crux, 5.5 - 5.6 PG-13 / R?) to a large flake.  From the flake's top climb directly up to a bolt, then a 2nd bolt and on to a double bolt anchor.  115 ft  5.5 - 5.6    NOTE: A rap with a single 70m reaches the ground; a single 60m would probably reach the top of the line of trees.     P2 - Move up and right onto the pegmatite rock. Climb this up and through the "headwall".  200-210 ft  5.4 - 5.5  This pitch may be broken up; a good belay is under a small overhang that is 15-20 ft above the lose-looking 3-4ft flake-lieing-on-the-slab. (which may get "trundled off, if it is actually lose)    .   * ?Alternate Start? - Scramble up the line of trees and step right onto the slab about where RW is in the photo.

name: Hank Chinos
description: Absolutely amazing climbing on solid pegmatite rock.  I don't know whether P2 of "Contact" or P2 of "Hank Chinos" came first, but if they are not the same then they are probably within a few feet of each other on "wide open rock". When we were there, this was the first climb we did, and we utilized the "Contact" double bolt anchors.  START - About 15-20 ft right of "Contact" where the pegmatite streak/band starts.  P1 - Climb easily up the pegmatite 50-60 ft (nuts useful) and cross a smooth slab* (crux ? 5.5 PG-13?) and then up through a minor "headwall" (Here you are about 20-25 +/- ft right of Contact's P1 protection bolts.) Either continue another 40-50 ft up on the pegmatite and establish a gear belay [15-20 ft above the 3ft-flake-on-the-slab], or move left to the double bolt anchor of Contact. 140-150 ft [or 115ft +/-]  5.5 * See COMMENT below by "Chinos"   P2 - Up and through the headwall. Belay at a birch tree. 200-210 ft from the Contact belay, 120-140 ft from the gear belay mentioned. 5.4 - 5.5 (and, yes, I know the FA-er's listed the climb as 5.6, maybe we missed the 5.6 )  NOTE: On a subsequent ascent we noticed that from the gear anchor mentioned, another 30-40 ft (150 +/- ft total) up and slightly left there's a Pine Tree with a rap anchor. But even doubled 60m's don't get you back to the Contact dblt bolt anchor. We rapped to the gear anchor with doubled 60m's, then down climbed 5.0-5.2 40 ft down and climber's right to a pine tree and rapped down from there to high-angle dirt & leaves.  Descent - We rapped down the tree line to the right with a single 70m. (See "Tree Line Rap", below) Better to have 2 x 70m ropes and rap from the birch tree to the Contact P1 anchors.  Tree Line Rap- From the Birch tree, Traverse (Class 4 / 5.0) 40-50 ft to a pine tree on the right. This tree has no nice place to stand, so we actually lowered down, the sling and biner still there. 115 ft (35 m) to a White Pine tree. Rap#2 115ft (35 m) to a tree ledge, move 5-6 ft to Rap3 80ft off a 4" diameter beech to the ground

name: It’s a Pinkham Thing
description: [From Barker] Submitted by Ron Birk, edited with permission by R Hall     START: About 50-60 ft left of the toe of the slab (i.e.50-60 ft Left of the start of "Old Route Direct") at a 10-12-inch diameter tree that forms "double trunks" about 6 ft off the ground. If you stand back a few feet from the tree you should be able to see 2 or 3 of the bolts.      P1. Climb slab 10-12 ft and then pull the overlap (gear) at the base and climb up to a stance on the slab.  At this point a pink tri cam might be slotted in a pocket. (Certain sized "Stoppers" might also work) Now commit to the slab past 3 bolts, and continue on pegamtite past a 4th bolt to a big overlap.  Pull throughout this (5th bolt) to a ring anchor. 115-120 ft  5.8  (Rapping this with a 60m rope leaves you 10 ft from the ground to downclimb the opening slab.)       P2. The next pitch goes up and right to the large pine tree, all on natural gear pulling many overlaps along the way.      P3. The 3rd pitch is a scramble over some really cool rock.

name: Old Broad's Birthday Bash
description: A fun easy route on the far right, good for beginner leaders or for an easy relaxing outing.    P1. Start up the pegmatite and veer left, following a left facing corner (slanting left). Then up the head wall (crux) and to a pine tree. To keep the grade low and more consistent on the route, you can circumvent the crux by going left for a move or two. Or go straight up (and a grade or two harder) for more interesting moves. 5.4 100'    P2. Go straight up (veering slightly right) to a small pine tree, through two fun decent size overlaps. 5.3 170'    P3. Go left and up over easy slab and finish up a clean beautiful low angle arete to a tree. 5.2 180'    From here you can scramble to the top of the cliff and take the Ledge Tr back out.

name: Old Route Direct
description: NOTE: The route described was as we did it, our P2 and/or beginning of P3 may not be the exact line of the FA.     Start at the "toe" of the slab. (photo)    P1 - Pad up the smooth, unprotected slab [5.5 R?] to the first overlap and a bolt. Over the overlap (crux, 5.7 / 5.7-) and then continue straight up the magnificent slab above, passing a 2nd bolt. We belayed under an overlap above, but I think a much better belay (gear) is to the right in a curved flake (photo) 120 ft 5.7 / 5.7-    NOTE: Either P1 and P2 can be combined, or P2 and P3, but we thought is very pleasant as a 3-pitch climb.       P2 - We followed sort of a diagonal slash up and right through overlaps to a good stance and gear belay just left of the pegmatite. 75-90 ft 5.5     P3 - Up and slightly left-ish through impressive looking overlaps, passing a Lost Arrow piton [photo], to a double bolt anchor. A very interesting pitch, in that the overlaps are "tricky" in that a foot or two and a different sequence can make the moves a grade or two different. 80 feet 5.5 to 5.7 depending..    DESCENT - You can rap from the double bolt anchor (2 ropes ) to the double bolt anchor on Contact [off to rapeller's/ climber's right] and then to the ground, or if you want to go back to the car...    P4 - Climb the clean, low angle slab above. Go through a small tree island to a bit more rock above and end at a flattish boulder about 3 ft across.  100 ft Class 3/4    From here, move up and right generally keeping to the rock, then cut back left-ish up with a class 3 or two move on trees/rock to the trees where you should hit a boundry-survey line. Follow this down and climber's left. When you "cliff out" at a survey sign and post-in-rock, backtrack 40-50 ft and descend the gully back to the "path" to the road.

name: Pope on a Rope
description: Climbs the slabs past a few bolts and gear right to the base of the headwall, to a 2 bolt ring anchor.

name: Choco
description: Nice moves on good holds. Start hold is a bit unsteady...

name: East Of Eden
description: Amazing climbing up a overhung seam to a sweet mantle topout.

name: The Sword
description: start on good incut crimps and slopey arete bottom of cave climb straight through the leaning block with some fun compression climbing and committing bumps over a few boulders. work to the arete and traverse right on slab and out. super classic

name: Weenie Route
description: This route ascends a low angle slab with many moss-filled cracks up the middle of the 5th flatiron.P1. Climb the initial slab from your choice of cracks. Easiest right but also blockiest/looser. Once you reach a large ledge, build a belay w/ gear (60ft)P2. Step right off the belay and climb a small mossy chimney. Top out the cliff and sling a large boulder about 20ft back from the ledge for the anchor. Watch for loose blocks (40ft)Descent: Rock hop a short distance up to the Cornice Trail and either summit Mt. Jefferson or take your choice of trail down

name: The Big Short
description: The Big Short is the most obvious, striking line on the tallest, steepest part of the Yellowjacket Boulder. The hardest moves are concentrated in the first 10 feet; however, the climbing on the upper wall remains relatively tough (mid 5.11) and is definitely heady. The Big Short is a tall problem; at Rumney, it probably would have been bolted.     Start in the scoop with your hands matched on a big sidepull/undercling. Make a move up to a pinch and figure out how to get your right hand in a high picket (crux). Surf out left to some cool crystally holds, and make deadpoint-style moves up the face until you reach a good ledge. Make sure to grab the left or center of the ledge, as the right side of the ledge devolves into a dubiously thin flake. The moves from the jug to the lip are just hard enough to keep your attention given the height.      In the fall of 2015, Tim Kemple Jr. added a sit start that clocks in at V8 or 9.

name: The Bottom Falls Out
description: The Bottom Falls Out climbs a wall/corner on the right side of the main face of the Yellowjacket Boulder. Start sitting with good crimps and bad feet. Make a big move to a jug, make another big move to the lip, and work left to a huge pocket on the lip to top out. Finally, negotiate 30 feet of easy slab to the very top of the boulder.

name: Cakewalk
description: Get onto the slab and friction straight up to the top. The hardest move is getting onto the slab. At the top there is a psychological crux but the move is solid. Top out and walk off the back.

name: Cavaletti
description: Cavaletti is a perfect warmup on the far left side of the main face of the boulder. Start in a corner and climb huge pocket jugs to a friendly topout. Every boulder should have a line like this.

name: Little One
description: Little One is a fierce little problem on the far left side of the main face of the Yellowjacket Boulder.     Start sitting just left of Cavaletti, with a low sidepull for your left hand and a crystaly crimp in the corner for your right. Make a move up to a cool, shallow two-finger pocket and then pull hard to stab your right hand to a crimp.  Move left to an ear-like sidepull, come in to a right hand sidepull, and throw to the lip.     Both the left corner and the good holds on Cavaletti are off.

name: Phillip Rivers
description: Jump start to a good hold/small rail, make a couple moves, then top out. The route is mediocre overall but still worth doing for the top out.

name: Rock Shop
description: Rock Shop climbs the face between Cavaletti  and Trillium. Start crouching with your right hand in a cool two-finger pocket. Work your way up the face, taking care not to stray too far left into Cavaletti. Top out as true to the line as possible.

name: Rose Trillium
description: Rose Trillium is an indirect start to the mega-classic Trillium. It takes a 10-move path through the coolest holds on the left side of the Yellowjacket Boulder's main face.  Start sitting down and left of Trillium with your left hand on an edge and your right in a big pocket. Use feet down low in the pit. Pull up, make a stylish rose move to the two finger pocket, and roll out of the rose move into Trillium's starting holds. Finish as per Trillium.  Because of the pockets and the movement, this climbs more like a limestone sport route than the typical granite boulder problems around here.

name: Short Sale
description: Boulderers Rejoice! There is now a difficult route on the breath taking Yellowjacket Boulder that doesn't require the mental fortitude of John Bachar.    Start with your hands crossed in two unique looking geode pockets and get right down to business from the moment you pull on. Make a long move out right to a side pull jug and then readjust your feet to set up for the crux. Using speed and accuracy, move your left hand up into a side pull pocket that doesn't feel as good as it looks. Once you have the left side pull, tap dance you feet up and prepare for the final hard move. Launch right to the long awaited jug at the lip and then roll over on the slab. Walk up the slab to the top of the boulder and down climb on the opposite side.    At the top of the boulder resist the urge to look over the lip of The Big Short. This decision would make it more difficult to eventually muster the courage to attempt the true 5 star line on the boulder.

name: Trillium
description: Trillium climbs up the central face of the Yellowjacket Boulder and tops out at the shelf at about two-thirds height. Start with your left hand on a sloping sidepull and your right hand on a sloping crimp. Make a dynamic move to a good pocket and follow crimps and pockets to a tricky move to the lip. Top out on the ledge.    The climb is so named because one of the pockets up top is filled with three perfect little stones. All three wiggle in the pocket, but can't be pulled out. It seems like there should be a lesson there.

name: Trillium Right
description: Yet another variation on Trillium, this tops out right of the original finish. Start as per Trillium, and make the big move to the good pocket. Match the pocket and make another big move out right to gaston a small left-facing corner feature. Top out straight up.     There are many linkups possible-- the best being Rose Trillium Right (V7) and Trillium Right Sit (V6)

name: Trillium Sit
description: This is a harder, and arguably better variation to Trillium. Start sitting with your left hand on a good edge (the starting foothold for the Trillium stand), climb up crimps to get into the position of the Trillium stand problem. Finish as per Trillium.

name: Buell Kazee
description: Hand Traverse and mantel to top out.

name: Staggolee
description: Start by stemming, then crunch up and pass through the constriction with chimney like moves, get a hand jam and drop into the crack. Continue along the crack and pull out and up to finish. There is a crux moving into the crack and then coming out of the crack and topping out.    Staggolee is a great route that will utilize much of your climbing knowledge.

name: Bloody Chin
description: The far left route on the tall face of the Dark Crystal Boulder, Bloody Chin starts on a cool crystally pocket. Work up left, eventually using a sloping corner and/or small crimp, and make a committing move to the lip. Top out and avoid using the tree.

name: Landstrider
description: Unique sequence and interesting moves make this a solid 3 star route. Once covered in "potato chip" lichen and after cleaning revealed 3 crucial finger pockets.

name: Mystics Master
description: The crux is figuring out how to use the side pull. Clever moves will unlock the secret and lead to an easy top out.

name: Podlings
description: This is the route that really makes The Dark Crystal Boulder unique! A series of pockets that traverse this side of the boulder and it's slightly overhanging angle combine for an excellent set of natural features.    Start on the right side at a good pocket. Traverse the pods left then top out. Your feet will never be more then 3ft of the ground.     The sit start (either continuing into Podlings or topping out straight up) is still a project.

name: Skeksis General
description: This route really has just one tough and committing move.  In addition it is above some protruding rocks (I've done a little bit to flatten the landing) which can be fully covered with a standard pad. If you look inside the large pocket you'll see crystals and garnets.

name: Jen
description: There is a crux at the start and another towards the top as the arete  steepens,luckily the feet get larger the higher you go.  The landing is very flat and soft.

name: Kira
description: the crux is moving onto and off of the rail then topping out.  move slow and use your balance.

name: Nanobots
description: the hardest part is getting up the first 5 feet of the route, once your feet are that high the rest will go down easily.  There is no gear but a big tree at the top will protect you if you want it.

name: Hatchet
description: Hatchet is the right-most line on the wall. Start with a crimp for your left hand and a sidepull/pinch with your right. Put your feet on the wall and make an off-balance throw to the good sidepull. Establish on the sidepull and surf this corner-feature to the top.

name: The Heist
description: Stand start on the obvious holds just to the left of Logarithm , climb straight up through a crimp rail, to the interesting top out.    This can be climbed from the start of Logarithm  and has potential for a left hand start as  well.

name: Log Splitter
description: Log Splitter climbs just right of Logarithm.  Start on on two obvious crimps for your hands and stand onto the wall using small footholds. Make a big move up to a shelf, and then top out straight up. Avoid using holds on Logarithm.

name: Logarithm
description: The best line on the boulder, Logarithm is a must-do for the area. It's also destined to become a popular warmup given its friendly holds, flowing sequences, and convenient location.     Begin down and to the left with your left hand on an edge under a little steepish wall. Work up and right, eventually gaining the left-facing corner/fin. Continue up this feature to the top.     It's possible to start farther right, but this lessens the number of moves and the quality of the problem.

name: First Impressions
description: First Impressions climbs the tall-ish arete near the stream. Start sitting with your left hand in a sharp pocket and your right hand around the corner. Work your way up the arete to a classic topout.

name: One Foot
description: One Foot is the warmup of choice for the area. Start on a good hold for your hands, and work up crimps to the top.     There's also a sit start that's been done into One Foot. It's a crimpy V4.

name: Some Nights
description: Start with your hands on a big flat sloper. Reach up and left to a bad hold on the lip. Use clever footwork to set up to throw right hand to the higher, better part of the lip. Negotiate the exciting topout.

name: Hold Steady
description: A sit start problem just right of Thank You For Holding. Start left hand on a crimpy rail, right hand on a sidepull and throw to a good hold. Use a cool triangular hold. Stay as true to the line as you top out straight up.

name: Hold Your Horses
description: The definitive sit start - grab left crimp and right side pull and huck for the jug.

name: If You're Holding, Don't Hold Out
description: Start sitting on the left-side arete and move up to gain the first flat jug. Make big pulls on big holds and heel-hooks as you climb the steep prow. Move all the way right before you top out.

name: Lack of Holdz
description: This problem climbs a cool sloping shelf on the right side of the main face of the Holds Boulder. Start sitting, and work up and left using slopers, and top out up and left.

name: Monkey Bars
description: Hang straight-arm from the lowest diagonal rung and enjoy classic and surprisingly sequential moves to gain the good feet and top out. Super fun with potential for a really hard sit start?

name: Thank You for Holding
description: Start on a low right sidepull and left crimp and boulder up and left along the fun sloping rail to a relatively juggy top out. The line of choice on this boulder: you'll be glad you held on!

name: The Squeeze
description: Start sitting on an inviting sidepull and flat hold that look like perfect start holds. Get really bunched up (it's entertaining to watch a taller person do this part) and lever up left to traverse fun slopers and slap to the rounded feature at the top. Traverse the lip a bit to the right to top out.

name: Outrage Arete
description: The awkward arete on the left. Try not to use the adjacent rock for a foot. This has a hard topout, but it's easier than the harder (and better) line to its right.

name: Outrage Fatigue
description: Climb the weakness in the center of the face to a heinous topout.

name: The Catfish
description: Start on a good left hand crimp and a decent right hand side-pull about six feet off the ground. The starting holds are five feet right of the arete of Don't Jump!.    Grab the starting hold get a good high right foot, lock off and go for the lip to a nifty mantle.

name: Don't Jump!
description: Don't Jump! climbs the left arete on the steep face of the Turnstile Boulders. It's one of those problems that could be easily negated with a quick hop off the ground. In order to get all the V points and all the style points, you must not push off the ground while doing the first move. Sounds classic, eh?    Once you figure out the initial standing beta (seriously), the problem does flow pretty well. Start left hand on the arete and right hand on a terrible crimp. Put left foot up on a crystal, ease yourself on and throw to the good crimp out right. Slap up the arete to finish the problem and top out by using a stylish heel hook out right.

name: Windchill
description: Windchill climbs a cool lip traverse on the right side of the main face of the Turnstile Boulder.    Start sitting with your hands matched on a good edge. Throw your right heel up and follow slopers leftward across the feature. I topped after about 10 feet, once I reached the good holds, mostly because I didn't feel comfortable traversing over the menacing adjacent boulder.      It'd be possible to continue the traverse across the whole lip, topping out at Don't Jump. Since the lip is pretty juggy, I don't think it would change the grade, but nonetheless it'd be a fun 30 foot traverse.

name: The Balance Dyno
description: The Balance Dyno is the most unlikely of boulder problems. Start on the left corner of the steepest part of the Lower Wall.     Clamber up onto a ledge and throw a left toe-hook into the big horizontal crack. This should allow you to stand up straight.  Then grab a nothing crimp with your left hand, and jump up to a sloping ledge. Hold the considerable outward swing and match the ledge. The crux is getting your feet established on the wall and reaching for a crimp just below the lip.     The dyno is definitely a crowd-pleasing move, but getting established on the face after the dyno is incredibly awkward and maybe a bit height dependent.

name: Full House
description: This is a super fun compression-style problem. Start with your right hand on the corner and your left on a sloping sidepull feature. Bump your right hand up the corner, and then surf the corner to a somewhat tall topout.

name: Smear Tactics
description: Smear Tactics lives up to it's name. Start on the far left side of the fin and work right until the lip becomes less juggy. Top out.     Smear Tactics is a good warmup and a good exercise in smearing on granite. It's probably about 5.7/5.8 in difficulty.

name: USS Cyclops
description: Sit start with a very low foot that is right off the ground and a heel up on the arete. Put your right hand on the  good starting hold and your left hand on one of the two other holds. Pull off the ground and reach up with your right hand to a small crimp in from the arete a little. Move your left foot onto a little chip and throw up the arete to a descent slopey full hand hold. bring your right foot up for another heel and bring your left hand up to the top of the triangle and work on rocking over the edge of the arete. It's a few tough moves for a fun problem. Might be a little more challenging for the tall climber.    Have fun

name: USS Nereus
description: Stand start the slab to the left of the twin aretes. Using good little quartz knobs and a good seam for your feet pull onto the scooped face, crimp up knobs  until the exciting topout.

name: Standard Deviation
description: Standard Deviation climbs the right arete on the steep face of The Outlier Boulder. Start low on the arete and throw a right heel up. Work across the arete using both heel and toe hooks and holds with varying degrees of slopy-ness. Eventually top out up and left as per Variance.    Climbing this kind of reminded me of the Tin Arete in Pawtuckaway

name: Variance
description: Variance climbs the left arete on the steep face of The Outlier Boulder. Because it actually has holds, albeit small ones, Variance doesn't climb like many of the aretes in the area. Start with a left hand sidepull and stand up on a pretty good left foot. Work your way up the arete by using small crimpers for your hands and hard foot movements. The difficulty eases when you get both feet on the less-steep face.

name: Deadly Pillars
description: A beautiful but terrifying line, Deadly Pillars climbs the lower face on the downhill pillar boulder. Start on a sloping jug and work up the arete to get your feet established on the jug. Now, make insecure, horrifying moves, up the less-steep face. As you notice the pads recede into the distance and your fingertips start sweating, steel yourself for the sloping topout.

name: Nintendo
description: I thought this problem looked a bit like the famous Atari in Bishop as it climbs a narrowing feature on a steep wall. Start with your right hand on a sloper, and your left hand on a slightly better sloper. Smear your feet, work up to better holds with your left hand, and topout.

name: The Hangover
description: What a cool little problem! The Hangover climbs an arete that faces downhill at the lower part of the Skyfall Area.     Start standing with your left hand on the arete and your right on an awkward undercling. Work out some tricky feet and then try to technique your way up the arete. When you get frustrated with trying to technique your way up the arete, turn to your spotter(s), tell them to get ready to witness your supreme coolness, and make a big throw to the lip.

name: Pair of Kings
description: Do you like compression? Want to squeeze with your whole body instead of crimping? Then give this boulder a go.    Start on your back under the low triangle roof. A left hand on a good dish on the left side and your right on the rightmost dish on the right side, is the starting point. Now heel and toe hook you way to the point of the triangle and then top out. Now be surprised how much fun you just had.    Below is a iphone video of the FA, sorry about the poor quality, I will try to get good footage at some point... Also because of the poor quality it looks like m but is on the ground for much of it, that isn't the case, its just a lowball :)   youtube.com/watch?v=0o1RODr…

name: Pop Goes the Weasel
description: Start standing with your right hand on a good sidepull and your left hand on a crimp/dish thing. Get your right foot on a decent chip, pull off the ground and pop to the good crimp. Find some good feet and grab the jugs for the finish.     Have fun!

name: Punch to the Face
description: Start with a toe hook around the side with your right foot and a low smear with the left. Reach up and around the face to grab the sloper with a thumb catch for your right hand and a terrible pinch for your left is on the rock face. Pull yourself off the ground to gain a good crimp with your left hand Then get your right foot on the better knob and bring your right hand up to another sloper. Get your left foot on the terrible pinch and stand up to a good horn/jug thing and work your feet up as you go. After that the top out is kinda funky with a not so good sloper and smearing.     Have someone throw your shoes up to you and walk off the far side of the boulder. It might be kinda like a shimmy down.

name: The Steepness
description: A steep face with holds is hard to find in the Waterville region, and The Steepness would be amazing were it not for the small boulders guarding a low start.     The idea is to start as low as possible to maximize the steep climbing. Start with your left hand on a low crimp and your right heel on a pretty obvious dish at the same level as your hand. Make a hard move with your right hand to a crisp edge, and then move your left hand to a slightly sloping hold (crux). Lock off, and follow jugs to topout. Starting higher significantly lessens the difficulty.

name: Maine
description: Not much of a crux on this problem.  The landing is OK but there should be no reason to fall and a pad will be enough to cover the lumps in the ground here.  It has not been cleaned.  Only a 1 star route but once cleaned might serve as a easy warm up.

name: Bildungsroman
description: Unfortunately the crux is at the top.  It is a sloped mantle.  I fell attempting the move on my first try and walked away a bit scared but was in good enough condition to get it clean on the second go...the ground is very soft here.

name: Lead Belly
description: There are a lot of moves in a short distance at the beginning but once you get past the crux (8ft up) it is a very easy top out.  This is a excellent route though the tree behind it removes a star.  (you will not hit the tree if you fall but it would be nice if it wasn't there)

name: Sundays with Noah
description: This is the first route one will come to when arriving at The A Wall.   It looks like a stack of pancakes made of rock.   Start under the roof. The initial couple moves are the most difficult. Then you'll move left on pump causing moves and finish with a powerful top out.  The rock here is smooth but gripy and not sharp like much of the Yellow Jacket area.  In addition the climb is only 5 feet at it's highest so it favors the boulderers out there.

name: Tiara
description: The whole route/problem is pretty much the same difficulty, the first 2/3 is micro feet and small holds, then balance, and a slope/mantel finish

name: Vacation Station
description: This is just left of "Sundays with Noah".  The climbing is very easy until the top out.  It also needs a little more cleaning.  All in all I would suggest this route as a warm up or cool down.

name: Pho   5
description: I'd say the crux is the first couple of moves.  Thin holds and tiny feet to start then a couple of arete holds to a final, somewhat positive hold and the top out, I used one of the three trees to get back down, the top is not clean yet either.

name: Vertex
description: This route starts up the huge obvious flake. It breaks left with difficulty and hand traverses up the arete to am exciting finish up the tip of the steep prow.

name: Axiom
description: A wild route that has a lot of climbing in it's short length. Fun at times and brutal as well. Stretch or jump to the rail. Move left to the crux. Small holds on steep rock to gain a mid way jug. One more slightly easier boulder problem gets you to the top. watch your back on the tree behind you. You can extend the last bolt down to clip it from the jug if you want to reduce the tree danger.

name: Lateral Thinking
description: Crimp straight up to a nice left hand hold and then traverse straight to the right on a steep slab. The climbing is so deviously technical it is hard to imagine. The sequence is impossible to remember completely but it so fun! The falls are cush. The thing is a must do for a granite slab master.

name: No Hard Feelings
description: A fantastic route deserving of traffic. gotta be able to crimp but don't forget to bring your slab game for the upper half. Classic granite movement.

name: White Tigertail
description: A short route with cool moves but it is marred a little by it's short length and it's position on the hillside. Not a bad warm up as far as getting you out of your head and waking your body up to movement.

name: Adventurer's Route
description: If you enter from the bolder blocked passage, right before you scramble down into the main cave this is a line of least resistance that moves up the chimney and around stuck boulders before you make a horizontal squeeze back into the world of daylight.

name: Gollums Escape
description: OW/squeeze chimney with a short stemming traverse at the top.  With some OW technique this will go down easily then you'll finish 45/50 feet above the crevasse, straddle either side and pull around right for the top out.

name: Risen from khazaduum
description: This route fulfilled a dream for me. To put up a climb that climbs one wall and then transfers to an opposing wall to finish the climb. Start on easy low angle rock past 3 bolts. Maybe 5.6. stem across the divide and clipped a fixed draw (I left a fixed draw in case you were short on reaching the bolt). It is a good idea to step back down and extend the last draw on the initial wall. Make the transfer to the other side. Climb up placing trad gear under the roof. Move around to the right placing another piece and move back left to the anchor. Lower back down out of the sun and into the void.

name: The secret Fire
description: Slick clip the first bolt or climb up to the left and reach out from a good foot hold to make the clip. Smear your way up past the first 2 or 3 bolts more easily and then face a crimpy crux past the 4th bolt. Beyond that the wall steepens and the holds get bigger. What a cool and unlikely place to have a sweet slab climb. It would be possible in parts to stem across or chimney to the wall behind you but I like it best as a pure face/slab route. Do it however you see fit though, it's going to be fun either way and there is unlikely going to be anyone in the cave to judge you for your choices ;)

name: Ashwinder
description: Climb up the blocky rock between the main Cavern Cliff wall and the Block aiming for the right leaning crack in the steeper upper wall. The first half is maybe a 5.5 scramble. Make crux moves through the groove at the bottom left end of the crack. Climb around to the right following the crack. Jam your way up past a wide section and on to the top out. There is a sling anchor on a tree with 2 fixed lower off biners.

name: Gypsy Cafe
description: The first route I noticed when exploring the area with Jay Knower in early September 2013. This line is the most direct and obvious line to ascend The Upper Cliff.  It is also the same crack that forms Gollums Escape (located inside of Gandalf Cave).  Climb the first 20 foot section with lay backing then mantle onto the low angle shelf and get ready for the off width.  The 20 foot off width section is the best and most difficult part of the route.  Getting into the off width is the first crux as it bulges out to give you blind footing.  Towards the top there is a good hand hold inside the crack.  Finish the off width and continue up the Low angle slab another 20 feet and  either cut left and hike off or mount another 4 foot wall and top out to hike off.

name: Mettle
description: Mettle is the thin and crimpy face to the right of Gypsy Cafe.  Start in front of a small cluster of trees, gain a rail the figure out how to get the rail under your feet. Once your standing on the rail work up the vertical face on smears, crimps, and small feet.  Grab the edge and move slightly right to large positive holds, mantle the low angle shelf and walk off left.

name: Yellowjacket Slab
description: As you walk to the right from the cavern itself look for a ledge that you can just reach (or not quite) with your feet on the ground. The first bolt is over the lip on the ledge. Stick clip it and pull a V2 boulder problem to get up on the ledge (or just pull on the draw A0  style) your reward will be a much more moderate slab moving left at perhaps 5.8 and then up a truly easy beautiful white slab. At the top you may look out to the amazing view of the valley or look down into Gandalf's Cave.

name: Astro Creep
description: Starting in the wide crack on the far left move up to a good stance and make moves out to the right and up to a jug on the vertical face. The crux involves a tiny crim, a decent crimp and a move to the right to grab a solid jug. Another big move or two and you are clipping the anchors. Short but quite sweet.

name: Escape Room
description: This one is a little extra interesting. I think it has some of the best movement of the routes on Bald Knob. Somewhat unfortunately it is stuck behind the block in a narrow passage. I think that makes it kinda cool but it is a little contrived since you could totally stem off the wall behind you if you decided to. You also need an attentive belayer. The falls can all be done safely but not every belay is a solid belay (hint, don't keep a big loop of slack out on this one.... or anywhere that's not a clean overhanging pumpfest). Okay, enough with the set up. Walk around The Block and through a comfortable passage into "the back room". This line climbs the detached flake to a jug, traverses left on edges, moves up the arete and back right to the anchor. The last bolt is a little oddly placed but can be clipped easily if you find the position. Rock quality dictated its position. Expect a variety of movement and holds and expect to use your core muscles!

name: Moss Line
description: If you love a good crimpy face route in the hard 5.12 range you must do this one! Once a mossy streak just left of the 90 degree arete on the block Jay cleaned it off and made it work. Basically a 5.12a that leads to a really hard finish involving a tiny hold, a sloper, an arete and a dynamic deadpoint or jump depending on your reach. There are options for shorter folks but it is better suited to longer climbers.

name: Steady State
description: As you approach The Block you will see an off-width crack on the left side where is it detached from the cliff, Steady State starts by laybacking that crack. It is too big for gear so there are bolts to protect it. After the crack, stand on the ledge and ponder the delightful crimpy boulder problem that gets you to the lip of the boulder. Execute that and traverse left to the highpoint and the anchor.

name: June Bug
description: The start is the crux. Thin moves up the corner to get your hands on a beefy ledge. Place a thin cam (.3 BD works well). Continue up the corner to its yop. move left into an under-cling (there is a bolt just over the lip. Clip it). Make thin but solid moves up onto the slab (best part of the climb) and do a quick jog to the anchor.

name: Michael Boltin
description: A little route up the right arete just before you get to the alcove. Climb crux moves off the ground heading over toward the arete. Get some easier climbing on the arete and then head back left onto the slab finish.

name: One Mind
description: Though it looks like an off-width crack it climbs a bit more like a sport route for the most part. Stick Clip the first bolt. Layback the crack by it's right wall until you can transfer hands to the left wall. Use a little chimney style to inch your way up past 2 more bolts to the ledge. Walk the ledge to the upper wall and dance your way to the anchors. You can climb the 5.7 to the left to set this up on TR if you aren't feeling the lead.

name: Two Bodies
description: A delightful start and a puzzling finish for the grade. Climb the crack up the corner which goes at maybe 5.6 until you reach the top. The exit is perhaps 5.7. step up the slab to the last 2 bolts. Tricky face moves lead to better holds and a two bolt anchor. This route shares an anchor with the wide crack on the right so maybe you want to run a top rope lap on that.

name: Frame of Mind
description: Climb up below the first bolt then traverse left below the overlap. Clip a second bolt and manage a tricky pull onto the slab. Move up and left to gain a point of rock that feels great after all that slab friction. Stand on the point and get ready for round two. A mixed protection puzzle session trying to work your way up the slab/chimney. Romp up and right to a two bolt anchor shared with Thunder Buddies.

name: Thunder Buddies
description: Before it was cleaned this looked like it would be a splitter hand crack. Unfortunately in some ways, in the upper half it narrows right down to nothing in the back. This does make it a more formidable challenge however and that's always fun. Climb the easy first half to a stance then navigate the interesting flaired upper half taking care in gear placement as it is pretty particular and tricky to protect in the crux.

name: Divination
description: Another line that just needed to be climbed. A thin line of dark stone shows the way to a sweet hand crack (which is sadly choked by a stump but maybe that will go away some day). Start in a pocket. Friction up to a crux mantel. Move right to another unlikely pocket and up to the crack. Jam it damnit. Sail on good gear around the unfortunate stump and up to the anchors. If the stump goes it will earn another star.

name: Never lonesome
description: Climb the stunning friction slab on the left side of the wall past 4 bolts and placing a small to mid sized cam in the horizontal crack. Pure friction and some micro features keep you working most of the way. Reminiscent of Lonesome Dove at Rumney which inspired the name.

name: Rib Flair
description: The easiest and most committing route on this wall. Start up the thin Dike on the right side. Keep your eyes out for a sneaky placement about where you start wanting one. Follow cracks and grooves up the right side of the wall. At the top you may either go less directly around the right at 5.7 or more directly at 5.8+ which I think is more fun. Either way that section is bolt protected. Move left and clip the 2 bolt anchor.

name: Stop Motion Silence
description: This is the hardest route in the Slablands but it sticks with the theme. The crux is less than vertical and thin as can be. Climb up to the first bolt mantling onto a thin rail and gaining a shallow pocket. Better holds above lead to 5.8 friction and onto the main course. Place a .75 cam or similar and take a step right as you mantle to stand in the crack. Clip two bolts on the imposibly thin face. Manage a slopy sequence at the lip and sink into a finger crack. Move right to clip the DIvination anchor.

name: Drowning Upstream
description: This is the loose blocky chimney in the corner of the alcove. With a cleaning it might just be fun. In it's present state I Have to say, sadly, don't bother. We climbed it in a fit of excitement when it was soaking wet. Although it was cool in a way, I guess my lead was a bad call even though I pulled through. I couldn't find protection aside from a VERY tipped out #6 cam for the crux exit and the lichen was comically slippery...If my life didn't depend on friction. Sometimes simply surviving isn't enough. Next time I hope I have the presence of mind to wait until it's dry, clean it and make it feel good. You think I will? Or will I get up to my old tricks again?

name: Slipstream
description: This was Torie's first 100% her own, route she put up. It is delicate and technical and every time I climb it I think about how slippery it was soaked in parts on the first ascent. Start on the vertical wall around the right hand corner. Make steep moves over onto the slab and then get dancing! Tictac your way past 4 bolts and onto a 2 bolt anchor.

name: Stream Line
description: What a feature! you can't miss the wide off-width flake that marks the upper half of the route. Every time you walk by and don't climb this route you are taking a year off of a baby seal's life. Pad up the friction slab past 2 bolts (optional gear between) and stand beneath the flake of the gods. Place more gear on your way up the crack (I hope you brought your number #6 camalot! Once the #6 is in place rock your way up the flake to the top out. Clip the tree-sling/Biner anchor and take another lap... If you care about seals...

name: Tributaries
description: Connect the cracks up the scarred wall past one bolt. Moving left can be tricky as the grooves trend right. Take care placing 1 more cam (#2) after the bolt, as it is good but can be finnicky. This is just fun. Climb it. Stay on your feet and enjoy.

name: Descent
description: The crux is in the middle and is basically one move the rest of the climb is easy slab. This first climb wasn't a ascent it was a descent. A friend of a friend of mine has gone and bolted the beautiful friction climbs we used to top rope. These top roped climbs varied from (5-7 to 5-10). There won't be any waiting to get on a climb here.

name: Journey to Lost World
description: Located on Bald Knob (southern end of the Acteon Range) in the col. on its southern end.     Find the 40' diagonal crack in a right facing wall. Steep and pumpy to 2 bolt belay. The 2nd pitch climbs up the slab past one bolt. Bold.   Rap w/2 ropes or descend a gully.

name: Lose Yourself
description: A hard friction testpiece that starts thin as can be and gets a little easier as you ascend. Stick clip the first bolt. Climb the thin as can be slab past 3 bolts to the first actual feature. Slight run out to the 4th bolt then follow the right trending undercling to it's conclusion. Break straight up the smooth slab for 2 more honestly spaced bolts to the final romp to the anchor on the wall above.

name: A Dilemma
description: And a life lesson.     P1. 75, 5.6 Climb the only clean section of cliff in the vicinity up to a small ledge with a tree.     P2. 75, 5.7+ From the ledge move right and up past a bulge (crux) protected by a small cam placement under a flake (the only gear on the route) continue up to the trees.     While exploring the area one day I thought I would just take a short cut to the top. The plan was to solo up this clean section of cliff. After passing the tree ledge with a full pack on I was held up at a bulge. I down climbed back to the ledge and after some sole searching tied off to the tree and led the second pitch rope solo. Although not the type of thing I would like to do everyday it was a fun adventure and a good experience.

name: Conehead direct
description: Climb up face using crack sometimes. Belay at large tree. move up right and then head left into very shall ridge and belay near end of ridge. Climb directly up to shallow ceiling go through into v-groove to the top. This is the first climb on Conehead I know of. It is a cliff that most rock climbers hate because of lichen, weak wood like rock flakes and dirty top offs.    A few of us love it, a very few! Therefore my ratings will be tuned to the drum of an audience of participants, that would believe one star for any climb on it would be to high a rating for the cliff. I finished leading the climb in a snow storm.

name: Left Buttress
description: This climb begins left of the central wall and offers the best climbing up the buttress where the first pitch is moderate (5-6) with decent small stopper protection in the crack for the whole distance of the buttress. The top half has practically no protection up a corner dike and then moves are made out away from the dike to the left horizontally to finish up a steep wall to the top at an easy grade (5-3) for most of a ropes length little to no pro.

name: Love to Hate it
description: Start up face to an arching corner and belay. Go over outside edge of corner to another outside corner and follow it to the top. Ted's one and only climb at Conehead.

name: Murphy's Rule
description: Climb face (no pro, 5-4) and surmount arch and make belay 20ft higher. Stopper contrived belay and very little protection as a Belay. Go up and left across ceiling to next ceiling. Go up right side of ceiling to dirty face climbing. Finish the climb with much dirt on the rock at the top. It is very exciting climb though a dirty finish. Protection in the hard (5-7) ceilings is excellent.

name: Variation to Left Buttress
description: After the buttress move right under ceiling to inside diagonal corner and follow it to the summit. Corner near summit often has seepage. A better protected an higher difficulty way to the summit.

name: Variations to Cone Head Direct
description: There are a few variations to this climb. You can go up the left central face and join up with the ridge. From the ridge belay you can move right and travel past large flakes to the furthest outside corner and take this corner to the summit. you can move left from the ridge belay and climb up the face instead to the v-groove.

name: Apples and Regalia
description: But I thought Apples was a cat?Climb broken rock up to a ledge below a blunt arete. Climb the arete using a thin crack for pro. At about halfway is a technical and engaging crux section. Atop the arete step right across the face to the anchor on Puppies.Lower off

name: Bear S**t Corner
description: A beautiful, striking right leaning corner and crack. Although the corner is only about 30 feet tall that's 30 feet of great climbing that's every bit of 5.8.    Climb the corner plugging in cams. Above run it out up easy ground to a tree and belay.    Either scramble back down to the starting alcove on from the right or walk off left back to the main wall.

name: Chicken Dinner
description: A top rope route that weaves its way up the left side of the buttress using the arête, cracks and the face right of Sharkey.     Start to the left of the toe on the buttress. climb up to the arête  on its left side. Climb rightward then back left stepping over the arête and onto the face. A little face climbing leads the buttress's top. Step left over the fist crack on Sharkey to a hand crack leading to the trees.    Rap/Lower from trees.

name: Dickey's Eliminate
description: Okay, yes this is quite a contrived route...Climbing up twin cracks is just great fun though if you can get over the urge to make easier moves on Dickey's proper.     From the left, step into the crack left of Dickey's Notch. With one foot and one hand in each crack climb past the ledge where the corners start crossing a pillar and ending up at the ledge above the Stone frogs corner. Instead of moving up look left climb a juggy wall to a stance again stepping left to the final crack on Ride the Turtle.

name: Dickey's Notch
description: I bet you just can't wait to stick you fingers into dickey's notch, hehe. Seriously though the crack is awfully small.     A sequential move off the ground leads to a stance to place gear (small nut), fun sporty climbing leads up the crack depositing you on a small triangle ledge below the first corner. Stem up this, a little tough to place pro but its all right there, finding better holds out left before pulling up to ledges and a tree below a final short corner. climb the corner past a bolt to it's top.     Rap lower from bolted anchor, or trees.

name: Possom 20:13
description: Climb the toe of the buttress to a stance. Technical climbing up its right side lands you on a thank goodness jug and a big cam. Another push takes you to the top of the buttress. Progressively easier climbing up a crack then slab leads to the top.    Walk off climbers left.

name: Puffin Express
description: The quickest and easiest way to the top.     Kind of a choss pile with a couple of good moves along the way. Climb a right facing corner up past an overlap then up dirty ledges to the top. Belay from trees.

name: Puppies n' Knapsacks
description: A great route showcasing typical climbing at the park.    Jam up an 8 foot perfect hand crack, swing over right and mantle to a ledge. Step up left towards a thin left leaning crack and carefully get in a piece of gear (I think a red c3 did the trick). Commit to the crack, clip a piton and move left on worsening holds until you're at a mono crimp. Another big move left finds juggy climbing back right up a crack to a spruce tree anchor. Lower off.     Stepping into the crux crack can be a little spooky on this one but the holds are good to start and once the piton is clipped the crux is about as well protected as it gets, small falls.

name: Ride the Turttle
description: Ride, ride, the turtle. This is a super cool rock climb with great moves, variety and a few cruxey sections.     Start up a short but thuggish hand crack to a ledge in a left facing corner that tapers out above. Climb the corner (bolt) to the top then push and pull to make a step right gaining a sloping stance before the crux, bolt. Traverse right a few thin moves into a crack then follow it to the top.     Lower from bolted anchor with biners.    Originally led on all gear and a pin it was a very committing route. The addition of a couple of bolts make this a real fun route for anyone comfortable at the grade.

name: Sharkey
description: There are any number of ways to start this, the driest probably being the best.     Face climb to the right of the gully/corner on the left side of the buttress. After reaching the top of the buttress climb a fist crack to its end. Either step left to lower or continue up a slab to the top and walk off to the climbers left.

name: Stone Frogs Don't Eat
description: They do however leap from ledges with little provocation.     Start off a toe in the middle of the wall at the base of a splitter right slanting crack. Jam and layback up the crack then rock right to two stepped ledges before gaining an attractive corner. There are now two finishes after the layback corner. 1) move right around a tested but uneasy feeling block to the tree ledge and an easy corner leading to the top. 2) The now preferred finish, atop the corner climb the left face using quartz holds to a stance on the final crack of Ride the Turtle, climb the crack and lower from a bolted anchor.

name: Autumnal Skylour
description: Follow an left angling hand crack to near the top, then straight on up.

name: Come Spring
description: Good crack climbing up the center of the crag.

name: The Furrow
description: A boulder start leads to an easy crack and the top.

name: Winter Wheat
description: Climbs the Steepest crack on the crag staying right to finish.

name: AKA Crack
description: Obvious layback crack in the middle of the face. A sit start, involving grovelly jams in a flare, is possible for the displaced trad climber.

name: Circle Circle
description: The left most line on the back face of the boulder. Start with both your hands and your left heel on an obvious shelf. Reach up to crimps, use the right arête, and throw to the lip. A great little problem.

name: Corridor Crack
description: Climb the obvious layback crack located in the "corridor". Fun laybacking with the crux coming at the top.    This gets the PG-13 rating because a fall from the crux could send you crashing into the walls behind you. Also the corridor is narrow so a crash pad is hard to put down. Good climbing though!

name: Green Face
description: Climb the face just right of Yellow Blazes. A hard pull gets you onto the face.

name: The Red Line Arete
description: You could walk past this line a hundred times and not notice it. This problem is not tall, but it's fierce.    We thought this was a project until we heard that Bobby Hardage climbed this circa 1998/2000. I believe he started sitting and he kept both hands on the arete and worked to the top that way.      Another possible variation is to start with your left hand on the corner and your right hand on an edge in the red streak. Then, climb the face by slapping your left hand up the corner. I'm not sure if this variation has been done.     The grade is just an estimate and could be off +/- 3 V points.

name: The Thanksgiver
description: This is the striking s-shaped corner feature in the middle of the face. Sit start, and climb the corner to a crux just before the lip. The landing is bad.

name: Tilted Tree
description: Start with your right hand on an edge and your left hand around the corner. Slap to the lip, move left, and top out. Try to avoid grabbing the tree roots.

name: Yan's Slab
description: Many variations are possible on this slab. The best variation is on the far left side, at a point where you can actually place a crashpad below.

name: Yellow Blazes
description: Classic. Start by two yellow blazes and climb holds and the arête to a fun topout. The rock on this is perfect, maybe among the best granite in New Hampshire.     Since the trail passes right through these boulders, I wouldnt be surprised if some intrepid hiker nabbed the FA of Yellow Blazes.

name: The White House
description: White House  is currently the hardest line in Waterville, and was climbed in a very impressive effort by Dave Wetmore.  It follows a striking line up the steepest, tallest part of the House Boulder. Start with your hands crossed on two crimps and go left to a pocket in the seam. Work your way to the lip and then climb the towering arete to the top.

name: Bear Claw
description: The left-most climb on this face. Start on the obvious flake and immediately top out. Not classic.

name: The Comma Splice
description: The Comma Splice climbs the unlikely bulging face on the left side of the trail as you walk up from the House Boulder.     Start with an edge for your left hand, a sloper for your right, and a perfect left foot under the bulge. Throw right hand to a great hold, then throw left hand to another great hold. Press out the topout. The moves flow so well on this problem.

name: Diagonal
description: Start as for Bear Claw and climb right up the obvious diagonal crack. Devious and technical.

name: Iron Face
description: Not as good as it looks, this problem climbs the center of the face on unique rock.

name: Mini Moo
description: This is a surprisingly good little problem despite being about five feet tall. Sit start on the steep face left of Bear Claw. Slap to the lip, throw to a big left sidepull and top out.

name: Slopers
description: Sit start on the jug on the shelf. Work up and left, heel hook the jug, match the next sloping shelf and top out. This climb took several days to clean, as it was encased in eons of mud, leaves, lichen, and neglect.

name: The Triangle
description: Often wet. Always contrived. Climb the triangle feature on the right. Top out the boulder, or more likely, grab the tree and call it good.

name: Mayhem
description: Awesome. Theres no question as to where the line is. Grab the only big hold on the whole face, a sidepull, and paste your feet on the wall. Match on the sidepull and gun to the lip. The topout is a bit heady, but it's classic.

name: Lucky Strike
description: Start immediately right of Shallow Corner on a right hand sidepull and a high right foot. Stand up and brave the slopey topout. A great find.

name: Shallow Corner
description: This is another problem that I wouldnt be surprised if it had been done before, though it was pretty dirty when we got to it.  Climb the corner feature to the top. Its a really good problem because it requires a perfect combination of balance and power.

name: Bitter Smile Stand
description: Start with your left hand on a pinch, and your right on a sloping edge around the corner. Slap to the slopey lip and top  out. The sit start is still a project.

name: Double Heelix
description: Some people dont like lip traverse boulder problems. Those people have not climbed Double Heelix. Start on the far right on the obvious spike. Throw a heel up, and start traversing left, past a slopey section, an awkward section, and to the left corner. Top out. Now thats what a lip traverse is supposed to be.

name: The Handyman
description: This is an interesting and unique problem that climbs the right side of the main Widowmaker face. It has a sketchy start, strange routefinding, and a hair-raising topout. One must be pretty handy to successfully complete this problem.      Start standing on the slab on the right. This slab sticks out from the base of the boulder, so make sure to pad it correctly and be mindful of the edge when you do the first few moves of the problem.  Reach high to a good hold at the lip, pull onto the wall, and start traversing left. Traverse a few moves left, about to the center of the wall, and then figure out the topout. Luckily, the leftward traverse moves one away from the scary slab ledge below, so the topout, though heady, has a pretty good landing below it.

name: Paint Chips
description: Did you eat paint chips as a kid?    Climb the cleaned face to the left of Widow Left. The climbing is much harder than it looks.

name: Single Heelix
description: Double Heelixs younger sibling. This climb is much more mellow, shorter, and easier than its relative up the hill.

name: Sunset Crack
description: The Davis Boulders answer to Hobbit Hole at P-Way, though this is a bit harder and arguably better than its cousin to the south.  Sit start on the left of the face. Use the left arête and thin holds to gain the crack. Follow the crack up and right to an easy topout. The stand start is V2.

name: Widow Leftside
description: Start sitting on the left arête with your left hand on a good edge. Stand up to a crimp, heel hook left, and reach to a surprisingly good hold. Top out as for Widowmaker.

name: Widowmaker
description: Classic. This climb relies on an obvious pinch hold. Start with your right hand on the pinch (use the cheater stone if need be), and your left on an obvious crimp. Pull up, and throw to the left corner. Keep bumping up the corner to a heroic topout.

name: I Got 99 Problems, But this Crimp Ain't One
description: This is a powerful little problem on an out of the way boulder. I think its worth the thrash to get there. Start with your hands on crimps at head-height. Lock off hard, reach left hand to another crimp and throw to the top.

name: AA
description: Much, much harder than it looks. AA stands for Awkward Arete. Or is it Amazing Arete? I cant remember...anyway, start in the pit and place your right foot on a low edge by the block. Use slopers on the arête to get your feet on the huge foothold. The topout is exciting.

name: Slopey Crimp Project
description: The face just left of AA has some nice crimps, but they're all just slopey enough to make them difficult to use. Plus there's not much for feet. Whoever can piece together the holds on this wall will open up a really cool problem.

name: Tomahawk
description: Tomahawk is THE classic arête in an area filled with classic arêtes. Start sitting with your hands on an edge, move to the left corner using slopey holds, and top out.

name: White Fang
description: Start right of Tomahawk with your right hand on a large fang hold and your left on an edge. Heel hook your left foot by your hand, and reach to the pinch with your left hand. Establish on the pinch and throw to the lip. Awesome.

name: The Noise
description: Climb the face and arête right of the tree. The crux consists of a tenuous mantle on the holds at head height. Perfect rock.

name: The Signal
description: Start in the middle of the face with a good foothold and climb crimps to the top. Sharp, but good.

name: High Chair
description: Climb crimps to a topout. Harder if you avoid the good fin way to the right.

name: Outlier
description: A classic stem to arête problem with a great topout.

name: The Prow
description: Sit start and climb decomposing rock up the prow.

name: E-xcavator
description: This climbs the blunt prow facing the trail. Start with a cool left sidepull and a fight edge. Lock off to a good slopey hold and navigate the awkward topout.    The sit start is a really great-looking project.

name: Green Shoots
description: Green Shoots climbs the arete/corner on the right side of the boulder. Start with your left hand on a cool sloper and your right hand on a hold on the arete. Bring your foot to a big right foothold, bring left hand to a good small crimp, slap right hand to a bump around the corner, and move up and left to topout.

name: Ground Up
description: Ground Up climbs the slab on the right side of the boulder. Start on a big foothold and smear your way up.    This problem was cleaned free on the lead. As such, it's still really dirty. It might be a nice little problem when clean.

name: John Henry Traverse
description: Start on good holds as far right as possible. Traverse left until you can get a heel on and rock to the slopy lip. For extreme lowballs, this one's pretty good.

name: Waiting
description: This is an aesthetic line up the face of the Midway Boulder as seen approaching from the trail. The crux is the first move then the climb eases a bit in difficulty.  Start matched on the cool sloper hold in the middle of the face. Use a far left foot to pull into a hard lock off and shoot out left to gaston a positive hold. Match then go up and right to a good hold and lock it off to reach the lip.  A stream runs directly through the landing zone early spring but it was completely dried up by mid May.

name: Abandon Ship
description: crimp and balance your way up

name: Evening Arete
description: Classic. Climb the obvious sweeping arête on the left side of the Wooden Ship formation.

name: Haiku
description: Haiku is a perfect little boulder problem. Start sitting with your left hand on an arete and your right on a crimp. Slap up the arete and throw to the lip. The topout is just difficult enough to make you pay attention.

name: Mark 12:28
description: Very good climbing, solid moves on positive holds. The hardest moves are in the first 10-15 feet then it eases to 5.9/VO moves with big holds.    I would put this route at the level of Black Jack Crack in Rumney as far as quality.    I first top roped this with a mini ascender and back up knots, took some lead like falls and dialed in the moves. After I realized that the hardest climbing was at a safe height, the landing is flat, and was overall a reasonable risk I completed the route by bouldering/free soloing it.
